<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE IN NINTH 2-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. -- It went down in the scorebook simply as
a stolen base, but the ninth-inning play enabled the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays to steal a game from the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Johnson's bases-loaded single in the bottom of the ninth
drove in Miguel Cairo from third with the winning run in the Devil
Rays' 2-1 victory before 13,210 Thursday night at Tropicana Field.
But it was Cairo's steal of third moments earlier that set up the
game-winning hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays had runners on first and second with nobody out
in the ninth and the game tied at 1. The Angels called for the
``wheel'' play. In anticipation of a bunt attempt, third baseman
Troy Glaus charges the plate while shortstop Benji Gil covers
third.
</P>
<P>
   But when batter Bobby Smith didn't square to bunt, Gil stopped.
Cairo broke for third and beat Gil to the bag. With the potential
winning run now on third, the Angels walked Smith intentionally to
load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Darin Erstad was brought in from left field to give
the Angels five infielders, but Johnson's line drive off Shigetoshi
Hasegawa (5-2) sailed just over Gil's outstretched glove and into
center field.
</P>
<P>
   After the game Gil re-enacted the play in the Angels clubhouse
with coach Alfredo Griffin, a major league shortstop for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play is designed for me to beat the baserunner to third
base if (the batter) squares,'' Gil explained. ``Once he didn't
square, I have to stop as quickly as possible and play the
position. I never thought he was that close to me, I should have at
least two or three steps on him. It wasn't so much that he had me
beat, but that he was inside of me and (catcher) Bengie (Molina)
had no throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my responsibility. It's a funny game. I've never seen
that happen, much less happen to me. If that situation comes up
again, I promise now one will beat me. I don't care who it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Gil's mistake was set up by another Angels mistake earlier in
the inning. With Cairo on first and no outs, Steve Cox hit a slow
chopper to Adam Kennedy at second base. In his haste to turn a
double play, Kennedy bobbled the ball and got nobody. Kennedy
appeared unsure of whether to try to tag Cairo or get the force at
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really sure what I was going to do,'' Kennedy said.
``I was trying to catch the ball first. Once you commit to go get
it, you can't stop. I never had it to commit either way.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss ruined another stellar outing by an Angels starting
pitcher. One night after Brian Cooper threw eight scoreless innings
only to watch the Angels lose in the ninth, Jarrod Washburn gave up
just one run and two hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Before Bubba Trammell's solo homer with one out in the sixth,
the last three Angels starters -- Seth Etherton, Cooper and
Washburn -- had combined for 17 consecutive scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   But Devil Rays starter Steve Trachsel was just as good. Trachsel
gave up a run in the seventh inning and nothing more, throwing a
complete game. Before Wednesday, the Devil Rays had one complete
game all season. But Albie Lopez threw one Wednesday, and Trachsel
made it back-to-back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story of the game, and the story the last two nights, is
we're not swinging the bats,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said.
``We're going through a little dry spell and we wasted real good
efforts from the starting pitchers. That's the way it goes. The
hitters have been picking up the pitchers for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   With runs at a premium, the Angels lost one early in the game.
With Darin Erstad on second and two out in the third, Scott Spiezio
singled to right field. Right fielder Jose Guillen made a strong
throw to the plate, but Erstad clearly slid across the plate and
under the tag of catcher John Flaherty. However, homeplate umpire
Mark Wegner called Erstad out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was safe,'' Scioscia said. ``He missed the call. But we
can't hang our hat on a missed call. If we're going to be a
championship club, we have to overcome those breaks. And that was a
break for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
