<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NILE-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST NILE TEST MAY SET OFF INSECTICIDE SPRAYING IN QUEENS
</HEADLINE>
  By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City health officials said on Thursday that
they were preparing to spray insecticide over a broad swath of the
Corona section of Queens next week after tests showed that a
chicken in the area had been infected with the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   At a City Hall news conference, Dr. Neal L. Cohen, the city's
health commissioner, said the spraying in Corona would take place
only if follow-up tests on the chicken confirmed the diagnosis of
West Nile encephalitis, which is transmitted by mosquitoes. The
tests should be completed over the weekend, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If spraying is ordered, officials said, it could begin as early
as Monday night, using trucks that would spray only at night. The
officials said it would not involve either aerial spraying from
helicopters or the insecticide Malathion, both of which provoked
protests when they were used to combat an extensive outbreak of the
virus last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the city would use Resmethrin, marketed under the
brand name Scourge, a substance he described as ``relatively
nontoxic to humans, dogs, cats and other mammals.'' But he urged
people in Corona with asthma or respiratory conditions to stay
indoors when the spraying occurs and to keep their doors closed and
air-conditioners turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the Corona chicken provided the first example of the
city's efforts this year ``to identify the possible return of West
Nile virus as early as possible.'' The chicken was part of an early
detection procedure in which 14 small flocks of chickens have been
placed in coops _ providing a form of mosquito bait _ across the
city.
</P>
<P>
   The effort also includes intensive monitoring of dead birds in
the region and the use of millions of tiny fish that eat mosquito
larvae in the city's waste treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
   If the chicken from Corona is found to be carrying the West Nile
virus, it will be the first confirmed case in New York City this
year. Last week, the disease was found to have killed three crows
not far from New York City's borders, in Rockland County and in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The city's selection of Resmethrin came after angry protests
last year over the use of Malathion, an insecticide that some
experts had associated with severe health side affects. After its
use by the city, Malathion was subjected to a fresh safety review
by federal environmental officials, who last month said they had
concluded that it was safe for routine use in killing mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Philip J. Landrigan, director of the Center for Children's
Health and the Environment at Mount Sinai Medical Center, said
yesterday that Resmethrin was ``much safer than Malathion.'' He
said the city's plan to confine its spraying in Corona to trucks
and avoid aerial spraying would ``greatly reduce the risk of
insecticide drifting into areas beyond its control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
