</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BRYANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: AT 21, THE LAKERS' BRYANT IS LIVING HIS DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Kobe Bryant was tracked down in a dark corridor
at the Conseco Fieldhouse Thursday by an admirer who shared an
opinion with the wunderkind guard of the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know with that game last night, the way you pulled it out,
you crossed the threshold,'' the man said. ``You know that,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you're right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever invisible barrier exists between the spectacular and
the transcendent, Bryant stepped into another world Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the numbers _ he scored eight of his 28 points in
overtime _ that piggybacked the Lakers to a 120-118 victory over
the Indiana Pacers in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the body language, the way he sneered at Reggie
Miller on the perimeter before blowing past him to the basket. It
was not the way he kept his right wrist cocked in a follow-through
motion after dropping in a 23-foot jump shot with 1 minute 20
seconds left in overtime, a pose reminiscent of Michael Jordan's in
1998, when he nailed the coffin shut on the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the sweet reverse layup off a rebound with 5.9
seconds left that demoralized the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the interview room _ the sweat barely dried and a 3-1
lead in the NBA finals secure _ where Kobe Bryant showed he was 21
going on 40. He understood the moment, carrying the team after
Shaquille O'Neal fouled out with 2:33 left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the game I've been dreaming about, to be honest with
you,'' Bryant said. ``These are the type of situations I dream
about every day. When I was a kid, watching the NBA on TV, I always
wanted to be in a game like this, where you can't stop them from
scoring and they can't stop you. This is what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When exactly was Kobe Bryant a kid? The player who starred in an
NBA heirloom in the heartland looked older and sounded much wiser
than 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome,'' Larry Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe was great,'' Phil Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was so enraptured with Bryant's performance that he
deigned to bestow a nickname on Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Little Brother,'' O'Neal said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has deftly avoided the Jordan comparisons. Of Bryant's
performance on Wednesday, the Lakers' coach said: ``I've seen a lot
of great ones, but, you know, when you compare the fact that I
probably coached, what, 100 games, 110, 115 games with Michael
Jordan, I saw a lot of games above or beyond that level from an
individual performer. But that's not to take anything away from
Kobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant Thursday led everyone along on the journey _ from the
cocksure 18-year-old rookie who fired up air balls against the Jazz
in the playoffs to the impetuous, one-on-one All-Star who had
trouble co-existing with O'Neal to the consummate star and
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought the game to me in a different light,'' Bryant said
of Jackson. ``It was more kind of relaxing, going with the flow of
the game, you know, just investigating the floor really.
</P>
<P>
   ``You penetrate. You know that you can get to that spot, so you
say: `O.K, I know I can get there. I'll come back there later. I
might come back there in the fourth quarter.' Little mind games
that you play. That's how he approached it with me. He taught me
very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, after the Lakers were knocked out in the second
round by the San Antonio Spurs, Bryant intimated to several of his
former high school teammates that life in L.A. was not all good.
</P>
<P>
   He and O'Neal were privately feuding _ they engaged in slap
fight before last season _ trying to work out the dynamics of their
relationship on and off the floor. Worse, observers in and out of
the league wondered aloud if Bryant was not more about himself than
the Lakers, whether he could ever get out of his one-on-five
shoe-commercial mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset that we kept losing in the playoffs,'' Bryant
said. ``I was upset with people talking about my game as far as not
being a team player or being great defensively. I just wanted to
make a change. I wanted to make it happen. I wanted to prove, you
know, that what they were saying was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   This season Bryant passed more often, improved his shot
selection and slowed the game down in his mind, picking his spots
rather than attacking the basket on every possession. Now, he and
O'Neal are on the cusp of their first title.
</P>
<P>
   You have to feel for the other poor souls in Bryant's class at
Lower Merion High School outside Philadelphia. At the 10-year
reunion, bank presidents and biophysicists will have to compete
against a fistful of championship rings, unimaginable wealth and a
keen understanding of the world their classmate has attained
without setting foot in a university lecture hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's planning on getting married this summer at 21,'' Jackson
said. ``That seems pretty young in this day and age. Maybe not when
I graduated from college. But I think he's mature beyond his years.
I think he's handling this very well. I think he's grown a lot in
one year. And yet, I see a young man who's still got 13, 14 years
of excellent basketball ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made about Bryant's decision to get engaged _ as
if there was some unwritten rule that an NBA player must have 29
girlfriends in 29 cities before settling down _ that the kid can't
possibly know what he is doing by committing to a 17-year-old high
school senior.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he is already an old soul, who needs neither the bar scene
nor hotel groupies to validate the continued adolescence that
professional sports promotes.
</P>
<P>
   Hypocritical, no, given how fast we want our young stars to grow
up. Whether it is Tiger Woods telling a crude joke or Allen Iverson
paying blind homage to his trouble-making friends from the
neighborhood, we often malign young athletes for transgressions we
made at their age. We give them no grace period to grow up, to
learn to be adults before they take over their companies and
dominate their chosen professions.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, here is Bryant, ruining the curve for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   This is what he did after the most 47 scintillating minutes of
his career on Wednesday. Bryant did not celebrate with childhood
friends until the wee hours of the morning. He retreated to his
hotel room, telephoned his fiancee, Vanessa Laine, his mother, Pam,
and father, Joe ``Jellybean'' Bryant, a former NBA player, elevated
his sore ankle that kept him out of Game 3 to reduce the swelling,
and fell asleep. No clubs, no parties. Just a responsible employee,
readying himself for work the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   When Bryant was 19, cruising through Venice Beach in his
jet-black BMW, he admitted that he liked the music of the Spice
Girls. Now, this could be seen as culture suicide, the end of his
hip-hop icon status. But Bryant liked the idea of young kids
pushing the limits, and we was not afraid to share that opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know a single 19-year-old in America who would make such
an admission about the Backstreet Boys today?
</P>
<P>
   Byrant also felt a kinship with Martina Hingis and the Williams
sisters, Venus and Serena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're out there doing the impossible at such a young age,''
he said. ``You can't help but admire that, that they know what they
want that young.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most conventional thoughts circulating in the league
was that Bryant had somehow been coaxed by his management into
early marriage; that in order to project a cleaner, corporate image
like Michael the Infallible, he needed to have the appearance of a
family on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we reach for things that aren't there. Closer to the
truth, Kobe Bryant probably went after the girl he dreamed of
marrying with the same passion and zest he went after Game 4. Not
everyone needs their 20s to grow up anymore. The kid knows what he
wants.
</P>
<P>
   Now fit him for two rings: one for the wedding and another for
the championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
