</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-ABUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY PASSES BILL ON FALSE ABUSE CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
  By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The New York state Legislature passed a measure
Thursday that would remove the names of hundreds of people who have
been wrongly accused of child abuse from a state registry of
suspected child abusers.
</P>
<P>
   The registry has been in existence since 1973, though the
information it contains is only available to child abuse
investigators, not to the public. It contains the names of about a
million individuals accused of child abuse, as well as the names of
their victims.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, the names of suspected abusers were
removed from the registry when the authorities concluded that the
allegations against the suspect were unfounded or determined that
there was not enough evidence to substantiate the claim.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed after the 1995 death of 6-year-old Elisa
Izquierdo. The child was killed by her mother, who had repeatedly
come to the attention of child welfare workers as a result of
allegations of child abuse that were leveled against her.
</P>
<P>
   Although the mother's name was never on the state list, there
was a public outcry resulting from the case, and Gov. George Pataki
and the Legislature changed the registry rules to prevent unfounded
allegations from being expunged until 10 years after the 18th
birthday of the youngest child in the alleged abuser's family.
</P>
<P>
   The measure that was passed Thursday will allow people who were
wrongfully accused to get their names removed from the list when
they provide ``clear and convincing evidence'' of their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, similar proposals have failed because of
disagreements about how much proof would be required to remove a
person's name from the registry. The new law was sponsored by state
Sen. Nick Spano, a Republican, and state Assemblyman Richard
Brodsky, a Democrat, both of Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was passed in the Assembly Thursday morning; the
Senate ratified it Wednesday night. It is expected to be signed
into law by Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky said the new law would balance the needs of
investigators to know as much as they can about a suspect with the
rights of the wrongfully accused who want to protect their names.
``We unintentionally created a new class of victims and we're now
giving them a chance to get out from under a bureaucratic nightmare
that is not of their own making,'' he said. ``I'm only sorry it
took this long to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear precisely how many people currently on the
registry have been wrongfully accused. Brodsky and other experts
estimate that there are at least hundreds. The two houses also
passed a bill that would allow the state's Department of Correction
to grant work-release to women convicted of killing their spouses
or boyfriends, provided that the woman can show that they were
being abused by the person they killed.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Scott Stringer, a Democrat from Manhattan who
sponsored the bill, said there are about 100 such women in state
prisons today. He said the legislation is especially important
since the state's decision to eliminate parole has meant that these
women have no choice but to serve their whole sentences just like
other convicted killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of tough-on-crime legislation, this is one of the
few times we've moved in the direction of mercy,'' Stringer said.
``These women deserve a second chance at life, at rejoining their
families. There's basically no recidivism among women like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
