<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET GAMBLING BILL HITS SNAG IN HOUSE COMMITTEE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congressional effort to ban Internet gambling ran
into a roadblock Thursday as a House committee questioned whether
the bill had already been hijacked by gaming interests.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, a version of which passed the Senate by
unanimous consent last November, would ban Internet gambling,
except for horse racing, dog racing, jai alai (a game popular in
Florida), ``fantasy sports'' and some Indian gaming. According to
some surveys, online gambling is growing explosively and is
expected to reach an estimated $2.3 billion next year.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Commerce Subcommittee on Telecommunications and
Trade questioned the exceptions, wondering if by allowing certain
types of betting, the bill might actually expand Internet gambling,
as the Justice Department contends.
</P>
<P>
   But the controversy also highlighted the rising difficulties
Congress faces in grappling with the broader issue of whether and
how to attempt to regulate the Internet, a decentralized medium
that by its nature evades control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has serious implications for electronic commerce and the
whole issue of regulating the Internet,'' said Rep. Anna Eshoo, a
Palo Alto, Calif., Democrat and one of congress's leading sponsors
of high-tech legislation. The bill is attempting, she argued, ``to
put artificial boundaries on the Internet, when the Internet was
designed specifically to transcend boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo said the legislation was full of loopholes and could
threaten privacy and civil liberties and put an ``inappropriate
burden'' on the high-tech industry by forcing Internet service
providers to block online gambling sites.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Goodlatte, the Virginia Republican pushing the
legislation, insisted that one of the reasons the Internet ``has
not reached its true potential'' is that ``many folks view it as a
wild frontier, with no safeguards to protect children'' and prevent
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of the Internet to ``penetrate every home and
community across the globe,'' Goodlatte argued, poses ``a challenge
to the sovereignty of civilized communities, states and nations to
decide what is appropriate and decent behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Interstate gambling is already outlawed under as many as five
federal statutes, primarily one covering gambling over ``wire
communications.'' But the bill's supporters said the federal ban
needs to be strengthened to cover non-wire Internet transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Goodlatte maintained that the exemption for online horse and dog
race betting was necessary because some states already permit such
betting on ``closed-loop, subscriber-based systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodlatte also said his bill would prevent states from putting
their lotteries online, by requiring that such lotteries only sell
tickets in public places. No state has yet offered an online
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   But critics charge that the measure was shaped by powerful
interest groups, from the pari-mutuel horse racing industry to
convenience stores that see the Internet as a threat to state
lottery ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major lobbies pushing for the legislation is the
casino industry, which similarly views online betting as potential
competition.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the congressionally charged National Gambling Impact
Study Commission predicted that online wagering ``promises to
revolutionize the way Americans gamble because it opens up the
possibility of immediate, individual, 24-hour access to the full
range of gambling in every home.''
</P>
<P>
   The report found that one web site, ``Rolling Good Times''
provides links to 1,000 Internet sites that offer some form of
betting, including 110 sports betting sites.
</P>
<P>
   Goodlatte argued that online gambling posed a threat to children
and families, citing stories of people betting their families into
financial ruin over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is supported by the National Collegiate Athletic
Association and religious groups, including the Christian Coalition
and the Family Research Council. But the Traditional Values
Coalition withdrew its support arguing that the bill would actually
expand gambling through its various exemptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
