r s BC-GLF-USOPEN-SIDE-LADN     06-16 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTTON'S FAST START IS SPOILED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH - ``The back is fine,'' Hal Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Golf's aging comeback kid couldn't say the same of his back nine
Thursday, plummeting from the lead he had forged with the help of
the first opening-hole eagle at a U.S. Open in 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to take a lot of medicine coming in,'' said Sutton, who
couldn't stay out of the club-twisting rough at Pebble Beach Golf
Links and bunched a double bogey and two bogeys in his final four
holes.
</P>
<P>
   The staggering finish left Sutton at 2-under-par 69 and four
strokes off the lead after he had moved to 6-under par with
consecutive birdies on Nos. 12 and 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a typical U.S. Open golf course,'' the Shreveport, La.,
native said. ``You hit it in the rough, you're gonna pay a price.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was just golf's way of evening things out.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton has been sizzling lately, no small feat for a 42-year-old
man who appeared washed up in 1993. Ten years after after upsetting
Jack Nicklaus to win the '83 PGA Championship at Riviera Country
Club, Sutton had slumped to 185th on the money list and needed his
final exemption to remain on tour.
</P>
<P>
   He somehow rediscovered his game in '94 and hasn't slowed since.
The revived Sutton has won six times including the 1998 Tour
Championship and this year's Players Championship
</P>
<P>
   and was both inspirational and playing leader on last year's
winning U.S. Ryder Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing slowing Sutton's progress has been nagging
injuries, the latest of which struck him Monday, when his back hurt
so much he couldn't swing a club.
</P>
<P>
   Turned out, all he needed was tincture of time.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton rested Tuesday, tested the back Wednesday, then opened
his Open with an eagle on the par-4, 381-yard first hole, finding
the cup with a punched 8-iron from 146 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kinda eased up there and went right in,'' said Sutton,
whose opening eagle was the first since Deane Beman holed a 4-wood
from 230 yards in the 1967 Open at Baltusrol.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, long known for his strong driving and accurate iron
play, has added patience to his power during a comeback that
rekindled memories of his 1980s label as the next Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not quite as much of a risk-taker now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Solid, if less-spectacular play has paid dividends, particularly
at this year's Players Championship. There, Sutton's steady
shotmaking kept him narrowly in front of runner-up Tiger Woods
throughout a tense final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, that was the highlight of my career,'' he said,
``winning at that tournament and certainly winning against Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sutton can muster up the kind of play he had going for 14
holes Thursday (six birdies, one bogey), he might find himself
pushing for another career highlight this week.
</P>
<P>
   Pebble Beach rough could foul the plan. But the injury-forced
lack of practice won't slow Sutton much if recent history is any
indication: He played just nine practice holes before defeating
Woods at the Players Championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
