<HEADLINE>
WOODS OPENS WITH FLAWLESS 65 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ The first round of the 100th U.S. Open
turned into a pillow fight Thursday. The guy in the striped pajamas
was the winner. Not everyone went to bed, either.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed by atmospheric conditions and out-of-this-world
expectations, the Open office-pool pick, Tiger Woods, emerged from
the fog with a flawless effort at Pebble Beach Golf Links, shooting
six-under-par 65 to lead by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Play was stopped because of the low-hanging clouds that obscured
vision and left 75 golfers on the course. Because so many rounds
went unfinished, the Open could be pushed into Monday, or even
Tuesday with a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   They might as well give Woods the silver cup now. Why anyone
would want to go three-plus more rounds with this guy defies
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Woods hit four shots inside two feet. He hit irons off the tee
and a driver off the fairway. He waded through the thick haze
buffeting the Monterey Peninsula, rough steeper than U.S. Open
tradition and the world's best players _ and he didn't bogey.
</P>
<P>
   He was so good, in fact, that his 65, coming on the heels of his
final-round 64 at the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro Am, was the
lowest U.S. Open score recorded on this regal oceanside track.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining himself, Woods was almost smug about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt if I could drive the ball well I could score,'' he
said. ``I drove the ball beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   Fog suspended play at 3:56 p.m., but hardly anyone noticed.
Woods had finished playing three hours earlier. He came away one
shot ahead of Spaniard Miguel Angel Jiminez, two in front of
journeyman John Huston and three better than moonlighting CBS golf
analyst Bobby Clampett.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was unflappable on a day when he had every reason to be
distracted.
</P>
<P>
   Fans called his name from an oversized yacht as he walked the
front nine. Boaters honked at him on the back nine. San Francisco
FBI agents and Monterey County sheriff's deputies walked all 18
holes with him, on the watch for overzealous fans. The caddy he
fired, Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan, was in Woods' group, carrying Jim
Furyk's clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was that shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Not his _ Jesper Parnevik's bright-orange madness. The Swedish
golfer was dressed so garishly, fans joked that he must be
considering a career change _ maybe a jockey _ or was headed for
the disco.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was noticeable out there,'' Woods said, grinning. ``You
could see him in the fog. He was our beacon so nobody could hit
into us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a more conventional black Nike shirt with red and white
stripes, Woods was dressed immaculately. He played that way as
well.
</P>
<P>
   He tapped in for his first birdie on the 331-yard fourth hole
and drained a 20-foot putt for another on the par-3 seventh. He
birdied the 10th, rolling in a 15-footer, and the 13th, 14th and
18th with more tap-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Woods didn't make a mistake until the 11th hole, when he sent
his tee shot sailing deep into the right rough. It was his first
missed fairway. He took it personally, muttering, ``Damn it,'' and
thumping his club on the ground before uttering another expletive.
</P>
<P>
   He composed himself and recovered nicely, slashing his ball out
of the thick stuff and near the green with what he called his
``shot of the day'' for another par-saver.
</P>
<P>
   Woods also rebounded on the par-3 17th. His tee shot to a back
pin went long and his chip shot coming back skipped 12 feet past.
But he found the cup with another putt.
</P>
<P>
   He had people talking excitedly when he pulled out his driver
for his second shot on the par-5 14th, 257 yards from the front
edge. He missed the green to the left. He only wanted to get close,
maybe land in a bunker, certain the power of his big club would
leave him with a good lie. He chipped close and birdied.
</P>
<P>
   Woods called this his second-best Open round, surpassed only by
a 69 he shot as an amateur after a first-day 76 in the 1996 event
at Oakland Hills near Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   In the press tent, the only issue that golf's great one had to
answer for was skipping Payne Stewart's greenside tribute the day
before. He didn't dodge it. Woods said he needed to prepare for the
Open. He had been to enough memorials. He had moved on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I handle things a little differently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weaving his way through the fog, Woods reaffirmed as much.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
