<HEADLINE>
LAKERS LOOK TO END L.A.'S TITLE DROUGHT TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON KANDEL, LISA VAN PROYEN AND RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just one win away from Los Angeles' first national
championship in 12 years, the city has gone wild about the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Instant fans are everywhere - at water coolers, schoolyards,
neighborhood bars, even at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight could be the night when the drought ends. The Lakers, up
3-1 after Wednesday night's thrilling overtime win over the Pacers,
play for the NBA title in Indianapolis at 6 p.m. Or maybe it will
be back home at Staples Center on Monday night or Wednesday night
or ... don't even think about it.
</P>
<P>
   The town is in a tizzy like it hasn't been since Ronald Reagan
was president and the Lakers and Dodgers both took home world
championships. The excitement creates a moral dilemma for those who
must work tonight like Rabbi Steven Jacobs of Temple Kol Tikvah in
Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I will be in temple,'' Jacobs said Thursday. ``My heart
is with the Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no divided loyalty at Dodger Stadium on Wednesday:
Laker-mania was in full effect.
</P>
<P>
   Rhiannon Talley attended the game between the Dodgers and the
first place Arizona Diamondbacks with her fiance. She said the
Dodgers game felt like, well, a Lakers game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everybody in the stands was glued to portable
TVs,'' said Talley. ``Everybody was screaming and there was nothing
happening on the field. During the seventh-inning stretch everybody
ran to the TVs in the smoking areas. They were yelling and
screaming over the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was madness.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was just as boisterous at the Rich Man, Pour Man's Bar
and Lounge in Panorama City.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, patrons and employees still were cheering on their
home team - a day after the Lakers and Pacers kept them on the edge
of their seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lakers, Lakers,'' a few women hollered out, before giving a
high-five and reflecting on Wednesday night's pivotal moment:
Reggie Miller's three-point shot at the buzzer that fell just
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Are they going to make the shot or not?' It was
too close for comfort,'' said Lisa Hersom, who ordinarily is not
interested in the game of basketball, but admits, ``The adrenaline
was up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was hyped up about the game. I don't even like
basketball, but it was nerve-racking to watch them go into overtime
and it was so close. It was a good game,'' Hersom said.
</P>
<P>
   Hersom isn't the only recent addition to the Lakers bandwagon.
In fact, it's hard to find any Angelenos not rooting for the Purple
and Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sociological thing,'' said Stan J. Katz, a clinical
psychologist in Beverly Hills. ``People tend to get excited when
other people get excited. It's nice to have something that all
colors and creeds can get together and be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 12,000 people will get together at Staples Center tonight
to watch the Lakers play - only the Lakers won't be there. The game
at Conseco Fieldhouse will be televised on giant TV screens at
Staples.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the virtual-live event were gobbled up in less than
10 minutes Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Police will add patrols around Staples Center tonight, but say
they expect more euphoria than mayhem. A few officers may even get
caught up in the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the Lakers,'' said Los Angeles Police Department Capt.
Sharyn Buck. ``When they win this thing, we're going to be out
there in a ticker-tape parade.''
</P>
<P>
   So will a lot of people. City officials, expecting the Lakers to
restore sportsman-like honor to Los Angeles and unafraid of the
``Curse of Celebrating Early,'' have planned a victory parade
through downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers win tonight, plans call for the parade Monday. If
the Lakers clinch the championship on Monday, the parade will be
Wednesday. And if victory doesn't come until the seventh game, the
parade will be next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever day it occurs, the parade will start at 11 a.m. at the
Department of Water and Power Building on Hope Street with a brief
ceremony. Players in double-deck buses or other vehicles will start
on First Street, go down a ramp to Figueroa Street and down that to
Staples Center at 11th Street and Figueroa, where the big
celebration will be held outside the arena in parking lots 2 and 3,
which can accommodate 90,000 people. Jumbotrons also will be set
up.
</P>
<P>
   As a Lakers fan, Mike Anello hopes to see the trophy tonight.
But as manager of Yankee Doodles in Woodland Hills, a seven-game
series wouldn't exactly hurt business at his sports bar/restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked the Lakers, even when they were stinking way
back when,'' Anello said. ``If I get a chance to watch - I'll be
really inundated - I'll stop by and check out the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Fire Department spokesman Brian Humphrey, a big
Lakers fan, said the department is hoping for a quiet night.
Usually they answer 40 calls every hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we're not permitted to listen to civilian radio
during our calls,'' he said. ``And the Fire Department dispatch
radio does not hold a candle to Chick Hearn's play by play.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
