<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN OR LOSE, BIRD'S TIME NEARS AN END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It could happen as soon as Friday night. It
definitely will conclude after a possible seventh game Wednesday in
L.A.
</P>
<P>
   As the end of Larry Bird's NBA coaching career approaches, the
retrospectives, replete with soft background music, are leaving
Hoosiers morose.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the man himself sees it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I want to keep it going (to Wednesday). I have
nothing else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pressroom laughter subsided, the thought occurred that
the only man in the house unsloppy about Bird's retirement from his
second career was Larry Joe himself.
</P>
<P>
   That would include players, reporters and the NBA. Something
about his standards, his candor and his Mohave-dry wit have again
endeared him to a hoops nation that was barely getting over his
retirement as a player.
</P>
<P>
   The forum of the NBA Finals, where his Pacers in Game 5 try to
climb out of a 1-3 ditch dug for them by the Lakers, has brought
home how unexpectedly successful was his tenure, and how
unexpectedly abrupt is his imminent departure.
</P>
<P>
   When he succeeded Larry Brown in May 1997, with no previous
experience, the sport's wise guys recoiled, figuring he was doomed
to spoil his legend by doing what most superstars do who turn to
coaching _ fail.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Pacers made three consecutive Eastern Conference
finals as well as _ for the first time in franchise history _ the
NBA championship round. Yet despite the success, he is sticking
hard to a commitment that might be referred to in Seattle as a
traditional Seahawks offense:
</P>
<P>
   Three and out.
</P>
<P>
   In his case, that means years.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bird, 43, has been vague, Pacers guard Mark Jackson was
asked to explain how someone so successful and driven could pack up
his ego and go bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't,'' Jackson said. ``I don't think anybody can. I
respect the fact that he made a decision from day one and then
stuck to it, where a lot of people probably wouldn't have.
Especially after they get a taste of what has been accomplished
this year. So I respect that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, he's a different breed.''
</P>
<P>
   A different breed? That only hints at the distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   As the first coach in Finals history who's already made
basketball's Hall of Fame (another 17 coaches eventually made it to
a Springfield enshrinement), Bird brought magnum prestige and
almost no Xs-and-Os formality to the Pacers position.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he assemble an entourage of assistants that make the
bench look like a law firm's Monday meeting on billable hours. He
has two, Dick Harter and Rick Carlisle, to whom he freely gives all
responsibility and credit for offensive and defensive strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Bird hasn't been the perfect coach _ Bird-bashers will refer to
his use of Travis Best and Sam Perkins instead of starters Jackson
and Rik Smits in the final minutes of Wednesday's epic Game 4
defeat _ but he has been the perfect antidote for these basketball
times.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it seems that star players, using their
multimillion-dollar guaranteed contracts as cudgels, are beating
their teams and the game to death, Bird has stepped in with
honesty, directness and wisdom and revived the position of field
general _ an intimate, intimidating leader of his troops.
</P>
<P>
   At least a part of the success is right place, right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in Indiana, man _ he does no wrong here,'' said Perkins,
laughing. ``He can spit, he can jaywalk, he probably can get into a
car accident and it won't be his fault. And he also coached here
because he had a pretty good nucleus of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Perkins is quick to point out that Bird won over his players
not just because of his r &UR; gfacute &LR; esum &UR; gfacute &LR; e and birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike all the other coaches I've played for, he doesn't try
to sugar-coat,'' he said. ``He'll joke with you when it's not
basketball-related, but other than that, he's straight. He comes in
with a plan that isn't much on paper, but it's real to-the-point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man who's so well respected, players do listen, even
younger players.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this series, as well as his coaching career, Bird has
been as blunt as the front end of his pickup truck when it comes to
assessing his players.
</P>
<P>
   He has said after Finals games that ``Jalen Rose didn't show up
tonight,'' that Smits ``isn't getting the job done,'' that Reggie
Miller ``wastes his energy on officials'' and of his point guards,
``We'd be a lot better if they were more consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   On many other teams, such public criticism would be grounds for
revolt. But since he's usually right, and since he says the same
things to players in private, they recognize the words are honest
and without a political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some coaches have favoritism, and when guys see that, they
hate it,'' said Perkins, who could well be speaking of his Sonics
experiences. ``Some guys who (benefit) don't even like it, because
they get teased afterwards: `He's your daddy,' stuff like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're better off treating everybody the same. Even
veterans appreciate that. No nonsense. Nobody's in anybody's
pocket, trying to schmoose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He treats everybody the same. Coaches around the league try to
do that, but not everybody does.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird is in a small class of coaches _ which most prominently
includes his Finals rival, Phil Jackson, along with Utah's Jerry
Sloan and Miami's Pat Riley _ who recognize the primacy of players
in the NBA game but also can maintain control through force of
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked the player-first demeanor that coach Bird
has taken into this game, understanding that players are what make
coaches,'' Jackson said Thursday. ``Players have to be promoted.
Coaching is an important job that goes along with it, but it's the
players that you've got to get playing for you, and together.''
</P>
<P>
   As for himself and his departure from the sidelines, Bird will
acknowledge the difference in competitive zeal between him and
today's players has taken a predictable toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get frustrated sometimes when I don't get the effort that I
want in practice and in the games,'' he said. ``But you have to
learn to deal with it, and over the course of the three years, I
think I improved immensely. I feel I've been very patient with
these guys. You have to be. This has been my best year as far as
watching younger guys develop. I've enjoyed it. It's been a hell of
an experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want it to end next Wednesday. I want these guys to have
the opportunity to play for the world championship in the seventh
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are in a strong position to deny him the opportunity.
But there's always been more talented opponents in the way of the
pasty country boy with no hops and, later, not enough coaching
smarts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the man has nothing else to do _ except the only thing
he's ever done.
</P>
<P>
   Win.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
