<HEADER>
A5514 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-NY     06-16 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHTE SOX, AIDED BY 3 THROWING ERRORS, CRUSH YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everybody has a breaking point, Chuck Knoblauch said
last month after his throwing jitters resurfaced, and the New York
Yankees' second baseman apparently reached his after his problems
erupted worse than ever on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing away three balls in the first six innings of
Thursday night's 12-3 loss to the Chicago White Sox, Knoblauch left
the game. Then he left Yankee Stadium, as well, walking out in his
street clothes while the game was still in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch said last month that he had two possible career paths.
Either he would solve his throwing problems, or he would ``take it
to the house'' _ as in quit baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Yankees Manager Joe Torre said that Knoblauch came to
him and was ``pretty low.'' Torre said he told Knoblauch that he
was taking him out and to leave the park to avoid the reporters who
would be waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, shortly after Knoblauch made his third
error of the night, the Yankees made a pitching change. While the
rest of the infielders gathered at the mound and three outfielders
met in center field, Knoblauch stood alone at second base, his
hands on his hips, his frustration apparent in his expression. The
inning ended on a ground ball to shortstop Derek Jeter, Knoblauch
circling behind first base to back up the play, as he has done so
many times in his 10-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, Knoblauch had left the Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, who turns 32 next month, has the rest of this season
and next season on his current contract, at $6 million a year.
Shortly after the Yankees traded for him in February 1998, an
agreement _ never announced _ was made to pay him $9 million
annually for the 2002 and 2003 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch has played in four All-Star Games, collected 1,584
career hits and ranked among the game's best leadoff hitters since
he broke into the majors in 1991, successes he has reminded himself
of constantly since he began having throwing trouble in 1998. But
Knoblauch has eight throwing errors in his last 21 games, and 12
errors over all this season.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch made several nice plays in games against Boston on
Tuesday and Wednesday. But his throwing problem errupted fully on
Thursday night, only one inning after he made a nice scoop and
throw on a grounder hit by Herbert Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the third inning, Ray Durham smacked a grounder
directly at Knoblauch, who fielded it easily before stepping and
throwing to first base. All season long, Knoblauch has tried to
throw the ball harder, rather than loop it tentatively. But this
throw was far to the left of the first baseman Tino Martinez, who
came off the bag to catch the ball, and he was unable to tag Durham
passing by. There was a burst of murmurs and jeers, and some booing
when Knoblauch ran off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, Paul Konerko was on third with two outs when
Carlos Lee grounded to Knoblauch. It was another easy play, but
Knoblauch again threw wide of Martinez, pulling him off the base.
The boos in the Stadium crowd were louder this time, and they
continued when Knoblauch led off the bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The error that drove him from the field occurred the next
inning. With runners at first and second, Frank Thomas hit a
routine double-play grounder at Jeter, and the shortstop shoveled
the ball to Knoblauch. With the runner closing on him _ but not
enough to really impede the throw _ Knoblauch fired far to
Martinez's right, eluding the dive of the first baseman. The ball
got away and the runner who had been at second, Ray Durham, raced
around third, to a torrent of boos.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch made a terrible throwing error against the White Sox
May 24, and after that game he suggested he would quit baseball if
he couldn't conquer the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need this,'' Knoblauch said at the time. ``I'm not out
here for the money. I'm out here to have fun. I don't need the
money. I don't need this. The money is not keeping me here. The
competitiveness is keeping me here. I mean, I know I can play. This
isn't about money at all, it's never been about the money. But
everybody has a breaking point.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was asked at the time if he was close to the breaking
point. ``Pretty close,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't need the frustration,'' said Knoblauch, a
Gold Glove winner in 1997, who made 26 errors last season and is on
a pace to make about that many again this year. ``I don't need it.
I know baseball is a small part of life, but when you're playing
it, it's a big part of life, it's what we do. And if you continue
to not do something well, you can't keep going out there and not
doing it well, because, No. 1, you'll drive yourself crazy, No. 2,
it's not any fun. It's a job, but you're supposed to have fun
playing baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
