<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER LEADS BY ONE AS FOG SHORTENS OPENING ROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH - First Hal Sutton's terrific start, then the
entire Pebble Beach Golf Links.
</P>
<P>
   Much faded away in Thursday's fog-suspended opening round of the
100th U.S. Open - but not the primary protagonists of Valderrama.
</P>
<P>
   On a day fog halted play with 25 groups on the course,
tournament favorite Tiger Woods and Spain's Miguel Angel Jimenez
wound up atop the mist-shrouded scoreboards - Woods a shot ahead
after his lowest round in six U.S. Open appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The world's No. 1-ranked player bunched six birdies into a
bogeyless round of 6-under 65 that got better as visibility got
murkier. His last birdie came on the potentially disastrous par-5
18th in fog so thick Woods' group could barely see their tee-shot
targets or the green on their second shots.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez, who lost on the third playoff hole to Woods in last
year's Wold Golf Championships event at Valderrama in Spain,
finished 66 with seven birdies - five on the front nine - and two
bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   They were among only 81 players who completed play Thursday. The
remainder of the 156-man field will resume first-round play today,
starting at 6:45 a.m. Second-round play, originally scheduled to
start at 6:30 today, will get underway about an hour and a half
later.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Jimenez got to sleep in and enjoy rounds that are
their best in this tournament and rank with their best anywhere,
given the difficult course and playing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely one of my better rounds I've played.'' said
Woods, whose previous low in a U.S. Open was 67 at Congressional in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 156 players and all good players,'' said Jimenez, who
had never shot better than 69 in two previous U.S. Opens. ``I like
to be in this position.'' Pre-fog starter and finisher Sutton would
have liked it too, had he not got stuck in Pebble Beach's thick
rough coming down the stretch, when his 6-under score dipped to
2-under 69 in his final five holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said Sutton, who held a two-stroke lead
before taking a double bogey on No.14 and bogeys on 16 and 18. ``I
played pretty well. Hit a couple of shots that I paid the price
for.'' He wound up sharing fifth with Angel Cabrera of Argentina,
both a stroke back of CBS commentator Bobby Clampett, a qualifier
who grew up in nearby Monterey. Clampett, who has played often at
Pebble Beach, used course familiarity to record four birdies in the
first 10 holes of his round of 68.
</P>
<P>
   John Huston, another early starter, held third place alone at 67
on a leaderboard that might have included several others had play
not been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Three-time Masters champion Nick Faldo, 1995 U.S. Open winner
Corey Pavin and Kirk Triplett - winner in this year's Nissan Open
at Riviera were all 4 under after 13 holes. Loren Roberts was 3
under through seven holes.
</P>
<P>
   Before the murky conditions left 75 players waiting for two and
a half hours, then sent them home, Woods trudged toward his
improbable birdie on 18th aided by a foglight of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik, playing in the same group, was wearing an
orange shirt so bright it lit up the threesome, if not the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see him in the fog, that's for sure,'' Woods said.
``He's our beacon. No one would hit into us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clampett, thrilled as he was by his round, started early and
didn't face any fog but probably wished he could have seen more
putts drop. He missed four birdie attempts within 15 feet and had a
20-foot par attempt lip out on No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But the 40-year-old commentator was hardly about to complain
after needing the right television schedule, then surviving a
first-stage qualifier playoff, then an agonizing wait as fourth
alternate just to get to Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Had CBS been broadcasting this year's U.S. Open instead of NBC,
or had his network not been broadcasting the Kemper Insurance Open
near his sectional qualifying site, Clampett never would have
participated in this memorable homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a gift from God just even being here and playing in
this championship,'' he said. ``And then to play as well as I did
today, especially the first 10 holes, it was almost like playing
golf in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Huston also dodged the fog with his early start but got wind,
especially on Nos.17 and 18. He survived those for par and offset
three bogeys with seven birdies on a day he said he got many
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I was in the rough today, I had a good lie,'' said
the man who holds the PGA Tour 72-hole scoring record of 28 under
par. ``So certainly, I was fortunate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
