<HEADER>
A5519 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON     06-16 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SURPRISE SHUFFLE, GORE NAMES DALEY TO HEAD CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ In another major shakeup at the top of his
presidential campaign, Vice President Al Gore announced Thursday
that Commerce Secretary William Daley will replace campaign
chairman Tony Coelho, who abruptly resigned, citing health
concerns.
<P>
   Daley, son of legendary Chicago Mayor Richard J. Daley and
brother of the city's current mayor, joined Gore at a campaign stop
in Cincinnati late Thursday and is expected to step down from his
cabinet post July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Daley has been a loyal soldier for President Clinton and Gore
since 1992, when he ran their Illinois campaign. He also was the
point man in the administration's push to pass the North American
Free Trade Agreement in 1993, and more recently, to secure
permanent normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to miss a beat,'' insisted Gore, even as labor
leaders who had battled Daley on the free trade accords expressed
dismay with the selection.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he offered the 51-year-old Commerce secretary the job
late Wednesday night, but had not informed Clinton until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took his Cabinet secretary before I told him,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Daley said he called Clinton to inform him of the development on
his way to the airport to catch up with Gore. There was no word
from the White House on who might replace Daley as Commerce
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The shakeup comes less than five months before election day, and
with Gore, the Democratic candidate, trailing Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee, by 5 to 10 points in most
public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's recent lackluster performance on the stump and in public
opinion match-ups fueled rumors over the past several weeks that
Coelho, a former congressman from California's Central Valley,
might be forced out.
</P>
<P>
   But Coelho, 58, who had been hospitalized since Monday for an
inflamed colon, said Thursday that concern for his health was the
only reason for his departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctors have told me that I need to slow down, eat better
and travel less for a period of time,'' Coelho said in a statement
released by the Gore campaign. ``Unfortunately, none of this advice
is consistent with the rigors of chairing a presidential
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush had speculated earlier this month that Coelho would
go, telling Chris Matthews, host of MSNBC's ``Hardball,'' ``They're
going to dump him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark my words,'' Bush said during a break in the taping of the
show that was nevertheless recorded. ``Oh, they'll dump him. ...
There's no loyalty in those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho joined the Gore team a year ago when the campaign was
viewed as unfocused and losing ground. He is credited with bringing
discipline and order, engineered an early endorsement from the
AFL-CIO and oversaw Gore's commanding defeat of Bill Bradley in the
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he also carried baggage. He resigned from Congress amid
accusations of wrongdoing in 1989 (Coelho denied any wrongdoing)
and was under investigation for his role as head of the American
exhibit at the 1998 World Exhibition in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony is like a Gen. Patton,'' said former White House chief of
staff Leon Panetta, who served with Coelho for years in the House
of Representatives. ``You want to take the hill, he'll take the
hill. ... He may make some mistakes and slap some people around in
the process, but he takes the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans used the opportunity Thursday to chide the Gore
campaign for its instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish (Coelho) well and hope his health improves,'' said
Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes. ``I wonder whether naming a new
chairman involves yet another reinvention of the Gore campaign.
Which Vice President Gore will campaign next week?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials said the vice president was stunned by
Coelho's departure and that it had nothing to do with the state of
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony has been an invaluable friend and adviser,'' Gore said
Thursday. ``I look forward to calling upon Tony's counsel and help
once again just as soon as his doctors give me the word.''
</P>
<P>
   Panetta, echoing many other political observers, said he did not
doubt Coelho resigned due to health concerns, but suggested that
the difficulties of the past several months may have contributed to
the ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho was ``obviously having to deal with a lot of incoming
fire, and I think that was part of it,'' Panetta said.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho was admitted to a suburban Washington hospital Monday
night, complaining of stomach pains. He was being treated for
diverticulitis, an inflammation of the colon, and told the
Associated Press that he will undergo tests in hopes of ruling out
cancer in about six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho also said he had suffered three epileptic seizures this
year, and doctors had told him he needed to lessen his workload or,
better yet, quit the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Daley is a highly regarded inside player who is well connected
in the Democratic Party and carries less controversy than Coelho.
He was chairman of the 1996 Democratic National Convention in his
hometown of Chicago, and was thought to be front-runner to become
Clinton's first secretary of transportation, a job that went to
then-Denver Mayor Federico Pena.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Daley goes on `Face the Nation' or `Meet the Press,' the
questions are going to be about the Gore campaign, not about him,''
Panetta said.
</P>
<P>
   Daley succeeded Ron Brown, who died in a plane crash in the
Balkans, as commerce secretary in 1997. The announcement of his
appointment was memorable for his fainting and stumbling off the
stage into a row of reporters at the Old Executive Office Building
in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore reportedly offered Daley the job of campaign chairman a
year ago, but Daley said he was not ready to leave the Commerce
Department. Gore said it was Daley who recommended Coelho for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   John Sweeney, the AFL-CIO president who muscled through an early
labor-federation endorsement for Gore, issued a surprisingly biting
statement. Daley's stewardship of NAFTA and the China trade bill
``put him squarely on the opposite side of working families,''
Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Caldwell, a spokesman for the Teamsters union, called the
appointment a ``slap in the face of labor'' that would not help
Gore win the union's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho, who made a good living as an investment banker after
leaving Congress, drew no salary from the Gore campaign and will
continue to offer his advice informally, aides said. Daley,
however, will be given a salary, Gore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
