<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5521 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUDGET-CALIFORNIA-SFC     06-16 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STATE SENATE BUDGET SPENDS BIG ON SCHOOLS  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The state Senate approved a $95 billion budget
Thursday that sharply increases public school spending and gives
taxpayers $2.7 billion in tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by the state's red-hot economy, lawmakers had a record
$12.3 billion more dollars to spend than anticipated in January
when the budget process began.
</P>
<P>
   And spend it they did, increasing the budget by more than $15
billion over last year.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the new money was spent on public schools, tax
cuts and transportation, other areas of state government also were
lavished with income.
</P>
<P>
   University of California funding rose 18.5 percent over last
year. Money for the California State University system rose by 13
percent, community colleges by more than 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More than $575 million was earmarked to make rental housing and
home ownership more affordable. Another $5.8 billion was slated for
projects paid for by park and water bonds approved by voters in
March.
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers worried that the heavy surplus spending was
shortsighted or wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``This document and work product could have been an
extraordinary long-lasting legacy. We didn't do that. That's
unfortunate,'' said Sen. Steve Peace, D-El Cajon, chairman of the
special committee that cobbled together the budget. ``I doubt we
will be judged well by history.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican opponents took an even dimmer view, portraying the
budget as an orgy of pork-barrel spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget is nothing more than a spending spree,'' said Sen.
Ray Haynes, R-Riverside. ``The swill generated by the pigs of big
government is the byproduct generated by this budget. The people of
this great state will pay a price for our irresponsible behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Gray Davis praised the spending plan, saying it
reflected the priorities he outlined in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a great believer there should be something for everyone in
the budget,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is required to approve a budget by midnight June
15, a deadline routinely missed. The Senate met the deadline last
year, but the Assembly did not.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly appeared headed that direction again Thursday with
most of the day spent in closed-door meetings and no action taken
on the budget by early evening.
</P>
<P>
   The plan proposed by the Democratic governor wanted the state's
windfall spent mainly on three things -- education, tax cuts and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The budget approved by the 40-member Senate on a bipartisan
31-to-9 vote largely does that.
</P>
<P>
   But it comes at the expense of cities and counties, who had
billions in property tax revenue taken by the state during the
recession of the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $12.3 billion in unexpected cash, $200 million is
earmarked for fiscal relief of local government.
</P>
<P>
   Schools are the biggest winner in the Senate's budget.
</P>
<P>
   About $30.6 billion is spent on public schools, including $1.8
billion that districts can spend on what they wish, including pay
increases for teachers or other staff.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative budget writers estimate per-pupil spending will rise
by 11 percent over last year to $6,716 -- an additional $691 per
pupil over last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers did part ways with Davis on several key education
spending proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Davis wanted teachers to be exempt from state income taxes, an
idea lawmakers said discriminated against other worthwhile
vocations and cut into the state revenue given to schools.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Legislature gave teachers tax credits that increase
based on experience. A teacher with four or five years experience
would get a credit of $250. A teacher with 20 or more years
experience would receive $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's budget also spends more on child care, summer
school and after-school programs than Davis'. And it includes $425
million in one-time block grants schools can spend on anything they
want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our budget reflects a desire to see districts have more
flexibility to meet their local needs,'' said Sen. Dede Alpert,
D-San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Davis got the amount of tax cuts he asked for -- $2.7 billion --
but in a far different form than he proposed.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to give individual taxpayers a $150 one-time rebate
check, double that for couples.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators rejected that as benefiting mainly the state's more
affluent residents.
</P>
<P>
   They persuaded Davis to accept a one-time sales tax rebate of
from $50 to $125, depending on income, which would go to a much
larger number of Californians and be more helpful to lower-income
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have preferred an income tax (rebate) to sales, but a
check is a check, and it will have an economic impact on its
recipient,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis rejected a legislative plan to increase the state tax
credit for dependent children. His main objection, lawmakers said,
was that it wasn't his idea.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they substituted an increase in the state's child care
credit and a 0.55 percent reduction in each of the state's tax
brackets.
</P>
<P>
   That means the state's highest bracket would fall from 9.3
percent to 9.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $224 million that tax cut will cost, taxpayers earning
$100,000 or above will see $165 million in relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very Republican tax cut,'' grumbled one liberal
Democratic legislator.
</P>
<P>
   Despite misgivings over its workability, lawmakers largely
approved Davis' transportation plan.
</P>
<P>
   That plan, which some GOP and Democratic lawmakers oppose as a
glorified pork barrel list, is a series of transit and highway
projects picked by Davis.
</P>
<P>
   He proposes spending $5.3 billion in seed money over the next
five years to begin construction on them, although that
construction cannot begin with another $10 billion in state and
local revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate's budget takes half of the sales tax paid on
gasoline sales -- roughly $500 million -- and earmarks it for other
transportation projects.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk is split between state highway projects and local
streets with some for projects of regional benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have better, it could have been worse,'' shrugged
Sen. President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco, of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``But because of our input there is more money for mental
health, more day care money, more money for clinics and more money
with less strings attached for schools,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
