<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY TARGETS HOUSTON SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Injured catcher Todd Hundley is hoping to return
to the lineup when the Dodgers open a three-game series in Houston
after missing the last 15 games with a strained right oblique
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the injury, Hundley took his first
right- handed swings in a batting cage session Thursday, and he's
aiming to hit left-handed today. He's been playing catch and
running in the outfield since the beginning of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuesday would be perfect,'' Hundley said. ``If everything goes
perfect, yeah, the Houston series. That would be good. If not
there, then St. Louis. But during the road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers can get Hundley's bat back in the lineup, it
would make it a more potent attack. Hundley was hitting .290 with
13 homers and 33 RBI in 35 games before he hurt his right side
running the bases May 30 against the Mets. Before the injury, which
came three days after Adrian Beltre was hurt, the Dodgers averaged
six runs per game. Since, they've average 4.6 runs.
</P>
<P>
   However, before Hundley's activated, manager Davey Johnson said
he wants Hundley to get his throwing arm back in shape. And the
Dodgers will make sure of that given Hundley's elbow troubles
before this season.
</P>
<P>
   City of Dodgertown: According to a proposal drafted jointly by
the Dodgers and local officials from Vero Beach, Fla., and Indian
River County, if the Dodgers sign a long-term lease to remain at
Dodgertown, the property would be split in half and include a hotel
and a ``small town'' section.
</P>
<P>
   For $1 a year for 20 years, the Dodgers would lease 64 acres for
a training center, a stadium and several practice fields. The other
62 acres would be sold and turned into hotels and possibly stores.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the Dodgers would pay for operating costs
but also keep all the revenue the spring training complex
generates.
</P>
<P>
   More melee insight: Just another tidbit the players association
will use during the appeals hearing next week:
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Camacho, whom Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter allegedly had
his hands around the neck of during the May 16 fight at Wrigley
Field, has been arrested at least nine times since 1987, a Chicago
paper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Todd Hollandsworth started in center field and
batted leadoff, marking the first time he's played since June 3 ...
Third baseman Adrian Beltre still has swelling in his right
hamstring. He said it would be three or four days, at the earliest,
before he could return from the disabled list. Right-hander Al
Reyes, acquired in a trade for Alan Mills on Tuesday, arrived and
was available ... The Diamondbacks optioned Turner Ward to the
minors to make room for Thursday's starter, Todd Stottlemyre...
Tickets are available for all three games this weekend against St.
Louis.
</P>
</TEXT>
