<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAREHOLDERS-MEETING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SHAREHOLDERS ARE COOL TO WESTERN RESOURCES' UPBEAT MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ Utility shareholder meetings are typically sedate
affairs with a few questions and a quick adjournment. Then there
was Western Resources Inc.'s annual meeting Thursday at the Topeka
Performing Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Topeka company has gone through a tumultuous year. Its bid
to buy Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. failed in January, and
Western's stock continued to languish. So when the company gave an
upbeat presentation Thursday about how things had begun to turn
around, many shareholders were clearly having none of it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the skeptics was John Oubre of Sulphur, La., who said he
had come to find out why his investment in the company was doing so
poorly. Somehow, he said, he found it hard to accept the company
line that nobody was doing anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company is stinking,'' he said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Before the meeting, shareholders got copies of an open letter
signed ``concerned shareholders'' and a list of suggested
questions, including why David Wittig, Western's chief executive,
should continue to be employed by the company, given its
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The tone continued inside when Wittig, in his initial remarks,
said: ``This is a very different company than it was a year ago.''
The audience laughed. A year ago, Western's stock was 27 1//2. On
Thursday, it closed at 16.
</P>
<P>
   Wittig and other company executives did follow up with some
encouraging figures.
</P>
<P>
   Wittig said the company is on track to have record earnings for
the first six months of the year. Earnings for April and May were
50 cents a share, compared with 27 cents a share for the full
second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Wittig also said the company hopes by fall to identify a company
that will be interested in merging with or buying Western's
electric operations, which should boost the company's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Additional upbeat numbers came from Annette Beck, president of
Protection One Inc., a monitored security firm that is 85 percent
owned by Western.
</P>
<P>
   Protection One has struggled since Western bought much of the
company in 1997. But Beck said that the cost of gaining new
customers had been slashed in half, to $600 to $700 a person, and
that the number of customers being lost was also down.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the question-and-answer period. Wittig said that
there had been a board meeting just before the annual meeting and
that he had the full support of the board.
</P>
<P>
   One shareholder wondered whether the board was simply a rubber
stamp. He asked whether John Dicus, one of the directors, could
speak to shareholders about the board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But Wittig said he was chairman of the board and could speak for
it. ``There is no rubber stamp,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another shareholder said a recent cut in the dividend, the
continued languishing of the company stock's price and the
downgrading of the company's debt to junk status raised questions
about the company's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need new leadership,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting adjourned at 4 p.m. _ 2 1//2 hours after it had
begun _ with at least one person still wanting to ask a question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
