r a BC-WIRETAP-DRUGDEALS-LAD     06-16 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRETAP-DRUGDEALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE WIRETAP VIOLATIONS MAY RESULT IN RETRIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON AND BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bolstering a year-old federal ruling that police
backed by prosecutors conducted illegal searches and seizures, a
judge ruled Thursday that two convicted drug dealers may be due
retrials because they were not told they were the subjects of
wiretaps.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in that ruling and the previous ruling - involving
seizure of $265,000 from a man who was never charged - is whether
Los Angeles police and the District Attorney's Office used wiretaps
illegally to gain search warrants and convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings raise many of the same questions about civil rights
violations and how they are handled by the criminal justice system
in Los Angeles that have surfaced in the Rampart Division scandal
where anti-gang officers planted evidence, illegally searched
suspects and testified falsely in court.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's ruling by U.S. District Judge A. Howard Matz is
related to the case before Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Larry
Paul Fidler - a sweeping lawsuit brought by the Public Defender's
Office over wiretaps of thousands of people who were never told
that their cell phone calls were taped, as the law requires.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Fidler said prosecutors and police did not follow
his order in some cases to disclose wiretaps to people so they
could defend themselves properly. Fidler is expected to issue a
final ruling next week, but Thursday he said he wants convicted
drug dealers Ramon and Martha Perez to appear before him on a
motion seeking reversal of their 1997 cocaine conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In his order March 8, 1999, Matz condemned the nondisclosure of
the wiretap in the search warrant application used to seize money
from Efrain Rodriguez Alvarado's account on Oct. 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Matz ruled LAPD officers obtained a search warrant to seize the
$265,000 by falsely claiming the officer eavesdropping on the cell
phone conversations was a confidential informant. The judge ordered
the money returned 2 years after it was seized, saying the police
lied to conceal the wiretap.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, U.S. Attorney in Los Angeles Alejandro
Mayorkas said a confidential informant cannot be used in a search
warrant if the information was instead obtained by wiretap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be done,'' Mayorkas said. ``It's an inaccurate
statement in an affidavit.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Public Defender Michael Fischman said the Matz ruling
shows how police and prosecutors work together to cover up improper
use of wiretaps. ``It's an example of how they lie to the judges.''
</P>
<P>
   Matz said that a federal prosecutor apparently initially didn't
know the search warrant was falsified when a judge granted it, but
he sought to defend the ruse anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, however, even after learning that fact, in
opposing these motions the government insisted that this Court
should pay no attention to the falsehood,'' Matz concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Matz said he was shocked a prosecutor would ``rely upon such
statements from a detective who herself had executed a false
affidavit and then would advocate to this Court a position that was
dependent upon a finding that a state court judge had been
complicit in a violation of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Falsification of probable cause to win convictions is central to
the Rampart police corruption scandal exposed by
dirty-cop-turned-informant Rafael Perez. It was illegal searches
and false testimony by corrupt officers - not planted evidence -
that tainted most of the 78 vacated felony convictions, a recent
Los Angeles Daily News investigation uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   John Yzurdiaga, former president of the Criminal Courts Bar
Association and defendant in another wiretap-related case, said
Matz's opinion revealed what usually is a hidden secret in the
justice community: that probable cause is routinely fudged by
police and prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not new to people in criminal defense, but to a citizen
it's shocking that a police officer who commits perjury is subject
to zero consequences,'' he said. ``This is a perfect example of how
a Rampart happens. Officers begin to believe they're untouchable.''
</P>
<P>
   Several local law enforcement and prosecutorial officials
insisted Matz was wrong, and that the deceit was an acceptable,
routine method to mask probable cause on search warrants.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy LAPD Chief David Gascon said the department investigated
shortly after the ruling and concluded none of the officers did
anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aware of what the judge said, and we think the judge is
mistaken,'' Gascon said.
</P>
<P>
   An LAPD supervisor in the asset forfeiture division, Detective
Hugh Wilton, said the police were following district attorney
guidelines in disguising the source of information on the search
warrant and that it was done with Superior Court Judge William
Pounders' approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do the confidential reliable informant as a term for the
wire with the permission of the District Attorney's Office so that
we wouldn't disclose we used a wire,'' Wilton said. ``It's a common
practice. It went all the way up the line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Pounders issued the warrant, he was well aware that
`confidential, reliable informant' meant a wire; Hermosillo told
him; we interviewed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pounders could not be reached immediately for comment.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Gil Garcetti's spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons
denied there is a policy to disguise wiretaps in search warrants by
claiming information came from confidential informants.
</P>
<P>
   She said that since the ruling, prosecutors have worked to
educate LAPD officers that such deceit is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have notified Judge Fidler that this is not our policy, and
that we have gone to great lengths to make sure this doesn't happen
again on any search,'' Gibbons said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Fidler said the District Attorney's Office made
``mistakes'' but did not act maliciously by failing to notify
defendants that key information in their case was gathered through
wiretaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there was no deliberate attempt to do it, they
clearly were negligent. There was negligence involved in this
because of all the cases that got overlooked,'' said Fidler, the
criminal courts supervising and wiretap judge.
</P>
<P>
   The Huntington Park couple were arrested carrying a suitcase
containing 24 kilos of cocaine as a result of information derived
from a wiretap, said Deputy Public Defender Michael Fischman. Both
are serving time in state prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only evidence against them was obtained from an unlawful
wiretap,'' Fischman said. ``This is the first case where there is
an order bringing people from state prison for this purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Schirn, head deputy in charge of the District Attorney's
Major Narcotics and Forfeiture Division, said after the hearing
that more than 100 people have been notified their cases were
derived from wiretaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given the discovery notices to all the defendants we
think have had their cases derived from wiretaps,'' Schirn said.
``Fidler is concerned there may be some more cases out there we
haven't identified.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
