<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5532 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-REUNION-AZR &LR;      06-16 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUNION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANDMA CRIES FOR TOT, JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARK SHAFFER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(UNDATED) - OAXACA, Mexico _ Paula Galindo Flores couldn't stop
kissing her granddaughter and caressing her face.
</P>
<P>
   The baby girl was returned to her Thursday, June 15, more than a
month after she was found in the Arizona desert in her dead
mother's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen-month-old Elizama and her mother were part of a group
of 10 Mexicans who followed a smuggler of illegal immigrants into
the United States, only to be abandoned in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Gonzalez, 19, had walked about 14 miles when she gave
her baby the last ounce of water she had, then collapsed beneath a
paloverde tree.
</P>
<P>
   The baby was turned over to Mexican authorities, who decided
that Elizama should temporarily go to her grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   `Mi pequena hija (My little girl),` Galindo repeated softly as
the baby lay in a crib, kicking at a pink plastic bunny and then
drifting off to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But Galindo, 43, had more on her mind than reunions.
</P>
<P>
   She called on U.S. and Mexican officials to identify and arrest
the smuggler who abandoned her daughter and the others on a hot,
late May day near the border on the Tohono O'odham reservation.
</P>
<P>
   `I want this miserable `coyote` who sent my daughter to her
death brought to justice,` said Galindo, surrounded by a battery of
microphones and video cameras from the national Mexican press.
</P>
<P>
   Galindo also blasted her son-in-law, Hermilo Hernandez Velasco,
who was working in Portland, Ore., at the time of the desert
crossing. She said he ignored demands from the smuggler to come up
with more money to guide the group across 20 miles of desert at
temperatures well above 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   `My son sent a lot of money to this coyote, but my daughter's
own husband did not respond when he was asked for some more money,`
Galindo said.
</P>
<P>
   Hermilo Hernandez, 22, who returned to his home village of San
Pedro Chayuco, Oaxaca, a week ago, denied in an interview earlier
this week that he had any dealings with smugglers. He said he had
never asked his wife to come live with him in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will seek custody of the child, but so far he hasn't
been able to afford the cost of the documents required by the
Mexican government for custody.
</P>
<P>
   `This is my child,` he said. `I named her Elizama, which is a
name from the Bible that means `God listens.` I believe that God is
listening now to my prayers for my child.`
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said a decision concerning custody will be
made Monday, June 19, but that Galindo had been the only person to
submit paperwork to take in the child.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who had been working in a restaurant in the Portland
area, apparently without the proper paperwork, said he refused to
meet with U.S. officials, Mexican diplomats and social-service
workers in northern Mexico about Elizama because he feared he would
be deported.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he and his family scraped together enough money for
him to get home. He made his way to the Mexican border at Tijuana
and then rode the bus nearly 2,000 miles to his impoverished
mountain village.
</P>
<P>
   He did not, however, appear in Oaxaca, where Elizama was brought
Thursday, June 15. That left the spotlight on Galindo, who waited
stoically for the baby on a wooden bench outside a government-run
nursery, where state officials stockpiled a large supply of
clothes, diapers and baby formula for the big day.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, a van pulled up, and a government worker handed
Galindo the baby. Galindo broke into tears, thanking the officials
and walking to a nearby fence to talk to reporters. She asked the
reporters to thank the U.S. Border Patrol for saving her
granddaughter's life.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Luciano Paz, a pediatric surgeon in Oaxaca who examined
Elizama, said the child had been given antibiotics for a cold
before leaving Mexico City, which delayed the flight 30 minutes,
but was generally in good health. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
