<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DNC-MONEY-LADN     06-16 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-MONEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ASKING LOS ANGELES FOR $4 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Faced with what is now projected to be a $10
million shortfall, planners of this summer's Democratic National
Convention are breaking from their pledge to fund the event
privately and asking the city for $4 million in cash, the Los
Angeles Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   However, knowing that the request could be a political hot
potato, city officials have been reluctant to come forward with the
money or even to discuss the request publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, who has devoted several hours a day for
the past several months to fund raising for the convention,
supports the request, according to an aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor does support this,'' spokesman Manuel Valencia said
Thursday. ``The fund raising is continuing, and to the extent the
city can assist financially, it would be appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   But public opposition is already mounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a city where they can't even afford to fix the
sidewalks, and they're talking about a contribution for a political
party,'' said Kris Vosburgh of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayer's
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think even Los Angeles Democrats, if asked, would rather see
the money spent on the sidewalks. It's not so much a question of
the cost, but of what is not being done in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   City Council President John Ferraro confirmed through an aide
that he has been approached by the convention committee chairman,
Terry McAuliffe, about the need for millions of dollars in city
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Ferraro is looking at it, and to his way of thinking the
potential benefit to the city from a successful convention and the
additional money it would bring to local businesses could make it
worthwhile,'' spokeswoman Gayle Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thinking is the request would be a mere fraction of that
potential benefit, plus avoid the embarrassment of a failed
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   She said no specific proposal to the City Council had been put
together, however, as of late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe, who was brought in this month to chair the committee
after former Colorado Gov. Roy Romer was selected to be Los Angeles
schools superintendent, spent most of Thursday talking with city
officials about his plans and the convention's needs.
</P>
<P>
   When organizers first proposed hosting the convention, they said
it would be financed with private donations while the city would
provide in-kind services, such as security and traffic control,
expected to cost roughly $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money needed for the convention and the pace at
which it has been raised have long been a concern of local and
federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to appear at a fund-raiser next
week to raise a portion of the money that is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The state also has budgeted $4 million to cover security costs
of the California Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Broad, one of the co-chairmen of the host committee, said he
was unaware of any request to the city but believes one would be
appropriate because of new requirements from convention planners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have raised 85 to 90 percent of what we pledged, and the
mayor and I and others will make sure we get to what we promised,''
Broad said. ``I do know we want to raise more money to do some
additional things the DNC has put on the agenda, and we will do our
best to accommodate them.''
</P>
<P>
   The host committee pledged to raise a total of $35.5 million and
has raised $32 million, said Noelia Rodriguez, chief executive
officer of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to show the world
what Los Angeles is all about,'' Rodriguez said. ``We would welcome
an enhanced partnership with the city of Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying she would need time to consider the matter, Councilwoman
Laura Chick noted the other contributions the city would be making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it isn't from the general fund, but we're making a
significant payment in services,'' said Chick, who is running for
city controller in next spring's election. ``And, when this first
came to council, we were told it wouldn't involve taking any money
from the general fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do want the convention to be a success and it's just very
regrettable that a commitment was made by the mayor and others that
the necessary dollars would be raised, and now we are looking at
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Nate Holden, who has opposed using city funds for
private enterprise in the past, said he believes the spending would
be justified in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that the Republicans are getting something like $14
million from the city of Philadelphia and the state of
Pennsylvania, I think this is appropriate,'' Holden said. ``We will
be getting a big boost here and will more than make up the money
with all that will be spent here.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden said he believes the committee also should ask Los
Angeles County government to help with some of the costs since it
also will benefit from the tax dollars generated during the
presidential nominating convention, expected to draw tens of
thousands of people to Los Angeles from Aug. 14-17.
</P>
<P>
   But Councilman Joel Wachs said he opposes such a use of public
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way. I think it's outrageous,'' said Wachs, a candidate for
mayor in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that the amount requested for the DNC is roughly
equivalent to the amount the city plans to spend from the general
fund next year to fix only a few dozen miles of the 4,600 miles of
broken and crumbling sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they want is the equivalent of every sidewalk we're going
to repair in this city when we have a 4,600-mile backlog. There's
never enough money for basic services. People who have power get
money, and the average person doesn't get money. You ask for trees
to be trimmed or sidewalks to be fixed, and there's no money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already providing for the things we should be providing
- police and security and traffic. We haven't even had an
accounting for the services we're going to be providing.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
