<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5535 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-COELHO-2NDLD-WRI     06-16 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-COELHO-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-460(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE NAMES BILL DALEY CAMPAIGN CHAIRMAN AFTER AILING COELHO
RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS grafs 8-11 with background;   Subs last graf before optional
trim with Gore doubling tax cut proposal; EDITS 2nd graf after
optional trim to conform)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT9 and 10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE and KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In yet another reshuffling of his presidential
campaign, Vice President Al Gore announced Thursday that William
Daley, the U.S. secretary of commerce and a shrewd operative in
Democratic politics, would replace the campaign chairman, Tony
Coelho.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho, who was hospitalized on Monday night with an inflamed
colon, said he decided to step down on the advice of his doctors,
who urged him to restrict his travel and slow his pace. But many
Democrats said the move was inevitable, given the way Gore's
campaign has struggled in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Daley flew to Lockland, Ohio, a Cincinnati suburb, from
Washington to join Gore at a prescheduled campaign event Thursday
afternoon as Gore advisers sought to project a sense of forward
energy and optimism despite the latest upheaval to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He is to visit the Gore headquarters in Nashville next week and
relocate there to become what Gore called a ``full-time, hands-on''
manager. He will leave his Cabinet post on July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Coming less than five months before Election Day, the change
seems unlikely to bring any immediate strategic or visible changes
to the campaign. Even so, Daley is taking over at a time when
crucial decisions will have to be made about a running-mate, the
national convention and where to pump the campaign's resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to miss a beat,'' Gore told reporters at a
food warehouse as he announced Daley's appointment, the secretary
at his side.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Daley said of the campaign: ``I don't see any
problems whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign has been largely on the defensive since the
primary season ended. Although national polls show the race is
relatively close, his opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, has
pulled ahead in many surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Most troubling to Democrats, however, is that in many states
that could help decide the outcome in November, surveys show that
Bush is ahead. There is also a sense among strategists in both
parties that Bush has been far more successful in making the
transition to the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When Coelho came to the campaign a year ago, he was former House
majority whip, known for his aggressive fund-raising prowess. He
had served in Congress from 1978 to 1989, representing part of
California's Central Valley. He resigned 11 years ago after
questions were raised about whether he had profited from a junk
bond in what looked like a sweetheart deal.
</P>
<P>
   Daley has never run a national campaign. But he is known as a
skilled manager who is highly regarded in Democratic circles, as
well as in the business community. In 1992, he helped the Clinton
campaign navigate the politics of the Midwest, the crucial
battleground for the coming general election. He is a son of the
late Chicago Mayor Richard J. Daley, who dominated Chicago politics
for two decades, and the brother of current Mayor Richard M. Daley.
</P>
<P>
   While the overhaul was prompted by Coelho's health, several Gore
campaign officials said that in recent weeks the vice president had
recognized that he needed to make changes in his campaign, which
seemed to drift after Gore clinched the Democratic nomination
nearly three months ago. Two people close to the campaign also said
that Gore's wife, Tipper, had expressed concerns about Coelho's
health for the past month or more, wondering whether he was up to
the job.
</P>
<P>
   And while Democrats hoped that the shift would energize the
campaign, it created another unwelcome distraction for Gore and
largely overshadowed his effort to promote the prosperity of the
Clinton years and offer new proposals that take advantage of the
growing budget surplus. Thursday, in fact, Gore doubled the size of
his proposed tax cut, to $500 billion over the next decade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Campaigns, generally, are not won or lost by campaign managers.
But Coelho's departure is significant because it reflects how, even
after years of preparation, Gore still has had trouble assembling a
stable inner circle to run his organization.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Bush has maintained the same tight circle since
announcing his candidacy, and Bush's aides seemed to take delight
in the Gore campaign's woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder whether naming a new chairman involves yet another
reinvention of the Gore campaign,'' said Karen P. Hughes, the Bush
communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's move also underscores worries among Democrats that
Gore needs to move quickly to energize his campaign as it prepares
for the Democratic National Convention, a time when the vast
majority of voters traditionally begin to pay close attention to
the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This transition better be seamless, and it better be fast
because there is no time to lose,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli,
D-N.J. ``George Bush is well-funded and well organized and clearly
has developed a sense of momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem, of course, may not be Coelho himself, but
the overall health of the Gore campaign. ``If anyone understands
that you live or die by the sword it is Coelho,'' said Rep. Luis
Gutierrez, a Democrat from Chicago. ``He's a consummate politician.
I'm sure he left for two reasons: He's genuinely sick and he
understands there are genuine problems with the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to Coelho and Gore said the two never worked well
together, and that the vice president was increasingly bypassing
him and turning to other advisers like Carter Eskew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony and Al Gore never really liked each other,'' said a top
Democratic official who knows Coelho well. ``There's little mutual
respect and no affection. They're very different people.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gore named Coelho his campaign chairman in May 1999, the
campaign was beset by overspending, and many Democrats credit him
for cutting costs and successfully steering through a treacherous
series of primary contests.
</P>
<P>
   But other one-time allies said that his controlling personality
had led him to reach into virtually every aspect of the campaign
and that an abrasive manner had alienated many of those with whom
he worked, including Donna Brazile, the campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they said, federal investigations into his past
financial activities created even more problems. For example, one
Gore ally said, Coelho could not be an effective spokesman for the
vice president because he declined to appear on television, largely
out of concern that he might be questioned about the federal
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   While most of his problems were internal within the campaign,
Coelho also took the blame for one of Gore's biggest political
fiascos, his call for Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban
castaway, to be given permanent residence in the United States, a
position that put him at odds with President Clinton and others in
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore said today that he had expected Coelho to last
through November, if not for his health problems. And he said he
was not concerned ``in the least'' that the investigations of
Coelho would have undermined the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Coelho has had less of a role in running the
daily operation, as Tad Devine, one of Gore's top consultants, had
been shifted to a more central role at the campaign headquarters in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The news was delivered at campaign headquarters this morning,
and was not unwelcome. ``If you're in the doldrums, you need a
cathartic event to turn things around,'' said one adviser. ``Our
biggest challenge at this point is to stay disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Coelho acknowledged there had been
mistakes, particularly that the campaign allowed Gore to become
enmeshed in the Gonzalez case. But Coelho also said he brought
discipline and order to the campaign _ and stepped in so the vice
president did not have to make all the decisions. Asked if Gore was
a micro-manager in the mold of President Jimmy Carter before Coelho
took over, he said, ``I think he probably was. People said he did.
But since I've been on board, he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many inside the campaign and out perceived the illness as a
convenient cover for Gore to ease Coelho to the sidelines after a
somewhat tumultuous year-long reign.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat who works closely with the campaign said that while
Coelho's health concerns were ``legitimate,'' they also made for
``a very convenient'' excuse for Coelho to depart.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Coelho, who turned 58 Thursday, said the move came
strictly for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The call I made to the vice president last night informing him
of my doctor's advice is one of the most difficult calls I have
ever had to make,'' he said in a statement released by Gore
headquarters in Nashville. ``My doctors have told me that I need to
slow down, eat better and travel less for a period of time.
Unfortunately, none of this advice is consistent with the rigors of
chairing a presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Two people close to Coelho, who has epilepsy, said he had
suffered several seizures recently.
</P>
<P>
   Daley had been under consideration as a running mate for Gore.
But Gore said in an interview Thursday night that he removed Daley
from consideration because ``it is not possible to be a full-time
hands-on campaign manager all the way through the election and also
be a vice presidential running mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has such confidence in Daley that he has offered him the
post in the first place before he turned to Coelho. Daley, who has
been commerce secretary since January 1997, resisted the
entreaties, saying he had not been in office long enough.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Thursday that Daley sprang to mind Wednesday night
immediately after he spoke with Coelho. Coelho had called Gore, who
was attending a fund-raising dinner in New York, about 11 p.m.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that after talking with Coelho, he talked with Frank
Hunger, his brother-in-law, who was with him in New York, and
called Mrs. Gore, who was campaigning in Florida. He said he then
called Daley in Washington after midnight, waking him up. Gore and
Daley said that neither of them had notified President Clinton
until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took his commerce secretary away before I told him,'' Gore
said, adding that he called the president Thursday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
