<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOG COULD START CHAIN REACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH - The fog that canceled first-round play in the
100th U.S. Open at Pebble Beach Golf Links may have started a
domino effect that could affect playing times through Saturday's
third round.
</P>
<P>
   That was the scenario described Thursday night by Tom Meeks,
Director of Rules and Competition for the U.S. Golf Association.
</P>
<P>
   Because 75 players could not complete first-round play, they
will return to finish their rounds today at 6:45 a.m., forcing
second-round play to be moved back from a 6:30 start to 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks anticipates that will also mean second-round play cannot
be completed today, and that some players might have to come back
Saturday to finish rounds which will determine which players make
the cut for the final two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The top 60 and ties and all players within 10 shots of the lead
qualify to play in the final two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to come to be known as the Foggy Open,
unfortunately,'' said Meeks, who said play was originally halted
when Jeff Maggert told an official at about 3:45 p.m. that he was
not going to play his tee shot at the 10th hole because he couldn't
see the landing area.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Ridley, the Chairman of the Championship Committee, and
Meeks went to the 10th and agreed with Maggert, even while Ernie
Els, playing one group ahead, was jokingly insisting that he had
played Maggert's shot and could see fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was having a little fun with us,'' Meeks said, ``but we
knew we were close (to having to stop play for lack of visibility.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think our call to stop it when we did was right.
Because although we had five or six holes that were very visible
and very playable, those around 8, 9 and 10 know that it was not
fair to make those players play those shots down there.'' Play was
halted for nearly two and a half hours before being discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we stop play, we have to stop it for everybody,'' Meeks
said.
</P>
<P>
   The big question for Meeks was what will the weather be like for
the second round?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to tell you, I don't know,'' he said. ``I've heard
rumors even to the fact that the fog (for the second round) is
supposed to be worse than it was today.''
</P>
<P>
   Local watch: Area qualifiers David Berganio Jr. of Sylmar and
Jon Levitt, the former Cal State Northridge golfer from Alhambra,
both struggled on the back nine in their opening rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Berganio, one-time Alemany High standout and 1997 PGA Tour
regular appearing in his fifth U.S. Open, finished 6-over-par at 77
after playing the front nine in even-par 35.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt, playing in his first U.S. Open after missing on four
previous qualifying attempts, made the turn at 3-over-par 38 before
finishing bogey-triple bogey for a 79.
</P>
<P>
   Out with a bang: John Daly, the long-hitting but erratic crowd
pleaser who has won two major titles, withdrew from the U.S. Open
after a first-round 83 that included a 9-over-par 14 on his final
hole.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in heavy fog, which later resulted in play being
suspended and then postponed until today, Daly hit his first shot
OB to the right of the par-5, 543-yard 18th.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't discover the penalty until walking up the uphill hole,
then returned to the tee and hooked his next two shots into
adjacent Stillwater Cove. His next shot his seventh stroke with
penalties wound up in the fairway, from where Daly laid up short of
the green, only to knock his following approach into a bunker and
against a seawall.
</P>
<P>
   That forced the right-handed Daly to hit a shot left-handed, and
he failed to get the ball out of the bunker. He reached the green
on his next shot, two-putted for the 14 to complete a 12-over-par
round that had been 3-over starting the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is always unfortunate when a contestant withdraws prior to
completion of his regulation rounds,'' said Marty Parkes, Senior
Director of Communications for the USGA. ``We were very sorry that
John's struggles at the end of his round today caused him to
withdraw.''
</P>
</TEXT>
