<SLUG> BC-MURDER-CHARGES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES AGAINST SERIAL KILLER SUSPECT ARE PRESENTED IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA and TONY RIZZO  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ John Edward Robinson Sr. on Thursday made the
first of what is likely to be many appearances in Johnson County
District Court.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old Olathe resident is charged in Johnson County
with two counts of capital murder, aggravated kidnapping, two
counts of aggravated sexual battery and felony theft.
</P>
<P>
   A weeklong preliminary hearing on the charges is to begin Oct.
2.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Cass County, Mo., Robinson is charged with three
counts each of first-degree murder and armed criminal action.
Prosecutors there said the Johnson County case would be prosecuted
first.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also have linked Robinson to four women and two
girls who have disappeared since 1984. On Thursday, they asked for
help from people with information about Sheila Dale Faith, who
would be 51, and her daughter Debbie Lynn Faith, who would be 21.
They disappeared between 1994 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   - The owner of an Olathe self-storage facility said Thursday
that police searched a locker there on June 2, the day Robinson was
arrested at his Olathe mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson had rented a locker at the facility since 1998, the
owner said. Robinson paid the rent using an account from his
company, Specialty Publications of America, the owner said.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty Publications, incorporated in Missouri, still exists
but has not filed an annual report that was due April 15, according
to the Missouri secretary of state's office.
</P>
<P>
   The storage facility owner said police did not say what they
found in Robinson's unit.
</P>
<P>
   A task-force detective declined Thursday to discuss whether
investigators had searched the Olathe locker.
</P>
<P>
   - Another address linked to Robinson is a duplex in Overland
Park, Kan., that was rented by a woman who is listed as a witness
on court documents in Robinson's case.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and the woman co-signed the lease for the duplex in
September 1999, according to a lawsuit filed against them in April
for not paying rent. The woman is not his wife, to whom he has been
married since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was dismissed in May, but no reason is given in the
documents.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, to whom detectives have spoken, no longer lives in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Task-force spokesmen also declined to comment on the duplex.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's court appearance, Robinson was represented by
three attorneys from the Kansas Death Penalty Defense Unit. They
took over his defense after murder charges were filed.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was not required to enter a plea at the hearing and
spoke only once, answering yes to a question from District Judge
Pro-tem Earle Jones.
</P>
<P>
   At the preliminary hearing in October, prosecutors will present
evidence to a judge who will decide whether there is probable cause
to proceed to trial. He would then be arraigned, and prosecutors
would have five days to file a motion to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County District Attorney Paul Morrison said Thursday it
would be premature to discuss whether such a request would be
filed. He also said it was ``way too early'' to talk about the
possibility of plea negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just looking at it as a capital case with the potential
of the death penalty,'' he said after Thursday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's attorneys, Ron Evans, Christian Zoller and Mark
Manna, received a copy of the charges against him and waived their
reading in court. They left the courthouse without commenting to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said the process of turning over to the defense
thousands of pages of investigative reports would begin next week.
</P>
<P>
   In Johnson County, Robinson is charged with killing Suzette
Trouten, 28, and Izabela Lewicka, 21. Their bodies were found June
3 on land owned by Robinson in Linn County, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   He is charged in Cass County with killing Beverly J. Bonner,
whose body was found June 5 in a Raymore, Mo., storage locker. He
also is charged with killing two other women found at the same time
who haven't been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, police said they had connected Robinson to three
other women _ Paula Godfrey, Catherine Clampitt and Lisa Stasi _
and Stasi's baby girl, Tiffany, who disappeared in the 1980s after
being in contact with Robinson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
