<SLUG> BC-CAR-HADDOCK-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAR-CRASH COSTLY TO KANKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ MK Kanke's lead in the NASCAR Featherlite
Southwest Series was short-lived - one week to be exact. The
Kennedy High graduate entered Saturday's Snap-On 125 at Rocky
Mountains Raceway in West Valley, Utah, with a one-point lead over
Matt Crafton.
</P>
<P>
   Now he trails Crafton by nine after a sixth-place finish in
Utah. An incident on the last lap of the race almost cost Kanke his
top-10 finish and could have added more damage to his championship
run.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Pratt, who was driving in fourth and one place ahead of
Kanke, got sideways coming out of turn two on the 3/8-mile oval. As
Kanke and Pratt came into turn three, Crafton tried to pass low,
making it three-wide on the final turn for the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Kanke backed off and settled for sixth. Crafton ended up fourth
with Pratt in between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have done the same thing as Matt,'' said Kanke, who
drives the Buyer's Choice Auto Warranty/Air Gas Pontiac. ``But if I
stayed in there, I would have put all three of us into the wall.
That's not the way I drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Nelson of Hemet earned the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Woodside of Saugus finished ninth, Bob Lyon of Agua Dulce
was 14th, Greg Pursley of Newhall was 15th and Frank Maronski Jr.
of Quartz Hill was 20th in a 26-car field.
</P>
<P>
   The next race on the Southwest Series is the Snap-On Tools/AAA
200 at Sears Point Raceway in Sonoma on June 24. The Southwest
Series will accompany the NASCAR Winston Cup circuit for a weekend
of racing in Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   When Kanke beat Daddy E: Sears Point Raceway is a 1.949-mile
road course, one of two road courses on the Southwest Series
schedule. As an accompanying race to the Winston Cup event, it's a
good bet that some of the Cup drivers will compete in the Southwest
Series event. Which is fine with Kanke, who has fond memories of
racing against Darrell Waltrip, Neil Bonnett and Dale Earnhardt in
1980 at Ascot Park in Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip, Bonnett and Earnhardt were at Ascot for a Winston Cup
race and also ran in a NASCAR Late Model event at the old track.
Bonnett even had to borrow one of Kanke's back-up cars to compete
in the Late Model race. Not that it really mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Kanke had the fastest car of the night, winning the Late Model
race and holding off Earnhardt, who finished second. Earnhardt went
on to win his first NASCAR Winston Cup points title later that
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Earnhardt were battling all night long,'' Kanke said.
``It was a lot of fun, probably the highlight of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday in front of rookies: Ron Hornaday Jr. of Palmdale
reclaimed the rookie lead in the NASCAR Busch Grand National
Division with a fourth-place finish at the Textilease/Medique 300
at South Boston Speedway on Saturday. Hornaday had fallen to second
for the first time this season in the rookie standings after the
Dover Downs International Speedway race on June 3.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday and his team liked the results in the NAPA Auto Parts
Chevrolet at South Boston so much that they are taking the same car
to Myrtle Beach this weekend. However, the car needs a little body
work after Hornaday narrowly escaped two disasters at South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This car is the best short-track car we have,'' Hornaday said.
``The damage to the nose was just cosmetic and isn't that hard to
repair. This car just had the right feel. I could feel the car for
the first time all year and that made adjustments a lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really looking forward to Myrtle Beach. We tested very
well there and I expect to have a shot at the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday, who is also fourth in championship points and
searching for his first victory on the Busch series, leads Kevin
Harvick of Bakersfield by five points in the rookie standings.
</P>
<P>
   The Myrtle Beach 250 at Myrtle Beach Speedway is on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth time's a habit: It's becoming automatic for Rip Michels
of Mission Hills in the NASCAR Grand American Modified division at
Irwindale Speedway. Michels won for the fourth straight time on
Saturday night, finishing ahead of Travis Thirkettle of Sylmar for
the second week in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In other action at Irwindale Speedway, David Gilliland won the
Food 4 Less NASCAR Super Late Model main event; Gary Scheuerell of
Temecula won the Legends Cars main event and Bill Helgeson of
Riverside won the Ultra Wheels Spec Trucks main event.
</P>
<P>
   Local leaders on USAC Midget circuits: Jay Drake of Val Verde
closed the gap Saturday on Kasey Kahne in the USAC MCI Worldcom
National Midget Car series standings, while Bobby Boone lost some
ground in his drive toward the USAC Western Midget Car series
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Both USAC classes were at Heartland Park Topeka in Kansas for
the races. Drake won the National Midget Car race and closed to
within a point of Kahne, the series leader, who finished second.
</P>
<P>
   Boone, who has a 36-point lead in the Western Midget Car
standings, had mechanical problems and failed to qualify for the
Topeka race.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop for the National and Western Midgets is at Pikes Peak
International Raceway this weekend. In addition to the Midget
races, the Indy Racing Northern Lights Series Radisson Indy 200
will be at Pikes Peak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
