<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, June 16.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-MINES (Kandahar, Afghanistan) _ Afghanistan, one of the
world's most enduring battlegrounds, is also among its most
booby-trapped landscapes. It has an estimated 5 million to 7
million of the deadly devices concealed in the rocky soil _ about
one for every three of the nation's people. A mine-clearing
operation has in 10 years managed to reduce the number of maiming
explosions by half. Each day now, only 10 to 12 people make a
misstep that blows them apart. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photos
[NYT5,6) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA-ASSESS (Washington) _ News analysis on how the
summit meeting has changed geostrategic equations. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA-REACT (Seoul, South Korea) _ From farmers tilling
lush rice paddies to professionals walking through high-rise office
towers, South Koreans seemed relieved and elated at the promises of
peace and reconciliation that their president brought back on
Thursday. By Samuel Len.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA-CHINA (Beijing) _ There is perhaps no third-party
country that has so much to gain from peace on the Korean peninsula
as China. And so, as Kim Jong Il and Kim Dae-jung ended their
three-day summit meeting with an agreement and a hug, China's
officials were understandably thrilled. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-ERITREA (Nairobi) _ The Ethiopia-Eritrea war may be
over now that both sides have accepted a peace plan. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MEAT-PLANT (Tar Heel, N.C.) _ The first thing you learn at
the Smithfield hog plant here is the value of a sharp knife. The
second thing you learn is that not everyone has to work with a
knife. Whites, blacks, American Indians and Mexicans, they all have
their separate stations, but it is blacks and Mexicans that are
left to battle over the dirty jobs at the factory, one of the only
places within a 50-mile radius in this muddy corner of North
Carolina where a person might make more than $8 an hour. While
Smithfield's profits nearly doubled over the past year, wages have
remained flat. So a lot of Americans have quit and a lot of
Mexicans have been hired to take their places. But the workers see
one another, more than management, as the problem, and they see the
competition in skin tones. By Charlie LeDuff.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT601-606) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT (Valparaiso, Neb.) _ Pockets of extraordinary drought,
by some measures the worst in a century, have struck farms and
homes in parts of the South and the Plains. In Florida, alligators
are roaming out of lake and ponds that have all but disappeared. In
southeast Louisiana, rice crops and drinking wells are being ruined
by salt water that has seeped into the parched aquifer. In West
Texas, ranchers are selling off goats and sheep as the grasslands
dry up. In Georgia, the red soil is baked hard as concrete. By Jo
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DEATH-PENALTY (Houston) _ Nineteen years ago Bernadine
Skillern caught a fast glimpse of man who had just committed a
murder. She identified him then as Gary Graham, a young punk who
had confessed to a string of armed robberies. Now Graham has become
a cause celebre for many death penalty opponents and a headache for
Gov. George W. Bush, who may ultimately decide his fate. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-PROMS (Huntington, N.Y.) _ The days when proms were simple
affairs in high school gyms festooned with crepe paper streamers
and balloons are long gone. Driven by boom times, youthful
exuberance and the matrimonial-industrial complex of high fashion,
catering halls and luxury car rentals, the prom is no longer just a
rite of passage; it has become a serious expenditure. By Michael
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-PRIMARIES (Washington) _ On high-level Republican
thinking about the effort to reshape the primary schedule. By Adam
Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ADVISER (Washington) _ Arrayed behind George W. Bush as he
unveiled his nuclear policy initiative last month were two former
secretaries of state, two former national security advisers and a
former secretary of defense. But once Bush left the stage, the
foreign policy expert who fielded questions on the specifics of the
Texas governor's proposal was 45-year-old Condoleezza Rice, a black
college professor who is tutoring a presidential candidate who
concedes that he has much to learn about the world. By Elaine
Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-DALEY (Washington) _ A profile of William Daley, the
commerce secretary, who is expected to be named head of the Gore
campaign. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMAKERS-EFFICIENCY (Undated) _ Productivity has improved
across the U.S. auto industry in recent years. While the Ford plant
in Atlanta ranked as No. 1, the biggest overall efficiency gains
last year took place at General Motors, which was once known for
inefficiency. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCH-INTERNET (Undated) _ After an early and expensive Web
fiasco, Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., which owns Fox television,
Twentieth Century Fox, HarperCollins and a worldwide collection of
other media assets, has kept a low profile on the Internet. Murdoch
has publicly criticized the pending sale of Time Warner to America
Online and has said that Internet companies are valued far too
highly for the News Corp. to consider a similar merger. But since
the AOL-Time Warner linkup, Murdoch has been working feverishly to
put in place a huge media-technology deal of his own that will
answer questions about his digital strategy. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD-NORRIS-COLUMN (New York) _ The biggest accounting fraud
ever _ one that cost investors $19 billion and involved more than
$500 million in phony profits over just three years, now turns out
to have gone on almost forever. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ In a series of television
commercials, Microsoft's leaders describe the company's values and
its importance to the economy. The first began shortly after a
federal judge ruled in April that Microsoft had repeatedly violated
the nation's antitrust laws. The current installment, titled
``Vision,'' began running Sunday, four days after the judge ordered
that Microsoft should be split in two. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
