<P>
   BKN-LAKERS-BRYANT (Indianapolis) _ On Kobe Bryant, who, at age
21, was mature and smart enough to recognize the moment when he hit
the winning shot in Game 4 Wednesday. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-KOREAS (Undated) _ Even as North and South Korea negotiate a
historic agreement aimed at achieving peace, the ramifications are
already being felt in the Olympic movement. The two are being urged
to march together in the opening ceremonies in the Sydney Games,
and to play together as one team in the world table tennis
championships this summer. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-NOVELS (Undated) _ Film and the novel are cousins not far
removed, and the DNA they share is narrative. But their narrative
codes _ owing partly to obvious differences of media and partly to
their divergent histories _ have grown farther and farther apart.
By A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   PORTUGUESE-MODERNIST (New York) _ Modernism may or may not be
over, but that hasn't kept historians from widening its roll call,
adding names from more parts of the world. One of the latest
additions is the Portuguese painter Amedeo de Souza Cardoso, whose
work is now being seen in the United States for the first time in a
show of pieces borrowed primarily from the Gulbenkian Museum in
Lisbon. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BOWERY-HISTORY (New York) _ The Bowery deserves better than
its skid row connotations. When the aging buildings and their fire
escapes shimmer in the morning light, it's a place of urban beauty,
alluring as an Edward Hopper painting. By Sandee Brawarsky.
</P>
<P>
   MACBETH-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ On the Music Box Theater's
opening of Macbeth, starring television personality Kelsey Grammar,
best known as the charmingly ineffectual shrink on the hit sitcom
``Frasier.'' Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   SHAFT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ It's unusual for a movie to stack
the deck with a fistful of jokers, but the new version of ``Shaft''
_ part remake and part sequel _ does just that. Reviewed by Elvis
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   BOYS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ If you're still disconsolate over
the demise of ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' then ``Boys and Girls'' may
be the movie for you. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   TITAN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ If the basic ingredients of Don
Bluth and Gary Goldman's ambitious animated film ``Titan A.E.''
sound awfully familiar, it's because in some ways this handsomely
designed intergalactic adventure could be described as Son of
``Star Wars.'' Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERFLY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Butterfly,'' Jose Luis
Cuerda's delicate, quietly devastating new film fashioned out of
several linked short stories by Manuel Rivas, filters its tale of
ideological cataclysm through the eyes of a child. Reviewed by A.O.
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   INTERVIEW-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Interview,'' an
Australian film directed by Craig Monahan, is a cat-and-mouse game
set up on a board very similar to ``The Usual Suspects,'' a
situation in which the truth is constantly in play. Reviewed by
Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIS-SEA-PAINTINGS (New York) _ At first look, the quaint
fishing port of Gloucester, Mass., seems an unlikely hangout for
the jazzy city painter Stuart Davis (1894-1964). But according to
``Stuart Davis in Gloucester,'' a show of some 45 oils, watercolors
and drawings at the National Academy of Design, Gloucester and its
well-worn motifs play a role in the lively and innovative American
Cubist style that Davis eventually developed. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   SARGENT-GRAPHICS (New York) _ The Metropolitan Museum has opened
a very large exhibition of watercolors and drawings by John Singer
Sargent. By John Russell.
</P>
<P>
   SEDARIS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Me Talk Pretty One Day'' by
David Sedaris. Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
