<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRID CAMERON TORCHES TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Inside the Metrodome, a place where the sun never
shines, the Mariners offense finally started to see the light.
</P>
<P>
   The primary source of light in the Seattle attack these days
comes from center fielder Mike Cameron, who has been positively
incandescent lately.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night was center stage, the total spotlight. He had his
first career four-hit game, hit his first career grand slam and
matched his career best with five RBIs in the Mariners' 12-5 win
over Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for this one,'' Cameron said. ``It seems
like I've been up a lot with the bases loaded this year. The
closest I got was a ball I hit off the wall, and all I got out of
that one was a single.''
</P>
<P>
   The center fielder did three bases better this time around by
sending the ball over the wall. That came in the second inning,
moments after Rickey Henderson's RBI single broke a 1-1 tie.
Cameron left the Mariners in charge with a 6-1 lead, and Seattle
had the game well in hand the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   For all their offense _ 18 hits, 12 runs _ Seattle scored in
just four innings. In three of those, Cameron was directly involved
in getting the offense to click.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there. Cameron has reached base in 14 of his past 18
trips to the plate, with 10 hits and four walks. In that stretch,
he's also grounded out twice, struck out once and dropped down a
sacrifice bunt. He has two homers during the first seven games of
this 10-game road trip, the season's longest. The rest of the team
had three until Alex Rodriguez and John Olerud both hit two-run
shots in the ninth Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron showed the rest of the lads the way. Seattle has been
miserable hitting with the bases loaded (.224); he hit a homer with
the bases full. Seattle has been mediocre hitting with men in
scoring position (.276); he had a hit each of the three times he
came up with men in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   A .200 hitter on April 24, he goes into tonight's game with a
.293 average that includes nine homers and 25 RBIs since his April
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cammy's been great for us, defensively and offensively,''
Rodriguez said. ``He's been doing this all year. And as good as
he's been, we know he can be even better. We expect more from
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez expects more from himself, too. He took almost no
pleasure in his ninth-inning homer, which helped expand the comfort
level after the Twins had cut the lead to 8-5. Rodriguez's 18th
blast made it 10-5, but he couldn't forget his third-inning at-bat,
when he'd popped out with one out and the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The homer is a little consolation,'' Rodriguez said. ``But
when you have the opportunity to put a team away like I did (in the
third) and you don't do it, it stays with you. I've got to do
better. We've got to do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to be in this (pennant race), we've got to be more
effective with our hits. We had something like 20 hits tonight, but
a lot of them didn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   One item of note that had a great deal of meaning was the win,
which was credited to Rob Ramsay, of Vancouver, Wash., and
Washington State University. The lefty reliever, who took over
after starter Paul Abbott came down with cramps in his right
hamstring, won his first big-league game. It was a special moment,
and Ramsay's teammates didn't let him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we get our first? Did we get our first?'' Mark McLemore
said in a comic falsetto from across the clubhouse. He kept saying
it until he worked his way across the room to high-five Ramsay.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Ramsay's teammates were more upbeat about the win
than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to get the first one,'' Ramsay said. ``But you'd
like to think you earned the first one, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay gave up two runs in 22/3 innings after Abbott allowed
just one run in four innings. Under baseball rules, the starting
pitcher must go five innings. Abbott couldn't _ ``I wanted to, but
nothing good would have come of it; I could only have hurt
myself,'' Abbott said _ so Ramsay took over and vultured the win,
the first for a Seattle reliever since Jose Mesa won on May 19
against Tampa Bay. Since then, Mariners relievers had been 0-6.
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Abbott isn't expected to knock him out of the
rotation, but his early exit meant the Mariners had to run through
more relievers than they'd have preferred. Ramsay, Frankie
Rodriguez, Arthur Rhodes and Jose Paniagua all pitched before the
Twins were put away for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking about (adding) a 12th pitcher,'' manager
Lou Piniella said. ``But with the McLemore situation (McLemore is
due to serve a suspension early next week), I think we're going to
have to made do with 11.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager did make it clear that Abbott will eventually wind
up in the bullpen once starter Freddy Garcia comes off the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott would rather start, but he wasn't about to whine. He
didn't even let the win that could have been his, but wasn't,
impact his night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good for Ramsay,'' Abbott said. ``I'm glad I could
accommodate him.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached
</P>
<P>
   at 206-448-8004 or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
