<HEADLINE>
BROWN SHUTS OUT ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Center fielder Todd Hollandsworth made up for
nearly two weeks of missed time in one night and Kevin Brown made
sure some early run support was much appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth led off the bottom of the first with a homer and
had three hits and Brown threw his first shutout of the season as
the Dodgers beat Arizona 4-0 to earn a split in the four-game
series Thursday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (6-2) allowed four hits, struck out a season-high 10 and
didn't issue a walk. Gary Sheffield added a two-run homer and leads
the Dodgers with 19 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good,'' Brown said. ``I don't know if you'll
ever get in a situation, or they're very few and far between, where
you walk out there and say, 'Oh, my goodness. I feel so good
they've got no chance.' It's just a matter of trying to make do
with what you've got that night.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Brown's 17th career shutout and second since joining the
Dodgers. He beat the Chicago Cubs 6-0 Sept. 4, 1999. At one point,
Brown retired 13 straight Arizona hitters with only one ball
leaving the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown was something else,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``He's turning it up a notch, kind of raising the bar up. He
was filthy. He was in complete command of the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Dodgers are without Todd Hundley and Adrian
Beltre, considering they lost the series opener, and considering
Carlos Perez had to oppose Randy Johnson the day before, the
Dodgers will certainly take the split.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a pathetic part to the series. With NL
West-leading Arizona in town for a quartet of games, the Dodgers
averaged 29,264 per game, including 30,103 for the finale. But the
Dodgers ended the series as they began it, two games behind the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're banged up ... and just to be able to hold on with the
leaders in the division is important,'' Johnson said. ``Not only in
the standings but psychologically.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown made sure of the series split by throwing his third
straight complete game. Brown's won four of his last five decisions
and with the effort against Arizona, he lowered his ERA from 2.41
to 2.18.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers gave Brown all he would need in the first.
Hollandsworth, who pulled his right hamstring June 3 in Anaheim and
hadn't played since, led off a game with a homer for the fourth
time this season. Hollandsworth singled in the second and doubled
in the fifth, but his bid to become the second Los Angeles Dodger
to hit for the cycle (Wes Parker did it in 1970) ended when he
popped out to third in the seventh. He also made a catch against
the center-field fence off Bernard Gilkey in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark Grudzielanek singled to center and Sheffield
homered to center field to make it 3-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
