<SLUG> BC-BOX-ALI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALI'S DAUGHTER WINS IN FIRST ROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One thing about Laila Ali. She may or may not be a
legitimate boxer, but her name certainly is.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old daughter of Muhammad Ali packed the Universal
Amphitheatre on Thursday night and delivered a first-round knockout
of Milwaukee's Marjorie Jones - and the crowd of 3,845 loved every
minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, one minute and eight seconds. That's how long it took Ali
(7-0, seven knockouts), a 173-pound former nail salon owner from
Los Angeles, to dispose of the embarrassingly inept Jones (2-5),
whose peculiar style of leading with her chin wasn't exactly a
model of textbook boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Ali knocked down Jones three times, the first in eight seconds,
finishing her with a right to the jaw, as proud papa looked on from
the first row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice being here in front of my family,'' she said, ``but
I told the ref to let me knock her out cold. I didn't even break a
sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   In the main event - in name only - Carlos Navarro of Los Angeles
retained his IBA junior lightweight title by knocking out Nestor
Lopez (Tabasco, Mexico) at 2:19 in the ninth round.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro (22-1, 17 knockouts) spent most of the evening chasing
Lopez (19-7, 15 knockouts) before finally pinning him against the
ropes and putting him away with a crisp right cross.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, hurt for the first time by a series of body shots a round
earlier, went down for the 10 count and never attempted to get back
on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Oba Carr improved to 51-3-1 with a unanimous 10-round
decision over Juan Soberanes (Culiacan, Mexico). Soberanes
(44-25-2) went down in the fifth and was in trouble in the sixth
but rebounded to briefly hurt heavily favored Carr in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Cruiserweights Ted Cofie (Nottingham, England) and George
Ibidiro (Las Vegas) opened with a six-round draw. Cofie is 15-4-2;
Ibidiro is 3-5-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
