<HEADLINE>
AFTER 14 ON 18, DALY PACKS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ John Daly added to his collection of
surreal golfing accomplishments yesterday while competing in a
surreal setting.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in a heavy fog, Daly closed his opening round with a 14
on the par-5 18th hole, then closed the books on his bid to win the
U.S. Open at Pebble Beach Golf Links.
</P>
<P>
   Daly withdrew after posting an 83, his highest score at the Open
since a first-round 88 in 1986. In reaching a 12-over-par total,
Daly did most of his damage at No. 18. He headed to the tee box at
3 over and putted out at 12 over.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way to posting a 14, Daly hit his first tee shot out
of bounds to the right. He pulled two additional tee shots into the
Pacific Ocean before landing a 5-iron in the fairway. With
penalties, that was his seventh stroke. Daly laid up roughly 115
yards from the green, then pulled his approach into the ocean.
After another penalty stroke, he dropped in a greenside bunker and
was forced to play his 10th shot left-handed when his ball wound up
next to the seawall. He advanced the ball slightly, then hit a sand
wedge to 20 feet on his 12th stroke. From there, he two-putted.
</P>
<P>
   It marked Daly's highest score on a hole since he took an 18 at
No. 6 during the 1998 Bay Hill Invitational in Orlando, Fla. After
completing his round, Daly withdrew from the tournament and left
the course without comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' said Rocco Mediate, one of Daly's playing
partners. ``I didn't know \Rabout the 14\S. I thought it was a
seven or eight.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1999 Open, Daly received a two-stroke penalty for
hitting a moving ball after an uphill putt did a U-turn and rolled
back toward him at Pinehurst (N.C.) Country Club. \Nsubheds:Erratic
Sutton Hal Sutton began his day by holing an 8-iron approach for
eagle, then added two birdies in the next three holes. He finished
with five birdies but offset them with three bogeys and a
double-bogey at the par-5 14th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, the only person other than leader Tiger Woods to reach 6
under during the opening round, finished at 2-under 69.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said Sutton, who flew the green at No. 14
and took double-bogey from the deep rough. ``I hit a couple of
shots that I paid the price for. I'll just have to regroup.''
\Nsubheds:Shots in the dark Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks began
warming up before dawn's early light in preparation for yesterday's
6:30 a.m. (PDT) tee time, the earliest start of his professional
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the first golfer on the range, at 5:15, and it was still
dark,'' said Brooks, who pushed the first competitive shot of the
2000 U.S. Open into the right rough but rallied to par the hole.
``That's too early for me. This is just an observation, but I think
7 o'clock is plenty early to start. At least it would have been
daylight when we got to the range.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, who was greeted by 50 fans at the first tee, said the
early start did not create a problem with shadows on the greens or
play a role in his opening 74. Instead, Brooks found only eight of
18 greens in regulation and took bogeys on both back-nine par-5s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed some good chances there,'' said Brooks, whose
approach at the par-5 14th hit within a foot of the pin but bounded
into the deep rough behind the green. ``Overall, I played decent. I
hit three bad shots, and that's the difference between what I shot
and even-par.'' \Nsubheds:Campbell rises, falls Chad Campbell, an
Andrews native and five-event winner on the 2000 Hooters Tour,
surfaced briefly on the leader board after a birdie on the sixth
hole moved him to even-par and gave him a share of 10th place.
Campbell made only one birdie the rest of the way, fading to 74,
but said he was pleased because he ``got pretty much everything I
could'' out of a round where he hit only 10 of 18 greens in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed in my score,'' Campbell said. ``I just
need to keep the ball out of the rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, 26, said he never felt awed by playing his first
competitive round at Pebble Beach. But his caddie, Fort Worth
resident Jud Burkett, termed the walk between the ropes ``really
cool.'' Burkett, a former UT-Arlington golfer, wore a Colonial cap
during the round. \Nsubheds:Jobe surges late Brandt Jobe, a
Southlake resident, said he avoided ``a complete mess'' by
collecting four birdies in his final six holes during a round of
72. Jobe reached 5-over par with a double-bogey at No. 10 and said
he ``was ready to keep walking'' back to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But he stabilized matters with a 15-foot birdie putt at No. 13,
added another on the next hole and closed with consecutive birdies
at Nos. 17 and 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a long way to come back,'' said Jobe, who has missed
the cut in three of his past five PGA Tour events. ``It was a nice
way to end the day. That kept me in the tournament.''
\Nsubheds:Briefly Afternoon starters endured a 21/2-hour fog delay
before play was suspended. As a result, 75 players must return
beginning at 6:45 a.m. (PDT) today to complete their opening
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's Sergio Garcia wore knickers in honor of the late Payne
Stewart, the 1999 Open champ.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, on playing partner Jesper Parnevik's bright orange
shirt: ``You could see him in the fog, for sure. He was our
defense, so no one could hit into us.'' nn
</P>
