<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-CLAMPETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS ANALYST LIVES DREAM BY FIRING 68
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Bobby Clampett redefined the concept of
role reversals in professional golf yesterday at Pebble Beach Golf
Links. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clampett, a CBS golf analyst, helped describe Tiger Woods'
historic comeback from a seven-stroke deficit to win a sixth
consecutive PGA Tour event at Pebble Beach in February. Four months
later, Clampett has emered as one of Woods' primary roadblocks in
winning a U.S. Open on the same course. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Playing in only his second professional tournament in the past
21 months, Clampett collected four birdies and a bogey. He posted a
68 in his first round at the Open since 1986 and stands three
strokes behind Woods. Among the golfers who completed play in
yesterday's fog-shrouded opening round, only three finished ahead
of Clampett. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clampett, who retired from the PGA Tour in 1995 and has only
played about one round per month for the past two years, said he
considered his startling success ``a gift from God.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Words can't describe my emotions right now,'' said Clampett,
40, who choked back tears on the ninth green after draining a
25-foot, downhill birdie putt to move within a stroke of the lead.
``Is this unbelievable, or what? The first 10 holes were like
playing golf in heaven. Even the putts I hit too hard went in.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of those occurred at No. 10, a sliding 10-footer that put
him _ briefly _ in a tie for the lead with Hal Sutton at 4 under.
With a chance to take a solo lead, Clampett missed a two-foot
birdie attempt at No. 13, which he termed ``my only bad stroke of
the day.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clampett collected his only bogey after visiting a greenside
bunker at No. 16, which hardly diminished the enthusiasm of the
Carmel, Calif. native, who grew up playing at Pebble Beach. As a
tour rookie, Clampett finished third in the 1982 Open at Pebble
Beach. But his swing soured, causing Clampett to turn to the
television booth in recent years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He attempted to qualify for this year's Open only because it was
at Pebble Beach and because NBC, not CBS, is handling the weekend
broadcasts. That provided Clampett a week off, which has begun
unfolding in a manner Clampett said he would not have envisioned in
his wildest dreams. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nantz, CBS' lead golf announcer who traveled to Pebble Beach
to follow Clampett, said his colleague ``just delivered the most
special, most unexpected round of the year'' in professional golf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is amazing stuff,'' Nantz said. ``The guy is retired. He
had to qualify to get here. He's the ultimate underdog, everyman
golfer. And he just shot 68 at the Open.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As he left the course, Clampett exchanged hugs with family
members, as well as Nantz. He reflected on his lifelong goal: to
win a U.S. Open at Pebble Beach, his home course. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream is still alive,'' Clampett said, smiling broadly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For one more day at least. &QL; 
\Ntagtop:Jimmy Burch, (817) 390-7760 &QL; 
\Ntagbottom:jburch\Nstar-telegram.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
