r s BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     06-16 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERTIME WIN LEAVES IMPRESSION ON WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Sunday, when the Lakers were beaten by the
Indiana Pacers, Jerry West was at a cinema in West Los Angeles
watching ``Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best movies I've ever seen,'' says the architect of
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, West felt relaxed enough to watch Game 4 at
his home in Bel Air, and the epic battle that went to the Lakers in
overtime left a deep impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best games I've ever seen,'' says the man who on
June 26, 1996 traded Vlade Divac to the Charlotte Hornets for a
17-year-old high school senior named Kobe Bryant and three weeks
later convinced Shaquille O'Neal to sign with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the vital contributions West has made in putting
together these Lakers, you would think that West would be basking
in the limelight of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   You would think he would be getting vast television exposure,
and would be the feature subject in off-day articles of the some
1,000 newspaper reporters on hand for the Laker-Pacer series.
</P>
<P>
   You would think that the NBC TV cameras would be zooming in on
him during games as he sat in the crowd either at Staples Center or
Conseco Fieldhouse. But Jerry West hasn't even attended a game yet.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago he was in Chicago at an NBA Draft combine.
</P>
<P>
   This week he has remained in Los Angeles, even though the Lakers
were conducting their business in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just better for me from a health standpoint to stay
away,'' says West, whose stress level has been known to get
dangerously high during Laker games.
</P>
<P>
   West isn't surprised that the Lakers hold a 3-1 advantage over
the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a better team,'' he says simply. ``I think right
now that we have two of the five best players in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   West isn't given to loosely throwing out bouquets, but the stout
work of Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant has him doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq has been unstoppable ... no one can handle him,'' says
West. ``He's taken his game to a level few centers in basketball
history have been able to reach. And his discipline and restraint
are so impressive. Remember, this is a man who routinely gets
flagrantly fouled, but because of his size it's seldom ever called.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for Kobe, it speaks volumes of him that his teammates
wanted him to have the ball in overtime. I think having him back
gave the team renewed confidence. It also put less of a burden on
our role players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable to see the way Kobe has grown and matured. I
think the fans of L.A. are fortunate to get to see Kobe go from
being a teenager to an adult. And he's going to get better and
better in the upcoming seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West has made many deft moves across the seasons in his
position as executive vice president for basketball operations for
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But his greatest legacy as an executive might turn out to be
Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I saw Kobe in a workout, he was so spectacular that I
felt we had to get him regardless of the cost,'' says West.
</P>
<P>
   The cost was modest, and the Lakers are benefiting from West's
keen foresight.
</P>
<P>
   Without it, the Lakers wouldn't be on the doorstep of their
first NBA title since 1988. ...
</P>
<P>
   - I've never seen Shaqille O'Neal expend as much energy at both
ends of the court as he did during his 36-point, 21-rebound
performance Wednesday evening against the Pacers. I'll be surprised
if he can repeat such a passionate effort tonight. ...
</P>
<P>
   - I'm going to say it again to those over-50 types immersed
hopelessly in the fog of the past Shaquille O'Neal is better than
Wilt Chamberlain. ...
</P>
<P>
   - That proverbial torch just might have passed from Michael
Jordan to Kobe Bryant during that Game 4 overtime session in which
Bryant gave a rousing impersonation of Jordan. ...
</P>
<P>
   - Maybe it's just me, but I keep getting the feeling that the
NBC commentator, Doug Collins, fired once by the Chicago Bulls and
replaced by Phil Jackson, is rooting for the Pacers. ...
</P>
<P>
   - They say NBA superstars get special treatment from the
officials Michael Jordan, Magic Johnson and Larry Bird certainly
did but that isn't the case with Shaquille O'Neal. He routinely
gets called for fouls that aren't called against the men who guard
him. ...
</P>
<P>
   - I still don't understand the reasoning behind Phil Jackson's
decision to start A.C. Green over Robert Horry. But I've never
understood the reasoning behind Green, badly past his prime, being
on the Laker roster in the first place. ...
</P>
<P>
   - In order for Sugar Shane Mosley to emerge victorious Saturday
night against Oscar De La Hoya, he will either have to knock De La
Hoya out or dominate him so thoroughly that the judges will have no
choice but to award him the decision.
</P>
<P>
   But if the fight is even faintly close, you can be sure that De
La Hoya's hand will be raised at the conclusion because De La Hoya
has all the political edges aligned on his side.
</P>
<P>
   While the California State Athletic Commission assigned the
officials referee Lou Moret and judges Pat Russell, Marty Sammon
and Lou Filippo you know all these men are quite aware that the
match is sanctioned by the WBC.
</P>
<P>
   And that Oscar De La Hoya holds the WBC title. And that the
WBC's biggest sanctioning fees come from De La Hoya's matches. And
that the WBC's president-for-life, Jose Sulaiman, has become close
pals with De La Hoya's promoter, Bob Arum. And that Sulaiman
assigns officials to work WBC title fights in faraway countries.
</P>
<P>
   And that no forthcoming cushy foreign assignment will be offered
by Sualiman to any official brazen enough Saturday night to cast
his ballot for Mosley in a close encounter. ...
</P>
<P>
   - Actually, on second thought, the one judge I doubt would be
swayed by such peripheral influences would be Lou Filippo, the
long-time Downey resident and ex pug who's a beacon of probity.
Filippo is a fiercely independent sort who gained lasting notoriety
for himself in April of 1987 when he was the lone judge to vote for
Marvelous Marvin Hagler in Hagler's split decision loss to Sugar
Ray Leonard. ...
</P>
<P>
   - Monsignor Gualderon's 17th annual St. Anthony's Golf Classic
will be staged Monday at Recreation Park. The famed Long Beach
religious icon has raised more than $480,000 in his charity event
for athletic equipment and student scholarships for St. Anthony
High. ...
</P>
<P>
   - But At Least He Doesn't Take Credit For The Salk Vaccine: He
hasn't scored a point, or grabbed a rebound for the Lakers, but
KFWB's dreaded Big Nasty, Joe McDonnell, feels he's had a major
impact in the team being on the brink of a world championship. ``I
give Jerry Buss credit for coming up with the money, I give Jerry
West credit for coming up with the players and I give myself credit
for kicking off the campaign to get Del Harris fired,'' says
McDonnell, never one to minimize his role on human events. ...
</P>
<P>
   The McDonnell-Douglas show, featuring Press-Telegram columnist
Doug Krikorian and radio personality Joe McDonnell, can be heard
Sunday evening on KABC (790 AM) between 9 p.m. and midnight.
</P>
</TEXT>
