<HEADLINE>
NHRA SEASON HITS TOUGHEST STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lazy days of summertime?
</P>
<P>
   Not for National Hot Rod Association competitors, who beginning
with this weekend's Pontiac Excitement Nationals near Columbus,
Ohio, embark on the toughest portion of the 23-national event
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the heat just wears guys out,'' said Top Fuel veteran
Doug Herbert, referring to the eight-race summer season that also
includes stops at St. Louis, Denver and Sonoma before concluding
with the U.S. Nationals in early September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess over the years I've gained a lot of experience running
on slippery surfaces in some other racing circuits, so I'm not
afraid to try some things that others might not.''
</P>
<P>
   But mainly it's the hot, slippery track conditions that concern
drivers. The summer heat makes an already narrow tuning window even
smaller for crew chiefs who must find a way to tame their
6,000-horsepower machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat and less-than perfect racetracks should even out the
field a little bit, which then puts things more in the driver's
hands,'' veteran Funny Car pilot Whit Bazemore said. ``Instead of
just flooring it and seeing what the car will run, you'll see
pedaling contests, where two Funny Cars are fighting for traction.
In that case the better driver is going to win. I truly enjoy those
situations, and believe that could work in the Kendall/Matco team's
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows that better than nine-time Funny Car champ John
Force, who hasn't won at Columbus since 1990 and hasn't advanced to
the semifinals since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The track has) been marginal a lot of times over the years,''
said Austin Coil, Force's crew chief since 1984. ``The heat and
humidity in that location certainly has made it difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   -The NHRA is expected to release both its 2001 national event
and television schedule within the next month. Industry sources
indicate that the national event schedule will include major
changes, including a possible second date for Route 66 Raceway near
Chicago. Bristol Motor Speedway, which has hosted the special
non-points Winston Showdown the past two seasons, is expected to be
awarded a national event. The schedule would remain at 23 national
events with the second Chicago date and the Bristol event replacing
races at the Texas Motorplex near Dallas and the fall race at
Houston Raceway Park. Both of those facilities have hosted two
events since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It's also speculated that The Strip at Las Vegas Motor Speedway
will host that special event next season, possibly in late October.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in the television schedule are expected to include
coverage by ESPN, which will have a void to fill next season when
NASCAR Winston Cup begins a multi-year TV deal with NBC and Fox
Sports. Both ESPN2 and TNN, which have shared NHRA coverage this
season, will continue in that role in next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought NASCAR leap-frogged everybody 10 years
ago,'' Force said. ``I think (with NASCAR's) move to (NBC and Fox)
that has opened the door for us, if I got the story right. NHRA is
going to make a move. NHRA president Tom Compton has already proven
with the 90-percent nitro rule and the 75-minute rule that he can
make the right changes to make it better. Now there is going to be
a big announcement by NHRA. I don't know what it is, but I know
ESPN, ESPN2 has been around us right now.''
</P>
<P>
   -Glendora's Donnie Hendricks dominated a Castrol NHRA Junior
Drag Racing League event earlier this month, winning a pair of
races at the Jr. Dragsters West racetrack in Rialto on June 3-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
