<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN HAS DRIVING AMBITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randy Brown addresses everyone around the race track as
``Mister'' or ``Sir.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old looks more like a tall 12-year-old. He's a
rail-thin, 5-foot-9, 120-pounder with peach fuzz. He will become a
West Covina High senior after today, when the semester ends. He
hopes to receive his first graduation present as a high school
senior on Saturday a victory when he races in the Mechanix Wear
Speed Truck series event at Irwindale Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   But he's quickly gaining respect from the other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   A rookie in the series, Brown has yet to reach victory lane. But
he's come close. He was fourth at El Cajon Speedway two weeks ago,
is seventh in the series point standings and leads the rookie
points race by 12 points. He has made the Irwindale trophy dash
twice.
</P>
<P>
   All in eight races in the truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just learning and gaining experience,'' Brown says. ``I
hope I'm gaining respect from the other drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   The series is not Brown's first foray in racing, but it is the
first time he's raced in a NASCAR-style series and the first time
he's raced on asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who has been racing since he was 9, won 10 quarter midget
series championships, four track titles at Pomona and four
California State Monza titles. But he could only race in the series
until he was 16, so late last year, his father, Bob, a former
racer, bought a Speed Truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seemed like the natural class to get into,'' Randy said.
``I think this could lead to Super Late Model and then Busch Grand
National.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Brown raced until the death of his wife, Connie, 14 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I couldn't race any more and raise two children,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has a 19-year-old daughter, Wendy, and he helps Randy prepare
the truck as the crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone way beyond our expectations,'' Bob Brown said.
``We're tickled to death.''
</P>
<P>
   -A field of more than 100 cars is expected on Saturday, as
NASCAR Late Model, Super Stock and Mini Stock and the American
Racing Truck series take to the track.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary heat races will be run before the 7 p.m. opening
ceremonies. Gates open at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   -With the NASCAR Winston West Home Depot 250 at the speedway for
the first of three visits next week, teams have been testing at the
track. On the track Wednesday was defending series champion Sean
Woodside, who is in a one-race-only deal; Ben Walker, who is second
in Irwindale's Super Late Model points race; Jason Small, last
year's NWWS rookie of the year; and Eric Norris, son of actor Chuck
Norris. On Thursday, El Monte's Kenny Smith tested. Testing ends
today.
</P>
<P>
   -The Winston West series will hold a golf tournament to benefit
Motor Racing Outreach.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston West Open will be held June 23 at Azusa Greens
Country Club and an awards banquet will follow at Glendora
Performance Motorsports, which is the home of series driver Joe
Bean.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, which begins at 11:30 a.m., will include lunch,
prizes, raffles and gifts. The banquet will include food and music.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (909) 394-3341.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
