<HEADER>
A5634 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CREDITCARD-COPS-ECONO     06-16 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDITCARD-COPS-ECONOMIST-675&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVE OVER, BILL GATES: ANTI-TRUSTBUSTERS NOW HIT `PLASTIC-GATE'  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 100; 1,100 words uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: TWO OPTIONAL TRIMS, AT 675 AND 825, TOTALING 100
WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,100 WORDS.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fifty years after the credit card was invented in
Manhattan, its popularity knows no bounds. But the structure of the
industry supplying credit and other charge cards faces
unprecedented scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the trial began of an antitrust lawsuit launched by
America's Department of Justice (DOJ) against Visa and MasterCard,
which together account for around 75 percent of the country's $1.3
trillion credit-card market.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's antitrust watchdog also said it is probing
``Visa and credit cards in general.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, another trial will start, of a class-action suit by
many of America's retailers, seeking damages of $8.1 billion from
Visa and MasterCard for antitrust violations in the debit-card
business.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that the card industry is uncompetitive may seem
bizarre to most consumers, particularly in America, where,
typically, a couple of card-solicitations arrive in the mail every
day. Almost anybody can get a card _ bankrupts, infants, even pets.
</P>
<P>
   If lack of opportunity for consumers were the alleged antitrust
violation, the charges would surely be thrown out more quickly than
you can say ``American Express.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is slightly more to the accusations than that. The DOJ
is unhappy for two main reasons. One is that it believes that Visa
and MasterCard are not really competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike American Express (Amex), a single company, and Discover,
owned solely by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Visa and MasterCard are
each owned mutually, by associations of thousands of financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   These two associations operate under what is known as
``duality''; member banks are allowed to issue both Visa- and
MasterCard-branded plastic. According to the DoJ, this duality
means that the two leading brands are, in effect, one business.
</P>
<P>
   And second, the DOJ thinks that, although there is competition
between banks using their brands, the dominant market position of
MasterCard and Visa has enabled them to stifle competition from
rivals such as Amex and Discover, notably through exclusivity rules
forbidding banks from issuing rival cards.
</P>
<P>
   Since the DOJ launched its lawsuit in October 1998, the
Visa-MasterCard duality has started to unravel. In February 1999,
Citigroup, the world's biggest card-issuer, resigned from the board
of Visa; it is shifting all its business to MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the suit was started, John Reed, until recently
the joint-boss of Citi, admitted to Joel Klein, assistant
attorney-general, that it had been a mistake for banks to become
overlapping owners of both brands. He urged Klein, to no avail, to
give the industry more time to sort out the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan has since gone with MasterCard, while BankOne's
FirstUSA and Bank of America have thrown in their lot with Visa.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing the scene of the crime in this way might seem evidence
of guilt. Not necessarily. Some big banks have long wanted to
downplay the MasterCard and Visa connection, and increasingly their
cards emphasize their own brand.
</P>
<P>
   Some might even quietly welcome the antitrust action. They argue
that they have been subsidizing these two brands at the expense of
their own. The benefit has gone mainly to small banks, which have
been able to compete in the card business only because they carry
the MasterCard or Visa logos.
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, one of the main arguments that the two brands offer
in their defense is that the DOJ's lawsuit could result in many of
these small banks leaving the industry, reducing competition.
</P>
<P>
   The claim that Visa and MasterCard do not compete vigorously
will be hard to prove. Internal documents suggesting this will be
submitted by the DOJ. They will be met with what is known in
antitrust circles as the ``demented middle-manager defense.''
</P>
<P>
   True, their advertisements do not criticize each other, though
they sometimes badmouth rivals such as Amex. On the other hand the
presence of competitors such as Amex means that the two cannot
afford to be an entirely cozy duopoly. Moreover, it is not clear
that the DOJ's action will increase competition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 50 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 675) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The system of duality was actually introduced back in 1975 at
the behest of the DOJ, which then feared that Visa was becoming
dominant. As it unravels, the immediate impact has been to
strengthen Visa's position further. It had anyway increased its
market share, from 43 percent in 1990 to 49 percent in 1999
(against MasterCard's 28 percent). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The argument that the current market structure inhibits
innovation has worked well for the DOJ in its case against
Microsoft. So it is no surprise to hear it used again in this case.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence suggests that innovation in the provision of
financial products to consumers has been more advanced in America
than in the rest of the world. It has been ahead in offering cards
to lower-quality borrowers, in varying interest rates and terms and
conditions, and in offering rewards and affinity programs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 50 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 825) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Notable exceptions have been ``smart'' cards, which have had
more success elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The development of wireless products, such as Palm Pilots or
mobile phones that can download money from an ATM and digitally
transfer it to a retailer, is more advanced in Europe than America,
but that is probably because the wireless infrastructure is more
advanced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,100) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Nor do Visa or MasterCard seem to be less innovative than rivals
such as Amex. They were quicker to introduce affinity programs,
such as MasterCard's pioneering tie-up with AT&AMP;T (no annual fee)
and its air-miles arrangement with American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   True, Amex has been first with its ``Blue'' smart card _ though
this is primarily a marketing coup, as the rest of the economy is
not yet smart enough to let it do much more than any other charge
card does.
</P>
<P>
   The DOJ will also struggle to prove that merchants are paying
higher fees because of the dominance of Visa and MasterCard. Amex
has typically charged merchants more (though Discover has usually
been cheaper).
</P>
<P>
   Yet it will not be surprising if the DOJ succeeds in its attack
on the rules banning MasterCard and Visa's bank partners from using
other cards, if only because they look so dodgy.
</P>
<P>
   Such restrictive agreements are not always unacceptable: nobody
objects to Coca-Cola banning Pepsi from its soda fountains. And
banks can always choose to quit MasterCard and Visa if they want to
offer Amex cards.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic benefits claimed for the rules do not seem
large: if there were fewer small banks offering credit cards, would
they be missed?
</P>
<P>
   In sum, the case against MasterCard and Visa looks weak. But, in
contrast to the Microsoft suit, the result is unlikely to make much
difference, at least to consumers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 0541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 05:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-DVD-VS-VHS-ECONOMIST-     06-16 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DVD-VS-VHS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DVD VS. VHS VIDEO WARS _ THE SEQUEL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 800-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   TOKYO _ It looks for all the world like a rerun of the video
wars of the 1980s, when Sony's clever little Betamax cassette
recorder was eventually trounced by the Matsushita camp's clunkier
but more versatile VHS machine.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Japan's two consumer-electronics giants have been
girding up over the past few months to do battle again.
</P>
<P>
   And, appropriately enough, they are butting heads over which of
their digital video disc (DVD) recorder designs will replace the
aging video-cassette recorder (VCR) that they fought over a decade
and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   The difference today is that Sony and Matsushita may have left
it too late for either to gain any real advantage in the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Delayed by wrangles with film studios and digital broadcasters
over how to prevent pirates from making pristine master copies of
their intellectual property, the two rival DVD recorders may turn
out to be obsolete even before going into mass production.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, Japanese manufacturers at last agreed on the
royalties to be paid to organizations that represent the
broadcasters and film producers. A 1 percent surcharge, with an
upper limit of Yen1,000 ($9.50), is to be added to the wholesale
price of all DVD recorders and blank discs, so that copyright
holders can be compensated for the copying done by legitimate
users.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Hollywood studios have accepted a copy-protection
scheme that allows them to decide whether their copyrighted
material can be copied freely, copied just once, or not copied at
all.
</P>
<P>
   With the royalty and copy-protection issues resolved, Japanese
manufacturers at last feel confident enough to start cranking up
production of DVD recorders and discs for the huge American market.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Matsushita has the upper hand. It had delayed
launching its DVD recorder until the copy-protection scheme that it
developed with Toshiba, IBM and Intel was accepted universally.
</P>
<P>
   The new Matsushita machine goes on sale in Japan on June 30, at
a list price of Yen250,000 ($2,375). The industry expects to ship
150,000 units by the end of the year, with a third of those going
to America.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping the gun, two of Sony's allies, Pioneer and Sharp, have
already launched video recorders based on variants of a rival
technology known in Japan as DVD-RW. But because their video
recorders use a copy-protection scheme that has not been accepted
abroad, they will have to develop wholly new models for export.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pioneer is pushing hard, Sony and other members of the
DVD-RW family are expected to miss this year's pre-Christmas rush
for DVD recorders in America.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, however, the advantage could swing back to the Sony
camp, thanks to a gamble taken on how digital video recorders will
be used.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD-RAM design adopted by Toshiba and Hitachi, as well as
Matsushita, functions as a replacement for both the VCR and the
recordable CD drive that is increasingly used in personal
computers. The advantage is that material recorded from a
television or video camera on a DVD-RAM disc can be edited on a PC.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, useful though that sounds, the DVD-RAM is not particularly
user-friendly, according to Masami Fujino, an industry watcher in
the Tokyo office of Nikko Salomon Smith Barney, a stockbroker. The
recording disc has to be stored in a special cartridge, making it
impossible to replay it on an ordinary DVD player.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 12 million DVD players in use around the
world, with a further 14 million expected this year.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the DVD-RW, developed originally by Sony in Japan
and Philips in the Netherlands, is a stand-alone product designed
solely to work as a replacement for the VCR. Besides being easy to
operate, its discs can be played back on existing DVD players.
</P>
<P>
   A DVD-RW machine can also record up to six hours' worth of
material, compared with its rival's more limited four hours.
</P>
<P>
   During the video wars of the 1980s, it was the longer recording
time of Matsushita's VHS that finally put paid to Sony's Betamax
design. But any success that the Sony/Philips offering might enjoy
is likely to be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, a new recording technology will be in production that
uses a blue-green laser instead of the red one found in today's CD
players and DVD machines.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its much higher frequency, the blue-green laser will
cram three or four times more video on to a standard DVD disc _
enough, should it be needed, to record up to 24 hours of video at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody pondering what wondrous new gizmo should replace their
VCR had better wait. The latest episode of the video wars has
barely begun. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 0542EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
