r k BC-OIL-SANDS-CANADA-ECON     06-16 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-SANDS-CANADA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL SANDS: `BLACK GOLD' LIES BENEATH CANADIAN FORESTS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 475-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   EDMONTON, ALBERTA _ Since the great Klondike gold rush of a
century ago, this rugged corner of Canada has seen plenty of booms
and busts.
</P>
<P>
   The next big boom looks likely to come from the ``black gold''
that lies under the region's forests: oil sands.
</P>
<P>
   When Peter Pond, a British explorer, ran into the local Cree
tribe in 1778, he found them caulking their canoes with the bitumen
that is common in these parts. Three decades ago, firms began
commercial exploitation of the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to advances in technology and declining costs of
production, optimists now think the region's huge reserves of this
mucky material could meet half of Canada's oil needs by 2010, up
from just a quarter five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes of such a bonanza might explain the upbeat mood in
Calgary, Alberta's second city and arguably its real oil capital.
The World Petroleum Congress (WPC) met there this week, and many of
the thousands of participants came to find out about the oil sands
of northern Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   The oil is trapped in a viscous tar that is found under forests
the size of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   There is reckoned to be 300 billion barrels' worth of oil here,
greater than Saudi Arabia's proven oil reserves; if brought to
market, it could fetch trillions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but there's the snag: extracting the oil from the tar-like
bitumen (tar sands is what old lags call oil sands) is not as easy
as sticking a pipe into the Saudi desert. It takes over a ton of
bitumen to make one useful barrel of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Yet firms have invested some $33 billion in the area to turn oil
sands into oil. Why? One reason is that oilmen see Canada, for all
its fissiparous tendencies, as much less risky than the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   It is also close to the giant American market. What is more,
says Wayne Kubasker of Exxon Mobil, ``The oil sands are there.
There is no risk in finding them. Finding and development costs are
much less than for conventional oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Production costs of $17 a barrel have fallen to less than $13 a
barrel over the past decade. The government helps with lavish tax
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Syncrude, whose main partners include Exxon Mobil, Gulf and
Occidental, mines two-thirds of the sands extracted today and plans
to do so for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   All this is encouraging, but the local optimism is probably a
bit excessive. After all, a barrel of Middle Eastern oil costs less
than $5 to extract. And little over a year ago, oil fetched less
than $10 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Until the cost of extracting oil from the sands drops by a lot
more, Saudi Arabia's supremacy in the petroleum world is probably
not under serious threat from Alberta. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
