<HEADER>
A5747 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN17-COX     06-16 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    That `dirt bag' Springsteen
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a time for healing,'' John Puglissi said at a news
conference announcing New York police officers' boycott of Bruce
Springsteen's Madison Square Garden concerts. Springsteen's new
song about the shooting of Amadou Diallo ``just reopens old
wounds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement begs the question: Just whose wounds have started
to heal?
</P>
<P>
   The wounds of Kadiadou Diallo, the mother of the victim? When
she arrived at the Bronx apartment building where police fired 41
shots at her unarmed son, she crumpled to the street and cried out,
``Amadou, Amadou, Amadou.''
</P>
<P>
   The wounds of New York's black community _ have they healed? The
folks who are forced to think twice before they ``pull'' a wallet
or a cell phone?
</P>
<P>
   Puglissi said patrolmen object to the song because it ``is based
on racial profiling'' _ as if the mere mention of the problem were
an affront.
</P>
<P>
   Which begs an even more important question: How can such wounds
ever heal if we pretend the injury doesn't exist?
</P>
<P>
   ``If wounds are healing, it is only the wounds of those who
committed the offense,'' said Dennis Lieberman, attorney for three
Ohio youths who accused police of racial profiling. ``We're not at
the time where we need to heal wounds; those wounds are not opened
enough for us to be able to heal them.''
</P>
<P>
   We all feel outrage when police officers are second-guessed,
even in clear-cut, self-defense cases. We all know that police must
make split-second, life-and-death decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the controversial song is hardly an Ice-T-style,
anti-police diatribe. It recognizes those complexities in a chorus
that repeats the thoughts that might have run through the officers'
minds:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a gun? Is it a knife? Is it a wallet? This is your life.
It ain't no secret you can get killed just for living in your
American skin.''
</P>
<P>
   The last line ``could apply to both Diallo and the policeman,''
notes New York Times critic Jon Pareles. Such subtleties apparently
are lost on the song's detractors, including an FOP president who
called Springsteen a ``dirt bag.''
</P>
<P>
   What's troubling here isn't the name-calling or the boycott, but
the ostrich mentality they represent: ``Let's not talk about it;
let's make the mere mention of racial profiling a thought crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The village of Waynesville, Ohio is still grappling with what
happened on Feb. 26, when three minority teens accused police of
needlessly detaining them at gunpoint for almost an hour. The
Warren County Sheriff's Department exonerated police in a 62-page
report that often seemed less interested in investigating the
incident than in discrediting the background of the teens as well
as witnesses. (We learn, for instance, that witness Justin Bledsoe
``keyed'' a car in 1998.) No drugs were ever found and the teens
were never cited, yet the report concludes that there was probable
cause for the traffic stop.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Warren County officials haven't made racial
profiling a verboten subject. Since the controversial incident,
many communities have established policies banning the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is a sincere policy, it is a start,'' Lieberman said. He
worries, however, that it's a ``legal tactic.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope it's a good-faith effort. We may never know what
really happened Feb. 26, but we do know this: The community must
move on from here.
</P>
<P>
   And the slowest way for the wounds to heal is by pretending it
never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
