<HEADER>
A5748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN17-COX     06-16 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Today's newspaper ethics clash with home-cooked cravings
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ga. _ The newspaper business has changed a lot
since I first hired on nearly a half-century ago. Thanks to
computers and a lot of other technical stuff, the process of making
your newspaper is quicker, cleaner and safer. I doubt it's nearly
as much fun.
</P>
<P>
   When I started to work in the old Atlanta Journal building at 10
Forsyth St., we had decrepit pre-Depression typewriters and no air
conditioning. Everything had to be put on paper. We glued pages
together and yelled for a copy boy to ship them through pneumatic
tubes to the composing room, where rows of operators sat at
clanking Linotype machines, turning deathless prose into lines of
metal type, which were then transferred to a heavy frame the size
of a newspaper page.
</P>
<P>
   Next was a boiling-hot metal impression that cooled into a
half-circle-shaped plate to be trundled off to the press, paired
with another plate, and then bolted onto a cylinder where words and
sentences were finally married with paper and ink.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper business 50 years ago had not progressed much past
the horse and buggy. In the newsroom, rows of teletype machines
brought news in from wires strung all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody smoked, either cigarettes or cigars. Most of us had
seen Walter Matthau in ``The Front Page,'' the comic but accurate
movie about old-fashioned journalism. In our ignorance, we didn't
have to worry about cancer, but cigarettes made fires a constant
threat. Puffing away in Hollywood style, reporters paid little heed
to ashtrays and frequently threw their butts into the nearest
wastebasket.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing makes me feel older than walking into a modern newsroom.
There are no chattering teletypes, no paste pots to glue stories
together, no paper flying around, no noise. The newsroom could just
as well be an accounting firm. Smoking is against the law. Copy
boys no longer exist. They are politically incorrect, which the
Constitution's legendary Flash would find insulting.
</P>
<P>
   Flash made a career of being the Constitution's ace copy boy. He
ranked near the publisher in respect and knew more about the
newspaper than most editors and reporters, even after he slowed
down in old age and spent a lot of time napping in the supply
closet.
</P>
<P>
   Change hasn't been limited to technology. There has been a
seismic shift in newspaper ethics, and that is what troubles me at
the moment. Newspapering used to carry a lot of perks that
compensated for small paychecks passed out by stingy publishers and
owners.
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s, and later, we got free tickets to baseball and
college football games. Movie passes were available for the asking.
</P>
<P>
   All of this changed, along about Watergate, as I recall.
Newspapers, like Congress, finally caught on about ethics and
conflicts of interest, and got around to banning gifts of value,
which is why I'm afraid I'm in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   When I complained about the scarcity of good Brunswick stew, the
Cawthon sisters showed up with a batch made from their daddy's
famous recipe. Our neighbor Webb Mask decided to share his annual
making. Bill Corry, the old coach, brought a sample from a secret
source in Morgan County. Items of value? Absolutely!
</P>
<P>
   When I whined about the sad state of my drought-stricken garden,
Dr. George Patton delivered beets, onions, a cabbage only slightly
smaller than a No. 2 washtub and an offer of lettuce. Webb Mask
showed up with sugar snaps and Vidalia onions he raised himself.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's visit with the sugar snaps reminded me that I'm guilty of
a serious oversight in failing to rank him among our local master
gardeners, along with Dr. Patton, Lester Bray and Johnny Lester.
Perhaps I have associated Webb and his wife too much with getting
me involved in the goat business a few years ago. However, I doubt
anyone can top him in the peach business.
</P>
<P>
   When I stopped by his house on some errand last summer, he made
the offer of a sack of fresh peaches off his backyard trees. When I
reluctantly accepted, he got out a stepladder and placed it under a
tree. Instead of picking peaches as I pick them, he eased the palm
of his hand under each candidate for my sack. If the peach came off
the tree when he lowered his palm, it went into the sack. If not,
it stayed on the tree for more ripening.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what I'll do if he makes his peach offer again this
year, or if Lester (aka Otis(at)Delta) Bray calls about his
fabulous snap beans, which should be about ready.
</P>
<P>
   My only hope is that when I'm hauled before the ethics police I
can get off on grounds of advanced age that qualifies me to be
grandfathered and allowed to play by 1950s rules. When it comes to
fresh vegetables and homemade Brunswick stew I'm clearly on the
take.
</P>
<P>
   To contact Jim Minter, write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, 692 N. Glynn St., Suite A, Fayetteville, GA
30214.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
