<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Back to diet basics
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Americans spend billions of dollars each year
trying to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   The bloated federal government has announced an expensive new
effort to crack down on the proliferation of diet doctors and
weight-loss outfits that promise quick and easy weight loss.
</P>
<P>
   With all this money being thrown around in search of an
effective way to lose weight and keep it off, I felt the time was
right to offer the public my sure-fire weight-loss program.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it's fair to wonder if I know what I'm talking
about.
</P>
<P>
   This is where slick television weight-loss pitchpersons plug in
a testimonial from someone who lost 30 pounds drinking an expensive
diet supplement and following the complicated directions that
accompanied several cases of costly diet drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Besides testimonials, many weight-loss programs that can be
purchased in easy installments tout how their plans were developed
by scientists after extensive research.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I am no scientist. I also haven't done a lick of research
into diets, nutrition or weight loss.
</P>
<P>
   But I have dropped more than 70 pounds in the last six months. I
probably will lose a few more pounds before I reach my optimum
fitness level.
</P>
<P>
   NO-WORRY WEIGHT LOSS
</P>
<P>
   What's more, I haven't tried to lose weight. That's the key to
my sure-fire, weight-loss program. Don't worry about losing weight.
Don't make losing weight a goal. You don't even have to think about
losing weight if you don't want to. Still, the pounds gradually
melt away.
</P>
<P>
   You also don't have to buy a diet book, drink dietary
supplements or even go on an actual diet if you follow my sure-fire
weight-loss program. You don't even have to cut back on your food
intake. Eat as much as you want whenever you get hungry.
</P>
<P>
   My weight-loss program does not include an actual diet that
demands keeping track of calories or regulating the size of meals.
It does, however, include a dietary aspect. I'll come back to this
facet of my weight-loss plan later.
</P>
<P>
   First, let me give away my weight-loss secret that will save you
and other Americans billions of dollars spent each year on
expensive weight-loss programs that don't work. Here it is _ sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that's all there is to it. Sweat. Work out until you break
into a sweat and keep it up for as long as you can stand it.
</P>
<P>
   Do that five or six days a week and you'll lose weight. Keep it
up and you will continue to lose weight. At this point, I'm not
sure where my weight loss will end but I'm guessing somewhere
between 180 and 185 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   About six months ago, I weighed 260 pounds when I went to a
three-day motorcycle riding school in Nevada. That's when I
discovered that riding a motorcycle fast around a race track was
more complicated than a fat guy twisting the throttle.
</P>
<P>
   I came away committed to getting into shape. My goal was to get
fit, to turn fat into muscle. I did not set a goal to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   The key to losing weight, it seems to me, is to not worry about
how much you weigh. Rather than fret over gaining or losing a pound
or two, instead put your energy into workouts designed to get you
into good physical shape.
</P>
<P>
   The way I see it, getting into shape requires more effort than
30-minute walks around the neighborhood, a weekend round of golf or
an occasional tennis match with a friend. Working out means a
sustained investment of sweat equity in your body at least five
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   The diet aspect of my sure-fire weight-loss program is to avoid
food with high sugar and fat content.
</P>
<P>
   There you have it _ a free sure-fire weight loss program.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
