<HEADER>
A5750 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0617-CO     06-16 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Making a concave table _ don't ask
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today's topic will be methods of producing a concave
surface, inspired by a somewhat odd question found on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to create 'sprung' boards for a tabletop project,''
the gentleman writes. ``I tried intentionally sagging the outfeed
table on my jointer and just got lots of dips instead of the
concavity I was expecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it possible to produce a nice concave surface?''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it is, but not this way. Making a concave surface on a
jointer is possible, but tedious and rather uncertain. To start
with, it would be better to drop the infeed table rather than the
outfeed.
</P>
<P>
   I'm dying with curiosity, though. What place do concave boards
have in a table top? Gentlemen, however, don't ask those things.
</P>
<P>
   PLANE IT
</P>
<P>
   If I only wanted one concave board, I'd hand-plane it. If it
needs to be a sharp dip, I'd use a spokeshave, or get a circular
plane, an instrument which has a flexible steel sole that can be
pressed out into a curve shape.
</P>
<P>
   If a long board, a smooth plane would do it.
</P>
<P>
   The concavity would need to be carefully laid out. The simplest
way to do this is to take a piece of scrap at least as long as the
workpiece and saw a very thin slice off the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Use this very flexible strip to mark out the desired concavity
on the edge of the workpiece. Plane down to the line.
</P>
<P>
   If a concave surface made up of multiple boards is wanted, then
I'd go about it differently. I'd make a carriage jig for a plunge
router.
</P>
<P>
   You do this by preparing two guide blocks, each somewhat longer
than the laminated workpiece. Mark the length of the workpiece
centered on one of the guide blocks, and then use that flexible
stick to draw out the concavity on the side of the block.
</P>
<P>
   Tape the blocks together and bandsaw out the curve. These blocks
will be clamped, center to center, on each side of the workpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Now make a carriage for the router. Some routers have holes
through the base for the edge guide; you can use these. It's
difficult to go into great detail on how to do this, especially
without illustration, but the idea is that the carriage allows the
router to be slid from side to side across the workpiece, while
riding forward and backward on the curve of the guide blocks.
</P>
<P>
   This way, taking bites no greater than an eighth of an inch, you
quickly rout a concavity into the entire workpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
