<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, June 17 and Sunday, June 18,
2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Americans spend billions of
dollars each year trying to lose weight. The bloated federal
government has announced an expensive new effort to crack down on
the proliferation of diet doctors and weight-loss outfits that
promise quick and easy weight loss. With all this money being
thrown around in search of an effective way to lose weight and keep
it off, I felt the time was right to offer the public my sure-fire
weight-loss program. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVEDMINTER-COLUMN _ The newspaper business 50
years ago had not progressed much past the horse and buggy. In the
newsroom, rows of teletype machines brought news in from wires
strung all over the world. (MINTER, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVEDMCCARTY-COLUMN _ We all feel outrage when police officers are
second-guessed, even in clear-cut, self-defense cases. We all know
that police must make split-second, life-and-death decisions. Yet,
the controversial Bruce Springsteen song is hardly an Ice-T-style,
anti-police diatribe. It recognizes those complexities in a chorus
that repeats the thoughts that might have run through the officers'
minds. (MCCARTY, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Tom Teepen writes about the 527s,
special-interest political players who raise and spend literally
untold millions secretly and who are named for the tax-code section
that provides the loophole for them. They can retain their
anonymity as long as they pull up just short of directly urging the
election or defeat of a specific candidate. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ If Cuban exiles want to declare war on Fidel
Castro, they should not fight that war in the United States and TV
ads should not be their weapon. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.)
MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ It seems that in every U.S. election
cycle, pundits pluck out a group of voters for in-depth study who
are said to be in flux. In the 1996 race for the White House,
President Clinton was widely seen as winning out with so-called
``soccer moms'' _ shorthand for married middle-class women with
young children seeking to juggle competing demands. This time
around, so-called ``wired workers'' have taken an early lead in the
media contest to see who will emerge as the key group of ``swing
voters.'' (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service in the
Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
