<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCI-HEALTH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   CoxNet HEALTHY LIVING 0613 -- What separates osteopaths from
M.D.'s may the the route they take to their diagnoses. (Lore,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 4-column color
illustration of an M.D. squaring off against an osteopath.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: COMPARISON BOX -- A box showing the similiarities and
differences between osteopaths and M.D.'s.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BACK PAIN RELIEF -- Physical therapy may offer relief for
back-pain sufferers. (Allmon, Waco Tribune-Herald) Art includes a
1-column color photo of a therapist working on a patient's back.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CANCER TREATMENT -- A new treatment for cancer comes close
to achieving that ``magic bullet.'' (Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH NEWS -- A newly published report documents how
cameras at a Atlanta medical center were able to catch mothers
hurting their children in Munchausen's syndrom by proxy.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ON THE WEB -- An association's Web site offers sound
advice on using health-related Web sites. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal
Constitution) Art includes a 6-pica color illustration of a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI-ZOO _ CINCINNATI _ When you're a 2,200-pound
2-year-old, keeping cool on a hot day is a major priority. Ganesh,
his mother and two other Asian elephants are the inhabitants and
main attractions of the new Schott-Unnewehr Vanishing Giants
display at the Cincinnati Zoo and Botanical Garden. And if Ganesh's
reaction when he finally got to enter his pool is any indication,
the elephants love their expanded home. (DAYTON DAILY NEWS). 20.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ ATLANTA _ Today's topic will be
methods of producing a concave surface, inspired by a somewhat odd
question found on the Internet. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-FATHERS _ He's just a guy one day; the next day, he's a
father. It's a miraculous transformation through birth or adoption
that changes a man's identity and outlook forever. We look at the
spiritual dimensions of fatherhood through fathers, and through the
eyes of doctors and nurses who have witnessed families being made.
(GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-MERRITT _ Everybody's somebody in Snellville, as the
saying goes, but the Rev. James Merritt , pastor of Snellville
First Baptist Church is now somebody all across the 15.8 million
member Southern Baptist Convention. Merritt is expected to be
elected Tuesday to head the body for at least the next year. He
follows in the footsteps of Atlantans Charles Stanley and Bailey
Smith in a line of conservative leaders who stretch back two
decades. But Merritt marks a generational change. He's the first
Baby Boomer president of the convention. (Gwhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   PASTOR-GOINGHOME _ After 50 years of distinguished ministry, the
Rev. D.D. Chestang, pastor of Mount Carmel Missionary Baptist
Church, is going home. The energetic Alabama preacher, who has been
a spiritual divining rod for scores of faithful throughout southern
Ohio, will deliver his farewell sermon June 25 in the sanctuary of
his Jefferson Twp. church. (Dayton Daily News). 21. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ-CAMP _ BIRMINGHAM - The neck of his Fender Jazz Bass seems
almost too long for Jason Turner. He squeezes down the note for a
blues arrangment, looking as if he were holding a dance partner too
tall for him. Turner has played bass for just a year. But the
13-year-old has rhthym. During an improve class at the 11th-annual
City Stages summer jazz camp, he is rhythm. With nearly 100 other
summer campers, Turner is learning how to swing. Professional
musicians are training aspiring jazz artists who will perform today
(saturday) at a downtown music festival. You see, this is your
grandmother's jazz. Dixieland. Blues. It's the smoking riffs built
in the Deep South in the early 1900s. This is the stuff of Louis
Armstrong, John Coltrane, Miles Davis, Ella Fitzgerald. This is not
the commercial fluff from, say, Kenny G. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-MOVIES _ The Internet's embrace of movies isn't in the
future. It's right now. At least a dozen Web sites (like
cinemanow.com, mediatrip.com and thenewvenue.com) feature movie
shorts and/or full-length flicks that film fans can watch for free.
For Hollywood studios, ``there's an element of panic,'' says
director Mike Figgis, whose recent ``Time Code'' illustrates
another aspect of filmmaking challenging conventional Hollywood _
digital technology. ``There's a real nervousness because they
regard the technology and the people who come with it like the
rabble at the door of the castle.'' Many see a mad scramble for
``web site territory'' (cinemanow.com, for example, is an arm of
Trimark). (BLonginio, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 16. EMBARGOED
FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   JAZZLAND _ NEW ORLEANS _ Checking out Jazzland theme park, with
six themed sections containing 30 rides, shows, food and music _
all with a Louisiana flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Teases inside to tour story. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 18.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   JAZZTOUR _ NEW ORLEANS _ A long day at Jazzland theme park in
New Orleans: We arrived when the park opened at 10 a.m. and
stumbled out when it closed at 10 p.m. During those 12 hours, we
were drenched on the Spillway Splashdown, scared senseless on the
MegaZeph rollercoaster, tapped our toes to Zydeco music at the
Cajun Dance Hall, chowed down on Creole cuisine, saw the revue
``Jazz, Jazz, Jazz'' twice and tossed beads from the lead float in
the Mardi Gras parade. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 18.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Dozens of shops and galleries line the red-bricked
streets of Waynesville, N.C., where the annual summer Art Studios &AMP;
Gallery Tour will be June 17. Also, coming up in July, is the
annual Folkmoot International Festival which features 10 or 12
troupes from around the world. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SKUBE _ Michael Skube reviews Robert Putnam's ``Bowling
Alone.'' (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-CIRCUS _ Review of Stewart O'Nan's nonfiction ``The Circus
Fire.'' (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 24.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WALKER _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Singer/Songwriter Jerry Jeff
Walker was born and spent his early years in a small upstate New
York town. While still in his teens, he traveled across country
many items, stopping along the way in such diverse places as Key
West, Florida, New Orleans and Greenwich Village, Manhattan. At
each stopover, he learned new songs, new ways to sing them and new
guitar licks to stir into his developing style as a ``songman.''
The songs he wrote as he traveled tell the story of his life and
way of living and making music. Now, he's written this book that
fills in the details. It's a fascinating tale, whether or not you
are a Jerry Jeff fan. (Milner, Lufkin Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-KIDS _ Roundtution) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of
book jacket.
