<HEADER>
A5756 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     06-16 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Friday, June 16, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday or
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ARCHEOLOGY (Keeran Ranch, Texas) _ Rings, musket balls and
charms to ward off the evil eye are gingerly pried from the dark
clay here, as investigators piece together the rugged lives and
deaths of the inhabitants of the first European settlement in
Texas. For one of the few times since a ranch worker armed with a
metal detector found eight buried iron cannons in 1996 _ confirming
the location of the legendary Fort St. Louis _ state officials
permitted outsiders to view its remains. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLINIST-FINGER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Violinist Jill Levy cut her
left hand in a mundane kitchen accident six months ago. After
surgery and therapy and more therapy and, later, therapy, she's
able to play again. By AMY BIANCOLLI. (For release Sunday, June
18.)
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN-RESEARCH (San Antonio) _ Brain researchers used to have to
rely on the cadavers of patients who died with odd brain deficits.
Now they have sophisticated technology and can watch neurons fire
away while the brain performs its duty as the body's command
center. But the science is still its infancy and many mysteries
about the brain remain. By CINDY TUMIEL.
</P>
<P>
   TANKARDS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Tankards are drinking vessels that are
mainly used for consuming beer or ale. Like most decorative
vessels, there are many variations. In the 17th and 18th centuries
some of the tankard handles were whistles that were used to summon
a refill. Tankards were often made from or in the shape of an
animal horn that was meant to be hung from a sword belt. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM HEINS. (For release Sunday, June 18.)
</P>
<P>
   GARAGES (Undated) _ What would most homeowners do without a
garage? This boxy structure not only provides shelter for cars, but
extra storage space for bicycles, the barbecue grill, lawnmower,
snowblower, ski gear, sleds, trash and recycling barrels and, in
some cases, a workbench, snowmobile, seasonal clothing and the
omnipresent basketball backstop. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS. (For
release Sunday, June 18.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-TRIAL (Fresno, Calif.) _ The trial of former motel
handyman Cary Stayner _ charged with killing and beheading Yosemite
naturalist Joie Armstrong _ apparently is on its way Seattle
because of extensive news coverage here. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (Laredo, Texas) _ More than half of the 430 new
Border Patrol agents to be hired nationally this year will be
deployed to South Texas, according to the Immigration and
Naturalization Service. By BONNIE PFISTER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SHAFT (Undated) _ The original Shaft, played with
such splendid unflappability by Richard Roundtree in the 1971 film
by the same name, would have been flummoxed by the current
landscape of complex sexual and racial politics. He would have been
flummoxed, moreover, by the forced jokiness and summer-action
mayhem of this newly released update, which kowtows to movie
stereotypes as much as the first ``Shaft'' changed them. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BOYS (Undated) _ Former television director turned
teensploitationist Robert Iscove is at it again. The maker of
``She's All That'' returns with ``Boys and Girls,'' and he's
brought with him his cottage-cheese-chunky storytelling skills,
patented dance-so-no-one-notices-we're-tanking musical interludes,
and, oh yes, the redoubtable Freddie Prinze Jr. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   DIXIE-CHICKS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ There are a lot of people
who dismiss the Dixie Chicks as a trio of bubble-headed bleached
blondes who have been riding a wave of good looks and hoedown music
to a truckload of music awards, destined to soon fade into
oblivion. And a lot of people are wrong. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   FLIM-REVIEW-SHAKESPEARE (Undated) _ Kennth Branagh has made the
first attempt to meld Shakespeare with old-style Hollywood
musicals. ``Love's Labour's Lost,'' the play, is considered lesser
Shakespeare, a rare romantic comedy. Branagh's adaptation isn't a
masterpiece either, but the writer-director has come up with a
sumptuous, happy piece of fluff. By G. ALLEN JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   KOREAN-BANDS (San Francisco) _ For 17-year-old Anna Jin, the
five-member boy band that gets her feet racing and her heart
thumping is not 'N Sync or the Backstreet Boys. It's H.O.T. The
Korean hip hop group H.O.T. and its musical brethren have grown in
popularity to the point where they compete with American stars for
the hearts of Korean-American youths. By RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-MAZDA-MPV (Undated) _ Mazda, that underrated but
outstanding little Japanese car company controlled by Ford Motor
Co., has gotten serious about the minivan market this year with an
all-new version of its long-running MPV model. The MPV _ that
stands for ``multipurpose vehicle _ has been a best seller during
most of its lifetime. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEPPERS (Albany, N.Y.) _ As much as I hate to admit it, I didn't
know what ``Italian frying peppers'' were when I moved to the
Albany area a year and a half ago. I saw them listed as an
ingredient in a recipe sent to me by ``retired'' area chef Ken
Linden and had to claim ignorance. He educated me. They are
wonderfully sweet, much thinner skinned than the ordinary green
peppers, and do ``fry'' well. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-CRUISES (Undated) _ Carnival Cruise Lines' first-ever
``Vacation Stores,'' opening soon in the Houston and Dallas areas,
are raising eyebrows within the travel industry. Citing research
that indicates Texans take 40 percent fewer cruises than the
national average, Carnival's president is bypassing traditional
travel agencies with what he describes as a ``high-tech,
high-touch, cutting-edge'' marketing approach. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS-EATS (Benton, Ark.) _ Instead of rushing from Point A
to Point B by interstate, why not take time to to celebrate our
nation's beauty, culture, history? Why not linger awhile at Jerry
Van Dyke's Soda Shoppe near the courthouse square in Benton, a
community of 18,000 outside Little Rock. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-DALY (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ After recording 14
strokes on the par-five 18th hole, John Daly signed his scorecard
and then announced he was withdrawing from the tournament. He had
nothing else to say, marching off to the players' locker room,
where he spent about two minutes before bolting for parts unknown.
By MARK FAINARU-WADA.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-SUGAR-MOSLEY (Los Angeles) _ Often there is little beauty in
the beast called boxing. But there is ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley. A
solid citizen and family man, Mosley is more familiar with rap
music than rap sheets. And at 28, he's a big part of the reason why
his showdown with Oscar De La Hoya at L.A.'s Staples Center on
Saturday night could be a classic, not to mention the dose of
credibility the fight game so desperately needs. By JOHN WHISLER.
</P>
</TEXT>
