<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BREAST-CANCER17-COX     06-16 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BREAST CANCER HAUNTS AFRICAN AMERICAN WOMEN
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Marilyn Gaston, the nation's assistant surgeon
general, was 59 when a routine mammogram discovered the beginnings
of cancer in one of her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   It was too early to even feel a lump, she recalled. But knowing
that risks of recurrence increase with age, she elected to have a
surgeon remove both breasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went for the gusto to get a total cure,'' explained Dr.
Gaston. And her diagnosis has been good in the two years since
then.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the medical system is supposed to work _ but how
it too often does not function for African-American women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breast cancer deaths are coming down for other women, but not
for us,'' said Gaston. ``We, as a group, need to take charge and
address this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaston will deliver the keynote speech here Saturday in the
first of a series of national symposiums aimed at educating black
women to their special danger of dying from breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A National Cancer Institute study showed that black women are 12
percent less likely than white women to get breast cancer, but 29
percent more likely to die from the disease. African-American women
are also more likely to be stricken at a younger age. Among women
with breast cancer, blacks are 50 percent more likely than whites
to get the disease before the age of 35 and 50 percent more likely
to die of it before reaching the age of 50.
</P>
<P>
   The symposiums will bring together community activists and
experts on prevention, early detection, surgery and other aspects
of breast cancer and its treatment. The sessions are being
organized by the Breast Cancer Resource Committee, a non-profit
advocacy group for African-American women, and sponsored by
AstraZeneca PLC, manufacturer of the drug tamoxifen, which is used
in treating some breast cancers.
</P>
<P>
   A similar symposium is planned for Atlanta in the fall, said
Zora Brown, president of the Breast Cancer Resource Committee. The
conferences will be held in communities around the country, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 50, co-founded the group with her sister to increase
community awareness after seeing how breast cancer had haunted
their family for four generations. The disease had stricken Zora
Brown, her three sisters, her mother, grandmother, great
grandmother, three great aunts and a niece. The co-founding sister
and niece died from breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put forth a concerted effort to reach
African-American women,'' Brown said. ``And we want to collect data
to understand why more of us are dying. We have a crisis and we
need to take control of it within our own community.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier detection is the key to ending the disparity in breast
cancer deaths between black and white women, said Gaston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no difference in outcome if it's caught in the stage
that it should be,'' she said. ``Our five-year survival rate is not
as good because we're getting it too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Because black women tend to be stricken at an earlier age, they
should begin to get routine mammograms in their 30s rather than
waiting until reaching the currently recommended age of 40 for
baseline screening, said Gaston.
</P>
<P>
   Medical researchers need to reach out to African-American women
to conduct more studies and the women need to overcome reluctance
to participate in the studies, she urged. It could be that the
disease is more progressive within black women and perhaps should
be treated differently, but research is needed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, African American women are uninsured or otherwise cut
off from the sort of health care that detected her own breast
cancer at an early stage, Gaston said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had been seeing the same doctors for 15 years and
``they had all my mammograms,'' so tiny changes were readily
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to mobilize the African-American community'' so all
women get such screening and treatment, she said. ``And each one of
us, on a personal level, needs to take charge our health.''
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.afamerica.com/bcrc/
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
