<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-ARKANSAS-EATS-HNS &LR;      06-16 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARKANSAS-EATS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ARKANSAS SODA SHOP HAS TASTE OF YESTERYEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENTON, Ark. _ I sometimes wonder if America's high-speed
expressways represent a blessing or curse.
</P>
<P>
   Like many road warriors, I find myself rushing from Point A to
Point B, concocting timetables and setting goals as to how soon I
can zip past the next town while adhering to the speed limit. Lunch
break? Will it be McDonald's, Burger King or DQ? And here's
crossing my fingers that the gas station I approach has ``fast
pay'' services at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like the quickest routing from Houston to Branson, Mo.,''
I routinely informed the AAA agent in advance of this trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are beautiful scenic routes through Arkansas,'' the
agent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't afford the time,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as the drive commenced and I began bypassing Lufkin and
Nacogdoches, Texarkana and Hope _ President Clinton's Arkansas
birthplace _ I rethought those words: Can we afford not to take
time to celebrate our nation's beauty, our culture, our history?
Our fellow men and women?
</P>
<P>
   To savor surprises we'd never encounter while speeding down an
Interstate?
</P>
<P>
   So it is that I'm now lingering into a third hour at Jerry Van
Dyke's Soda Shoppe near the courthouse square in Benton, a
community of 18,000 outside of Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   You remember Jerry? No, not brother Dick, the doctoring sleuth
in television's Diagnosis Murder and the former star of the Dick
Van Dyke comedy series with Mary Tyler Moore. Jerry, as in Luther
Van Dam, football's most unlikely defensive coordinator _ and
perpetual clown _ for the Minnesota Screaming Eagles in Coach, a TV
comedy running from the late 1980s and into the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Luther _ whose antics remain on display thanks to reruns _ was a
mess, albeit a fun-loving, good-hearted mess (and a
characterization performed well enough to earn Van Dyke four Emmy
nominations). ``There is a lot of Luther in Jerry, too, and he's
one of the nicest guys you'd ever want to meet,'' says Jeremy
Ricketson, a waiter here when he's not performing at Jerry Van
Dyke's Royal Theater next door.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Van Dyke retired from show business and
purchased a block of property in downtown Benton. His wife,
Shirley, hails from nearby Malvern, where they own a ranch, and he
told the Arkansas Democrat-Gazette at the time, ``I love small
towns, but they're becoming all the same. Everybody goes to the
same fast-food restaurants, the same stores. There's nowhere to
meet people.''
</P>
<P>
   The soda shop and a candy store, which jointly occupy the site
of a former drug store, have become a gathering spot for locals and
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry mentioned the shop during a guest appearance on
Diagnosis Murder, and a lot of people started looking for us,''
says Ricketson.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Dempsey, who now operates the eatery with husband Dan (an
Arkansas Parks and Tourism commissioner), says, ``We had visitors
just yesterday from Anchorage. But we're thrilled, too, that people
who live in Benton like to come here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The establishment is filled with posters and other memorabilia _
including a ``Screaming Eagles'' sweatshirt _ associated with Van
Dyke's television and movie career, but the decor also captures a
Benton of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has helped revive our town and build community spirit,''
says longtime resident Salley Biggs, who points proudly to
photographs on a wall showing her and contemporaries as youths.
``Look at this picture; can you tell that I'm upset?'' Biggs asks,
``It's because I didn't get to sit by my best friend that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Luther's _ er, Jerry's _ fun-loving spirit is evidenced by model
trains circling on tracks just below the ceiling. By a player piano
situated near the front window. By a loud whistle sounded when kids
age 8-to-80 pull two handles. By Coach episodes playing on a TV
above the soda fountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry is a collector of things unusual, and he's had a hand in
everything done here,'' says Dempsey.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry isn't here today. He and Shirley now live much of the time
in Mexico but return frequently to visit their daughter and
grandson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever he's back, he's at the soda shop,'' Ricketson says.
``Sometimes he'll sit outside for hours and greet people. Or he'll
go behind the counter and make sodas. One day he got down on the
floor and played with a little boy and his fire truck. And he sings
and dances with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The townspeople relish Van Dyke's appearances. ``We were having
lunch one day, and he just sat down and joined us,'' Benton
resident Marvalene James says.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs says, ``I ordered something, and he said, `You don't want
that today. Let me go fix you something special.' '' The food alone
_ touted as ``Luther tested, Dauber approved'' _ is worth exiting
I-30 (or making a 30-minute side trip from Hot Springs). The
``Coach Fox'' burger basket and ``Christine'' patty melt are
monstrous proportions. Dempsey's homemade broccoli-and-cheese soup
is delectable.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, those sodas and shakes _ five flavors, seven toppings,
everything made the old-fashioned way _ and peach cobbler.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad that my brief visit doesn't coincide with one of eight
or nine live performances scheduled each year at Van Dyke's
theater. ``Two groups put on shows: the Jerry Van Dyke Studios and
Central Arkansas Community Players,'' says Ricketson. ``Some
productions last up to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets only cost about $10, or half that for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when we did Grease, Jerry volunteered for a cameo
as a Teen Angel. We never knew what he'd do next on stage. He had
us laughing so hard we almost couldn't continue.''
</P>
<P>
   If only I could stay all afternoon. ``Here, take some candy for
the road,'' Dempsey says. ``We keep it affordable _ 25 pieces of
bubble gum for $1.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do here is bring back good memories, to
help people feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   I feel good. And I'm reassured that there are other delightful
small towns worth leisurely exploration along my route.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, I'm well behind my timetable. The Interstate beckons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jerry Van Dyke's Soda Shoppe is located at 117 South Market
St., about a half mile from I-30. Hours are 11 a.m.-9 p.m.. Call
501-860-5500. Call that number or 501-778-3456 for theater
information. Another Jerry Van Dyke's Soda Shoppe is located in
Flower Mound, Texas.)
</P>
</TEXT>
