<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5780 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TEXAS-CRUISES-HNS &LR;      06-16 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CRUISES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CRUISE LINE TRIES TO LURE TEXAS LANDLUBBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They will cover only 130 square feet in vast shopping malls.
``Retail islands,'' promoters dub them. Fancy booths.
</P>
<P>
   But Carnival Cruise Lines' first-ever ``Vacation Stores,''
opening soon in the Houston and Dallas areas, are raising eyebrows
within the travel industry.
</P>
<P>
   Citing research that indicates Texans take 40 percent fewer
cruises than the national average, Carnival president Bob Dickinson
is _ one or more answers allowed _ (A) supplementing, (B) prodding,
(C) assisting or (D) bypassing traditional travel agencies with
what he describes as a ``high-tech, high-touch, cutting-edge''
marketing approach.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Soon you can find Inspiration, Fascination,
Ecstasy, Paradise and Destiny in a mall. You can book a cruise,
too, on these or any other Carnival ships _ including the
Celebration, which begins 4- and 5-night sailings from Galveston on
Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The first Carnival Vacation Store opens this month in Arlington.
A second outlet debuts in August at The Woodlands shopping mall in
the Houston area. Each will sell only Carnival cruises, even though
the line is allied with Holland America, Cunard, Seabourn, Costa
and Windstar.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival sales personnel will staff the stores during regular
mall hours, including evenings and weekends _ periods when most
travel agencies are closed but when, Dickinson suggests, families
are most apt to consider (and shop for) vacation alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Is this direct-to-the-consumer marketing approach yet another
blow to travel agents, who already are at war with airlines over
commission cuts and online marketing ploys? With rare exceptions,
cruise lines have remained dedicated to _ and dependent on _
agencies in selling their product. Is Carnival, the world's largest
line, radically altering its strategy? Just the opposite, insists
Dickinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``No agent should be scared of this,'' he says. ``The irony is
that if we went into Houston and said we're going to spend $360,000
on advertising our product, agents would kiss us. This is no
different: We're spending $360,000 on a three-dimensional promotion
for cruise vacations.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Dickinson says that spurring agency business is a prime
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to generate $1.5 million to $2 million in annual sales
at each Vacation Store,'' Dickinson says. ``But we expect to
generate 5-to-10 times that amount with incremental sales through
travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five percent of our business is through travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our ideas is to offer people a coupon for a credit
toward shipboard expenses, and they could take it to their travel
agent for processing.''
</P>
<P>
   Houstonian Joe Galloway, president of the American Society of
Travel Agents (ASTA) and owner of Trans-Continental Travel in the
Galleria area, says he welcomes any endeavor that promotes
cruising.
</P>
<P>
   ``From ASTA's standpoint, we've never been concerned with people
buying directly, as long as we have a level playing field,''
Galloway says. ``And Bob Dickinson has assured us that they will
not be undercutting our prices at their stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't know how many people will buy something as
expensive as a cruise on a Saturday night,'' Galloway says. ``My
agency once had a mall location and found that people weren't
interested in buying travel there. Maybe that's changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway has concerns, too, about potential Carnival Vacation
Store customers understanding the huge variety of cruise products
in today's marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson has broached the concept of brand outlets for some
time, but he first envisioned travel agents operating the stores.
Agents could better serve consumers, he reasoned, by focusing their
expertise and sales on select cruise lines _ even on one line. In
theory, one existing agency would serve as a Carnival store,
another as a Royal Caribbean store and so on.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't happened, for good reason, according to Galloway.
Although many agencies establish relationships with what they refer
to as ``preferred suppliers,'' Galloway says, ``The strength of a
travel agency is that it's not a brand store. A good agent should
be working for the customer, not one company.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Carnival cruise may be ideal for one person but wrong for
another.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, there are a lot of questions that should be asked. A
travel agent can talk one-on-one with a customer and fit the
product to his or her needs.''
</P>
<P>
   One intriguing aspect of the Vacation Store concept _ ``old dog,
new tricks,'' Dickinson labels this adaptation of his original idea
_ is that Carnival plans to offer ``internships'' to travel agents
who want training in marketing the line's cruises. ``They will be
able to sell Carnival cruises at our store, and the agency will get
credit,'' Dickinson says.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what will happen, though, when a consumer asks a travel
agent _ not a Carnival employee _ at a mall store, ``How do you
compare Carnival Destiny with Royal Caribbean's Voyager of the
Seas, the Grand Princess and Norwegian Sky?'' Will the travel agent
speak the Carnival party line or provide the unbiased evaluation
expected at an agency? A conflict of interest seems inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   I'll also be interested to see _ as will travel agents _ if
Carnival initiates a trend. Will we soon shop at Royal Caribbean,
Princess and Norwegian cruise outlets?
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson cites two main reasons for placing the first two mall
stores in Texas (with a third planned for Illinois). ``One is that
Texas, for reasons I'm not really sure, generally underperforms the
rest of the nation (in cruise purchases). The other is that we're
bringing the Celebration to Galveston.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson describes early bookings for the Celebration _
primarily through travel agents _ as ``tremendous. Texas is a
sleeping giant. The growth potential here is enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   He's banking that a retail island will spur that growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1208EDT &QL; 
