<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5782 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-BRAIN-RESEARCH-HNS &LR;      06-16 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-RESEARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCHERS TRY TO CRACK MYSTERIES OF THE BRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ On a projector screen inside the darkened
Municipal Auditorium here, identical images of actor Harrison Ford
flashed side by side.
</P>
<P>
   But the two pictures weren't really identical. One captured the
true Hollywood hero, with his classic chiseled jaw, strong brow
line and serious demeanor. The other picture was subtly different.
Computer magic had softened Ford's brow, rounded that sturdy chin
and puffed his lips a tad.
</P>
<P>
   David Perrett, a professor of psychology from the University of
St. Andrews in Scotland, posed a question to the audience: Which
Harrison Ford would you be more likely to loan money to?
</P>
<P>
   The chairs were filled with some of the world's foremost brain
researchers, but they readily played along with the psychology
experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly, the ``feminized'' Ford was judged more
trustworthy and got a thumbs-up for a loan _ if the millionaire
actor ever really needs to borrow a few bucks from a bunch of
brainy professors.
</P>
<P>
   But the test demonstrated one point in a growing body of
fascinating findings about the human brain _ that it perceives
personality traits as it views faces.
</P>
<P>
   Protruding jaw lines and thinner lips are masculine traits and
often are perceived as signs of strength, emotional coldness and
untrustworthiness. Feminine faces are softer and often are equated
with honesty and warmth, whether or not that really is the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to realize that complex social behavior can
rely on very discrete neural systems,'' said Perrett, the keynote
speaker this week at a conference of brain scientists. ``Where they
are and how they work is intensely interesting for neuroscientists,
and the public, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrett is one of 1,200 scientists in San Antonio for the
Organization for Human Brain Mapping annual meeting, which
concluded Friday. The researchers came from 29 different countries
to talk about their latest explorations into the mysterious world
of human brains.
</P>
<P>
   Brain researchers used to have to rely on the cadavers of
patients who died with odd brain deficits. Now they have
sophisticated technology, combining magnetic resonance imaging and
high-powered computers, and can watch neurons fire away while the
brain performs its duty as the body's command center.
</P>
<P>
   The volume of research has increased exponentially in the past
decade, but it still is considered a science in its infancy, said
Dr. Peter Fox, director of the Research Imaging Center at the
University of Texas Health Science Center, the conference host.
</P>
<P>
   So far, brain mapping scientists have found 3,000 to 5,000
functional areas on the surface of the brain, and they are
exploring how these areas connect with inner brain structures.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have begun to grasp how normal brains act, Fox said,
and are exploring abnormalities as varied as genetic birth defects,
learning disorders and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a systems-level approach,'' Fox said. ``We want to
understand what areas of the brain do, how they interact normally
and how they interact when abnormalities are present.''
</P>
<P>
   In Perrett's laboratory, the imaging technology is being used to
understand just how much is involved in the perception of a face.
The brain's complex circuitry detects features, recognizes familiar
faces, and imbues personality traits in fleeting milliseconds, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do so many things with faces,'' Perrett said. ``We can
recognize faces; we can recognize emotion. These are all different
systems in the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Cindy Tumiel by e-mail at ctumiel(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
