<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-SHAFT-HNS     06-16 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SHAFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW `SHAFT' DOESN'T LIVE UP TO THE ORIGINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all know Shaft. He's the stone-cool guy in the turtleneck and
snappy leather coat. He's the man who can amble, unfazed by any
little thing like mortal peril, through bustling Manhattan traffic
without getting scratched. He's _ what did Isaac Hayes call him? _
the black private dick who's the sex machine to all the chicks.
</P>
<P>
   Sex machine: Now there's a term that went out with streaking.
You don't hear that used much any longer, unless it's meant to
describe some new, post-Viagral bio-mechanical device devised by
Harvard researchers. The original Shaft, played with such splendid
unflappability by Richard Roundtree in the 1971 film by the same
name, would have been flummoxed by the current landscape of complex
sexual and racial politics.
</P>
<P>
   He would have been flummoxed, moreover, by the forced jokiness
and summer-action mayhem of this newly released update, which
kowtows to movie stereotypes as much as the first ``Shaft'' changed
them.
</P>
<P>
   This new ``Shaft'' was directed by John Singleton, who has built
his career from insightful, in-your-face talk-ups of race relations
in America. It stars Samuel L. Jackson (as John Shaft the Younger,
nephew to John Shaft the Elder, played in a few brief scenes by
Roundtree), for whom ``in your face'' is a vaunted art form. The
resulting collaboration lacks any and all subtlety _ the
all-encompassing coolness of the original _ and winds up portraying
this iconic black figure as a renegade hothead. It's not Shaft;
it's Mel Gibson, freaking his way through a ``Lethal Weapon''
sequel.
</P>
<P>
   If you remember anything about the original ``Shaft,'' remember
this: Despite touches of humor, it was a deadly serious
undertaking. It was a film about the brothers taking care of
things, about a private detective and a crew of rag-tag black-power
activists rescuing a dope king's daughter from the clutches of the
Mafia. Later classed as ``blaxploitation'' (along with ``Superfly''
and its kin), ``Shaft'' was actually about empowerment _ about
African-American heroes attacking the heart of urban lawlessness.
Police were on the periphery. Whites were on the periphery. Only
blacks were at the center of things, making do for each other.
</P>
<P>
   In the new ``Shaft,'' the race lines aren't gone; they're
exaggerated. Shaft is now a New York cop with a mercurial
disposition and a wink-wink way with the ladies _ though we never
actually see him getting naked with chicks, perhaps indicating some
rusty gears on the part of El Machine. In any case, Shaft's hackles
are raised when a yuppie scumbag (Christian Bale, who played a
similar yuppie scumbag in ``American Psycho'') cracks the skull of
an African-American guy outside a tres-hip downtown club.
</P>
<P>
   The yuppie scumbag, who does double duty as a dirty racist pig,
jumps bail and phones Shaft from Switzerland, which of course
raises Shaft's hackles even higher. When the
yuppie-scumbag-dirty-racist-pig returns to the States two years
later, Shaft arrests him a second time and then watches, hackles
raised to nosebleed, as a judge lets the bail-jumper out on bail
again. But not before the YSDRP hooks up with a jailed Latino pot
dealer (Jeffrey Wright), who has a grudge against Shaft, who might
or might not be able to help the YSDRP in his quest to eliminate
the murder's one witness, who's played by Toni Collette in a
criminal waste of talent. Busta Rhymes plays Shaft's a rasta
sidekick; Vanessa Williams and Dan Hedaya play cops.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. True to its action-movie aspirations, the script
(by Singleton, the usually trustworthy Richard Price and Shane
Salerno, who contributed to ``Armageddon'') is a bullet-riddled
quilt of arch one-liners and hyper-edited bloodbaths, none of them
compelling as drama. This ``Shaft'' is more violent than the
original; its humor is more contrived; its limning of racist
attitudes is much more simplistic. It also makes less sense: At no
point does anyone think to test the murder weapon for fingerprints
or the murderer for blood traces (d'oh).
</P>
<P>
   As for Jackson, he's no suave gumshoe. Despite Armani
turtlenecks and a broad repertoire of scowls, he lacks the
imperturbable poise of Roundtree's proto-Shaft. He's best, and the
film is best, at the very beginning, as Isaac Hayes' mellow theme
song comes rolling over the soundtrack. David Arnold's score rides
that '70s wave to great effect for the next 100 minutes, but the
movie itself never finds the same groove: It never gives us the
black private dick in all his funky calm. The funk isn't there any
longer, or the calm. Just the dick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
