<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5795 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-FAIRCHILD-CAMILLA-PAR     06-16 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-CAMILLA-PARKER-BOWLES-UPDATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE LIVES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 By JAMES FALLON  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Camilla Parker Bowles is playing it safe.
</P>
<P>
   The mistress of Prince Charles was expected to adopt a higher
profile following the couple's first public appearance together in
London in January 1999, and her much-publicized trip last fall to
New York, where she was feted by everyone from Brooke Astor to her
favorite decorator. Social queens were all prepared to turn Parker
Bowles and the heir to the British throne into the next hot couple
on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Well, forget it. The Prince of Wales and Parker Bowles are
continuing with the same low-key approach they adopted when they
renewed their affair 13 years ago. They're seen in public more
often and are regularly photographed by the paparazzi at the
theater or opera, two of their many mutual passions. But they
aren't about to become the next Duke and Duchess of Windsor,
grabbing social invitations wherever possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things haven't changed that much, because I don't think they
want them to change much,'' one acquaintance says, as always
insisting on anonymity. ``I don't think Camilla wants to be out on
the party circuit every night. That doesn't interest her.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the couple is aware that the mere mention of the
name Camilla still generates antagonism among a large section of
the British public.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year she was voted the person the British would
least like to spend Valentine's Day with _ along with William
Hague, the balding, shrill leader of the Conservative party.
</P>
<P>
   Unfair as it may be, Parker Bowles still gets blamed for the
breakup of the fairy-tale romance between Prince Charles and Diana,
Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and observers insist that for this reason it's unlikely
Charles, 50, and Parker Bowles, 53, will ever marry. No matter,
they essentially live together like husband and wife already.
</P>
<P>
   Parker Bowles, who doesn't bother to keep a place of her own in
London, stays at Charles' apartments in St. James's Palace, except
in hunting season, when she spends more time in the country to ride
with the Beaufort Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   If Charles has an official evening engagement in London, Parker
Bowles will invite friends to the palace for dinner or go to their
homes. Her grown children, Laura and Tom, also pop into the palace
to see their mom.
</P>
<P>
   The couple spends most weekends at Charles' Highgrove estate,
where Camilla is the undisputed hostess. She now spends little time
at her own country house, Ray Mill, 16 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Their friends remain the same as always, including the Edward
van Cutsems, the Earl and Countess of Shelburne, actor Stephen Fry
and antiques dealer Piers von Westenholz and his wife, Jane, with
whom Charles and his sons, William and Harry, recently went skiing
in Klosters, Switzerland (along with the von Westenholzes' two
beautiful teen-age daughters, Violet and Victoria).
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles and Camilla live the life they always have and the
same one as their peers _ shooting weekends, fishing weekends,
holidays structured around the school term and friends to dinner,''
a friend says. ``It's a very low-key lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike with Diana, whose every step was chronicled ad infinitum,
little of Parker Bowles' comings and goings is actually known. She
and Charles didn't go on vacation together publicly until last
summer, when they took their children on a Greek Islands cruise,
although they'd had other, more private holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Parker Bowles regularly sees Charles' sons in the privacy of the
palace or Highgrove but has rarely been seen with them away from
home. One of the most recent times was when Harry watched her ride
with the Beaufort Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been absorbed into the family,'' a friend says. ``When
Charles and the boys are at Highgrove, or the boys are at home in
London, it's the four of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the low profile, Parker Bowles is hardly oblivious to
her public image. She and Charles are much more open about their
relationship among even casual acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more telling, Parker Bowles has become much more
conscious of her appearance, now favoring Valentino and Antony
Price, chic shoes with two-inch heels, the ubiquitous pashmina or
scarf and simple diamond jewelry, some of it presents from Charles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She dresses like what she is _ an affluent, well-bred,
middle-aged Englishwoman who is expected to look smart, not
fashionable,'' a friend says.
</P>
<P>
   But big questions remain. When will Parker Bowles, Charles and
the boys be seen in public as one big happy family? Will she be
invited to the Queen Mother's 100th birthday celebration in August?
And when will she be photographed with the Queen?
</P>
<P>
   Many speculate that William's 18th birthday on June 21 _ Charles
is hosting a dinner before William gets to go off with his friends
for a wilder bash _ might provide an opportunity for the young
future king and his father's paramour to be photographed together.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Queen Mother's party, observers say there's a 50-50
chance Parker Bowles will attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that Camilla decides to go on holiday with her
children,'' a friend says. ``But she could be invited. The Queen
Mother has seen her on numerous occasions. The Queen Mother dotes
on Charles.''
</P>
<P>
   The British press plays up the fact that the Queen continues to
refuse to receive Parker Bowles. But friends laugh off those
reports, slyly saying that no one really knows what the Queen does
in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Queen has known Camilla for over 30 years,'' one says.
``It's perfectly possible that she goes to see Charles at Highgrove
and Camilla is there. No one would know.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, friends say, it doesn't matter whether the Queen
ever formally recognizes Parker Bowles' role in her eldest son's
life. The Prince and Parker Bowles are a couple, period.
</P>
<P>
   They no longer skulk about and, most important, they're no
longer desperately seeking public approval of their union.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the feeling that they've done what they can to make
people view them as normally as possible,'' a friend says. ``Now
they're just going to let things take their course.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (James Fallon is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5796 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l BC-FAIRCHILD-CAMILLA-PAR     06-16 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-CAMILLA-PARKER-BOWLES-UPDATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE LIVES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 By JAMES FALLON  
