<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BORDER PATROL TO SEND MORE AGENTS TO SOUTH TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE PFISTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ The government plans to deploy more than half of
the 430 new Border Patrol agents to be hired nationally this year
in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service announced it will
place 100 new agents in McAllen, 95 in Del Rio and 45 in Laredo
before Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Ten new agents also will be sent to El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Garza, sector chief in McAllen, said he was pleased by the
reinforcements, which will bring to nearly 1,400 the number of
agents on patrol along 280-mile stretch of the border between South
Padre Island and Falcon Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Staffing in Garza's sector has nearly tripled since 1994, while
at the same time apprehensions have dropped to 140,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Del Rio will see a 14 percent increase in its agents, to 792.
</P>
<P>
   John Montoya, the Laredo sector chief, said he was disappointed
with getting just 45 new hires, a 6 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya said concentrations of agents in the Lower Rio Grande
Valley have forced changes in immigration patterns and have pushed
attempted crossings in the Laredo sector up 17 percent in the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   In the same period, apprehensions in the McAllen sector dropped
by a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate that the resources sent to McAllen and Del Rio
will incur more attempted crossings in Laredo,'' Montoya said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said Thursday through an aide that
while every new agent is welcome, 430 are too few.
</P>
<P>
   Congress funded the hiring of 1,000 new Border Patrol agents in
2000, as it did in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   However, the agency hired only 370 agents last year. Even with a
$2,000 signing bonus, the agency can't attract enough qualified
prospects. Montoya cited the low U.S. unemployment rate as the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith aide Allen Kay said the INS lacks the political will
to hire enough field agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They managed to fill their full complement of citizenship
processors last year, despite the tight labor market,'' Kay said.
``When they want to hire people, they find a way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
