<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BOX-SUGAR-MOSLEY-HNS &LR;      06-16 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-SUGAR-MOSLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIGHT SHOWCASES ROLE MODELS OF BOXING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN WHISLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They call him Sugar for the sweetness in his
style, like Sugar Ray Robinson and Sugar Ray Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   And there seems a genuine goodness and civility that shines
through.
</P>
<P>
   Often there is little beauty in the beast called boxing. But
there is ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   A solid citizen and family man, Mosley is more familiar with rap
music than rap sheets. And at only 28, he's a big part of the
reason why his showdown with Oscar De La Hoya at Staples Center in
Los Angeles on Saturday night could be a classic, not to mention
the dose of credibility the fight game so desperately needs.
</P>
<P>
   For, in the City of Angels, Mosley and De La Hoya are as close
to heaven as boxing gets.
</P>
<P>
   Good in the ring. Maybe even better out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both fighters are very respectful, even of each other,''
promoter Bob Arum said. ``Oscar and Shane are both legitimate role
models who deserve to have young people look up to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that boxing doesn't have to be thuggery and insults
and bad behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But also in boxing, that often is what sells, even if it isn't
always authentic. Fighters usually are told to snarl at the camera
and talk a little trash to help hawk a few tickets.
</P>
<P>
   This fight so far has seen none of that. And it doesn't appear
to have hurt at all. It is expected to be the richest fight in
California history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't create havoc or have any real adversity in my life,''
Mosley said. ``This sport needs success stories, and I feel I am
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Successful, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known, no.
</P>
<P>
   At 34-0 with 32 knockouts, Mosley has one of the highest
knockout ratios of all time. His mix of speed, skill and passion
often invoke comparisons to Robinson and Leonard. But there is
substance behind the style.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he held a 2 1/2-year reign as International Boxing
Federation lightweight champion. He beat Philip Holiday on Aug. 2,
1997, to gain the title, then made eight successful defenses before
moving up 12 pounds and two weight classes to welterweight.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other than in the neighborhood in which he grew up in
Pomona, a suburb of Los Angeles, no one has really ever heard of
him.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike De La Hoya, Mosley is anything but a household name to
the casual fan.
</P>
<P>
   Had he won an Olympic gold medal as De La Hoya did, things might
have been different. He was a three-time national amateur champion,
but a loss to Vernon Forrest cost him a spot on the 1992 U.S.
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, on the other hand, won gold that same year and
riches followed immediately.
</P>
<P>
   For Mosley, the rise to the top has been much slower. In his
first four years as a pro, Mosley went 21-0 with 20 KOs, yet earned
a total of $65,000. De La Hoya loses more than that in his sofa
cushions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Mosley fought at the Pond in Anaheim in front of 504
paying customers. Just last year, he headlined a card at the Hard
Rock Hotel &AMP; Casino against Willie Wise that drew a crowd of 1,400.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mosley maintains there never were hard feelings toward De
La Hoya, who is from neighboring East L.A. and was a frequent
sparring partner of Mosley's growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jealousy is a sickness,'' Mosley said. ``I'm grateful for what
I've gotten. Oscar's got what he's got because he earned it. I
think things not coming so easy for me has made me more
appreciative of what it took to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, his opportunity has arrived. A sellout crowd of 20,000
is expected Saturday night when he meets De La Hoya at the Staples
Center. Mosley is expected to earn $4.5 million for the fight _
more than all 34 of his previous fights combined.
</P>
<P>
   Add possible pay-per-view revenues, and Mosley could see an $8
million payday. Coupled with a new, multiyear contract with HBO,
Mosley is set for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the hype and money is nice,'' said Mosley, who is the
single father of a 6-year-old son. ``But I could push all that
aside and still have family. That's what's important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Contact John Whisler by e-mail at
jwhisler(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
