<HEADER>
A5812 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TANKARDS-$ADV18-HNS &LR;      06-16 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANKARDS-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TANKARDS: THE DRINKING VESSEL OF CHOICE IN YESTERYEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, June 18)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Tankards are drinking vessels that are mainly
used for consuming beer or ale. Shaped like oversized coffee mugs,
they were popular in northern Europe, Scandinavia, Germany, the
British Isles and in Colonial America from the second half of the
16th century.
</P>
<P>
   The body of a tankard is cylindrical, with a hinged lid (making
it different from a stein, which is open on top) that's often
topped with a finial. The scroll-shaped handle sports a thumbpiece
on top.
</P>
<P>
   Like most decorative vessels, there are many variations. In the
17th and 18th centuries some of the tankard handles were whistles
that were used to summon a refill. Tankards were often made from or
in the shape of an animal horn that was meant to be hung from a
sword belt.
</P>
<P>
   Tankards have been made from horn, porcelain, pottery, carved
ivory and wooden staves hooped together, and precious metals
including pewter and silver. They are also made from a combination
of materials such as glass and silver or pewter and leather (waxed
or varnished to keep the hide from absorbing moisture).
</P>
<P>
   The term tankard originally applied only to a vessel holding
three gallons of liquid. By the 18th century, the term was also
used to signify a small, healthy-sized drink container with a lid,
which is how the term ``getting tanked up'' came about.
</P>
<P>
   Tankards vary in shape from 12 ounces to 36 ounces or more. Some
of the very large tankards were used as jugs.
</P>
<P>
   Antique tankards will often have dings or dents in them, from
centuries of merrymaking and toasts. It was common to clank
tankards together and slam them down on the bar or table. It was
easy to be rowdy with them because the closed lid kept the beverage
contained.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 17th century, tankards (usually large ones) were
commissioned by guilds or businesses for presentation or ceremonial
use.
</P>
<P>
   Reproductions of traditional tankard styles date from the 17th
century and continue to be reproduced.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two decades ago, Christie's auction house sold an
18th-century pewter tankard for a record-breaking price of $15,000.
Prices vary with material, style, age and condition, but a new
polished pewter tankard should cost $28 to $100 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they are often inscribed with initials, a date or decal
to commemorate a special occasion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
