<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5832 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOREA-EUPHORIA-BOS &LR;      06-16 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-EUPHORIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES FOR PEACE ON KOREAN PENINSULA SOAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The leaders of North and South Korea ended their
first summit Thursday as tens of millions of captivated Asians
watched on live television and saluted what many saw as a historic
step toward peace for the volatile Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   After a sendoff featuring hysterical cheers from half a million
flower-waving North Koreans, a military brass band, and a warm hug
from his longtime nemesis, Kim Jong Il, South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung returned home to an equally ecstatic hero's welcome on the
streets of Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   More than any event in the 55 years since Korea split into the
capitalist south and the communist north, the summit raised hopes
of eventual reunification to a fever-pitch on both sides of the
world's most militarized border, and across Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest event of our history,'' Kim Dae-jung
declared before thousands of emotional, flag-waving South Koreans
Thursday. ``The people of the whole world want our cooperation and
reunification. . . . If we fail, the disappointment of the world
will be great. If we succeed, the great benefit we can expect will
be enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   The aura of good feeling was reinforced by word that Washington,
in a dramatic turnaround, was poised to lift economic sanctions it
imposed on North Korea half a century ago when Pyongyang invaded
the south.
</P>
<P>
   Lifting sanctions would be the logical culmination of
Washington's rocky attempts to engage Pyongyang in recent years,
and could be a reward for the North's keeping its promise a year
ago to suspend missile tests, analysts said. The timing of the
announcement, expected Monday, seemed calculated both to avoid
upstaging the North-South dialogue and to ensure first that the
summit produced positive results.
</P>
<P>
   But almost nothing could have upstaged the astonishing scene
Thursday of the leaders of the two longtime enemy states, hands
clasped, singing a patriotic hymn and posing for photos like
long-lost brothers. In South Korea, experts and common people alike
found reason to believe that the move toward reconciliation would
succeed where earlier attempts had failed.
</P>
<P>
   The summit has tremendous implications for a peninsula long
regarded as a dangerous nuclear flashpoint, as well as for the
security of Asia as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of eventually dismantling of the world's last Cold
War frontier raises obvious questions about America's future
strategic role in the Pacific and could have a dramatic impact on
proposals in Washington to develop a missile defense shield against
potential rogue states _ notably, North Korea. The United States
has 37,000 troops in South Korea to protect its ally from
aggression by a neighbor that boasts a million-man army, a
long-range missile program, and an alleged record of
state-sponsored terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul is almost certain to continue its tight military alliance
with the US. But Kim Changsu, director of US military studies at
the Korea Institute for Defense Analyses, warned that summit
euphoria could also evolve into anti-Americanism and protests
against US forces stationed on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ``For five to 10 years, as we approach the final stage of
reunification, we need safeguards, and US troops give that,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Even skeptical North Korea watchers in Seoul joined politicians,
diplomats, and common people in hailing the five-point agreement.
But as with any broad agreement full of niceties between longtime
enemies, the devil will be in the details _ and in the
implementation.
</P>
<P>
   Just last year, the world rejoiced as rival neighbors India and
Pakistan signed a declaration of detente and cooperation in Lahore,
Pakistan _ a document that was became obsolete three months later
when Pakistan-backed insurgents set off a limited war in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the Korean accord to that debacle, Han Seung-soo, a
former South Korean ambassador to Washington, conceded that ``a
small incident somewhere along the DMZ (Korea's de-militarized
zone) could derail the whole process.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet unlike North/South agreements in 1972 and 1991 that failed
to produce enduring results, the new declaration is the first
signed by the top leaders on each side, making this deal much more
likely to be implemented, observers said. As supreme leader of the
world's last Stalinist state, Kim Jong-il's ``word is final, and
once he decides something, it has to be carried out,'' said Park
Young-ho, senior fellow at the government-funded Korea Institute
for National Reunification in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, North Korea needs rapprochment more than ever _ or at
least the aid and trade that would come with it. Even those who
distrust the North say an economic boost through ties with the
South is the only way for Kim Jong-il to preserve his regime. The
North's factory-based command economy _ once light-years ahead of
the South's and the envy of many third-world nations _ is now
obsolete and paralyzed. Aid workers estimate that famine has
claimed 2 million lives in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can buy peace, I welcome that,'' said Cho Woong-kyu, a
national assemblyman from South Korea's opposition Grand National
Party, who fled south when war broke out 50 years ago. ``Kim
Jong-il needs assistance from us, and he and Kim Dae-jung could win
the Nobel Peace Prize if this works.''
</P>
<P>
   The summit document called for eventual reunification by
``independent'' means, cross-border visits by relatives long
separated by war, economic cooperation, a resolution of the fate of
political prisoners, and a return visit to the South by Kim
Jong-il.
</P>
<P>
   One element that the summit agreement did not address was
weapons and defense, a thorny issue between two
intensely-suspicious neighbor states that never signed a peace
treaty after a truce ended the Korean War in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   But Kim said Thursday he had had ``fruitful discussions and . .
. saw great hope'' on the sensitive issues of nuclear weapons and
missile testing.
</P>
<P>
   Defense and security issues are likely to be the last resolved
on any road to reunion, along with the question of what kind of a
political system a unified Korea would have.
</P>
<P>
   For the South, the cost of absorbing and resucitating the
economy of its communist brother _ estimated at $1 trillion _ is
bound to be another worry, especially with the vivid example of
Germany's problems since reunification.
</P>
<P>
   But from the halls of power to the streets, it escaped no one
Thursday that the ultimate payoff of peace in Korea would be a more
stable Asia. China said it ``heartily rejoices'' at the summit's
success, and Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori compared the
agreement to the fall of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously things could go bad. (But) I don't think that's
likely,'' said one foreign diplomat in Seoul. And ``if it does
collapse, we wouldn't be any worse off than we were before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5835 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SYRIA-ASSAD-BOS &LR;      06-16 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-ASSAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRIA POWER ELITE POSES PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QORDAHA, Syria _ Hafez Assad was born in a stone house in this
mountain village, and he came of age amid the hard, rural life of
the minority Alawite community that would help keep him in power
for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three days, Assad's son, Bashar, has greeted
throngs of mourners who have climbed the hills to the family
village, both to express condolences for the Syrian president's
death last Saturday and to pay political homage to the 34-year-old
heir to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But this weekend, when Bashar descends from this mountain to
begin the process of accepting leadership of Syria's ruling Ba'ath
Party, diplomats and analysts wonder how long the Alawite community
can hold power in a land dominated by Sunni Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Bashar Assad's transition to power appears to
be ``very smooth and very well-scripted,'' said one veteran
diplomat in the region.
</P>
<P>
   But if he continues an aggressive campaign to root out
corruption among the Alawite military elite and a tight circle of
businessmen, he runs the risk of alienating those he needs to hold
on to power.
</P>
<P>
   And if he fails to go after this elite circle, he runs the risk
of losing the popular support he appears to be inheriting.
</P>
<P>
   The Alawite, which represent about 12 percent of Syria's 17
million people, are considered to be an offshoot of Shiite Islam.
Among Syria's elaborate mosaic of different faiths and ethnic
groups, the largest is the Sunni Muslims, who make up more than 70
percent of Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   The Alawite incorporate elements of Judaism, Christianity and
Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Mohammed Bad'r, one of the Alawite clerics at Qordaha's
Naisa Mosque, which is named for Assad's mother, said, ``We believe
all of the messages of Moses, Jesus, and Mohammed come together in
one essence.'' Asked how a small minority could maintain power,
Bad'r replied, ``The brain is a small part of the body.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand Hafez Assad's rule it is necessary to understand
his Alawite background, and how adherents to the faith emerged from
poverty and persecution to become Syria's leaders. Most followed a
path through the military to rise, as did Assad, a general and
defense minister before taking power in a 1970 coup.
</P>
<P>
   The Alawite elite that surrounded Assad until his death were and
still are in control of the Army, the secret police, and the
Republican Guard, which virtually precludes a coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Alawite control, though, Assad was not a sectarian, and
throughout his tenure Sunni Muslims often held positions as defense
minister, prime minister, and foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   But according to a biography of Assad by Patrick Seale, the
Alawite made up ``the security bedrock of the regime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He depended on his own community for security of tenure and
ultimate survival,'' Seale wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Riad Seif, an opposition politician and Sunni Muslim merchant,
said the Sunni majority supports Bashar Assad's stated moves toward
modernization and improving telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Bashar would have to continue to fight the
corruption within the Alawite ruling elite that surrounded and
supported his father.
</P>
<P>
   Seif said this would not pose a danger to Bashar, as the elite
only represents a fraction of the Alawite community.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are weak enemies,'' he said. ``They have nothing to stand
on. What can they say, `We support corruption?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The strongest challenge to Hafez Assad's rule came 16 years ago
in Hama _ and Assad brutally suppressed it.
</P>
<P>
   Today the farming center stands as a reminder of how Assad dealt
with opposition. In 1984, Assad ordered a military offensive on the
community and killed, by conservative estimate, 10,000 people.
Human rights groups have put the toll as high as 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few buildings still standing show the marks left by tank
and machine gun fire. After the massacre, huge tracts of a town
were bulldozed and left in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the place where most of the corpses are believed to have
been has been converted into a park and the grounds of a
government-run luxury hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no opposition left in Hama,'' said one businessman in
his mid-30s, who was raised in Hama but now lives in Damascus.
``They were either killed or they fled or they are very afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   The loudest opposition to Bashar Assad has come from within his
family. His uncle, Rifaat, 63, asserted this week that Bashar does
not have the authority or experience to be president.
</P>
<P>
   A former vice president, Rifaat was forced into exile after a
failed coup attempt in 1984. Few see a scenario in which Rifaat,
now living in Europe, could emerge as a legitimate power.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rifaat's son, Moudar, dismissed his father's challenge.
``My father has a good heart, but he has people around him who do
not,'' said Moudar, 34, who is close to his cousin Bashar.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside the family home in Qardoha Wednesday, he said,
``There is no challenge to Bashar with any support. He is very
humble, very smart, and very forward thinking. And this is what the
country wants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
