<HEADLINE>
PEBBLE BEACH IS AN OPEN BOOK TO CLAMPETT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ The word no one ordinarily pays much
attention to is ``Open.''
</P>
<P>
   It happens to be the ``United States Open'' just as it happens
to be the ``British Open.'' Now this doesn't mean you, me, or the
guy next door can take any of our pathetic parodies of a golf game
up to the first tee at Pebble Beach, but it does mean that any
certified professional, including the assistant pro at your club
who just this spring took the metal cleats off your shoes and
replaced them with the plastic ones, and any amateur with a
handicap only slightly higher than Pedro's ERA can go through the
qualifying process. If the fates are smiling, he might find himself
one of the 156 starters in a US Open.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, this tournament, like all major golf tournaments,
will belong to a highly skilled and highly dedicated
52-weeks-a-year member of a Tour, either the PGA Tour or the
European Tour. But on Day 1, the most eyebrow-raising story will
always be some absolutely improbable guy who bubbles up from the
ranks of the qualifiers to shoot a wonderful score. This year, they
don't get any more improbable than Bobby Clampett, a qualfier who
shot a 68 at Pebble Beach Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a gift from God just even being here and playing in
this championship,'' he gushed.
</P>
<P>
   So while Tiger Woods shoots a bogey-less 65 a day after spending
two extra hours on the putting green even though ``I was making
them, yeah, but there are certain ways of making putts . . . I
didn't like the way I was rolling the ball,'' Bobby Clampett, who
has played in one tournament the last 21 months, goes out in 32 and
comes in with a 36. You've gotta love it.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Clampett. The name might ring a bell or two. Once upon a
time, he coulda been a contendah. Actually, he was a contendah,
finishing as high as third in this tournament back in 1982, when he
was 22 years old and, in the eyes of many, the Next Great Thing on
the PGA Tour. A three-time All-American at BYU, he shot a 70 in his
first Open round as an 18-year old.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, Mr. Can't Miss missed. His only tourney win
was the 1982 Southern Open. He last played on the Tour in 1995. If
people these days know his name at all, it's probably because he is
a full-time commentator for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   He is here for many reasons, but start with this: he is a
hometown boy, born in Monterrey. Pebble Beach is his course. He's
played it more than 200 times. That third-place finish 18 years ago
took place at, well, you've already guessed it.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's off the actual players' radar screen, he's still a
certified pro, and therefore eligible for the Open qualifying
process. He started out on May 18 by making it through the local
qualifying round as an alternate in his current place of residence,
Cary, N.C. From there he advanced through sectional qualifying in
Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about who he used to be. It's all about what he is, and
right now he explains his circumstance very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of years, I've been a once-a-month golfer,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was just Pebble Beach muscle memory, or some kind of
damn memory, but he started his magical day with a birdie when he
hit a 7-iron ``about 4 feet below the hole and made it for 3.'' He
likewise birdied five, nine, and 10. By this time he knew he was
playing with house money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I made the putt at nine, I was fighting back the tears
all through the front nine,'' he said. ``And when I made the putt
at nine that I hit too hard and was going to go probably 10 feet
past the hole, and it went right in the middle, I just looked up at
heaven and just thank God for that, because it was just _ it was
unbelievable. My eyes just swelled up with tears. It's hard to
describe that kind of emotion. It was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   He wobbled some in the back nine, but he made the shots he
needed to save every par but one. ``I've said this on the air many,
many times before,'' he declared. ``I don't care what the
circumstance is. I don't care whether you're in the lead or whether
you're behind. The only three things that matter most when you're
playing the game of golf are execution, execution, and execution.
Nothing else matters.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like something His Tigerness would say, and, speaking
of Tiger, wouldn't you know that Bobby Clampett couldn't get
through his own press conference without invoking the name of the
man with the 65, even though nobody was asking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things that's helped me is watching Tiger
Woods so much,'' said Clampett the Player on behalf of Clampett the
Broadcaster. ``The guy is so good, I'm fascinated by him. I love
watching him. I try to stay out of his way _ I love watching him.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have that opportunity tomorrow, because shooting a 68
Thursday is no guarantee he won't shoot a 78 today. Tiger would
never do that, of course, but Open qualifiers have been known to do
it, and Clampett has no illusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have no expectations, to be honest with you,'' he
confided. ``Because I don't know. My swing is not tested. I know
that I have to play my A-plus game here to have any chance of being
in contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me, but qualifiers, even qualifiers who once finished
third in this tournament, don't have an A-plus game.
</P>
<P>
   So relax, Bobby. Let Tiger search for the Perfect Putt. You just
take that Thursday scorecard back to Cary, N.C., and tack it up on
the wall. You've already had the qualifier's Open to die for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
