u f BC-TECHNO-CORNING-ART-BO     06-16 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-CORNING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 CORNING STEPS UP ITS ROLE IN THE FIBEROPTIC NETWORK MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, Mass. _ Next year, Corning Inc. will celebrate the
150th anniversary of its birth as a little workshop making bottles,
lamps, and glassware just outside Union Square in Somerville.
</P>
<P>
   After several transformations, a divestiture of its cookware
division and a move to upstate New York, Corning is still making
plenty of glass products in Massachusetts _ but a thousand times
smaller, and a million times more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 18 months, Corning has spent roughly $5 billion
snapping up Massachusetts start-ups in the white-hot world of
optical networking, the use of tiny devices that send pulses of
light over fiber strands of glass to meet the exploding
communications demands of the Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the world is adding more than 37 million miles of
optical fiber, equivalent to roughly 6 times the entire optical
network owned by Bell Atlantic in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   While attracting less notice than start-up buying binges by
Lucent Technologies, Cisco Systems, Nortel Networks, and Siemens
AG, Corning now counts 1,100 employees at eight sites in Greater
Boston and expects to add 300 more by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies added to the Corning stable in the last 18
months were Oak Industries in Waltham and its Bedford-based
Lasertron subsidiary, optical filter maker NetOptix of Natick, and
NZ Applied Technologies of Woburn.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, Corning completed a $500 million acquisition of
the 67 percent stake it did not previously own in IntelliSense of
Wilmington. IntelliSense is developing microengineered mirrors to
build switches that can move voice and data traffic on optical
networks without converting it back to electricity to pass through
high-speed routers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where it all bubbled up from, but there is a lot
of optics activity in the Boston area, and the units we have added
there play a very important role in our strategy,'' Corning
president John Loose said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Loose declined to name other area optical start-ups Corning is
considering buying. But he said: ``I can't imagine that we're
finished. There are new technologies continually emerging, and that
(Boston) area is just a hothouse of new technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we see a company that has a technology that's six months
ahead of ours, we will immediately move,'' Loose said. ``We don't
have a `not invented here' attitude. I think there are a lot of
companies in that quarter of the country that we are interested
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Corning dates back to 1851, when Boston entrepreneur Amory
Houghton bought an interest in a predecessor of Union Glass on
Webster Street in Somerville.
</P>
<P>
   The company, along with Lucent, in recent decades has dominated
the production of fiber-optic cables that can carry tens of
thousands of times more voice and data calls than standard copper
phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last two years, the once-conservative company has
moved aggressively to cover a much wider range of the optical
networking market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sort of gone all out in this space,'' said Gerald J.
Fine, vice president and general manager of Corning's photonic
technologies division. ``We are very serious about covering every
aspect of the optical network. We are all trying to stay ahead of
the raging bull.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1990s, Corning's share of revenues from
telecommunications has soared from 25 percent to more than 70
percent, helping the company grow to nearly $5 billion in annual
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In part, its buying spree has been boosted by Wall Street's
exuberance over the optical communications segment. Corning shares
have soared fivefold in value in the last year. And Thursday they
closed at $249.75, up $12.75 in New York Stock Exchange trading
after analyst Hasan Imam at Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities
raised his estimate of the company's target price to $270 from $230
per share.
</P>
<P>
   That runup has given the company ample currency to buy start-ups
in the form of stock swaps and keep up with acquisitive rivals such
as JDS Uniphase of San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Corning's $2 billion acquisition of NetOptix, formerly based in
Sturbridge, which makes devices to carry as many as 160 different
wavelengths of light over a single fiber, made NetOptix the
top-performing Massachusetts stock on this year's Globe 100 list.
NetOptix shares soared in value 35 times in the year ended March
31, thanks to Corning's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Clavenna, a consultant with Pioneer Consulting LLC in
Cambridge who follows the optical market, said that even with the
rich prices Corning has paid for Massachusetts optical start-ups,
``they have done extremely well, and they keep making good moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years they did a good job controlling the optical fiber
market, and only a modestly good job as a component company,''
Clavenna said. But in recent years, he said, ``they've been very
keen on operating like a start-up and trying to be as dynamic as
the optical networking market requires them to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have speculated that big Corning component
customers such as Lucent, Nortel, Alcatel, and Sycamore Networks of
Chelmsford could over time become anxious that their vendor is
becoming a foe.
</P>
<P>
   But Loose said: ``We do not compete with any of our customers. I
hear that speculation, but at the highest levels of those
companies, I think they're comfortable that we're not going to move
into their space'' and will leave the market for developing systems
and network software to existing players.
</P>
<P>
   Corning now has five main units involved in optical
communications: fiber and cable factories; modules for amplifiers
to move traffic over continental networks; ``passive components''
like NetOptix filters that divide light into colors; ``active
components'' that transmit light, such as Lasertron's lasers; and a
new division working to switch light pulses in purely optical
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Corning Lasertron's Bedford plant, technicians dressed in
gowns, gloves, smocks, and masks from head to foot use
vacuum-sealed equipment to grow cookie-size chips of laser material
that are built literally molecule layer by molecule layer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a process comparable to scraping the canvas off a
painting to leave only the painted image, the metal plate
supporting a laser material is carefully etched off, producing up
to 4,000 source lasers from a wafer barely the size of an
Eisenhower dollar coin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
