<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NAZI-WEB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES YIELD NO CLAIMS ON LOOTED ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN DEZELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been two months since four major American art museums
posted information on their Web sites about works in their
collections whose provenance, or history of ownership, may
implicate them in the widespread looting of art in Europe during
the Nazi era.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the Cold War, as evidence has mounted that tens
of thousands of paintings, sculptures, and decorative objects owned
by Jewish families and collectors were systematically pillaged
during World War II, Jewish organizations have pressured museums to
document and publicize ``spoliated'' paintings and objects that
have gaps in provenance and, because they were in Europe during the
Third Reich, might rightfully belong to the heirs of Holocaust
victims.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no claimants have come forward to identify and seek
restitution for objects on the Web sites put up by the Museum of
Fine Arts in Boston, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Museum of
Modern Art, or the Art Institute of Chicago. Nor have the sites
yielded significant evidence that could lead to the recovery of
stolen objects.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the queries and communiques the MFA has received have
been from members of ``the press, people interested in the issue of
Holocaust-era art, and people with inquiries about the provenance
of paintings that are not in our collection,'' said museum
spokeswoman Dawn Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Museum's web site list ``has generated an
incredible amount of visitorship, but absolutely no claims,
challenges, or inquiries,'' according to spokesman Harold Holzer.
</P>
<P>
   The Art Institute of Chicago has received ``no claims
whatsoever, and the overall reponse has been very slim,'' said
spokeswoman Eileen Herakel. ``We've also had a ton of queries from
people like a woman who said: `I have a piano. Can you tell me how
much it's worth?' ''
</P>
<P>
   MOMA ``has received some information that has helped fill in
some provenance gaps'' for paintings on its Web site, though none
have yielded the definitive histories of the paintings, according
to a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA and the Art Institute have been negotiating with
families seeking possession of what were identified as spoliated
objects before the Web sites went up. According to Museum of Fine
Arts director Malcolm Rogers, the museum is negotiating with a
party identified as the owner of a painting in the European
collection that was stolen and sold in France during the Nazi
occupation. ``The claimant wishes to keep the painting at the MFA,
and we are working toward that end,'' Rogers said early this
spring. ``The family has asked that the MFA not to reveal personal
information or details of the painting and negotiations to the
press.''
</P>
<P>
   The MFA is also involved in ongoing discussions with Christine
Koenigs of Amsterdam and the Dutch government, both of whom want to
take possession of a 16th-century Flemish painting, ``Landscape
with Burning City,'' by Herri met de Bles, which the Boston museum
acquired in 1948. In 1998, Koenigs filed a claim for the painting,
one of many owned by her grandfather until 1940. Following her
filing and reports in The Boston Globe about the de Bles and other
possible spoliated art at the MFA, the museum sought arbitration
among the parties, saying it wanted to return the painting. The
Netherlands, which has set up its own organization to review
Holocaust art claims, rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Koenigs and the heirs of two other victims of Nazi plunder
recently asked the World Jewish Congress to pressure the Dutch
government, which Koenigs holds accountable for the delay in
returning her family property.
</P>
<P>
   The Art Institute this week announced the settlement of a claim
to a 17th-century Italian sculpture by heirs of a prominent Jewish
art collector. The amount of the settlement was not disclosed, nor
was the name of the family involved.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, the North Carolina Museum of Art announced
that a 16th-century painting identified last year as stolen and
returned to a pair of elderly sisters living in Vienna, is now
coming back to the Raleigh museum. The sisters agreed to resell the
painting at a fraction of its appraised price.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jewish organizations and local media have criticized the
MFA for not being comprehensive or expansive enough in posting its
collection. But the MFA's site provides a digital image,
provenance, and an explanation of why gaps in the paintings'
histories raised researchers' suspicions. The Met and The Art
Institute have posted long, unannotated lists of paintings and
owners that do not indicate how likely or unlikely it is that they
were part of Nazi plunder. MOMA's roster, like the MFA's, is small
and includes digital images, though not the sort of detail provided
by the Boston museum.
</P>
<P>
   Jehuda Reinharz, president of Brandeis University and a member
of the Presidential Advisory Commission on Holocaust Assets in the
United States, has said that the MFA is ``is absolutely in the
forefront of museums that are doing the right thing in posting
suspicious art on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Klothen, executive director of the commission, isn't
``surprised there haven't been more claims,'' he said Thursday.
``It's very early. And as good a step as (the museums posting of
information) is, from a claimant's perspective, it doesn't do much.
People don't know where to look for these paintings, or what museum
they may have ended up in, or whether that museum has a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's needed is a broad-based comprehensive, accessible
database. What's been done is enormously significant, but it's not
enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
