<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5841 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-TITAN-BOS &LR;      06-16 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TITAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRESTING IMAGES MARK SCI-FI `TITAN' LANDSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
TITAN A.E. 
Animation directed by: Don Bluth and Gary Goldman 
Screenplay by: Ben Edlund, John August, Josh Whedon 
With the voices of: Matt Damon, Bill Pullman, John Leguizamo,
Nathan Lane, Janeane Garofalo, Drew Barrymore, Ron Perlman, Alex D.
Linz, Tone-Loc, Jim Breuer 
Running time: 95 minutes 
Rated: PG (action violence, brief sensuality and brief language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years of leaving full-length animated sci-fi to Japanese
anime, Hollywood fields a good-looking entry in ``Titan A.E.'' In
fact, it's been years since Don Bluth and his forces have turned
out anything this snazzy. Its young protagonist's heroics, pitched
at preteens, are pretty standard. But the visuals are terrific in
this story of humanity fighting for a second chance after a
malevolent super-race known as the Drej wipes Earth out, but not
before a scientist blasts off in the globe-shaped spaceship that
gives the film its name, having already dispatched his young son in
a different escape craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titan A.E.'' echoes ``Star Wars'' in more than a few respects,
from its spaceships disappearing into warp drive to its Luke
Skywalker-like hero, Cale, grown into young manhood, working a
lowly job on a salvage station, not realizing that he holds the key
to humankind's survival. A few zaps later, he's hurtling across
space with an older space veteran, Korso, in a crate piloted by a
hot-rodding young woman, Akima, right out of the world of anime.
Matt Damon voices Cale with just the right mix of surliness,
idealism, and naivete, while Drew Barrymore is a persuasively
spirited and autonomous character who gives teen girls someone with
whom to identify.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pullman's Korso is the most interestingly layered character
(John Leguizamo, Nathan Lane, and Janeane Garofalo voice the crew
members), but the film is too busy maintaining forward motion to
spend much time probing anyone's dark side. The three earthlings
have their differences, but the smartly paced film doesn't get
bogged down in them. It pushes on, trying to beat the Drej to the
hidden Titan, the location of which is contained in a genetically
encoded map that Cale never knew he harbored. There's treachery,
and a galaxy full of narrow escapes and dogfights with Drej probe
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the insect-like title-roleist from ``Alien,'' looking
like a blue gas flame. That's the Drej, pure energy, all focused.
They give ``Titan A.E.'' visual punch, but where the film really
comes into its computer-generated own is in the various worlds the
human underdogs visit. ``Titan A.E.'' peaks when the space
guerrillas touch down on one planet with trees that release
hydrogen bubbles that amount to floating bombs, and especially in
another planet of giant ice crystals. Their slow motion and
zero-gravity shattering when something hits them is hypnotic, and
their highly reflective surfaces add a hall-of-mirrors tension to
the showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Damon, Pullman, and Barrymore impart tanginess to their
literally and figuratively two-dimensional characters. The 2-D
rendering is a stylistic tie to anime, but the computer-generated
3-D environments through which Bluth and his collaborators propel
them are original and first-rate. Although the rock soundtrack
seems mostly like insipid pandering to the teen demographic, the
soundtrack becomes arrestingly interesting and creative in its use
of Tuvan throat singers to supply the voices of the Drej and,
later, in the sounds of the ice crystals straining and cracking. On
balance, the delivery system here feels fresh, the content rather
less so. Still, ``Titan A.E.'' is a space shot worth taking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
