<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A $2 HANGOVER FOR US GUZZLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If I'm Alan Greenspan, I'm shedding my sleek worsted suits of
businessman's blue and donning gas station coveralls to spy on gas
prices.
</P>
<P>
   As our designated First Mechanic of Inflation Fighting, the
place for Big Al's proboscis to sniff out the faintest whiffs of
inflation is at the pump. General Motors economists estimate that
American drivers are paying $40 more per month for gas than last
year _ about the price of one large coffee per day.
</P>
<P>
   But multiplied by more than 100 million drivers, that's a large
enough number to register on Big Al's Geiger counter of inflation.
People who used to fill 'er up and get change back from a 20 now
have to hit the ATM before driving to work. Gas prices again lurch
toward the $2-a-gallon level nationally and in the Midwest have
spiked higher than the dreaded deuce.
</P>
<P>
   For Guzzler Nation, this is an unwelcome development at the
onset of summer vacation drive time. Have a nice drive. Like, over
a cliff if you need to wheel the old DeSoto a long way to work and
back. There's nothing like a rocket ride in price-at-the-pump to
angrify up the blood of your basic motorist/voter.
Two-dollar-a-gallon gas could cook Al Gore's campaign. People don't
pay attention to a lot of what we put in the newspaper daily. But
the price of fuel is as accurate a barometer of voter blood
pressure as there is.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last flurry of gasoline price rises, that became the
news that most concerned the public. More Americans (58 percent)
paid attention to OPEC's chokehold on our gas station tab than any
other current news. The only comparable news interest in the Pew
Research Center tallies going back to last year were the Columbine
shootings (68 percent) and the death of John F. Kennedy Jr. (54).
</P>
<P>
   A few months back, a gallon of regular unleaded could be had for
95 cents _ cheaper than bottled water. Oil tripled by the barrel,
and gasoline, diesel, and home heating oil ratcheted up. Jawboning
by the Clinton administration against OPEC was aimed at heading off
gas at two bucks by election day. But like a boozer coming off a
bender, we gas guzzlers wake up to a hostile environment with
another king-size energy hangover. Wha' happened?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is that the price of a barrel of crude went
from $11 to $30-plus in 15 months, as tracked by a brilliant
detective job in The Wall Street Journal. The roller-coaster ride
began late in 1997, when the oil-producing countries met in
Indonesia and agreed to increase production to meet predictions of
higher demand. Wrong. Asian economies slowed down, oil consumption
dropped, and suddenly there were oceans of surplus crude.
</P>
<P>
   Things like oil, wheat, and precious metals are bought and sold
in a very complicated fashion. To smooth out huge swings in prices,
the futures market exists. But futures traders, seeing rising
production and falling demand, drove the price down, down, down.
The 11 OPEC nations need higher prices to fund their governments.
Usually they cheat one another by lying about how close they stick
to their agreed-upon quotas.
</P>
<P>
   But last year they began living up to their production cuts, and
the futures traders started driving the price up. A newly elected
president in Venezuela halted his country's traditional quota
fudging. The Y2K deadline apparently derailed some oil forecasting.
Iraq pulled the plug on its production for a time, further skewing
forecasts, the Journal found.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics about inventories, notoriously inaccurate, varied so
wildly as to be unreliable. By the middle of winter, crude oil
prices were rocketing up faster than prices at the gas pump.
Result? Refiners slowed their production, using the classic market
rationale: If it costs me more to make and I can't sell it for as
much, why don't I slow down till the situation gets closer to
normal?
</P>
<P>
   We are now in a wait-and-see mode. The US refineries are
supposed to be hitting on all cylinders now, but if one of them
breaks, as seems to happen every summer at just the wrong time, we
may see $2 a gallon. Sure, we still pay much less for gas than just
about every other modern country. And the administration claim that
the US inflation index is less energy-dependent is accurate but
rather futile. People vote on perception, not reality.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer price index rose only one-10th of 1 percent in May
_ but it is up 3.1 percent over 12 months for the country as a
whole and 4.2 percent in New England. It may be time to jog OPEC
and our own oil barons by flooding the market with government-owned
stored oil. Goosing the market with controlled release of
government oil stocks will catch some speculators short and restore
market pressures, say some oil traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes no sense not to sell oil to this market,'' said one
options trader. ``Even the threat would drive down the price. I
find it kind of laughable that people buy the claim that nothing
can be done about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
