<SLUG> BC-GARAGES-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GARAGES: A HOME AWAY FROM HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, June 18)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would most homeowners do without a garage? This boxy
structure not only provides shelter for cars, but extra storage
space for bicycles, the barbecue grill, lawnmower, snowblower, ski
gear, sleds, trash and recycling barrels and, in some cases, a
workbench, snowmobile, seasonal clothing and the omnipresent
basketball backstop.
</P>
<P>
   A garage may look like just another room from the outside but,
for decades they have featured a bare-bones type of interior, with
unpainted walls and humble slab concrete floors. The most exciting
feature was the labor-saving automatic garage door.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, garages have been customized and are
going high tech. Not only are they getting bigger to accommodate
vans and sport utility vehicles, but accessories like a custom tile
dog bath area with a shower hose and hair dryer and track lighting
for various tasks make them more useful.
</P>
<P>
   Garages today are a far cry from the 18th century, when owners
drove their carriages under the porte-cochere, a decorative
extension of the porch, with a roof that provided shelter from the
elements. Carports sheltered automobiles in the mid-20th century.
In many cases, they featured an additional wall. Although not as
grand an architectural statement as the porte-cochere, it served as
the forerunner of the modern garage.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most homes have garage of some sort. And they are getting
bigger: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, 16 percent of all
single family homes completed last year featured three- (or more)
car garages.
</P>
<P>
   Architects are designing new ways to make garages more
attractive, like splitting them up to eliminate a long line of
bays, and adding amenities.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most unusual features is a turntable that revolves
the car in the garage so that it exits facing out. The driver
doesn't need to back out into heavy traffic, down a steep driveway
or from a blind entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Turntables are of most interest to people who have several cars
and don't want to move them all around to get to any particular
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``One car buff has a circular garage, and the car is driven onto
the turntable and revolved to point to its parking stall,'' said
Jeff Engelberger, product manager for the Macton Corp. in Oxford,
Conn. ``When he wants a car, he drives it out of the stall and onto
the turntable, which revolves to the garage door and exits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done several of these for private residences,''
Engelberger said. ``The deck is made from poured concrete, or a
client can inlay their own imported tiles or hardwood floor. You
can also get a diamond plate steel top, which offers excellent
grip.''
</P>
<P>
   The Macton Corp., a 50-year-old company, began installing train
turntables for switching tracks and then moved into other
applications, such as revolving restaurants for the Hyatt and
Mariott chains, the Canadian National Tower in Toronto and a
restaurant in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   When selecting a garage turntable, Engelberger said to get one
that's larger than the overall dimensions of your vehicle. This
will prevent your car from coming in contact with anything that may
be stored around the garage.
</P>
<P>
   The cost ranges from $25,000 to $40,000 for a garage turntable,
depending on the size and flooring surface. A remote control
operates the turntable from inside the car.
</P>
<P>
   Engelberger said that these turntables can also be installed
outside the garage, to keep the fumes out. The steel members are
galvanized to protect them from the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Freihofer of Menands, N.Y., placed his garages on
different levels.
</P>
<P>
   He put in a two-story garage to park extra cars _ it can hold up
to 10. A driveway leads to the lower level.
</P>
<P>
   Freihofer likes the hands-on approach and had a pit installed on
the lower level for changing oil. The building also has two exhaust
ventilation systems: one for the air and the other for the exhaust
pipe on the car; compressed air for tires and tools and floor
drains, so that the cars can be washed inside.
</P>
<P>
   Other safety features in Freihofer's garage include fume
detectors for gas and carbon monoxide. Both levels are air
conditioned and heated and have a painted interior and security
system.
</P>
<P>
   The most spectacular garage in the country would have to be the
one built by Microsoft tycoon Bill Gates near Seattle, according to
architect Jim Cohen, of the architectural firm Mesick Cohen Wilson
&AMP; Baker in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' 50-car concrete garage is underground on the compound of
his $53 million-plus house, covering some 66,000 square feet
overlooking Lake Washington with views of Seattle, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daylight comes from light tubes that go up through the ground.
When not in use, it becomes a basketball court.''
</P>
<P>
   Even homeowners without Gates' billions can add interest to
their garages by putting in do-it-yourself features such as a
storage room or a half-bathroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
