<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5846 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-16 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTING FEVER OUT OF CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Historian John Hope Franklin does not think very much of the
testing craze in American public schools, a frenzy fueled in part
by the high-stakes exams in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tests should not be the sole basis on which to base a child's
academic ability,'' he said over the phone from his home in Durham,
N.C. ``I would think you would need some measures of knowledge.
Yes, you want to know if a student can add or subtract or read in
certain way, but the nation has been carried away and students are
being swept away by all this testing.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's words should always be considered. The 85-year-old
scholar will be honored at the Museum of Fine Arts by Primary
Source, a nonprofit education resource center that promotes a more
inclusive and accurate social studies curriculum in schools
throughout New England schools.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Coonly of Primary Source said it is honoring Franklin
because, ``All of the work he has done is so parallel to our
efforts to uncover histories that are not taught in mainstream
history classes.'' Franklin, who has seen everything from the Great
Depression to the Internet and has over 100 honorary degrees, also
does not want to see history repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly true for education. He vividly remembers
the day in the spring of 1935 where he walked from Fisk University
across town to white Vanderbilt University to take a test to
qualify for graduate studies at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The professor at Vanderbilt literally threw the SAT at me,''
Franklin said. ``He was such a poor, crude critter. When I walked
out of the building, I passed a black janitor who told me that I
was the first black person he ever saw even being allowed to sit in
that building.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five years later, Franklin warns that too much reliance on
tests, particularly when schools receive vastly different
resources, is less about education than erecting new barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is much more important to know than a test score is a
student's family life, personal life, their socialization and so
forth to help you determine what their abilities are and might
be,'' Franklin said. ``I think the tests are stacked against any
group that has disadvantages. The tests come out of these
laboratories where people have had certain kinds of experiences,
say at prep schools and elite colleges and have had various kinds
of activities and social groups that are not part of an
underprivileged student's experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not altogether racial, it's class. The message being
sent is if you don't get it, you don't get in. It will continue to
exclude people who are not only deserving but qualified in ways you
cannot tell from a single test.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, author of ``From Slavery to Freedom: A History of
Negro America,'' and winner of the 1995 Presidential Medal of
Freedom, took on what often seemed to be a thankless job in running
President Clinton's advisory panel on Clinton's race initiative.
Franklin said he thought the series of town halls elevated the
discussion of race, but much of the efforts went unheralded amid
what he said was the media's focus on controversies surrounding the
panel, such as the participation of black conservatives or how
central black/white frictions should be to the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   He remains deeply disappointed that at a plenary speech at a
massive American Society of Newspaper Editors convention, only
about 100 people showed up. ``The most permanent impression I have
of that year, the one that affected me the most, was how the media
operates,'' Franklin said. ``What I got from it was that the only
free press is the one you own yourself. They had their way of
dealing with race. What they were saying was they didn't need me or
the president to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin also praised Clinton, despite his failure to produce
his book on the initiative. This was understandable since Franklin
took the long view. A decade ago, when I interviewed Franklin, he
was so disgusted with the White House's attempts to roll back
affirmative action that he said President Reagan's ``abysmal''
leadership had ``given racism and racial aggression respectability
at the highest level.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Clinton, Franklin said that at least this president ``tried
to set a tone,'' by appointing more African-Americans to the
Cabinet than any prior president. He said the way that Mike Espy,
the late Ron Brown, and Alexis Herman were scrutinized, to the
degree of formal investigations, told him how resistant the nation
remains to high-level promotions of African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It is a reason he said affirmative action is necessary. It is a
reason that high-stakes tests should be carefully considered, less
the underprivileged be left behind. ``That hostility (toward
Clinton's black appointees) tells you a lot about what other people
(outside the administration) were really willing to accept,''
Franklin said. ``I wrote in one of my books that the legacy of the
color line would be alive and thrive well into the 21st century.
I'm sorry to say, it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
