r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     06-16 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR': AS PHONY AS IT IS REPELLENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An associate of mine, a producer of documentaries and a jaded
New Yorker to boot, called the other day to admit an infatuation
with ``Survivor,'' the part-game show, part-reality program,
part-experiment in public back-stabbing that is now cruising into
its fourth week on CBS. Surely you've heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say that this appreciation unnerved him, but judging
from the suddenly lower tone of his voice, it was clear that such
an affinity was surprising and slightly embarrassing, if not a wee
bit disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   He is, by his own admission, a man of intellectual girth and
artistic substance, and he's supposed to see right through what
producer Mark Burnett and the network are doing, which is creating
video voyeurism disguised as a game show disguised as realism,
hence the name, as one writer termed it, ``televoyeurism.'' (Try
finding that in Webster's, pal.)
</P>
<P>
   But something is tugging at his senses and pushing his emotional
buttons, and his attempts at justifying these, well, feelings, as
though he's pondering an affair outside marriage or considering a
sex change will more than likely run his already high blood
pressure to dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
   I'll tell you what I told him: Chill, bro. ``Survivor'' is among
us, folks, and there's more coming, just in different clothing and
walking with a slightly altered limp, so brace yourself for this
latest, innovative way they've come up with to sell soap and
cookware and those menacing, road-hogging sport-utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me while I watch the ``Survivor'' SUV zoom by and don't
attempt to leap on.
</P>
<P>
   All the talk of this series capturing the imagination of
television viewers aching for something different is the silliest
thing I've heard and the most audacious form of marketing since
Paramount's promise that its upcoming Dr. Laura TV show will lay
off gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' is destined to be a much-discussed program through
the summer, now that it has shown an ability to lure viewers and
thus give television and newspapers like this one the excuse to run
the thing even further into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 castaways, or participants, who are ``competing'' for a
$1 million prize in this 13-episode series set on a remote island
describe ``Survivor'' as good dramatic TV because it's real people
doing real things. No actors, no scripts, no manipulation. But in
the stuff I've seen thus far, what's so real about it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' is melodrama so calculated it's as if it were
coming from a scriptwriter holed up at a roadside motel, and if you
look closely at the edits and the highly selected dialogue and
images (nice, quick, cropped shots of the womenfolk in their
bikinis and short-shorts, or of anyone showing some sign of
disapproval or disgust with someone else), it's actually quite easy
to see beyond the charade. The whole mud-orgy thing, the talk of
Him having a crush on Her, is a mixture of an after-school special
and the who-can-diss-who-de-most kind of TV we've come to know and
love from Jerry Springer and his ilk.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be careful not to label ``Survivor'' a creative or
cultural phenomenon, which is what CBS would have you believe,
since it is, at least, a financial phenomenon. The series, like
ABC's ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire,'' is doing quite well in
this era of niche audiences, when every fractionalized demographic
in the nation is pandered to by its own cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' has managed to attract those young adults with low
attention spans at a far greater clip than ``Millionaire,'' yet it
still manages to gather those Americans (age 50 or so) who have
their TV speed dials set to CBS. Ah, a G-rated value the whole
family can veg out on.
</P>
<P>
   And what's the whole family wallowing in? Greed, actually, and
lessons in harsh politicized socialization, although we all seem to
forget this as we discuss in our offices and living rooms whether
``we'' would eat a rat, whether the older woman should have been
booted in the first episode, and, by the way, how could someone so
annoying be a corporate trainer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' is based on the premise of winning at someone
else's expense, and we don't seem to mind, since we're only the
spectators here. Is it that, or because that's how we govern our
lives, anyway, in our own offices, among our social peers?
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure as a talk host, Arsenio Hall once told me of
being burdened by the notion that since he had a late-night talk
show, no other African-American could. As if he had to be pushed
off a cliff in order for someone else to get a shot.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the thinking behind ``Survivor,'' which, as my
associate pointed out, we see as fun and games although we'd be
sick to our stomachs if our colleagues went behind our backs to
sabotage our lives in order to lift their own.
</P>
<P>
   The scene that defines ``Survivor'' best occurred in the second
episode when two female contestants were discussing ``strategy'' of
staying on the island. They were pinpointing whom to kick off, and
suggesting that siding with another female participant who felt the
same way would only solidify this new united front.
</P>
<P>
   But the women, as ``individuals'' salivating over a $1 million
payday, bragging rights and appearances on every talk show in the
land, had to also be plotting how they could rid themselves of the
other two partners making up this alliance within an alliance. It's
a working relationship at its most insincere.
</P>
<P>
   A reader e-mailed me recently, saying she likes this sort of
thing, that ``Survivor'' can actually serve as education in how we
deal with the real cutthroats of the world.
</P>
<P>
   I had to ask: ``Are you a corporate trainer?''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
