<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5848 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-MOSLEY-BOS &LR;      06-16 1618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MOSLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY HOMES IN ON TITLE SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was the biggest disappointment of his life but
so many other things were out of kilter at the time Shane Mosley
hardly noticed he had blown the biggest chance of his life back in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Right up until he failed to make the US Olympic team, Mosley was
considered America's best amateur boxer and a lock to win a medal
in Barcelona. Although a kid who grew up near him in southern
California named Oscar De La Hoya was getting more publicity, the
people who understood boxing knew who the best amateur was back
then. It was the Mosley kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an amateur I was always the No. 1 guy in town,'' Mosley
recalled recently. ``I was the No. 1 amateur from 1989 to 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was.
</P>
<P>
   And then he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   And he's suffered for it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Something went wrong for Mosley during the Olympic trials that
year but so many other things were going wrong he took the losses
to Vernon Forrest as if they were meaningless. Then he sat home in
Pomona, Calif, 40 miles from the East Los Angeles neighborhood
where De La Hoya had grown up, and watched De La Hoya turn those
Games into his personal coronation as Crown Prince of Pugilism.
</P>
<P>
   He watched and read and ever since Mosley has been chasing De La
Hoya the same way they used to chase each other as amateurs whose
paths kept crossing in gyms around southern California. Saturday
night, he'll finally catch him. Then what?
</P>
<P>
   ``After those Olympics, all of a sudden it was like he shot past
me,'' Mosley recalled this week while relaxing in his hotel suite
in downtown L.A., less than a mile from the Staples Center where he
and De La Hoya will square off for the World Boxing Council
welterweight title in what is expected to be one of the highest
grossing non-heavyweight pay-per-view shows in history. ``I just
never got the same kind of recognition he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Not, at least, until this week. Not until a week in which
Mosley, now an undefeated former International Boxing Federation
lightweight champion with 34 straight victories (32 of which ended
in early siestas for his opponent), has promised he will take
boxing's Golden Boy ``soul searching.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley has shown not a hint of nervousness all week. His
confident smile and amiable disposition have been unchanged from
all the other days and nights he has visited with the press or his
friends in the past. He has spoken respectfully of De La Hoya yet
always made clear what he believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a better fighter than he is,'' Mosley says. He says it in
words and in every action he takes. Despite the fact De La Hoya has
become one of the biggest draws in boxing and a national Latino
phenomenon, nothing has changed since 1992 for Mosley. To him, at
least, there is no question who is the best fighter in southern
California and the world. De La Hoya may be good, Mosley says, but
I was always better.
</P>
<P>
   Except, that is, for those few weeks eight years ago when
everything fell apart for Shane Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, I had so many things in my life going wrong
that not going to the Olympics was not a shock at all,'' he said.
``It was just, `Oh, I didn't go.' I was going through some trying
times. There were a lot of pressures on me. Too many for a kid to
handle at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not taking anything away from Vernon. The better man
won that night. Next time, though, it won't be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time Mosley's young son had just been born and he was in
a nasty custody battle with the child's mother. He also was still
mourning the death of his 16-year-old nephew, who died in a car
accident and Mosley was unable to accept that sad reality.
</P>
<P>
   He was spending nearly as much time in custody fights as he was
in real fights and surrounding all that was the mounting pressure
that comes with being your country's leading amateur boxer in an
Olympic year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about going to the Olympics,'' Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya faced many of the same pressures because America
adopted his story of fighting to win the gold medal in the memory
of his dead mother as their own and he triumphed over it. Mosley, a
year older but buffeted by too many ill winds, did not and lost to
Forrest and then became lost in the forest of professional prize
fighting for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Small at 139 pounds and without the special entree of being an
Olympic champion, Mosley kicked around southern California for
nearly a year before he got his first professional fight. His
father was training him then, as he does today, but the kid had
lousy promoters and spent more time sparring with pros like Zack
Padilla, Paul Gonzalez, Genaro Hernandez, and Hector Lopez in
Pomona than he did fighting for money. In his first professional
bout on Feb. 11, 1993 he stopped former California champion Greg
Puente in five rounds at the Hollywood Palladium.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley made about $600 that night. De La Hoya had already made
his pro debut by then, knocking out Lamar Williams on Nov. 23, 1992
after signing a promotional deal worth more than a million dollars.
The gap between the two rivals couldn't be much wider and it has
stayed that way through the years, even after Mosley hooked up with
promoter Cedric Kushner and eventually landed a shot at the IBF
lightweight title.
</P>
<P>
   It took Mosley 23 victories to get into the ring with Philip
Holiday for short money and a shot at the IBF championship, which
he won by taking a unanimous decision. De La Hoya, in contrast, won
his first world title in his 12th fight and was already on HBO.
Mosley's first title defense was on USA Network.
</P>
<P>
   That is how it has gone since 1992. Both fighters winning but De
La Hoya always winning bigger. Much bigger.
</P>
<P>
   For this fight Mosley will earn $4.5 million, by far the biggest
payday of his career. De La Hoya will earn more than twice as much
and it will be a paycut from his last big fight, the night he
tasted defeat for the only time in his career when he lost a
controversial decision to Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone on different roads,'' Mosley said of De la Hoya.
``My first couple of years (as a pro) were difficult but they
helped me become stronger as a person and as a fighter. I had to
stay disciplined. I was out for a year and had to go through going
to the gym every day without any fights and sparring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked as a sparring partner in those hard times. I moved
back in my father's house. You can say I've been in Oscar's shadow
a long time. That's why it's important to be the best I can against
him, to define who I am as a fighter. God works in mysterious ways.
Maybe if I beat Vernon Forrest I'd be in a different place today.''
</P>
<P>
   The gamblers who have made De La Hoya a 2 1/2-to-1 favorite
believe Mosley will be wishing he was in a different place because
they believe De La Hoya is the Jolly Green Giant while Mosley has
sprouted from the land of the Lilliputians.
</P>
<P>
   While economically it could be argued that is true, physically
there is far less difference between the fighters than people
think. Because De La Hoya has been fighting as a welterweight for
more than three years while Mosley made his name as lightweight
(135 pounds) champion, there is the tendency to believe this is a
small man against a big man. Fact is, for six of the eight years
they have been professionals, Mosley has fought at the same or in a
bigger weight class because De La Hoya began his career fighting at
130 pounds and won his first title at that weight while Mosley has
always been 135 or bigger.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, while De La Hoya is probably four inches
taller than Mosley, the shorter man (who claims to be 5 feet,
inches but looks 5-7) actually has a 2-inch reach advantage at 74
inches. At 11 1/2 inches, Mosley's fist is 2 1/2 inches bigger than
De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is of little significance but the reach advantage may
be because although Mosley fights like a perpetual motion machine,
he has the speed and skills to box on the outside or fight to the
body on the inside and he knows it. Now all he has to do is
convince De La Hoya and the world of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``De La Hoya's people keep saying I may be overwhelmed by the
moment,'' Mosley said. ``Why? I can't be afraid of something I
want. There's no need to be afraid of what I want _ greatness. This
is my opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he pressures me like he says he's going to . . . the people
will get a great fight.''
</P>
<P>
   After he says those last words, Mosley smiles like a man who
knows a secret. He had seemed to want to say something different
about the consequences of De La Hoya attacking him but thought
better of it. But only for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can know the future, but I believe in my heart I can
knock out Oscar,'' he said. ``I believe this is a fight for who's
the best pound for pound fighter in the world. Bragging rights in
L.A. come along with that but this is about who's the best fighter
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't go into this with any concerns. I feel I'm the
stronger, faster, better man. I don't have any doubts. I have no
concerns about walking down that aisle to the ring . . . This fight
is for honor. It's for who's the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it is, the kid from Pomona who has been chasing De La
Hoya for so many years has already promised to do the honorable
thing. Four days before he was to box De La Hoya for the first time
since they were teenagers, Mosley promised him a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, I'm counting on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he flashed his trademark smile and nodded as if to make one
last point clear: ``This ain't going to be like 1992.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
