<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-16 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RASHAD ANSWERS CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By most accounts, Ahmad Rashad shouldn't be anywhere near the
word journalism. Critics say he is too soft, too chummy with
players, too friendly to ask tough questions.
</P>
<P>
   However Rashad has one of the most recognizable faces on
television and people have liked him for a long time. More
importantly, NBC sports chairman Dick Ebersol likes him, and Rashad
won't be leaving NBC anytime soon. In fact, once the NBA Finals are
over, Rashad is boning up for the Summer Olympics in Sydney, where
he will report nightly features with Bob Costas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is getting through all of this while continuing to
smile,'' Rashad said. ``There's a lot of jealousy out there. But my
critics tend to forget that this is a business of relationships.
This is sports entertainment. It's about relationships; it's about
contacts. My relationships are my strength. One of my best friends
is Michael Jordan, who just happened to be the best basketball
player on the planet. My access was unlimited, and there was a lot
of jealousy over that relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Rashad doesn't apologize for being friendly with the athletes he
covers. ``Hey, if my boss wants to know the status of Kobe Bryant's
ankle problem, I'll call Kobe at home or on his cell phone. Put it
this way: If I need any top athlete, I can get him or her.''
</P>
<P>
   Rashad is not simply talking trash. He plays golf with Tiger
Woods; he hangs out with Ed Bradley, Bill Cosby, and Sidney
Poitier. As executive producer of ``Inside Stuff,'' an NBA program
aimed at kids that celebrated its 10th anniversary this year,
Rashad is the only black executive producer of any weekly network
show. He has talked with everybody in the NBA for the last decade
and remembers little things about each one of them.
</P>
<P>
   He first talked with Shaquille O'Neal about two weeks after he
left LSU. ``He tried to be funny,'' Rashad said. ``He came up to me
and said, `Aren't you Phylicia Rashad's husband?' '' Rashad
answered with some crack about O'Neal's highwater pants. ``A lot of
people think Shaq is a difficult interview,'' Rashad said. ``But he
is like the kid when you are growing up that has a younger brother
that everybody just beats on from time to time. It just so happens
this particular kid grew up huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rashad is cool, old-school cool. But the playa-haters always
have something negative to say.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard the stuff about softball questions before. He said
he asked Jordan about his gambling problem. He asked Jordan about
his father. ``Those were very pointed questions that generated
poignant answers,'' Rashad said. ``I can't help it if I didn't ask
those questions with a scowl on my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, not bad at all for the former All-Pro wide receiver who
knew that one day his playing days would end. His father taught him
to have options and so he did, working at a local television
station while he played for the Minnesota Vikings. He covered a
little bit of everything, paying his dues at tractor pulls, girls'
basketball games and boys' hockey. When he retired in 1983, Rashad
joined NBC as a football analyst, working in studio on NFL pregame
shows, then as a game color commentator. Football had served him
well, but he never wanted to limit himself to one sport. He is
still not the smoothest television personality, but he has worked
hard at his skills and knows his limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Rashad is now better known for basketball than the sport he
played, but he knows football. When he played at the University of
Oregon, he learned from assistant coaches George Seifert and John
Robinson. The quarterback was Dan Fouts. Rashad also wrote a book
about his NFL playing days. ``Rashad: Vikes, Mikes, and Something
on the Backside'' didn't go over too well with Vikings management.
Rashad wrote about drug use, excessive drinking, and players
hitting the field on Sunday afternoons with hangovers. Rashad has a
history of being unafraid, starting in his freshman year when he
was kicked off the basketball team for refusing to trim his afro.
He converted to Islam in the early 1970s and lost his previous
name, Bobby Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Rashad is softer now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an entertainer,'' he said. ``I'm not on the nightly news.
Most of the people watch sports for entertainment, not breaking
news, and I'm very comfortable with my role as an entertainer. My
goal was to be like Howard Cosell or Brent Musburger back in the
day _ when you saw those guys at an event, it must have been a big
event. That is what I aspired to.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the record, very few people criticized Cosell for his
relationship with Ali. What astounded Rashad about some of his
critics is that they would trash him publicly, then turn around and
ask him for a favor, usually involving Jordan. The worst was the
silence.
</P>
<P>
   When Jim Gray badgered Pete Rose, Rashad's name was often
dropped as the opposite extreme of Gray. Rashad said that he
doesn't want to be the star, but would rather be the one to get the
star to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about me,'' Rashad said. ``It's about the other guy,
and if people think that I'm too friendly, then that's their
problem. It doesn't change things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
