A5854 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     06-16 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV18-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT FINAL COAT `NEVER' COMES OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June   18, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband sandblasted the first two coats of paint from our
fireplace. The third coat will not budge; 5F5 (a potent paint
stripper) did nothing. Now what can I do?
</P>
<P>
   THERESA FLYNN, Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's an old story, the bane of a homeowner's existence and a
mystery as to why that third coat doesn't come off.
</P>
<P>
   But try this: Apply a coat of the 5F5, wait 15 minutes, and
apply a second coat. Then scrape, and scrub with very coarse steel
wool. No dice? That third coat (the first that went on) may be milk
paint, which will not yield to standard strippers. Try a milk paint
stripper; Yankee Powder Paint Stripper is one, made by Viking Mfg.
Co. of West Bridgewater, Mass., 508-580-5888.
</P>
<P>
   Another trick: Continue sandblasting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I noticed that Brosco (a large distributor of building items,
windows, and other goods in New England) has a window balance
system called Tilt and Clean. Can I use that system on my Andersen
windows?
</P>
<P>
   BILL MULCAHY, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I am pretty sure you cannot. With windows, you need
brand-for-brand parts. So, call Andersen, at 612-439-5150.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to put brick on top of my concrete patio. A
friend suggested I rent a Bobcat instead and break up and tear out
the old concrete. Isn't there an easier way?
</P>
<P>
   VINCENT CAIANI, Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There sure is, and do not break up the concrete; breaking it
up is one thing, disposing of it is another. You cannot leave those
concrete chunks for the street collection.
</P>
<P>
   So, here is what to do: Drill holes in the concrete every 12
inches in both directions for proper drainage. You can rent an
impact drill at a rental store. Put a border around the concrete so
that the bricks will not spread; the bricks must be held in
position. Large pressure-treated timbers or 2 x 12 boards will do.
Now to the nitty-gritty: If the patio surface is even, you can put
bricks directly on the concrete. If the concrete is not even, you
may have to put in an inch or two of stonedust or sand to allow
bricks to line up properly and be at the proper plane.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the bricks touch each other; then sprinkle sand or
stonedust in the joints. I prefer sand.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to raise the patio too much, as a full-sized
brick will do, you can install half-thick bricks. Strangely, they
are more expensive than the full-sized bricks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The maple bed set in my bedroom is very nice. The bureau is
good, but the chest has handles hinged at the top and are
free-standing. They shake and make a racket when I walk on the
floor. How can I prevent that?
</P>
<P>
   HELEN YOUNG, Weston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah, the old shaking handle syndrome, brought on by a bouncing
floor. When you walk, the floor bounces up and down; then the chest
bounces and finally the handles.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest way to fix this is to reinforce the beams holding up
the floor, or add more beams, to stop the bouncing. That is
difficult if the beams cannot be seen from below. You can imagine
it is a thankless job.
</P>
<P>
   But, how about the easy way? Buy small rubber bumpers of the
type used to keep a glass slab off a deck top. Glue one on the
plate of the handle sysem, so that the handle when it is down will
touch that rubber bumper. If there is no plate, you can glue or
nail the bumber to the front of the chest. If that doesn't work,
wrap the handle with duct tape. Not pretty, but like a lot of
unpretty things, it works.
</P>
<P>
   ufqWhen I had a new roof installed last October, the gutters
were removed and some vinyl replaced. Last winter I got a lot of
icicles; they were all over, hanging from the eaves, the fascia and
the gutters. What is wrong and how can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   SUE McDERMOTT, Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If what you call vinyl replaced was a vinyl gutter, the
icicles formed because the water is not dripping into the middle of
the new gutter, the gutters are overflowing and the overflow is
turning to ice. You might be able to adjust the gutters up or down,
or nearer to the fascia, but the water must drip into the middle of
the gutter. If the water drips too close to the back or the front
of the gutter, the gutter will overflow.
</P>
<P>
   If the gutters were removed and new ones were not put up, the
dripping water will turn to ice in winter and there is nothing you
can do about it, except put up new gutters.
</P>
<P>
   If the icicles don't get too big and become a hazard when they
fall, you can live with them. The handyman has no gutters on most
of his house, and the icicles never get more than 6 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
