<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     06-16 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS OF OIL ARE SLIPPERY IN CAR-LOVING US: YERGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is deja vu all over again in the oil market.
</P>
<P>
   The price of a barrel of oil is hovering around $33, and
gasoline is expensive. In some Midwestern cities, the price has
topped the politically sensitive $2 a gallon mark.
</P>
<P>
   To find out what's going on and what lies ahead, we called up
Daniel Yergin. For 20 years, in books like ``Energy Future'' and
``The Prize,'' Yergin has chronicled the history and politics of
the oil business.
</P>
<P>
   Yergin is also chairman of Cambridge Energy Research Associates,
a consulting firm that recently put out a report entitled
``Gasoline and The American People.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed to
pump more oil in March. Why are gas prices still so high?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's a combination of things. The world economy has been
strong, US gasoline inventories have remained very low, and you
have some new environmental regulations that have Balkanized the
gasoline market and made it difficult to move supplies around. We
think of gasoline as a commodity, but today you can't move it 20
miles without violating federal rules. The result has been not
quite panic, but a very high-strung psychology in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Q. One thing comes through loud and clear in your report:
Americans love to drive and use gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   A. That's right. One thing we found that amazed me was that in
1980 the average licensed driver traveled 9,700 miles. In 1998,
that figure was up to 13,000 miles, an increase of 34 percent.
There are now over 185 million drivers in this country and 203
million light vehicles. About one out of every nine barrels of oil
used in the world every day is consumed by the American motorist.
</P>
<P>
   Q. OPEC is meeting next week. Will they agree to pump more oil?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think they will. Their target band for prices is $22 to $28
a barrel, and they are way over that now. Countries like Saudi
Arabia and Mexico know it is not in their interest to have prices
so high. The Mexican finance minister said recently that the number
one risk to the Mexican economy was a slowdown in the American
economy. I also don't think OPEC wants oil to be an issue in the US
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Once upon a time, the OPEC countries had lots of spare
capacity. Now we read that many countries couldn't pump any more
oil if they wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   A. Supplies are not quite as tight as people think. There is
probably four to five million barrels a day of spare capacity in
the world, but half of that is in Saudi Arabia. Many countries like
Iran and Nigeria are pumping as much as they can. When oil prices
collapsed in 1997 and 1998, investment fell off. Some of the oil
producers lost 40 percent of their national revenue. They didn't
have the ability to maintain investment.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So the current rise in prices is a result of the fall in
prices we had a few years ago?
</P>
<P>
   A. One thing I learned while writing ``The Prize'' was that each
boom plants the seed for the next bust, and each bust plants the
seed for the next boom.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have we moved into a period where prices are going to stay
high?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think we are in a period where the floor on oil prices will
be $20 to $22 a barrel. And the ceiling? It's hard to say. When you
have a system that is this tight, any number of things could cause
prices to spike. You could have a pipeline accident in a local
market. On an international scale, a political crisis in Nigeria or
Iraq could create a risk of much higher prices. Still, it is
important to say that the key oil producers don't want to see
prices as high as they are now.
</P>
<P>
   Q. People may not appreciate it, but in your report you say that
by historical standards today's prices are not all that high.
</P>
<P>
   A. That's right. At $1.50 a gallon, Americans are spending about
3 percent of their household incomes on gasoline, which is just
about the historical average. Adjusted for inflation, prices were
higher in the 1960s and much higher in 1980. When gasoline prices
fell below $1 a gallon in 1999, they were even lower than they were
during the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But that is not how the public thinks about gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   A. People don't think in an inflation-adjusted way. If gas
prices get closer to $2 a barrel, you can bet they will be a big
political issue. Gas prices are the most visible prices we have.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre 2918) and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
