<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-FANTASIA-BOS &LR;      06-16 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FANTASIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW MAGIC ANIMATES DISNEY `FANTASIA/2000' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FANTASIA/2000 
Animation directed by: Pixote Hunt, Hendel Butoy, Eric Goldberg,
James Algar, Francis Glebas, Gaetan Brizzi 
Music by: Beethoven, Respighi, Gershwin, Shostakovich, Saint-Saens,
Dukas, Elgar, Stravinsky 
Performed by: Chicago Symphony Orchestra, James Levine conducting,
Itzhak Perlman, violin soloist 
Hosted by: Levine, Steve Martin, Bette Midler, Perlman, James Earl
Jones, Angela Lansbury, Quincy Jones, Penn and Teller 
Running time: 74 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes size does matter at the movies, and seeing ``Fantasia
2000'' in a regular theater, and not IMAX, where it was unveiled,
does make a difference. The difference is magnified by the fact
that the best sequence in the new Disney blend of animation and
classical music is one involving whales, and size is part of what
whales are about. It could be worse. On TV, they'd look like
mackerel. Still, the pod of whales rising out of the sea to float
like zeppelins in the clouds when they aren't gliding among ice
floes makes this new ``Fantasia'' mandatory viewing. Those whales
are the stars of this new ``Fantasia,'' and they're still pretty
impressive. If the sequence's cool greens and blues don't get you,
the trancy mystery of it all surely will.
</P>
<P>
   Set to Respighi's ``Pines of Rome,'' the whale number is an
instant classic that reminds us that it's much easier to set a
riveting ballet to a piece of second-rate music than to a towering
masterpiece. Still, the whales would arguably be even more
impressive against silence. As for the figurative big picture,
``Fantasia/2000'' consists of seven new segments and a reprised
Mickey Mouse in ``The Sorcerer's Apprentice.'' In part, it's a
demonstration of what Disney's artists can do with their new
computerized toys. It's impressive, but, like the original
``Fantasia,'' a bit undersupplied. In baseball terms, it's a solid
two-bagger, not a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Disney intended to update his 1940 ``Fantasia'' every few years.
But World War II intervened, ``Fantasia'' was a flop that didn't
move into the black until its abstract patternings turned it into a
money-making head movie in 1969, and music education itself took a
big leap forward in the intervening years _ partly due to
``Fantasia.'' Its signature frame is the one in which conductor
Leopold Stokowski is shown shaking hands with Mickey Mouse before
conducting the Philadelphia Orchestra. ``Fantasia'' was kitsch from
the start. And the music was truncated. But Stokowski fulfilled a
function few conductors could have. He was the most unabashedly
hammy of conductors, whose flamboyance earned him armies of
detractors. Yet he possessed artistic credentials that meant he had
to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In a time when America was still climbing out from under its
inferiority complex about Europe, he bridged a gap. James Levine,
who mostly conducts the Metropolitan Opera, but who has a history
with the Chicago Symphony, brings ease and poise to his
intermediary role here, reflecting the rollback in stiffness
between Americans and classical music. Disney has had the good
sense to divide the hosting among a handful of savvy, engaging
pros, ranging from Steve Martin to Bette Midler to Quincy Jones to
Angela Lansbury to Penn and Teller, who drolly reintroduce what
today looks like a very grainy Mickey Mouse, in his borrowed pointy
hat with the stars and the moons, trying to turn the magic off
before the brooms flood the sorcerer's lair with the pails of water
Mickey can't make them stop carrying in.
</P>
<P>
   If the grainy ``Sorcerer's Apprentice'' was included to show off
today's technical dazzle, provide continuity, and repeat
science-fiction's curiously reactionary warning to avoid
venturesomeness, the new episodes more than once genuflect to it
stylistically. In fact, they spend more time looking back than
forward. The geometric shapes that morph into butterfllies and bats
in the opening section (to Beethoven's Fifth) seem perfunctory,
less inspired than the corresponding abstractions accompanying
Stokowski's Bach in the original. The flamingos dancing to
Saint-Saens's ``Carnival of the Animals,'' if no less inspired than
the hippos twinkle-toeing their way through Ponchieli's ``Dance of
the Hours,'' are certainly no more inspired.
</P>
<P>
   The whale segment makes the best use of the computer's ability
to convey an almost lunar stillness, but the same director, Hendel
Butoy, is also behind the very different but certain to be the most
beloved new segment, the one that most potently feeds off the
vitality of its music. Setting Hans Christian Anderson's ``The
Steadfast Tin Soldier'' to the Allegro from Shostakovich's Piano
Concerto No. 2 freshens the film's traditional spirit with a
classy, affecting interplay, dark when it has to be, among a
ballerina, a menacing jack-in-the-box, and the brave one-legged toy
soldier.
</P>
<P>
   The kinetic, propulsive sequence set to Stravinsky's 1919
``Firebird'' Suite (second _ and leanest _ of the three he
extracted from the full score), depicting a pagan goddess
regenerating the earth after a volcanic demon consumes it in
flames, seems to owe more to the demon rising up out of
Mussorgsky's ``Night on Bald Mountain'' than to, say, the more
recent and more innovative take on nature in ``Princess Mononoke.''
It works as spectacle, whooshing through its motions as slickly as
``Tarzan.'' Yet it typifies much in the new ``Fantasia/2000'' in
that it seems more intent on establishing a firm link to the
traditional Disney house style than to pushing into challengingly
innovative territory.
</P>
<P>
   The episode in which Donald Duck acts as a gatekeeper for Noah,
ushering animals into the Ark to Elgar's Pomp and Circumstance
Marches, while nearly losing Daisy in the process, is attractive
enough, but it's just there, never really leaping off the screen in
a way that surprises and delights. The chapter played out to
Gershwin's `Rhapsody in Blue'' by characters from the pen of
Broadway's legendary Line King, Al Hirschfeld, is, surprisingly, a
bit of a letdown, too. New York never rides higher than on
Gershwin's music, while Hirschfeld's drawings, with their elegant
panache, are in themesleves a logo for Manhattan glamor. But these
modest Jazz Age vignettes are underwhelming. Too bad they couldn't
have included a few period celebs. The closest we get is a rich
woman's henpecked husband, who suggests Alexander Woollcott doing a
Walter Mitty number. See it for the whales and the tin soldier, but
``Fantasia/2000'' won't retire the first ``Fantasia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
