<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5866 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-CLIBURN-BOS &LR;      06-16 1420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CLIBURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNUAL VAN CLIBURN COMPETITION CELEBRATES THE JOYS OF AMATEURISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Rangy Van Cliburn strode to the podium and
spoke to the audience that eagerly awaited the results of the
second annual International Piano Competition For Outstanding
Amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank the 75 incredibly talented people who took
part in this competition,'' Cliburn said. ``They are wonderful
musicians, and they are all pianists, which is the most thrilling
thing in the world to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliburn, who emerges from semiretirement to play the Tchaikovsky
Concerto at Tanglewood Aug. 4 and a Fleet Celebrity Series recital
in Symphony Hall March 4, went on. ``I always found the stage to be
the loneliest place in the world. It's a strange kind of
loneliness, when you try to take something which exists only as ink
on paper and make it come alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The marquee on the movie theater in downtown Fort Worth last
weekend told the whole story of this competition _ ``Dinosaur,''
``Gladiator,'' ``Mission Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The piano no longer occupies the central position in musical
culture and family life that it held for at least a century. Those
who learn to play the instrument well are dinosaurs; those who
enter competitions are gladiators; those who hope to make society
recognize and respect the place the piano and its literature
occupies in their lives and imaginations have embarked on a mission
that is probably really impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But they do it anyway _ these doctors, lawyers, scientists,
computer whizzes, and homemakers, not to mention the TV anchor, the
blackjack dealer, the astrologer, and the assistant manager of a
Starbucks at Second and Ninth in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Cliburn was right to find this second amateur competition
inspiring. There was a lot of wonderful playing, and the collective
spirit felt incomparably better than it did last year, when I also
served on the press jury. Last year some veterans of the
professional competition circuit let nothing get in their way as
they played to win. Even in the second edition, there were several
pianists of professional caliber with impressive professional
credentials who are ``amateurs'' only because they have other
interests or face economic imperatives. Out of the corner of my
mouth I wondered if the next competition should institute a new
award for ``the best real amateur.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jury and press jury again worked for the love of it, like
amateurs, although the Cliburn Foundation did pick up the tab for
travel expenses and lodging, and the incomparable Fort Worth
hostesses vied with each other to produce the most sumptuous lunch.
A restaurant offered pie a la mode at breakfastime, and I had me
some; chicken-fried chicken came with two vegetables, which turned
out to be red beans and french fries _ my idea of vegetables.)
</P>
<P>
   Inspiring as the competition was, it was also profoundly
depressing. It represented a celebration of the piano and the
discipline of playing the instrument; it was a celebration of
music, and of the people who have to make music, no matter what.
But it was also an indictment of a society that has so little place
for people with musical gifts to exercise them, especially if they
want to live the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   The winner this year was the guy from Starbucks, Christopher
Basso, 41. He is a wonderful pianist and musician with a boyishly
engaging platform presence. He played a Scarlatti Sonata with
polish and dash; a poised and poetic Chopin Nocturne; some
elegantly voiced Rachmaninoff. Lots of people this year rushed in
where party animals fear to tread and offered ``L'Isle Joyeuse''
(known as ``Pleasure Island'' within the piano community), but
Basso was the only one who could actually play the notes and
transmute them into orgiastic delight. In the final round Basso
offered only one work, Prokofiev's Sonata No. 8, one of his war
sonatas. Basso used his corruscating virtuosity, his flexible
rhythmic spine, and his chameleon colors to communicate the sorrow,
the irony, the rage, and the compassion of this great score. He was
the unanimous first choice of the jury, the press jury, and the
audience (which was polled).
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation afterward, Basso said he had been at Starbucks
for six years. He works the early-morning shift, and counts that as
his social life, so he can spend the rest of the day with music.
``I've had a long series of odd jobs,'' he said. ``I've been a
bartender and waited tables like an actor between auditions. I
guess I'm afraid I never thought I was good enough to make a career
in music.''
</P>
<P>
   Basso did not study at one of the major East Coast
conservatories or work with teachers plugged into power-networking.
Although his bio says he won a ``top prize'' in a previous piano
competition in Cincinnati, he seems to have slipped through the net
_ which represents a damning criticism of the net. One hopes
Basso's victory in Fort Worth will produce something more
substantial than an amateur-size prize ($2,000, a recital in
Washington, D.C., and some CD goodies) and the opportunity to
become a poster boy for Starbucks. Basso is an artist, and there
are never enough of them.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the other pianists were interesting. There were three
contestants from New England. Gertrude Jonas, a retired string
teacher who is in her 80s and taking piano lessons at the New
England Conservatory, didn't make it past the first round, so I
didn't hear her, but she certainly embodied the spirit of the event
by remaining for the rest of the competition to hear and applaud
all the others. Robert Finley, an electrical engineer who lives
near Worcester, played straightforwardly and strongly in works by
Chopin and Brahms, but ran into some trouble with Ravel. He played
very late at night, and sheepishly came forward the next day to
explain that he was not used to playing ``Ondine'' after bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hawley, a professor of media technology at MIT and
onetime Duncan yo-yo champion, returned this year for a second try
at the gold. Hawley certainly deserves an honorable place on
Boston's incredible roster of significant, skilled, and exploratory
pianists. He was at his best in the semifinal round, playing a
group of nocturnal pieces. He opened with Faure, the gorgeous,
demanding, and rarely played 13th Nocturne. Then he doffed his
blazer, folded it on the floor, and offered lilting rags by William
Bolcom and a swinging virtuoso performance of Art Tatum's ``Sweet
Lorraine.'' It's no wonder he won the award for the most
adventurous programming.
</P>
<P>
   Hawley might have come in higher than fourth if the competition
had stopped at this point. In the Liszt Sonata during the final
round, the pianist offered was big, enthusiastic, and generously
detailed, but he did not succeed in pulling the work together and
hurling it like a bolt of lightning.
</P>
<P>
   I enjoyed court reporter and travel guide Michael Moore's
uncompromising performance of the Griffes Sonata, which he preceded
by Gottschalk's sentimental ``The Last Hope.'' There were some
flustered moments in Mozart's F-Major Sonata played by Allan
Fuller, director of casino games, but some very lovely ones too.
Flight attendant Charles Chien played Schumann's ``Waldszenen''
with haunting gradations of tonal color before nerves destroyed his
control in the Liszt Sonata.
</P>
<P>
   The most unusual pianist was Debra Saylor from Iowa. She is a
private voice teacher who did not bother to mention that she is
blind on her application. Like most of the other contestants,
Saylor is not a world-class virtuoso; what set her apart was that
she didn't pretend to be, and played well within her limits. She
has big enough chops to play Chopin's ``Fantaisie-Impromptu'' and
the finale of Beethoven's ``Moonlight'' Sonata, but she also
offered little bon-bons like Dvorak's ``Humoreske,'' played with
infectious zest, reminding us that what made this piece familiar
was how surprising it once was _ it never goes anywhere you expect
it to. You could tell Saylor is a singer from the size, beauty, and
warmth of her tone, and the breathing legato of her phrasing. Best
of all, every note means something to her, and she made it
meaningful to the rest of us. She plays straight from the heart,
and if more people did that, the recital business wouldn't be on
the skids. Saylor made us believe that being a pianist is the most
thrilling thing in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
