<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GROOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A GROOVE IN THIS DUO'S FUNKY HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The name couldn't be more perfect. Outfitted with a fleet of
funk-drenched samples and narcotic loops, British electronica duo
Groove Armada has scored the first full-bore dance hit of the
millennium _ and for good reason. Fatboy Slim's epic remix of ``I
See You Baby,'' along with the rest of Groove Armada's sophomore
disc ``Vertigo,'' is like manna from heaven for house music fans
who've had it with recycled disco snippets. Andy Cato and Tom
Findlay, both 27, ventured far beyond the beat-heavy confines of
the usual DJ fare, cobbling a collection of blissed-out club tomes
with such eclectic components as a 1957 Patti Page vocal, jazz
horns, endless references to doo-wop, and a deep and abiding
reverence for soul titans Sly Stone and Al Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see as our heritage people like Sly, and Stevie Wonder, and
funk bands,'' says Cato, on the phone from a hotel room in Chicago.
``We're trying to combine the brilliance of those grooves with
technology. We want to play modern music but keep that human
element.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Groove Armada has launched a US tour that inverts
the fundamental notion of contemporary dance music, bravely going
where no DJ has gone before. When Cato and Findlay take the stage
it isn't be behind a bank of turntables and DAT machines. Rather,
Groove Armada plays the music live, on instruments, with a
nine-piece band.
</P>
<P>
   The fleshed-out Groove Armada has played shows in LA, New York,
Denver, Dallas, and Chicago, and ``so far it's been amazing,'' says
Cato _ who grew up in Leeds, England, playing bass, keyboards, and
trombone. ``We'd done DJ trips to these cities, but a club show is
very, very different, and it kind of confirms what we expected.
Dallas is a good example. For the first couple of songs it was
really bizarre. People were just staring at the band. Nobody was
dancing. They were just watching. But then at the end of the song
they just exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   Explains Findlay, a native of Cambridge in England and veteran
of countless jazz and brass bands: ``We tried, even as we were
recording the album, to write musical phrases that sound human. We
didn't have the idea then that we would tour with a live band. With
us, you know, it's one hour at a time. But it makes the music feel
so personal. It's really rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   What many people don't realize is that many of the samples and
loops on ``Vertigo'' weren't lifted from other records, but were
recorded by Cato and Findlay, both of whom are
multi-instrumentalists. In that light, the leap to live performance
isn't as great as it might seem. ``The album was done in a
technology-based studio setting, but a lot of the grooves were
played live,'' says Cato, who adds that the impetus for this tour
came in part from industry biases against Groove Armada's style of
music. ``There's this perception in rock that dance music is a bit
of a fad, or a sham. Time and time again at festivals it's the rock
bands up front, and the dance music kind of stuck in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Groove Armada's music is being hailed as a bridge
between the underground club scene and mainstream pop. ``It's
accurate insofar as we can DJ the smallest, dingiest clubs playing
the weirdest dance music and we also have songs that your mom and
grandma like.'' The band has in fact amassed quite a collection of
fans, among them Elton John _ who reportedly bought 200 copies of
``Vertigo'' to pass out to his friends, and who insisted that Cato
and Findlay be flown in to play at an Interview magazine party he
was headlining at New York's Kit Kat Club. Madonna, another devoted
follower, put ``Vertigo'' on her top five list of albums for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is, Groove Armada just sounds different.
Likewise, Cato and Findlay neither look nor act much like what one
would imagine the DJs du jour would. They don't sport designer
labels, trendy haircuts, or Teflon gear. Both laugh heartily and
often. They're hardly career club crawlers; Findlay studied history
at Oxford, while Cato received a degree in American Studies at
Manchester University and worked as a soccer journalist and PR
person for Nike. The two were introduced through Cato's girlfriend
and soon after launched the Groove Armada nightclub in London in
1996, where they spun the hypnotic disco-funk that would eventually
wind up on their 1998 debut, ``Northern Star.''
</P>
<P>
   To make ``Vertigo,'' they retreated to a cottage in England's
bucolic Lake District _ once again skewering the conventional image
of gritty urban chic that's historically defined dance music. ``We
feel completely at home there,'' says Cato. ``It's a lovely
routine. There's no phone, for a start, and there's usually no cell
phone reception. All there is to do is get up in the morning, check
the tune you did late the night before, and go into the village to
get logs for the fire and some food.'' It's also where they found
``Back to the Fifties'' in a basket of 50-pence CDs _ the source
for Patti Page's sweet refrain of ``if you're fond of sand dunes
and salty air'' that forms the melancholic backbone of Groove
Armada's single ``To The River.''
</P>
<P>
   Cato and Findlay have begun work on the follow-up to
``Vertigo,'' this time in a rustic house in Wales. Groove Armada's
touring band (which includes a guitarist they met doing
door-to-door radio surveys and an MC who is on Tom's soccer team)
holed up for a week of non-stop improvisation, all of which was
captured on tape. ``We've got about 20 15-minute-long jams that
will be our starting point,'' says Cato. ``Next, we'll sample to
give it a contemporary feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing the record will have to happen in piecemeal fashion,
though, says Cato, who hopes to complete it during downtime between
European festival dates this summer. In the meantime, Groove Armada
is busy mastering the translation of flawless, machine-made music
into the very imperfect setting of live instrumentation. ``It's a
technical challenge,'' says Cato. ``Playing this stuff on big PA
systems, you have to thin out the sound, keep it simple, give it
space. We're trying to combine that looped, hypnotic feel and not
restrict these amazing players.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Findlay is grooving mightily on the mere idea of
getting out from behind his turntable, and in turn upending the
whole idea of what it is to be a DJ playing dance music. ``You know
some people in the UK think it's a bit tacky that we get up on
stage and jump around. There's this overwhelming sense of cool that
surrounds dance music, and we're just up there enjoying ourselves.
And we're not ashamed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
