<HEADLINE>
`BOYS AND GIRLS' GETS IT TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BOYS AND GIRLS 
Directed by: Robert Iscove 
Screenplay by: The Drews: Andrew Lowery and Andrew Miller 
Starring: Freddie Prinze, Jr., Claire Fiorlani, Jason Biggs, Amanda
Detmer, Heather Donahue 
Running time: 
Rated: PG-13 (sexual content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing that isn't a delight about ``Boys and Girls'' is
its generic title. Otherwise, it's a screenful of nonstop charm and
credibility with smart, hip dialogue and a radical determination to
allow its young couple to take their time before the inevitable
get-together. When Freddie Prinze Jr.'s Ryan and Claire Forlani's
Jennifer finally kiss, there's really something behind it,
including that rarest of ingredients in a campus romance _ a shared
history and a few years of friendship before the big clinch.
</P>
<P>
   Forlani was one of the few bright spots in that black hole of
moviegoing, ``Meet Joe Black.'' At the time, you wondered what she
could do in a movie that didn't have a death wish. Here's where we
find out. Forlani's Jennifer is that rarest of romantic comedy
heroines, a commitmentphobe whose neuroses never rain on her
appeal. She's the big reason ``Boys and Girls'' plays like a
college version of ``When Harry Met Sally.'' She's needy, but
Jennifer's brains and empathy make her adorable, and Forlani has
the chops to stay with her zigs and zags.
</P>
<P>
   Prinze's Ryan, who looks like a blend of Robert Downey Jr. and a
young Tim Robbins, is believable as a cautious, plan-ahead type who
would know enough to wait for Jennifer's inevitable retreat once
the first few steps beyond friendship had been taken. His charm is
not the kind that has to break through a muted exterior; he's
charming precisely because he comes on softly, insofar as he comes
on at all. Screenwriters Andrew Lowery and Andrew Miller _
economically known as The Drews _ give them lots of bright,
sentient lines to volley while their fears recede.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Jennifer and Ryan live in states of near-perpetual
retreat demand a pair of zany sidekicks. These are provided by
Jason Biggs and Amanda Detmer, who find ways to snatch just enough
individuality and verve from their stereotypes to put a fresh gloss
on them. For once, you can believe these kids could actually hold
their own academically in a good college, in this case the
University of California's Berkeley campus, which, ever since ``The
Graduate,'' has imparted a built-in advantage to romantic comedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys and Girls'' knows how to use its seductive settings _
Berkeley, San Francisco, and the Marin foothills, with their
terrific view of the Golden Gate Bridge and the city behind it.
Audiences accustomed to the usual brainless boy-girl stuff may find
themselves fighting impatience with the time it takes until this
couple couples. But they're such engaging company that it's worth
the wait. ``Boys and Girls'' is a comedy with a keen awareness of
everything that can go wrong in a relationship. That's one of the
things that makes it go so right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
