<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SHAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIGH-VOLTAGE, 21ST-CENTURY `SHAFT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SHAFT 
Directed by: John Singleton 
Screenplay by: Richard Price (novel: Ernest Tidyman) 
Starring: Samuel L. Jackson, Vanessa Williams, Jeffrey Wright,
Christian Bale, Dan Hedaya, Busta Rhymes, Toni Collette, Richard
Roundtree 
Running time: 94 minutes 
Rated: R (strong violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, someone has remembered how to remake a slick, bang-bang
action movie. We're talking about ``Shaft,'' as in John Shaft, the
private eye invented by a cherubic newspaperman from Ohio. Shaft
was a big screenful of flamboyant fun when Richard Roundtree played
him in 1971 and became the king of blaxploitation. At least half
the reason the new ``Shaft'' is cooler, grittier, and more
explosive than the original is the casting of Samuel L. Jackson in
the title role. Jackson is today's undisputed king of cool. Wearing
Shaft's long black leather overcoat as if he was born to it, he's
both righteous and believably dangerous as the new Shaft, a cop
with a short fuse, running a vicious racist killer to ground.
</P>
<P>
   With Jackson in command of the Harlem streets, maintaining a
tension and an edge, director John Singleton charges the air around
the new Shaft with equivalent electricity and involvement. As a
boy, Singleton fell in love with the original ``Shaft,'' has wanted
to remake it for years, and has successfully rejiggered it for the
new century as a smart screenful of copz 'n' crookz 'n' the hood.
The new ``Shaft'' isn't so much a remake of the original as a
reinvention of it. It's as different in its tone, in its details,
in its world, as 2000 is from 1971. Still, it reminds us that while
the original ``Shaft'' may have been a landmark of black
empowerment, there's still a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   The new film is dominated by seething racist simmer. Much of it
takes place in bleak daylight and the virus of racism is much more
upfront. The original arose from the kidnapping of a Harlem gang
kingpin's daughter. This new one pushes off from a racist taunt in
a Manhattan bar that results in the vicious bludgeoning to death of
a black man. The problem lies not in identifying the murderer _ an
arrogant narcissist played by Christian Bale as a sort of extension
of his ``American Psycho'' character _ but in bringing him to
justice. In large part because the killer is the son of an
immensely wealthy real estate mogul, it isn't easy, but Shaft is
not one to shrug his shoulders and walk away.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to Jackson's impact is his economy. Although he isn't
stingy with bullets in the shootouts, he mostly scores by standing
there and doing just enough to look both dangerous and unflappable.
Not easy when you've also got to float the wiseguy lingo of the
private eye genre, and make a definite fashion statement in that
long, swirling trademark coat _ all that's left of the fly clothes
of the original. But Jackson does it all by never overdoing. He
leaves the flapping to Bale's nasty brat and to his unlikely ally,
a Harlem neighborhood drug dealer who isn't afraid to think big,
or, in Jeffrey Wright's juicy performance, act big. Jackson and
Bale are simply too high-profile to be eclipsed here, but Wright
comes out of left field to go toe-to-toe with them.
</P>
<P>
   Roundtree climbs aboard, too, providing validating presence.
Looking amazingly fit considering that he originated the role 29
years ago, Roundtree low-keys it as uncle Shaft, who wants his
nephew to stop trying to fight crime from the inside as a cop and
join his detective agency instead. Roundtree even low-keys Shaft's
babe-on-each-arm-exit from a bar, but then one of the smart things
about this new ``Shaft'' is that it knows when to low-key things.
Vanessa Williams's police officer reminds us with presence that the
race gulf has been narrowed. Toni Collette, as an eyewitness on the
run because she's afraid to testify, says almost nothing, which
makes her seem all the more convincingly traumatized. The new
``Shaft,'' driven by Richard Price's gritty screenplay, is as
naturalistic as it it cartoony. Maybe a bit more so. With Jackson
leading the way, ``Shaft'' has style, punch, and street cred. It's
a hot cool update.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
