<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOU REED TALKS UP `ECSTASY,' PLAYS DOWN CHARITABLE SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crusty and cynical are words often used to describe street poet,
punk-rock survivor Lou Reed. Caring and charitable are not words
that jump to mind, yet Reed has somehow been at many of the benefit
shows of magnitude in the past 15 years, from Farm Aid to a
performance for the Pope in Rome last year to dramatize the cause
of allowing Third World countries to be released from their debt to
industrial nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing to talk about, really,'' Reed says, downplaying
the socially conscious side of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always done these things,'' he finally adds. ``It's an
easy, fun thing to do and it's one of the few uses of celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The thick-skinned Reed has also been part of the Rock Against
Racism movement and Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a zillion worthwhile charities,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   However, don't expect to lure Reed into an elaborate discussion
of these issues in an interview. ``I don't want to pontificate,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   He's also often quick to make light of his involvement. Asked,
for example, what it was like to play for the Pope, Reed says, ``I
tell people we got together and played checkers and I let him
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The other side of Reed, of course, is the unflinching street
observer who, since his '60s involvement with the Velvet
Underground, has written songs about mean streets and misfits that
are unsurpassed. His latest album, ``Ecstasy,'' is more of the same
_ a rough-hewn, rock 'n' roll manual on the highs and lows of city
life, with scarifying, sometimes profanity-laced, looks at everyone
from troubled couples to crack dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very physical album,'' he says in an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   And a very uncensored one, which is Reed's stock in trade. The
lyrics aren't about to land him on Top 40 radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they would. That wasn't the intent. The intent
was to make a great record,'' Reed says.
</P>
<P>
   The album rocks hard right away with a Reed gem, ``Paranoia Key
of E.'' The lyrics say: ``Let's play a game the next time we meet/
I'll be the hands and you be the feet/ And together we will keep
the beat/ To paranoia key of E/ Now you know mania's in the key of
B/ Psychosis in the key of C/ Let's hope that we're not meant to be
in paranoia key of E.'' He adds: ``Let's have a coda in the key of
K _ something only we can play.''
</P>
<P>
   It's clever, insightful, and unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The song `Paranoia Key of E' is about one of my favorite
subjects _ paranoia,'' he says. Lovers of his lyrics should also
know that he just issued a complete book of lyrics, ``Pass Thru
Fire,'' put out by Hyperion Books. It spans his career from the
Velvet Underground through today.
</P>
<P>
   Reed is rocking again on the new album, but, in recent years, he
has also developed an instinct for theater that has kept him busy.
He and His friend, Robert Wilson, finished ``Poetry,'' a play about
Edgar Allan Poe that is being performed in Germany and will have a
10-day run at the Brooklyn Academy of Music in November of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, he's hitting the road with a band that he has
proudly kept together for some time. ``This is the band I record
with, too,'' he says. ``We're a real band. It's not me and backup
musicians. It's a real band.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Reed's tour will be opening act Victoria Williams. She
has multiple sclerosis, yet Reed is one of the musicians who
appeared on the benefit album for her, titled ``Sweet Relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Is she going to join his set?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll play it by ear,'' he says. ``I've played with her
before. She's a great guitar player. Keep your eye on Victoria.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1354EDT &QL; 
