<HEADER>
A5893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-SYRIA-BASHAR-$ADV18-C     06-16 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-BASHAR-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BASHAR ASSAD FACES SYRIAN PUBLIC UNCOMPROMISING ON ISRAEL, PEACE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QARDAHA, Syria _ As Syria's likely next president, Bashar Assad
took condolences here in his family's hometown last week amid the
forces that had ensured his father's 30-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   Loyal troops lined the streets. Businessmen, farmers and rent,
he would say, could kill me if I gave up any of Syria's land.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be right to kill me,'' Assad would add.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, deep in the narrow streets of Damascus' walled old
city, Abu Hassan agreed. The 39-year-old father of four has been
serving tea for 12 years. He hears enough talk to know the pulse of
the ancient city.
</P>
<P>
   Told of Assad's comments, he concurred. He made a pistol with
his index finger and pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any president who gives up one inch of land, he will be
dead,'' he said. ``If it is not poison, something else will happen
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel captured the Golan Heights, on the border of the two
countries, in 1967. Israelis say Syrian gunners used to fire down
from the strategic high ground at citizens below.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians deny that charge. They say Israel took the Golan Heights
so it could have more room to settle Jewish immigrants from Europe
and the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In the loss, more than 80,000 Syrians fled the land where they
had lived for generations. With family growth, they now number
several hundred thousand refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians feel like they should not have to deal, or even ask, to
receive land that was theirs. They also believe that they should
get land according to borders that would take Syria right to the
shore of the Sea of Galilee. Israelis want to keep the lake's(CQ)
edge, citing an older set of borders.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than give in, Syrians commonly say that they will
continue to pay the price that their opposition to peace with
Israel has helped bring. Most analysts agree that Syria's hard line
has helped isolate it from the West and hindered its economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The land is more important to us than our suffering,'' said
Monsour Ajak, a 37-year-old accountant watching Assad's funeral
last week.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Syria is, after all, where Salah Ed-Din and Mamluke Sultan
Beybars, who trounced the European Crusaders, are entombed. They
are heroes here like George Washington and Abraham Lincoln are in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Assad was sometimes compared to Salah Ed-Din.
</P>
<P>
   He ruled three decades. Though he often crushed dissent with
prison terms or executions, Syrian public opinion still mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Arab leaders, Assad would use his hard line against
Israel to build popular support. He felt that it was his firm
stance that gave him credibility with Syrians and Arabs throughout
the region.
</P>
<P>
   That credibility helped keep him in power while he fought other
internal challenges, such as insurrections from Islamic
fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   He also helped reinforce the intransigence. The Syrian press,
controlled by the government, is notoriously anti-Israel and has
even engaged in Holocaust denial to build its case.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean a deal is impossible. The Syrian public today
might not be any more anti-Israel than Egyptians were in the early
1980s, when then-President Anwar Sadat signed a treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He made a bold move, but paid the price for it when he was
assassinated in 1982. Assad was among the Arab leaders who refused
to attend his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   King Hussein of Jordan also faced stiff local opposition for his
treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Egyptian and Jordanian deals just make Syrians feel
that their resistance is even more needed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bashar Assad is young and untested. He was originally
trained to be an eye doctor, not a president.
</P>
<P>
   He has built his reputation on fighting corruption and seeking
to reform Syria's economy. He may still face rivals for his job and
most expect him to set aside tough foreign policy issues until his
power is secure.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, U.S. President Bill Clinton and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright seemed to be trying to give Bashar Assad a nudge
onto the peace path.
</P>
<P>
   They did it by adapting his father's legacy to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Hafez Assad had entered peace talks, they said he
had made a ``strategic decision'' that Syria needed peace. They
appeared to hope that would help Bashar Assad make the same
decision.
</P>
<P>
   But, Syrians may read Assad's legacy differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was steadfast from the very beginning of his life,'' said
Ajak, the accountant. ``He never signed any agreement that did not
guarantee the rights of the Arabs. He died and never signed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.washingtoninstitute.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
