<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER FATHER WHOM I KNEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was a tall, quiet-spoken Dane with blue eyes, an aquiline
nose and a distinctive blond flat-top that he wore habitually until
the day he died _ except for that brief experimental phase when he
let it grow out, along with a goatee that came in red. He took so
much ribbing from us kids _ stuff about Eric the Red and his Viking
roots showing _ that it was back to the barber and the burr.
</P>
<P>
   He was an aerospace engineer by training, a graduate of the
University of Arkansas who was inwardly disappointed that none of
his kids decided to attend his alma mater when they reached college
age. It didn't take much goading to get him to call the hogs, and
the usually reticent speaker would go on and on about his
experiences at the Fayetteville boarding house where he lived while
at school.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny the things you remember about a parent years after he
is gone. When Daddy Warren wore shorts, you could see that his
ankles to about mid-shin were as hairless and smooth as a woman's.
In his Chicago youth, he was a competitive speed skater, and the
repeated application and removal of the tape used to bind his
ankles left him permanently plucked.
</P>
<P>
   He never ate anything with his fingers, not even a sandwich.
Using a knife and fork, that man could clean a fried chicken bone
slicker than any two-fisted diner ever imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Details about everyday life would often escape him, which was
intriguing to my brother, sister and me because his highly
technical mind earned him super-classified status at the aerospace
company where he worked. He traveled a lot with his job, overseeing
manufacturing and facilities development for General Dynamics
around the globe. Mom tried to mess with him when he returned home
after extended leaves _ she'd change her hair color and see how
long it took for him to notice. She invariably had to tell him what
was different because it just didn't register with him.
</P>
<P>
   The family has wonderful high school graduation pictures of my
twin brother and the gal standing in line ahead of him _ instead of
Jack and me, who was in line behind him. Daddy had the camera
focused on the long blond hair nearest my brother. I had shorn my
locks weeks before graduation; Daddy just hadn't noticed.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't an openly demonstrative man, but we knew he adored his
pre-assembled family. It couldn't have been easy for him at first,
to marry the widow with three young children and then almost
immediately move them from Fort Worth to San Diego, where he had
been transferred. But he worshipped his new bride, whose
personality was so opposite of _ yet so compatible with _ his, and
her little ones.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rotating duty every Christmas Eve for one of us kids to
accompany Daddy on his shopping trip for Mom, which always included
a fabulous piece of jewelry. He waited until the last day because,
he said, that's when you captured the true holiday spirit. (It must
have been his latent Viking thirst for adventure).
</P>
<P>
   My sister and I spent late into the night wrapping boxes, and he
spent late into the night writing limericks and verses to go on
each tag, hinting at the contents of the package. Hearing Mom read
those aloud on Christmas Day was as much fun as watching her face
when she'd open the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   He offered one piece of career advice as I was about to begin my
post-college life. He had worked for the same company for 39 years.
As a child of the Depression who watched his own father scramble to
take care of his family, Daddy Warren was bound and determined to
provide stability for his own family, even if it meant passing up
on opportunities to change companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had it to do all over, I'd take more risks,'' he said.
``You'll never know how far you can go unless you try.''
</P>
<P>
   Like my biological father, who died too soon in a test flight at
Edwards Air Force Base, my stepfather died too soon of a massive
heart attack shortly after his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He had built a beautiful life for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Not every child is blessed to have one wonderful father. I was
blessed to have two.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
