<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARING SECRETS ABOUT OURSELVES LEADS TO HEALING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's always something that compels some readers to write.
</P>
<P>
   Others keep putting it off and eventually make a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   I understand. I do the same thing myself.
</P>
<P>
   I've been looking at a card from a reader for three weeks now,
telling myself over and over that only a personal note in response
will be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of you write on your personal stationery, preferring to
communicate via e-mail, in which case I can respond right away. Or
rather, I try.
</P>
<P>
   Some of you are like old friends now. Sue Williams, DH and
Deborah Evans-Young come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   When I wrote about my mother recently, Deborah Evans-Young
responded with this: ``Beautiful! I am so sorry you lost your
mother at an early age. Happy Mother's Day!''
</P>
<P>
   She was among dozens who wrote to comfort me. Others who also
lost their mothers simply wanted to thank me for saying what they
hadn't found the words to express.
</P>
<P>
   You tell me I do that a lot. And so I'm reminded daily how much
of humanity is the same, and wouldn't it be wonderful if we cared
for each other that way all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading your article was like reading about myself and six
siblings,'' one mother wrote. ``I learned to appreciate Mother's
Day and to share it with second moms that God brought into my life.
... This year, I celebrated my first Mother's Day with my husband
and 8 1/2-month-old son. Thank you for reminding me of that truth
and for once again sharing your heart so beautifully. Keep touching
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   I liked that note, recognizing that we all have the opportunity
to touch one another. Often, though, that means revealing something
of who we are, being willing to share even those things that
another person might use to hurt us.
</P>
<P>
   I've hesitated invoking my religious beliefs, for instance, more
than once. Not because I'm ashamed of my Christianity, but because
I recognize I am not perfect, and for many people, being Christian
means never making wrong decisions.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, I thought I might use this space today to
thank those of you who share shameful and painful events in your
life with me, especially those who allow me to tell your stories in
this space.
</P>
<P>
   You're touching lives as well.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen _ the woman who was sexually abused by her brother,
step-grandfather and a neighbor when she was a girl _ comes to
mind. Like my Mother's Day story, hers was at once singular and
universal.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Carmen, others found the courage to share their
painful stories about abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Perkins, executive director of the Women's Center of
Tarrant County, says that part of the problem in dealing with
victims of sexual abuse is that many of them are still in denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to look beyond our door and admit people are
hurting,'' she says. ``But they are, and this is one of the last
horrible secrets we still haven't confronted in this society.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mind in Sacramento had this to say: ``Just read your
column about Carmen and abused women. Really powerful and
insightful.''
</P>
<P>
   And a local reader wrote: ``Sunday's column on sexual abuse
really hit home. ... DON'T leave this subject alone _ for so long
no one would talk about it. Sexual abuse is something that affects
your whole life FOREVER.''
</P>
<P>
   There might be others who still can't speak about their pain.
The Women's Center can help. So can other social service agencies.
If you need help, PLEASE call.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7400, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
