<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5906 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FOSSE-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-16 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSSE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ENERGETIC CELEBRATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after Sun., June 18, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If watching Kobe Bryant go through his airborne acrobatics makes
the average spectator want to grab a basketball, head to the
nearest court and dust off some choice moves, it stands to reason a
few hours spent gazing on the efforts of the ``Fosse'' dancers
might provoke a similar inspiration: Honey, have you seen my tap
shoes and bowler?
</P>
<P>
   Don't even think about it. The director/choreographer who
inspired ``Fosse'' dropped dead of a heart attack at age 60. He may
not have been dancing at that fateful moment, but after seeing,
say, the very fit Terace Jones maneuver his way through Fosse's
difficult ``Percussion 4'' from the 1978 musical, ``Dancin','' you
can imagine how somebody could literally expire in mid-stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say Jones or any of the 20 expert dancers in
``Fosse'' _ the celebratory revue of Bob Fosse's work now on stage
at the Shubert Theatre through July 9 _ appear to be in any danger.
In this energetic and highly entertaining musical, the company
makes very difficult choreography look all but effortless. Quite
simply, they and the show are a pleasure to watch. And with Don
York holding the baton, there figures to be steam heat aplenty for
the next few weeks in Century City.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a ``let's get up and dance'' kind of pleasure? Only
sporadically. The selections, which span four decades of Fosse's
work in film, television and stage, are dark, moody, and even a
little deranged as often as they are joyous. For every ``I Wanna Be
a Dancin' Man'' _ the straw hat, white pin- stripe-suited ode to
Fred Astaire _ there's a sneering number like ``Razzle Dazzle''
from ``Chicago.'' Once again, no knock on the man or his product:
Fosse lived hard and his work _ selected for ``Fosse'' by director
Richard Maltby Jr., Chet Walker and Ann Reinking _ reflects the
edginess of his vision.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the chorus of taxi girls in ``Big Spender'' (from
``Sweet Charity''), slinking and cajoling their way up to a
railing, trying to entice customers. Watch the aggression with
which they seem to attach themselves to a railing at the front of
the stage, starring down the audience. Equally angry is ``Big
Spender's'' counterpoint number which finds the Kit Kat dancers
chair-dancing a kiss-off through ``Cabaret's'' ``Mein Herr.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexuality, in case you hadn't guessed, plays a fairly explicit
role in much of Fosse's work, although the ``Fosse'' selections
don't include a lot of partner or couple dances. (The silhouetted
male-female and same sex ballet, ``Take Off With Us,'' is the most
notable exception). Instead, we get group numbers, trios and an
occasional solo. Reva Rice, the smooth as velvet headliner, handles
most of the torch songs including two renditions of ``Life is Just
a Bowl of Cherries.''
</P>
<P>
   With the inclusion of a set from Fosse's autobiographical 1979
movie ``All That Jazz,'' Maltby and Reinking give us dance trying
to beat back death in ``There'll Be Some Changes Made.''
Immediately following that number is the less desperate but equally
sad version ``Mr. Bojangles'' where we watch a legendary dancer
(Cassel Miles) reaching the end of his reign.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Fosse II'' might opt to display some of the choreographer's
more playful work, but the current selection has more than enough
white gloves, thigh patting and sheer verve to please both Fosse
devotees and those simply looking for a good show. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
What: ``Fosse.''
</P>
<P>
   Where: Shubert Theatre, 2020 Avenue of the Stars, Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: Through July 9, performances Tuesdays-Saturdays at 8 p.m.,
Saturdays and Sundays at 2 p.m.; Sundays at 7:30 p.m. &QL; 
Tickets: $40-$70. Call (213) 628-2772. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5908 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CARREY-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      06-16 1765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARREY-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TAMING OF JIM CARREY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after Mon., June 18, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Settling down doesn't work quite the same way for Jim Carrey as
it does for most guys.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the manic, raunchy, Canadian comedian who became a
superstar by seemingly never outgrowing puberty is starring once
again in the grossest comedy of the summer, ``Me, Myself and
Irene.'' Next up, he'll be seen as the most alarming holiday party
pooper since Ebenezer Scrooge in the ``How the Grinch Stole
Christmas'' feature film. Meanwhile, the media is all abuzz, as it
has been before, about Carrey's new, high-profile romance.
</P>
<P>
   And, asked to offer parenting tips for Father's Day, the first
suggestion that pops out of his mouth is, ``Just make sure that
they don't end up on a building with a 'scope.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is, nonetheless, a Jim Carrey at peace with himself.
Speaking confidently and thoughtfully in a New York hotel room,
looking understatedly sharp in a Navy suit and finely woven, coral
blue t-shirt, the box office superstar shows no signs of the mental
unease evident late last year, when he was infamously still
possessed by the spirit of Andy Kaufman, whom he so fiercely
impersonated in his last, atypically unsuccessful feature, ``Man on
the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrey is polite, self-revealing, effortlessly witty without
ever begging for a laugh. He is the picture of hard-won
contentment.
</P>
<P>
   Getting paid to go psychotic, obviously, has a therapeutic
value. &QL; 
He's a gentle, wacky character
</P>
<P>
   In ``Irene,'' Carrey plays a gentle-to-a-fault, Rhode Island
state trooper, Charlie Baileygates, whose suppressed rage comes out
in another personality that calls itself Hank, a sleazy, abusive,
gratification-hungry sociopath. When both personae fall in love
with Renee Zellweger's title straightwoman, the physical and vulgar
humor that's made Carrey famous in ``Liar, Liar,'' ``Dumb &AMP;
Dumber,'' ``The Mask'' and the ``Ace Ventura'' movies kicks into
gear like never before.
</P>
<P>
   And we do mean like never before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what's happening is that a little more realism is
coming into the characters that I play,'' Carrey says. ``Now, it's
becoming a mix between the dramas and the comedies; in a sense, a
little bit more believable.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Charlie and Hank may be extreme types _ the film is,
after all, written and directed by Peter and Bobby Farrelly of
``There's Something About Mary'' and ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber'' notoriety _
Carrey shades each one, and the area between them, with an
unexpected range of subtle, convincing touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came internally, actually, and that was the weird thing
about creating these characters,'' he explains. ``It wasn't just
about making a face, it was more like where the guy's coming from,
and the rest creates itself. I can't say I didn't think at all
about the physicality of it, because the two guys had to be
different, but the thing was, you wanted a little of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be funny, first of all,'' he acknowledges. ``But
you've got to know the psychology of both characters, what's
missing from the one guy _ which I recognize completely, because I
come from a long line of people who'd rather just keep the smile on
their face and take the shot in the chops to avoid confrontation _
and make Hank the embodiment of everything that Charlie's missing,
but too much so.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's not afraid to get `physical'
</P>
<P>
   According to his co-star, watching Carrey put all that and more
together for any given scene was a marvel to behold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept thinking, God, I wish everybody had the opportunity to
see this,'' Zellweger says. ``It's very easy to underestimate the
skill that's required to pull that stuff off. He makes it look so
easy, he's so good at it and he's so unique in his physical ability
to animate those comedic moments, that you don't think about all
the work that's behind it. I guess that's the point. But at the
same time, watching him create it makes you appreciate the vast
range of ability that he had to apply.''
</P>
<P>
   To say nothing of pain tolerance, too. Carrey puts himself
through as many physical contortions in ``Irene'' as he did in
``The Mask,'' but without the aid of reality-warping computer
graphics. He's beaten, bonked, bowled over and defiled in a
kaleidoscope of torment not seen since his days as Fire Marshal
Bill on the ``In Living Color'' skitcom. And, as was the case with
that defining character, his worst tormentor is himself, as Hank
and Charlie fight over control of the tortured Baileygates body.
</P>
<P>
   All in a well-paid day's work, the actor reckons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was probably one of the most physical things that I've
ever done,'' says Carrey, who suffered a sprained ankle during
rehearsals and admits being hurt just about every day during the
shooting of ``Irene.'' ``I don't like the stuntman to do it unless
it's, like, life-threatening in some way. If it means a bruise or a
bang if you do it wrong, than I'd rather do it myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Buster Keaton comedy tradition, y'know? The
audience wants to know that it's you doing the bit. A lot of these
things won't look the same with somebody else's physicality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, beating myself up comes easy,'' Carrey jokes, sort
of. ``I love to beat the hell out of myself, I've done it
emotionally for years, so I just physically manifested it.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Really.
</P>
<P>
   There is, not unusually, a sad child at the core of the crazy
clown. Although he was born into a middle class home in the Toronto
suburbs, Carrey's father suffered job setbacks that forced the
family to live out of a van. The teen-age Jim had to quit school to
pitch in with the janitorial business that was the only thing that
kept the family going.
</P>
<P>
   Years of struggle on the comedy club circuit and the lower rungs
of the Hollywood casting ladder followed. There was a marriage, to
actress Melissa Womer, that produced a daughter, Jane, before
coming apart just as film stardom finally hit big, in 1995. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's finding happiness in his real life
</P>
<P>
   Whatever damage these and other traumas have done to Carrey's
psyche, they apparently haven't destroyed the fundamental sweetness
that's made even his darkest, most offensive comic gambits
palatable (well, except for maybe ``The Cable Guy'').
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, when Zellweger was promoting her previous movie ``The
Bachelor,'' she spent the better part of a weekend denying reports
that she and Carrey were an item.
</P>
<P>
   ``For days I was telling everybody, 'Yeah, he's wonderful and I
really like him and we had a great time and he's warm and generous
and really kind and I've never had so much fun working with
somebody and it was one of the greatest summers of my life . . .
But we're not dating.' And then I went home and started thinking,
wow, I really miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Carrey tends to use the word gem a lot when
speaking about Zellweger, whom he started seeing publicly early
this year. For a star who has developed something of a reputation
for hitting on leading ladies (Carrey was briefly married to ``Dumb
&AMP; Dumber'' co-star Lauren Holly and was reported to have had an
affair with Courtney Love when they made ``Man on the Moon''), the
drawn-out courtship was, by all evidence, a euphoric experience for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renee is a great person, and she is what she seems to be, very
straightforward,'' Carrey says of the remarkably sweet-natured,
bright and unpretentious Texan. ``I don't go into these things
hoping, `I'm gonna get this one,' that's not how I operate. Why I
wanted Renee in the movie in the first place was not to go after
her, but to be supported by somebody who I could learn something
from and trust to stand on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly think that she's one of the most incredible
actresses out there,'' he continues to gush before letting a little
Hank take over. ``She makes me envious, frankly, and insecure about
myself and what I've done. It's only a matter of time before she
wins the Oscar, and I'll have to sit there and smile and applaud.
It's really going to be hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny. But like Carrey's best gags, also loaded with multiple
levels of sarcastic, satiric meaning. He's riffing here on the
widely held belief that he made his last two movies, the Media Age
existential drama ``The Truman Show'' and ``Man on the Moon,'' in
pursuit of Academy Awards he was not even nominated for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the hardest thing about all that is people's
perception that I would be destroyed by it in some way,'' Carrey
says of Oscar's indifference. ``I appreciate that people are
pulling for me, for sure. But anything that happens like that, that
might not be exactly what you want it to be, just makes you
stronger and better at what you do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I had made I don't know how many films in that
total, whacko comedy mode. I do two dramas and I'm not expecting to
be recognized critically at all for them, but I got good critiques
in droves and I was very happy and surprised by that. But I don't
expect (academy voters) to give in so soon. They still remember Ace
Ventura talking through his butt _ and they'll remember it again
because I've gone back to `Irene,' and I don't ever want to lose
that part of myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact is that I'm allowed to do `The Truman Show' and
`Man on the Moon' and this very heavy film called `Phone Booth'
next, which is basically a two-week shoot that takes place entirely
in a phone booth and is a tremendous challenge that would probably
scare the best of actors. Plus, I have a great life. I have a
beautiful daughter and a wonderful girlfriend, amazing things. You
know, what do I need? I don't need a statue. But I would appreciate
it if I got it.''
</P>
<P>
   We've heard about the girlfriend. Carrey's daughter, now 12,
reportedly enjoys an involved father who, to her classmates'
delight, attends school functions and the whole bit.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, Carrey's second, real bit of Father's Day advice?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just love your kids, period. Make them feel like they're the
most important thing in the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   So you see, Jim Carrey really is a mature, stable, gentle
fellow. Those things he does to the neighbors, that cow and the
nursing mother in ``Me, Myself and Irene''? Hey, just think how
much fun it would be to have a dad like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this streak which is, like, `Where can I go that is two
steps beyond where they would expect me ever to go,' '' he
explains, ``and still, somehow, be funny, and somehow within that,
have there be a sweetness to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
