<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5909 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-VIOLINIST-FINGER-2TAK     06-16 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLINIST-FINGER-2TAKES-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INJURIES CAN LEAVE MUSICIANS PLAYING THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, June 18)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Violin in her left hand, bow in her
right, Jill Levy glanced up at the soaring maple arc of United
Methodist Church in Saratoga Springs. She looked around at the
chairs, the cool green carpet, the knotty pine ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I was here it was in February, and I couldn't play
at all,'' she said, preparing to rehearse on a sunny Thursday
afternoon for a recital three days later with pianist Jacinthe
Couture. ``And now I can play, and it's still strange.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been six months, just about, since Levy cut her left hand
in a mundane kitchen accident at her home in Stony Creek, six
months of surgery and splinting and therapy and more therapy and,
later, therapy. The injury to her ring finger _ violinists call it
the third finger; doctors call it the fourth _ occurred while she
was washing dishes late one night and grabbed at a falling glass.
The glass broke and sliced into her hand, severing tendon and
nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was, for 18 hours, just devastated, thinking I might never
be able to play again in the same way,'' she said. When the Glens
Falls surgeon who sewed up her hand reassured her that ``most''
people regain ``most'' flexibility following such a procedure, Levy
``was horrified. ... I said, `Most? I need all.'''
</P>
<P>
   Levy's tale has a happy ending: The Albany Symphony Orchestra
concertmaster is back performing, her left hand holding up
reasonably well to the digital rigors of the violin. But her story
is hardly unique. Like athletes and dancers, musicians train their
bodies to perform extraordinary tasks. They devote hours a day and
years of their lives to that end. In many cases they start their
training as small children, crafting not just careers out of music
but often whole identities: Simply put, music becomes their lives.
</P>
<P>
   And when an kitchen flub or a stress injury threatens to end the
music, those lives are thrown into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Pianists Gary Graffman and Leon Fleischer, two of the more
prominent examples, both lost the use of their right hands _ and
both found ways to adjust, mining the repertoire for left hand
alone or, in Fleischer's case, conducting. Cellist Lynn Harrell
suffered carpal tunnel syndrome in both hands and needed surgery to
correct it.
</P>
<P>
   Others have coped with even more dramatic injuries: a Maryland
violinist mangled her left hand in a lawn mower and retooled her
technique as well as her fiddle until she could finger with her
right hand and bow with her left. And an Irish pianist who slashed
his hand in a bagel mishap shortly before a concert went on stage
anyway, bleeding profusely on the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   For many, giving up music is unfathomable. It's an
impossibility, a notion so appalling that they'll pursue any
curative method to keep on playing. Harrell told the Baltimore Sun
he was terrified at the prospect of a surgeon cutting open both
hands, ``but the thought that I'd lose all feeling in my hands and
never be able to play again frightened me even more.'' So under the
knife he went.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with an injury, musicians ``panic and they get depressed,
whether it's a home accident or a musical accident _ particularly,
I think, among string players and keyboard players, who tend to
have started so early,'' said Alice Brandfonbrener, who directs the
Medical Program for Performing Artists at the Rehabilitation
Institute of Chicago and is widely regarded as the ``grandmother''
of performing-arts medicine. Many such early starters ``have really
little other self-identity. You know, you lose being a musician,
and you're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandfonbrener, who literally wrote the book on artists'
injuries (``The Textbook of Performing Arts Medicine,'' with Robert
Sataloff and Richard Lederman), has treated ailing instrumentalists
for more than 20 years. Some, like Levy or Taylor, are trying to
bounce back from a nonmusical injury _ be it a wayward bread knife
or a devastating crash. Others are coping with debilitating pain or
numbness caused by years of repetitive stress and the ergonomic
contortions of music-making. In either case, recovery can demand a
combination of surgery, therapy and time. And, sometimes, a
willingness to change.
</P>
<P>
   Rachelle Taylor was a young pianist with a burgeoning career
when she broke her neck in a car accident. Paralyzed in all four
limbs and informed by doctors that she wouldn't sit up again, she
never once doubted that she would still, somehow, make music. ``I
never, ever let that enter my mind,'' said Taylor from her home in
Montreal. ``I did not hear them. I would not hear them because I
couldn't. And I could only attribute that to grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Music is so crucial to her being, she said, that ``I can't even
sort of articulate it. It was just such a fundamental thing, as
though my whole being was participating in that. ... I don't have a
choice: I'm a musician.'' People become musicians ``because that's
what they're meant to do. It's almost, You Are Music.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Taylor was right: She did make music again.
Though she never regained use of her legs _ crucial for pedalwork
on the piano _ she did recover her arms and hands and embarked,
following a long recovery, on a successful, global career as a
harpsichordist and early-music specialist. Her dark night of the
soul (``quite mystical in that vein'') clarified her priorities and
led _ unexpectedly, paradoxically _ to new hope.
</P>
<P>
   A life-changing accident ``is just a horrible thing, but on the
other hand it's such an opportunity,'' she said, ``and once you get
through finding out what it is about yourself that wants to
survive, it becomes an incredible joy to do that because it becomes
so clear what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not all stories are as extraordinary. Among the injuries
Brandfonbrener sees most frequently, the broadest and most common
``garbage pail category'' is muscular-skeletal pain. In other
words, problems relating to the muscle-tendon units.
</P>
<P>
   About 85 percent of all the Chicago program's patients complain
of sore muscles. There are joint problems as well, and nerve
troubles, including the less common carpal tunnel syndrome, and,
for brass players, chronic mouth and lip difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   At the Texas Center for Music and Medicine in Fort Worth, where
the biomechanics of music-making is the subject of continuing
research, a new study on clarinetists outlines the intense,
repetitive pressure put on the musician's hand. It amounts to this:
A clarinetist uses all nine fingers to press down on the 10th _ the
right thumb, which supports the instrument via a curved metal rest.
Pressure against the thumb is increased when the musician blows air
into the clarinet, yielding a sustained compressive force that can
damage the muscles and ligaments. These injuries are more prevalent
among women, who have, on average, smaller hands and weaker grips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've experimented with the use of an elastic neck strap,
which is marketed and sold to clarinetists'' and would relieve
pressure on the thumb, said Kris Chesky, co-director of the center.
``But it's nontraditional and doesn't look good, and musicians
don't want to wear it.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y.: x x x to wear it.'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such resistance points to the need, he said, to raise awareness
among instrumentalists and encourage them to change habits that
could turn painful _ and professionally traumatic _ down the line.
``Our idea is not only how best to treat somebody, but how best to
prevent it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Francine Schutzman, an oboist and English horn player with the
National Arts Centre Orchestra in Ottawa, learned firsthand about
the biomechanics of music-making. About three years ago, she
started to prepare an English horn concerto for an upcoming
performance. ``I found that I couldn't practice more than 45
minutes at a time _ after 45 minutes, my thumb would simply give
out. It would collapse,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, she dismissed it as nothing serious. She was getting
older, she figured, she'd been playing the oboe for more than 40
years, she felt fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   But after a while the pain became so severe _ along with a
numbness in her hands and recurring neck and shoulder troubles _
that she had to quit playing altogether. She dropped out of the
orchestra. Then a former student suggested she try an oboe support
called the Finger and Hand Retraining Ergonomic Device, or FHRED
for short _ basically, a small pole that connects the instrument's
thumb rest to the musician's chair. She tried it. The results
renewed her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes all the weight off. All of it, which is why it's so
much better than the neck strap, which then puts pressure on the
neck,'' said Schutzman, who returned to the orchestra after a mere
week. Asked to describe the impact of FHRED on her professional
life, she replied: ``Um, I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   FHREDs are also used by a handful of musicians at State
University of New York at Potsdam's Crane School of Music, where 15
or so of the school's 600 music majors struggle with tendinitis,
carpal tunnel syndrome and the like in any given year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor training in the early stage sets them up for problems,
and poor technique,'' said Glenn Guiles, professor of oboe and
chair of the music performance department at Crane. Although some
students attend a nearby sports-medicine clinic, he said, the staff
there ``are not music people, so it's difficult.'' Guiles himself
has experienced carpal tunnel problems and numbness in his right
arm but has relieved them with a series of exercises prescribed by
an orthopedic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, he said, more students are more aware of such
ailments _ and are less willing to live with them. ``Instead of
students just suffering in silence, thinking something's just wrong
with them, they realize there are things they can do,'' Guiles
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, musicians have had a lot of problems, but they
kind of were in the `no pain, no gain' theory _ the idea that it
just goes with the territory, so you plow through it,'' said
Brandfonbrener, who started seeing ``the same kinds of things in
the same kind of players'' when she signed on as festival physician
for the Aspen Music Festival in 1978. The realization that certain
types of musicians suffer certain types of injuries led to the
formation of a physicians association devoted to the subject and
the founding of a journal, Medical Problems of Performing Artists.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the masses today are more cognizant of musicians'
injuries, whether instrument-specific or incurred in the kitchen,
and the profound personal and professional ramifications that
result. Still, Brandfonbrener said, physicians who don't specialize
in the field have a few things to learn about sensitivity. Using
Levy's problem as an example, she said one of the problems faced by
musicians with injured fingers ``is that they get handled lightly,
because there's no fracture, but there's a lot of soft tissue
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy knows about soft tissue damage. Though her repaired tendon
is almost good as new, the nerve has been a long time coming
(nerves regenerate slowly, and Levy's finger is still partially
numb.) She can't always feel the string beneath her finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then, when I'm doing certain things,
occasionally my finger doesn't land on the string the way I think
it has, and I'll get a squawk instead of a good sound,'' she said.
``It's happening less now, but it was a big problem at first. I'd
go to play a chord and get these funny sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Methodist Church that recent Thursday, Levy easily
navigated the angular turns and sneaky tonalities in Prokoviev's
``Five Melodies.'' She handled tricky fingerings high on the E
string. She hit double-stops without a squawk. But when she took a
break to chat about her injury, she clenched her hand, relaxed it,
clenched her hand, relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers me is when I flex it, it does ache a
bit, and when I play I feel (like there's) this clothespin closing
on it. I feel this pressure holding me back when I play,'' Levy
said. She held up her left hand: a thin white scar curled around
the tip of her ring finger and wormed downward toward the palm.
</P>
<P>
   The nerve is coming back, she knows. Nerves take time. The
tendon has healed better than anyone expected _ particularly her
surgeon, who, she later learned, didn't actually believe she'd
regain so much movement in her finger. And while Levy had some
black moments in those hours after her accident, it didn't take
long for hope to take hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember driving home from the emergency room at 4 in the
morning. My 11-year-old daughter was in the car, and she said,
`Well, one good thing about this is you're gonna have lots of time
to spend with me,''' Levy recalled. ``And she was right. So, you
know, it hasn't been all bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
