<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TEXAS-ARCHAEOLOGY-HNS     06-16 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ARCHAEOLOGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS ARCHAEOLOGISTS CHRONICLE THE ROOTS OF FRENCH DISCOVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DANE SCHILLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEERAN RANCH, Texas _ Rings, musket balls and charms to ward off
the evil eye are gingerly pried from the dark clay here, as
investigators piece together the rugged lives and deaths of the
inhabitants of the first European settlement in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The hills and scrub brush of this remote, mosquito-plagued
stretch of the Coastal Bend are all that guard the remains of an
ill-fated fort set up in 1685 by the French explorer Robert
Cavelier de La Salle as he searched for the mouth of the
Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the few times since a ranch worker armed with a metal
detector found eight buried iron cannons in 1996 _ confirming the
location of the legendary Fort St. Louis _ state officials
permitted outsiders Thursday to view its remains.
</P>
<P>
   About 180 French men, women and children settled the fort, which
was built in April 1685 from timbers salvaged from a shipwreck.
</P>
<P>
   With the blessing of King Louis XIV, they were expected to have
set up a permanent colony at the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   Inaccurate maps led to a landfall in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Settlers slowly succumbed to Indian attacks, disease,
rattlesnakes and alligators that thrived in the brackish waters
that flow toward the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty dismal for those people,'' said James Bruseth,
head of the archaeology division of the Texas Historical
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Salle and his men were constantly fighting during their
stay here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Eve 1688, Karankawa Indians attacked the fort and
killed everyone who remained there except three children.
</P>
<P>
   La Salle, the famed explorer, had been away on an expedition and
later was killed by his own men.
</P>
<P>
   His nude body was dumped in the brush, according to a journal
from the time.
</P>
<P>
   La Salle's fort is seen as particularly significant because it
was the focus of a battle against time.
</P>
<P>
   The French sought to control a massive stretch of land later
known as the Louisiana Purchase, and the Spanish sought to defend
silver mines in northern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are gaining insight into Fort St. Louis and a
Spanish presidio that later took its place, as about 20,000
artifacts, from the cannons to shards of pottery, have been
unearthed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most common are gunflints, glass beads, religious
medallions and arrow points.
</P>
<P>
   The structures are long gone, but investigators have unearthed
portions of walls and foundations within the 32.5-acre compound.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists still are hunting for a graveyard where as many
as 50 French are believed to be buried.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators face a financial battle, as the project's
budget is expected to run out before autumn, project director Mike
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is running,'' he said. ``We would regret if finances
forced us to shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature approved $250,000 for the excavation, and
private donors kicked in about $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   About $250,000 more is needed to wrap up the excavation and keep
the project running until the end of the year, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The site, located on a private ranch, had been kept largely
secret since the discovery of the cannons, which are on display in
nearby Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the ranch have shunned publicity to deter looters
and limited the number of archaeologists that can work the site at
any given time.
</P>
<P>
   But archaeologists wanted the public to know more about the
significance of the project.
</P>
<P>
   To do so, they permitted a few reporters and photographers to
visit the site.
</P>
<P>
   Drenched in sweat, University of North Texas archaeology student
Robyn Pry said she feels the long dead settlers tugged at her soul
as she digs through the earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me goose bumps,'' she said. ``They must have been
hearty, brave people. I cannot imagine the mosquitoes with no
(insect repellant) and the sun with no sunscreen.''
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologist Mike Fulghum said aching muscles are soothed by
the passion of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find a big old piece of French (pottery) and you are the
first person to see or hold that in your hand in 313 years,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At a Texas Historical Commission office in Victoria, volunteers,
young and old, help catalogue artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is history,'' said Benjamin Gossett, 11, ``everything you
find is important in some way or another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
