<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5931 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CHRISTOPHER18-COX     06-16 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTOPHER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QUIETLY, CHRISTOPHER WEEDS GORE'S VICE-PRESIDENTIAL GARDEN
 &HT;    560&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories
for release Sunday, June 18.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, after wrapping up the
Democratic presidential nomination this spring, turned to a man
whose judgment he trusts to help him choose a running mate _ Warren
Christopher, who also ran the selection process that put Gore on
the ticket with Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job last time, don't you think so?'' Gore
recently quipped to reporters on Air Force Two as he fended off
questions about Christopher's search, which began in early April.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the process is a little more complicated than
Christopher just coming up with a name for Gore. And if
Christopher's current efforts are anything like those for Clinton
in 1992, Christopher won't even offer a specific recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren Christopher acts as an honest broker,'' said Frank
Greer, who was part of Clinton's campaign brain trust in 1992. ``He
vets the candidates in order to identify their liabilities, but
leaves the recommendations to the political types in the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   And with Christopher, Gore can be confident that the process
will remain confidential. To date, Christopher has declined all
comment about the prospects and the process.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher is notoriously gracious.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1998 book, ``In the Stream of History,'' about his
service for Clinton, there was not a whisper of criticism of the
president or any member of the administration. In fact, the
harshest thing Christopher had to say about anyone was his
assessment of Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. ``Our positions on matters
of substance were at such variance that it placed severe
limitations on our relationship,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The way Christopher works in his vice presidential head-hunting
is to ask a large number of prospective running mates for a
dizzying amount of documents _ tax returns, personal financial
statements, medical records and, if they are politicians, campaign
finance reports. He then interviews the candidates, often asking
them to recommend someone other than themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he made a round of visits to a half-dozen
Democratic senators' offices last month, touching off a spate of
rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dick Durbin of Illinois, one of the senators Christopher
visited, said that ``95 percent of the conversation (was) prefaced
(by Christopher) with, 'Take yourself out of this conversation and
talk about who would be a good running mate for Al.' ``
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Christopher had as many as 40 names on his initial list
of possible running mates for Clinton. But for Gore, the list is
not expected to be as long, although Gore spokesman Chris Lehane
said, ``There is no long list. There is no short list.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher, 74, is the senior partner in the international law
firm of O'Melveny and Myers, which is based in Los Angeles. He
co-chaired the transition team when Clinton was elected in 1992 and
served as Clinton's secretary of state from 1993 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Most critics view Christopher's term as rather lackluster,
especially in contrast to the larger-than-life figures who have
often held the job of secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   A slight, gray man who seldom smiles in public, Christopher is
known among his friends as ``Mr. Neat'' for his meticulous grooming
and wardrobe. Clinton, remarking on Christopher's formality, once
joked that he was ``the only person who ate Peanut M&AMP;M's on Air
Force One with a knife and fork.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Christopher served as deputy secretary of state during the
Carter administration and was the chief negotiator in the release
of the 52 Americans who had been held hostage for two years in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Scranton, N.D., the son of a banker, Christopher
graduated from Stanford Law School in 1949 and clerked for Supreme
Court Justice William O. Douglas, one of the most liberal justices
ever to serve on the high court.
</P>
<P>
   After practicing law in California for 17 years, he joined the
Justice Department during the Johnson administration, working for
Attorney General Ramsey Clark, another political liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, he has been actively involved in human
rights issues, both at the local and international level. In Los
Angeles, he headed the commission that investigated the police
beating of Rodney King.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Marie, have four children.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's E-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
