<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Saturday, June 17.
</P>
<P>
   JULES-FEIFFER (Undated) _ Jules Feiffer's moody modern dancer,
the comic strip figure who has leaped and stretched interpretively
to every spring, summer, autumn and winter for over 40 years, is
finally hanging up her tights. The reason? Her only venue,
``Feiffer,'' Feiffer's doodly comic strip of personal, sexual and
political rants, is ending on Sunday. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   GARBAGE-STUDIES (Undated) _ Increasingly, academics are finding
that garbage _ the previously ignored contents of wastebaskets and
dumpsters _ holds vital clues to American culture. By Katherine E.
Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-PANTHER-MEMOIR (Undated) _ Thirty years ago, Kathleen Neal
Cleaver, instantly recognizable by her iconic Afro and knee-high
leather boots, was writing polemics for the Black Panther Party.
Today she is plumbing her turbulent past for a book aptly entitled
``Memories of Love and War.'' By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MAN-PROFILE (New York) _ A talk with Craig Bierko, the
lead in ``The Music Man.'' By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   NYCBALLET-DANCE-REVIEW (New York) _ Some ballets can be faked.
``Liebeslieder Walzer'' is not one of them. Without first-rate
performers, the ballet is like too much chocolate cake. But the New
York City Ballet presented a shining performance of this
problematical ballet on Thursday night. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   SONGWRITERS-FAME (New York) _ James Brown, Glenn Frey and Don
Henley of the Eagles, Curtis Mayfield, James Taylor and Brian
Wilson became members of the Songwriters' Hall of Fame on Thursday
night, in the National Academy of Popular Music's 31st annual
induction into a hall that is about to have its first physical
home. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
