<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-KOREAN-BANDS-HNS &LR;      06-16 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAN-BANDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KOREAN HIP HOP _ A NEW TEEN FAD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RYAN KIM  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For 17-year-old Anna Jin, the five-member boy
band that gets her feet racing and her heart thumping is not 'N
Sync or the Backstreet Boys. It's H.O.T.
</P>
<P>
   Never heard of them? Relax, you haven't slept through the latest
teen fad sweeping the nation. The Korean hip hop group H.O.T. (High
Five of Teenager) and its musical brethren have grown in popularity
here to the point where they compete with American stars for the
hearts of Korean American youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm really Koreanized,'' said Jin, who lives in
Piedmont, Calif. ``I would choose the Korean group over the
American group because of who I am and how I think.''
</P>
<P>
   While Korean popular entertainment has grown in favor over the
last decade, the phenomenon masks a chasm between Korean Americans
and the homeland of their parents. The rift is evidenced by the
general lack of knowledge and interest among second-generation
Korean Americans about the historic summit talks between the
leaders of North and South Korea that concluded this week.
</P>
<P>
   The summit could be the first tentative step toward
reunification of the countries, which have remained technically at
war since the end of the Korean conflict in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   But while many older Korean American immigrants watched the
meetings closely, the proceedings and their significance haven't
registered with their children.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Lee, a 28-year-old campus minister at the University of
California at Berkeley, said that when people ``talk about what's
happening in Korea, it's almost like they're talking about another
country. There's just no sense of how the unification of Korea
would affect me personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Many younger Korean Americans said that while growing up, they
rarely engaged in conversations about Korean history, news and
culture with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Time with parents, often a scarce commodity in Korean culture,
was and continues to be devoted to more immediate issues, said Sue
Kim, 28, an advertising account executive in San Francisco. ``You
talk about a certain script of things: finances, grad school, when
are you going to get married.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the pressures of immigrant life have helped shape
the cultural chasm that exists between second-generation Korean
Americans and their ancestral motherland.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Lee's father, Kae Hwan Lee, a contractor, struggled over
the years to provide for his wife and two children. He had little
time to share his personal history with them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're over here struggling to make ends meet, you really
don't have that much time to think about teaching your children the
way things were back in Korea,'' said Lee, 65, of Daly City, Calif.
``You just barely have time to check on their current existence and
schooling.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming to the United States also afforded many immigrants a
chance to forget a bleak, tragic period. ``It was so rough, we were
anxious to get out of there and just forget about it,'' Kae Hwan
Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with traditional Korean culture, which values
patience and silence, many older Koreans have kept their memories
of the war to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many parents don't share their experiences with their kids
because it's too painful. They don't want their kids to go through
the same experience,'' said Youn-Cha Shin Chey, executive director
and president of Korean Center Inc. and the Intercultural Institute
of California in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But for a number of younger Korean Americans, assimilation has
left them in search of a deeper identity. Many, even those with
limited Korean language skills, have turned to Korean music and
television to channel a heritage that has eluded them.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the media provide a reaffirming tool for Korean
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in America, you don't always feel like you belong. You
don't have a clear identity, especially being Asian,'' said Lewis
Choi, a 22-year-old information and technology consultant. ``But
when you hear the Korean songs that sound pretty good with good
beats, you're proud of it and you identify with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Choi, who lives in Berkeley, recalled his introduction to Korean
music 10 years ago during a trip to Korea. He came away with
several tapes of popular artists and a taste for the sound.
``Korean music gives you a feeling of belonging to something,''
Choi said.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Korean pop music lacked the pizazz and production
values needed to lure Korean Americans entrenched in the States.
Earlier Korean singers belted out warbly traditional tunes that
suited older audiences but did little for youths.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last decade, Korean music has made huge strides, to
the point where it mimics the best of American hip hop, techno, pop
and hard rock. While the lyrics are in Korean, the sound is
undeniably Western.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like listening to any teenage music,'' said 15-year-old
Joyce So, of San Bruno, Calif. ``It's catchy and it's not
old-fogey.''
</P>
<P>
   Korean television also has evolved, and has spawned a following
of Korean Americans, who pick up the shows on videos and on
Korean-language channels in the United States. The most popular
shows are dramas, similar to an extended miniseries. Often they are
love stories.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lee, a Korean American former history lecturer at
UC-Berkeley, said Korean pop culture is much more readily available
today and serves as a validating force for Korean Americans, who
may be American but still long for some link to Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Korean Americans that flock to these things
to authenticate their Korean-ness,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee expresses some disappointment, however, when her Korean
American students know the latest Korean pop star but not the
president of South Korea. But she said that's a phenomenon not
limited to Korean Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a level of historical amnesia`` and general lack of
interest in what happens outside the States, said Lee, 32. ``It's
part of a larger trend of American ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Jin, try to keep up with events in Korea. But staying
abreast of the latest news overseas is not as easy as picking up
the latest Korean CD or following a popular drama.
</P>
<P>
   Jin, who owns almost 100 Korean CDs, said she might not be
listening to teen idols H.O.T. years from now. But she doesn't
envision abandoning Korean music or TV. ``I want to keep my culture
and I don't want to ever lose that,'' said Jin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
