<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-YOSEMITE-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      06-16 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NATIONAL PARK MURDER TRIAL MAY BE MOVED TO SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. _ The trial of a former motel handyman who is
charged with killing and beheading a Yosemite National Park
naturalist is likely to be moved to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Presented with an agreement by prosecution and defense lawyers
to transfer the case out of Fresno because of extensive news
coverage, U.S. District Judge Anthony Ishii said Thursday he would
approve a change of venue if submitted in writing by both sides and
signed by murder suspect Cary Stayner.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing lawyers also agreed that the best location would be
Seattle, where news coverage has been less extensive and where a
courtroom is available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle does appear to be as neutral a place as can be
found,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Dawrence Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Ishii said he would continue to preside over the trial wherever
it is held.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner, 38, has pleaded not guilty to the murder, but he has
confessed to authorities and in a news interview to killing
naturalist Joie Armstrong last July and three others in the
Yosemite area in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The judge rejected most of the challenges by Stayner's lawyers
to the death penalty, but deferred a final ruling whether it can be
sought in his case. Ishii also ruled that prosecutors could present
evidence of the killings of three Yosemite sightseers if Stayner's
trial reaches a penalty phase.
</P>
<P>
   The federal trial was scheduled to start Oct. 17, but defense
lawyer Robert Rainwater told Ishii that it probably would have to
be delayed because evidence still is being gathered and reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said if Rainwater wanted to delay the trial, to let
him know as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner, who is being held pending the trial, did not attend the
75-minute hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, 26, was an environmental educator with the Yosemite
National Institutes who lived in a cabin in the park and taught
visitors about its natural wonders. Her headless body was found in
a creek near the cabin last July 21.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest three days later, Stayner admitted stabbing
Armstrong to death and killing the three tourists: Carole Sund, 42,
of Eureka; her daughter Juli, 15; and their Argentine friend,
Silvina Pelosso, 16.
</P>
<P>
   They disappeared in February 1999 from Cedar Lodge, just outside
the park, where Stayner worked as a handyman. Their bodies were
found in remote areas. The police said the two girls had been
sexually assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is prosecuting Stayner for Armstrong's
murder because it occurred on U.S. property. He is charged in
Mariposa County with killing the three tourists, also a potential
death-penalty case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1449EDT &QL; 
