<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5960 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-ANGER-CENTER     06-16 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ANGER-CENTERPIECE-ADV18-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV18 
 NO MORE MR. NICE GUY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, June 18, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's CENTERPIECE news service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of CENTERPIECE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By STEPHEN S. HALL  
 c.2000 Stephen S. Hall  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the 1970s, fresh out of college and living in Rome, I
was often invited to eat Sunday dinner with a working-class Italian
family. The conversations, almost all of which were about politics,
invariably escalated from ``Ciao'' to an invective-filled uproar in
about 60 seconds, with eye-popping epithets hurled across the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Typically American, I experienced a visceral unease at such
displays of anger and yet also a voyeuristic fascination. That same
complex emotional response has begun to set in during the current
political season. Anger is already a leitmotif in this year's
presidential campaign. In April, George W. Bush vowed to ``end the
arms race of anger'' in American politics and called for a return
to comity in the public conversation. Al Gore's handlers,
meanwhile, have been trying to make him more huggable. In New York,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has molted his cutworm skin and emerged as
the Love Bug.
</P>
<P>
   But here's what comity gets you: that picture of Hillary Clinton
and Rep. Rick Lazio stiffly shaking each other's hands with
transparently insincere smiles as brittle as frost.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have long been uncomfortable with displays of anger
from their public servants. Senior journalists still tend to
referee politics according to what might be called the Smithereens
Infraction. Presidential candidates in particular dare not betray
the slightest hint of being short-tempered, lest this pique be
perceived as the kind of hotheaded instability that might bring the
world to the brink of nuclear annihilation _ or, nowadays, Nasdaq
to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure that the reflexive distrust of anger serves
politics well now. The Republicans are talking about making their
convention a vitriol-free zone this summer, even trotting out a
rehabilitated Sen. John McCain. But his participation will serve
only as a reminder of the kind of healthy political anger that
Bush's victory managed to quell.
</P>
<P>
   Back in February, conceding to Bush after the South Carolina
primary, McCain was mad. With barely contained indignation, he
condemned Bush's winning strategy _ the below-the-belt questioning
of his military valor, the relentless attack ads, the courtship of
the religious right. On CNN, Jeff Greenfield and Judy Woodruf
wagged their fingers at McCain's outburst _ and his temper, not
what prompted it, became the story. Bush wiped the mud off his
hands and, his party's nomination safely in possession, suddenly
became the king of comity.
</P>
<P>
   We could use more anger, not less, in the campaign. Not the kind
of anger recently forsworn by Giuliani _ the aggressive,
mean-spirited, egocentric kind fired by self-interest _ but the
kind that cuts through the Muzak of politics-by-focus-group and
causes voters to believe that a candidate might actually believe in
something larger than the latest in-house poll.
</P>
<P>
   High-minded anger can be a great rhetorical tool, precisely
because it is genuine, passionate and often unscripted. Martin
Luther King Jr.'s ``I Have a Dream'' speech is one of the
masterpieces of 20th-century oratory because of the smoldering
indignation that warms every word.
</P>
<P>
   The defining failure of Bill Clinton's presidency is that his
most public expression of anger in nearly eight years in office did
not serve to galvanize public sentiment on poverty or health care
or racial injustice. The full-throated fury of the man's political
soul was directed at ``that woman.'' His rage got our attention,
but it did so in the service not of an idea but of his own
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem. In these self-absorbed times, no one in
politics gets publicly angry about anything larger than his or her
ambitions. Oh, there's plenty of anger afoot in the culture at
large. Each of us boils over in response to insults of breathtaking
triviality: being put on hold, getting cut off by a motorist,
waiting for a table at a restaurant. Little incivilities produce
enormous hemorrhages of bile, which may explain our simultaneous
horror and fascination on those rare occasions when a politician
does let loose.
</P>
<P>
   Our sense of outrage has become so self-centered, so
circumscribed, so small that our collective social anger has itself
become small-minded, and we've lost the ability to hear righteous
anger for what it can be _ a principled recalibration of society's
moral compass. In learning to distrust and discourage political
anger, we have delegitimized the things that should make us angry.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is no righteous anger, only self-righteous anger,
which is always easy to dismiss. Hence, our current politics of
small-minded vitriol, with its undermining negativity, its huge
economies of energy devoted to stalemate and sinecure.
</P>
<P>
   When I lived in Italy, it was commonplace (as it still is) to
make fun of the operatic parade of dysfunctional Italian
governments. The truth is, we have effectively adopted all the
salient principles of Italian politics _ the art of obstruction,
the rhetoric of obfuscation, the elevation of self-interest above
public interest, all with the oily, insincere veneer of comity.
</P>
<P>
   The coming anger-free election season promises more of the same,
and if recent trends are any predictor, voters will stay away in
droves.
</P>
<P>
   (Stephen S. Hall is a contributing writer for The New York Times
Magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on
CENTERPIECE and other features. &QL;
