<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HOUSING-STARTS-STREET     06-16 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-STARTS-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING STARTS FALL 3.9 PERCENT TO LOWEST LEVEL IN NEARLY A YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN VAMES   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Housing construction slowed considerably in May, as
higher mortgage rates dampened the demand for new single-family
homes, the Commerce Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Housing starts dropped 3.9 percent in May to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.592 million units, the lowest rate since
June of last year. May's decline was bigger than the 1.8 percent
drop that economists had been expecting. Meanwhile, the April rate
of housing starts was revised downward to 1.656 million units, a
1.6 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   New building permits, a forecaster of future home construction,
fell 4.3 percent in May to a 1.49 million annual rate, following a
decline of 2.4 percent to 1.56 million in April.
</P>
<P>
   The solid pullback in home building is yet another sign that
certain areas of the U.S. economy have begun to show convincingly
slower activity in response to the Federal Reserve's yearlong
efforts to reduce the threat of inflation by raising interest
rates. Higher rates, which affect everything from credit cards to
business loans to mortgages, make it more costly for consumers and
businesses to borrow and spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report gives us more confidence in saying that the
housing market is past its peak and higher mortgage rates are
having an effect on home buying and new construction,'' said
economists at the Dismal Scientist, an economics Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The housing market in particular is one of the most
interest-rate-sensitive portions of the economy, because the vast
majority of home sales are financed. As the Fed raised its target
for short-term interest rates six times over the past year, the
interest rate for an average 30-year fixed-rate mortgage rose to
8.52 percent in May, vs. 8.15 percent in April and 7.15 percent in
May 1999, according to the mortgage giant Freddie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists believe that the recent signs of slower home
sales and home building, along with slipping levels of retail sales
and benign inflation readings, will be enough to convince the Fed's
policymakers to leave interest rates unchanged when they meet on
June 27 and 28.
</P>
<P>
   A separate report Friday also showed that consumers, who account
for about two-thirds of U.S. economic growth, are growing less
confident, in a sign that higher interest rates and a pullback in
technology stocks may cause them to curb their spending in months
to come. The University of Michigan's consumer sentiment index for
the first two weeks of June dropped sharply, to 106.8 from 110.7 in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Despite signs that the economy is slowing, however, many
economists warn that the Fed might not be finished raising rates
for the year. While measures of the housing market are slowing,
they remain near historically high levels. Meanwhile, other parts
of the economy, such as the labor market and the nation's
factories, continue to show signs of strength despite higher
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported that new construction of
single-family homes fell a sharp 5.4 percent, the fourth drop in
single-family housing starts in the past five months. In contrast,
builders began work on 3.9 percent more multi-family buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The disproportionate drop in single-family housing starts
indicates that consumers are having a rougher time with higher
mortgage rates than commercial builders of apartment buildings. But
analysts said starts of all types of housing are likely to start
falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although apartment building is less sensitive to interest
rates, builders are also likely to become more cautious during the
spring,'' said Lynn Reaser, chief economist and senior market
strategist for the Bank of America Asset Management Group.
</P>
<P>
   Regionally, the slowest construction activity was in the Midwest
and the West, where housing starts fell by 13.6 percent and 8.9
percent, respectively. Housing starts rose 5.6 percent in the
Northeast, and they rose 2.8 percent in the South.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
