<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5973 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BRITAIN-HOOLIGANS-$AD     06-16 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-HOOLIGANS-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VIOLENT 'HOOLIGANISM' THREATENING CIVILITY OF EUROPEAN SOCCER
MATCHES
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ European authorities will be on high alert
Saturday(6/17) against bands of determined and well-organized young
men bent on violence.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorists?
</P>
<P>
   No. Soccer fans.
</P>
<P>
   With England scheduled to play Germany in Belgium in a crucial
Euro 2000 match, police are bracing for an onslaught of perhaps
thousands of beer-guzzling toughs who use soccer matches as a
pretext for brutish street warfare. An estimated 40,000 English
fans are expected in Charleroi, the industrial city southeast of
Brussels hosting the match. Many are going without tickets.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, police and customs officials in the Belgian port of
Ostend were stopping all cars with British license plates coming
off the ferries. The authorities matched passports against a list
of 1,000 known hooligans provided by the British government. At
least three young men were sent back to England.
</P>
<P>
   Police, politicians and soccer officials dread the prospect of a
repeat of the near riot that exploded in central Copenhagen last
month when hundreds of English and Turkish fans launched into
street battle using cafe chairs and beer bottles as their primary
weapons. Dozens were injured, and 64 were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The melee was fueled by anger over the fatal stabbings in April
of two English soccer fans attending a match in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The antics of the crass, beer-swilling hordes are a source of
profound embarrassment among England's gentler folk, who view
civility as fundamental to the national identity.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Straw, the British home secretary, has called for zero
tolerance of thuggish behavior. ``They bring disgrace to all of
us,'' he said. ``They have no part in the Britain I want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   An obviously frustrated Straw also pleaded with the wives and
girlfriends of hooligans to blow the whistle on their men if they
hinted that they planned to cross the Channel to attend Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind almost every football hooligan setting off for Europe
is a wife or girlfriend or employer who knows the score,'' Straw
said this week. ``They have to let the thugs know that such
violence is unacceptable. And they have to help the police and the
courts to bring them to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain's National Criminal Intelligence Service, which monitors
football violence in England and Wales, maintains files on 5,000
hooligans, of which 500 are rated as hard-core organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-hooligan laws passed by Parliament last year allow judges
to prevent troublemakers from traveling to international matches.
However, only about two dozen have been subjected to the
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the peace, about 3,000 Belgian police will take to the
streets Saturday with another 70,000 on standby. The anti-hooligan
defense has been boosted with mounted police units, 13 water
cannons and two helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the hooligans seem to bask in the attention.
``Everybody hates us,'' according to a posting on a hooligan
Internet message board. ``But we don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooligans seem to get a kick from the campaign to control them.
Hooligan Websites, sponsored by such groups as the ``Chelsea Head
Hunters'' offer advice _ such as posing as businessmen _ to elude
police.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fears, violence was at a minimum at Monday's match
between England and Portugal. Some police officials believe English
hooligans were keeping a low profile so as to minimize the risk
that they would be prevented from going to Charleroi for the more
important confrontation with Germany. England's team hasn't
defeated Germany since 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials attributed the good behavior to the fact that
marijuana is legal in Holland, and many hooligans were rendered
docile after smoking it in the city's pot shops.
</P>
<P>
   Even in their stupor, the mob managed to be ugly. After England
lost to Portugal, English soccer star David Beckham became outraged
as he left the field amid taunts and shouted threats to kill his
new baby. His wife is a member of the girl-power band, Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the peaceful respite seemed to be coming to an end.
Hooligans across the continent were on line swapping obscenity-rich
insults and promising a show of force in Belgium. ``Kill them all,
white power,'' one hooligan chatter said referring with insulting
racial slurs to Belgium's large population of Turks.
</P>
<P>
   Police and journalists in Britain have found links between
hard-core hooligans and the assortment of white supremacy groups
that have cells across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   One BBC television reporter who produced an undercover expose on
hooligans that explored these connections was moved by the
state-owned broadcaster to a safe house after he and his family
received death threats. However, Sean Perkins of the Leicester
University Centre for Football Research, argues that most hooligans
are relatively normal people who are swept away in a river of beer
and emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many of them it's the buzz, the adrenaline rush,'' Perkins
said. ``'They want their 15 minutes of fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though hooliganism most often is associated with English
soccer fans, the phenomenon has become common across Europe,
particularly in Germany and Holland. The German government has a
list of 2,600 registered hooligans, and authorities confiscate
their passports during
</P>
<P>
   international matches.
</P>
<P>
   As the match between England and Germany _ dubbed the battle of
Charleroi _ neared this week, hooligan stories have dominated media
coverage of Euro 2000, which is the European equivalent of the NCAA
basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   For average soccer fans, this has taken away from the pleasure
of watching a long-loved sport.
</P>
<P>
   Martin O'Hara, a husband and father of two boys, believes the
media have exaggerated the problem. ``I have been to many games
with on my own and with my son, and we never see anything,'' O'Hara
said.
</P>
<P>
   He worries that hooligans could permanently damage the image of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these people aren't fans, not really,'' he lamented.
``They're just thugs who have nothing to do with sport.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information: (Caution: Hooligan sites tend to contain
obscenities, racial slurs and other material not suitable for young
people):
</P>
<P>
   http://www.geocities.com:0080/Colosseum/Stadium/3763/hoolie.htm
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ec-2000.com, http://www.uefa.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
