   MUSIC-CLIBURN (Fort Worth, Texas) -- The annual Van Cliburn
competition celebrates the joys of amateurism. By Richard Dyer.
1480 words.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-GROOVE (Undated) _ Outfitted with a fleet of funk-drenched
samples and narcotic loops, British electronica duo Groove Armada
has scored the first full-bore dance hit of the millennium. By Joan
Anderman.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROCK (Undated) _ Caring and charitable are not words that
jump to mind, yet Lou Reed has somehow been at many of the benefit
shows of magnitude in the past 15 years. By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRAMINGHAM-HEART (Undated) _ Boston University has joined the
rush to turn personal patient information into profit by allowing a
company to commercialize genetic data from the largest and most
prestigious cardiac study in the world _ The Framingham Heart
Study. By Ronald Rosenberg and Liz Kowalczyk. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNO-CORNING (Bedford, Mass.) _ Corning Inc. was born 150
years ago as a glassmaker in Somerville. Several corporate
transformations and a move to upstate New York later, Corning is
still making plenty of glass products in Massachusetts -- only a
thousand times smaller and a million times more profitable. By
Peter J. Howe. 1120 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Oil guru Dan Yergin discusses the
rise in gasoline prices ahead of next week's OPEC meeting. By
Steven Syre and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;   &UR; (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOX-MOSLEY (Los Angeles) _ It was the biggest disappointment of
his life but so many other things were out of kilter at the time
Shane Mosley hardly noticed he had blown the biggest chance of his
life back in 1992. By Ron Borges. 1670 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-JOCELIN (Undated) -- She answers to only one handle now.
It's Jocelin, just Jocelin. But she was born in Waterville, Maine
as Jocelin Joy Veilleux and now is a 29-year-old rookie on the
American Motorcycle Association Pro Series circuit. By Michael
Vega. 1180 words.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYAN-COLUMN (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ On Day 1, the most
eyebrow-raising story is always some improbable guy who bubbles
shoots a wonderful score. This year, they don't get any more
improbable than Bobby Clampett, a qualifier who shot a 68 at Pebble
Beach. By Bob Ryan. 990 words.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SPORTS-COLUMN (Undated) -- Ahmad Rashad has one of the most
recognizable faces on television and people have liked him for a
long time. By Howard Manly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
