<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5989 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-HNS     06-16 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOLDEN AGE OF THE NBA RETURNS, FOR A NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There. That's it. That's the way the NBA used to be. That's the
way the NBA can be again. That's the way the NBA has to be if it
wants to recapture its status as a hip, hot, happening sport.
</P>
<P>
   For those who didn't stay up past midnight Wednesday on the off
chance that the NBA and NBC would collaborate on a playoff
production and have actual entertainment break out, Game 4 of the
Finals was a sight for sore and sleepy eyes. Basketball fans have
the Los Angeles Lakers and Indiana Pacers to thank for providing
some must-see-to-believe TV. It truly was a game for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   The golden ages of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   If you're too young to have seen Magic Johnson and Larry Bird
lift the NBA out of its late-1970s doldrums, this is what happens
when coaches and referees provide an environment that allows great
players to flourish. There was ebb. There was flow. There was show.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, the Lakers and Pacers made 90-of-175 shots from
the field (51.4 percent) and committed only 25 turnovers in 53
minutes. The losers made half their field-goal attempts, buried
24-of-28 free throws and connected on 10-of-19 shots from behind
the three-point line.
</P>
<P>
   The winners lost their center, the league's Most Valuable
Player, halfway into overtime. At that point, they had no choice
but to put all their hopes in the hands of a 21-year-old guard with
a gimpy ankle. And he delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers 120, Pacers 118. From start to frenetic finish, the two
teams brought out the best in each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost played a picture-perfect game,'' Lakers coach Phil
Jackson said. Still, Jackson had to hold his breath like everyone
else in Conseco Field House when Pacers guard Reggie Miller
launched a three-pointer just before the buzzer in overtime. The
ball kissed off the front of the rim, just short of tying the
series at two games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was an all-time great game,'' said Hall-of-Fame
coach Jack Ramsay, who guided the Portland Trail Blazers to the
1977 title. ``Not just in recent years, but over the history of the
NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers got 50 minutes and 35 points from their shooting
star, Miller. Kobe Bryant, who sat out Game 3 with a sprained
ankle, answered with 28 points and five assists in 47 minutes. The
Pacers got 24 points (on 11-of-14 shooting) from the heretofore
useless Rik Smits. Shaquille O'Neal answered with 36 points and 21
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were moments we'd score, they'd come back and score,
we'd score, they'd come back and score,'' Bryant said. ``You could
get mad because our defense was lacking, but at the same time, it
was fun. Because this is the type of thing that you watch growing
up, these types of games where the competition is just the
ultimate.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a throwback to a time when the best offense was an
offense. During the golden '80s, the winning team in the Finals
averaged 112.9 points per game. The winning team's scoring average
for the '90s plummeted to 98.6. That may be a fine body
temperature, but it's the NBA equivalent of a
three-yards-and-a-cloud-of-dust offense.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's Lakers met Bird's Celtics in the '84, '85 and '87
Finals. The winning team scored at least 120 points 10 times in
those 19 games. Of course, the Lakers and Celtics had an
embarrassment of talent riches.
</P>
<P>
   The best of those Celtics teams, the '86 edition, had perhaps
the best frontline of all time (Bird, Kevin McHale and Robert
Parish) to go with a starting backcourt of Dennis Johnson and Danny
Ainge. A former league MVP, Bill Walton, and a former All-Star,
Scott Wedman, came off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The '85 Lakers had the star power of Johnson, Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar and James Worthy. A former league MVP, Bob McAdoo, and
a member of the all-defensive team, Michael Cooper, came off the
bench. Suffice it to say, expansion has watered down the talent
considerably since those days.
</P>
<P>
   The league took another turn for the worse at the end of the
'80s when the Detroit Pistons' Bad Boys style of play became the
prevalent style. Lost in the splendor of Jordan leading the Bulls
to six championships in the '90s on his own was an infestation of
control-freak coaches. The micro-managing of almost every
possession sucked the spontaneity out of the game. Not once during
the Bulls' last three championship runs did they score 100 points
in a Finals game.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came the Lakers and Pacers, turning back the clock to
a better time. O'Neal fouled out with 2:33 left in overtime, with
the Lakers leading by three.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thought was, `This game just became a lot more interesting
than it was a couple of seconds ago,''' Bryant said. He proceeded
to score eight of the Lakers' 16 points in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure? ``Pressure makes coal,'' Lakers forward Robert Horry
said. ``Pressure makes diamonds. Pressure bursts pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure revealed Kobe Bryant to be a polished diamond. For one
glorious night, it was a glimpse of the NBA the way it used to be.
It's the way the NBA can and will be again, if we're lucky, and the
coaches and referees allow the great players to shine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5996 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-REVIEW-SHAKESPEA     06-16 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SHAKESPEARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRANAGH MELDS SHAKESPEARE WITH OLD-STYLE HOLLYWOOD MUSICALS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kenneth Branagh seems to have the maniacal need _ like that of a
circus barker selling the uniqueness of the dog-faced boy _ to show
the world how wonderful his favorite guy, William Shakespeare, is.
For the last dozen years, since ``Henry V'' in 1989, Branagh has
been executing his master plan of popularizing the Bard.
</P>
<P>
   From an uncut ``Hamlet'' to the odd romping of ``Much Ado About
Nothing,'' he seems to feel the need to connect with a mass
audience rather than an art house crowd. And my theory is he's
willing to sacrifice a ``unified'' feel to his productions _
perhaps a little quality even _ for the sake of accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   So now from Branagh comes the first attempt to meld Shakespeare
with old-style Hollywood musicals. ``Love's Labour's Lost,'' the
play, is considered lesser Shakespeare, a rare romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Branagh's adaptation isn't a masterpiece either, but the
writer-director has come up with a sumptuous, happy piece of fluff.
</P>
<P>
   It uneasily throws together people like Alicia Silverstone and
Nathan Lane, Matthew Lillard and dancer Adrian Lester, Natascha
McElhone and Timothy Spall and, of course, Branagh himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1939 and the kingdom of Navarre, situated between France
and Spain, is isolationist. While tension is building in pre-World
War II Europe (there are several newsreel sequences in this film),
the King of Navarre (Alessandro Nivola) has publicly announced his
intention to devote three years exclusively to study. He'll swear
off women, fast once a week and sleep only three hours a night.
</P>
<P>
   The king gets three of his most trusted nobleman to take this
vow with him. They are Berowne (Branagh), Longaville (Lillard) and
Dumaine (Lester). Only Berowne initially has resistance. ``The mind
shall banquet while the body pine,'' he points out.
</P>
<P>
   Or try this line at a party sometime: ``Abstinence engenders
maladies.'' One last task awaits the king and his court before
abstinence takes the upper hand, and that is a diplomatic visit
from the Princess of France (Silverstone) and her court _ Katherine
(Emily Mortimer), Maria (Carmen Ejogo) and Rosaline (McElhone).
</P>
<P>
   Love is in the air already, thanks to the arrival of Spanish
nobleman Don Armado (Spall), who chases the local girl, Jacquanetta
(Stefania Rocca). Costard Lane), a vaudeville clown, is around for
entertainment value.
</P>
<P>
   The king and his court face a dilemma: Because of their vow,
they must keep silent about their feelings of love. So silent, no
one will be the first to admit what they are all thinking _ that
the vow should be deep-sixed.
</P>
<P>
   During this pining, there are secret meetings, love letters, and
yes, musical numbers. Standards like ``The Way You Look Tonight,''
``I Get a Kick Out of You'' and ``There's No Business Like Show
Business,'' are dressed up with dancing, tuxedos, sumptuous set
design and lush cinematography (by Alex Thomson).
</P>
<P>
   ``Love's Labour's Lost'' almost collapses from its own
featherweight. We
</P>
<P>
   know from the first 10 minutes that these mates will trash their
oath and match up with the four French women; so there's no
dramatic tension. The musical numbers are inconsistent _ sometimes
winning and inventive and other times rather weak. And the
slapstick comedy doesn't mesh well with either
</P>
<P>
   Shakespearean dialogue or today's movie audiences.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something infectious about this movie. Its cheery
countenance is impossible to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love's Labour's Lost'' isn't high-minded culture or a film
that will bring back the musical. Instead, it achieves its own
ethereal brand of colorful escapism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
