<HEADER>
A5997 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PASTOR-GOINGHOME0617-     06-16 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTOR-GOINGHOME0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mission accomplished
 &HT;    By Khalid Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ After 50 years of distinguished ministry, the
Rev. D.D. Chestang, pastor of Mount Carmel Missionary Baptist
Church, is going home.
</P>
<P>
   The energetic Alabama preacher, who has been a spiritual
divining rod for scores of faithful throughout southern Ohio, will
deliver his farewell sermon June 25 in the sanctuary of his
Jefferson Twp. church. Soon after, Chestang _ his wife Mary at his
side _ will return to his hometown, completing a mission that began
decades before when he received his first call to the pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew at age 9 on a Sunday at 2 o'clock that I was being
called to preach,'' the 81 year-old minister said as he fiddled
with a jar of candy in his Mount Carmel office. ``Fact is, it was a
dramatic situation because I even had a vision of the first church
I would pastor and I had never even been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The urge to preach, for me is a thousand times more powerful
than the bonding and love a man would have for a woman he wants to
be his wife. It has always been an unavoidable, irresistible,
dynamic influence in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Born March 28, 1919, in Mobile, Ala., Chestang did his
undergraduate work at Selma University and earned a doctor of
theology degree from Faith Bible College in Ashland, N.C. For 14
years, the father of one daughter served as principal of Cedar
Grove Academy in Pritchard, Ala. In 1977, he founded Northwestern
Bible College in Lima, Ohio. He is a retired trustee of Selma
University, which awarded him an honorary law degree in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Chestang, who speaks with the measured, nuanced diction of a
preacher who has delivered his share of fire-breathing sermons,
pastored at Moffattsville Missionary Baptist Church in Wilmer,
Ala., and Delaware Street M.B. Church in Mobile for 30 years before
being selected to take over the reins at Mount Carmel in 1972. At
the time, the church was on North Jefferson street in downtown
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chestang's guidance, Mount Carmel began to flourish. In
1987, the church purchased property and began construction on a
$2.5 million spiritual home. The modern, one-story structure _
which Chestang notes is entirely paid for _ sits on 32 heavily
wooded acres. After Chestang leaves, church officials say a
successor won't be chosen to take his place until at least 60 days
after his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Chestang says one of the most rewarding aspects of his ministry
has been observing how the Holy Spirit can bring about profound
changes in individual's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely gratified when I see people change for the
better spiritually, morally and economically,'' he said. ``I've
seen tremendous changes in people. I've seen them change in such a
dramatic way that it's almost unbelievable. Hopefully, I have
played some part in their growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his frustrations during a half-century of saving
souls, Chestang's eyes narrowed as he leaned forward in his chair
to drive home a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any,'' he insisted. ``When I came to Ohio, there
wasn't one Baptist Bible school for blacks in the whole state. I
founded the first one. Over the years, I might not have been able
to do everything I wanted to do, but I've been too busy with God's
work to have any frustrations.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returns to Mobile, Chestang plans to set up a new
institution for Christian education called Creekside Bible College.
Not only will it mark the return to his Alabama roots, but, for
him, it also represents a rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know anything about salmon?'' he asked. ``They always
return to their spawning ground. That's what I feel like I'm doing,
only I'm going to start a new generation down there. I'm not going
home to sit, I just need to get out of the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
