<HEADER>
A5998 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-16 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PC MAKERS ARE THINKING OUTSIDE THE BIG BOX STORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The choices shoppers have for buying computers in retail stores
are rapidly dwindling. Tiny profits and scarce shelf space have
driven many PC makers out of stores and onto the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Some very familiar names are missing from store shelves _
including IBM, Packard Bell and Acer. In fact, there are now only
three national brands available at retail: Compaq, Hewlett-Packard
and eMachines.
</P>
<P>
   Those that have moved to the Web are trying new approaches to
selling and design to make their products stand out.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a look at two PCs, one from a PC maker that sells in
stores, and one from a manufacturer that used to:
</P>
<P>
   eMonster 600 _ $974, eMachines. You have to hand it to eMachines
_ this relatively young PC maker has probably done more to drive
down the cost of PCs sold at retail than anyone else. While it may
cut some tight corners to do it, its computers usually are a good
value.
</P>
<P>
   The company usually scrimps in two areas _ processor speed and
memory.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't offer the priciest, fastest, top-of-the-line chips,
correctly assuming that the average home computer user doesn't need
them.
</P>
<P>
   With this model, however, eMachines is making some interesting
claims.
</P>
<P>
   It's touted as the PC for those who like to play games or who
have, according to promotional materials, ``demanding computing
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The eMonster 600 comes with a 600-megahertz Intel Pentium III
chip, 64 megabytes of memory, a 20-gigabyte hard drive, an 8X
DVD-ROM drive, an nVidia TNT2 Vanta graphics card with 8 MB of
memory, a 56K fax modem, stereo sound and speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The processor falls into the midrange of offerings from Intel _
it's not the slowest, but it certainly can't match the company's
1-gigahertz chip, either. The memory is generally what I would
consider the minimum to run Windows 98 comfortably, but twice what
eMachines offers on its lowest-priced models.
</P>
<P>
   The video card has potential _ the TNT2 graphics chip is
relatively fast and gives a good, clean look, but here it's
hamstrung by having only 8 MB of memory.
</P>
<P>
   The audio card is decent, though it doesn't support the latest
3-D audio standards from Creative Labs or Aureal. However, the
tiny, tinny speakers that eMachines ships with all its computers
don't do the card justice.
</P>
<P>
   Of the components, only the hard drive stands out as a
``monster'' part.
</P>
<P>
   It's fast and roomy.
</P>
<P>
   So how does this package come together? For many games, it does
quite well. For example, Ultima Online and The Sims ran quite
smoothly and without problems.
</P>
<P>
   However, higher-end titles, such as Quake III Arena or Flight
Simulator 2000, required that graphics settings be ratcheted way
down before they were comfortable to play.
</P>
<P>
   The eMonster handled everyday applications just fine, including
e-mail, America Online, word processing and home finance software.
</P>
<P>
   While I can't really recommend the eMonster for ``demanding
computing needs,'' I am comfortable saying that it's an excellent
computer for everyday needs. With a better graphics card, more
powerful speakers and additional memory, the eMonster would deserve
its name.
</P>
<P>
   Veriton FP 550 _ $2,150, Acer America Corp. Acer's computers
used to be easy to find in stores, but the company got out of the
retail consumer business last year. Now it sells its consumer PCs
online, but also sells computers to businesses via resellers and
independent Web vendors.
</P>
<P>
   The Veriton FP 550 is one of its business machines, but it would
make an excellent general-use PC at home _ particularly in a home
with minimal space. This is a one-piece computer with a flat-panel
display, and it's nifty.
</P>
<P>
   The Veriton comes with a 550-MHz Pentium III chip, 128 MB of
memory, a 12-GB hard drive, a 24X CD-ROM drive, stereo sound and
built-in speakers, an ATI Technologies Rage LT Pro graphics chip
with 8 MB of memory, a built-in Ethernet port and a 15-inch
active-matrix LCD monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many one-piece systems, the Veriton is not legacy-free,
or even legacy-light. It has a full complement of older style
ports, including serial and parallel ports. The keyboard and mouse
use PS/2 connections, instead of Universal Serial Bus ports.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is not a gamer's PC, it does the job with
entertainment titles. The Rage LT Pro chip works fairly well with
games that use Microsoft's DirectX 3-D graphics system. Its
performance with games that use OpenGL, another 3-D scheme, is not
quite as good as the eMachines' nVidia chip.
</P>
<P>
   One thing about the Veriton that might hinder it as a home PC is
its lack of a built-in modem. You can connect an external model via
either the serial or USB ports, of course. But the inclusion of an
Ethernet port makes it an excellent choice for use on a home
network, or with a cable or DSL modem.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this would be an excellent PC for anyone who wants a
fast, broadband connection and a no-hassles, plug-and-go computer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
