<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6003 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-POLITICAL-DONATIONS-A     06-16 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-DONATIONS-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ONE HOUSEHOLD HAS TWO POLITICAL AGENDAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, June 18) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leslie Wiesenfelder and his wife, Phyllis, are not what you
would call big donors to political campaigns _ certainly not the
kind of fat cats singled out by reformers for contributing to a
debasement of the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   But this Maryland pair, who joke about canceling each other's
votes, are a political odd couple that still typify a growing
phenomenon: families that give money to opposing sides. Though the
Wiesenfelders appear to manage it harmoniously, such cross-giving
in other households sometimes jeopardizes domestic tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's far more liberal than I am,'' said Wiesenfelder, a
lawyer and registered Republican who, according to the Federal
Election Commission, sent $286 last year to Sen. John McCain, the
former presidential candidate. Wiesenfelder, a Democrat, is listed
as a $500 donor to another former contender, Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The Wiesenfelders, who live just outside Washington in Chevy
Chase, even write checks for their dueling contributions from a
joint account. ``It's not a consultation and it's not a tradeoff,''
Wiesenfelder said of their less-than-fully-collegial method. But
it's also ``not personal, not an affront'' to the other, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Some politically opposed couples find contributions a somewhat
greater threat to harmony. ``There's a higher risk you run when
money is involved,'' said John Buckley, a former top official in
Republican presidential campaigns and now a senior vice president
at Fannie Mae, the federally chartered home-financing corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, who is married to Anna Bennett, a consultant to
Democratic candidates, said he recently contributed from their
joint account to George W. Bush and received in return a mail
solicitation for more money _ addressed to both him and his wife.
On an earlier occasion, he had to move quickly to intercept a
letter thanking both for a contribution he made to Sen. Christopher
Bond, R-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been quite embarrassing if it had gotten
noticed'' by his wife or, perhaps worse, by her clients, Buckley
said. ``I think it's probably time for separate accounts, given the
fact that many of the people she most supports are running against
those I'm most supportive of.''
</P>
<P>
   Combing through the 1999 records of the Federal Election
Commission, the Center for Responsive Politics in Washington found
scores of politically contrary contributions, a figure that may be
rising with economic prosperity, which affords more people the
resources to indulge political passions.
</P>
<P>
   And while political giving was long dominated by men ``there's
absolutely more women giving now,'' especially at the presidential
level, said Clyde Wilcox, a government professor at Georgetown
University.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best-known unmatched pair is James Carville, a chief
troubleshooter for President Clinton, and Mary Matalin, a top
campaign aide for former President George Bush who now appears on
CNN's ``Crossfire'' and advises George W. Bush's presidential
campaign. Then there is Ronald O. Perelman, the billionaire
businessman who splashes money around to an assortment of mendicant
parties and politicians, and Patricia Duff, a major fund-raiser for
Democrats. The pair had a loud confrontation at the Democrats' 1996
convention in Chicago, just before the breakup of their stormy
marriage of less than two years.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, politically mixed marriages remain a distinct
minority. ``Most folks marry people who share their values,
including their partisanship,'' said Paul Herrnson, a political
scientist at the University of Maryland and author of a book on
congressional elections. ``And in cases where they disagree, they
probably don't have much animosity about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Kramer of Shaker Heights, Ohio, for example, gave
$1,000 to McCain, while Vice President Al Gore got $1,000 from her
husband, Leonard Schwartz. ``His leanings are more Democratic,''
said Kramer, who administers a charitable foundation. ``I'm sort of
a Ripon Republican,'' referring to the centrist organization. Even
so, the ``discussion'' rarely escalates into argument, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudi Lee, an Atlanta homemaker and periodic contributor to
Republican candidates, is more than a little discreet about it with
her husband, Michael, a paper-company manager. He is also a
Republican, but they disagree on various issues, including abortion
and whether there is a glass ceiling for female executives. But the
subject of donations ``just doesn't come up,'' said Lee, who draws
such checks on her account. ``He probably doesn't even know.''
</P>
<P>
   In households where parents are politically engaged, there is a
good chance the children are, too. The 1999 records of the Federal
Elections Commission include one extended family in Missouri whose
members gave to the campaigns of Sen. John Ashcroft, a Republican
seeking re-election, and his Democratic opponent, Gov. Mel
Carnahan, in the most expensive Senate race outside New York. The
records show that 16 people with the same family name and
small-town address made donations _ more than two dozen to the
Ashcroft campaign and more than one dozen to Carnahan's.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say cross-purpose donations within families appear
especially common in primaries, when disagreement often centers on
which candidate is most electable, rather than on fundamental
principles.
</P>
<P>
   And in some cases donations are spread among opposing candidates
or parties for business, not personal, reasons. According to the
records, Stephen K. Lambright, general counsel for the
Anheuser-Busch Companies, gave $1,000 to George W. Bush, $1,000 to
Al Gore and $2,000 to the Democratic Leaders' Victory Fund 2000
last year, while his wife, Gail, gave $1,000 each to Bush and Gore.
``You could look at any given election and probably find us both on
both sides,'' Lambright said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes campaigns ask a donor to let it reallocate, say, a
$500 donation, assigning half to the original donor and half to the
spouse so that more of the total qualifies for matching funds; the
federal government matches the first $250 an individual gives to a
presidential primary candidate. The strategy sometimes extends to
children.
</P>
<P>
   But ideology remains a prime motivator in generating campaign
cash. Consider Bruce Teitelbaum and his wife, Suri Kasirer. He is a
former campaign manager for Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican mayor
of New York; she is a prominent Democratic consultant and activist
and a delegate to the party's national convention in Los Angeles
this August.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife is a loyal Democrat, right to the core,'' Teitelbaum
said. ``Our house is flooded with solicitations, and she never
fails to contribute. Sometimes I ask her why in the world she gives
to people she doesn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasirer, who acknowledges that her husband is not ``as
ideological as I am,'' bristles when he wonders out loud whether
she ought to discuss contributions with him _ the couple make their
donations from separate accounts. ``We each do our own political
giving,'' she said, her voice suggesting that their marriage
benefits from the fact that travel and work commitments often
separate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not together enough to argue about it,'' Teitelbaum said
with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-POKEMON0617-COX     06-16 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POKEMON0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pokemon starting to show age
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Barchas
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Keep your eyes peeled for an obituary like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Pikachu and his fellow friends in the Pokemon universe, age 2
in America, died today of natural toy fad causes.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon began as a hand-held video game and expanded across the
globe into a veritable phenomenon with trading cards, game leagues
and paraphernalia from bandages to ice pops. Pokemon will be
greatly missed by those who enjoy little animated monsters,
although parents probably aren't too sorry to see it go.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon was preceded in death by Transformers, Cabbage Patch
Dolls and Garbage Pail Kids.
</P>
<P>
   The game is survived by Digimon, Gundam Wing and DragonBall Z.
</P>
<P>
   No memorial contributions are necessary, as corporate America
has already claimed billions in sales during the height of the
Pokemon phenomenon. (Plus, toy stores can discount Pokemon products
and unload them before too long.)''
</P>
<P>
   While it may be too soon yet to ring the death knell for
Pokemon, many stores report that the fad is fading as children move
on to newer games. ``Basically, we're seeing Pokemon slip a bit,''
said Greg D'Andrea, store director at Toys ``R'' Us in Austin.
``Right now, Pokemon is starting to fall. They're not as hot as
they once were.''
</P>
<P>
   Pokemaniacs, devoted solely to selling Pokemon and anime
products, reports a similar decline in sales. ``We're getting more
and more kids nowadays who just want to trade their cards in for
cash,'' said manager Danny Butler. ``I mean, the game itself was
pretty good when it came out, but eventually it just turned into a
fad. There are other things out there nowadays. Some kids just get
into sports or other video games.''
</P>
<P>
   This decreased interest in Pokemon products is simply a product
of time, according to D'Andrea. ``The toy business is a fad
business,'' he said. ``Kids slowly switch to the newest product.''
</P>
<P>
   But that may disappoint the business world as companies continue
to funnel money into new Pokemon products. Warner Bros. will be
releasing a summer follow-up to its original smash hit ``Pokemon:
The First Movie.'' Nintendo plans to introduce dozens of different
characters this fall in new games Pokemon Gold and Silver. Even
Welch's has jumped on the bandwagon by featuring nine Pokemon
characters on its 25th series of collectible jelly jars.
</P>
<P>
   But this hype might not be enough to resurrect Pokemon.
KidGenius owner Jeff Hunt, who generally avoids handling
collectible items unless there's such a demand it will hurt overall
business not to carry a toy, says his store will likely stop
selling Pokemon this year. ``I think that toward the end of the
year I'll not be carrying them, largely because I don't believe
there will be as much of a demand,'' Hunt said. ``I think they'll
become primarily a collector's item because I don't think there's a
tremendous amount of intrinsic play value in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents shouldn't be breathing sighs of relief about Pokemon's
demise yet, though. New games are already waiting to take its
place. Digimon is eerily similar to Pokemon, combining a trading
card game with a television show, and Gundam Wing, a space
adventure series also originating in Japan, has already gained a
solid fan base.
</P>
<P>
   But Matthew Kaminski, assistant manager at K B Toys, says that
even with these other fads on the horizon, no one should be saying
the Pokemon craze is over yet. ``It's not as popular as ever, but
it's not declining any time soon,'' he said. Kaminski said the
newest set of Pokemon trading cards, Team Rocket, offers something
for everyone. ``It's an entirely new set with all different
drawings,'' he said. ``It's the same Pokemon with a different
twist. People who are collectors will like the art work. For people
who actually play the game, they're overall better cards, and it
gives you an edge while you are playing.''
</P>
<P>
   And although they don't release exact numbers, Wizards of the
Coast, the Washington company that manufactures Pokemon trading
cards, says sales are still high. ``I think that some retailers
have seen a slowdown, and with others, it's still being snatched
off the shelf, so it depends on the retailer and the location,''
said Carol Rogalski, director of corporate communications. ``I
think that what's happening for us is that it's leveling off a bit,
and there's not as steep of an increase in sales. But people are
still very interested in Pokemon. It certainly isn't going
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Llewelyn, public relations manager at Nintendo, predicts
that Pokemon sales will reach $3 billion this year. She says she
isn't sure why people think Pokemon is losing popularity. ``It
could be that one kid decided to trade in his cards, and it rippled
off from that,'' Llewelyn said. ``From what we've seen and heard,
it's still going very, very strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   But just in case, be on the lookout for this: May Pokemon rest
in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
