<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BONFIRE (College Station, Texas) _ Texas A&AMP;M cancels its
bonfire this year and will have a very different operation when the
annual tradition resumes. To avoid a the collapse like the one in
1999 that killed 12 people, future bonfires will be smaller and be
better supervised. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS-INTERNET (Milwaukee, Wis.) _ The National Conference of
Catholic Bishops reviews a 2,500-word statement that forms its
response to complaints about obscene and hate-filled material on
the Internet. Noting that cyberspace can have its downside, the
draft statement says Internet use can be a little like visiting the
best theme park in the world and coming across a toxic waste dump.
By CECILE HOLMES.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CANADA (Washington) _ Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister
Lloyd Axworthy, who has helped broker several international
treaties, says most conflicts now occur within nations, rather than
between them, and that casualties increasingly are civilians rather
than soldiers. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The choices consumers have for
buying computers in retail stores are rapidly dwindling. Tiny
profits and scarce shelf space have driven many personal computer
makers out of stores and onto the Web. Some familiar names are
missing from store shelves _ including IBM, Packard Bell and Acer.
Only three national brands of PCs are available at retail: Compaq,
Hewlett-Packard and eMachines. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-LAKERS-PACERS (Undated) _ For those who didn't stay up past
midnight Wednesday on the off chance that the NBA and NBC would
collaborate on a playoff production and have actual entertainment
break out, Game 4 of the Finals was a sight for sore and sleepy
eyes. Basketball fans have the Los Angeles Lakers and Indiana
Pacers to thank for providing some must-see-to-believe TV. It truly
was a game for the ages. By STEVE CAMPBELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-ELECTION (Washington) _ The future makeup of the
nine-member U.S. Supreme Court is a top behind-the-scenes issue in
this year's presidential race between Republican George W. Bush and
Democrat Al Gore. The winner may have the rare opportunity to
appoint as many as four new justices to replace jurists who are
expected to step down over the next four years because of age or
ill health. By STEWART M. POWELL and MARK HELM. (Filed Wednesday,
will update.)
</P>
