<SLUG> BC-MOTORCYCLES-RDUP-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW AND FAST ON 2 WHEELS FOR THE SUMMER OF 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 18) 
 By JIM McCRAW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are heady times for motorcycle enthusiasts. Not only has
the weather turned perfect for riding, but the thriving industry is
serving up a host of new models.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, there is more advanced technology, extra power, better
brakes (even antilock brakes, like those in cars), longer
warranties and emergency road service.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a roundup of some highlights of the motorcycle market
this season:
</P>
<P>
   APRILIA _ This maker of high-style, high-tech Italian
motorcycles has been in the American market for only a year or so.
It offers three distinct models, the RSV Mille, a V-twin
1000-cubic-centimeter superbike ($13,799), the SL 1000 Falco V-twin
1000 cc sportbike ($11,299) and the Pegaso 650 cc single-cylinder
street bike ($7,877) with the dual-purpose on- and off-road look so
popular in Europe. Aprilia already has about 70 dealerships in the
United States, and it recently signed an agreement to acquire
another Italian motorcycle giant, Moto Guzzi, which makes large
V-twin shaft-drive cruiser, touring and sport bikes.
</P>
<P>
   BUELL _ The Buell sport bike division of Harley-Davidson has
produced its first single-cylinder ``starter'' bike, a low-priced,
no-frills model called the Blast, a 500 cc high-style street bike
that sells for only $4,395 and is aimed at novice riders. In
addition, Buell offers the Cyclone ($8,599), the Lightning
($10,599), and the Thunderbolt ($11,999), all using Harley engines
of 91 or 101 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   BMW _ After a record sales year, BMW has more models than ever,
including the new 2001 F 650 GS single-cylinder chain-drive machine
that won the Granada-Dakar rally. The F 650 ($8,110 to $8,600) has
optional antilock brakes, electronic engine management and a
catalytic converter in the exhaust system _ technologies found on
no other single-cylinder bike. Also new for 2000 is the R 1150 GS
on- and off-road bike ($14,190), a traditional BMW opposed-twin
machine with high-mounted front and rear fenders, two asymmetrical
headlamps and a three-way-adjustable windscreen.
</P>
<P>
   CAGIVA _ Cagiva owns the Cagiva and MV Agusta street bike brands
and the Swedish Husqvarna dirt-bike line. Cagiva's Grand Canyon
($8,995) uses a 904 cc V-twin Ducati engine _ the company used to
own Ducati _ and electronic fuel injection in a half-fairing body
that's part off-road bike, part street bike and part pack mule. The
limited-production MV Agusta 750 F4 Strada ($18,895) is the
company's technological tour de force, a four-cylinder race bike
for the street with a passel of patented technologies from its dual
polyellipsoidal headlamps to its Ferrari-designed radial-valve
engine.
</P>
<P>
   DUCATI _ The vaunted Italian company tried something new on Jan.
1, an Internet sale of some special machines, the MH900e 900 cc,
Mike Hailwood Evolution. Designed to look like the bike that the
world champion rode in his heyday, it was sold only online,
starting at one second after midnight. All 500 were sold in a few
minutes. The Ducati product line continues unchanged for 2000: the
Monster 750 ($6,995) and 900 ($10,495); the Supersport 750 ($8,295)
and 900 ($10,995); the ST2 and ST4 touring bikes ($12,495 and
$14,695); the 748 ($12,495) and the new 996, replacing the
legendary 916, at $16,495 for the standard and $20,995 for the S
version.
</P>
<P>
   EXCELSIOR-HENDERSON _ Excelsior-Henderson, of Belle Plaine,
Minn., started and finished in 1999, declaring Chapter 11
bankruptcy late in the year. The company has been rescued by new
investors who formed a new company, E-H Partners. Production is
restarting, and a new model of the Super X V-twin cruiser, with a
new front suspension, has already been shown.
</P>
<P>
   HARLEY-DAVIDSON _ Harley's most significant news for 2000 is
that it has passed Honda as the leading seller of motorcycles in
the United States (based on sales for the 1999 calendar year). Then
there's the new 88 cubic-inch ``Fathead'' engine that, with its
internal balancing system, has virtually eliminated the
characteristic rolling vibrations inherent in Harley's big-engined
bikes. The new engine was introduced late in the last riding season
to rave reviews. Among the new models for 2000 is the Softail Deuce
($15,995) with stacked exhaust pipes, a stretched fuel tank, new
fender designs, bigger brakes and a chromed front suspension.
</P>
<P>
   HONDA _ For 2000, Honda has introduced two high-performance
motorcycles, the CBR929RR and the RC51, each with completely
different designs. The CBR929RR ($9,999) is a 150-horsepower
in-line four-cylinder sport bike that weighs only 379 pounds. The
RC51 (also $9,999) is a 125-horsepower 999 cc V-twin that, while
completely street-legal, is made for AMA Superbike racing. On the
touring/cruising side of the house, Honda has a new Shadow Sabre,
an 1100 cc liquid-cooled V-twin cruiser bike starting at $8,199 for
basic black.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN _ The 2000 Indian Chief ($23,995), a new motorcycle
design faithful to the original Indian last produced in 1953, has
fully valanced front and rear fenders, an Indian-head running lamp
on the front fender and retro logos. The design is wrapped around
an 88 cubic-inch S&AMP;S-modified Harley engine and transmission. Later
this year, a new Indian Scout model will be introduced, and shortly
after that, Indian expects to produce its own V-twin engines.
</P>
<P>
   KAWASAKI _ Kawasaki has just introduced the Ninja ZX-12R, the
quickest and fastest motorcycle it has ever built, limited to a top
speed of 185 mph. The 1,200 cc ZX-12R is joined by a new 900 cc
ZX-9R Ninja, a new 600 cc Ninja ZX-6R, and three new cruiser bikes.
Cruisers are led by a new Vulcan 1500 Nomad with electronic fuel
injection, saddle bags and a windshield; a Vulcan 1500 Classic,
also with fuel injection; and the Vulcan 800 Drifter, an 800 cc
version of Kawasaki's 1940s retro cruiser, also available with a
1500 cc engine.
</P>
<P>
   MOTO GUZZI _ Aside from its acquisition by Aprilia, Moto Guzzi
has a wider array of its transverse V-twin, shaft-drive bikes.
Built around a 1,064 cc engine and a five-speed transmission are
the California Jackal ($8,495), the California Special ($11,700),
packing a good deal more chrome, and the 90-horsepower V11 Sport
($11,900).
</P>
<P>
   MZ _ Germany's MZ makes a full line of lightweight bikes wrapped
around a monster Yamaha XTZ 660 cc single-cylinder engine, and an
unusual large-tubing frame. The line includes the on- and off-road
Black Panther ($6,195), the bare-bones Tour ($4,995), the Skorpion
full-bodied sportbike ($5,795) and the Skorpion Traveller touring
bike with saddle bags and windshield ($6,495).
</P>
<P>
   SUZUKI _ With several 1999 racing championships to its credit,
along with the the 1,300 cc Hayabusa _ the quickest and fastest
production motorcycle in the world _ Suzuki goes into the 2000
riding season with a wide array of machinery, including the all-new
GSX-R750 race bike replica and the bargain-priced ($5,749) SV650
fun bike, The Hayabusa ($10,799), perhaps the biggest
high-performance bargain on earth _ car or bike _ is available in
slightly less garish colors for 2000. It is not quite as quick or
as fast as the 1999 model, which was timed at 194 mph.
</P>
<P>
   TRIUMPH _ The last survivor of the once-dominant British
motorcycle manufacturers, Triumph has thrived in the American
market over the last five years. For 2000, there are two brand new
models. The first is the TT600, a lightweight, 600 cc 4-cylinder
machine in a stunning black and yellow livery aimed directly at the
Japanese 600s. It is joined by an all-new Sprint RS, using
Triumph's proven 955 cc three-cylinder engine in a lightweight
machine with a half fairing and exposed engine.
</P>
<P>
   VICTORY _ In only its third year as a motorcycle manufacturer,
Victory now has two 1,500 cc cruisers, the original V92C and the
new V92SC, distinguished by its bobbed fenders and very large
chrome muffler on the right side. (The original has twin pipes and
mufflers.) The standard cruiser, updated for 2000 with more power
and a better-sounding exhaust system, retails for $13,399, the SC
for $13,999. Victory plans a whole series of factory-sponsored
touring and cruising rides for Victory owners in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   YAMAHA _ After nearly 50 years of cooperation on engines and
research, Toyota bought 5 percent of Yamaha, Japan's second-largest
motorcycle manufacturer, earlier this year; in turn, Yamaha Corp.
and Yamaha Motors each bought 500,000 shares of Toyota. Yamaha's
2000 product line is led by the lighter, stronger, better handling
1,000 cc YZF-R1 performance bike, with a new chassis and a new 150
horsepower engine for $10,299. On the cruiser side, there's a new
Venture MM Limited 1,300 cc V-4 ($16,099), a loaded cruiser with
special cream paint and limited-edition dress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
