<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ROCKBANDS-NUMBERS-TEX     06-16 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKBANDS-NUMBERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUNCHING NUMBERS: HERE'S THE 411 ON TODAY'S HOT NEW
NUMERICALLY-NAMED BANDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a recent phone interview, Matchbox Twenty singer Rob Thomas
explained why the band changed its name from 20 to, um, Twenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want people to get us confused with all those other
number bands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there are indeed a ``number'' of alternative-rock bands that
use numerals in their names _ and, just as Thomas said, it's easy
to confuse them, they share so many likenesses.
</P>
<P>
   Like, say, their looks. There are two numeral-band looks. The
first one is alterna-hottie _ short spiked hair, handsome but
kind-of innocuous features, maybe an earring or a tattoo. They look
like they bathe in money.
</P>
<P>
   Look No. 2: bad-boy. Baggy clothes, mangy hair, lotsa tattoos
and body piercings. They look like they don't bathe at all.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the music _ which is either angry Korn-inspired
metal, or addictive but middle-of-the-road Third Eye Blind-inspired
rock-pop.
</P>
<P>
   And the names? They are: Project 86, Apartment 26, 3 Doors Down,
Blink-182, Stroke 9, 8Stops7 _ whew! So, between the similar names,
looks and music, how ``do'' you keep track of 'em?
</P>
<P>
   Here's how _ with our number-band breakdown:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blink-182
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: 92101 (San Diego)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: Melodic pop-punk trio, with a heaping of
juvenile humor.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: Several: ``What's My Age Again, All the Small
Things'' and, the trio's current chart-climber, ``Adam's Song,'' a
touching song about the suicide death of a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: Originally, they were simply called Blink,
but an Irish band with a similar name threatened to sue, forcing
them to tweak it. Thus, they added the 182. ``It's how many times
(a specific expletive) was said in `Scarface,''' says band
publicist Leona Megerdichian.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apartment 26
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: SW14XT (London)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: Young electronic-rock quartet (think Nine Inch
Nails) whose lead singer, Biff Butler, is the son of Black Sabbath
bassist Geezer Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: Working on first one, ``Basic Breakdown,'' which is
currently getting airplay on hard-rock stations like Dallas'
KEGL/97.1 ``The Eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: Also derived from a movie. This one being
David Lynch's ultra-weird cult classic, ``Eraserhead.'' The movie's
main character, played by Jack Nance, lives in apartment No. 26.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matchbox Twenty
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: 32801 (Orlando)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: Enormously popular, earnest pop-rock quintet
that, along with the also numerically named Third Eye Blind, opened
the floodgates for other modest pop bands.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: Just about half the songs on their 1996 debut,
``Yourself or Someone Like You,'' have been ingrained into our
subconscious. Chances are, same thing will happen with the group's
recently released second CD, ``Mad Season by Matchbox Twenty,''
which has already yielded the hit ``Bent.''
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: Drummer Paul Doucette thought of it when he
was working in a restaurant. A patron came in wearing a softball
shirt with the No. 20 on it; a patch on the shirt said
``matchbox.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Doucette was going to use the name for a clothing
company he was hoping would take off. Instead, the band did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Project 86
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: 92801 (Orange County, Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: Christian rap-core, a pro-God version of
Deftones and Rage Against the Machine.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: Currently climbing metal charts with first single,
``One Armed Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: Using ``86'' as slang for starting over or
starting fresh, band singer Andrew Schwab says Project 86
translates to ``new project.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 Doors Down
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: 39552 (Escatawpa, Miss.)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: Guitar-fueled Matchbox Twenty sound-alike with
at least one interesting trait: drummer Brad Arnold is also the
lead singer.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: One, but it's a biggie _ ``Kryptonite,'' which has
been sitting in the No. 1 slot of ``Billboard's'' Mainstream Rock
Tracks charts for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: It was dreamed up while the band was on a
road trip. ``We came out of this building, and some of the letters
had fallen off the front. ... It said `doors down,''' Arnold says.
``At the time, there were just three of us, so we said, `3 Doors
Down.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eiffel 65
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: 10128 (Torino, Italy)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: The odd ones of the number bunch: they're a
dance-pop trio. No guitars or tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: The ridiculously annoying Top 10 single ``Blue (Da Ba
Dee).''
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: Not able to think of anything on their own,
the band members let a computer randomly choose it. On the computer
printout that had the chosen word ``Eiffel'' on it, someone
inadvertently scribbled two digits of someone's phone number beside
it: 65. The name stuck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nine Days
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: 11729 (Deer Park, Long Island)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: Straightforward guitar-pop.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: One huge modern-rock single, ``Absolutely (Story of a
Girl)'' (Do we see a one-hit-wonder trend here?)
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: Coined by singer/guitarist Brian Desveaux
when someone in the band asked him how long they had been in the
studio working on their debut, ``The Madding Crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8Stops7
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: 93001 (Ventura, Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: Headbanger quintet with mystic lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: They've had two Top 20 rock-radio tracks, ``My
Would-Be Savior'' and ``Satisfied.'' A third single, ``Question
Everything,'' is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: Drummer Adam Powell came up with Eight
Stops Nowhere. Singer/guitarist Evan Fula-Goff tweaked it to
8Stops7 for ``artistic'' reasons. ``Seven is a symbol for something
you want to get away from and 8 is the door you go through to get
there,'' he states in the band's bio. We'll take his word for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sevendust
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: 30301 (Atlanta)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: Rap-rock school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: A handful on modern rock radio, including ``Waffle''
and ``Denial,'' from their second disc, ``Home.''
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: Originally called Crawlspace, the band was
forced to change its name when another band already claimed dibs on
it. Band bassist Vinnie Hornsby came up with Sevendust, the name of
a combustive chemical.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stroke 9
</P>
<P>
   ZIP code: 94101 (San Francisco)
</P>
<P>
   Band one-liner: Well-crafted pop quartet that's not afraid to
detour into reggae and ambient territory.
</P>
<P>
   Hit count: Two: The inescapable and hilarious ``Little Black
Backpack'' (about kicking the crud out of your ex-girlfriend's
backpack) and the far more poignant ``Letters.''
</P>
<P>
   The 411 on the name: Taken from a line in a T.S. Eliot poem,
``The Waste Land'' _ fitting, since the band's lyrics often border
on the poetic.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
