<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6015 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-16 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T EXPECT THE HIGH ROAD TO BE CROWDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It says here that Hillary Clinton is taking off the gloves in
her U.S. Senate race against Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reports that Clinton has adopted a ``new,
aggressive approach'' designed to brand Lazio as a right-wing
extremist whose votes in Congress have hurt women, children and
families.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, this isn't a new strategy. When Lazio came
off the bench recently to replace New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani
as Clinton's opponent, the Clinton campaign's immediate reaction
was to attack the Republican congressman as a clone of ex-House
Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   That was the ideological equivalent of declaring war, of course,
and Lazio fired back by raising the carpetbagger issue against
Clinton, a barely unpacked New York transplant whose motives are
highly suspect in the eyes of some Empire State residents.
</P>
<P>
   After that initial exchange of rhetorical warheads, both
candidates seemed to back off and begin focusing on their own
ideas. But now, says the Times, Clinton has launched a nuclear
attack by delivering a campaign speech in which she blasted Lazio
on gun control, abortion rights and education policy.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper quoted the speech:
</P>
<P>
   ``On issue after issue, my opponent has been a follower, not a
leader. He voted to shut down the government. He voted for a
trillion-dollar budget that would have slashed so many services
that we need here in New York. He would squander the surplus and, I
believe, endanger the economy. And yet he says he agrees with me on
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Times offered some analysis as well:
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's speech underscored a shift in strategy by a
candidate who has, with the loss of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as an
opponent, seemed unsure how to proceed in an unexpectedly tight
race with his replacement, a little-known Republican representative
from Long Island. In taking on Lazio so directly _ the speech
sounded like the kind of attack candidates save for the final weeks
of a campaign _ Clinton was trying to shape New Yorkers' perception
of her new opponent before he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Giuliani dropped out of the race to deal with cancer and
other personal problems, Clinton's campaign strategy was
cut-and-dried: Attack, attack, attack.
</P>
<P>
   With Giuliani embroiled in controversy more or less constantly
in connection with his responsibilities as mayor, he was an
inviting target for criticism. He virtually had a bull's-eye
tattooed on his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the mayor often hurt his own cause by
being defensive, insensitive and just plain jerky.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio couldn't be more different. His early campaign appearances
were amiable, charming and relentlessly upbeat _ which might be why
Clinton put away the heavy artillery after that early assault on
Lazio's past association with Gingrich. The first lady might have
feared that hammering a nice guy too hard could prove
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   She might have figured that her unfavorable ratings were high
enough _ 31 percent in a recent poll cited by the Times _ without
alienating even more voters with overstated attacks on Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, when Lazio first jumped into the race, Clinton enjoyed
a colossal lead over him in most public-opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The lead evaporated quickly, however, once Lazio started
campaigning. That caused some of Clinton's supporters to worry that
her campaign had become ``overly placid,'' the Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   So. Down with placid. Up with aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   But as quickly as Clinton tore into Lazio and his record in
Congress, Lazio tore into Clinton and her negative tactics. He
derided her criticism as ``mudslinging,'' according to the Times,
and accused her of distorting his ``mainstream record.''
</P>
<P>
   This could get very interesting. Not to mention very nasty,
considering that the election is nearly five months away.
</P>
<P>
   How long will Lazio keep traveling the campaign high road if
Clinton is determined to drag him into the gutter?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guess: Not long.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
