<HEADLINE>
CRITIC PICKS THE BEST SHOWS OF THE YEAR; TOO BAD THE NETWORKS DON'T
AGREE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``La Femme Nikita'' has aired on USA for four years, but I don't
personally know a soul who watches it regularly. There are those
who peruse and sample, and return disoriented, disengaged and
disenchanted _ as if they'd stumbled into a maze with no form of
escape.
</P>
<P>
   How unfortunate, though certainly understandable. ``La Femme
Nikita,'' which extends Luc Besson's feature film about an
ambivalent female assassin working for a secret government
organization, is a thriller for the information and MTV age _
high-tech and high-brow in its somber mood and survivalist methods.
It could very well be the darkest, most complicated and most
humorless series ever made.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the most stylish, enigmatic, sensuous and savagely
engrossing series to air this season.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who have been in the ``La Femme Nikita'' camp since day
one, and those who came late but have stuck around long enough to
``get'' this drama, are in for life _ or at least until USA drops
the series, which, if reports are true, will be this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Femme Nikita'' is the best show on TV because it delivers
the standard goods _ cool gadgets and gizmos, illogical
predicaments, global menaces, massive explosions, shootouts,
oblique and enigmatic characters. But even more so because of the
ongoing battle by Nikita (Peta Wilson) to save a few vestiges of
humanity (not to mention that doomed romance with Michael, the
stone-faced operative) in a brutal, inhuman world. That is what
gives this series its complexity and gut-level entertainment value.
</P>
<P>
   When I tell people that ``La Femme Nikita'' is an hour as
dramatically satisfying as ``ER'' and ``The Sopranos,'' they often
dismiss me. Go right ahead, sneer. But the fact is, few shows can
balance corny and campy action without a trace of corniness or
campiness, and, let's face it: Even fewer manage to offer such a
tasty show of female empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   So which shows round out my top 10, you ask? Here you go:
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' (WB) _ Fans who feared the Buff
would sour as the gang moved from high school to college (and as
creator Joss Whedon pulled a double shift with ``Angel''), have
been in a state of pleasant shock. Whedon has managed to make
``Buffy'' just as enticing as ever while changing almost everything
this past season. Willow's (Alyson Hannigan) love affair is the
most subtle and sensuous gay romance I've witnessed on TV _ or
film, for that matter. And Whedon has managed to keep the
fatalistic love affair between Buffy and Angel (David Boreanaz)
going with crossovers so seamlessly crafted they didn't feel like
the shamelessly calculated contraptions they really were.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Once and Again'' (ABC) _ This drama was among a batch of
new shows to actually deal with grown-ups and grown-up issues.
Created by writer-producers Edward Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz,
the series proves to be as much about the pain of divorce and
parents struggling with their children's adolescent sexuality as it
is about the protagonists _ two newly single parents _ trying to
find a love life of their own.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Malcolm in the Middle'' (Fox) _ Shot with a single camera
and using a kid genius as narrator and guide, this energetic sitcom
bottled the mood of family life _ noisy, disorganized, loving _ and
poured it out in hilarious, sidesplitting dollops. Frankie Muniz is
a joy as the wide-eyed Malcolm, but it's the parents, the
cheerfully spaced-out dad (Bryan Cranston) and the all-seeing,
all-knowing warden of a mother (Jane Kaczmarek) who kept the series
fresh even after the initial you-gotta-see-this excitement wore
off.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Freaks &AMP; Geeks'' (NBC) _ Not since ``My So-Called Life''
has the mystification of adolescence appeared so real and
pronounced. That ``Freaks'' performed this trick with humor and a
cast chosen for ability and pragmatism, not looks, made it that
much more remarkable. Its cancellation was nothing short of a
cultural crime.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``GvsE'' (USA) _ USA canned this low-rated series, which
isn't as surprising as it is simply unfortunate, considering that
it was one of the most inventive, funny, ambitious and deliciously
unusual series in some time. Its premise, about a couple of dead
guys fighting demons for a secret organization, was outlandish,
perhaps even silly. But it worked gloriously ... well, it did for
me, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   7. ``Sex and the City'' (HBO) _ This racy, profane and decidedly
insider look at the dating scene in New York blithely bulldozes the
conventional wisdom of half-hour comedies. ``Sex'''s four single
femmes navigating Manhattan nightlife and lust manage to really
``say'' something about female sexuality and the always strange,
mystifying dance of the sexes. That it's usually over raw oysters
and vodka stingers makes it all the better.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Wonderland'' (ABC) _ Engaging and engrossing and in trouble
from the moment it was scheduled, this drama set inside a mental
ward of a city hospital was yanked after just two episodes. I saw
four of them _ and, while I agree that the opening episode was a
downer and rather unfair in showing the mentally ill as violent,
future episodes presented more of a balance, and, therefore, a
prime opportunity to understand a world we fear.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Now and Again'' (CBS) _ You wonder if viewers knew what to
make of this pleasant, playful series, which would switch gears _
and genres, even _ several times in the course of an hour. ``Now
and Again,'' canceled by CBS, was also hurt by its ``Six Million
Dollar Man'' association. A shame. This Glenn Gordon Caron
(''Moonlighting'') series was hardly campy or lightweight, even
while breaking into a quick song-and-dance. It delivered as a
drama, comedy, thriller, sci-fi, romantic adventure, and, yeah,
musical. It'll be missed.
</P>
<P>
   10. Tie: ``The West Wing'' (NBC) and ``Judging Amy'' (CBS) _
Aaron Sorkin's fantasy tale about the doings of a White House
administration was smart and gooey and rarely boring. Its cast
members were first-rate and never for a moment forgot that they
were saving the world. ``Judging Amy'' was more understated and far
more effective. Where ``The West Wing'' appeared at times to be a
show doing a serious take on what's actually ripe for parody,
``Judging Amy'' used its drama to explain how the law is a living
thing evolving every day, every ``minute,'' and that change comes
so quickly that many rulings learned by law students are obsolete
by the time they pass the bar. But what doesn't change, it told us
even more powerfully, is the value of family.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
