<HEADER>
A6018 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BOYSANDGIRLS-TEX     06-16 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOYSANDGIRLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDS, BEES, `BOYS AND GIRLS' _ NOT MUCH NEW HERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Boys and Girls,'' which entered the youth-film sweepstakes
when it opened Friday, platonic buds Ryan and Jennifer (Freddie
Prinze Jr. and Claire Forlani) take in a double bill of John
Hughes' ``Sixteen Candles'' and ``The Breakfast Club'' in an
attempt to find answers to their romantic confusion. It's meant to
be a tribute to the youthful savvy of Hughes' mid-'80s movies, but
it's merely lip service, since ``Boys and Girls'' appears to be
completely out of touch with ``anything'' savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Ryan and Jennifer have never heard of ``When Harry
Met Sally,'' because if they had watched it instead, they would
have saved themselves _ and us _ a lot of time and grief. Like that
movie, ``Boys and Girls'' tells the story of friends who were
obviously meant to be together, and since everyone but them
recognizes this, we wait for more than an hour and a half for the
inevitable climactic scene in which they both wise up.
Unfortunately, unlike ``When Harry Met Sally,'' ``Boys and Girls''
doesn't have much warmth _ or wit _ to keep us entertained while we
wait.
</P>
<P>
   Like Harry and Sally, Jennifer and Ryan meet while traveling,
except that in this case they're 12-year-old seatmates on a plane
flight, and _ in what passes for the filmmakers' idea of charm _
she's candidly telling him that she just had her first menstrual
period and baiting him with sexual references. Jennifer is
free-spirited and spontaneous; Ryan is uptight and nerdy. They
immediately clash, and they clash again when they run into each
other a few years later at a high-school football game. But when
they meet again at college, they click, especially after they're
dumped by their respective significant others.
</P>
<P>
   Director Robert Iscove (''She's All That'') appears to have
stumbled on a cynical strategy for cliches and situations: If you
haven't seen it, it's new to you. So Iscove and screenwriters
Andrew Lowery and Andrew Miller (billed, absurdly, as ``The
Drews'') shoplift from any number of sources that might not be
familiar to their target audience. We get earnest, wide-eyed and
idealistic conversations (name your favorite mid-'60s teen flick),
a Berkeley setting (''The Graduate''), a park scene in which Ryan
and Jennifer make up identities for the people they see (''Annie
Hall''), and, of course, the ``Harry Met Sally'' riffs. Iscove even
rips off himself, repeating the choreographed prom dance from his
``She's All That'' with a choreographed club sequence that seems to
have been inspired by Gap commercials.
</P>
<P>
   It's all just such a waste. Prinze and Forlani struggle to be
engaging, but often come off like high-school drama students doing
a series of scenes from ``Friends.'' Jason Biggs, so likable in
``American Pie,'' barely escapes being grating as Ryan's lecherous
roommate who doesn't know how to _ gasp _ ``be himself.'' Amanda
Detmer, as Jennifer's flaky roommate, is subject to the confused
whims of the screenwriters _ she shares a moment with Forlani that
could have been turned into a crucial and interesting plot twist
but is never pursued.
</P>
<P>
   Alyson Hannigan, who steals scenes on TV's ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' and had the ``money'' line in ``American Pie,'' is in the
movie so briefly, it's a wonder she accepted credit. ``The Blair
Witch Project's'' Heather Donahue shows hints of energy as Ryan's
no-nonsense girlfriend, but it's a minor role.
</P>
<P>
   The most stupefying thing about ``Boys and Girls,'' however,
comes at the end, in a closing-credit sequence involving Biggs,
four Victoria's Secret models and flatulence. It doesn't have a
thing to do with the rest of the movie, and its tone is so much
more crass than the irony-free story that preceded it, its
grossness is jarring. It's as if the filmmakers, having thought
they had already reached the lowest common denominator, discovered
an even ``lower'' one, and had to take advantage of it. Somebody
stop them before they find something even lower.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Boys and Girls''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Robert Iscove
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Freddie Prinze Jr., Claire Forlani
</P>
<P>
   Length: 97 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ strong language, sexual situations, bad hair and
cultural larceny
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
