<HEADLINE>
LEARNING TO FLY WITHOUT FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, June 18) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By my watch, it took six minutes from the time I
entered Molly Jong-Fast's book party at the Harmonie Club for sour
grapes to sprout. A young man, bound for law school, announced that
he would rather publish a novel, too. ``If it were this easy for
me, I would write,'' he said churlishly, taking in the
photographers snapping shots of Jong-Fast with her mother, the
novelist Erica Jong, hovering and smiling nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Now, now, boys and girls, play nice. Having a famous mommy, a
famous daddy (novelist Jonathan Fast) and a famous grandpa
(novelist Howard Fast) doesn't mean it's always rosy for the
offspring. As Jong-Fast writes in her first novel, ``Normal Girl,''
(Villard), ``The children of famous people are a bit like
Communism, better in concept than in practice.'' But in our
celebrity worshiping culture, not to mention this
attention-grubbing city, envy is stuck on automatic pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``Normal Girl'' has been published at the author's tender
age of 21. While that is a rather stunning achievement, it seems
somehow in keeping with the fact that Jong-Fast has lived much of
her brief life in fast forward. Her parents were divorced when she
was four, and she and her mother moved to Manhattan from
Connecticut. Jong-Fast went to the Dalton School until she was
asked to leave in the third grade, after testing dyslexic. She
transferred to the Day School where her academic life improved, but
by the time she was 13, she was close to 200 pounds and bulimic. At
16, she was drinking three vodka martinis at a clip, and after
graduating from the Riverdale School, she shot through stints at
Wesleyan, Barnard and New York University, supplementing her
cocktail of choice with cocaine and valium. By 19, she was at the
Hazelden drug and alcohol rehabilitation center.
</P>
<P>
   Her novel, unsurprisingly, is about a seen-it-all girl who ends
up in rehab. ``It's such a cliche, it's gross,'' Jong-Fast groaned
a few days after the party. She was seated at an outside table at
the Barking Dog Luncheonette here, even though the temperature was
in the 90s. She wanted to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I weren't me, I would hate me, too,'' she went on
agreeably, lighting up. ``I know the perception is I'm this
princess who gets advantages and is so privileged. I had a really
hard time making the character in my book sympathetic. Children in
Sarajevo are sympathetic already. Rich Jewish kids from the Upper
East Side aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a coming-of-age story, ``Normal Girl'' is the
latest entry in the fast-lane, club-kids genre that has included
``Bright Lights, Big City,'' ``Story of My Life'' and ``Slaves of
New York.'' Jong-Fast sums up contemporary New York City when she
writes, ``Nothing ever really changes ... Maybe disco has become
techno, promiscuous sex has morphed into cautious promiscuous sex
and cell phones have replaced religion as the opiate of the masses,
but our relentless obsession with The Next Big Thing-ism (TNBT-ism)
remains the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony that Jong-Fast's book is being pushed as TNBT does not
escape her. Neither does the fact that people assume the novel's
heroine _ who takes heroin _ is the author herself. Her book's
title is satirical; ``Everybody thinks their reality is normal,''
she said, even teen-agers who call funerals ``the cotillions of the
'90s'' and wear Prada boots in summer. Sober and drug-free for
almost three years, she is looking to define a different
``normal.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, she is forsaking what she calls the ``Madison
Avenue Mafia,'' a group that she describes in her book as having
one guiding principle: ``No matter how large the nose or how bad
the birthmark, whatever it is, it'll look better waxed, tweezed,
trained, starved and squeezed into a miniskirt.''
</P>
<P>
   So, she continues to teeter between childhood and adulthood,
celebrity and privacy. For starters, this supposedly hard-partying
girl lives in the same Upper East Side high rise as her mother and
stepfather, Ken Burrows. ``The shtetl mentality,'' she said wryly.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of her many contradictions. Jong-Fast walks with a
confident stride while simultaneously ducking her head, almost in
apology, which turns the overall effect into something of a
reluctant lope. She approached the podium at her book party
muttering, ``I'm going to trip,'' but instead she took the mike,
dithered just enough to seem like a kid, then saved herself
gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   In her lunchtime conversation, she makes wise statements about
her feelings, then giggles and calls herself silly. She claims her
childhood ambition was to be a junkie. ``My yearbook quote was
``Dream: Coke. Reality: Diet Coke,'' she said. ``I grew up reading
`Less Than Zero,' and I thought taking drugs was so glamorous. It's
something the New York media still perpetuates, with all those
stories about clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Did she find it glamorous? ``It was expensive, and I was really
sick all the time and always in a bad mood,'' she said. ``And I had
nose bleeds 24 hours a day. I always felt I was missing things
before, a better party, some list, some club. Now, I want to miss
everything. I read about it in the Post and feel happy I wasn't
there. I think growing up here you get an inflated idea of how
important you are. When I was at Hazelden, no one knew anything
about me or who Erica Jong was. It wasn't important. I realized the
world is much bigger than New York City. All this stuff doesn't
mean anything.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A strong wind scattered cigarette ashes over the table. ``It's
going to be appealing to eat here,'' Jong-Fast said, suddenly
self-conscious, trying to brush them off. She made rapid small talk
about her dog, eager to be liked. Though her painstakingly made-up
face stayed composed, her chest stained pink with anxiety under her
V-neck dress.
</P>
<P>
   She left NYU when she started writing ``Normal Girl'' at 19,
which went through many revisions. ``My editor, Mollie Doyle, was
tough on me,'' she said. ``I needed someone to tell me to stop it.
I was so profound, writing about the meaning of life. She told me
to write like I speak. I'm happy with it now. It feels like me.''
</P>
<P>
   The book was well-received in London; early reviews here have
been mixed. ``None of the reviews were as bad as the ones I wrote
in my head,'' she said. ``The important thing was that I was able
to find my own voice and be my own person. I got to it by doing
what my parents had done, but I got to it. I'm very clear on the
fact that I'm not my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I did grow up with a lot of pressure,'' she continued.
``In my family, the only way to get attention was to talk with them
about what they wanted to talk about. They were obsessed with
publishers, editors, agents. Everyone in my family was so
accomplished, I was sort of afraid to do anything. I'd lose by
default. I realize now it's OK to do something and not do it
perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that she has not read her mother's books. ``I grew up
idolizing her,'' she said. ``She always seemed so exciting. She
would sweep into the house with duty-free presents wearing
good-looking clothing, speaking Italian, and she was so beautiful.
Last year, my stepfather had a heart aneurysm, and I got to see my
mother as a real human being with doubts and failures. It was
amazing. I realized she was weak and intrinsically flawed. I hadn't
wanted to see that before.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled tentatively, and you could suddenly see the oddity of
being the child of celebrity: All children grow up idolizing their
parents, but with a famous person, everyone else joins in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a choice of normal parents and a two-car garage, no,
I wouldn't have wanted it,'' she said. ``I wouldn't have been able
to suspend disbelief to write a novel, if I hadn't grown up this
way. It made me who I was. Yes, I did a lot of weird stuff. I was
impossible. But I got to live two lives in one lifetime. When I
wrote the book, I interviewed heroin and crack addicts, because I'm
not as brave as my character. I would be at an after hours club,
thinking I'm so cool with my emergency $20 in the bottom of my
handbag.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Jong-Fast said she might go back to school, she is
currently writing a collection of satirical essays about dating in
New York. ``The best part of the whole book thing is my parents
being so blown away by me,'' she said happily.
</P>
<P>
   Jong, reached by phone, said she was impressed by her daughter's
willingness to compete in her world, because she had avoided a
similar situation herself. ``My mother and grandfather were both
painters,'' she said, ``and I ran away from it, because I didn't
want to compete with them and the family racket. I hadn't the guts
to take my mother on directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, apparently, learned different lessons. ``I know my
mom supports me,'' Jong-Fast said, smiling. ``And I know I can
always use her for material.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
