<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMERSOUNDTRACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW PLAYING AT A THEATER NEAR YOU: HOT SUMMER SOUNDTRACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 29 years old, it's got that great wah-wah guitar opening
and those women telling you to shut your mouth, and it's shaping up
as one of the summer's biggest hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theme From Shaft.'' Can you dig it?
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Hayes' 1971 song about private detective/superstud John
Shaft _ the guy who's a sex machine to all the chicks _ defined
hot-buttered soul, won Hayes an Oscar for Best Film Song, was later
sung by Bart Simpson, and linked soul music and film in a way that
had never been done before.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 edition of ``Shaft,'' which features the theme song
again as well as new music by soulsters R. Kelly and Angie Stone,
and rappers Big Gipp and Mystikal, looks to be one of the breakaway
soundtrack hits in a summer when they'll be as common as sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   From the hard-rock-stuffed ``M:I-2'' collection to the odd and
sometimes wonderful companion to the new Jim Carrey film ``Me,
Myself &AMP; Irene'' to an upcoming Elvis Presley package, soundtracks
are going to figure into the summer music landscape as much as, or
more than, ever.
</P>
<P>
   Here are five of the biggies, and whether they're worth your
time and money:
</P>
<P>
   ``Music From and Inspired by Shaft''_ Sometimes stirring,
sometimes downright awful, this collection is a deeply
schizophrenic stab at being all things to all R&AMP;B fans, from those
who are up on the latest hip-hop to veteran and newbie fans of
retro-soul. The remake of the theme song is virtually a remake of
the original, and Chicago's R. Kelly scores early with two more
throwback songs, the playa anthem ``Bad Man'' and the
I-miss-you-babyisms of ``Up and Outta Here.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, though, this is a mixed bag: Newcomers Carl Thomas
and Angie Stone do well with ``Summer Rain'' and ``My Lovin' Will
Give You Something,'' both of which reek of '70s production
touches.
</P>
<P>
   But the CD is also clogged with horrible _ and sometimes
horribly misogynistic _ rap by the likes of Too $hort and the
all-but-talentless Mystikal. Somehow I can't imagine John Shaft
(then or now) listening to this stuff; the way I figure it, he's a
Stevie Wonder/Donnie Hathaway/Al Green guy all the way. The
soundtrack has broad cross-generational appeal and will sell very
well _ look for the theme song and ``Bad Man'' to bust out.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas ``Shaft'' starts out strong, ``Music From and Inspired y
M:I-2'' almost implodes from the outset. Limp Bizkit's hard-rock
recasting of Lalo Schifrin's famous theme melody is horrible _ and
the Foo Fighters/Brian May butchering of Pink Floyd's ``Have a
Cigar'' is not much better.
</P>
<P>
   Metallica's pro-forma ``I Disappear'' has already become an
across-the-board rock hit, and in this mediocre company it actually
impresses as one of the CD's better tracks, as does Rob Zombie's
barreling ``Scum of the Earth.'' And when Rob Zombie is among the
best things on a CD, you know there are problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Farrelly brothers' Jim Carrey vehicle ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene''
has gotten advance press as one of the summer's most interesting
blockbusters-to-be, and the soundtrack follows suit _ to a point.
</P>
<P>
   The film's musical consultants are Walter Becker and Donald
Fagen, which may well explain why eight of the CD's 15 tracks are
young bands covering Steely Dan chestnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Wilco lovingly and faithfully eases through ``Any Major Dude
Will Tell You,'' Brian Setzer adds some rockabilly guitar licks to
an otherwise faithful cover of ``Bodhisattva,'' Marvelous 3 adds
hard-rock punch to ``Reelin' in the Years'' (I was skeptical but
this works, trust me) and Ben Folds Five treats the wistful
``Barrytown'' with respect. Play these, and skip over Smash Mouth's
awful take on ``Do It Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Can any summer be complete without a new Elvis collection? On
July 21, RCA Records re-releases the soundtrack to his 1970s
concert film ``Elvis _ That's the Way It Is.'' The original
12-track LP fared poorly on the charts and with critics; this
version is 66 tracks spread across three CDs, all drawn from his
comeback period when he ruled Las Vegas and played to more than
80,000 people in Houston in 1970. The second CD is a complete Vegas
show in August 1970; only two of the tracks have been previously
released.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, we turn to television and the disco-friendly
soundtrack to ``Sex in the City.'' Tom Jones' ``Sexbomb'' and Bette
Midler's ``Love TKO'' are winners, as is Trisha Yearwood's spare,
pretty ballad ``For Only You,'' but there are also some
yawn-inducing dance tracks interspersed with the good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
