<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6026 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-COURT-ELECTION-$ADV18     06-16 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-ELECTION-$ADV18-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CANDIDATES IN FIERCE BATTLE OVER SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday June 18)  
 &HT;     (Eds: Recasts 12th graf beginning: If elected and adds material
to 30th graf beginning: Thomas' addition .) &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL And MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Their names won't appear on the November ballot.
Their views on hot-button issues won't be grist for 30-second
campaign ads. And their visions for the future won't be the focus
of televised debates.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake: Supreme Court appointees are the focus of a
fierce battle between Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The two don't agree on much these days. But they do agree that
the winner of their struggle may have a rare opportunity to appoint
as many as four new high court justices to replace those who are
expected to step down over the next four years because of age or
ill health.
</P>
<P>
   A first-term president has not been able to shape the Supreme
Court in such a way since Richard Nixon appointed four justices at
the outset of the 1970s and Herbert Hoover named three in the early
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes have rarely been greater, says Douglas Kmiec, a
constitutional law professor at Pepperdine University in Malibu,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that the Supreme Court is a major _ maybe the
most important _ prize in the presidential election,'' says Kmiec.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the court's nine justices were appointed by
Republicans. President Clinton named the other two _ Stephen Breyer
and Ruth Bader Ginsburg, the first appointments by a Democrat since
1967.
</P>
<P>
   Except for William Henry Harrison, Andrew Johnson and Jimmy
Carter _ none of whom filled a high court vacancy _ the nation's 42
presidents have appointed 108 justices.
</P>
<P>
   In its next term, starting Oct. 2, the court is expected to
grapple with issues that could affect the daily lives of all
Americans _ school choice, prayer, affirmative action, sex
discrimination, police powers, abortion rights, the death penalty
and the legislative powers of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Court scholars speculate that one or more of the following could
retire fairly soon: John Paul Stevens, 80, appointed by Gerald
Ford; Chief Justice William Rehnquist, 75, nominated by Richard
Nixon and elevated by Ronald Reagan; Sandra Day O'Connor, 70, named
by Reagan, and Ginsburg, 67, appointed by Clinton. O'Connor and
Ginsburg are both cancer survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The scholars say the new president could be dealing with far
more than the selection of individuals to fill those vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Bush could augment the narrow 5-to-4 conservative
majority that has coalesced around certain issues since Clarence
Thomas' appointment in 1991 and possibly create an iron-clad
conservative majority that could steer the court for decades.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore victory could give Democrats a chance to temper the
conservative bent of the high court. David Garrow, a law professor
at Emory University in Atlanta, says, ``With just one nominee, Gore
could immediately turn the court to the left.'' But he would need
more appointments to completely reverse the court's current
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins, his imprint on the Supreme Court could last for
years.
</P>
<P>
   High bench appointees often serve in their guaranteed-for-life
posts well beyond the term of the president who named them.
Stevens, for instance, has served through the terms of four
presidents since his 1975 appointment.
</P>
<P>
   The next president's influence could also endure longer thanks
to the languid pace of constitutional challenges that work their
way through other courts before reaching the so-called Supremes.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken more than 60 years, for example, for a 5-to-4
conservative majority to emerge on the court to reverse a number of
rulings of the 1930s that expanded Congress' authority to protect
civil rights and to regulate commerce-related activities within
states.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the high court's 1960s-era restrictions on police
powers, advanced by then-Chief Justice Earl Warren, are only now
coming before the current court for another look.
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake, each candidate or his surrogates are
raising the specter of his rival's prospective court appointments
to rally concerned voters to turn out for the November balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Chairman Jim Nicholson warns that a Gore
victory would lead to the appointment of justices who would
``undermine the Constitution of our country and not defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore voices alarms that abortion rights could end under Bush,
who favors steps to outlaw the procedure with exceptions only for
rape, incest and saving the life of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court is at stake,'' Gore warned on March 7. Since
then he charged that many ``individual rights and civil rights are
going to be at risk if the Republican Party controls the majority
on the Supreme Court for the next 30 or 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the political fireworks, Bush and Gore are carefully
giving themselves leeway when they outline the types of justices
they would nominate for confirmation by two thirds of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates reject any ``litmus tests'' demanded by some
interest groups on abortion. Bush refuses to promise to appoint
only anti-abortion jurists despite pressure from conservatives such
as Gary Bauer, Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will appoint judges who strictly interpret the Constitution
and who will not use the bench to legislate,'' is all Bush will
say, echoing campaign language that Reagan used successfully in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   As Texas governor, Bush has appointed 106 state judges including
four of the nine state Supreme Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is equally circumspect, saying, ``There are ways to find
out the kind of judgment somebody has without posing a specific
litmus test.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president says only that he will seek appointees who
``understand and reflect in their decisions the philosophy that our
Constitution is a living and breathing document.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The professed flexibility by both candidates follows tradition
among presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1988 presidential campaign, for example, then-Vice
President George Bush _ father of the Texas governor _ outlined
judicial criteria so inclusive that one of his subsequent
appointees, Thomas, turned out to be a staunch conservative, and
the other, David Souter, a pragmatic moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' addition to the court cemented a conservative majority
of himself, Rehnquist, O'Connor and Reagan appointees Anthony
Kennedy and Antonin Scalia, who have joined forces on certain
issues.
</P>
<P>
   They have been the five in 5-4 decisions that limited racial
preferences in federal contracting; ended the use of race as the
predominant factor in redrawing congressional districts; rejected
Congress' attempt to allow victims of gender-motivated crimes to
sue their attackers in federal courts, and allowed police to stop
and search citizens merely for running away when the officers
approached them.
</P>
<P>
   Candidate Bush in 1988 decried what he called the ``excessive
judicial activism'' of the 1960s and 1970s, but he vowed merely to
``appoint moderate persons of conservative views.''
</P>
<P>
   Such vagueness appears to satisfy most Americans. A January poll
showed that 61 percent of 1,010 adults questioned said a
prospective Supreme Court nominee's views on abortion ought to be
just ``one of many considerations'' in the selection process. Only
8 percent said those views ought to be the ``single most important
consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, no matter what selection criteria a candidate touts
during the campaign, subsequent appointees rarely stick to the
expected script once they're on the court. Three Supreme Court
justices chosen by Republican presidents never publicly expressed
their views on abortion until they were confronted with an appeal
in 1992. In that case, all three _ O'Connor, Kennedy and Souter _
rejected a request to overturn the 1973 landmark Roe v. Wade
decision that legalized the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920
or at e-mail addresses stewart(at)hearstdc.com or
mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
