r d BC-PEPPERS-HNS &LR;      06-16 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPPERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOW TO USE ITALIAN FRYING PEPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As much as I hate to admit it, I didn't know what
``Italian frying peppers'' were when I moved to the Capital Region
a year and a half ago. I saw them listed as an ingredient in a
recipe sent to me by ``retired'' area chef Ken Linden and had to
claim ignorance. I couldn't find them on the Web, or in cookbooks
or even a book titled ``Peppers, Peppers, Peppers,'' by Marlena
Spieler (Firefly, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know an Italian frying pepper?'' e-mailed Linden in
reply. ``Yes, you do. In the produce department, you have probably
seen long, pointed, slim pale green peppers, that are usually more
expensive than the bull-nosed short and squat dark green bell
peppers. Those are known to me and usually signed in the produce
department as `Italian frying peppers.' They are wonderfully sweet,
much thinner skinned than the ordinary green peppers, and do `fry'
much better.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was January and Linden's Italian frying peppers were not
to be found. ``They're a summer item around here,'' Anthony
Battaglia at California Produce told me. ``You'll know them when
you see them.''
</P>
<P>
   And just recently I started to see them, stacked in the produce
department of area supermarkets with the red and green bells, the
jalapenos and such. And I did know them -- as CUBANELLES.
</P>
<P>
   Not to take anything away from Italy, but part of the world
named these sweet pointed peppers after Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing: As with all peppers, look for those with firm, shiny
and smooth-skinned. Avoid wrinkly peppers. Peppers that are too
dark for their particular variety may be slightly immature, writes
Spieler.
</P>
<P>
   Storing: Peppers are one of the few vegetables that can be
frozen without being blanched, according to the ``Joy of Cooking.''
Simply stem and seed and cut to the desired size. Pack in freezer
bags and store.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peppers Stuffed with Summer Vegetables and Couscous
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 2 servings)
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from http://www.canadianliving.com
</P>
<P>
   1 cup drained chickpeas
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup couscous
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   4 Italian frying peppers
</P>
<P>
   2 cups button mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   6 small cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Combine chickpeas, lemon juice, 2 tablespoons oil, 1/4 teaspoon
salt and 1/4 teaspoon pepper in a food processor. Process until
almost smooth. Stir in 1 clove garlic, minced.
</P>
<P>
   Halve zucchini lengthwise and cut one half crosswise into
1/4-inch-thick slices. Set aside. Reserve remaining half for
another use.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, stir 1/2 cup water with 1/8 teaspoon salt; bring
to a boil. Stir in couscous; cover, remove from heat and let stand
5 minutes. Using a fork, stir in basil. Let cool slightly, then
stir in chickpea spread.
</P>
<P>
   Split peppers in half, seed but leave stems intact. In skillet,
heat 1 tablespoon oil over medium-high heat. Add peppers, cut side
down and cook just long enough for edges to brown, Turn over. Add
1/4 cup water; cover and simmer for 1 minute or until peppers are
slightly soft.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a plate; drain water from pan. Pack couscous mixture
into peppers. Cover with foil and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   In the same pan, heat remaining oil. Cook zucchini, mushrooms,
garlic, 1/4 teaspoon salt and a pinch of pepper over medium heat
for 8 to 10 minutes or until tender. Stir in tomatoes and vinegar;
cook, stirring 1 minute more. Mound over stuffed peppers and serve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
