<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEAVE THE `BOYS AND GIRLS' AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Former television director Robert Iscove is at
it again. The maker of ``She's All That'' returns with ``Boys and
Girls,'' and he's brought with him the redoubtable Freddie Prinze
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that if Iscove is going to go down in a whoosh of
flames he's determined to take Prinze with him, and after ``Wing
Commander,'' ``Down To You'' and now this, I think I speak for
thousands of Teen People subscribers when I say ``into the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   As an actor, Prinze has an unfathomable capacity for humiliation
and the remarkable curse of never being believable as a happy
person. Sounds like a reason for a couch trip, not another
young-bucks-in-love romance. But here he is starring in ``Boys and
Girls'' anyway, as though he'd made a pact with Satan, or, even
better, Harvey and Bob Weinstein: ``Please get me that ALMA award
for Outstanding Actor in a Feature Film in a Crossover Role, and
I'll do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Boys and Girls,'' Prinze plays Ryan, a
structural-engineering major, harangued into friendship by a chatty
Latin major named Jennifer (Claire Forlani). Together they walk
around San Francisco and the campus of the University of California
at Berkeley saying things about love and relationships that stars
you respect couldn't make sound believable.
</P>
<P>
   They spend four years, and too much of our time, almost hooking
up. Once they do, we don't get Freddie-Forlani sex. We get a pan up
to the constellation glo-stars on her ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   There are episodes of ``Rugrats'' with stronger sexual suspense
_ and better ideas of what to do with carnality: Jennifer's
roommate Sarah (Amanda Detmer) plants one on her. It was nothing.
She's eventually paired off with ``American Pie's'' Jason Biggs,
who plays Ryan's roommate. He's having his own identity crisis
evinced by the ever-changing frosting in his hair that looks like a
variety pack of Pop Tarts died on his quills.
</P>
<P>
   As the film's overseer, Iscove desperately beats a horse so dead
he shuttles the film's two platonic lovers off to a John Hughes
double feature. It's the ``I could have had a V-8 instead'' moment
of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
