<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREA'S KIM SAYS DANGER OF WAR IS GONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., will be updated later if needed) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The propaganda war in the DMZ fell silent
on Friday for the first time at least 50 years and South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung declared that ``the danger of war on the
Korean peninsula has disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   In a striking move just a day after talks between North and
South Korea ended in Pyongyang, the South ordered an end to
anti-communist broadcasts that its military has transmitted for
decades from giant loudspeakers along the heavily fortified border
with North Korea. The move came in response to North Korea's
decision on Tuesday to switch off its loud speakers that had
blasted anti-South insults over the border through the years.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to end the broadcasts was just one of several
symbolic steps the two nations made on Friday intended to signal
that their half-century of hostilities were indeed coming to an end
and to dispel skeptics who question whether the summit meeting will
lead to peace on the divided Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, North Korea allowed a South Korean fishing boat
that had strayed across its heavily patrolled sea border to sail
back to its home port without incident on Friday. A year ago this
week, North and South Korean naval vessels exchanged gun fire over
fishing rights in the same area. One North Korean warship sank and
about 30 communist sailors were believed to have died.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's defense ministry also announced that it would
reconsider how to handle a $40-million program to commemorate the
50th anniversary of the outbreak of the Korean War on June 25,
1950. The agency had planned numerous parades, ceremonies, battle
re-enactments, and other events that were to be attended by
thousands of veterans and dignitaries, many from the United States.
``We are looking for ways to commemorate the anniversary in
compliance with the spirit of the agreement reached at the
summit,'' a ministry spokesman, Yoon Il-young, said.
</P>
<P>
   President Kim Dae-jung also told his cabinet on Friday that Kim
Jong Il had agreed to his suggestion to invite Pope John Paul II to
visit North Korea. The South Korean president, who is Catholic and
visited the pope in March, said he had instructed the foreign
ministry to convey the wishes of his North Korean counterpart to
the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea is widely considered to be the world's most
totalitarian society, and organized religion there has long been
suppressed in favor of leader-worship, first for the country's late
founder, Kim Il Sung, and now for his son, Kim Jong Il. Of a
population of 22 million, 4,000 are believed to be Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Dae-jung instructed his cabinet to implement a wide variety
of reconciliation measures that grew out of the three-day talks,
which concluded in an agreement calling for the two Koreas to
pursue peace, economic and other exchanges. The South Korean
president said that he hoped the efforts would coax Stalinist North
Korea out of its self-imposed isolation and help rebuild its
faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials said they hoped that the two heads of
state could meet again in Seoul on or around the Aug. 15 holiday
that celebrates the anniversary of Koreas liberation from nearly 40
years of Japanese colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean President Kim also said that he held a 20-minute
telephone conversation with President Clinton on Friday in which he
informed the American leader that he raised North Korea's nuclear
and missile programs in talks with Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that the missile and nuclear problems do not help
regional and world peace as well as inter-Korean cooperation,''
aides to the Korean president quoted him as having told Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of 37,000 American troops in South Korea was also
discussed, Kim Dae-jung told Clinton. The South Korean leader's
position is that the U.S. military presence is needed for regional
security even after the unification of the Korean peninsula. The
aides said that Clinton thanked Kim for raising the North's nuclear
and missile issues, saying that ``those issues are important for
all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
