<HEADER>
A6031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BAPTISTS-COLUMN-0617-     06-16 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-COLUMN-0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Baptist edict is sexism, not Scripture
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Southern Baptist Convention uses the
Bible to preserve power for men only.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus must weep at such apostasy. Lottie Moon, the equivalent of
a Baptist saint, may be spinning in her grave.
</P>
<P>
   The convention of the largest Protestant denomination in the
world met in Orlando this week for its two-day annual meeting. More
than 11,000 messengers, as delegates are called, adopted a revised
statement of belief that declared the office of pastor was
restricted to men.
</P>
<P>
   The statement insists that is what the Bible teaches, but the
decision seems to be based not so much on Scriptural warrant as on
a lust to keep the levers of power in the hands of men.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus deliberately became powerless to demonstrate the wonder of
God. That foolishness is the power of the Gospel, according to St.
Paul. He declared that weakness was strength for Christians.
Worldly power was an aphrodisiac of the Evil One.
</P>
<P>
   Still, men vigorously reserve to themselves all authority in
Southern Baptist life. They make the decisions. Women can do
everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Women have gifts for service to the church, according to the
Baptist Faith and Message statement. But they cannot take a place
in the principal seat of authority in church life.
</P>
<P>
   That sexist conviction does not prevent the church's leadership
from using women to support and pay for their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   They make no apology for collecting from the faithful more than
$100 million a year for missionary work in the name of Lottie Moon.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Moon became a foreign missionary for the Southern
Baptist Convention in 1873. She served in China for 40 years. She
founded a school, preached the Gospel, introduced Jesus to
countless Chinese and taught the Bible with such grace and
consistency that she became known as ``the Heavenly Book Visitor.''
</P>
<P>
   During a time of famine, she pleaded with the male hierarchy of
the church in the States to send relief. They sent excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Moon, not unlike Jesus, embraced the lot of her starving flock
and stopped eating. She died shortly thereafter to become a Baptist
icon for raising money.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions of the Convention are not binding on the 40,000 or
more Southern Baptist churches, but they set the tone for the
denomination.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson seems clear. Southern Baptist leaders are drawn
inexorably to the preservation and exercise of power for themselves
_ in defiance of the Gospel they claim to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
