<HEADER>
A6035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FAA-SAFETY17-COX     06-16 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-SAFETY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAINTENANCE DECISION ON ALASKA AIRLINES DUE NEXT WEEK
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration will announce
next week whether it will suspend Alaska Airlines' authority to do
heavy maintenance following the January crash of one of its planes,
administrator Jane Garvey said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If Alaska Airlines were forced to contract out heavy
maintenance, it could result in service cutbacks and perhaps a
smaller airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety is the heart and soul of the FAA's mission,'' Garvey
said. ``Our first focus is to discover the cause of the Alaska
Airlines crash, and then make sure that this does not happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines Flight 261 crashed into the ocean Jan. 31 about
20 miles northwest of Los Angeles International Airport after
reporting trouble with its stabilizer trim. The reason for the
crash is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey said part of the investigation included an internal audit
of Alaska Airlines' flight and maintenance systems by the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the facts are not yet in from the crash so there is not a
need to jump to any conclusions,'' Garvey said, ``But we have
serious questions to ask ourselves, and this internal audit may be
a basis for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Garvey said she received a full report on June 9 from Alaska
Airlines on why the FAA should not suspend its ability to do heavy
maintenance on their aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey added that the FAA should look at airlines' maintenance
systems for any ways to make improvements. She also said that the
audit of Alaska airlines could lead to audits of other airlines for
precautionary measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not opposed to the audit of airlines because I think it
is good to monitor ourselves as a precaution,'' Garvey said. ``With
these audits we can make improvements to our training, oversight
and maintenance systems, and we can make changes before a tragedy
like Alaska Airlines happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is robo(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
