<HEADER>
A6038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-NAGAKO-NYT &LR;      06-16 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NAGAKO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAGAKO, 97, JAPAN'S DOWAGER EMPRESS AND WIDOW OF HIROHITO 
</HEADLINE>
   By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dowager Empress Nagako of Japan, the 97-year-old widow of
Emperor Hirohito, died Friday after a life that saw the
transformation of her homeland several times over.
</P>
<P>
   ``She passed away because of old age despite strenuous
nursing,'' said Sadame Kamakura, the grand steward of the imperial
household, at a news conference in Tokyo. ``We feel unbearable
grief.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagako spent much of her life insulated deep inside a Japan that
no longer exists. Indeed, she was one of the last Japanese who
could remember life inside the aristocracy early in the 20th
century or in the palace during the time when people spoke an
archaic, imperial form of Japanese that has largely disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Born on March 6, 1903, the eldest daughter of a prince, Nagako
was chosen at the age of 14 to be the consort of Hirohito, who was
then the crown prince. They were formally married in 1924 _ their
wedding delayed by the catastrophic Tokyo earthquake of 1923 _ and
just two years later the Emperor Taisho died and Hirohito succeeded
him.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Nagako became wife not just of the emperor but of a
``living god,'' a deity in the Shinto state religion that then
prevailed. It was not initially a love marriage at all, and they
seem to have lived their heavily scripted lives for duty and
responsibility more than for pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Nagako's main duty, as most Japanese then saw it, was producing
a son. Under Japanese law, then and now, only a son can inherit the
throne, and there was growing disquiet as she produced four
daughters in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials are said to have arranged elaborate temptations
for Hirohito, in the form of gorgeous young women who might produce
an heir. By the time Nagako became pregnant for the fifth time, in
1933, it was widely expected that Hirohito would formally take
another consort if Nagako's child was again a girl. But then
booming cannon proclaimed to an overjoyed nation that the child was
a boy, today's Emperor Akihito.
</P>
<P>
   For a deity, Emperor Hirohito had relatively little power. Even
day-to-day decisions were made by bossy court officials, and when
Akihito was 3 years old he was taken away from his parents and
raised by attendants who treated him with more veneration than
warmth. He seems to have had a painfully lonely childhood, but
Nagako never complained publicly about the separation.
</P>
<P>
   The emperor was used by Japan's military rulers as a rallying
symbol during World War II, and he periodically appeared in a
military uniform on a white horse, making comments like, ``Your
life is as light as a feather, but your loyalty is as heavy as a
mountain.'' There has been a debate about the degree to which he
bore responsibility for the war fought in his name, and even less
is known about Nagako's views of the war or of the militarism of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Nagako once described the war years as ``the hardest time of my
life,'' and there was uncertainty afterward whether the Americans
would execute Hirohito or at least force him to abdicate. But
instead, the United States decided to pin the blame for the war on
Japan's other leaders, like Prime Minister Hideki Tojo, and
Hirohito was allowed to remain emperor as long as he repudiated his
divinity.
</P>
<P>
   Japan was changing, and Nagako tried to change as well. When the
Palace arranged for an American woman to teach Akihito English,
Nagako asked for lessons as well.
</P>
<P>
   But she often came across as a remnant of a different era.
Akihito fell in love with a brilliant and beautiful young college
woman, the present Empress Michiko, but traditionalists were
horrified because Michiko had entered a Catholic college (although
she was not Christian) and because it would be the first time a
crown prince had ever married a commoner. It is not clear whether
Nagako was among those who disapproved of the marriage, but it is
known that her relations with Michiko were strained.
</P>
<P>
   Michiko was criticized for carrying her babies in public, for
breastfeeding them and for trying to raise and shape her children
herself. It seems that Nagako took the traditional side in these
quarrels; a senior chamberlain recalls, in a published memoir,
Michiko plaintively asking why her mother-in-law disliked her.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Michiko regarded her chief lady-in-waiting as a spy
for Nagako, and together Akihito and Michiko tried to dismiss the
servant. The Imperial Household Agency did not allow this.
</P>
<P>
   These intrigues took an enormous toll on Michiko, who became
gaunt and possibly suffered nervous breakdowns in 1963 and again in
1993. Empress Michiko is still a beautiful and intelligent woman,
but she is said to be only a shadow of the confident young college
student she once was.
</P>
<P>
   Nagako was a talented artist, and three collections of her
paintings have been published. She was a good singer as well as
proficient in the piano, violin and Japanese harp, or koto.
</P>
<P>
   Hirohito died in 1989, but even then Nagako was regarded as too
feeble to attend his funeral. And since then she has remained out
of the public eye, living quietly in a modest home in the Imperial
Palace grounds in Tokyo. She has not been shown in public since a
1993 video that showed her in a wheelchair beside a window.
</P>
<P>
   The Imperial Household Agency, never known for its candor, said
Thursday that Nagako was suffering breathing problems but that her
illness was ``not serious.'' The next day, with Akihito and Michiko
at her side, she died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
