<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6039 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-DADS-FASHION-$ADV18-N     06-16 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DADS-FASHION-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAD WHO DOESN'T WANT TO LOOK HIS AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 18) 
 By DAVID EDDIE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it my imagination, or do the kids in the hip-hop shops and
skateboard stores look at me funny when I _ pushing 40 and
sometimes a stroller _ roll in?
</P>
<P>
   What does that geezer want?
</P>
<P>
   That's the look on the face of the youthful clerk as he sidles
up to where I'm poking through racks of rave wear and baggy rap
slacks, and says, ``Um, you realize those pants are quite full cut,
don't you, sir?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, yes,'' I respond testily. ``All the Alien Workshop stuff
is like that, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   I like to think I win them over by my knowledgeability and
expertise. Then I'll try on the pants, twisting and turning in
front of the three-way mirror as my 3-year-old, Nicholas, stares
from the stroller, sucking on his pacifier, with an expression on
his face that says, ``Dad, don't you realize it's just not about
you anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm mutton dressed as lamb, I admit it. A man of a certain age
consciously and determinedly dressing like a much younger person. I
wear huge, baggy jeans. My question for a prospective pair of pants
is always, ``Would these look good running from the police in a DMX
video?'' I try never to leave the house with fewer than three
products in my (thinning, graying) hair, usually including Knotty
Boy Dread Wax, a mixture of beeswax and hemp oil designed to bestow
short-term dreads. (``If you like it nappy, Knotty Boy will make
you happy.'')
</P>
<P>
   My footwear ranges from the impractical to the improbable, and
when I die I want them not only to say, ``He died with his boots
on,'' but also, ``Wonder where he got them?''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to be a rebel at 19, or 29. But at 39, it's a
challenge. Epictetus tells us, ``First decide who you are and adorn
yourself accordingly.'' Perhaps I'm a bit confused on that score.
I'm no longer the Raskolnikovian punk I once imagined myself,
living above a rattan furniture store in a sketchy part of town,
doomed to a lifetime of penury and outsider status. Born to rent.
</P>
<P>
   I styled myself an eternal, tragic bachelor _ until the right
woman came along and choppered me out of a life of mice-filled
sinks and rendered me a homeowner and a father. Now I stay at home
with my two kids. I look after them in the afternoons. I said
bonjour to the bourgeoisie some time ago, and I've been in that
milieu ever since. I recently surprised every acquaintance, and
myself, by actually getting involved in my community, going to
meetings, thumping my fist on the table on behalf of two beautiful
old Japanese maple trees in the park across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as much as I have embraced the joys of do-gooding dadhood,
there is a part of me that is doggedly in denial. Perhaps my life,
now, is more about errands than I'd like to admit. I wake up
thinking about what to make for dinner. I have found myself
screaming at my kids, ``Please, please, I beg you to let me finish
mopping the floor.'' The highlight of some days is the purchase of
broccoli (I can feel my pulse race just thinking about it).
</P>
<P>
   But does that mean I have to look like a guy who gets excited
about grocery shopping and housecleaning? Just because I'm a dad,
does that mean I have to wear pleated khaki shorts and a fanny
pack? I like to think something of the old flame, the old steel, is
there still. In my breast beats the heart of a punk and underground
man, although what kind I'm not so sure anymore.
</P>
<P>
   I have noticed that many punks in my neighborhood are associated
with some sort of transportation: we have car punks, bike punks.
I've even seen a couple of scooter punks tooling around. So that
makes me a stroller punk, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 5, with a goatee, army pants, skateboard shoes and
spiked, sometimes dyed hair, I'm nothing like the other parents at
the PTA meetings, in their urban-camper gear, baseball caps and
sensible shoes. Smoking, reading a hardback, wearing shades, I
stand out like a sick frog at the park among the mommies, nannies
and grannies, some of whom knit. When I was a teen-ager, adults
were suspicious of me. Now everyone is.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I went toe-to-toe with a girl, 17, in a vegetable
store. I'd left the stroller (in full view) just outside the door
when I went in to grab a couple of items.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you read the papers?'' she screamed at me. ``I could
have snatched your kid.''
</P>
<P>
   She then offered a number of suggestions on how I could improve
my parenting techniques. Part of me was awash in respect for her
for taking on such a huge, unpredictable-looking character, a total
stranger, and pushing the hottest of hot buttons, the ``Bad Dad''
button. I had a suggestion for her, that she mind her business,
which she actually wound up taking.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm not the only unconventional dad. My friend Daniel
Richler, for example, who is 43 and a well-respected writer,
television producer and television host, has not relinquished his
Goth style in the name of fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to express his inner vampire in his clothes _ black
T-shirts and leather jackets (not too brunchy) _ and in his house.
Up the sleepy striver's row from mine, he and his wife and daughter
live in an Addams Family mansion with dark purple walls, heavy
velvet curtains blocking out the sunlight, first editions,
devil-mouth ashtrays and old absinthe ads.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how all this will affect our kids. I think it will
be good for them to see their parents as free-thinking and
independent. In his otherwise excellent book, ``I'll Be the Parent,
You Be the Kid'' (Random House of Canada, 1998), Paul Kropp writes
that children want parents to be ``dull as dishwater.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact they need us dull as dishwater,'' he writes. ``They
want us to drive them in the car, tell the appropriate corny jokes,
nag them about eating beans and otherwise behave like Ward and June
Cleaver. When parents become too interesting, we can overwhelm our
kids and really interfere with their growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   I must respectfully disagree. I had the sort of father Kropp
recommends, of the tweedy, professorial subvariety. We went on
interminable family rides in the car, sometimes straying onto the
gravel as he pointed out various sights of local interest. Other
Saturdays, we organized the basement together, and I fail to see
how any of this was good for me, unless, like Dunbar in
``Catch-22,'' you believe boredom is intrinsically good because it
makes life seem longer.
</P>
<P>
   And I don't see how it could hurt my kids to see me in army
surplus pants. I have to believe it will be good for them to see
that I'm a little unusual. And maybe even inspire them to stand out
from the crowd when they start shopping for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows what kind of Internet sunglasses kids will be
wearing then, or if I'll have the stamina to try to keep up.
Probably not. The truth is, teen-age fashions already change so
fast, it's nerve-racking to try to stay current without looking
ludicrous to our peers or, even worse, be objects of teen-age scorn
and pity. ``We can never hope to survive the basilisk stare of the
teen-ager,'' my friend Daniel says, referring to the mythological
beast that could kill with a single look.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, shopping for clothes is already becoming less fun. Kids
can turn a simple shirt purchase into a hail of negotiations,
tears, frayed nerves. But I guess I can't relinquish my youthful
dandyism yet. ``Elegance and fitness are our last line of defense
against the aging process,'' says my friend Andrew Livingston, who
recently trumped my entire wardrobe when his father-in-law died and
left him a beautiful collection of James Bond-style suits and
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not ready for the next sartorial phase _ the cardigans and
sweater vests, suits and little glasses. I think I'm still of the
age that when I wear these things, it's taken ironically. When the
time comes, I will make the switch suddenly and boldly. As St.
Augustine said, ``Lord, make me good, but not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6040 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-OPEN-DALY-HNS &LR;      06-16 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-DALY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JOHN DALY NOTCHES ANOTHER U.S. OPEN SNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK FAINARU-WADA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Even you, duffer that you are, might not
have done this before:
</P>
<P>
   Tee shot out of bounds. Tee shot into the water. Tee shot into
the water. Tee shot onto the fairway (at last). Lay up with an
iron, 115 yards short of the green. Pitch into the water. Drop in a
bunker. Flip the club over and hit left-handed, knocking the ball a
few feet. Blast out of the sand. Two-putt.
</P>
<P>
   That's 14, and yes, that was John Daly. Who else? Just a tidy
little 9-over par (what is that, a noctuple bogey?) on the 18th
hole in the first round of the U.S. Open, which also happened to be
the last round for the tumultuous Daly.
</P>
<P>
   Down goes Daly _ again _ yet another sudden implosion in a
career of them.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to last year's Open, when Daly made it through all
four days but let loose with a rip-roaring tirade after shooting a
final-round 83 that included an 11 on the eighth hole at Pinehurst,
Daly went quietly but quickly this time.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring the 14 on 18, he signed his scorecard and then
announced he was withdrawing from the tournament. He had nothing
else to say, marching off to the players' locker room, where he
spent about two minutes before bolting for parts unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Golf Association, which last year absorbed the
brunt of Daly's verbal wrath, released this muted statement: ``It
is always unfortunate when a contestant withdraws prior to
completion of his regulation rounds. We are very sorry that John's
struggles at the end of his round caused him to withdraw.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly showed no signs he was in the midst of a two-touchdown
scoring performance at 18, which only added to the torment of the
whole incident Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no temper or anything like that,'' rules official Ed
Gowan said of Daly's deportment during his demise. ``He was totally
in control. He tried all the way through. . . . He played very
well. He had some bad breaks, or he could have easily been under
par.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly was 3-over par as he came to the 18th, all seemingly
forgiven and forgotten from his 1999 U.S. Open melodrama. A year
ago, in a rant about pin placement among other things, Daly vowed
not to come to Pebble and ``watch the USGA ruin that golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   This was after his septuple bogey at the eighth hole, where he
watched not one but two putts roll up a hill and come back his way.
As the second putt made its agonizing trek back toward Daly, he
took a swat at it to earn a two-stroke penalty.
</P>
<P>
   He later implied it was a premeditated act of protest against
the USGA, of which he said, ``They love to embarrass people.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, though, Daly wrote a letter of apology to USGA
executive director David Fay. And so there he was Thursday
afternoon _ as the fog began to lay thick over Pebble Beach _ on
the verge of logging a decent opening round. Instead, his first tee
shot sailed wide right and hit a cart path, which launched the ball
over a fence and into someone's backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tee shot was very difficult, it was very misty, nobody
could see the fairway really,'' said Retief Goosen, who, along with
Rocco Mediate, was in a group with Daly. ``He got unlucky and hit
the cart path.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, though, Daly didn't know the ball had bounced out of
bounds, and so he made the walk toward where his initial drive was
headed. But he discovered the bad news and had to march all the way
back to the tee box, where he teed the ball back up and launched
his next drive into the water. And then a repeat left him lying
six, still sitting on the tee of the par-5, 543-yard hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't make anything out of it,'' Gowan said of Daly's
decision to quit. ``He's obviously very discouraged and what he's
done doesn't bother me in the least. I'm sure a lot of the fans
would like to see him come back (Friday) and do better, but with
all he's been through, I understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Daly has been through a lot and more, from alcohol
rehab stints to a messy divorce, plus various other course blowups.
The Open, in particular, has not been kind to him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, at Congressional, Daly simply walked off the course
halfway through the second round. Then there was '99 and now this.
But this might have been Daly's last Open episode, for better or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's British Open victory in 1995 earned him a five-year
exemption into the U.S. Open _ meaning this was the final year of
his free ride. So to get into next year's field at Southern Hills
in Tulsa, Daly would either have to qualify through his play, or
get a special exemption from his good pals at the USGA.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Fornoff of The Examiner staff contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1655EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
