<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DEATH-PENALTY0617-COX     06-16 1665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shift in public attitude toward death penaltyBy Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former President Bush had Willie Horton.
Soon-to-be-former President Clinton had Ricky Ray Rector.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Bush used the face of a convicted murderer to pummel
his rival, Michael Dukakis, whose anti-death penalty stance cost
him sorely with voters. Four years later, Clinton became the first
presidential candidate to preside over an execution when he flew to
Arkansas to make sure Rector, who was so mentally impaired that he
saved his last dessert ``for later,'' was put to death.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians from both major parties have long relied on
emotional images to score points with voters. Suddenly, all that's
changed. With murder rates down as much as 50 percent in big
cities, the death penalty debate has shifted from a morality play
to a scientific and legal lecture. Images of unrepentant killers
have been replaced with charts illustrating the nuances of DNA
testing, tales of incompetent lawyers and the names of wrongly
convicted men set free.
</P>
<P>
   Public support for the ultimate punishment has been softening
for more than a decade and while Americans are not ready to throw
out the death penalty, they are worried. New evidence of wrongful
convictions is intensifying that worry and leading to what the
folks at the Gallup Organization consider a substantial shift in
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do believe, looking at the data, that we have undergone a
shift from our peak in 1994,'' said Frank Newport, editor-in-chief
of the Gallup Poll. ``It's still high, 66 percent who approve of
the death penalty for murder, but that's down 14 points from 1980.
We study trends for a living and we do think this represents a
significant downturn.''
</P>
<P>
   Newport believes that reports of DNA testing exonerating death
row inmates is contributing to the downturn. He offers Gov. George
W. Bush's first-ever decision to grant a 30-day reprieve as
evidence that politicians are aware of shifting public opinion.
Bush granted the reprieve, pending further DNA analysis, to Ricky
McGinn, who was convicted of raping and murdering his 12-year-old
stepdaughter. He also pardoned A.B. Butler _ who was serving two,
concurrent 99 year sentences for a kidnapping and rape _ after DNA
testing proved Butler did not commit the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Still, executions have not slowed. Thursday, Paul Nuncio became
the third Texas inmate executed this week and the 22nd this year.
Next week, Gary Graham is scheduled to die by lethal injection in a
case that has drawn national attention because Graham's conviction
rests on the testimony of a sole eyewitness.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, a death penalty supporter, has been
largely silent during the recent debate. He has said
post-conviction DNA testing should be available in some cases, but
a campaign spokesman said Gore is also concerned that a Senate bill
that would make the testing available to all death row inmates
would place limits on the government's ability to seek the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said politicians can win even
when they disagree with the larger public on an issue as potent as
the death penalty. Cuomo never abandoned his opposition to capital
punishment. Gov. George Pataki beat him in 1994 and promptly signed
the death penalty into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got three terms so nobody could tell me that you couldn't
win,'' Cuomo said. ``The last time I got clobbered because they got
tired of me and so they wouldn't forgive me the death
penalty...Once you make the whole case to people, you can get them
off the death penalty. It's just that politicians don't want to
make the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent Gallup polls show that support for the death penalty
falls to around 52 percent when the possibility of life without
parole is also offered up. And 91 percent believe that an innocent
person has been sentenced to death in the last 20 years. The
question now is not whether Americans are ready to abolish the
death penalty, but how flawed a system they are willing to
tolerate, said Newport and death penalty researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations at Northwestern University's Medill School of
Journalism and The Chicago Tribune helped trigger the national
debate. The state has released 13 wrongly-convicted death-row
inmates and Republican Gov. George Ryan, who supports the death
penalty, has suspended executions in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   A Columbia University study released Monday found that
two-thirds of the death sentenche debate.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters at the Chicago Tribune raised serious questions about
the quality of legal representation and the use of jailhouse
informants in 106 of the 134 people executed while Bush has been in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, former Texas Court of Appeals Judge Charles Baird told
the Senate Judiciary Committee that the state is in,'' a
crisis....regarding representation in capital crimes.'' Wednesday,
Congressman Ciro D. Rodriguez (D-San Antonio), a death penalty
supporter, wrote to Gov. George W. Bush asking him to suspend
executions and to establish a commission to study DNA technology,
sentencing bias in capital cases and legal representation for
capital defendants.
</P>
<P>
   All the questioning isn't changing Bush's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is satisfied that everyone who has been executed
in Texas is guilty and had full access to the courts and to court
appeals,'' said campaign spokesman Ray Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's office did not respondek, Gary Graham is scheduled to die
by lethal injection in a case that has drawn national attention
because Graham's conviction rests on the testimony of a sole
eyewitness.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, a death penalty supporter, has been
largely silent during the recent debate. He has said
post-conviction DNA testing should be available in some cases, but
a campaign spokesman said Gore is also concerned that a Senate bill
that would make the testing available to all death row inmates
would place limits on the government's ability to seek the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said politicians can win even
when they disagree with the larger public on an issue as potent as
the death penalty. Cuomo never abandoned his opposition to capital
punishment. Gov. George Pataki beat him in 1994 and promptly signed
the death penalty into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got three terms so nobody could tell me that you couldn't
win,'' Cuomo said. ``The last time I got clobbered because they got
tired of me and so they wouldn't forgive me the death
penalty...Once you make the whole case to people, you can get them
off the death penalty. It's just that politicians don't want to
make the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent Gallup polls show that support for the death penalty
falls to around 52 percent when the possibility of life without
parole is also offered up. And 91 percent believe that an innocent
person has been sentenced to death in the last 20 years. The
question now is not whether Americans are ready to abolish the
death penalty, but how flawed a system they are willing to
tolerate, said Newport and death penalty researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations at Northwestern University's Medill School of
Journalism and The Chicago Tribune helped trigger the national
debate. The state has released 13 wrongly-convicted death-row
inmates and Republican Gov. George Ryan, who supports the death
penalty, has suspended executions in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   A Columbia University study released Monday found that
two-thirds of the death sentences meted out in the past 23 years
have been overturned on appeal. Fifteen of the 38 states that have
the death penalty are now assessing its effectiveness. The New
Hampshire legislature voted to repeal its death penalty, but
Democratic Gov. Jeanne Shaheen vetoed. The state has not executed
anyone since 1939.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had the same problems Illinois has with its death
penalty statute, I would have taken the same step,'' Shaheen said
in response to questions e-mailed to her office.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, which executes more people than any other state, has
become ground zero for the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters at the Chicago Tribune raised serious questions about
the quality of legal representation and the use of jailhouse
informants in 106 of the 134 people executed while Bush has been in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, former Texas Court of Appeals Judge Charles Baird told
the Senate Judiciary Committee that the state is in,'' a
crisis....regarding representation in capital crimes.'' Wednesday,
Congressman Ciro D. Rodriguez (D-San Antonio), a death penalty
supporter, wrote to Gov. George W. Bush asking him to suspend
executions and to establish a commission to study DNA technology,
sentencing bias in capital cases and legal representation for
capital defendants.
</P>
<P>
   All the questioning isn't changing Bush's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is satisfied that everyone who has been executed
in Texas is guilty and had full access to the courts and to court
appeals,'' said campaign spokesman Ray Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's office did not respond to e-mailed questions for the
governor regarding the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Whit Ayers, a Republican pollster from Atlanta, said Bush loses
nothing sticking to his position. He noted that a recent Newsweek
poll had support for the death penalty at 73 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do people want assurances that those who are executed are
actually guilty? Of course,'' Ayers said. ``But do they want people
who commit heinous to crimes to suffer the death penalty for those
crimes? You better believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why debate over perfecting the system could have ironic
consequences for death penalty foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of this new opposition is based on DNA evidence and
wanting to make sure we get it right,'' said Tim Floyd, a Texas
Tech University law professor. ``With improved science, it may be
more possible to choose the right people...and that would lead to
more support of the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
