<SLUG> BC-CHINA-UNICOM-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE PHONE COMPANY'S OFFERING SAID TO BODE WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Capitalizing on the recent popularity of
telecommunications stocks and the enduring appeal of the world's
most populous country, China Unicom Ltd. raised $4.92 billion on
Friday in the largest initial public offering in Asia outside
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The company, China's second-largest telephone carrier, priced
its shares at 15.58 Hong Kong dollars each, or about $2 U.S. That
is near the top of the range set by the company earlier this week.
Unicom had already raised the range by 10 percent because of the
buoyant demand.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Unicom said the institutional part of the
offer, which accounts for most of the 2.46 billion shares, was
subscribed three times over. Unicom priced its American depository
shares at $19.99 a share. The shares will begin trading in New York
on Wednesday and in Hong Kong the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unicom is going to be very successful,'' said Seton Lor, a
fund manager at Manulife Financial, an investment firm here.
``Telecom stocks are very much in vogue these days. The stock is
also priced at a lower multiple than China Telecom, because it has
businesses other than cellular.''
</P>
<P>
   China Telecom, the nation's largest telephone carrier, held the
record for the largest previous offering, raising $4.2 billion in
late 1997. Unicom, which was started by the Chinese government in
1994 to create competition for Telecom, has languished in the
shadow of its powerful rival.
</P>
<P>
   It has less than one-third the mobile-phone subscribers: 4.15
million vs. 15.6 million. It has had a revolving door of senior
managers. It has zigzagged confusingly on cellular technology. It
has been forced to unravel partnerships with foreign investors. And
it derives 63 percent of its revenue from paging _ a service that
many experts regard as the horse-and-buggy of the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all that, China Unicom now has its own page in the
annals of China's corporate reform. Even people who faulted the
company agree that it has bright prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unicom has an enormous opportunity in front of it,'' said Hani
Abuali, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette in Hong Kong.
``China is going to be the world's largest cellular market.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of cellular subscribers in China jumped from 13.7
million in 1997 to 43.2 million at the end of last year. That still
represents a penetration rate of only 3.4 percent. China Unicom's
executives note that the company's franchises, which extend up and
down the country's economically prosperous coast, cover 67 percent
of the total cellular subscribers in China.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics like that have made China Telecom a shooting star on
the Hong Kong Stock Exchange. Since May 24, its shares have risen
over 30 percent. That performance goaded Unicom's executives to
raise the price range of their offering. Analysts say the timing
was impeccable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``From my discussions with fund managers, people are looking for
alternative ways to invest in China,'' Abuali said. ``This is a
good alternative investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Unicom's success is also a good omen for other large Chinese
state-owned companies, which the government hopes to begin
privatizing in the coming months. These include China National
Offshore Oil Corp. and Sinopec, an oil and petrochemical giant.
</P>
<P>
   China Unicom's offering is managed by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
and China International Capital Corp., a Beijing-based investment
bank partly owned by Morgan Stanley.
</P>
</TEXT>
