A6050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-COMEDY-CENTRAL-NYT     06-16 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COMEDY-CENTRAL-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTRAL SOURCE FOR VARIED COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Comedy Central, the new season starts this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other cable networks, Comedy Central is taking
advantage of the sleepyheads at the broadcast networks, who
basically switch to auto pilot each summer with night after night
of reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sunday, Comedy Central launches its season premiere
week, with fresh episodes of seven returning series and the debuts
of three new shows.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy on the network is a relative thing. Comedy Centrals
offerings range from the brilliant wit of ``League of Gentlemen''
to the crass, sexist humor of the returning ``The Man Show,'' the
network's least appealing series.
</P>
<P>
   The season premieres are scheduled at 10 p.m. and 10:30 p.m.
Sunday through Thursday, beginning this weekend with ``The Man
Show,'' followed by the offbeat and slightly engaging ``Strip
Mall,'' set in a suburban Los Angeles strip mall.
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Julie Brown stars as a former child star, Tammi Tyler,
who wants to regain the fame she lost years ago when she killed her
popular co-star. She's now working as a barmaid with the
delightfully daffy Victoria Jackson as her co-worker. The show
focuses on businesses in the mall, including a Chinese restaurant
run by a bizarre lesbian couple who spend more time taunting and
insulting each other than serving food and a video store that is a
front for porno films. Maxwell Caulfield plays one shop owner who
becomes a porn star.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesdays offer the return of ``Strangers With Candy,'' with Amy
Sedaris as a grown woman returning to high school, followed by the
network's best new show, ``The League of Gentlemen.'' This BBC
series recalls Monty Python's Flying Circus, with a British sketch
comedy troupe bringing to life the bizarre residents of the small
village of Royston Vasey. The troupe of four men _ three
performer-writers and one writer _ and a small group of guest
actors, play all the men and women in town, including murderous
shop owners who hate strangers and a transsexual taxi driver. It's
bizarre and often hilarious. Cast members are gifted at
transforming themselves so that you don't recognize them in some of
their characters.
</P>
<P>
   The network provided only a clip of the new game show ``Don't
Forget Your Toothbrush,'' which features former ``Hangin With Mr.
Cooper'' star Mark Curry as host. Contestants are put through
embarrassing tests, like ``What's Under My Kilt.'' A woman is
blindfolded and asked to reach under the kilts of four men and
guess what's hanging there. Items include a hammer and a lobster.
There's a last-minute twist with her boyfriend that might make you
groan more than laugh. The series will be paired with episodes of
the British version of ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   The outrageous, funny and offensive ``South Park'' returns at 10
p.m. Wednesdays, followed by ``Comedy Central Presents,'' a
half-hour stand-up comedy show.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is Ben Stein night, with new episodes of the quirky
game show ``Win Ben Stein's Money'' followed by the second season
of ``Turn Ben Stein On,'' featuring interviews with such guest
stars as Drew Carey, Charlie Sheen, Craig Kilborn and Carmen
Electra.
</P>
<P>
   Of the new shows, only ``League of Gentlemen'' will have me
tuning in for more. The others might be worth a look once in a
while when there's nothing else to watch, which could be pretty
much every night this summer.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
