<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6051 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-MAZDA-MPV-HNS &LR;      06-16 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-MAZDA-MPV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAZDA UPDATES ITS MPV MINIVAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mazda, that underrated but outstanding little Japanese car
company controlled by Ford Motor Co., has gotten serious about the
minivan market this year with an all-new version of its
long-running MPV model.
</P>
<P>
   The MPV _ that stands for ``multipurpose vehicle,'' not ``mostly
plastic vehicle,'' by the way _ was introduced in 1989 as one of
the most practical and affordable of the Japanese vans on the
market. It has been a best seller during most of its lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   But as good as it was, it had become somewhat outdated, with no
major redesigns during its 11-year history. Until now, that is.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, Mazda has hit another home run with the MPV, which
easily competes against the best Japanese and domestic models
available.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, as popular as the new Honda Odyssey is _ the
company has a huge backlog of orders and is rushing to build a new
plant to help fill them _ the MPV takes the best features of the
Odyssey and makes them even better.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: The middle row of seats, which can be either two
separate captain's chairs, or, when pushed together, a bench seat
for two. Honda's van does that, too, but the MPV's seats can be
moved forward or backward to create more leg room. The Odyssey's
can't.
</P>
<P>
   The new MPV has sliding doors on both sides, something that most
of the competition offers. But get this: The MPV has real windows
in those sliding doors so the rear passengers can finally get some
fresh air. These power rear windows are a first in the minivan
segment. I would not ride in the back of any car where I couldn't
roll down the window; I'm just one of those kinds of riders who has
to have fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   And the third seat is really cool. It can be turned over to face
to the rear to allow you to sit and watch the kids' soccer game in
comfort out the rear hatch, for a panoramic view. This is a nice
feature for tailgate parties, too.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo compartment offers another big advantage over the
MPV's competitors. It has a deep well for storage of groceries and
other cargo that keeps the stuff from sliding all over the place,
and with the third seat in place, there is still more than 17 cubic
feet of cargo space.
</P>
<P>
   And if you want to create a larger cargo area, fold the third
seat flat into that deep well, and you have 54 cubic feet of space.
But there's more: Those two middle-row seats can be easily lifted
out of the van and stored to increase space to more than 127 cubic
feet, enough to load up tons of stuff for Saturday gardening or
home-improvement projects. The middle seats weigh just 37 pounds
each.
</P>
<P>
   The seating options alone make the MPV one of the most practical
minivans ever. But the van has a lot more going for it. For one
thing, it's very nice looking _ more stylish than most of the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda used its design studio in Southern California to help make
this a beautiful vehicle. Even the interior styling is innovative
and refreshing, something unusual in a minivan. The V-shaped center
dash console, for instance, allows for more leg and foot room for
the front occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Cup holders abound. There are two in the dash for the front
occupants, and four more in the middle seating area, as well as
another four in the rear seat area. They will hold everything from
juice boxes to fountain cups, although they aren't quite deep and
wide enough for the 7-Eleven Big Gulp cups.
</P>
<P>
   Cubbyholes are plentiful for interior storage, too. There are
nine different places to stow things out of sight and out from
underfoot. One of my biggest gripes with most minivans is that when
you've got all the kiddies on board with all their stuff and your
stuff, that stuff is sliding all over the floor every time you turn
a corner or hit the brakes. You can tuck stuff out of the way and
avoid that with the MPV.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. It drives like a dream, too. In fact, there's nothing
boxy or van-like in the driving experience _ it seems more like
driving a sedan. It's powered by an adequate if not excessively
powerful 2.5-liter V-6 engine, supplied by Ford, that makes 170
horsepower and 165 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   This engine is perhaps the only slight drawback for the MPV; it
would be nice to have at least the option of a more powerful engine
if you're planning to tow a boat or if you live in the mountains
and need more torque on hills.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for most folks, the engine will be sufficient. It is
connected to a smooth-shifting Mazda four-speed automatic
transmission, and there are speed-sensitive power rack-and-pinion
steering and four-wheel antilock brakes to help with handling and
stopping.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is just as roomy as a standard-length Dodge Caravan
inside, the MPV has a compact exterior, which makes it easier to
park and to maneuver in city traffic or on narrow, woodsy state
park roads. Mazda calls the van ``smart sized'' because of its
smaller exterior but extremely efficient interior design that
maximizes space for people and cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Two major changes from the previous generation of the MPV are
the front-wheel-drive system (the old one had rear-wheel drive) and
the rear sliding doors. The old model had real rear doors, which
would swing open just like the front doors. I liked the old style
rear doors, as did a lot of MPV owners. But apparently Mazda had to
bow to consumer pressure and go with sliding doors to conform to
what all of the other minivan makers are using.
</P>
<P>
   Quality is truly job one with Mazda, and that's evident in the
MPV just as it is with all other Mazda products. Say what you will
about the quality of Toyota and Honda; they are very good. But
Mazda builds the best cars in the car business, period. I know that
from my own ownership experience over decades. You can beat a Mazda
up, but you'll have a hard time killing one. (I've tried).
</P>
<P>
   The MPV comes in three versions: the entry-level DX (base price
$19,995, plus $480 transportation), the midlevel LX (our test
vehicle, base price $22,050), and the top-of-the-line ES ($25,550).
</P>
<P>
   Standard equipment on the LX model includes the seven-passenger
seating arrangement I mentioned earlier, as well as velour seats,
AM/FM/compact-disc stereo with four speakers, power windows and
door locks, overhead console with map lights, under-seat storage
tray on the front passenger's side, privacy glass, rear
wiper/washer, air conditioning, 15-inch all-season tires with full
wheel covers, dual de-powered front air bags, tilt steering wheel,
halogen headlights and power heated outside mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Options on our test car included a rear-seat entertainment
system for the kids ($1,595), fog lamps ($250), roof rack ($200),
rear air-conditioning ($595), four-seasons package ($400), and the
LX touring package ($1,975), which added front side air bags,
remote keyless entry, wood-tone interior trim, carpeted floor mats,
nine-speaker super audio system with six-disc in-dash CD changer,
alarm system with immobilizer, 16-inch alloy wheels, and 16-inch
all-season radials.
</P>
<P>
   Total price for our vehicle was $27,545, including
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 18 miles per gallon in the city and
21 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 18.5 gallons of gasoline, and
unleaded regular is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is the San Antonio Express-News'
automotive columnist; telephone (210) 250-3236; e-mail:
chambers &LR; express-news.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
