u f BC-REVIEW-ACURA0617-COX     06-16 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ACURA0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Acura Type S coupe special
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Generally, manufacturers who put a ``Type''
designation on a car are up to something out of the ordinary, and
that's precisely the situation with the 2001 Acura 3.2CL Type S
coupe.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same pattern perceived rival BMW follows with its ``M''
versions and Ford with its SVT-tagged cars.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an Acura that's going to astonish folks who aren't
familiar with what parent company Honda has been doing of late with
its engines, which benefit from trickledown technology from Formula
One Grand Prix racing. The Type S is classified as a near-luxury
car, but there's nothing ``near'' about its sportiness.
</P>
<P>
   It's powered by an instantly responsive V-6 engine that delivers
260 horsepower at 6,100 rpm and 232 pounds-feet of torque at 3,500
rpm. Reach for maximum horsepower, and the Type S produces a
satisfying growl while getting there.
</P>
<P>
   As for the near-luxury aspect, this 3.2CL is so well-equipped
that the only option is a $2,000 navigation system. Some time spent
in a 3.2CL with the navigation system left the definite impression
that it's far better to invest the $29,980 that's the base price of
the non-S car and the money needed for the navigation system _ a
total of $30,435 _ toward a Type S and a good road map.
</P>
<P>
   The navigation system is difficult to operate, although its good
features do include zoom-in, zoom-out capability, and it will
recall frequently used routes and show how to get home from
wherever you happen to be.
</P>
<P>
   With its lengthy list of standard features _ including an
in-dash six-disc CD player, power everything and leather trim _ the
Type S shows that Honda is very serious about upgrading the Acura's
image. And its horsepower and torque numbers, along with a
zero-to-60 mph time of 6.6 seconds, indicate that the performance
is there, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's no fun getting in and out of the headroom-impaired rear
seat, but the ride, road-holding characteristics and soundproofing
of the Type S are all commendable. Fuel mileage is about what's
expected of V-6 engines with muscle, 19 mpg in the city and 29 mpg
on the highway, and so is the fuel recommendation (premium).
</P>
<P>
   The interior and instrumentation layout show both thought and
good workmanship. The far-reaching Xenon headlamps may aggravate
oncoming drivers, but they're a plus for whoever's behind the wheel
of the Type S (and other CLs).
</P>
<P>
   So never mind that the styling isn't as edgy or as appealing as
the mechanicals and creature comforts of Type S. Its performance
and utility _ yes, that too _ suggest that compared to some cars in
its class, it's a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
