<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTANIC-CONGRESS-NYTR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 FIRST WORLD BOTANIC GARDENS CONGRESS TO MEET 
</HEADLINE>
   By KITTY TURNER and LUANN LAUBSCHER   
 Times-News, Hendersonville, N.C.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ At 14-years-old, the North Carolina Arboretum
is an infant compared with the great gardens of the world. But its
staff and a devoted corps of volunteers have scored a coup: landing
the first-ever World Botanic Gardens Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The June 25 to 30 meeting is expected to attract 800 to 1,000
delegates from 50 countries. It will bring together members of the
American Association of Botanical Gardens and Arboreta, the Botanic
Gardens Conservation International and the Center for Plant
Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Arboretum Director George Briggs described the
work leading to the World Congress' decision to meet in Asheville
as ``the proverbial dog chasing the car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Botanic Gardens Conservation International has never
before met in the United States, and the American group usually
meets in major cities _ Boston, Philadelphia, Denver,'' Briggs
said. ``For both these groups to come to Asheville is quite an
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the conference is ``Creating Partnerships Within
and Beyond the Garden.'' A key goal of the World Botanic Gardens
Congress is the development of a new and focused global plant
conservation strategy among botanic gardens.
</P>
<P>
   One strategy is to pull related disciplines into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of natural collaboration that zoological parks have
in conserving animals is the model we're exploring for botanic
gardens,'' Briggs said. ``Sharing resources and information _ and
rare or endangered species _ - to best conserve what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference features more than 85 presentations, workshops
and sessions covering topics of interest to public garden
professionals and scientists working in plant conservation. While
the sessions are not open to the public, tapes of proceedings will
later be available.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina Arboretum covers 426 acres in the Blue Ridge
Mountains and is surrounded by the Pisgah National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Turner and Luann Laubscher write for The Times-News,
Hendersonville, N.C., which is a member of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group. This article was distributed by The New
York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
