<SLUG> BC-WINE-FIRE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE LOSS MAY COST WINERIES $36 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By MARY CALLAHAN   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALISTOGA, Calif. _ A devastating fire at the historic Kornell
Champagne Cellars site destroyed an estimated $36 million in
premium wine from around the Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze Thursday inside a cavernous bottling and storage
facility at what's now called Frank-Rombauer Larkmead Cellars wiped
out approximately 90,000 cases of wine, including about 70,000
cases of Frank-Rombauer wine and 20,000 cases of high-end wine from
other vintners, winery owner Koerner Rombauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Rombauer said some bottles were worth $100 each on the retail
market. Most were between $50 to $100, he said, making the loss an
estimated $36 million.
</P>
<P>
   Damage to the storage facility itself and equipment is likely to
push the loss total over $40 million, Rombauer said, easily making
this the costliest winery fire in Northern California history.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty firefighters from around Napa County battled the fire,
applying a steady stream of water to the top of the 120-foot
building in the hope of preventing the fire from spreading to other
buildings. A sea of runoff and wine that spilled onto the pavement
below was sucked up and carted away by trucks usually reserved for
septic tanks and portable toilets to ensure none of it reached the
Napa River some 100 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those individual wineries whose wines are stored there,
it's a devastating loss, and if they lose their inventory it takes
them out of the market for an entire year,'' said Eric Sims, an
industry economist at Motto, Kryla and Fisher wine business
consultants of St. Helena.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers might also feel the pinch, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only a limited amount of high-end Napa cabernet supply
and the demand's been pretty high, and to have the supply disappear
is only going to put more upward pressure on prices,'' Sims said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the losses, winery and fire officials were thrilled the
blaze spared the winery's 1906 stone building, a national landmark
shrouded in 125-year-old Dutch elm trees. ``Thank God we saved
this,'' said Rich Frank, co-owner of the winery with Rombauer.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials were uncertain of the cause of the blaze, which
was discovered about 7 a.m., when a worker arrived and found the
two-story steel and concrete bottling building flooded with smoke,
the floor soaked by fire sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, firefighters played hide-and-seek with
flames that kept popping up in different places after traveling
through the building's walls, and especially through a space
between the building's wooden ceiling and metal roof. Highly
combustible cardboard boxes encasing the wine and stacked three
deep on the second floor contributed to the difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Winery owners, meanwhile, attempted to assess the loss and look
to the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make wine for a lot of people, and we only sell our wines
here, we don't do retail,'' Frank said. ``So 100 percent of our
stuff is sitting here. It's not scattered at the A&AMP;P's. So for us,
we won't have wines for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who bottle and store their wines at the
40,000-square-foot, 18-year-old structure are primarily vintners
with small, ``but really, really expensive wines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The inventory included wines from Frank-Rombauer, Blair
Vineyards, Craig Bissonette, Cataculet Ranch, Club and Restaurant
Wines, Bacio Divino, D-Cubed, Dusinberre, Eklund, Elyse Wine
Cellars, G. Graham Wines, Queenfield Wine Co., Kathryn Hall,
Inniskillin Wines, Kuleto Ranch, Bravante, Mura Wines, Napa
Cellars, Parador Cellars, Leduco Vineyards, Pride Mountain Winery,
Perry, Point Reyes, Robert Foley, Rombauer Vineyards, Soda Canyon,
Shypoke Vineyards, Sparrow Lane Winery, Spellitch Cellars,
Salvestrin and Winston Hill Wines.
</P>
<P>
   The winery came into its own under Hanns Kornell, once known as
``America's champagne master,'' who for 30 years made sparkling
wines at the historic site, building a $14 million empire. Kornell
and his family, battling a downturn in the industry and heavy debt
due to expansion efforts, declared bankruptcy in 1991 and were
forced to sell the property.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary Callahan writes for The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa,
Calif., which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. This article is distributed by The New York Times News
Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
