<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6064 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-SIGNATURES-77     06-16 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SIGNATURES-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES BILL TO ALLOW ONLINE CONTRACT-SIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ore., Vt.)   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ and JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Without one disapproving vote, the Senate on Friday
passed a final bill that catapults electronic commerce to a new
level by allowing consumers and businesses to sign contracts online
with a click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now goes to President Clinton, who said Friday he would
sign it into law.
</P>
<P>
   By giving electronic signatures the legal weight of paper
signatures, the new law would give consumers the chance to buy
health insurance, complete bank loans or set up brokerage accounts
over the Internet, around the clock and with no delay.
</P>
<P>
   Without the Internet, consumers and businesses typically have to
wait days or weeks for documents to be written, mailed, signed and
then returned.
</P>
<P>
   Financial institutions and insurance companies are expected to
save billions of dollars by eliminating the cost of preparing
paperwork and mailing it. Most records would be kept
electronically, doing away with the need for giant warehouses to
store the material.
</P>
<P>
   The law goes into effect Oct. 1, and consumers could start
taking advantage of the new law soon afterward. Electronic commerce
companies, like e-loan, are all set to take advantage of the
legislation, and some of the larger banks, like Citibank, which
already do business online could easily make adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill revolutionizes the way consumers, industry and
government conduct business over the Internet,'' said Sen. Spencer
Abraham, R-Mich., who helped steer the bill through Congress. ``It
is a tremendous cost-cutting tool because people and businesses can
now enter contractual arrangements without having to drive across
town, fly thousands of miles for a meeting or mail reams of paper
back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a nod to Democrats and consumer rights organizations, the
bill also helps protect the millions of people who do not have
access to the Internet or who worry about being defrauded in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This landmark legislation will ensure that consumer
protections remain strong in the technology age,'' Clinton said
Friday. ``It will help create new rules of the road for America's
high-tech community.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would enable consumers to choose whether to do business
online or on paper. And banks would be required to verify that
consumers could receive documents and information online by
exchanging e-mail with them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, certain sensitive legal documents and procedures
would not be permitted to be done electronically. For example,
insurance and utility companies must still send cancellation and
termination notices through the mail, wills cannot be executed over
the Internet, and products may not be recalled online. Mortgages,
too, must be foreclosed on paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mantra through this all was consumer rights can't be
virtual rights,'' said Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who helped draft the
bill and shepherd it through a difficult round of negotiations with
the House. ``They have to exist in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill made several serious stumbles during negotiations
between the House and the Senate versions. For months, banks,
insurance companies, securities firms and the high-technology
industry _ a powerful coalition _ lobbied House and Senate members
to permit the use of these so-called ``digital signatures.''
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation hit a snag when Democrats, prompted by
consumer rights groups, said it was lax in safeguarding the rights
of the average person. Then the Justice Department and the nation's
governors expressed serious reservations about the legislation,
saying it could prompt businesses to skirt state regulations on
Internet transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, industry representatives were warned against
even speaking with Democrats,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., who
helped craft a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, businesses were concerned that states were hampering
interstate commerce by creating a tangle of laws on electronic
signatures and record-keeping. The bill created uniform standards
but it gives states some flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the logjam was broken _ a testament, in part, to
Congress' enthusiasm about the Internet and the economic boom it
has created. The Senate passed the measure Friday by a vote of
87-0. The House approved it on Wednesday, 426-4.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some concerns remain. Margo Saunders, a lawyer at the
National Consumer Law Center, said she worried that the bill would
serve to ``skyrocket'' fraud on the Internet. Computer hackers are
becoming more adept at stealing people's identities on the
Internet, and privacy concerns remain paramount among consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't sat down to figure out how to protect consumers,''
she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The bill does not specify exactly what a digital signature will
look like, allowing companies, and ultimately the free market, to
decide what kind of technology works best.
</P>
<P>
   A signature could simply be strings of numeric code that is
encrypted _ scrambled and unscrambled _ or it could involve more
sophisticated devices, like thumb-print scanners. Since many
consumers remain nervous about conducting these kinds of
transactions online, it is likely that many institutions will try
to improve online security. Congress, too, has a role to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a lot more focus on watchdogging against
hackers,'' said Wyden. ``A hacker today is sort of like the guy who
goes around rattling all the windows and doors in a neighborhood,
and there is a pretty good chance he will find one open.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that develop this kind of security clearance online
are already scrambling to offer their services. One Utah company,
iLumin, plans to launch a ``digital handshake system'' next week
that would gather all parties involved in a cyber signing room to
help them securely complete their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is also expected to be a boon in so-called
business-to-business transactions. ``For instance, an automobile
manufacturer will be able to have complete contract negotiations
with parts suppliers online,'' said David Colton, a lobbyist for
the Information Technology Association of America. ``There are huge
cost savings associated with this, and the cost savings will
ultimately be passed on to the consumers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
