<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hot and humid weather will precede a cold front as it moves
toward the northeast coast from the eastern Ohio Valley. Hazy
sunshine will prevail for much of the day near the northeast and
middle Atlantic coasts. Farther inland, clouds and a band of
thunderstorms will accompany the front as it moves slowly across
the crest of the Appalachians in the middle of the day. By late
Saturday, thunderstorms with the front will approach the coast.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the front, much cooler air will cover a large
area from the northern Rockies to the Great Lakes states. Scattered
light showers will form in the cool air from the northern Rockies
to the Dakotas. Farther south, damp conditions will occur near the
eastern slopes of the central Rockies as moist winds ascend the
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will be sultry with scattered thundershowers. A
stalled front in the southern Plains will be the focus for thunder
and heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SELF-DEFEATING HEAT
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, San Francisco tied its all-time record high, 103
degrees. One day later, the mercury hovered near 60. The reversal
was a direct result of the excessive heat. Hot air weighs less than
cold air, and air pressure is simply the weight of the air. During
the day of searing heat on Wednesday, the air pressure fell over
interior California. Since air flows from high pressure to low, the
air in contact with the cool Pacific Ocean was drawn inland,
bringing an end to the rare coastal heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
