<HEADER>
A6071 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      06-16 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 18, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-SYRIA-REVIEW (Washington) _ It was pure coincidence that
presidential succession in Syria and the rapprochement between
North and South Korea took place the same day. But there were
profound similarities in what was happening. Both North Korea and
Syria are relics of another age _ dictatorships where power has
been based on internal terror and hostility to external neighbors,
threatening to explode at any time in new conflict. In both places,
power has passed from a dictator to his son, and the son shows
signs of a more modern, outward-looking approach to solving his
country's problems. Perhaps that can make the world more peaceful.
But there is also the disquieting feeling that it won't be easy;
terror and isolation remain hallmarks of the systems in which these
two sons rule. By Elaine Sciolono. (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTISTS-SECRECY-REVIEW (Undated) _ As secrets on nuclear
terrorism and miniaturized warheads apparently slip out of Los
Alamos National Laboratory and other federal labs, the message here
would seem to be obvious: do not give dangerous secrets to
scientists. There is, of course, a flaw in this solution.
Governments need the scientists and their culture of openness to
produce weapons that are worth keeping secret in the first place.
That in a nutshell, is why science and secrecy have clashed. By
James Glanz. (Moving in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   ECON-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ It has been more than nine
years since the nation emerged from its last recession, and nearly
two decades since the last extended period of economic bad times.
It would be understandable, if delusional, for Americans to
conclude that prosperity has been woven into the fabric of life.
Politics, however, is still catching up with prosperity. After
decades in which the two parties fought over how to slice up a
shrinking pie and maneuvered to claim credit for periodic good
news, they now operate in a climate in which economic strength
seems a given and the biggest issue is not a scarcity of money but
a surfeit. By Richard Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-PLATFORMS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Conventional wisdom holds
that party platforms are archaic. But many experts say platforms
can be revealing documents _ not only of what an administration
will try to do once in office, but also of the power of various
constituency groups in the party and the extent to which the
nominee is willing to take them on. At a time when everything else
is so stage-managed, poll-driven and homogenized in politics,
platforms are where the activists often have their say. This, of
course, can be troublesome for the nominees. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   STUDENT-SORTING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Lusting after the academic
successes of European and Japanese schoolchildren, American
educators in recent years have imported the idea of a rigorous
system of tests, which other countries use to cull the elite from
the merely literate. But educators here insisted that America,
being the land of second chances, would instead use testing to snap
schools to attention, forcing them to raise standards for everyone.
They would lift up, not weed out. But the evidence so far suggests
that schools here are doing the very sort of gardening they
promised to avoid, employing tests to sort children, and at a far
earlier age than elsewhere. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION-REVIEW (Undated) _ Just a few years ago, lawmakers
were in full cry about the supposed dangers of immigration _ from
crime to welfare cheats to lost jobs. Yet now Congress is poised to
pass a bill that would grant visas to tens of thousands more
temporary high-tech workers from abroad. And an unlikely coalition
of business and immigrants rights groups is pushing to fling the
door open wider: to unskilled workers who could fill shortages in
hotels and on farms , and even to roll back an array of restrictive
measures passed with great fanfare in 1996. Clearly, the national
conversation about immigration has changed dramatically. By Somini
Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HMOS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Patients may be wondering
whose side the Supreme Court is on in the wake of its decision
shielding health maintenance organizations from some lawsuits by
patients in federal court. The decision favored HMOs but included
some blunt comments about their role in rationing health care. Such
rationing, the court said, is intrinsic to design and mission of
HMOs. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   MOB-WALLSTREET-REVIEW (Undated) _ A humorous imaginary look at
the mob's new lines of business.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS-REVIEW (Moscow) _ By any standard measure of
democracy, political opposition is just what Russia desperately
needs. But until last week, President Vladimir Putin didn't really
have any. But now, with the jailing of Vladimir Gusinsky, Putin may
have actually stirred up some real opposition, setting the stage
for an acid test of Russia's young democracy: how is the opposition
to act, and how will it be treated? By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-REVIEW (Washington) _ To hear some in NATO talk,
Montenegro _ the last republic of Tito's Yugoslavia remains
alongside Serbia in today's rump Yugoslavia _ is the unsinkable
aircraft carrier in the West's unfinished war against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic. But last week, the carrier was given
a significant holing by Montenegro's voters, a sizable minority of
whom want to remain inside Yugoslavia. By Steve Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-CIA-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some lessons to be learned from
the recently leaked CIA history of the agency's role in the 1953
coup that overthrew Iran's prime minister and restored the shah to
power.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STORY QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: &LR;
</P>
