<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6073 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w BC-STATES-MONEY-PA     06-16 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-MONEY-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; GEKAS ASSETS WORTH MORE THAN $685,000 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Melissa Vogt &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 States News Service &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (June 15) - Evangeline Charas-Gekas holds about 60
percent of the assets that her husband, Rep. George Gekas,
R-Harrisburg, reported in his annual personal financial disclosure
report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, Gekas' assets, including those held by his wife,
ranged from $685,000 to $1.62 million. Income from those assets
ranged from $15,200 to $36,800. The largest asset in Gekas' report
was Charas-Gekas' retirement fund valued at $250,000 to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. representatives receive a $136,700 base salary per year but
must list other sources of income, assets, liabilities and
financial transactions in annual financial disclosure reports filed
with the House Clerk on May 15. Spouse's holdings must be included.
</P>
<P>
   Challenger candidates for congressional offices must file a
similar report within 30 days of filing their candidacy. The report
for Gekas' Democratic challenger Leslye Herrmann of Mechanicsburg
covered Jan. 1, 1998 to May 15 of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann reported receiving $1,162 in consulting fees from Ohio
Insurance Co. in 1999. This year she received $10,013 from an early
withdrawal of a retirement fund.
</P>
<P>
   Gekas, who served 14 years in the Pennsylvania legislature,
received $16,641 from the state employee pension plan in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Gekas' report showed he owes $50,000 to $100,000 for mortgages
on three Harrisburg properties, including his home and two houses
his wife inherited from her father Louis Charas' estate.
</P>
<P>
   Gekas reported no trips paid by anyone other than himself aside
from official business. Congressional challengers must report any
compensation valued at more than $5,000 within the last two years.
Herrmann did consulting and survey work for the state of
Pennsylvania. While more than $5,000, the exact amount she was
compensated was not contained in her report.
</P>
<P>
   She also held consultant positions for the Pennsylvania Senate,
the Center for Independent Living in Camp Hill and Pennsylvania
State University. Again information about the amount of
compensation and when she performed these services was unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Calls made to the candidate were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann listed no liabilities. -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-CIRCUS18-COX     06-16 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CIRCUS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Circus Fire' smolders
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Circus crowds basically consist of two types of people: those
who want to know how, exactly, so many clowns managed to fit inside
that tiny car, and those who couldn't care less about such niggling
details, just so long as the end result is entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying story is much more tragic in ``The Circus Fire,''
but the same principle applies.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone looking for a precise, detail-rich account of the 1944
conflagration that killed 167 patrons of the Ringling Bros. and
Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus in Hartford, Conn., doubtless will judge
Stewart O'Nan's book a resounding success. Yet as entertaining,
compelling reading goes, ``The Circus Fire'' is regrettably low on
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   To O'Nan's credit, he appears to have accomplished precisely
what he set out to do. Had such a tragedy occurred today, there
would be no escaping any aspect of the story, thanks to the 24-hour
cable news channels, the tell-all books and ``very special''
movies-of-the-week about survivors and heroes, not to mention the
inevitable lawsuits filed and congressional hearings called to
assess damages and blame.
</P>
<P>
   But 1944 was a different time. World War II was the national
preoccupation and TV still rare. O'Nan, the critically acclaimed
author of five novels, including last year's ``A Prayer for the
Dying,'' first learned about the circus fire from a Life magazine
article about a decade ago; sometime after that, he moved to
Hartford and was shocked to discover that no one had written a book
about the tragedy. In taking up the task himself, O'Nan resisted
suggestions that he consider turning the circus fire into a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it deserved only the most stringent, very best
intentions of nonfiction, the idea being to tell the truth about an
event that changed the lives of tens of thousands of people,''
O'Nan writes in the book's foreword. ``As a history, it hopes to
fix a time and a place long gone, to preserve it so readers can
visit it and try to understand what the people of Hartford went
through.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``fix it'' he does. O'Nan the novelist perhaps would have
left a few things out. But in his admirable zeal to cover every
aspect of the Hartford tragedy backward and forward _ the book
begins with a confusingly long account of another circus fire two
years earlier and ends with a survivors' reunion in the late 1990s
_ O'Nan seemingly tells us everything he knows and even a few
things he doesn't know. Because the basic structure is
chronological, names and events sometimes seem to run together and
some intriguing stories drop off just when they seemed to be
getting going.
</P>
<P>
   On one page, for instance, O'Nan describes the out-of-control
flames racing toward diesel-fueled generators _ and one desperate
clown's attempt to stop them: ``In his Weary Willy costume _
complete with huge shoes _ Emmett Kelly came rushing over with a
wash bucket full of water, his painted frown a perfect exprTION
</P>
<P>
   The Circus Fire. By Stewart O'Nan. Doubleday. $24.95. 370 pages.
(Audiocassette: Brilliance Corp., $32.95 unabridged; $24.95
abridged.)
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A three-alarm letdown.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes about books, politics and popular culture
for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
