<HEADER>
A6075 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SKUBE18-COX     06-16 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Together all alone: America, the land of social dropouts
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 18.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next month, on the Fourth of July, Americans will again take a
day off from work, watch parades and salute their right to life,
liberty and the pursuit of happiness. It's the last one that's
elusive, and Robert Putnam thinks he knows why. We are a nation of
strangers, with fewer close friends than we once had, cut off from
neighbors, going our private way.
</P>
<P>
   We no longer belong to anything.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always so. Alexis de Tocqueville, in ``Democracy in
America,'' defined the distinctive American trait. We were joiners,
forming associations private and public to advance common cause or
simply mutual enjoyment. Throughout most of the 20th century, they
flourished in every neighborhood, from PTAs to the NAACP to Rotary
to the menagerie of what Putnam amiably calls the animal clubs _
Lions and Elks, Moose and Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   It all peaked in the 1950s and 1960s, and then membership rolls
everywhere began dwindling _ in many cases, dramatically. From the
American Medical Association to the Jaycees, the Masons to the
Kiwanis, people began dropping out. The Odd Fellows will soon be as
dead as dodos. Even the Optimists _ their very name an affirmation
of faith _ are seeing less of one another.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just club rolls that are thinning. So, too, is the
social glue that brings together people of different backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of isolation, Putnam argues in ``Bowling Alone,''
are both public and personal. Putnam is a professor of public
policy at Harvard and a happy crusader for sociability of every
sort. When he took the stage recently at Georgia State University,
dressed in a blue Oxford cloth shirt, striped tie and a khaki suit,
his ruddy cheeks set off by Lincolnesque whiskers, he was the very
picture of good-fellow conviviality. How many, he asked his
audience of a hundred or so, had been to a picnic or a block party
lately? How many had been to a bar with friends? How many had
attended a public meeting?
</P>
<P>
   He didn't ask how many had gone bowling. More Americans bowl
today than ever before, he said, but the point is that they don't
belong to leagues in the numbers they once did. They might bowl
with restless kids, a spur-of-the-moment way to spend a rainy
Sunday afternoon. And some people, apparently, just hang out in
bowling alleys. It was at a bowling alley, Putnam tells us, that
Timothy McVeigh met his accomplices in the bombing of a federal
building in Oklahoma City. If only, someone would say later,
McVeigh had gone bowling alone. Hence Putnam's somewhat misleading
title.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's larger purposes are civic and social. He wants us to be
better citizens, better neighbors, happier people who trust one
another more than we do. It sounds so warm and fuzzy you resist
poking around in Putnam's argument. And the survey numbers he
presents speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, and yet. ...
</P>
<P>
   The notion of ``social capital,'' by which Putnam means the
connections among people, is _ to say the least _ more suggestive
than explanatory. One might agree that ``A society of many virtuous
but isolated individuals is not necessarily rich in social
capital,'' and one should certainly agree that a society in which
more people read daily newspapers and supported their public
schools was a more cohesive one. But how far does any of this take
us toward understanding what a well-functioning community might be?
There are, as Putnam acknowledges, communities and then there are
communities. The Bloods and the KKK are, by some measure,
communities, conferring on their members a validation they cannot
secure on their own. Membership sometimes implies both inclusion
and exclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between privacy and belonging is scarcely new, and
Americans at different times want a little more of one, a little
less of the other. Putnam sees the obvious with the acuity of a
hawk: Television has anesthetized us, drawing us away from one
another. People driving 45 minutes _ and more _ to and from work
are going to be spending less time with friends. (But why? Because,
in most cases, they're spending that time with family.) And
two-income families are also going to have less time for clubs. If
careers compromise family life, they diminish social life still
more.
</P>
<P>
   One of the easy inferences from this should be that people in
suburbia are hermits in their cul-de-sacs. And yet anecdotal
experience _ which, admittedly, is personal _ suggests quite the
opposite. Community, if it exists anywhere today, exists in the
suburbs, where people are connected in ways not measured by the old
affiliations. The social glue, more often that not, is children.
People whose backgrounds are anything but homogeneous find in one
another common purpose. If it's not the baseball games every
spring, it's school functions, a neighborhood association, a swim
club or even something so unquantifiable as seeing familiar faces
on a nightly walk. And, whatever the survey data might show,
millions of people draw from this a mutual recognition that will be
remembered longer than all the Rotary meetings they ever attended.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bowling Alone: The Collapse and Revival of American Community.
By Robert D. Putnam. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $26. 541 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
