<HEADER>
A6076 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-GETAWAY17-COX     06-16 1660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waynesville will celebrate area's work this weekend
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAYNESVILLE, N.C. _ A visit to this scenic mountain town named
for Revolutionary War hero ``Mad'' Anthony Wayne will likely
inspire art and crafts lovers to shop like mad in the many
storefront galleries lining its red-brick sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the town's art galleries and studios will host the
annual Art in the Mountains open house and walking tour, featuring
demonstrations and refreshments, from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Galleries
will be freshly stocked, and artists will be on hand to discuss
their work.
</P>
<P>
   Most of downtown fits neatly into a three-block area, making it
as easy to see as it is to spend.
</P>
<P>
   At Burr Gallery and Studio, artist owners Dane and MaryEtta Burr
will be holding court in their new storefront on North Main.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been downstairs (on Wall Street),'' says MaryEtta, who
specializes in wheel-thrown pottery. ``We just came upstairs three
weeks ago. We still have the studio downstairs, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she was busy painting one of sculptor husband Dane's
2,000 limited-edition Santa Claus heads commissioned by the
Southern Highlands Craft Guild as its official 2000 Christmas
ornament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little low on my pieces right now,'' she says,
``because I've been working to get the gallery open.'' (Not to
mention painting Santas.)
</P>
<P>
   Down the street is Cross Currents Gallery: The Handcrafted Home,
which showcases Sheree White Sorrells' handwoven rugs, pillows and
wall hangings. Although the gallery has been open only seven
months, Sorrells is no newcomer. For 15 years, she has worked more
or less out of sight upstairs in her Whitewoven Handweaving Studio,
where she has three large looms, one of which can be used to make
rugs as wide as 11 feet.
</P>
<P>
   She set up shop in Waynesville after moving from Greensboro and
earning a fine arts degree in textile weaving from Western Carolina
University in nearby Cullowhee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more heritage here, more craftspeople, crafts
organizations and resources,'' says Sorrells.
</P>
<P>
   You'll likely find colored-pencil artist Teresa Pennington
working at a drawing board inside the front door of T. Pennington
Art Gallery. The self-taught artist, who grew up in nearby
Asheville, decided to open a gallery in Waynesville 15 years ago,
just as the town's revitalization program was gearing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful little town,'' she says. ``Asheville is so
spread out now that you don't have the same sense of community we
have here in Waynesville.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennington is president of the Downtown Waynesville Association,
which recognizes the arts' vital role in economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had a strong crafts tradition in Western North
Carolina,'' says Ron Huelster, executive director of the
association since its inception in 1986. ``Haywood Community
College here has one of the first production crafts programs in the
country with fiber, wood, metal and pottery. We wanted to focus on
our strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   The program has been so successful in attracting artists to
downtown that the vacancy rate is less than 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have artists continually coming through looking for a
building,'' says Huelster, ``but we're pretty much completely
occupied.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the art galleries, this town of about 9,000 _
which recently spent $312,000 on retro street lamps _ is
chockablock with shops that carry a wonderful mix of merchandise,
including antiques, collectibles, home and garden accessories,
apparel and gourmet food and wine.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cliche, but when Chamber of Commerce President David
Eberhard boasts there's ``something for everybody'' in Waynesville,
you tend to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Want the ambience of yesteryear? Visit the Mast General Store in
the former Belk location downtown. Got a kid's birthday coming up?
Drop into O.P. Taylor's. Want something out of the ordinary for the
cook in your house? Home-Tech has wonderful kitchen gadgets and
gear.
</P>
<P>
   It's definitely not art, but if you need a chuckle, stop by
Eberhard's Angel Connection and ask to see Big Mouth Billy Bob, the
mounted bass that belts out ``Don't Worry, Be Happy'' and ``Take Me
to the River.''
</P>
<P>
   For grumps who don't like to shop, gallery hop or be serenaded
by singing bass, there are benches strategically placed along the
sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   As you stroll around town, pause to admire _ or malign _ the
large-scale environmental sculptures selected for this year's
StreetScapes. One work in particular, ``The Cowlifters'' by metal
artist Jon Dawes, has provoked much debate among the locals over
its artistic merit. Installed in front of an office building on
Church Street, it is crafted in part from steering gear boxes from
18-wheelers, and it has winglike protrusions taken from the frame
of a Chevrolet car hood.
</P>
<P>
   See what you think. It'll be a good conversation starter in the
galleries.
</P>
<P>
   WAYNESVILLE GALLERIES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blue Owl Studio and Gallery: Features hand-watercolored
antique graphics and pottery. 11 N. Main St. 828-456-9596.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Burr Gallery and Studio: Clay sculpture and stoneware and
porcelain pottery. 136 N. Main St. 828-456-7400.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cross Currents Gallery: The Handcrafted Home and Whitewoven
Handweaving Studio: Woven throws, pillows and rugs by weaver Sheree
White Sorrells. 86 N. Main St. 828-452-4864.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Deja View Gallery: Original art and handicrafts created by
local, regional and national artists. 132 N. Main St. 828-452-9787.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Grace Cathey Gallery &AMP; Sculpture Garden: Nature artist Cathey
creates metalworks, many with vine or leaf embellishments. 136
Depot St. 828-456-8843.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cedar Hill Studio and Gallery: Home to painter Gretchen
Clasby's whimsical ``Sonshine Promise Birds'' and original
paintings of wildlife, children and flowers. 196 Main St.
828-456-6344.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Earthworks: An environmental gallery featuring fine art,
sculpture and jewelry from local and Native American artists. 21 N.
Main St. 828-452-9500.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hardwood Gallery: Wood sculptor Dennis Ruane creates wooden
spoons and large-scale nature sculptures from hardwoods from the
forests of Western North Carolina. 102 N. Main St. 828-456-3500.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  T. Pennington Art Gallery: Colored-pencil drawings of the
area's scenery, landmarks (including Asheville's Biltmore Estate),
flowers and wildlife. 15 N. Main St. 828-452-9284.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Twigs &AMP; Leaves: Potter Kaaren Stoner turns real leaves into
porcelain embellishments for her hand-turned pottery pieces. Also,
works of other artists who draw inspiration from nature. 98 N. Main
St. 828-456-1940.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ridge Runner Naturals: Watercolors by Jo Kelley capture the
beauty of the mountains. Also, gifts and other art that appeals to
nature lovers. 33 N. Main St. 828-456-3003.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Village Framer: Prints, some original and whimsical
artifacts and antique reproductions from the Far East and Latin
America. 56 N. Main St. 828-452-0823.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-85 north to I-985, which becomes U.S.
23. Follow U.S. 23/U.S. 441 north, then U.S. 23 north/U.S. 74 east
toward Waynesville. Take U.S. 276 east into downtown and turn south
on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to stay: Waynesville has several historic inns and
bed-and-breakfasts within minutes of downtown. We chose the homey
Grandview Lodge, less than a 10-minute drive from town, having
heard about innkeeper Linda Arnold's bounteous country breakfasts
and family-style dinners.
</P>
<P>
   Staying with Linda and Stan Arnold in this comfortable but
hardly fancy century-old farmhouse is like spending time with
kinfolks (ones you like). There's a hammock and lots of easy chairs
on the lawn. Apple orchards, grape arbors and rhubarb patches fill
the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   One night the tables groaned with pork roast, fried squash,
asparagus, new potatoes, corn pudding, baked mixed fruit, freshly
baked rolls, homemade jams and jellies, and a choice of homemade
strawberry ice cream or a brownie-like pie with vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   We wondered how the sheets could feel so good and smell so fresh
until we saw them flapping on the clothesline. Rates are $80-$115 a
night including breakfast and dinner. 466 Lickstone Road.
1-800-255-7826; www.bbonline.com/nc/grandview/.
</P>
<P>
   For other options, go to www.downtownwaynesville.com and click
on ``Where to Stay.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to eat: Lomo's Bakery and Cafe is a cozy
Mediterranean-style cafe a block off Main and around the corner on
Montgomery Street. We were pleased with our choices: a roasted
turkey breast panini with spinach, tomato and lemon garlic aioli
($6.95), one of the day's specials; spinach pie ($6.50); and
rotisserie chicken sub ($5.95). 11 a.m.-3 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays.
171 Montgomery St., 828-452-1515.
</P>
<P>
   Also good for lunch downtown: Stefano's, Mediterranean/Italian
grill, 111 N. Main St., 828-452-0027; the Hop, a '50s-style diner,
177 N. Main St., 828-456-9222; and Whitman's Bakery and Sandwich
Shop, operating in the same location since 1945, 18 N. Main St.,
828-456-8271.
</P>
<P>
   We hear good things about the fine dining at the Old Stone Inn,
109 Dolan Road, 828-456-3333 and at Michael's, 319 N. Haywood St.,
828-452-2620.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Upcoming event: Folkmoot USA International Folk Festival is
July 18-30. At least 10 folk groups from around the world will
perform in Waynesville and various Western North Carolina counties
and take part in the Parade of Nations on July 21 and the
International Festival Day on July 29, both on Main Street in
Waynesville. Groups are expected from Aruba, Huahine (French
Polynesia), China, Egypt, Greece, Ireland, Israel, Mexico and the
republic of Georgia. Information: 1-877-365-5872; www.folkmoot.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Downtown Waynesville Association, 828-456-3517;
www.downtownwaynesville.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
