<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZLAND18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Along for a jazzy ride in the big easy
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 18.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Jazzland is everything that's frivolous and
family-friendly about the Big Easy _ the good times rolled into a
140-acre theme park not more than 20 minutes from Bourbon Street.
</P>
<P>
   Think Louisiana lite: Mardi Gras without the sleaze. Bayous
without the alligators. A jazz hall without hard benches. Familiar
Cajun grub like red beans and rice, fried catfish and po-boys.
French Quarter treats powered-like sugar-dusted beignets and creole
pralines. Fruity frozen daiquiris in plastic souvenir ``Jazzhorns''
and icy Snoballs.
</P>
<P>
   The $110 million theme park has been enthusiastically welcomed
by area residents, who purchased more than 40,000 season passes
before the May 20 opening.
</P>
<P>
   Although its 30 rides put Jazzland in the league of sprawling
attractions such as Six Flags Over Georgia and Astroworld in
Houston, its size is not overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   The park reverberates with musical entertainment, including a
jazz band that pops up here and there, Cajun and zydeco bands at
Cajun Dance Hall and the Broadway-style revue ``Jazz, Jazz, Jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   Six themed sections encircle a body of water, with a spraying
fountain, called the Crescent City Basin. The fanciful architecture
reflects the region: the lacy ironwork of the French Quarter
balconies in Jazz Plaza; the wood bayou cabins in Cajun Country;
and the silvery art deco facades in the Pontchartrain Beach area,
which evoke the amusement park of the same name that closed in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   The park's towering piece de resistance is the MegaZeph. The
4,000-foot-long steel-structured, wood-track coaster, located in
the Mardi Gras section, is a modern version of the Zephyr at the
old Pontchartrain park. The first drop is 110 feet _ and it's a
head-spinning, stomach-churning ride at speeds up to 65 mph from
there.
</P>
<P>
   You'll feel so intoxicated, it might as well be Fat Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6079 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-JAZZTOUR18-COX     06-16 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZTOUR18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At Jazzland, high-flying fun rules
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 18.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The searing Louisiana sun was already cranking up
as we eagerly dashed through the gates of Jazzland theme park
shortly after 10 a.m., all crisp and fresh and ready to boogie.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve hours later, we stumbled to the car, limp and wilted,
sweaty and sunburned, the soles of our feet on fire from pounding
the concrete.
</P>
<P>
   We were flat worn out, but we loved every minute (if you don't
count the excruciating 100 seconds _ an eternity _ I spent on the
MegaZeph roller coaster).
</P>
<P>
   Jazzland opened May 20 on the outskirts of the Crescent City
expecting to attract 1.5 million visitors during its 110-day
season.
</P>
<P>
   Five themed areas _ Jazz Plaza, Kids' Carnival, Mardi Gras,
Pontchartrain Beach and Cajun Country _ feature a gumbo of rides,
shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Before there was Jazzland, there were 140 acres of marshy,
lightly wooded land below sea level at the intersection of I-10 and
I-510. The soft soil is the reason the park is built on a 4-foot
raised concrete platform supported by pilings. The 13-acre lake and
a 3.5-acre basin in the park's center are both man-made as well.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't notice the clever feats of engineering. You just
see the color-splashed rides spinning, flipping and dropping, hear
the jubilant rhythms of a roving jazz band and smell the aroma of
pizza, fried fish and spicy Creole concoctions.
</P>
<P>
   The fantasy begins in Jazz Plaza, where a sort of Disneyesque
Main Street leads from the front gate to the diamond-shaped ribbon
of concrete you follow through the park.
</P>
<P>
   My 12-year-old daughter and I got down to business in Mardi
Gras. We were variously spun, rocked and tilted on the Mad Rex and
King Chaos and fired yellow laser guns in Jocco's Mardi Gras
Madness, a ride-through fun house where the idea is to rack up
points by hitting lighted targets to ``save'' Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   Not inclined to make like bats, we passed on the Voodoo Volcano
and Krazy Krewe, both of which hang riders upside down.
</P>
<P>
   By late morning, with the temperature flirting with 90 degrees,
the Spillway Splash-Out looked refreshing. Nobody comes out with a
dry thread after sliding into Crescent City Basin in a 20-passenger
boat.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly drenched (and much cooler), we sloshed toward the
MegaZeph roller coaster, a wood-and-steel behemoth that looms over
the park.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in line for 35 minutes gave us a chance to work up
courage. When the moment of truth arrived, my daughter bolted, but
I sucked it up and hopped aboard with Laurie Trahan of Youngsville,
La.
</P>
<P>
   Up, up, up we creaked, 110 feet into the blue, then _ whoosh! _
down we went. Hanging on white-knuckled, eyes tight shut, I was
screaming bloody murder, praying it would soon be over. When we
finally came to a stop, my heart was pounding out of my chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was awesome, it really was!'' whooped my seatmate. ``It
was worth the wait in line for a two-minute ride. This is one of
the best (coasters) I've ridden in a while. I love the first
drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, my daughter and I wandered into Pontchartrain Beach, where
we were disappointed to find that the Big Easy _ the park's 90-foot
Ferris wheel _ was still being tested. Ditto the Zydeco Scream, a
boomerang coaster that takes riders through inversions and loops,
then reverses and does it all again.
</P>
<P>
   Beach Bang Up, a bumper car ride, lured my daughter. I sat this
one out to catch my breath and regain my equilibrium. I
contemplated the ups and downs of the twin towers of terror _ the
Sonic Slam, which lifts riders up and launches them to the ground
at 4.5 G's, and the Bayou Blaster, which shoots riders skyward at 4
G's, then free-falls downward.
</P>
<P>
   I instead took my chances on the Dizzy Lizzy. Imagine a Frisbee
attached to a pendulum. You're sitting on the inside perimeter of
the disc, and then the pendulum begins to swing in greater and
greater arcs as the disc spins around. Tummy-tickling and dizzying
but fun.
</P>
<P>
   We waited 30 minutes in line to ride the Pontchartrain Flyer,
which features double-seated winged aircraft that you steer to do
stalls and dives in flight at 100 feet. But it was no great thrill.
</P>
<P>
   Around the bend was Cajun Country, where we lunched on chicken
tenders and french fries ($6), a Jazzburger ($3.50), an order of
red beans and rice ($2) and giant Cokes ($3) at the Cajun Dance
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly 3 p.m. and we wanted to catch ``Jazz, Jazz, Jazz''
at Festival Hall (think Crystal Pistol at Six Flags) in Jazz Plaza.
The Broadway-style revue features seven fresh-faced young
singer-dancers who do a lively 30-minute tribute to jazz, blues,
Cajun and zydeco music. The featured performer is Tonya Boyd, whose
renditions of ``St. Louis Blues'' and ``Sweet Georgia Brown'' blew
us away.
</P>
<P>
   We backtracked to Cajun Country, where we happily found the
Zydeco Boneshakers band boogeying onstage at the dance hall
pavilion. A few hearty souls were dancing, but the heat had most
folks sitting at tables sipping cold beers or soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   The Daltons of Lafayette, La. _ Diane and Etienne and son Chad _
had driven over for the day to celebrate Chad's 10th birthday.
Chilling with them was a giant plush chihuahua Etienne had won in a
quarter-toss game at the arcade. ``Yo quiero, Jazzland?''
</P>
<P>
   Just outside the dance hall is the Cajun Market and the Roux
Gallery, which features a fine collection of works for sale by
regional artists including handmade dolls, jewelry, paintings,
pottery and folk art.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun worked its way closer to the horizon, we noticed the
line at the Cajun Pirates Show theater was shorter than it had been
all day and took our place in the queue. This three-part
audiovisual presentation about the privateer Jean Lafitte ends with
a wild ride on the high seas _ actually the rocking and lurching of
the moving platform on which we were seated. This is another
don't-miss.
</P>
<P>
   A quick dinner of red beans and rice with andouille sausage and
jambalaya at Rita's Creole Cafe, and we hurried back to Festival
Hall to see ``Jazz, Jazz, Jazz'' again. After the show ended, Boyd
motioned for my daughter and asked her if we wanted to be in the
Mardi Gras parade that caps the evening. Channa Thiel, 9, and her
uncle, Dominick Pizzutl, from nearly Chalmette _ who had visited
the park 20 of the 21 days since opening day _ had already been
selected, and we'd complete the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   So, there we were, scrambling up on the lead float _ one of six
in the procession, led by a marching brass band _ and zipping into
white satin costumes with gold sequin trim and donning crowns.
Soon, as the parade wound its way through the park, we were tossing
purple, green and gold beads into outstretched hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to be in a Mardi Gras parade for one night,'' marveled
Pizzutl, caught up in the magic of the moment. ``Anything can
happen in New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Fly round trip to New Orleans for $122 on
AirTran or Delta with a seven-day advance purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Park information: $31 a day for adults; $26 for children under
48 inches tall; $15.50 for senior citizens. Admission covers all
rides except the Skycoaster, which hoists riders 170 feet into the
air and lets them free-fall over Crescent City Basin ($25 for one;
$40 for two; $45 for three). Open daily through Aug. 20, then
weekends through Oct. 29. The park is east of New Orleans at I-10
and I-510, about 20 minutes from downtown. 504-253-8100.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  City information: 1-800-672-6124; www.neworleanscvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
