r l BC-RELIGION-FATHERS17-CO     06-16 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-FATHERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When children enter a man's life, Father's Day and every day
take on deeper meaning, even a sense of awe
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is said that, at the moment of death, a person's
life flashes before him. Kenneth Neighbors experienced a similar
phenomenon at the opposite end of life.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his son's birth, Neighbors mentally watched
little Kenneth Joseph mature from child to teenager to adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 17 or 18 years, he'll be graduating from high school,''
Neighbors said of his 34-hour-old infant. ``I look at him and think
how my mom must have felt watching us grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, a 33-year-old lawyer from southwest Atlanta, was
among new fathers visiting the maternity unit at Crawford Long
Hospital of Emory University last week. In the minutes it had taken
for a doctor to remove the baby from the womb in a Caesarean
section, Neighbors acquired a brand-new identity.
</P>
<P>
   Father, dad, daddy, papa or pops, men here on this bustling
hospital hallway know their lives will never be the same. Most are
awed by the little people who have suddenly overwhelmed their
lives. They stare, full of wonder, at every feature, from the tops
of silk-covered heads to the tiniest plump, stubby toe.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many fathers are involved in every step of the pregnancy
and birth, said obstetrician Dr. Michael Randell, 35 and single.
``It's wonderful to see women bring their spouses to prenatal
visits, see dads touch their bellies and listen to the heart tones,
see their excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching families being made ``is a great feeling,'' said
Randell, who practices at Northside Hospital. ``It's why I chose
obstetrics and gynecology.''
</P>
<P>
   A birth, even though the child is not your own, is ``a
spiritually incredible experience,'' said Dr. Andrew Toledo, 44, an
Atlanta physician who specializes in reproductive problems. ``The
more I watch what couples go through, the more I am humbled by the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a father of three teenagers, Toledo also knows that the
challenges don't end in the delivery room. ``Parenthood is tough,''
he said. ``It's not for wimps, especially in today's age. You have
to be intellectually, physically and emotionally tough to take them
on and raise them right.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatherhood ``redefines your entire self,'' said the Rev. Bill
Reeves, 29, of Menlo, Ga., ``It redefines your work. It redefines
your marriage. It really makes you value the importance of family,
to make sure they're first priority in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' wife _ also a United Methodist minister, the Rev.
Melanie Reeves _ gave birth to their first child, daughter Kinsey,
on Jan. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite mistakes, despite failures, out of God's abundant
grace, he gave us this child,'' said Reeves. Through Kinsey, Reeves
said, ``we have the opportunity to influence the world we live in.
It's just neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Neat, perhaps, but not always easy
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long-term challenge,'' said Harold Stiefel, 39, a
father of five. ``You don't just sprinkle water on them and watch
them grow. You become very aware of your own interactions. Children
do what they see, not what they're taught. What you want your child
to become, you have to be first.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiefel's family, Orthodox Jews, have a tradition that began
with their first daughter, now 12. On Friday evenings as they usher
in the Sabbath, parents and children gather in the living room to
sing traditional Jewish songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started with one kid sitting on a lap and it just became
part of our weekly tradition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The togetherness helps each child, with his or her unique
personality, to develop a sense of family.
</P>
<P>
   A child, no matter how he or she arrived into the family, is a
uniting of past and future, of ancestors and possible generations
yet unborn.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Patrick, 52, became a father when 4-year-old Ivan arrived
from Russia last summer. Unlike the fathers in the maternity unit,
Patrick had to have the recommendations of ``doctors, friends and
bureaucrats'' before he could become Ivan's dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Ivan is a happy American kid of 5 who speaks almost no
Russian but is proud of his heritage,'' Patrick said. ``He starts
kindergarten in late summer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Patrick and other men celebrating their first Father's Day
as fathers this year, the day will be very special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say thanks to God and thanks to Ivan,'' Patrick said. ``I'm
glad to be a dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
