<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-SCENE _ SANTA FE, N.M. _ First came the spy scandal.
Then the wildfire that almost swallowed them whole. Now, secret
nuclear files from Division ``X'' are missing. Over the past year,
event after event has dropped like bombs over America's Atomic
City, shaking up the isolated, orderly existence this northern New
Mexico town and its nuclear weapons laboratory have enjoyed for
more than half a century. Once the very center of the world's
scientific research, Los Alamos has become an embarrassment - and
once-proud town residents are taking it on the chin. (Guthrie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 70.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story can be found on the WAN in the Atlanta Location
with a category of Lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER _ WASHINGTON _ Marilyn Gaston, the assistant
surgeon general, talks about her experiences as a breast cancer
survivor and why African-American women such as herself have the
highest death rate of any group for the disease. On Saturday, Dr.
Gaston will be the keynote speaker at a symposium on the problem
sponsored by the Breast Cancer Resource Center. (Dart, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   DEATHPENALTY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush is just one
in a long line of public officials wrestling with his power to put
people to death. Gov. George Ryan, of Illinois, declared a
moratorium on executions and the New Hampshire legislature repealed
the death penalty, prompting a dramatic rethinking of what has
become a political cliche: that Americans want the death penalty
and that no politician can survive without supporting it. Is the
tide turning? We talk with public officials &AMP; those who monitor
public opinion. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DEATHROW _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Three death row inmates agree to talk
to the Statesman about the politics of the death penalty and their
hopes that political pressures will accrue to their benefit.
(Manfuso, Austin American-Statesman). 30. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE _ Texas A&AMP;M University has decided to suspend its
traditional bonfire before the annual football game with Texas to
give officials time to improve procedures after an accident last
year that killed 12 students. When the tradition does resume, in
2002 at the earliest, it will be much more professionally run,
Texas A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen said Friday at a news conference.
(Copelin, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
