<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Not bad for an impulse buy
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what apparently was his first foray into high-risk options
trading in 1997, Rick Lazio bagged a profit of about 600 percent in
less that two weeks on a company controlled by some of his biggest
contributors. Newsday and the New York Times reported that Lazio
spent $2,300 on securities trades in the Quick &AMP; Reilly brokerage
just before it was purchased by Fleet Financial Group. Lazio
unloaded the options for nearly $16,000 on the day Quick &AMP; Reilly
announced it was being bought by Fleet Financial. The windfall
contains some echoes of the trading success of his New York Senate
opponent, Hillary Clinton, in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   TURBULENCE IN POLITICAL BASE
</P>
<P>
   A new Los Angeles Times poll shows George W. Bush holding a
10-point lead over Al Gore. But the poll suggests Bush would face
some problems among conservatives if he chooses a running mate who
supports abortion rights. A significant number of religious
conservatives say they would be less likely to vote for Bush if he
made such a choice, while relatively few moderates say they'd be
more likely to support him. ``Bush in this election is not going to
be able to afford to alienate any of his base _ even 1 percent,''
said Colleen Parro of the Republican National Coalition for Life.
</P>
<P>
   TOO LITTLE, TOO LATE, TOO WRONG?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush mocked his rival's revised tax-cut plan today,
suggesting Al Gore was merely responding to polls and was still on
the wrong track. ``Yet another change,'' said Bush. ``What he ought
to do is release the results from the focus group he ran.'' Bush
said of his own plan, ``I thought mine was very good when I laid it
out; I still think it's very good.'' Gore had promised $500 billion
in tax relief over 10 years to help middle-class Americans pay for
tuition, buy health insurance and save for retirement, double his
earlier estimate. Bush's proposed tax cut would total $1.3
trillion.
</P>
<P>
   THREE DAYS, FIVE STATES, $5 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   After five days at his family's compound in Maine, George W.
Bush embarked on a five-state fund-raising drive expected to bring
in nearly $5 million for Republicans to wage the fall campaign.
After raising an estimated $100,000 in Portland, Maine, and about
$1 million in Boston, Bush was expected to raise another $1.1
million for Republicans today in appearances in Ohio and Kentucky,
and $2.75 million more in Florida on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   SURE, THEY PROBABLY GOT WHAT THEY DESERVED, RIGHT?
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a news conference held near the United Nations
to denounce the proposed creation of an international war crimes
tribunal, Pat Buchanan launched into an attack on Hillary Clinton,
saying that her ``liberal cop-bashing'' had encouraged the sexual
assault spree by a gang of men in Central Park on Sunday. He
suggested that the stripping, groping and robbing of several dozen
women with police allegedly failing to intervene was due, at least
in part, to declining police morale caused by criticism of police
tactics over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   BACK IN PLANTATION DAYS, THEY'D HAVE DUELED
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan lashed out at George W. Bush for removing Civil War
commemorative plaques from the lobby of the Texas Supreme Court in
Austin. ``Mr. Bush is kowtowing to the NAACP, quite frankly,''
Buchanan said in New York. ``Removal of plaques that respected and
honored Southern heritage is an act of political vandalism which
tells us that `compassionate conservatism' is but a synonym for
squishy Republicanism.'' The Reform Party candidate went on to
accuse Bush of ``sacrificing the honored heritage of the South to
the unappeasable gods of political correctness.'' The Bush campaign
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   LIDDY LOBBY PUSHES ITS MAGGIE
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole fans are putting George W. Bush on notice that
they want their woman on the Republican ticket this fall. ABC News
reports that a grassroots group of Dole supporters, Bush/Dole 2000,
is sending Bush more than 20,000 petition signatures to encourage
him to tap Dole, who endorsed Bush after dropping her own
presidential ambitions last year. Bush/Dole 2000 contends that
Dole's presence on the ticket would expand Bush's appeal to women.
Thomas Ratcliffe, the group's press secretary, called Dole a
``Southern belle Margaret Thatcher.''
</P>
<P>
   HE'S WAITING FOR THE BIG ONE
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Republican convention opened in Houston with Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry presiding, because the governor, George W. Bush, was out
of state. An estimated 16,000 people are in attendance.
Convention-goers will approve the state party's platform and select
124 delegates to the GOP national convention in Philadelphia before
adjourning Saturday. Texas first lady Laura Bush was one of the
speakers today.
</P>
<P>
   JUST ANOTHER KIND OF `GOING FOR THE GOLD'
</P>
<P>
   After months of touting this summer's Democratic National
Convention as a largely private venture that would not cost
taxpayers a cent of cash, backers of the effort now are preparing
to ask the city government for roughly $4 million _ on top of the
services Los Angeles already has agreed to provide. That represents
a significant about-face for the convention planners, who long have
compared it to the city's enormously successful, privately funded
1984 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   EMPLOYEE VS. BOSS
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Elliott should have been very happy about winning her way
into a Democratic runoff for Georgetown County clerk of court. The
only problem was the third-highest vote-getter was the current
clerk of court, Ruby Moore _ Elliott's boss. When Elliott, the
deputy clerk of court, returned to work after a leave of absence
since March 30, she was fired. ``She was waiting for me in the hall
with a letter,'' Elliott said. ``It said, `You are no longer
employed with the clerk of court's office.' '' Elliott, a four-year
employee who decided to run for the top post, beat Moore to the
runoff by 19 votes.
</P>
<P>
   HINSON VS. HINSON
</P>
<P>
   Former bedfellows make strange politics. In one of the more
dramatic Republican races of Tuesday's primary, South Carolina
state Rep. Shirley Hinson, 50, ended up in a runoff with her
estranged husband, Jimmy Hinson, 53, a high school teacher. She won
42 percent of the vote to his 32 percent. A third candidate got 26
percent. The couple's marital problems have been well-known and
include infidelity charges, alleged death threats and a restraining
order.
</P>
<P>
   10-POINT LEAD FOR CORZINE _ BUT IT'S SOFT
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Democratic Senate nominee Jon Corzine, who has spent
at least $34 million on his U.S. Senate bid so far, holds an early
10-point lead over his Republican rival, Rep. Bob Franks. The
ex-investment banker held a 43-33 percent lead in a
Star-Ledger/Eagleton-Rutgers survey. But more than 40 percent of
respondents said they might change their preference between now and
November, and only 23 percent said they were ``very sure'' about
Corzine, compared to 19 percent who were firmly behind Franks. The
poll had a 4 percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   NOT ALL REPUBLICANS ARE CREATED EQUAL
</P>
<P>
   It would seem like an easy decision for George W. Bush to
endorse the Republican challenger to Sen. Ted Kennedy (D-Mass.).
But Bush knows how to step around a political minefield. Asked in
Boston about Jack E. Robinson, the only GOPer to collect enough
signatures for a ballot spot, Bush said, ``It's hard to endorse
somebody I've never heard of.'' After some uncomplimentary news
articles, Robinson, a 39-year-old businessman, released an 11-page
list of embarrassing incidents in his life, and Republican Gov.
Paul Cellucci, who had originally backed Robinson, dropped his
support.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA GOP AVOIDS DIVISIVE FIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to avoid a divisive primary and protect their hold on
retiring Sen. Connie Mack's Senate seat, Florida Republican leaders
and Gov. Jeb Bush orchestrated a political shuffle that left Rep.
Bill McCollum as the party's likely Senate nominee and shifted his
chief opponent, state Education Commissioner Tom Gallagher, to the
race for his old job as insurance commissioner. The Democratic
candidate is Bill Nelson, the current insurance commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   BULL FOR HIS BIRTHDAY
</P>
<P>
   Logan Walters, personal aide to George W. Bush, thought he had
it made on his 26th birthday when the boss attended his surprise
party in Kennebunkport, Maine, and flew Walters' girlfriend in from
Texas. But Bush had one more gift: a new bull, named Logan, that
his cow Ophelia gave birth to at Bush's ranch in Crawford, Texas.
Walters' job is to follow Bush wherever he goes, collecting
business cards or gifts from well-wishers and snapping photos
whenever anyone has a camera. His day begins before Bush's first
meeting and ends after he's tucked into bed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
