<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-SAEKI-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS PROFILE: TED SAEKI, CHIEF OF NASDAQ JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 18) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ See this guy?'' asks Tatsuyuki Saeki, pointing to a
painting of a pastel-clad matador skewering a bull. ``That's me.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting hangs incongruously in his sleek mahogany and black
leather office. As for the bull _ his finger jabs it _ ``that's the
Japanese financial system.''
</P>
<P>
   A former senior executive at IBM Japan, the voluble Saeki, 59
and known as Ted, now finds himself on the attack as the president
and chief executive of Nasdaq Japan, which opens for trading on
June 19. It is the National Association of Securities Dealers'
biggest effort so far to go global, steering through one of the
most hidebound, idiosyncratic and bureaucratic financial systems in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, he will have radically overhauled the capital
markets here and, in the process, started nothing short of a
revolution in the way Japan Inc. functions.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, business success depended as much on cultivating
bureaucrats and bankers as on competitive edge. Acting on
government orders, bankers funneled money to the enterprises deemed
crucial to Japan's recovery after World War II. Japan's leviathans
_ its Toyotas, Sonys and Hitachis _ thrived, but untold others
found it impossible to get financing.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Japan is seeking to change that. Young companies will be
able to raise financing. Established companies that move from other
exchanges will be able to prove their mettle alongside the likes of
Microsoft and Starbucks. By the end of the year, Nasdaq Japan hopes
to allow such companies to apply for listings on a foreign section,
then let Japanese companies be traded on the American market.
``This is going to force the Japanese government, Japanese
industry, Japanese society to change,'' Saeki promised. ``This is
going to be one of those events that comes along only once or twice
every 100 or 200 years and fundamentally changes things.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are less certain. ``It depends on how active the new
market will be,'' said Kenju Ikeda, general manager of the initial
public offering department at Daiwa Securities, which is
underwriting three of the eight companies that will be listed on
Nasdaq Japan. ``If it turns out to be very active, it will be a
stimulus for changes. But right now, the possibility of Nasdaq
Japan bringing big changes is small.''
</P>
<P>
   Saeki must overcome regulations limiting small companies to
floating only a thousand shares. He must convince companies to
adopt new disclosure standards. He must woo skeptical Japanese
brokerage firms that dominate initial public offerings. He must
learn to curb his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, clean up my language,'' he pleaded in a recent
interview, having thrown officials at Nasdaq headquarters in
Washington into a tizzy over a question-and-answer magazine
interview that included the four-letter words he uses when talking
about bureaucratic obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest test so far was hammering out an agreement with the
Osaka Securities Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq's dream was to set up shop on its own, but a thicket of
regulatory requirements made that virtually impossible within the
one year its backers gave themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Osaka talks were torture, according to several people
involved. One hour before a March 15 news conference to announce
the formation of the market's board, the two sides were far apart
on five major issues. Saeki worked feverishly to resolve them,
wielding a hard-nosed analysis of the cost of failure. Ten minutes
before the conference began, all signatures were in place.
</P>
<P>
   Wrangling over complex partnership agreements was not on Saeki's
agenda a year ago when Masayoshi Son, the charismatic founder of
Softbank, rang him up and told him his future was with Nasdaq
Japan. At the time, Saeki was weighing the merits of various
ventures that would allow him to enjoy his planned retirement from
IBM Japan while leaving plenty of time for golf. (He has a handicap
of 9 and a wife, Junko, who can hold her own on the fairways.)
</P>
<P>
   But for every good retirement project that Saeki had, Softbank,
a huge backer of Internet ventures, got there first. ``All of a
sudden, I started seeing Son's shadow everywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, he had dinner with Son. He had met Son 20
years earlier and dismissed him as a dreamer. Then, in 1995, Son
startled Saeki by buying Comdex, the big computer technology trade
show.
</P>
<P>
   Saeki played golf three or four times a year with Son, and at
the 1998 dinner, Son suggested that they start Nasdaq Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Saeki demurred, but Son persisted, calling each day. Then IBM
threatened to take away Saeki's stock options if he left before the
company's mandated retirement age of 60, and he got mad. He started
thinking about how the 35 years he spent at an American company
mirrored Japan's limited role on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever noticed in those pictures they take after summit
meetings,'' he said, ``the Japanese prime minister is always
standing at the end of the line of world leaders, appearing as a
small figure in the corner of your TV screen? We Japanese are not
accepted as leaders. I know this personally, unfortunately, because
I spent 35 years at IBM Japan, and yet a Japanese has never been
elected to a senior executive job in Armonk.'' In fact, IBM
promoted a Japanese executive last November to lead its
Asia-Pacific operations, and Minoru Makihara, the chairman of the
Mitsubishi Corp., is on IBM's board.
</P>
<P>
   Saeki, who relinquished his retirement benefits by leaving
early, says he believes that Nasdaq Japan will win Japan a larger
role in the global economy. The Japanese establishment is fighting
back. Last December, the Tokyo Stock Exchange established a market
to attract entrepreneurial companies. So far it has 10 listings.
</P>
<P>
   The mere existence of the exchange, some financiers say,
confirms the impact that Nasdaq Japan and Saeki will have here.
``The fact is that this was a direct response to the threat posed
by Nasdaq Japan,'' said Karl K. Fooks, a managing director at J.P.
Morgan. ``That response, in and of itself, is a huge victory.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
