   FILM-SHAFT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Director John Singleton learned his moves from the
original ``sex machine with all the chicks,'' swaggering private
eye John Shaft. Now he's showing his appreciation by updating the
classic 1971 film for modern audiences. The new ``Shaft,'' starring
Samuel L. Jackson, opened Friday. By DOUGLAS PERRY. Story has moved
in ``e'' entetainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PERKINS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ All the talk of ``Survivor'' capturing the imagination
of TV viewers aching for something different is the silliest thing
TV critic Ken Parish Perkins has heard yet, and the most audacious
form of marketing since Paramount's latest promise that its Dr.
Laura TV show will lay off gays and lesbians. ``Survivor'' isn't
reality; it's calculated entertainment with serious implications.
By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-TOP SHOWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The season's over, the dust settled, the new fall
lineups announced, TV critic Ken Parish Perkins unveils his Top 10.
Don't agree? So sue him. By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story has moved in
``e'' entetainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER SOUNDTRACKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ From the soul/rap of ``Shaft'' to the
heavy-metal-redolent tracks of ``M:I-2,'' the summer's biggest
soundtracks are often a hodgepodge of the worthy and the woeful.
Pop music critic Dave Ferman takes a look at six of the summer's
collections. By DAVE FERMAN. Story has moved in ``e'' entetainment
