<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6087 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-HALSTON18-COX     06-16 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-HALSTON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On-track design: Halston chief knows exactly what he likes
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 18.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a good thing that the new honcho at Halston, 38-year-old
Craig Natiello, is so direct in his approach to designing simple,
slinky clothes in sensuous fabrications.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the born-and-bred New Yorker, who spent a decade
as Bill Blass' apprentice before taking the reins at Halston, gives
bafflingly indirect answers to questions about himself and his
work.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about his Fabio-length hair, for instance, and you'll
hear a circuitous soliloquy about it being ``the bane of (his)
parents'' existence,'' about it making him feel ``secure'' and how
its conspicuousness forces him to dress conservatively: ``There's
enough going on with the hair, and I guess with my voice and
personality as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as he tries to keep his personal appearance in balance, so
does Natiello endeavor to keep his clothes on an even keel. If he
designs a dress in nubby tweed, he makes it strapless. If a gown's
slit high on the thigh, the rest of the body gets fuller coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your eye can only go one place at a time,'' he explained
during a recent trunk show of his debut collection at Phipps
Plaza's Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   And if there's any designer with a singular vision, it's him.
Natiello says his ``my way'' mind-set stems from being raised an
only child and from the sort of advice he got from Blass to ``Be
yourself, and do what you like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And how do his designs differ from his mentor's?
</P>
<P>
   ``My day(wear) is a little sharper than Bill's. Bill is a
genius. But he loves mixing textures and fabrics; taking a real
man's jacket and putting it on a woman, and mixing tweeds and
checks. I can't. I'm better at shaping. My thing is creating
illusions. I can make anyone look 20 pounds thinner and 6 inches
taller. That's my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
