<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6088 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WEB-MOVIES18-COX     06-16 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-MOVIES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet is the place to find weird, wacky movie shorts or
full-length features
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 18.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dinner at the Tarantino Home.'' ``South Park Swing.'' ``George
Lucas in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most popular new movies aren't in theaters. They're
playing right now at a Web site near you.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen major Internet sites, such as www.dfilm.com,
www.mediatrip.com and www.thenewvenue.com, are virtual netplexes,
featuring independent movie shorts and sometimes full-length flicks
that film fans can watch for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like the nickelodeons'' of early cinema, says
Bruce Eisen, executive vice president of CinemaNow, the year-old
online studio offering roughly 500 features and 550 shorts, many of
them experimental independent films. In one recent week, Eisen
says, some 35,000 computer users watched movies on
www.cinemanow.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Web has become a new kind of film distributor, an emerging
player to challenge Hollywood's long-held movie industry dominance.
And many filmmakers, both across the country and in metro Atlanta,
are using the Internet to unclog conventional avenues in promotion
and fund-raising that have often kept their films off theater
screens.
</P>
<P>
   For Hollywood studios, ``there's an element of panic,'' says
Oscar-nominated director Mike Figgis (``Leaving Las Vegas,'' ``Time
Code''). ``They regard the technology and the people who come with
it like the rabble at the door of the castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very interesting scramble for Web-site territory.
It's like a gold rush. A lot of people don't know what they're
doing but know they have to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the innovative Web promotion for 1999's surprise
success story ``The Blair Witch Project,'' the studios have leapt
into Internet marketing, creating ever more elaborate Web sites to
plug upcoming films like this summer's ``The Perfect Storm'' and
``X-Men.'' That's just a part of what's happening in cyberworld.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Lions Gate Entertainment Corp., which
distributed ``American Psycho'' and ``The Big Kahuna,'' bought
Trimark Holdings, majority owner of the Internet's CinemaNow.
Blockbuster joined with the Web's AtomFilms to create Short Takes,
a section of www.blockbuster.com offering roughly 25 shorts, each
40 minutes or less, in animation, Claymation, documentaries and
live action drama and comedy. The Writers Guild of America-West
announced its first contract covering content made directly for the
Internet. Disney chief Michael Eisner formally urged Congress to
write a law requiring computer and Internet companies to include
technology to prevent content piracy off the Web. And Cisco Systems
completed the first transfer of a major Hollywood film _ ``Titan
A.E.,'' in a hefty 42-gigabyte file _ over the Internet to the
Woodruff Arts Center for a special digital projection presentation
as part of the Supercomm 2000 trade show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, our belief is you don't need to go to Hollywood to
make films anymore,'' says Franklin Lopez, 27, a free-lance
filmmaker in Atlanta and a member of Submedia, a confab of about
seven local filmmakers promoting and showing films via the Web site
www.submediatv.com.
</P>
<P>
   As Chicago Sun-Times film critic Roger Ebert has warned
Hollywood: ``The next `Blair Witch' won't be promoted online. It
will be online.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
