<P>
   NKOREA-SYRIA-REVIEW (Washington) _ It was pure coincidence that
presidential succession in Syria and the rapprochement between
North and South Korea took place the same day. But there were
profound similarities in what was happening. North Korea and Syria
are relics of another age _ dictatorships where power has been
based on internal terror and hostility to external neighbors,
threatening to explode at any time in new conflict. In both places,
power has passed from a dictator to his son, and the son shows
signs of a more modern, outward-looking approach to solving his
country's problems. By Elaine Sciolono.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTISTS-SECRECY-REVIEW (Undated) _ As secrets on nuclear
terrorism and miniaturized warheads apparently slip out of Los
Alamos National Laboratory and other federal labs, the message
would seem to be obvious: do not give dangerous secrets to
scientists. But governments need the scientists and their culture
of openness to produce weapons that are worth keeping secret in the
first place. That is why science and secrecy have clashed. By James
Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS-REVIEW (Moscow) _ By any standard measure of
democracy, political opposition is just what Russia desperately
needs. But until last week, President Vladimir Putin didn't really
have any. But now, with the jailing of Vladimir Gusinsky, Putin may
have actually stirred up some real opposition, setting the stage
for an acid test of Russia's young democracy: how is the opposition
to act, and how will it be treated? By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-REVIEW (Washington) _ To hear some in NATO talk,
Montenegro _ the last republic of Tito's Yugoslavia that remains
alongside Serbia in rump Yugoslavia _ is the unsinkable aircraft
carrier in the West's unfinished war against Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic. But last week, the carrier was given a
significant holing by Montenegro's voters, a sizable minority of
whom want to remain inside Yugoslavia. By Steve Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-CIA-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some lessons to be learned from
the recently leaked CIA history of the agency's role in the 1953
coup that overthrew Iran's prime minister and restored the shah to
power.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   STUDENT-SORTING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Lusting after the academic
successes of European and Japanese schoolchildren, American
educators in recent years have imported the idea of a rigorous
system of tests, which other countries use to cull the elite from
the merely literate. But educators here insisted that America would
instead use testing to snap schools to attention, forcing them to
raise standards for everyone. But the evidence so far suggests that
schools are employing tests to sort children, and at a far earlier
age than elsewhere. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION-REVIEW (Undated) _ Just a few years ago, lawmakers
were in full cry about the supposed dangers of immigration _ from
crime to welfare cheats to lost jobs. Yet now Congress is poised to
pass a bill that would grant visas to tens of thousands more
temporary high-tech workers from abroad. And an unlikely coalition
of business and immigrants rights groups is pushing to fling the
door open wider: to unskilled workers who could fill shortages in
hotels and on farms , and even to roll back an array of restrictive
measures passed with great fanfare in 1996. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
