<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-ISRAEL-LEBANON-A     06-16 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN SAYS ISRAELI WITHDRAWAL FROM LEBANON IS COMPLETE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Friday that
the United Nations has confirmed Israel's withdrawal from southern
Lebanon, opening the way to a more robust U.N. peacekeeping
presence along Lebanon's often troubled border with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end of the long road toward peace in the
region, but I hope it will be seen as the beginning of the end,''
said Annan, who promptly departed on a weeklong trip to a
half-dozen countries in the Middle East to discuss ways for the
United Nations to build on the achievement.
</P>
<P>
   His confirmation of the Israeli pullout, announced first to the
Security Council and then to journalists here, is significant
because it fulfills a key condition of Resolution 425, which the
council passed in 1978. It demanded that Israeli troops pull out of
territory they had just occupied in southern Lebanon to create a
security buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old resolution next authorizes U.N. peacekeepers to
help the Lebanese government restore peace and security in southern
Lebanon, enabling Beirut to reassert its lost authority.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping mission, called by its acronym UNIFIL, had
until now been largely limited to looking on _ and ducking _ while
Islamic guerrillas in southern Lebanon fired artillery and rockets
into northern Israel and the Israelis retaliated with airstrikes
and cross-border raids. The peacekeepers will now occupy fixed
positions and conduct mobile patrols along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Annan confirmed that the peacekeepers' main task now would be to
help the Lebanese government and its armed forces assume their
responsibilities along the border and throughout the area that
Israel has vacated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a happy day for Lebanon, but also for Israel,'' Annan
said. ``And it is a day of pride for the United Nations. It shows
that U.N. resolutions, when fully implemented by all parties
working together, can be the building blocks of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general's special representative in the region,
Terje Roed-Larsen, said that the peacekeeping mission would be
expanded to 5,600 troops, from the 4,400 now stationed in southern
Lebanon, in the first two weeks of July.
</P>
<P>
   Roed-Larsen, who was entrusted with handling the complex and
politically sensitive verification process, said that the Lebanese
government has already deployed 1,000 soldiers and internal
security troops in the border area.
</P>
<P>
   In his announcement, the secretary-general said he hoped that
the international community would help Lebanon rebuild its economy
in the south and re-establish ties to the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help move the whole country closer to peace and
stability,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed hope that the successful implementation of the
Security Council resolution on Lebanon would be seen by others in
the Middle East, ``especially Syrians, Palestinians and Israelis,
as well as Lebanese,'' as an incentive to move faster in
negotiating other peace treaties based on two earlier council
resolutions, which also called for Israel's complete withdrawal
from other occupied Arab land.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal from southern Lebanon got underway after Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel set a self-imposed deadline of July 7
for Israeli troops to leave there. When the Israelis started
pulling out last month, their local Lebanese allies, the surrogate
Southern Lebanese Army, collapsed, accelerating the Israeli
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Some patches of land along the border have been contested,
principally by Lebanon. A potential last-minute hitch developed
when President Emile Lahoud warned Friday that Lebanon might not
recognize the United Nations' findings if they were based on a
``fictitious'' line at variance with the internationally recognized
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will consider the Israeli withdrawal to be incomplete if it
is confined to a fictitious nonexisting line that does not reach
the existing internationally recognized frontier,'' Lahoud said in
a statement released by his office.
</P>
<P>
   But after Annan telephoned Lahoud to allay his concerns, Annan
went ahead with his Friday announcement. He is scheduled to visit
Beirut in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Roed-Larsen stressed that the United Nations is not demarcating
the border between Lebanon and Israel but merely identifying a line
of withdrawal. This has meant verifying Israel's pull-back across a
frontier imperfectly defined in 1923, with subsequent small
adjustments, according to contemporary maps.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. inspection teams in southern Lebanon visited all parts
of the 72-mile-long border to confirm that all Israeli forces had
departed. Because of the rugged terrain, the United Nations used
not only helicopter overflights by technical experts but also
ground surveys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
