A6113 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-BELLATLANTIC-GTE-NYT &LR;      06-16 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLATLANTIC-GTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC APPROVES MERGER OF GTE AND BELL ATLANTIC INTO `VERIZON' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story may be updated later.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Communications Commission on Friday
approved the merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE, clearing the final
obstacle to the creation of the nation's largest telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, which will be called Verizon, will control a
third of the nation's local telephone lines on top of 25 million
cell phone customers. The merger is the latest in a series of
mergers and acquisitions that has put the nation's telephone and
high-speed Internet system in the hands of a few huge corporations
that want to offer consumers a package of services from cable
television to cell phone and local and long distance calling.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC laid down 25 conditions for approval, designed to
promote competition and enhance local phone competition. One is
that the merged company transfer nearly all of GTE's Internet
business into a separate public corporation. Federal regulators
have approved the huge consolidation of the industry in the hopes
that a few telecommunications giants would have the capital and
expertise to roll out new technologies like high-speed Internet
service at a quicker pace. But consumer groups have raised concerns
that the domination of the industry by a handful of giants may
ultimately prove costly to consumers and discourage the kind of
innovations that accompany robust competition.
</P>
<P>
   The approval of the two-year-old deal had been expected for
months, but was delayed as regulators and lawyers for the companies
struggled over the difficult issue of permitting the consolidation
of a local telephone company, Bell Atlantic, with GTE, which has a
huge long-distance business, even though regulations now restrict
the local company from entering the long distance business.
</P>
<P>
   The problem results from GTE's Internet backbone unit, Genuity,
part of which the company is planning to sell. Under the FCC order,
Verizon would keep 9.5 percent of Genuity. But Verizon's interest
would later convert to 80 percent if Verizon ultimately won
approval to offer long distance service in the states other than
New York where it operates. (Bell Atlantic earlier this year was
given permission to offer long distance in New York, becoming the
first regional bell to win such approval, after regulators found
that the company had sufficiently opened its local market to
competition.)
</P>
<P>
   To encourage telephone competition, the FCC is requiring Verizon
to enter dozens of new markets on a tight time schedule, with
financial penalties if it fails to meet the deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals including AT&AMP;T and smaller competitors had sought through
months of lobbying to block the merger, and federal officials say
they expect a lawsuit to try to stop the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust officials at the Justice Department approved the
proposed merger more than a year ago, after the companies agreed to
sell one of their two interests in overlapping wireless telephone
systems in nine states. The divestitures included holdings in
Chicago, Houston, Richmond, Va., and Tampa, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1816EDT &QL; 
