<HEADER>
A6117 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ARREST-600&AMP;ADD     06-16 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ARREST-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MEDIA BARON ACCUSED OF EMBEZZLEMENT IS FREED FROM JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian media magnate Vladimir Gusinsky was released
from a Moscow jail Friday night, four days after an arrest that
raised alarms about the prospects for press freedom in Russia and
presented President Vladimir Putin with the first political
challenge of his young presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky, the 47-year-old head of a media empire that has at
times been harshly critical of the Kremlin, walked out of Moscow's
shabby Butyrka prison at about 10 p.m. Friday night after signing a
letter promising not to leave Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Looking both tired and agitated, Gusinsky arrived later at his
company headquarters in the center of Moscow, where after stopping
to greet reporters , he disappeared inside the building for a
meeting with his top managers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Gusinsky was formally charged with ``large scale
embezzlement'' in connection with the 1996 privatizaton of a St.
Petersburg television station, in which Media-MOST subsequently
bought 70 percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, now in its second year, has been widely seen
in Russia as a pretext for a final act in a long-running power
struggle between the Kremlin and Gusinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities have denied any political overtones to the
arrest but at a press conference Thursday in Germany, Putin said he
thought that Russia's prosecutor general had gone ``too far'' in
arresting and jailing Gusinsky.
</P>
<P>
   However, at another press conference Friday in Berlin, Putin
said he had no reason to believe that the prosecutor's office had
acted ``unlawfully.'' He also noted that Gusinsky would be eligible
for release under a recent amnesty that applies to people who have
been awarded special government honors. Putin, left Germany on
Friday for the former Soviet republic of Moldova, and returns to
Moscow on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Friday night, the prosecutor's office said that
it had accepted Gusinsky's request for release on the basis of an
Order of Friendship award, granted him by the Russian government in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Putin had stressed Thursday that he would not interfere in the
investigation which is being handled by Russia's prosecuting
authority, which is an independent office under the Russian
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Gusinsky's lawyers had expected their client to be
released today. Appearing Friday night on NTV, the television
station that is the flagship of Gusinsky's company, Genri Reznik,
one of his attorneys, scoffed at the idea of an ``independent''
prosecutor general in Russia, recalling the role played by Putin,
then head of Russia's internal security agency, in the Kremlin's
clumsy efforts last year to dismiss Yuri I. Skuratov, a prosecutor
general who tried to investigate corruption in the Kremlin and was
later exposed on state television in a sexually-explicit video
tape.
</P>
<P>
   Reznik on Friday night described the charges against Gusinsky as
an absurdity, designed to ensnare him in a lengthy and pointless
legal process with the goal of ``breaking him psychologically and
liquidating his business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gusinsky case is expected to take on political dimensions on
Wednesday when the Russian Parliament reconvenes. Some political
leaders have already said that the controversy may affect support
for the president's legislative effort to tighten the Kremlin's
control over regional governors.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the arrest has aroused protests from politicians,
journalists and business leaders, both Russian and foreign.
American Jewish leaders and 52 members of Congress had appealed to
Putin to release Gusinsky, who is also the head of the Russian
Jewish Congress.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Gusinsky case has proved to be an embarassment for Putin on
his trip abroad, where first in Spain, then in Germany, he has had
to face questions about why Gusinsky was singled out for
prosecution in a country where most business is practiced on the
edge of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Several people, including Boris A. Berezovsky, another one of
Russia's most prominent financiers and an arch rival of Gusinsky,
have noted that in the free-for-all that has passed for a free
market here, virtually all Russian business leaders have broken the
law at one time or another.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Gusinsky is pinned to an investigation into
Russian Video, a television station in St. Petersburg that was
privatized by its general director Dmitri Rozhdestvensky, who has
been in jail for two years pending a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Media-MOST have insisted that Gusinsky and his
company were not involved in the privatization of the state-owned
station. But according to newspaper accounts, the investigation has
focused on the low price Media-MOST paid for its shares in the
company _ then the equivalent of $5,000 _ and on an alleged $1
million kickback paid to Rozhdestvensky. The prosecutor's office
has said that the alleged value of property embezzled from the
state is $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Gusinsky's lawyers, the charges presented today
were vague and broad. ``What they actually mean is that all
entrepreneurial structure including Media-MOST created by Gusinsky
were created with the criminal goal of robbing the state,'' said
Reznik in a television interview. ``What is remarkable now, is that
the very fact of turning a company into a joint-stock company is
considered a crime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
