<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-U.S.-CANADA-HNS &LR;      06-16 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CANADA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CIVILIANS, NOT SOLDIERS, ARE VICTIMS OF WARS, DIPLOMAT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Canada's top diplomat, who has helped broker
several international treaties, said Friday that most conflicts now
occur within nations, rather than between them, and that casualties
increasingly are civilians rather than soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Civilians are feeling the dark side of this post-Cold War
world,'' Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy told an audience
of diplomats at the Canadian Embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, in World War I, 95 percent of the
casualties were in uniform, while in a recent civil war in the
African nation of Congo, formerly Zaire, the casualties were 95
percent civilian.
</P>
<P>
   Since the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, no country,
including the United States, can ensure its security alone,
Axworthy added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security is no longer so much about protecting the state or
increasing power now, security can only be achieved through
protecting civilians from massacres, stopping terrorism and
ensuring trade among nations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of this ``tectonic shift in world affairs,''
traditional diplomacy has been transformed from the aloof
maneuvering of leaders to protect national sovereignty to the
concerted efforts of individuals and organizations to care for
people, he declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot fight terrorism or genocide or natural disasters
without bringing together many different elements including other
countries, international organizations such as the Red Cross and,
I'd also argue, international corporations and banks,'' Axworthy
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was such a coalition _ led by Axworthy, Nobel Prize winner
Jody Williams of Putney, Vt., and others _ that persuaded more than
120 nations to sign the 1997 treaty to ban land mines even though
the United States opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has offered to sign the treaty only if it is
amended to allow the continued use of land mines along the tense
border between North and South Korea for at least 19 more years and
to allow the use of anti-personnel mines in conjunction with
anti-tank mines. Currently, the United States has nearly a million
land mines that seed the border between the two Koreas along with
about 37,000 American soldiers standing guard.So far, Axworthy
said, more than 20 million mines elsewhere in the world have been
destroyed because of the treaty. He added that 18 of the 34
countries than manufactured land mines before the treaty have
ceased production.
</P>
<P>
   Canada and Axworthy also were at the center of a push in 1998 to
establish a permanent international criminal court, once more
against the wishes of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States objected to the court because there were no
controls to make sure that it would not be used maliciously against
American soldiers and officials involved in missions like the one
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But Axworthy said Friday that the United States has ``nothing to
fear'' from the international court. ``If the court fails to
receive support, what kind of message does that send to war
criminals, and, more importantly, what kind of message does that
send to the victims?'' he asked.Axworthy said Canada and other
nations can lend moral authority to help solve global problems, but
he acknowledged that the United States as the world's only
superpower plays a pivotal role. ``If the United States is a player
it makes it so much easier,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A native of Winnipeg, Axworthy, 60, studied urban affairs at
Princeton University in the early 1960s before returning to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   He won a seat in the federal Parliament in 1979 as member of the
Liberal Party, where he staked out a leftist position in the
government of Pierre Trudeau.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, Axworthy was mentioned as a possible candidate
for prime minister. But a few years later his hopes were derailed
when he led the opposition within the Liberal Party to Canada's
first free-trade treaty with the United States. The treaty passed,
and the business community exacted revenge by denying him funds he
needed to wage a campaign to win leadership of his party.After the
Liberals returned to power in 1993 behind Jean Chretien, Axworthy
was appointed human resources minister and three years later,
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
