<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
 DEMS TRY TO AVOID MORTAL POLITICAL WOUND WITH DEATH TAX VOTE  
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ Southern Democrats
evidently believe that supporting inheritance taxes could mean
political death, making them a key group to watch if the
House-passed repeal of estate taxes draws a presidential veto.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conservative Democrats flocked to the GOP-sponsored plan to lift
estate taxes over 10 years despite complaints by President Clinton
and party leaders that the measure is mainly a windfall for the
very rich.
</P>
<P>
   The mutineers, many from rural areas, were more persuaded by
arguments that the tax was a hardship for farmers and small
business owners trying to pass their hard-earned holdings on to
their children or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is outrageous that today it makes more sense to sell a
family-owned business before death rather than pass the business to
one's heirs,'' said Rep. Bud Cramer, D-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Even a few Southerners a little farther to the left backed the
repeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``By doing what is prudent and right, we can ensure that the
lifeblood of many American families _ the small farm and the small
business _ will continue to survive,'' said Rep. Eva Clayton,
D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said while the proposal carries potent symbolism,
the GOP measure goes too far. They said present law already exempts
all but the largest estates and that a Democratic alternative to
cut estate taxes by 20 percent would assist people who need the
most help without an undue loss to the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   ``A married couple with a farm or a small business would receive
a $4 million estate tax exclusion,'' said Rep. Karen Thurman,
D-Fla., estimating 98 percent of American farmers would get relief
under the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The 65 Democrats who backed the repeal gave Republicans a
sufficient margin to override a veto. The question is whether those
lawmakers will stick with the GOP if the measure comes back or side
with Clinton out of party loyalty. The jury is out, but some
Southerners indicated they would not support the override.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reserve the right to sustain the expected presidential veto
... unless needed changes are made,'' said Rep. Bobby Etheridge,
D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT TO KNOW
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Republican Jim DeMint believes taxpayers should
get what they pay for _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker introduced legislation that would allow members of
the public to more easily get their hands on reports from the
Congressional Research Service, a congressional agency that does
important studies. Access to some of the information is now
restricted and is available online only to members of Congress and
their staffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people, students, teachers, small businessmen,
farmers should be able to get this information and facts on which
we as Congress base our decisions,'' said DeMint. He introduced the
measure on behalf of the Citizen Legislators Caucus, a group
comprised of lawmakers who agreed to limit their own terms in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT NOT TO KNOW
</P>
<P>
   Another Southern lawmaker is trying to limit the circulation of
information of the classified variety.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, the Alabama Republican who chairs the
Senate Intelligence Committee, is proposing legislation that would
make it a crime to disclose secret information to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   He and other panel members believe it will take criminal
prosecution if Washington is ever to lose its claim on being the
news leak capital of the world. The panel had a recent hearing on
the subject _ in secret of course.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the measure say it goes too far, particularly when
the government is inclined to put the top-secret stamp on documents
that don't qualify for such careful handling. The measure is
certain to run into a First Amendment fight though the bill does
not make publishing or receiving the material a crime.
</P>
<P>
   STAY IN SCHOOL
</P>
<P>
   Southern schools don't have the high dropout rates of a decade
or so ago but they show signs of slipping again, according to a new
report from the Southern Regional Education Board.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based group said that just two of 16 Southern states
_ South Carolina and Kentucky _ have dropout rates for teens 16-19
above those of 1986. But the overall regional rate crept back up to
13 percent in 1998 from 12 percent the year before. Twelve percent
is the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``States need to continue searching for ways to identify the
students who are most likely to quit school and need to provide
them with effective assistance and incentives to stay in school,''
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
