<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-BISHOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENOCIDE SURVIVORS BITTER OVER ACQUITTAL OF BISHOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ The acquittal of a prominent Roman Catholic
bishop on charges of genocide by a Rwandan court may help restore
relations between the church and the most Catholic state in Africa,
but it has also deepened bitter feelings among survivors still
waiting for justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican praised the exoneration Thursday of Augustin Misago,
the most senior Catholic official tried in connection with the 1994
slaughter of hundreds of thousands of Rwandans. The Holy See had
argued since Misago's arrest a year ago that indicting a bishop
meant indicting the church itself. Pope John Paul II took a
personal interest in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But as the news of Misago's release filtered through Rwandan
society Friday, reaction was divided. The decision comes at a
delicate time in the country's process of ethnic reconciliation.
Six years after the genocide, it is still in the early stages of
trying and punishing the murderers.
</P>
<P>
   Many Rwandans felt the church, which has given suspected Rwandan
clerics safe harbor across Europe and ignored pleas from
human-rights groups to apologize for failing to do more to halt the
bloodshed, would rather protect its image than promote healing.
Speculation spread Friday that the government, under the church's
influence, pressured the court to acquit Misago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are mixed feelings everywhere now,'' said Tarsis
Karugarama, a justice of Rwanda's supreme court. Misago was tried
by a lower tribunal. ``Quite a lot of people are feeling downbeat,
as if the decision of the court was not correct. There is no
question that the Vatican was actively involved in Misago's case.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, 1994, during the height of the genocide, Misago
traveled to Kibeho in southern Rwanda, a town in his diocese that
was the site of gruesome ethnic slaughter. Barely a month earlier,
the Hutu-extremist government called on the Hutu majority to kill
all Tutsi, a minority group making up roughly 14 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   Misago had gone to Kibeho to assure a group of 90 Tutsi
schoolchildren being held by Hutu extremists that they would be
safe. He brought policemen to provide for their security. Three
days later, the same police killed all but eight of the children.
</P>
<P>
   Across Rwanda, churches became killing fields. In two months,
according to most accounts, the Hutu killed at least 800,000 Tutsi
and moderate Hutu across the tiny central African state, which is
95 percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Under assault from every direction, even from neighbors and next
of kin, Tutsi sought refuge in the shelter of the church. In many
instances, they were tragically mistaken in doing so. According to
scores of witnesses, pastors led, or left, their parishioners to
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Among the witnesses in Misago's trial were nuns and priests who
alleged that the bishop sat in on high-level meetings as provincial
politicians planned the genocide. Neither he, nor his lawyers,
denied those claims. ``If he had refused to go, he would've been
killed himself,'' said Alfred Pognon, one of Misago's lawyers,
after the acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has never responded to appeals from survivors, human
rights groups, and Rwandan government officials to apologize for
the alleged actions of its officials. Critics call that a striking
omission in an age when Pope John II's has apologized for sins
committed by members of the church, from the Crusades to the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican declined to comment on the issue of an apology.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1998 meeting of Catholic clergy in the city of Butare,
the papal nuncio reportedly said the Vatican would not apologize
for its role in or response to the genocide, but encouraged the
faithful to testify on behalf of accused clerics. The church has
actively pressured Rwanda to remove the death penalty from its
penal code.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter a month ago, as Misago faced the death penalty if
found guilty, the pope assured the bishop that he was praying daily
for the accused cleric.
</P>
<P>
   Aloysia Inyumba, the head of Rwanda's Unity and Reconciliation
Commission, said the church should not be singled out for its
response the genocide. The commission and the Council of Bishops in
Rwanda are now working jointly on programs to promote ethnic unity.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen more Catholic officials await trial. Two priests have
already been convicted. But others have fled prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The French Catholic church protected Wenceslas Munyeshyaka, a
Rwandan priest, for several years before he was finally brought to
trial in France. Late last year, another accused Rwandan cleric was
found ensconced in a church in Florence, giving Mass under a
pseudonym.
</P>
<P>
   The London-based group African Rights has urged the Vatican to
act against nearly three dozen suspected church officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the pope in 1998, the organization wrote, ``There
is compelling evidence that a number of bishops, priests, nuns and
brothers were either complicit in genocide, or participated
directly in it. Given the scale and consistency of the accusations,
the reluctance of the Catholic church to act upon them is
regrettable. . . . The Catholic church cannot play a constructive
role in Rwanda for as long as it continues to provide sanctuary to
genocide suspects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
