<HEADER>
A6124 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CINCINNATI-ZOO0617-CO     06-16 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINCINNATI-ZOO0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Someplace like home
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ It was about 88 degrees and muggy, and little
Ganesh was anxious to get into the pool, which hadn't opened for
the day yet.
</P>
<P>
   Several times when his mother wasn't watching too closely,
Ganesh sidled up to the barrier around the pool, stuck his head
underneath and tried to reach out and touch the water.
</P>
<P>
   If he couldn't get in the pool, at least he could feel how cool
the water was going to be when he got his chance.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when you're a 2,200-pound 2-year-old, keeping cool on
a hot day is a major priority.
</P>
<P>
   Ganesh, his mother and two other Asian elephants are the
inhabitants and main attractions of the new Schott-Unnewehr
Vanishing Giants display at the Cincinnati Zoo and Botanical
Garden. And if Ganesh's reaction when he finally got to enter his
pool is any indication, the elephants love their expanded home.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanishing Giants habitat is built around the zoo's old
elephant house, where the elephants once trod day after day over
the hard-packed, nearly grassless clay soil around small enclosures
with all the charm of an abandoned gravel pit.
</P>
<P>
   Today the elephants have a half-acre compound including their
new 60,000-gallon outdoor swimming pool. With the new habitat for
giraffe and okapi, a species related to giraffe, Vanishing Giants
covers 4.3 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary reason for renovating the space was to give the
animals more room plus to simulate their native environment as much
as possible,'' said Dave Jenike, director of education for the
Cincinnati Zoo. ``The animals like it, and it lets us education
people about how the animals would live in the wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials said a contribution from Cincinnati Reds owner
Marge Schott helped make the $6 million Schott-Unnewehr Vanishing
Giants exhibit possible. The exhibit is named in honor of Schott
and her father and grandfather, Edward and Frank Unnewehr.
</P>
<P>
   The original elephant building was built in 1906 and is on the
National Register of Historic Places, so it was renovated rather
than replaced. The exterior of the building retained its original
shape, but its white walls were repainted and decorated with
ceramic tiles to mimic an Indian temple.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the building had a long center corridor with
animals displayed in cages along both sides. Now the building has
been reconfigured with small display areas just inside the
entrances for showing the animals during bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   But the emphasis is now on the outside areas surrounding the
building. The new outdoor display space was carved from areas that
were once walkways and parking lots, Jenike said.
</P>
<P>
   The top half of the elephant enclosure has a wide, grassy
plateau beside their swimming pool, and the lower end has shade
trees and a sand pit where the animals can toss sand on themselves
to discourage insects.
</P>
<P>
   For the Asian elephants as well as for the giraffe and okapi,
the zoo combined existing trees with new plants and some artificial
structures such as concrete termite mounds to give the displays an
authentic look.
</P>
<P>
   Jenike said, for example, that the okapi is a relative to the
giraffe that is native to the Ituri forest of the Congo, and the
okapi enclosure is built around a giant oak tree. ``The okapi's
native forests wouldn't have oak trees, but an oak has the same
kind of broad canopy you'd find there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we put some honey locust trees in with the Maasai
giraffes. Locusts aren't African, but they have the same leaf
structure as the African acacia. They even have thorns.''
</P>
<P>
   ALSO NEW AT THE ZOO
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Zoo is celebrating its 125th anniversary all this
year, and several new exhibits and special events are planned. In
addition to the Vanishing Giants exhibit, the zoo is opening the
Kroger Lords of the Arctic display for polar bears in July.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the zoo plans to add 125 animals to its collection in
2000 to commemorate its birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few things to look for this year:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tide's Zoo Babies: The zoo's annual series of events
highlighted recent births at the zoo began last week and runs
through July 2. The young animals are spread throughout the zoo in
exhibits marked with 7-foot wooden storks. Among the featured
babies are a black rhino, a lowland gorilla, ruffed lemurs, Jacob's
sheep, black footed penguins, egrets, roseate spoonbills and
alligator snapping turtles. On weekends, the zoo holds special
meet-and-greet days during the Zoo Babies promotion to allow young
zoo visitors to meet characters such as Paddington Bear, Batman
Beyond, Arthur and the cast of the ``Big Comfy Couch.'' A contest
is also being held to name the zoo's four recently born
Indo-Chinese tigers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wonders from Down Under: Through July 11, the zoo is hosting a
pair of koalas on loan to Cincinnati from their home zoo. The zoo
is using the koala visit to focus on other examples of Australia's
unusual wildlife such as the kookaburra, Australian walking sticks
and other birds and reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kroger Lords of the Arctic: The display, scheduled to open
July 8, features a 12-foot-deep, 70,000-gallon pool with an
underwater viewing area that will allow zoo patrons to come face to
face with the swimming bears. The 21,000-square-foot exhibit is
about twice as large as the bears' old enclosure and has five
waterfalls and a replica of a polar bear den. A small adjoining
display will feature the Russian red tree squirrel. Lords of the
Arctic will have four polar bears, including a young brother and
sister pair that zoo patrons will name in a contest that begins
June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
