<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6125 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-KIDNEY-DONOR-LADN &LR;      06-16 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNEY-DONOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIGGEST GIFT
</HEADLINE>
  When producer Jay Cohen needed a kidney, 
a total stranger just gave him one 
(For use after Mon., June 19, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
(Eds: This story is being sent to entertainment and lifestyle
wires.) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You look good, Jay.''
</P>
<P>
   The remark is delivered with gusto, and maybe a little bit of
amazement by Suzi Landolphi, a former radio talk-show host, to Jay
Cohen, producer of the just-released movie ``Boys and Girls.'' In
another context, it could be a shmooze line _ something you're
expected to say to the person who you know has been through a bad
stretch, whether or not you actually believe it.
</P>
<P>
   But when Landolphi tells Cohen he's looking good, she's being
truthful. That Cohen, a hearty, bronzed 39-year-old, now seems the
picture of good health is, in large part, Landolphi's doing. Nearly
one year ago, she gave him a kidney, which has allowed Cohen to
reclaim his health and his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, he looked so (BEGIN ITAL)bad(END ITAL) when I first met
him,'' Landolphi says. ``I never realized how bad. Every time I see
him now, I go, `(expletive), he was really, really sick.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the transplant, Cohen, who suffered from a rare
kidney disease known as Alport syndrome, had lost 30 pounds and had
seen his skin turn several shades of green and yellow from the
poisons his kidneys weren't able to filter. His days and nights
were filled with nausea, blackouts, and itching and swollen skin.
And he was having a rough time on dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   That's when an unusual thing happened: Landolphi offered her
kidney to Cohen. The two are not related, nor were they friends.
They had met once for two minutes before Landolphi offered, nine
months later, to be a donor.
</P>
<P>
   Even more unusual was that Landolphi wasn't even a proper match.
A relatively new therapeutic technique pioneered by Dr. Stan
Jordan, a nephrologist at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, has reduced
the risk of rejection and allowed Cohen to receive a kidney from
Landolphi, a non- matching donor.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen was given doses of intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG),
medication that has been used in past years to treat immune system
disorders. In this case, the medication would knock out a rare
antibody in Cohen's blood system that would likely reject a new
kidney.
</P>
<P>
   ``This opens up a big door in terms of donors,'' says Jordan,
adding that he is optimistic for Cohen's future. ``Suzi wasn't
related to Jay, and they didn't have a lot of compatibility, but
just being blood-group compatible was enough.'' As long as the two
of them were blood-group compatible.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as Landolphi was willing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was quite interesting,'' Jordan says. ``We discussed this
with her, the possibility that the kidney could be lost. It was a
big sacrifice, but she felt the most important thing was to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated in chaises next to the pool of Cohen's Tarzana home,
Landolphi and Cohen talk about those difficult days that remind
them how they can help other people know what experiences to expect
while waiting for an organ donor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people on dialysis, so many people waiting
for hearts and livers and kidneys,'' says Cohen. ``Less than 2
percent of the population is an organ donor. It's a joke. AIDS and
cancer get all the attention in the world. With kidney, heart,
liver and lungs, nobody does anything to get the research to make
transplants better or to figure out how to make the drugs better.''
</P>
<P>
   Landolphi and Cohen also banter and tease, make countless
off-color jokes, interrupt each other, occasionally disagree, but
never argue. They seem perfectly tuned in to each other's sense of
humor _ frequently of the gallows variety; and there appears to be
no boundary one or the other isn't allowed to cross.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sharing a vital organ establishes that kind of bond
between donor and recipient. Never one to crave sugary foods in the
past, Cohen is convinced he now has Landolphi's sweet tooth. When
he beats her at racquetball, Landolphi jokingly sniffs that Cohen
``got the fast kidney.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such a bond wouldn't be easy to research. The number
of people who have been living organ donors is slim enough. Rarer
still is a donor who isn't a relative of the organ recipient
(immediate relatives have the best chance of being a genetic
match).
</P>
<P>
   Almost a year after the transplant, Cohen has weathered one
substantial rejection and is back to his pre-illness routines. A
combination of 30 pills a day _ down from 50 _ has his system on
the right track. The medication _ which includes three
immunosuppressive drugs, steroids and vitamins _ raises his blood
pressure and reduces muscle mass. So Cohen has to work out to
maintain his weight and strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't gain weight no matter what. I could sit and eat all
day long and not gain weight,'' said Cohen, who now tips the scales
at 178 pounds. ``The good news is I have a whole new diet plan to
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen knows that he may need dialysis and another transplant in
the future, and you get the idea that if Landolphi had an extra
kidney, she'd go through the entire process again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can donate is half my liver,'' says
Landolphi, ``and I'm saving that for my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Landolphi's generosity of spirit talking, but it's also
her practical nature. To hear Landolphi tell it, she was able to
help a person in need. The question isn't why would she choose to
give up a kidney, but why (BEGIN ITAL)wouldn't(END ITAL) she?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a huge, big deal. I just felt capable of doing it,''
said Landolphi, 50, whose husband, David, was also willing to give
Cohen a kidney. ``There's something about being a living donor.
There's probably a mindset that makes you able to do this easily.
It doesn't make me better. It's just a mindset I happened to
have.'' Landolphi's decision had nothing to do with any bond
between her and Cohen _ that came later. She and her husband met
Cohen once at a mutual friend's wedding _ an event that Cohen had
to leave after 45 minutes because it was his second day off
dialysis and he was feeling sick.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, the Landolphis heard regular reports
about Cohen's condition. Later, upon learning Cohen had ended up in
the emergency room and had almost died, Landolphi started thinking
that she might be able to help. A week later, she told her husband
she was going to offer Cohen one of her kidneys. David Landolphi,
it turns out, had been thinking about making the same offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Landolphis called their doctor and then their daughter. Then
they called Cohen, who was prepared to nix the idea. Two earlier
donors had already backed out _ one two days before the transplant
was scheduled to take place _ and neither Cohen nor his wife,
Laura, was anxious to be disappointed a third time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dead against it; the hospital didn't want to do it,''
said Cohen. ``There are liability issues, questions about, `Why is
she doing this?' 'What did he promise her?' For me, I just didn't
want the guilt. I didn't want that responsibility. It was my life,
and I was either going to deal with it or I wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Replies Landolphi, ``That's such a wonderful, admirable value _
`I'll take care of my own problems and my own family,' but it's not
really realistic. We're put on this earth to take care of each
other. You can't do anything on your own today, and neither can I.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our success has helped Cedars get over some of their
fear about using live donors,'' she adds. ``A live donor is
physically better than a cadaver.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
