<SLUG> BC-TWA-AIRTRAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA AND AIRTRAN ARE IN MERGER TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of struggling Trans World Airlines Inc. and financially
strapped AirTran Holdings Inc. rose Friday after it was revealed
that the two airlines were engaged in merger discussions. But
people close to the talks said there was little chance of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If AirTran is going to buy TWA, it is going to need money,''
said an investment banker who has talked to both companies. ``I
don't see how they are going to do that other than with junk bonds,
and the junk-bond market is very weak right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Once one of the United States' leading airlines, TWA has seen
its fortunes decline in recent years as it sold its international
routes and focused on its hub in St. Louis. The airline was in
bankruptcy twice during the 1990s, and it continues to lose money
while other airlines are profiting from the booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has been searching for a buyer for some time, according to
industry insiders. But despite a young fleet of planes and
operational improvements that have the airline leading the industry
in on-time arrivals, there has been little interest from major
carriers, because TWA's financial and labor woes are seen as much
bigger than the strategic value of its route network.
</P>
<P>
   TWA would not say whether it was talking to AirTran. ``We have
had and continue to have conversations with many airlines about
possible business transactions,'' Mark Abels, TWA's spokesman, said
Friday. ``And we are always open to a transaction that makes sense
for our employees and shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   An AirTran spokesman also declined to confirm any talks, which
were reported Friday by the Atlanta Journal and Constitution and
The Wall Street Journal. However, Leslie Head, AirTran's vice
president was quoted in the Journal and Constitution as saying that
the talks were ``preliminary'' and that AirTran would be the
acquirer if there was a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers and analysts found that difficult to believe.
AirTran had only $100 million in cash at the end of the first
quarter. Last month Boeing Co. agreed to slow its delivery of 48
100-seat 717 jets to AirTran in order to give the carrier some
financial breathing room. AirTran also faces the challenge of
repaying $230 million in junk bonds due in April.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of TWA rose 31.25 cents, to $2.875, while AirTran shares
jumped 25 cents, to $4.5625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
