<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6145 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-Q&AMP;A-$ADV18-NYT     06-16 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-Q&AMP;A-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO EXPECT AT PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 18)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to turn a Ford into a Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is what a lot of investors expected would happen at
Procter &AMP; Gamble, the $40 billion consumer products giant, after
Durk I. Jager was installed as chief executive about 18 months ago.
Jager had committed the company to shifting out of cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   But some people on Wall Street now think that he nearly stripped
the gears. Procter missed its higher earnings estimates for the
last couple of quarters, and its stock is down nearly 50 percent so
far this year. This month, Jager resigned.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves A.G. Lafley, his successor, in a tough spot.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Hay, an analyst at Merrill Lynch, took some time last
week to talk about the company and its prospects. Following are
excerpts from the conversation: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some have argued that Durk Jager was victimized by Wall
Street, which wanted and expected Procter &AMP; Gamble to grow faster
than it realistically could. Do you agree? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Most companies have become much more sensitive to the demands
of their shareholders, and Procter is no exception. It had been
viewed as a slow-moving, ponderous kind of company, and Wall Street
was pushing for change.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, money managers have very short time horizons, and
companies are judged on 3-month, 6-month and 12-month results,
which are the same periods they themselves are judged.
</P>
<P>
   Given their size and sizeable market shares, Procter faces a
unique challenge. But in a perfect world you want to see the
company continually raise the bar. They have resources others
don't.
</P>
<P>
   If you are big it is hard to grow, but size gives them a
remarkable ability to negotiate with their suppliers, which means
they can keep costs lower than competitors. And they have more
leverage with retailers, which should give them an ability to get
new products on the market quicker than a small, untested company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So you were surprised that Durk Jager stepped down?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I was surprised it happened so quickly. Given the scope of
what he wanted to do, I would have thought there would have been a
little more time. There was such monumental organizational change
going on that it shouldn't have been judged in a short time frame.
</P>
<P>
   Procter's culture is very deliberate. Decisions don't get made
off the cuff. There is a lot of research and thinking devoted to
each move, and it might be somewhat more inward-looking than most
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Durk's job was to come in and shake it up a little bit. That
happened, but the outcome was not what they expected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What sort of changes was Jager trying to effect? And what is
going to survive? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Among other things, the company's reporting structure was
changed, and so were people's responsibilities and titles. At the
same time, the organizational mind-set was being changed to be more
risk-tolerant and fast-paced. I don't think they will undo the
change in organizational structure. And while they might encourage
a modest amount of risk-taking, they will be a little bit slower to
implement it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But hasn't Procter's performance been hindered by more than
just the effort to change its culture? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. While you have all this internal movement, outside of the
company raw-materials prices were rising and the euro was
plummeting against the dollar. Also, its product categories are
very mature. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you expect things to change with Lafley in charge? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Given his history, I think Lafley will focus on Procter's
core businesses and get out of things that are tangential. That
means that on balance they would be less likely to acquire
something than they were under Durk Jager. A bid for a food
business like Nabisco, for example, would surprise me.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Lafley strikes me as someone who will be more like the
Procter of old, someone who will make everyone feel more
comfortable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does the company need to do to get upward movement in
its stock price?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Procter has some issues that are unique to Procter, but the
environment is a tough one for household products.
</P>
<P>
   Given the current earnings outlook, I think the stock is pretty
fairly priced.
</P>
<P>
   But if Lafley can put together a credible plan, with objectives
people think are realistic, that will help.
</P>
<P>
   I really hope they lower their revenue and earnings targets.
Right now, I think they are stretch goals.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven percent growth in earnings is more realistic than their
current estimates of 13 percent to 15 percent. And top-line growth
of around 5 percent, while they are saying 6 percent to 7 percent,
is a credible revenue number. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there any new products in the pipeline that have the
potential to create lots of incremental growth? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. They have a lot of really interesting, technologically
innovative new products. But Procter is a $40 billion company, and
it needs a lot of them. There is not one that will move the dial
for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
