<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BAPTISTS-MERRITT0617-     06-16 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-MERRITT0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Baptist leader's church refuses to stand pat
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gather together its membership and First Baptist
Church of Snellville, Ga. is nearly as big as the city it calls
home.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15 years that the Rev. James Merritt has pastored the
church, membership has grown from 500 to nearly 11,000, just a few
thousand short of Snellville's population.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing Merritt's evangelical success, the Southern Baptist
Convention elected him president this week in Orlando. Merritt's
conservative views mesh well with the SBC.
</P>
<P>
   What's most striking about First Baptist's growth, say its
members, is that Merritt hasn't compromised his traditional Baptist
beliefs to gain congregants.
</P>
<P>
   ``He speaks straight from the book,'' said 42-year-old Mike
Ridgeway, a George W. Bush man, according to the bumper sticker on
his white Ford truck. ``There's none of this riding the fence
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when churches are struggling with progressive trends
toward the acceptance of homosexuality and a liberal reading of the
Bible, First Baptist remains firmly conservative _ the Bible is
infallible, homosexuality is sinful and divorce is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty agree with that message, especially in the largely
Republican area of Snellville. With a $6 million annual budget,
First Baptist is the county's second largest church in membership,
and it employs 75 people full-time. More than 4,200 worshipers pass
through the church on Sundays. Merritt's evangelical message and
beliefs have taken First Baptist into the ranks of metro Atlanta's
so-called megachurches.
</P>
<P>
   From busy U.S. 78, though, First Baptist could easily go
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring a Huddle House and surrounded by strip shopping
centers, the church's traditional red brick and white columns are
nearly lost within Snellville's congested commercial heart. The
church's tall steeple struggles to stand out among the fast-food
signs below.
</P>
<P>
   But First Baptist's parking lots betray its true scope. As if
marking a marathon route, a yellow line guides guests from the
street across acres of blacktop to various parking areas in the
rear. A Disney-like tram shuttles worshipers from the lots to the
sanctuary for one of four Sunday services and a university-sized
array of Bible study classes.
</P>
<P>
   While adults worship in the main sanctuary, children pass
through the mural-covered hallways of a three-story classroom
building that stretches back like a giant multiplex theater. The
pastoral scenes color every inch of wall space in certain areas.
Scenes depict Joseph and Mary, and a kneeling Jesus surrounded by
children.
</P>
<P>
   In the children's worship suite, kids watch puppet shows staged
in King's Town, a set made of colorful wooden facades. Teens listen
to Christian rock bands and pray in a room that looks much like a
nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you offer something of quality to a child, parents will
come,'' said Matt Wethington, minister to Church Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, that's the point. In true evangelical spirit,
Merritt has created a church that uses its facilities to ``bring
people to God,'' Wethington said.
</P>
<P>
   Music is important to that end. First Baptist's choir rehearsal
room is as big as some churches. A music school sponsored by the
church serves more non-members than members.
</P>
<P>
   But despite its success, First Baptist's ever-expanding outreach
programs are always looking for the next frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The church spends thousands of dollars a week to buy television
air time for Merritt's Sunday sermons, which are taped in a modern
sanctuary that includes an orchestra pit. An independent production
company the church founded edits the film at a high-tech studio
within First Baptist. The sermons are broadcast on local
television, and nationally on the Trinity Broadcasting Network and
on Family Net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
