<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ITALY-POPE-GUNMAN-NYT     06-16 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-POPE-GUNMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE'S ATTACKER SAYS HE WAS ONLY A PAWN IN '79 KILLING OF TURKISH
EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ In a brief but tumultuous court appearance
Friday, Mehmet Ali Agca, the gunman who shot Pope John Paul II,
declared that he was ``just an actor'' in the plot that led to the
1979 slaying of one of Turkey's most prominent newspaper editors.
</P>
<P>
   It was Agca's first public statement since he arrived in Turkey
early Wednesday morning. He had spent 19 years in an Italian jail
after being convicted of shooting the pope in 1981, but was
released and sent home after John Paul appealed to the Italian
authorities on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Agca was arrested in 1979 soon after the slaying of Abdi Ipekci,
editor of the daily newspaper Milliyet, but escaped from his
high-security prison before he could be brought to trial. He was
convicted of the murder in absentia and sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence was later commuted to 10 years imprisonment. Under
Turkish law, Agca (pronounced AH-jah) must now serve that sentence
minus the 158 days he served before escaping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not the killer of Abdi Ipekci,'' Agca shouted in the
Istanbul courtroom where he was brought for formal confirmation of
his sentence Friday. ``I am just an actor. I was playing the role
of a killer in that scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   After the presiding judge said he was considering new charges
against Agca for armed robbery and other crimes, the prisoner
called out: ``I am innocent. The robbery and extortion stories,
they are all fairy tales. I am innocent, definitely innocent. I
swear it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the judge ordered him to be silent, he appeared chastened
and said he was overly excited after returning to his homeland.
Soon afterward he was returned to his solitary cell, which is in
the same prison from which he escaped more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Special security measures have been imposed at the prison to
assure that people who may want to silence Agca are not able to
approach him. His cell is under continuous video surveillance, and
everyone entering the adjacent corridor is subject to fingerprint
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Streets around the courtroom were blocked off Friday during
Agca's appearance. Heavily armed security officers surrounded the
building, and sharpshooters were posted on nearby roofs. A handful
of demonstrators chanted slogans demanding that investigators find
the ``hidden hands'' that the demonstrators presume to have been
behind Agca's crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Agca was one of the ultranationalist gunmen who threw Turkey
into chaos in the late 1970s. In 1979 hardly a day passed without a
bombing or shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The military staged a coup the following year. There has been
much speculation that the terror was fomented by obscure forces
seeking to create a climate so frightening that such a coup would
be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   This and various other theories about the terror campaign in
which Agca participated have been revived by his sudden
reappearance here. Many Turks are wondering whether he can be
induced to reveal who ordered him to kill Ipekci.
</P>
<P>
   In the months before he was slain, Ipekci had written columns
attacking far-right groups, and others suggesting that heroin
smugglers were working with high-ranking security officers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ipekci is considered a martyr, with streets and parks
named after him in nearly every Turkish city.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the greatest newspaperman of the 20th century in
Turkey,'' said Haluk Sahin, a prominent columnist and television
news director. ``He made Milliyet a major credible newspaper by
introducing modern standards of journalism for the first time in
this country. The Turkish press has lost ground since his death. In
that sense he may have been a well-chosen target.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0232 </DOCNO>
