<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-GERMANS-HATRED-BOS &LR;      06-16 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANS-HATRED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITONS HOLD ON TO WORLD WAR II HATRED OF GERMANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARAZION, England _ Two weeks ago, Gabbi Muller wasn't too
surprised when a group of English people called the German high
school students she had brought to Cornwall a bunch of Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Muller, a teacher, knew there is latent hostility to Germans in
Britain, especially among those old enough to remember World War II
and the Blitz. What stunned and saddened Muller, and even some
Britons, was that a group of adults were encouraging some young
children to hurl stones, water balloons, and obscenity-laden
epithets at her and her students.
</P>
<P>
   While stories of British heroism and resilience during World War
II are passed down the generations, so, too, is hatred of Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Today, that disturbing blend of patriotism, jingoism, and
bigotry will reach a crescendo as England takes on Germany in the
European soccer championships being played in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   While English soccer hooligans don't need an excuse to hate the
Germans, they have plenty of inspiration, much of it emanating from
the mainstream media. Last year, the Sunday Times ran a magazine
cover story in which A.A. Gill, the newspaper's restaurant and TV
critic, wrote, ``We all hate the Germans. Come on, it's all right,
admit it, we're all agreed, we hate them.''
</P>
<P>
   While meant to be humorous, many Germans, and even some Britons,
considered the piece as racist as any propaganda produced by
Hitler's Third Reich. The then-German ambassador to Britain,
Gebhardt von Moltke, said he thought the article promoted the kind
of xenophobia that inspires verbal and physical attacks on Germans
in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   As he was preparing to leave his London post, von Moltke
delivered some parting shots, lamenting that British newspapers
``characterize us as Huns and Krauts who eat bratwurst and take the
best seats around the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   While relations between Britain and Germany as good, von Moltke
said, there needs to be greater ``recognition by the public and
some of the media that today's Germany is a modern, open, and
democratic society which differs fundamentally from the one of the
1930s and 1940s.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Moltke said hearing Britons dismiss him and his countrymen
as Nazis was especially hurtful _ two of his uncles were executed
after they attempted -- and failed -- to assassinate Hitler in
1944.
</P>
<P>
   While the perception is that soccer hooligans are often poor and
uneducated, research by British police has found that some are
actually middle-class, with good jobs, wives, and children. So are
some of those who mouth anti-German sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a pub in a comfortable neighborhood in North
London, an English lawyer and father of three said he had no
sympathy for the German tourists who were attacked in Cornwall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serves them right, the Nazi bastards,'' said the lawyer, who
only a few months ago lamented that the former Chilean dictator,
Augusto Pinochet, was allowed to escape prosecution for crimes
against humanity. The lawyer explained that many members of his
family died fighting the Germans in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   While others who suffered at the hands of the Third Reich have
gone out of their way to reconcile with the Germans, most notably
the French, the British have remained the coolest in western
Europe. Sir Roy Denman, the former European Union ambassador to
Washington, says that attitude has influenced Britain's ambivalence
toward European integration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British look at how well the Germans and the French get on
and it bothers them,'' says Denman, who argues Britain should be a
leader of the European Union alongside France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Denman believes the British attitude toward Germans and the
European Union is greatly influenced by its wartime experience.
While the Germans rolled across Europe, conquering and occupying
all in their path, only Britain held out. Londoners withstood the
Blitz, and the Royal Air Force fiercely defended against a
threatened German invasion in the Battle of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Denman says that history has led many Britons to conclude they
can stand alone without Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Gross, a spokeswoman for the German embassy in London,
said the attack on the German tourists was not unique, but
``neither are such attacks widespread or common.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross said the embassy had received telephone calls and letters
from English people saying they were outraged by the most recent
attack. ``Basically, they were apologizing for the behavior of some
of their countrymen,'' said Gross.
</P>
<P>
   But Muller, the German teacher who brought her students to St.
Michael's Mount in Cornwall, one of England's most famous
landmarks, said the episode was not an isolated act of intolerance.
She and her students were subjected to verbal abuse almost every
day of their weeklong visit to southwest England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the nightclubs and pubs and in the street,'' she said.
``We are German bitches and Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Smith, a spokeswoman for the Cornwall Tourist Board,
apologized to Muller's group, and called the attacks an aberration.
She insisted that Cornwall welcomes German tourists, who make up
one of the largest national groups to visit England every year.
Smith acknowledged she was deeply disturbed by the coaching the
children received from adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children appear to have been encouraged by their
parents,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gross, the German embassy spokeswoman, stressed that she
believes anti-German bigots here are a small minority. In fact, she
said a group of English and Germans planned to watch Saturday's big
soccer match together at a pub on the south bank of the Thames
River. The pub overlooks the HMS Belfast, a British warship that
did much to help end the war.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Henderson, the gentlemanly cricket correspondent for The
Daily Telegraph, may have surprised some of his readers on
Wednesday when he wrote that he would be cheering for Germany. He
said he is repulsed by those who, claiming to love England, insult
foreigners and even English players like David Beckham, who was
heckled viciously by English fans after Portugal beat them last
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``English football has become a revolting, festering sore,
bedevilled by poor standards on the field and unacceptable
nationalism off it,'' Henderson said. ``So come on, Germany. Don't
disappoint us true patriots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
