<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-DIV-OLY-LINGAMFELTER0     06-16 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIV-OLY-LINGAMFELTER0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lingamfelter spring boards into the future
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For onetime high school star Jenny Lingamfelter,
the upcoming U.S. Olympic diving trials are more than a just a
chance to win a trip to Australia. They're a huge fork in the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't make the Olympic team, medical school in San
Antonio starts in July,'' said the1999 NCAA 1-meter springboard
champion. Lingamfelter, who would be enrolled at the University of
Texas Health Science Center, has wanted to be a doctor since she
was 5. Yet, she wouldn't mind putting that particular dream on hold
for another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I want to make the Olympic team is that I'm not
ready to quit diving,'' she said. ``If I've only got two more weeks
in the sport, knowing that I have to retire is going to make me
much more upset than knowing I didn't make an Olympic team. I would
love to make the Olympic team, it would be a really great honor,
but mostly it would allow me to keep doing this a little bit
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Diving is something Lingamfelter has done very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's one of our best chances for an Olympic medal,'' said
Southern Methodist Coach Jim Stillson. ``She's a very technically
proficient diver with real good line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is really one of the beautiful divers in the air, very
graceful,'' said Hongping Li, Lingamfelter's coach at the Pan
American games, where she earned a silver medal on the 3-meter
springboard.
</P>
<P>
   Yet her grace in the air, in a way, belies the struggle it often
has been for Lingamfelter to practice her art. A record-shattering
performer as a high school phenom here, she was injured much of her
college career and only now might be approaching her true
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Like many divers, Lingamfelter got into the sport after doing
gymnastics, which she started when other kids her age were doing
daycare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the kind of child that you couldn't keep from bouncing
all over everything. I would try a forward roll off the couch, a
cartwheel over the ottoman or use the back of the couch as my
beam,'' she laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries, however, eventually kept her from progressing in that
sport and she turned to diving when she was 10. It was soon
apparent that she had found her special niche.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Lingamfelter won two state championships and was
kept from a third only by an accident. She won her first title as
sophomore, coming within a few points of breaking the state's
scoring record of 485 points set way back in 1972. The next year
she shattered that 22-year-old record, and the 500-point barrier,
winning with 510.5 points. Then in her senior season, right before
the state meet, she fractured a toe when she clipped the board on a
practice dive.
</P>
<P>
   Lingamfelter's success _ she was named national high school
female diver of the year _ came in spite of some physical problems.
She has scoliosis, curvature of the spine. Luckily, it curves in
two places in something of an S and balances out so that her hips
and shoulders are level. Still, the condition is a big reason she
competes only in springboard events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped doing tower when I was 15 or 16. The impact of
diving 33 feet alone is pretty difficult on the body. Since my back
was not straight I believe I absorbed even more on an impact,''
Lingamfelter said. ``A lot of this sport is muscle memory, and if
you take a couple of days off and come back, sometimes you're like
a whole different person. I would dive platform, then the back
would start hurting and then I'd take a day or two off and I felt
like it would take the whole week to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it finally felt good it was time for the next tower
practice. It was kind of a cycle for a while and my springboard
diving had gone downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   Lingamfelter dived for the Texas Diving Club, and her parents
graduated from the University of Texas. Yet, when it came time to
pick a college, she chose a smaller school, Southern Methodist.
There she worked with Stillson. After her freshman year they made a
decision to upgrade her dives with some more difficult ones,
perhaps sacrificing some short-term success with the hope of
eventually doing better on the international scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's doing the same dives that the Chinese and Russians are
doing,'' Stillson said.
</P>
<P>
   It was about that time, however, when Lingamfelter began
experiencing pain in her left shoulder. It was so loose that at
times it would almost feel detached from her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always a danger of it coming out of the socket. Both
of us were very nervous about trying to push my training too hard
and having my shoulder break down. We trained as hard as we could,
but still we were very careful,'' Lingamfelter said. ``But it's not
a good feeling to go to practice and have to sit on the side and
watch or go home.''
</P>
<P>
   She coped with it for two years and won the 3-meter event in the
spring national championships in 1998. Later, she had surgery in
May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the anterior ligaments was so stretched out that it
wasn't really doing what it was meant to do. It's meant to hold the
bone in the socket,'' Lingamfelter said. ``They reconstructed that
ligament and then what is typically done to people who have
shoulder injuries and whose shoulders are too loose, they shrink
the capsule by heating it. It's similar to cooking a steak, when
you cook it, it shrinks up. ``
</P>
<P>
   She didn't do a dive until September and it was late December
until she could do all her dives. In some ways, it was like
starting over. For years she'd been compensating for her shoulder.
Suddenly, she felt out of balance. She had trouble diving straight.
</P>
<P>
   Things were corrected sufficiently by the NCAA championships in
1999. There, in addition to her first place on the 1-meter, she
took third on the 3-meter. Not long after that high point and three
days after her 22nd birthday, however, Lingamfelter's 50-year-old
father, Pete, died from complications following a kidney problem.
</P>
<P>
   Lingamfelter was devastated, but continued diving.
</P>
<P>
   She once said, ``That was a low point in my life. My body was
going through the motions, but there was no coordination at all,
and it was like I forgot how to dive.''
</P>
<P>
   She finally pulled out that slump with her silver-medal
performance in the Pan American games. For the past year she's been
healthy and training harder than her body would allow her to do
before. Although she had a couple of disappointing performances
this winter she should be ready for the trials and whatever
follows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think Olympics until a couple of years ago. My love
is for the sport, the people, the competition and the places that
we get to go. The Olympics is a dream for me, like it is for
everyone else, but it's not my only goal,'' Lingamfelter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't make it my life hasn't changed at all. I'm still
going to go to medical school. None of my other life goals are
going to be affected . . . This year, looking toward the Olympics,
seeing the pressure that different people have put on themselves,
has made me try harder to put my life in perspective. Throughout
most of my career diving has been a very big part of my life. It is
right now. But I think I've done a pretty good job of preparing
myself for a life beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1847EDT &QL; 
