<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-DIV-OLY-DUMAIS0617-CO     06-16 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIV-OLY-DUMAIS0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sibling rivalry with a twist
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The apartment is shared by three cats, Tiger,
Squeak and Junior, who presumably always land on their feet, and
three brothers who always land on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Troy, Justin and Brice are three-fifths of the diving Dumais
family, which also includes younger sister Leanne and younger
brother Dwight. The Dumais are the Jackson Five of their sport.
Troy, who looks as much like a surfer as a diver, is the Michael
Jackson-talent of the family, minus all of Michael's quirks. A
University of Texas sophomore, Troy won a record 19 national junior
titles and has been compared to four-time Olympic gold medalist
Greg Louganis.
</P>
<P>
   Justin, who quietly transferred to UT this year, is the eldest
Dumais sibling. He's not exactly the Jackie Jackson or Tito of the
group, but he has been the Other Brother. In spite of his own
impressive accomplishments in and out of the pool, he's had trouble
escaping from Troy's long shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still gets to me every once in awhile,'' Justin said.
``Troy is great at diving. That's his thing. But how Troy is with
diving, that's how I was with school. I never really had to study.
It just came to me. No one really got to see my area of expertise.
It was you had a 4-point, whatever. I didn't even care because I
was so focused on diving.''
</P>
<P>
   With a quick shrug Justin adds, ``It's made me stronger. A lot
of other people might have quit because they couldn't have dealt
with it, but I'm starting to make my own name now. For the Olympic
trials I've gone from a dark horse to being a serious player.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin and Troy are pointing for the U.S. Olympic diving trials
that begin Tuesday in Federal Way, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, Justin is the only Dumais brother in
the pad, having taken a much-needed day off from practice. Tiger is
the sole cat creeping around on the black leather couches and
occasionally knocking something over on the desk. The others
felines are staying out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   Justin is sitting, but not sitting still. He can't. Like Troy,
he's all quick-twitch energy. He has to move his fingers. Or his
toes. Something, anything. There's nothing he likes better than an
adrenaline rush like he gets from diving off a tower. And he has
just finished watching a documentary of the flying Thunderbirds on
the piece de resistance of the apartment, a $3,000, 43-inch TV with
DVD players and stand-alone speakers that are higher than a 1-meter
springboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do anything little. I guess it's our personalities,''
Justin said. ``We almost got one of those flat screens ones, but
the biggest they made them was 36 inches and that just wasn't big
enough. This is big enough where it fits the apartment, but not
like obnoxiously 61-inch big.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy and Justin went in on the video system and have been living
together for this year and boarding Brice, who attends Southern
Methodist, for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   GOT ALL THAT?
</P>
<P>
   Not all that long ago, even the same state wasn't big enough to
hold Troy and Justin. Troy ended up at UT in part because it wasn't
the University of Southern California. That's where Justin enrolled
earlier and where the Dumais' longtime coach, Jeff Shaffer, was
entrenched.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Dumais drove daily from Ventura to Los Angeles to
work with Shaffer. First it was Troy and then Brice.
</P>
<P>
   Justin recalled, ``I was always forced to go and watch the
practices. My mom wanted us out of the house. I'm sure we were holy
terrors. I mean, look at us now. You can't get Troy or me to shut
up at all. Dad took us to practice. I just had to sit there and
watch. I probably got pretty fed up with that. I thought I may as
well try diving, too. It takes serious commitment. Diving is 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really had a typical high school experience. We went
to school, and then we drove three hours a day to and from
practice. We'd do homework in the car and pass out when we got back
and then do it all again the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to pick a college, Troy decided it was more
important to get away from the constant comparisons with his
brother than to stay with the same coach. UT was a nice fit for
him. Then, this past year, Justin and Shaffer had something of a
falling-out and Justin grew dissatisfied with some things at USC.
</P>
<P>
   Justin related, ``I didn't have anyone to dive with, no one to
work out with. That was the major consideration. That's how Troy
and I had gotten so good in the first place. We always had each
other to push. Everything was a competition. Everything still is,
and that's not always a good thing. But that's what has made us so
good.''
</P>
<P>
   So in the fall, Justin decided to join his brother and work
under Texas Coach Matt Scoggin. Justin misses the beach, and his
surfboard has been retired to a wall in his room. Still, he said,
``I like the atmosphere out here. People are so friendly. It's a
lot different than L.A. We're living a lot better here. I'm 21 and
taking care of myself and most of my major, steppingstone
performances have come since I've moved here.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, he finished sixth on the 3-meter springboard in an
international field in a World Cup event in Germany. Later that
month he won the three-meter competition in a strong American field
at the Sunshine Diving Invitational in Fort Lauderdale. Yet, the
progress has not come easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past six months have been quite an ordeal. A month and one
half ago I was ready to quit diving, to hang up the Speedo. Diving
had gotten to be a chore,'' Justin said. ``I've said I'll go
through anything to make that Olympic team. This may be God's way
of saying, I'm calling your bluff.''
</P>
<P>
   SLEEP? WHAT'S THAT?
</P>
<P>
   Justin, who was on an academic scholarship at USC, transferred
to UT in the fall and couldn't get an athletic scholarship to UT
for this season. He sat out this year and has two years of
eligibility left. To make ends meet, Justin worked three jobs in
the fall, parking cars for a valet service, interning at an
investment firm and coaching girls diving.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a mess. I was sleeping three hours a night,'' Justin
said.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 a.m., he'd get up for morning workouts, then grab a bite
and maybe a short nap. Then it was time for classes, followed by an
afternoon workout. Then he hit the weights and did his coaching. At
night he parked cars at some of the city's trendier night spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm big on schmoozing. That's what I'm good at,'' he said. ``I
get maybe a minute or two to interact with the customers and that's
when you make or break your tip.''
</P>
<P>
   After parking cars it was time for some homework and bed by
maybe 1 or 2 a.m. Then, it was up at five to start again.
</P>
<P>
   That insanity ended after the fall, but winter brought its own
troubles. In January he flew to Sydney, Australia, site of the 2000
Olympic Games, for a World Cup diving event. He wanted it to be a
coming-out party against an international field. Instead, he got
bronchitis and an ear infection that left him weaving when he
walked. Try diving off a 10-meter platform when you feel like that.
He finished 16th.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, driving in a drizzle, he hit a slick spot and
spun into oncoming traffic before overcorrecting and slamming into
a tree, totaling the tree and the car. Until he got a replacement
he had to depend on Troy for rides.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, without the money to pay for school again, Justin
concentrated on his diving.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect he probably needed to be in school, `` Scoggin
said. ``Diving became a job. But that's all changed in the last
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoggin has cut Justin's workouts to one a day, and he's been
diving much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a definite contender,'' Scoggin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transferring out here I had to make quite a few sacrifices,
but hopefully that will all culminate in making the Olympic team in
a few weeks,'' Justin said. ``I've always had to work my way up
inch by inch by inch. But if I dive like I can on platform, you
can't touch me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
