<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-MYSTICS-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE-TEAMING MONICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 18)  
 By NANCY HASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The private ``sky box'' at ESPN Zone had its own
waiters, several television monitors broadcasting a press
conference by Kobe Bryant of the Los Angeles Lakers and a spread of
hors d'oeuvres. Still, Vicky Bullett, Murriel Page and Nikki McCray
seemed bored by it all.
</P>
<P>
   The women, all members of the Washington Mystics, one of the
leading teams in the WNBA, hadn't come to eat fried chicken fingers
or to watch Bryant feign modesty. They were there, on the evening
before their Tuesday game against the New York Liberty, to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go upstairs,'' said Bullett, 32, a 6-foot-3 power
forward who has a reputation for rowdiness among her teammates.
``I'll show you all how it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Bounding out of the elevator at the top-floor video sports
arcade, they immediately jumped onto snowboard simulators. The ride
was familiar to them because the ESPN Zone in Washington is where
they hang out after home games. ``I love this one because I have
absolutely no idea what I'm doing,'' said McCray, 26, a 5-foot-11
guard pretty enough to model and poised even as she bobbed and
weaved.
</P>
<P>
   After half an hour of riding simulated Harley-Davidsons and
thoroughbreds and driving simulated Formula One racers (they passed
the free-throw area without so much as a glance), they were ready
to depart for the main event _ the American Foundation for AIDS
Research benefit at the Central Park boathouse. They conceded right
away why they were going. ``We're looking for famous people,''
Bullett declared. The one they were most hoping to see was Monica
Lewinsky, whom they seemed to root for like a home town underdog.
</P>
<P>
   In the town car (a tight squeeze of long slender limbs) they
gossiped about other players' weight gains and looked out the
windows longingly at the stores. ``Donna Karan,'' Page said. ``I
need some of that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the entrance to the boathouse, there was a gaggle of
photographers and a red carpet. The players switched into
celebrity-spotting mode, giraffing their necks above the crowd.
When one of the organizers of the event asked if they would pose
for a photograph, the women seemed shocked that they themselves
were considered celebrities. ``You want us?'' Bullett asked.
</P>
<P>
   The first celebrity they glimpsed once inside was Donald J.
Trump. The players introduced themselves and shook his hand. ``He's
got big bucks,'' Bullett said afterward. ``I wanted to ask him to
help the league, but I didn't have the nerve.''
</P>
<P>
   The players made their way to the VIP area, picking up plates of
food from the tables that had been set up by many of the city's
most stylish restaurants. All around, ingenue models and actresses
like Angie Harmon swooshed by in decollete cocktail dresses. The
players, dressed in casual slacks and tops, fretted that they were
underdressed. ``I should have worn my capri pants and heels,'' Page
said.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the celebrity trail, Bullett spied Sandra Bernhard
(well, she didn't actually recognize her by name, but she was sure
it was someone). It was growing near their self-imposed 9:30 p.m.
curfew when they saw Lewinsky across the room. ``We need to talk to
her,'' she said breathlessly to her teammates. ``We need to tell
her that Bill comes to our games in his sneakers. We need to tell
her that he looks fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky made her way toward the waving teammates and stood for
a photo. They didn't say a word to her about ``Bill,'' but just
stood and grinned. ``Us with Monica,'' Bullett said. ``Now I can
die and go to heaven.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
