<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GERMANY-FRANKEL-NYT &LR;      06-16 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-FRANKEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE-FRAUD SUSPECT MARTIN FRANKEL FACING EXTRADITION TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Martin Frankel, the fugitive American
financier wanted on charges of embezzling more than $200 million
from insurance companies, may soon be returned to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel, arrested in Hamburg in September after evading the FBI
for months after fleeing to Europe, pleaded guilty Friday to German
charges that he evaded taxes on about $5 million worth of diamonds
he had brought to finance his flight from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's plea removes the main obstacle to Frankel's extradition
to the United States, where he faces more than 30 charges of fraud
and money laundering, as well as civil suits claiming damages of
$600 million.
</P>
<P>
   German authorities have already approved the U.S. Justice
Department's request to extradite the financier, and they have
indicated willingness to do so as soon as they have prosecuted
Frankel on the German charges.
</P>
<P>
   Though German court officials declined to say exactly what the
next step in the process will be, Frankel could be returned to the
United States as early as the end of next week. Frankel's German
trial will be concluded Wednesday, after all sides make their final
statements.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the charge of evading about $1 million worth of
taxes on the jewels he brought to Germany, Frankel was also
indicted for carrying eight false passports and impersonating a
British citizen while in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel, bearded and rumpled and wearing a heavy wool overcoat
despite the spring weather, made it clear throughout his short
trial that he wanted to stay in Germany as long as he could. He
spoke English in the courtroom, and his remarks were translated
into German by a court official.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans respect human values,'' Frankel told reporters in
the courtroom Friday. ``An extradition to America would be the same
as an execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's guilty plea Friday is the latest in a series of
reversals that have befuddled Frankel's own attorneys and angered
the presiding judge. On Wednesday, Frankel balked at even
confirming his name and place of birth, and then refused to enter
any plea or make any statement on his own behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But later, under pressure from Judge Horst Muntzger, Frankel
announced that he wanted to call four witnesses _ three from the
United States and one from Italy. The witnesses included Mona Kim
and Cynthia Allison, two of his female associates who joined
Frankel for part of his time last year in Rome and Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
   German officials had worried that arranging for testimony from
the witnesses _ something Frankel had said earlier would not be
necessary _ would delay the trial for months. Hans-Gerd Meine, the
prosecutor in charge of the case, warned Frankel that the German
government might simply drop the charges and proceed immediately
with the extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Before his abrupt flight from the United States last year,
Frankel built up a convoluted business empire by acquiring small
insurance companies and then arranging to have himself put in
charge of investing the companies' assets.
</P>
<P>
   While secluded in his mansion in Greenwich, Conn., Frankel is
accused of illegally using a multitude of aliases and using the
insurance companies' money to pay for a lavish life. But as the
scheme was collapsing around him, he disappeared May 1999.
Firefighters in Greenwich found his mansion on fire and discovered
volumes of documents stuffed into the fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel led the FBI in a global cat-and-mouse game, first
reportedly hiding with Kim in Rome and then leaving for Hamburg
just as FBI agents were about to locate him. It took several more
months to track Frankel down at a small but luxurious Hamburg
hotel. German police arrested Frankel, who was accompanied at the
time by Allison, and he has been imprisoned awaiting trial and
extradition ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's German attorneys say he has experienced enormous mood
swings and habitually changed his mind on legal strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Though he does not speak German, Frankel apparently made
acquaintances in prison who recommended lawyers to represent him.
Thomas Piplak, the first attorney Frankel retained, said his client
decided to add a second and then a third attorney to the defense
team.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Piplak resigned as Frankel's attorney, and he has been
represented by Dirk Meinicke and Guenther Thiel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
