<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-     06-16 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
(Eds, describes seventh article in the series.)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors, managing editors, wire editors:
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday, June 4, and continuing for six weeks, The New York
Times has been publishing a series of articles, ``How Race Is Lived
in America.'' The series is the outcome of a yearlong effort by a
team of Times reporters to capture some of the voices of ordinary
people and some of the troubling issues that Americans continue to
face. These stories, two or three each week, will be approximately
6,000-7,000 words. The News Service will move each story in
advance, and an abridged version will also move, at approximately
3,000 words. They will move in the ``a'' news category and will
carry a slug of the form BC-RACE-SLUG-NYT. Because the articles are
organized into chapters, papers with severe space restraints may
choose to spread a single article over several days.
</P>
<P>
   Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients. For a special price,
nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   This is the seventh article, to be filed June 19 for release
June 20:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-POLITICS (Bainbridge Island, Wash.) _ The ferry from
Seattle is 10 minutes from landing as first light slips through the
mist of Puget Sound, and Ron Sims is still not sure what face he
will present to the world today. He wears a politician's suit _
standard uniform for the leader of a county with a population
greater than that of a half-dozen states. Passengers recognize him:
There are stares and smiles. But he is also attracting the kind of
curious glances that might fall on a square-jawed, rock-shouldered
black man sitting next to a sheriff's deputy as he arrives at a
place where blacks are more abstractions that neighbors. When he
was sworn in three years ago, Sims became one of three nonwhites
holding the top political jobs in the state. The others are Gary
Locke, the nation's first and only Chinese-American governor, and
Norm Rice, Seattle's mayor, who is black. Sims is known as an
ebullient man; he is also a natural storyteller with a compelling
one to offer, a bootstrap tale about a journey from anger to open
arms. Yet his friends and advisers have long urged him to keep a
large part of that story _ race _ bottled up. What people want to
hear are his views on property taxes, traffic growth and salmon. On
this day, however, Sims has been asked to say something in honor of
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., and he is tempted, he says, to
let them see the whole man. But do they really want to hear what it
is like for a black politician to live in two worlds? By Timothy
Egan.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT701-706 are being sent to NYT photo clients. For a
special price, nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a tentative schedule of publication dates for the
remaining articles in the series:
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, June 22
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, June 25
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, June 27
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, July 2
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, July 6
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, July 9
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, July 13
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a special issue of The New York Times Sunday
Magazine of July 16 will be devoted to this topic. Articles from
the magazine wil be available by special arrangement with New York
Times Special Features.
</P>
<P>
   The first six articles are available for repeating.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-CHURCH (Decatur, Ga.) _ Nearly 50 years after the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. scolded Christians for making 11 a.m Sunday
the most segregated hour of the week, the Assembly of God
Tabernacle here is the rarest of religious institutions: a truly
integrated church in the heart of the South. And yet the Tabernacle
is deeply conservative, socially and theologically. What draws its
members is the intensity of their Pentacostal faith, which teaches
that the Holy Spirit can move in the lives of all believers,
regardless of background. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT101-106 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-IMMIGRANTS (Miami) _ Before they left Cuba for America in
1994 Joel Ruiz, who is black, and Achmed Valdes, who is white, were
the best of friends. Today, in Miami, the two men live only 4 miles
apart, not even 15 minutes by car. Yet they are separated by a far
greater distance, one they say they never envisioned back in Cuba.
In ways that are obvious to the black man but far less so to the
white one, they have grown apart in the U.S. because of race. For
the first time, they inhabit a place where the color of their skin
defines the outlines of their lives _ where they live, the friends
they make, how they speak, what they wear, even what they eat. By
Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT201-207 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MILITARY (Fort Knox, Ky.) _ On a chill December morning,
two soldiers _ one black, one white, both part of an institution
portrayed as a model of race relations _ stood only yards apart in
the middle of this sprawling base, each believing himself the
victim of racism; one because of an award, the other because of a
transfer. The Army is not supposed to harbor racial resentment
anymore. Its work force is integrated. The Army is one of the few
institutions in America in which blacks routinely boss around
whites, and supposedly no one gives it a second thought. But that
is an idealized image. The Pentagon has found that two-thirds of
its men and women had experienced a racially offensive encounter in
the previous 12 months. And those findings are more or less
mirrored here at Fort Knox. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT301-307 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-TV-DRAMA (Baltimore) _ Who Gets to Tell a Black Story: When
David Simon proposed to HBO a television series based on his book,
``The Corner,'' about black inner-city drug addicts, he was not
thinking much about the fact that he was white. But as the project
began to take shape, the issues of race loomed ever larger. HBO was
not about to make a series about black drug addicts created by, as
one HBO executive put it later, ``a bunch of white guys.'' Charles
Dutton, who had grown up in the city, spent his early years on its
streets and had his own tale of redemption, was chosen to direct
all six episodes. But as he said, there would not be one moment
when he would forget that ``it's a white writer and a white
producer and it's HBO and a black director.'' By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT401-407 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-WEB-ENTREPRENEUR (Atlanta) _ On the eve of the year 2000,
Timothy Fitzgerald Stevenson Cobb Jr. had much to celebrate. Over
two sleep-deprived years, he and his partner, Jeff Levy, had built
an Internet research company in Atlanta and by May 1999 each man's
net worth had swelled by about $25 million. It conferred an
uncommon distinction on Cobb: He became one of the country's few
black Internet millionaires. To Cobb, Jeff Levy understood his
satisfaction in a way that probably no one else could. Yet Cobb
also recalled a creeping uneasiness that weekend. Shortly after
their company's IPO, Levy and Cobb went off to start separate
Internet ventures. Levy's was doing fine. Not so Cobb's. The racial
backdrop to Cobb's accomplishments went largely unmentioned by the
people he did business with, but he seemed never to forget it. When
things were good, being black made them better; when things were
not so good, it made them worse. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT501-506 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MEAT-PLANT (Tar Heel, N.C.) _ The first thing you learn at
the Smithfield hog plant here is the value of a sharp knife. The
second thing you learn is that not everyone has to work with a
knife. Whites, blacks, American Indians and Mexicans, they all have
their separate stations, but it is blacks and Mexicans that are
left to battle over the dirty jobs at the factory, one of the only
places within a 50-mile radius in this muddy corner of North
Carolina where a person might make more than $8 an hour. While
Smithfield's profits nearly doubled over the past year, wages have
remained flat. So a lot of Americans have quit and a lot of
Mexicans have been hired to take their places. But the workers see
one another, more than management, as the problem, and they see the
competition in skin tones. By Charlie LeDuff.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT601-606 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
