<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA EASES UP ON MEDIA MOGUL, BUT CHARGES REMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Responding to rising criticism within Russia and
abroad, Russian authorities Friday released media mogul Vladimir
Gusinsky, whose arrest and three-day imprisonment fueled
accusations that the Kremlin is cracking down on the press.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not drop the swindling and theft charges against
Gusinsky, whose Media-Most company owns broadcast and print media
that have criticized the Kremlin in recent months. Gusinsky's
lawyers said he was freed only after giving a written pledge not to
leave Russia, and following an unexplained, last-minute change of
heart by investigators that appeared to have been supported by
President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   If Gusinsky was disappointed with the terms of his release, it
did not show as he walked into Media-Most's central Moscow office
late Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank all those who supported me,'' a smiling
Gusinsky told journalists, in comments broadcast on his flagship
television station, NTV. ``First of all journalists and all my
colleagues, Russian and non-Russian.''
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky's arrest sparked a furor among Russia's political and
business elite, which accused the Kremlin of trying to shut up
critics, and prompted concern from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, on a three-day visit to Spain and Germany aimed at
improving Russia's ties with Western Europe, was instead put on the
defensive by embarassing questions about the arrest of the
prominent business and media leader. Thursday in Madrid, Putin
called the decision to arrest Gusinsky ``excessive'' and Friday in
Berlin repeated that he thought the arrest was a mistake, though on
both occasions the Russian president has denied the case was
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Gusinsky is suspected of taking part in the
theft of $10 million in state funds in a privatization deal. The
lead investigator, Valery Nikolayev, told state TV there were no
``political motives'' and it was ``a common criminal case.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gusinsky's lawyers and colleagues say the arrest smacks of
intimidation in response to Media-Most's journalistic edge. That
includes the constant criticism of Putin's crackdown in Chechnya,
the probes on corruption in the FSB security service Putin once
led, and investigations of alleged money laundering by Kremlin
insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky used to be an insider himself, but he broke with other
business and political leaders, particularly fellow magnate Boris
Berezovsky, who remains close to the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most officials charge that the Kremlin was behind the raid
by masked, machinegun-toting police on the company's offices last
month. Friday, editors of four Media-Most holdings said Gusinsky's
arrest had been preceded by informal bribe offers and threats.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksei Venediktov, editor of the Echo of Moscow radio station,
said he has met regularly in the Kremlin since last summer with
``two highly placed officials'' to discuss the government's
objections to critical coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They joked, with smiles, that Gusinsky would soon be put in
jail,'' Venediktov told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton chose Echo of Moscow to demonstrate his
sympathy for Media-Most, by giving the station an interview during
his visit to Moscow earlier this month _ instead of Russian state
radio or television.
</P>
<P>
   One theory popular in Moscow is that Putin had been unaware that
Gusinsky was about to be arrested. This theory has it that a
Kremlin clique led by Berezovsky made the move while Putin was
abroad to embarrass the president while reminding him of his
political weakness.
</P>
<P>
   But NTV head Yevgeny Kiselyov said that theory missed the point.
``Gusinsky is a political hostage who we consider has been taken by
the authorities in order to shut up NTV television and other parts
of the Media-Most empire,'' Kiselyov said. ``I am sick and tired of
hearing about the good king and the bad court. If he did not know
about the plans to arrest Mr. Gusinsky, it shows Mr. Putin does not
control the situation in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Gusinsky's lawyers had said investigators
formally charging him had initially refused to free him from the
overcrowded, 18th century Butyrskaya jail.
</P>
<P>
   But hours later, the Prosecutor General's office released a
statement saying investigators had changed their minds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
