<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARBAGE-STUDIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUST TO DUST MEANS US: GARBAGE PROVIDES CULTURAL INSIGHTS, EXPERTS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It occupies a marginal space between the public and the private.
It can signify wealth and virility. We always want to repress it.
And everyone has some of it in his or her kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Trash, the academy is ready for you.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, academics are finding that garbage _ the
previously ignored contents of wastebaskets and Dumpsters _ holds
vital clues to consumer culture. What people consume has long been
studied on college campuses and in academic journals. But, some
scholars argue, the nether part of consumerism, what people
discard, may be just as important.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Strasser, a history professor at the University of
Delaware, writes in her recent book, ``Waste and Want: A Social
History of Trash,'' that ``what counts as trash depends on who's
counting.'' In other words, a useless potato scrap in one culture
may be a crucial soup starter in another.
</P>
<P>
   Why trash now?
</P>
<P>
   Some have grumbled that trash studies are just another academic
jobs program: something grubby and controversial with shock value
from which to generate paper, so to speak. But others, like Robin
Nagle, who teaches a course at New York University on the
anthropology of trash, view it as a timely concern. ``There's so
much of it and it never goes away, and in considering our impact as
a species, it's a pretty significant mark,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Academic interest in refuse was awakened a decade ago by a
seminal real-world event: A garbage barge called the Mobro 4000
drifted along the world's waterways with over 3 tons of trash from
Long Island and no place to dump it.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with the prospect of homeless trash and limited
space, the nation was swept with garbage guilt. Under the title
``Buried Alive,'' Newsweek ran a cover story noting that the
Mobro's trip to nowhere was ``to the trash crisis what the sinking
of the Lusitania was to World War I.'' But while homeowners
envisioned overflowing Dumpsters and shrinking landfill space,
scholars focused on the social and political effects of detritus in
a culture of abundance. Had the state relegated our garbage to the
private realm, as a form of political control? Do we generate trash
to demonstrate our buying power, often a symbol of our sexual
power?
</P>
<P>
   Rubbish studies should not be confused with the more practical
work of solid-waste managers, who concern themselves with space: Is
there enough room in the world's landfills for the increasing
number of plastic diapers we use?
</P>
<P>
   Garbologists, on the other hand, concern themselves with
content: What's in whose garbage bag and what it means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wait till everyone who is throwing away stuff is dead
before we tell them why it's important?'' asks William Rathje,
director of the Garbage Project at the University of Arizona and
co-author, with Cullen Murphy, of the book ``Rubbish! The
Archaeology of Garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Rathje's class actually excavates landfill and analyzes its
contents to learn about what consumers use up. He got little
respect from academic circles, he said, until the Mobro sailed.
Then one archaeologist (who used to lump him derisively with
solid-waste managers) sent him a note urging him to change his
title from garbologist to garbage archaeologist. That is when
Rathje knew there was room for trash in the ivory tower.
</P>
<P>
   In his work on trash, Rathje actually gets his hands dirty; by
contrast, the theorists rummage through abstractions.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Johnson is a graduate student of Victorian literature at
Stanford University and the co-editor, with William Cohen, of an
forthcoming essay collection, ``Filth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone gets rid of trash, it's looked on as abject,'' he
said, ``but it recirculates symbolically and you can never really
get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The essays in Johnson and Cohen's volume will examine such
topics as the relation of sanitary reform to gender identity and
social class, the ideology of sanitary reform in colonial India and
the use of filthy language in the radical theater of 19th-century
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   For students of the Victorian era, the sanitary reform movement
of the 19th century reflected a changing attitude toward garbage,
and a broader shift in the individual's relationship to society. In
documents like Edwin Chadwick's sanitary report of 1850, they see
the desire for cleanliness, a value of the new bourgeoisie, leading
to a mountain of trash by encouraging people to throw old things
away. Strasser calls this ``the veneration of newness.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1850s, garbage was a commodity that dust pickers would
pay for the right to collect. Discarded scraps were the raw
material for quilts, soap, charcoal and fertilizer. Almost
everything was reused. In New York City, pigs wandered the streets,
eating garbage and, in turn, feeding the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But with reform, Londoners began paying for their garbage to be
taken away. Decades later, after the period of thrift imposed
during World War II, America went further and began to celebrate
disposability, using paper cups _ and even paper clothing _ for
purposes not only of cleanliness but of liberation from fuss as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Popularizing hygiene was bad news for dirt. It was no longer
welcome in the public or the private realms and needed to go
somewhere else _ out there, into those liminal landfills of the
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Academics are increasingly exploring the social and
psychological consequences of this repression of dirt. ``Dust: A
History of the Small and the Invisible,'' by Joseph Amato, laments
Windex and the dust-repellent household surfaces that have
relegated dust to the corners of our consciousness. The study
reminds us that, according to the Book of Genesis, we are all made
of dust and destined to return to it, so we should appreciate the
microscopic stuff that has been brutally repressed in a hygienic
society.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Strasser says, the richness of waste as a topic for
academic investigation lies in how people choose to designate it.
``I define my topic, and my interest, not just in piles of trash
but the sorting process that takes place in the marginal spaces
between the public and the private,'' she writes. ``The marginal
things we're not sure of we sort in marginal spaces of the house,
the attic, the basement.'' By such activities, people reveal
themselves. Or, as a German philosopher might put it, we are what
we throw away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
