<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: U.S. ACCEPTS VOTE RESULT
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. ambassador in Lima said the Clinton administration
accepts President Alberto Fujimori's re-election victory last month
despite widespread charges that the campaign and first-round vote
were tainted. ``It's our government position to respect the
decision of national authorities,'' Ambassador John Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: SHOTS ON ROYAL TRAIN
</P>
<P>
   A bodyguard in the elite Royalty and Diplomatic Protection Squad
fired two shots in the staff dining room of the Royal Train as the
queen and Prince Philip slept two carriages away during an
overnight stay in Wales. One shot embedded in the floor, the second
in a table. The police said they were treating the episode as an
accident. The unidentified officer was relieved of his duties and
returned to London pending an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: STREAMLINING MILITARY
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping said he has won cabinet
backing for plans to streamline Germany's conscript-based military.
Its armed forces would be cut to 277,000 from about 320,000, with
the number of conscripts falling to 80,000 from about 130,000, and
the number of professional soldiers raised gradually by more than
20,000 to 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA: NEW VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   Guerrilla violence claimed new victims as gunmen shot and killed
a moderate Muslim cleric, and the bodies of two beheaded Russian
police officers were found with the bodies of two Chechen
civilians. The cleric was described as an opponent of
fundamentalists among the rebels. Ambush attacks against Russian
federal forces and their civilian supporters have stepped up
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   MYANMAR: PRESSED ON FORCED LABOR
</P>
<P>
   The International Labor Organization has voted to open the way
for Myanmar to be sanctioned for its apparently widespread use of
forced labor. In a compromise between Western countries urging
rapid action and Asian nations siding with Myanmar, no measures
would take effect until Nov. 30. The agency's resolution asks other
member countries to review their links with Myanmar and take steps
to ensure it ``cannot take advantage of such relations to
perpetuate or extend the system of forced or compulsory labor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
