<SLUG> BC-NY-TOURISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWARE OF IMAGE DAMAGE, N.Y. CRACKS DOWN IN `WOLF PACK' CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With public indignation mounting, the city is
cracking down on the ``wolf pack'' of young men who stripped,
mauled, and terrorized dozens of young women in Central Park last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ten men have been arrested, six of them handcuffed and paraded
in a ``perp walk'' before news cameras Friday, as a sign that
law-enforcement officials consider them serious criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Police have examined 10 videotapes of the assaults _ shot and
provided by citizens who just happened to be taking pictures in the
park that day _ to identify and capture more suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the response, more than 40 women have come forward
to say they too were molested in the park _ 10 times the number
initially reported.
</P>
<P>
   Police commissioner Howard Safir pledged to hunt down every
assailant who took part in the attacks, stating, while staring into
a TV camera, ``We are going to find you.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir also announced Friday that he has stepped up an internal
probe into charges that police on the scene stood by while the
assaults were going on _ with 76 sergeants and several officers
interrogated so far.
</P>
<P>
   One police officer investigating the assaults, who asked not to
be identified, said the surge of arrests and detective-work has
been due to the sudden realization of the incident's impact on the
city's international image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm told these things happen at Mardi Gras (in New Orleans)
every year,'' the officer said, ``but this is Central Park, this is
the jewel of the world. If there's outrage about it in the world
community, and if this means people in Europe decide not to come to
New York on vacation, then that outrage _ that perception _ has to
be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   The new wave of action presents a bustling picture of what the
NYPD does best _ but it's also a far cry from the reaction in the
first 48 hours after the event.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani tried to minimize its
significance, noting that roughly the same amount of violence took
place the same weekend last year and that crime, in Central Park
and the city generally, is way down from the days before he was
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Safir issued a similar shrug. ``If I put 10,000 cops in Central
Park,'' he said, ``we couldn't cover every single area.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until public shock boiled and spread worldwide did they take
a harder stance.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if Giuliani had forgotten the basic principles of what
made his administration's crime-fighting policies so successful _
and made him, at least in his first term, such a popular mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Those principles, which he used to spell out repeatedly, were:
No tolerance of even apparently minor disorder in public places;
and, when it comes to group violence, or what used to be called
``wolf packs,'' no resting until every member of the pack was
tracked down.
</P>
<P>
   He and his first police commissioner, William Bratton, saw these
principles as the key not only to cutting crime, but also to
restoring confidence in the city as a safe place to live, work, and
visit _ and, therefore, as a tool of economic development, as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 interview, Giuliani said, ``An article in a foreign
magazine that says crime in New York City has gone down _ that's
much more effective than any ad I can buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet two of the first known victims of Sunday's ``wilding'' spree
were a French and a British tourist, one of whom, in the city on
her honeymoon, was stripped of all her clothing and mauled by
several men while two others held her husband down.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has since met with the tourists and with several other
victims, but it took him a bit longer to do so than might have once
been the case.
</P>
<P>
   It is still not known precisely how the mayhem erupted or
whether all the attackers _ now believed to number as many as 50 _
knew each other or whether some simply, spontaneously, joined in.
</P>
<P>
   Reports now indicate the attacks began much earlier in the
afternoon, while the Puerto Rican Day parade _ attended by a
million marchers, most of them young, some of them drunk or high _
was still making its way down Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The assault expanded after 6 pm, as celebrants spilled into
Central Park, with most of the incidents taking place along the
park's southern _ and most publicly visible _ edge.
</P>
<P>
   The videotapes, which have been repeatedly shown on local TV
newscasts, show dense crowds. If police were off to the side, it is
conceivable they did not see what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   However, while some victims who approached police afterward were
helped, others said they were turned away, in some cases
dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   There are also reports that police along the parade route
ignored open displays of alcohol and marijuana, possibly to avoid
provoking racial incidents. One police consultant, who asked not to
be named, said, ``If cops were relaxing in the face of public
drinking, that's an invitation to disaster when you've got a
million people on the streets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
