<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULES-FEIFFER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTOONIST JULES FEIFFER'S DANCER HANGS UP HER TIGHTS SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jules Feiffer's moody modern dancer, the comic strip figure who
has leaped and stretched interpretively to spring, summer, autumn
and winter for more than 40 years, is finally hanging up her
tights. The reason? Her only venue, ``Feiffer,'' Feiffer's doodly
comic strip of personal, sexual and political rants, is ending
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 52-week-per-year schedule was relentless,'' Feiffer said,
speaking of his comic strip, which has run every Sunday in The Los
Angeles Times, The Miami Herald, The Chicago Tribune and The
Observer in London. ``I'm getting to be an old man,'' he said. So
``the dancer is retired.''
</P>
<P>
   Feiffer started drawing his strip in 1956 for The Village Voice.
It was about the ``usual boy-girl stuff,'' as he described it. The
dancer made her first appearance in 1957 with ``a dance to
spring.'' Then she began doing interpretive pieces to the rest of
the seasons. In spring her dance was stretchy, hopeful and giddy.
In summer it was ``lazy, so lazy'' and ultimately wilted in the
heat. In the autumn she danced wistfully to the leaves falling. She
and the strip were syndicated in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   The dancer, who was given to leaps of ecstasy, ranting and
silliness, was modeled after ``the first girl who slept with me and
spent the night,'' Feiffer said. She was a modern dancer attending
Brooklyn College, he said, adding that he thinks she has died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early dancer looked just like her,'' Feiffer said, ``and
as I changed girlfriends, her body changed.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Feiffer can remember, he said the dancer was never
modeled on his wife, Jenny, but the dancer did come to represent
Feiffer himself. ``At a certain point, the girl became me and I
became her. She was there to talk about how lousy her life was.
That I will miss. It is not the cartoon I got tired of, it is the
weekly schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Feiffer, who is 71, writes plays, teaches a course on humor and
truth at Southampton College of Long Island University, writes and
illustrates children's books, and still draws political cartoons
for The New York Times, The New Yorker, American Prospect and
Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard work trying to make Al Gore and George W. Bush funny
all the time, he noted. ``Something had to give.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of Feiffer's farewell comic strips have already run, and
the last will appear Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to give up the strip two or three months ago,'' he
said. ``I was just going to drop it without saying anything, but
there are readers who are going to be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   So Feiffer devoted the last few strips to explaining to the
dancer why she is now out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   Feiffer tells the dancer that he is giving up the strip. The
dancer gasps, ``You're dying.'' But as she finds out that he is
quitting merely to devote more time to his life beyond his weekly
six panels, she starts berating him. She calls him pathetic and
asks whether he is abandoning the strip because it has become
boring or ``because no one of your generation knows you're around
anymore and young people have never heard of you?''
</P>
<P>
   Feiffer is unfazed: ``It's my turn to dance,'' he says, shoving
her out of the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
