<HEADLINE>
3.3-LEVEL QUAKE RATTLES WESTERN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would have been no big deal in Los Angeles or San Francisco.
An earthquake measuring 3.3 on the famous Richter Scale would send
barely a noticeable ripple through a glass of Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   But in Western Massachusetts, where such tremblors are rare,
residents aren't used to being rattled in their beds as the earth
sends jarring reminders about its geological stresses.
</P>
<P>
   The quake Friday at 12:03 am, although considered mild, was one
of the strongest ever recorded in New England west of the
Connecticut River. It sent worried residents out into the street
and had seismologists and other scientists pondering again if The
Big One could ever strike here.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought was that a plane went down,'' said Debbie
Christie, of Granville, Conn., who lives along one of the approach
lanes for Bradley International Airport in Hartford, Conn. ``There
was a loud crash and then a sound like thunder rolling down the
valley,''
</P>
<P>
   No damage was reported but the vibration was felt all the way
from Northampton to northern Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the West Coast, where earthquakes occur primarily along
well-known fault lines and in some cases even at roughly
predictable intervals, quakes in New England tend to leave
seismologists scratching their heads: they can occur virtually
anywhere, at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Though the region is riddled with ancient fault lines, most of
them more than 200 million years old, there are no known
currently-active faults along which earthquakes align themselves,
and they often occur in places with no known faults.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the East Coast is thousands of miles from the nearest
boundary between the ``plates'' which make up the Earth's crust. It
is along the boundaries of those plates _ for instance, in
California, Alaska and Japan _ that earthquakes are by far the most
common. The nearest such boundary is in the middle of the Atlantic
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   And, it turns out, that may be the place where the stresses that
cause earthquakes in New England originate. Research has shown that
most quakes in the region arise from the compression of the crust
in an East-West direction. That is just what would be expected if
the mid-ocean ridge, where the ocean floor is slowly but constantly
expanding outward, was the cause of the earthquake-triggering
stresses.
</P>
<P>
   But unfortunately that provides no clues as to where or when the
next temblor could strike. This region has suffered major
earthquakes in the distant past _ one estimated at magnitude 6 was
centered on Cape Ann in 1755 and caused damage from Boston to
Portland, and one in 1638, estimated at 6.5, was probably centered
in New Hampshire and was felt by the Pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   But such large quakes are rare hereabouts. John Ebel, director
of the Weston (Mass.) Observatory, which is the principal seismic
recording center for the region, said that earthquakes of magnitude
5 or greater _ the level at which there starts to be some damage _
occur somewhere in New England on average about once every 50
years. The last was a pair of such quakes centered in Ossipee,
N.H., in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Earthquakes of magnitude 6 or more, which cause severe damage,
are much more rare. They are estimated to occur only every 450 to
500 years, Ebel said.
</P>
<P>
   Quakes of between magnitude 3 and 4, such as Friday's, occur
about two or three times a year in the region.
</P>
<P>
   But, Ebel stressed, ``those averages really have no predictive
value at all. At any given locality in New England, instead of
stresses building up over tens or hundreds of years as in
California, it would probably build up over hundreds of thousands,
or even millions of years.''
</P>
<P>
   But while big, destructive earthquakes don't happen often in
this area, when the next big one comes along it could have
devastating effects. For one thing, Boston and surrounding cities,
though they have good building codes in place now, still have many
old unreinforced masonry buildings _ the kind that are most
vulnerable to earthquake damage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Boston is built on a lot of landfill,'' said
Ebel, including most of the Back Bay and much of South Boston, and
``areas of landfill and river muds tend to amplify ground
shaking.''
</P>
<P>
   One other important difference is that the shaking of
earthquakes tends to spread over an area 4 to 10 times greater in
eastern earthquakes than on the West Coast. This is probably
because the Earth's crust here is older and cooler and spreads the
motion more easily, Ebel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My seismologist friends in California are always amazed at how
widely even small earthquakes are felt here,'' Ebel said, ``and my
colleagues here are always amazed at how small the areas affected
by bigger earthquakes in California are.''
</P>
<P>
   While California earthquakes along previously unmapped fault
lines occur only occasionally, they are typical in the East, said
Charles Doll, a seismologist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and director of the New England Seismic Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be surprised by a big earthquake tomorrow,'' he said,
``in an area where we don't have records of any earthquakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
