   HOT-HOT-HOT (Los Angeles) _ Spring 2000 was the hottest on
record for the United States, following the warmest winter ever.
The national Climatic Data Center reported Friday that the nation
averaged 55.5 degrees from March to May - 0.4 degrees warmer than
the previous record, set in 1910. In the West, the average
temperature was 56 degrees, compared to 52.6 during a normal
meteorological spring. The agency also reported that the United
States experienced the hottest January-May in 106 years of
recordkeeping. By Erik Monroe. (Will move in the ``a'' national and
``n'' California state news files.)
