<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6209 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-ROCKIES-SPI &LR;      06-16 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROCKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ROCKIES' AIMS HIGH BUT MISSES MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B-  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Rockies'' is the kind of breezy documentary that makes The
History Channel the TV equivalent of Coors beer, which for years
had a fabulous mystique because many Americans couldn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   The History Channel has enjoyed the same cachet. People in
cable-poor areas were ready to surrender their firstborn for a hit
of THC that wouldn't get them arrested. They'd heard it was the
greatest thing since front-seat cup holders and generally made
pests of themselves inquiring of their cable providers as to when
their neighborhoods might be blessed with its arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Expectation is usually better than realization, of course. Turns
out Coors was no big deal, another light American lager without
bite. The History Channel _ alternate name: The Hitler Channel _ is
pleasing to the armchair historian, its programming neatly packaged
and stacked like cans on a supermarket shelf. But, like a lot of
convenience food, it frequently leaves one hungry for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rockies'' has this effect. Four one-hour programs, airing
on consecutive nights, scale the heights from different approaches,
providing a fascinating assortment of informational nuggets. But in
clambering across the scree of Rocky Mountain history, the series
sets off a cascade of unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday night's ``Great Explorers'' installment, no one ever
bothers to disclose why Maj. John Wesley Powell needed barometers,
which he almost lost, in his exploration of Colorado's treacherous
Green River in 1869. It probably had to do with measuring altitude
and perhaps the river's total drop in elevation from source to
terminus. But it is never fully explained and, as the film moves on
to the next subject, the omission leaves one of those nagging
little questions rattling around in the brain, the sort that
inevitably get in the way of total enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a segment in Wednesday's episode, ``War &AMP; Disaster,''
deals with a copper-mine fire in Butte, Mont., that killed 168 men
in 1917. In telling the story of Marnus Duggan, a heroic miner
whose quick thinking and resourcefulness saved many of his
co-workers, the film never explains how or why Duggan died after
the fire was out.
</P>
<P>
   The other two installments of ``The Rockies'' are Tuesday's
``Striking It Rich,'' including a segment on the creator of the
Coors brewing empire, and Thursday's ``Taming the Mountains,''
which may be the best of the bunch for its telling of John D.
Rockefeller Jr.'s secretive efforts to preserve the Jackson Hole
Valley in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Peter Fonda as narrator is understandable: He
lives in Montana. It's also troubling: Henry's son and Bridget's
dad is a fuzzy-tongued word swallower who makes Sly Stallone's
Rocky Balboa the paragon of erudition.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ``The Rockies'' succeeds modestly in spite of Fonda's
marble-mouthed, stone-faced delivery. What it might have been with
David McCullough or Bill Moyers hosting is something to ponder. As
it is, ``The Rockies'' is like a history book that could have been
better researched and better packaged. It doesn't alter the
incredible history pouring out of the Rockies like a stream in
springtime. And it doesn't destroy the notion that a documentary
series centered on the Rockies' place in U.S. history is a
terrifically good idea.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies. Four-hour documentary about the Rocky Mountains and
their place in American history. Narrated by Peter Fonda. Airing
Monday through Thursday on The History Channel. Repeating Sunday in
one four-hour broadcast. Parental guideline rating: TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
