<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOORING-AMERICA0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Chapter 11, Flooring America debt to Shaw Industries hurts
stock value
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Flooring America's bankruptcy filing will likely hit
Shaw Industries the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents for the Chapter 11 filing were not immediately
available, but Dalton-based Shaw was the first to acknowledge a
significant impact.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, the world's largest carpet maker and Flooring America's
largest supplier, said the retailer owes it about $14 million, plus
a promissory note of about $12 million. The manufacturer is also a
guarantor of certain leases for stores it sold to Flooring America
in 1998. Shaw will lose some of the $80 million in annual sales it
makes to the retailer's company-owned stores.
</P>
<P>
   That exposure prompted Credit Suisse First Boston analyst Dennis
Rosenberg to cut his earnings estimates on Shaw for this year to
$1.65 a share from $1.70, and its 2001 estimate to $1.70 a share
from $1.80. The estimate for this year does not include a possible
12 cents-a-share writeoff for the $26 million in accounts
receivable and promissory notes.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's stock fell 6.5 percent Friday to $12.44, down 88 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on other vendors wasn't clear Friday. Calhoun-based
Mohawk Industries, the second-largest carpet maker, said it doesn't
sell a lot of merchandise to Flooring America's corporate stores.
</P>
<P>
   Some suppliers had cut off shipments to certain Flooring America
stores before the bankruptcy filing. Flooring America Chairman and
Chief Executive Officer David Nichols said Friday that the company
is working with vendors on a cash-only basis and is trying to
re-establish credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm personally dedicated to paying (our vendors) back,''
Nichols said. ``This reorganization is allowing us to step back and
catch our breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
