<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MUSIC-MAN-PROFILE-ART     06-16 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MAN-PROFILE-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY MAKES THE MUSIC MAN SING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Craig Bierko had a good life in Los Angeles. He had
been working steadily as an actor for the last decade. He had a
nice house in Hancock Park and cruised the freeways in his Jeep.
Boyishly handsome, 6 foot 4, with thick hair and green eyes, Bierko
was socially in demand and found the hardest part of working on a
set was the waiting around.
</P>
<P>
   But something was missing. Perhaps it was that he was doing
guest appearances on popular television shows like ``Ally McBeal''
and ``Mad About You'' without landing a star vehicle of his own.
But Bierko says it was something deeper than that: At 35 _ corny as
it may sound _ he wanted to do more than coast through the rest of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   So he raised his hand for the role of Harold Hill in the
Broadway revival of Meredith Willson's ``Music Man.'' And somewhat
incredibly he won the part, even though the producers originally
wanted a more bankable star like Steve Martin, Matthew Broderick or
Alec Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bierko is performing night after night on Broadway and has
won a Tony nomination (losing to Brian Stokes Mitchell of ``Kiss
Me, Kate'').
</P>
<P>
   Though critics have said that he reminds them of Robert Preston,
who originated the role in 1957 _ indeed there are times when
Bierko seems to be eerily channeling the voice of his predecessor,
it is so similar _ the critics agree that he has brought his own
winning charm to the role of the slick but disarming traveling
salesman.
</P>
<P>
   Bierko ``steps into Preston's long shadow with remarkable
assurance,'' Ben Brantley wrote in The New York Times. ``At times
he seems to be patterning his gestures and inflections too closely
on his famous predecessor. But he has a gleaming impishness of his
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Inexperience notwithstanding, Bierko has also apparently won
over his fellow cast members.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the ladies love Craig,'' said Susan Stroman, director and
choreographer of the revival. He has also passed muster with stage
veterans like his co-star Rebecca Luker, who has been on Broadway
four times before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so consistent,'' she said. ``He's right there with me
every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he could attempt this role, Bierko said, he got to the
point where he believed he could survive falling on his face. He
has not read his reviews, he said, so he does not wholly realize
how well things turned out.
</P>
<P>
   He said the experience had proved to be precisely the
``something more'' he had been craving. He is working harder than
ever before. He has no social life. And he has never been happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how thirsty I was for a life like this,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the adjustment has been profound. ``I wasn't
psychologically prepared for what it means to do previews at the
same time that you're rehearsing eight hours a day, then promote
the show after you open,'' he said. ``I didn't know what it meant
to buckle down and really learn to dance. It's an entirely new
world of discipline for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bierko said the process of mastering this role had had a
maturing effect on him. ``I finally felt like I was older than 18
for some reason,'' he said. ``Grown-upness kicked in. I now have to
clean up. Up until now it was adorable to keep dishes in the
sink.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he had not performed onstage since he appeared in a
revival of ``The Boys From Syracuse'' in Los Angeles in 1989,
Bierko said he was not nervous about being on Broadway for the
first time. He credited this calm to Stroman, who he said taught
him his huge part one small bit at a time and made rehearsals feel
safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than creating a relationship where I was constantly
trying to prove something to her, where I felt like I was still
auditioning even after I had the role, she would light a fire,'' he
said. ``She inspired me. I wanted to come in and learn all this
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroman said her leading man came in with no Hollywood attitude,
that he was ready to make a fool of himself if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a fearless personality,'' she said. ``He was very
willing to learn how to twirl the baton, though the first day he
clipped his eye and was bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Bierko was not entirely new to the stage; he grew up around it,
because his parents ran the Harrison Players community theater near
Rye Brook, their hometown. As a boy he helped out with chores
there. His mother, who worked for Dolce International, a hotel and
conference-center company, and his father, a traveling salesman,
divorced when he was 10.
</P>
<P>
   At Northwestern University he studied theater, appearing in
plays like ``The Threepenny Opera'' and ``Twelfth Night.'' But he
also studied film and television, and when he graduated, the
glamour and sprawl of Los Angeles beckoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a weird freak who actually likes to drive, so it's a
perfect city for me,'' he said. ``It was a lifestyle choice.''
</P>
<P>
   His film roles have ranged from the villain in ``The Long Kiss
Goodnight'' to a comedic turn in ``Sour Grapes'' and a part in the
virtual-reality thriller ``The 13th Floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the things that I've done, I like the choices I've
made,'' Bierko said. ``But suddenly I developed a hunger to learn
other things. I felt I was beginning to fall into a groove in
L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroman said: ``He studied in school but went west instead of
east. Thank goodness he's finally come east, because we need him
here on Broadway. We don't have leading men like Craig Bierko.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Bierko said that he had grown up loving the 1962 movie version
of ``The Music Man'' and Preston's performance in it, but that he
was doing his own version of the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he kind of haunts this performance a little bit,'' he
said. ``But I didn't purposely try to recreate his performance.
Rather than try to copy him or go out of my way to disregard
everything he did, I was just going to try to honor his
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as hard work has sobered and intensified his outlook,
Bierko said, perhaps the most lasting impact of his ``Music Man''
experience has been watching firsthand how Stroman created a work
of such buoyancy even as she was weathering the loss of her
husband, the director Mike Ockrent, to cancer in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way she navigates her way through her life right now and
pulls so much beauty from the darkness _ it's been an amazing
lesson in keeping things in perspective and trying to achieve some
kind of balance,'' Bierko said. ``She's dealing with the
unspeakable grief of losing the love of her life and finding solace
in the work. What that is teaching me nothing can take away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It saves her, her work saves her,'' he continued. ``And it's
not an escape. It's a true healing experience. Some people are
workaholics, and some dive into work with their souls and heal
themselves. And that's what I've watched her do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bierko said he believed that Stroman's loss had added a darker
side to the show and that the searching quality of both Harold Hill
and Marian the librarian, who ultimately find companionship in each
other, is more pronounced in this production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is something in what Susan is going through
right now that is very attached to that sense of loneliness,'' he
said. ``She's living it every minute. It's the perfect example of
grabbing something joyful out of something horrendous.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a long journey from trying to get a sitcom deal
together. I feel like I've beheld something majestic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6233 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     06-16 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAR NO EVIL, SEE NO EVIL, SPEAK NO EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miami)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, June 18) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this, the information age, there is no shortage of data about
public companies available to investors. The phalanx of newspapers
and magazines devoted to financial matters has ballooned in recent
years, as have cable television programs and Internet chat rooms
focused on investing. And Wall Street research, once shared only
with a privileged few, has become widely available to investors on
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But as Edward Kerschner, chief investment strategist at
PaineWebber, points out, there is a big difference between
information and knowledge. He believes that the instant
dissemination of information today carries a substantial cost: the
tendency among investors to act first and think second. That
behavior, he said, may account for the recent jump in stock market
volatility.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate his point, Kerschner has tracked volatility on the
major stock indexes against the growth in daily household
viewership of CNBC, the popular investing channel on cable
television. As viewership has exploded, so has volatility,
particularly among Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, it is becoming increasingly difficult for
investors to pick through all the dross to find gold. Investing
chat rooms, with their anonymous contributors, are especially good
breeding grounds for misinformation. But wisdom can be found there
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Equally difficult to fathom are company research reports penned
by Wall Street analysts. While these reports include a great deal
of data, they can also be extremely biased. Researchers whose firms
have or want to have investment banking relationships with the
companies they follow are more inclined to be positive in their
forecasts and assessments than those whose firms do not have such
kinships.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how much more positive? According to five years of
research by Siva Nathan, associate professor of accounting at
Georgia State University in Atlanta, analysts whose firms have
banking relationships with companies they follow issue earnings
forecasts that, on average, are 6 percent higher than forecasts
issued by other analysts. Nathan's research also shows that
analysts writing about companies whose securities have been
underwritten by their firms put out 25 percent more ``buy''
recommendations, 46 percent fewer ``sell'' recommendations and 23
percent fewer ``hold'' recommendations than other analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In another study, three professors examined analysts' forecasts
from 1982 to 1997 to see what incremental value they provided to
investors over and above the data publicly available in companies'
financial statements. Eli Amir at Tel Aviv University, Baruch Lev
at New York University's Stern School of Business and Theodore
Sougiannis at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign
concluded that analysts, over all, made only a modest contribution
to investors' results beyond what could be divined from the
financials.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that analysts provided the most added value in
forecasts on technology companies, whose financial statements are
the least informative about new product developments, for example.
Analysts also contribute more to investors' returns in stocks of
companies that report losses rather than in those with profits. And
analysts provide more value to investors during economic boom times
than during recessions.
</P>
<P>
   But over all, the professors said, the results suggest that
analysts generally react to changes in stock prices rather than
cause those changes, Which makes it seem that investors would be
well advised to shut out all the yammering about earnings
expectations, consensus forecasts and whisper numbers and focus
instead on the financial information reported by companies
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, investors are deluged with data today. This is, after
all, the information age. The Enlightenment, however, it is not.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 1943EDT &QL; 
