<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USCAN-FIRSTPERSON0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grocery scanning not stress-free
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From now on I'm only picking the Vidalia onions with
coded stickers.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the lessons I learned during my first encounter
with a Kroger U-Scan.
</P>
<P>
   I hoped for a stress-free experience. Instead it was filled with
anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   I rolled the cart through the aisles, picking up romaine
lettuce, bananas, half-and-half and a few other things. I tried to
keep an eye on prices, in case they didn't scan properly.
</P>
<P>
   With 10 items I qualified for the U-Scan Express lane. When I
arrived, one machine was down, the other in use.
</P>
<P>
   I was cleared for scanning about 30 seconds later (it felt like
10 minutes). I was already feeling rushed as I approached the
machine. A line had formed behind me and the shoppers looked
impatient. The pressure was on.
</P>
<P>
   My first item scanned with ease. Then, a problem. My pole beans
had no code. Within 15 seconds or so, a nearby employee watching my
transaction through a camera noticed the problem and punched in the
code. I scanned on, only later noticing the clerk inadvertently
coded my beans as snap beans, which are cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   The people in line were watching. I tried to hurry.
</P>
<P>
   The machine stopped again because it sensed I had not placed an
item into a bag when I did. It's one of the ways U-Scan machines
guard against fraud. The employee could see I had and cleared me to
keep scanning.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I finished. Next came the payment. I had to dig into my
purse for my wallet, something I'd usually do while waiting for the
clerk to finish scanning my items. I found it after what seemed an
eternity, and pulled out my credit card to swipe. I never checked
prices on most of the items I bought.
</P>
<P>
   What's the total, I wondered? I wasn't sure, but my transaction
was done and the people behind me were staring. I grabbed my
receipt and made for the exit.
</P>
<P>
   On the way past the employee at his computer I noticed he was
sweating, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
