A6241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-USCAN-MAIN0617-COX     06-16 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USCAN-MAIN0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New machines allow shoppers to scan their own groceries.
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Robert Sunday never imagined he'd be a grocery
checkout clerk. But he gladly does the job for free at his
neighborhood Kroger.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, 29, uses the express self-checkout line, where he scans
and bags his own groceries, then feeds money into a machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've used it ever since the service started,'' Sunday said
during a recent shopping run.
</P>
<P>
   And how easy is it to use? Sunday cites himself as evidence.
``I'm not a computer-head,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The self-checkout stations, called U-Scan Express, have been
limited to shoppers checking out 15 items or less, and only some
stores have them.
</P>
<P>
   But they are showing up in growing numbers. Retailers view the
technology as a tool to help solve labor shortages and cut costs.
Other grocery chains and big-box retailers such as Wal-Mart are
experimenting with self-checkout, and there are models in
development for pharmacies and video stores.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a Kroger store in Atlanta became the first in the
nation to install a larger self-scanner, dubbed U-Scan Carousel,
that can handle bigger orders. Other grocers and superstore chains
could be getting them soon, according to the machine's maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kroger is the first company to jump on it,'' said Neil
Wechsler, chief executive officer of Optimal Robotics Corp., of
Montreal. ``By the end of the summeron't think that retail
understands that not everybody is obsessed with racing through the
store.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Kroger said there's no plan to eliminate the
human element entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one answer to help our customers get through the
line quicker,'' said spokeswoman Susie Brower. ``It's to address
the shortage of workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The retail industry is one of the lowest paying professions,
which makes hiring and retaining employees even harder.
</P>
<P>
   Self-checkout machines are appearing at time when bank ATM
machines, and more recently the Internet, have given people more
confidence with automated transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But there are issues associated with self-checkout.
</P>
<P>
   Cheating is one. Shoppers might try to slip extra items in their
grocery bag without scanning or paying. Kroger has an employee
stationed in front of the exit, who can view the action at each
U-Scan station through a screen connected to cameras in the
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Also, U-Scan senses when items are placed in a bag. Thes have
the machines and another 13 locations will have the Express
stations by the end of this year, Atlanta division President Paul
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Observers believe shoppers better get used to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kroger is thinking about replacing all the lanes in the
store,'' said Neal Johnson, an analyst with Robinson-Humphrey, who
follows Optimal Robotics. ``If the past is any example, Kroger will
test U-Scan Carousels in a few locations to get a fair analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Of shoppers spending $75 or more on groceries weekly, one in
three seek out interaction, said consumer researcher Britt Beemer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're making the people invisible _ even your best
customer'' said Beemer, president of America's Research Group in
Charleston. ``I don't think that retail understands that not
everybody is obsessed with racing through the store.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Kroger said there's no plan to eliminate the
human element entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one answer to help our customers get through the
line quicker,'' said spokeswoman Susie Brower. ``It's to address
the shortage of workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The retail industry is one of the lowest paying professions,
which makes hiring
</P>
<P>
   The cameras also enable employees to punch in codes for produce
items if they aren't marked.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem is logjams caused by customers who
either don't understand the process or are simply slowpokes. The
nearby employee can intervene when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Kroger is not the only grocery chain deploying such devices.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Teeter has express-lane scanners installed in 16 stores
in the chain. The chain plans to test a U-Scan Carousel at at
several stores in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has installed U-Scans in about 20 stores, but none in
Atlanta yet. Bi-Lo and Cub Foods also have the machines in some
locations.
</P>
<P>
   Winn-Dixie has self-scanners installed in 10 of its area stores
from Productivity Solutions, a U-Scan competitor. Those scanners
can handle any size checkout, a spokesman for the company said.
</P>
<P>
   U-Scan's Wechsler said part of U-Scan's appeal lies in giving
people the impression they are more in control of their own
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're actually doing something,'' Wechsler said, ``the
perception is it's faster than doing it in line.''
</P>
<P>
   Wechsler said the company has also developed a one-bag unit to
go into pharmacy or home-and-garden departments, or in video and
floral stores. He also thinks superstores and office stores will
sign on to the big-order scanners.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
