<HEADER>
A6262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-LOSALAMOS-B     06-16 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-LOSALAMOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANGEROUS SECURITY LAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disappearance of two computer hard drives from a vault in
the X Division, or nuclear weapons section, of the Los Alamos
National Laboratory was a cause celebre for grandstanding
politicians and wisecracking comedians right up until the minute it
was reported Friday that they had been found in a secure area of
the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing funny, however, about the security lapses
exposed in the case and the potential danger to Americans should
such information ever fall into the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   The data on the two small hard drives consists of information
that could enable members of the Nuclear Emergency Search Team to
locate and disable nuclear devices on American soil. This catalog
of nuclear signatures represents an indispensable instrument that
the team's experts may use to overcome an enemy's efforts to cloak
or conceal a nuclear weapon planted here.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the two hard drives could be thought of as components of a
defense against the nuclear arms most likely to be used _ or
deployed for blackmail _ against this country.
</P>
<P>
   In the possession of a terrorist, the missing hard drives could
yield hints on how to disguise a nuclear device on American soil
from the detection specialists on the Nuclear Emergency Search
Team. They could also disclose the designs of Russian nuclear
weapons as well as America's sources and methods for learning about
Russian, Chinese, or French nuclear weapons designs.
</P>
<P>
   The US Department of Energy, which has responsibility for Los
Alamos and other national nuclear labs, received most of the blame
for the lax security that allowed 26 of the 86 members of the
Nuclear Emergency Search Team to have access to the hard drives
without having to leave any record that they removed the hard
drives from the vault.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians have derided this laxity, saying there is tighter
security at their hometown libraries or Wal-Marts.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the Energy Department does not deserve the entire
blame for whatever went wrong at Los Alamos. Last December, the
Energy Department proposed and the Defense Department rejected a
plan to improve nuclear weapons security by reclassifying as ``top
secret'' information such as the data on the lost hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   That information is now classified as ``secret restricted
data,'' a less restricted category. Late in the Bush
administration, the government proposed that, for the sake of
openness, ``secret restricted data'' would not have to be tracked
and its users would not have to be identified. The change was
carried out by the Clinton administration in 1993, although it was
initially resisted by the labs.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the Pentagon's reasons for opposing the changes
in classification look penny-wise and pound-foolish. An assistant
secretary of defense wrote to the Department of Energy's security
chief last December to explain that the cost would be too steep for
``secret storage facilities and buying more secure computer
equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as investigators probe how the hard drives were misplaced
for more than a month _ and whether they might have been misused _
one crucial lesson should be that cyber-age security requires a
thorough revision of the rules governing access to such sensitive
information.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be hard to devise a security system that restricts
and monitors users of the data in the Los Alamos vault yet permits
the Nuclear Emergency Search Team members, in an emergency, to
remove the hard drives and take them to a site where they may help
detect and disarm a nuclear explosive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
