A6264 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CORONARY-BO     06-16 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CORONARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ROUTE TO A HEALTHY HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 18, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time and again, researchers have offered tips for warding off
life-threatening diseases by suggesting that we eat certain foods
or avoid others, or take this hormone supplement but not that one.
Much of this advice is based on incomplete experimentation, and
sometimes it doesn't hold up when better work is done. Lately,
scientists have focused on a new villain in our blood,
homocysteine, and are proposing that we keep it at healthy levels
by passing up animal protein and getting more of the B vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   Chastened, perhaps, by the recent finding that a high-fiber diet
does not in fact protect against colon cancer, researchers are less
emphatic than they might once have been in calling for dietary
changes to keep homocysteine down. What they do know is that high
levels of this amino acid, a product in the body's breakdown of
protein, are associated with arterial disease. Still to be proven
is that eating less animal protein or more vitamin B6, B12, or
folate (another B vitamin) will actually reduce our risk of
cardiovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
   While the jury is still out on that count, the evidence of the
benefit of folate (also known as folic acid) in preventing birth
defects is so strong that for the past two years bread, pasta and
cereals have been fortified with it under a mandate from the US
Food and Drug Administration. In addition, homocysteine has been
linked to miscarriages, Alzheimer's disease, strokes, and
osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   All of this builds a strong case for eating foods rich in folate
or vitamin B6: asparagus, broccoli, spinach, cabbage, orange juice,
bananas, avocados, wheat germ, lentils, oatmeal, chicken, and egg
yolks. The last two items on the list show that dispensing with
animal proteins altogether is tricky, especially since vitamin B12
is found only in liver and other meats, fish, eggs, and milk.
Vitamin supplements are an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be forgotten is the meditation factor. A study at Ohio
State University shows that stress can raise homocysteine levels.
The message is simple: yoga and yolks. Now if only someone would
invent an egg with a low cholesterol content.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
