<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-HEIR (Jackson, Miss.) _ The legend was that if you
touched Robert Johnson you could feel the talent running through
him, like heat, put there by the devil on a dark delta crossroad in
trade for his soul. It is why Claude Johnson's grandparents would
not let him out of the house that day in 1937 when Robert Johnson,
his father, strolled into the yard. Robert Johnson, the famous,
almost mythical blues man, had come to Lincoln County to see Virgie
Jane Smith and a son he had never seen. Claude wants to believe
that Robert came for him that day, and he always wondered what
would have happened if he had run across that porch to him, so that
everyone would know he was Robert Johnson's son. Now, 63 years
later, the Mississippi Supreme Court has ruled that Claude Johnson,
a retired gravel truck driver who lives quietly in Crystal Springs,
truly is the flesh and blood child of a man so mythologized that
many people do not know where the legend ends and the truth begins.
By Rick Bragg. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT15.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer: U.N.-ISRAEL-LEBANON (United Nations) _ Secretary-General
Kofi Annan certifies Israel's withdrawal from southern Lebanon,
opening the way to a more robust U.N. peacekeeping presence along
Lebanon's often-troubled border with Israel. By Christopher S.
Wren. (The story has moved in ``i'' category.) 1,000 words.
</P>
