<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6268 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DEATHROW0617-COX     06-16 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHROW0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death penalty politics brings media attention to inmatesBy Jamie
Manfuso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON, Texas _ Wednesday is media day on Texas' death row.
And the recent national glare on the state's justice system has
made the supersecure Terrell Unit, where death row is located, a
popular place.
</P>
<P>
   A television crew led by Geraldo Rivera shines its lights on
Gary Graham, the death row inmate whose case has become a cause
celebre in recent weeks. Cameras zoom in as Graham wrings his
hands, a symbolic moment for a man scheduled to die by lethal
injection on June 22.
</P>
<P>
   In a cubicle across the room sits Victor Hugo Saldano. He is one
of at least seven death row inmates whose sentencing hearings
included testimony that their Hispanic or black heritage made them
more dangerous in the future. Saldano hopes to get a new sentencing
hearing, and he, too, is telling his story.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the backs of the crew, in another cubicle, sits Paul
Nuncio, literally and figuratively out of the spotlight. Nuncio
grins nervously as he speaks, revealing a crooked gap between his
front teeth.
</P>
<P>
   A day later he would be dead, number 22 this year in the state's
modern and efficient capital punishment machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no fears,'' he says. ``I have made my peace.'' But his
upper body visibly trembles, and it takes him 20 seconds to sign
each release form granting an interview. He seems not to realize
what's going to happen the next day. He continues pulling out all
of the stops _ he's mentally unstable, he says, DNA will clear him,
his trial lawyer was incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they proclaim themselves guilty or innocent, some
inmates have taken advantage of the escalating national debate over
the death penalty and the attention surrounding Gov. George W.
Bush's run for president. Still, it remains to be seen if the
attention will have any impact for them.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Angel Flores, convicted for the 1989 kidnapping, sexual
assault and murder of a 20-year-old woman, said curiosity led him
to accept an interview with the Spanish language television
network, Telemundo. Still, he isn't sure being cast as a bit player
in a presidential contest will necessarily play out in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   He knows national support for the death penalty, though
decreasing lately in some polls, is still overwhelming, and that
any concessions could make Bush look weak on crime. Of course, he
adds, the execution of an innocent man, if discovered, could be
tragic for governor's presidential ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not jealous of the other guys,'' says Flores, referring to
better-known inmates like Ricky McGinn, who received a 30-day
reprieve minutes before his scheduled execution on June 1 to allow
for DNA testing. Flores is happy for them, but he'd like to see the
focus change to the widespread problems that affect more inmates,
like ineffective counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, whose execution date has not been set, doesn't contest
that he is innocent. ``All I want is a fair sentencing hearing,''
he says. In his first hearing, a psychiatrist testified that Flores
would be violent in the future without examining Flores himself or
his psychological records. The U.S. Fifth Circuit Court in April
said the psychiatrist's testimony lacked scientific validity.
</P>
<P>
   It is stories like Flores' that feeds the ongoing debate and
beckons journalists from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Media requests for interviews have increased ``1000 percent''
over the past two to three months, estimated Glen Castlebury, a
spokeman with the Texas Department of Criminal Justice. He
attributes most of the increase to national and international media
organizations. Over recent weeks he has been forced to limit the
visits mainly to Texas state media. Or at least he tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French, they do not translate the English word 'no','' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly not business as usual for prison officials.
Between shoots, Castlebury said, Rivera goes out to his vehicle, a
Lincoln parked in a handicap parking space, to dab at his makeup.
Prison guards on break venture out for photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The increased attention comes as Texas lawmakers and
representatives push reforms in the criminal justice system. Last
week, State Senator Rodney Ellis announced plans to introduce
legislation that would allow DNA testing in limited circumstances.
This week, a congresswoman from Houston and a congressman from San
Antonio called for a statewide moratorium on executions in the
state and a full review of Graham's case.
</P>
<P>
   A study released Monday by the Columbia University School of Law
said appeals courts found serious errors in 68 percent of murder
trials that ended with death sentences between 1973 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there's renewed questions and debates going on and
everybody's jumping on the bandwagon,''said Stan Schneider, a
Houston attorney with four clients on death row. ``You can't ignore
the fact that it's a presidential election year.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney David Cunningham, who visited three death row
inmates on Thursday, said inmates are ``glad for any ruling that
can help an inmate in their situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect recent events to have any immediate impact on
inmates' cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives us some hope, but they've killed two people in two
days,'' he said on Friday. ``It doesn't seem to be doing anything
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Cynthia Orr said most death row inmates have lost hope.
It's an environment that's tough on hope: inmates are locked up in
air conditionless cells 23 hours a day. They can still follow the
latest turns in the death penalty debate in newspapers and on the
radio. But restrictions against television in their cells means
most will never see Geraldo again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
