<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-AIRLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGERS IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, June 19, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prospective purchase of US Airways by UAL Corp., owner of United
Airlines, has already drawn concern from employees, competitors,
and regulators. While there are solid arguments in favor of this
undertaking, its size and the increasingly international character
of airlines call for better coordination of merger objectives not
just within the United States but among all countries.
</P>
<P>
   United and US Airways are well-suited to the combination because
they are to a large degree complementary to each other rather than
competitive. They have anticipated some antitrust challenges by
agreeing in advance to transfer critical landing rights in
Washington, D.C., to a new airline and by announcing a freeze on
air fares other than adjustments for fuel costs and inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidated airline would be significantly larger than any
other domestic carrier, which over time could provide it with
advantages in some intensely competitive markets. Its very broad
geographical reach would provide travelers with more single-carrier
options, reducing or eliminating the need to race through airports
to make connections.
</P>
<P>
   The UAL-US Airways agreement is far from complete but has
already spawned talks among other carriers _ American and Delta in
this country and British Air and KLM in the European Union.
Transnational mergers involving US carriers would be more complex,
but they are not intrinsically impossible or undesirable, assuming
they meet reasonable standards to guarantee passenger protection
against monopoly powers.
</P>
<P>
   Should there be international coordination, the critical
standard should be guarantees of competition in a maximum number of
markets and especially at key airports and in heavily traveled
corridors like Boston-New York-Washington in this country. The
industry has a history of international cooperation along with
competition, and national governments often negotiate over specific
markets. Such a merger would raise the level of negotiation to a
broader policy perspective _ and there is no need to wait for the
next consolidations before taking it up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
