</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-ING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS BETWEEN AETNA AND DUTCH COMPANY FALTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aetna Inc. indicated Friday that negotiations to sell
its financial services and international units to ING Group, the
Dutch financial services and insurance company, had hit a bump.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna said it had started talks with other, unnamed possible
buyers while continuing negotiations that it began two weeks ago
with ING.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Aetna fell $3.875, or 5.3 percent, to $69.50 Friday on
the New York Stock Exchange, reflecting disappointment among
traders who had bet on an imminent sale of the units to ING for $8
billion or $9 billion, as well as generally lower prices for
insurance stocks.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Donaldson, the chairman and chief executive of Aetna,
said that talks with ING, which were disclosed May 31, were
continuing. He said Aetna was evaluating ``numerous expressions of
interest'' by companies that wanted to buy its non-health-care
units.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said the announcement could mean that ING
was not interested in buying all of Aetna's financial and
international units. Some said ING probably did not want the
Hartford, Conn.-based insurer's Latin American health business,
which had been a drag on earnings. Others speculated that there
were tax issues for Aetna or ING or both that made it difficult to
agree on a price.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Richter, an analyst at Banc of America Securities, said
that if a buyer like ING did not take the whole package, selling
the units piecemeal could be a complicated, lengthy process. ``A
bird in the hand is often worth two, three or five birds in the
bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson reiterated that there were no assurances that there
would be a sale. When the talks with ING started two weeks ago, he
said Aetna was still ready to split the company into health and
``wealth'' divisions and spin them off to shareholders as separate
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Arun Kumar, an investment-grade bond analyst at Chase
Securities, said he was sure a sale of the financial and
international units was still likely. ``It's a matter of when, and
not if, they will announce a definitive sale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Laberge, a spokesman for the company, declined to say what
was holding up a deal with ING or how many interested buyers were
now talking with Aetna.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Clark, an insurance industry analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's,
said other big financial-services companies that might be
interested include Allianz AG of Germany, Fortis of Belgium and
Aegon of the Netherlands. He said American companies like Citigroup
and American International Group were less likely to be interested.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Aetna dropped into the $30s in February on news of
lawsuits against the company and disappointing financial results.
Under pressure from large investors, Richard L. Huber resigned as
chief executive on Feb. 25 and was replaced by Donaldson, a board
member and a co-founder of the Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
securities firm..
</P>
<P>
   After rebounding, the price slid back into the high $50s after
the company rejected an earlier offer in March from ING and
WellPoint Health Networks, a California insurer that wanted to open
discussions about paying $10 billion or so for all of Aetna's
businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
