<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6276 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DEATH-PENALTY-BOS &LR;      06-16 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL DEATH PENALTY IN MURDERS ON SHAKY GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aquilla Barnette lurked in the woods, along the Billy Graham
Parkway in Charlotte, N.C., a sawed-off shotgun in his hand. He
waited until a car paused at a light. Then Barnette rushed over,
that summer day in 1996, aimed the shotgun at motorist Donald Allen
and forced him out of his Honda Prelude.
</P>
<P>
   Barnette had the car, but shot Allen anyway: Three times in the
back as he begged for his life.
</P>
<P>
   The case _ similar to last week's execution-style slaying of
college students Amy Shute and Jason Burgeson in Johnston, R.I. _
is the first homicide prosecuted by the federal government under a
1994 carjacking statute that resulted in a death sentence. But in
May a judge ordered resentencing. It's a telling example,
specialists say, of how these cases typically ricochet in the
federal court system, frustrating family members hoping for the
ultimate punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The public reacted with outrage to the June 9 carjacking murders
of Shute and Burgeson. Residents immediately began signing
petitions, asking Attorney General Janet Reno to take the case and
apply the death penalty statute.
</P>
<P>
   But as Rhode Island prosecutors prepare to ask for federal
prosecution _ in part so they can seek capital punishment, which
would not be possible under state law _ they know the chances of
seeing the suspects executed are slim.
</P>
<P>
   The Barnette case is one of about 200 cases prosecuted under the
federal law, which allows the government to seek death sentences
for those who commit murders connected to drug dealing, robberies,
carjackings, terrorism, abductions, and a list of other offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Of those cases, only about two dozen have resulted in death
sentences, according to the Federal Death Penalty Resource Council
Project. And of those, 13 are either on appeal, or are being
retried or resentenced.
</P>
<P>
   No federal death row inmates have been executed since the
government reinstated capital punishment in 1988. Because the
penalty is irreversible, juries and judges take special care with
them, and the appeals process can take many years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is a growing sense that the US Supreme Court
will eventually chip away at the federal government's claim to
jurisdiction in these capital offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a few Supreme Court cases that seem to be
saying the federal government may have gone too far,'' said William
Matthewman, a Florida lawyer who has defended a number of federal
death penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   Congress gave the Department of Justice the right to prosecute
cases by tying it to a provision in the Constitution that grants
the federal government the ability to pass laws that prohibit
interference with interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But using this provision in murders, critics say, some
prosecutors have used some fairly twisted logic. For example,
Matthewman said, for a murder at a 7-11 convenience store, federal
prosecutors could argue that the store sells products trucked in
from other states.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rhode Island case the connection could be that the men
who allegedly carjacked Burgeson's SUV, before killing Berguson and
Shute, had stolen a car that was assembled in another state.
</P>
<P>
   Five men participated in the carjacking, according to
investigators: Gregory Floyd and Raymond Anderson, both 19; Sammie
Sanchez, 20; and 21-year-olds Kenneth Day and Harry Burdick.
</P>
<P>
   Shute, 21, of Coventry, R.I., had been at a Providence night
club with Burgeson, 20, of Lakeville, Mass., and other friends and
Burgeson was planning to drive her home.
</P>
<P>
   The five men ambushed the two friends in downtown Providence at
gunpoint, drove them to the Buttonhole Golf Course in Johnston, and
stole $18 from them. The two pleaded, ``Please don't kill us,'' as
Floyd allegedly shot them. Police say Floyd confessed on videotape
that he pulled the trigger of the .40-caliber gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crime was so horrendous. It was like they did it for
fun,'' said Ernest Burgeson, Jason's father. ``There was no reason
for them to kill. It was two in the morning and it was pretty dark.
If they had a halfway decent lawyer they could've beaten the
(carjacking) charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgeson said even if the men are sent to death row, and are
never executed, a death penalty sentence means they will at least
spend the rest of their lives behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Without federal prosecution, he worries, the men might spend a
few years in jail, be paroled, and repeat their crime. All five
suspects have criminal records. Providence and Johnston
investigators are now looking into whether Floyd was responsible
for other robberies and car thefts in Providence this year that
went unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island Attorney General Sheldon Whitehouse said this week
that he favors federal prosecution. If Reno accepts the case, it
would be one of dozens reviewed by the US Justice Department. A
justice department official said that 69 cases of carjackings
resulting in death have been reviewed by the department since 1994.
Of that number, 15 were accepted for prosecution. But only one has
resulted in a death sentence: The Barnette case of Charlotte, N.C.
He is currently awaiting resentencing.
</P>
<P>
   In the Johnston case, the federal government can prosecute using
the carjacking or firearms provision of the law, said Paul
Rothstein, a professor at Georgetown Law Center. Rhode Island,
however, is not supposed to forward the case just to seek the death
penalty, he said, according to the law.
</P>
<P>
   A similar case is headed for trial in Springfield, Mass. this
year. Federal prosecutors will seek the death penalty for Kristen
Gilbert, a nurse who allegedly murdered a patient with injections
of epinephrine, a drug that induces heart attacks. Because the
death occurred at the Veteran's Administration hospital in
Northampton, Mass., it falls under federal jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Burgeson, Jason's father, will continue to push for the
death penalty. In his eyes, it's the only way to deter these crimes
from happening. And he doesn't mind sparking fear in the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it,'' he said. ``You're at a light. Your door
ain't locked. It could happen to anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 2000EDT &QL; 
