<HEADER>
A6279 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FRAMINGHAM-HEART-BOS &LR;      06-16 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAMINGHAM-HEART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHICS   SPECIALISTS TROUBLED BY PLAN TO SELL HEART STUDY DATA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medical ethicists warned Friday that Boston University is
wandering into ethically challenging geography with its plans to
sell data derived from the famous heart study of 10,000 Framingham,
Mass. residents. But ethicists said that, with the right
safeguards, the for-profit venture could benefit the public.
</P>
<P>
   The university, which along with investors is forming a company
to compile, analyze, and sell the study's vast collection of
clinical, behavioral, and genetic data, must insure that the
Framingham participants consent to the new venture and that their
identities are protected, ethicists said.
</P>
<P>
   And because the families volunteered for a study largely funded
with public money, the new company should compensate the community
for its donation and make sure the data stays publicly accessible,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly things to be alert to,'' said Arthur
Caplan, director of the Center for Bioethics at the University of
Pennsylvania. ``The people who participated in the study for
decades, what are their rights? Whose permission do you get? Can
their data be used for any purpose? And given that it's a
government study, how do you distribute the money that's made?''
</P>
<P>
   BU officials said they're still working out the details of the
deal, but they are carefully addressing ethical concerns about the
new venture.
</P>
<P>
   Given the deal's preliminary nature, it's too soon to tell
whether the rights of participants will be protected, Caplan said.
But he added that those concerns must be weighed against the
potential benefits that investors, drug companies, and
biotechnology companies can bring to the data, X-rays, and DNA
samples, some of which now sits in boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to take this raw data to the next step takes a lot of
money,'' agreed Jay Lander, a lawyer in Framingham, a participant
in the heart study and a member of the organization formed to
represent the volunteers. ``We're not here to prevent that from
happening. It would be foolish to stifle research and keep it in
the academic archives. We just want it done above board and without
conflict of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston University, which runs the 52-year-old Framingham Heart
Study, has struck a deal with a group of venture capitalists, who
have committed $21 million to form Framingham Genomic Medicine Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Raw data from the heart study, which has been used by
researchers worldwide to publish more than 1,000 papers on the
causes of heart attacks and stroke, will still be available to the
public and to scientists cost-free.
</P>
<P>
   But Framingham Genomic Medicine will use computer tools to
analzye and expand the data, which the university believes it can
sell to pharmaceutical companies racing to create the next
generation of genetically developed drugs and diagnostic exams.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, the university must negotiate protections for
patients and ownership of the enhanced data with the National
Heart, Blood and Lung Institute, the government agency that has
spent more than $40 million to fund the heart study.
</P>
<P>
   One area of possible disagreement is genotyping, the process of
documenting variations among the participants' DNA that could
explain disease or differing reactions to drugs. Is the genotyping
raw data that belongs to the study and the government? Or, as
Framingham Genomics would prefer, is it proprietary data that
belongs to the company?
</P>
<P>
   BU spokesman David Lampe said the company does not intend to
obtain additional consent forms from participants because it
believes the existing consent forms cover commerical uses.
Volunteers can choose to withhold their data from the company, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Caplan said the issue of additional consent requires more
debate, while Ronald Green, director of the Ethics Institute at
Dartmouth College in Hanover, N.H., said ``as companies use
information given by generous volunteers, they have to think about
ways of giving back.''
</P>
<P>
   Framingham Genomics plans to donate stock to a charitable trust
for the town of Framingham and pay for an ethics oversight
committee and science education in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ronald Rosenberg of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
