<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6282 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-SIGNATURES-1S     06-16 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SIGNATURES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES BILL TO ALLOW ONLINE CONTRACT-SIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ore., Vt.)   (Eds: Rewrites story throughout. Adds art advisory.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ and JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted unanimously Friday to approve a
bill that catapults electronic commerce to a new level by allowing
consumers and businesses to sign contracts online and know that
their e-signatures are just as binding as those in ink.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, passed 87-0, had already been passed by the House and
now goes to President Clinton, who said Friday that he would sign
it into law.
</P>
<P>
   By giving electronic signatures the legal weight of paper
signatures, the new law would offers consumers the chance to sign
legally enforceable contracts for health insurance, bank loans and
brokerage accounts over the Internet, around the clock and with no
delay.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, consumers and businesses have to wait days or weeks
for paper contracts to be written, mailed, signed and returned.
</P>
<P>
   While many types of banking, insurance and brokerage accounts
can now be opened on the Internet, they still require a signature
on paper for final approval; that requirement would disappear.
Until now, taxpayers who have filed their taxes electronically with
the Internal Revenue Service have still needed to file a piece of
paper bearing their signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Financial institutions and insurance companies are expected to
save billions of dollars a year by eliminating the cost of
preparing paperwork and mailing it. Most records would be retained
electronically, doing away with the need for giant warehouses of
files to store the material.
</P>
<P>
   But while the legislation had overwhelming, bipartisan support
on Capitol Hill _ only four members of the House opposed the bill,
while 426 approved _ some consumer advocates expressed concern that
the law would lead to new types of fraud and identity theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't sat down to figure out how to protect consumers,''
said Margot Saunders of the National Consumer Law Center. She said
she worried that without a requirement for a paper signature,
criminals could easily ``forge'' electronic signatures on
everything from online purchases to credit-card applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are left to prove a negative,'' she said.
``Everything changes with electronic signatures.''
</P>
<P>
   The law goes into effect Oct. 1, and consumers and businesses
are expected to take advantage of it almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic commerce companies, like e-loan and Etrade, are all
set to take advantage of the legislation, and some of the larger
traditional banks like Citibank, which already do business online,
are expected to make adjustments quickly. A Baltimore company,
eOriginal, said it would offer completely electronic mortgages as
soon as the law allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill revolutionizes the way consumers, industry and
government conduct business over the Internet,'' said Sen. Spencer
Abraham, R-Mich., who helped steer the bill through Congress. ``It
is a tremendous cost-cutting tool because people and businesses can
now enter contractual arrangements without having to drive across
town, fly thousands of miles for a meeting or mail reams of paper
back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a nod to Democrats and consumer rights organizations, the
bill also helps protect the millions of people who do not have
access to the Internet or who worry about being defrauded in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This landmark legislation will ensure that consumer
protections remain strong in the technology age,'' Clinton said
Friday. ``It will help create new rules of the road for America's
high-tech community.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill does not specify what a digital signature will look
like, allowing companies, and ultimately the free market, to decide
what kind of technology works best.
</P>
<P>
   A signature could simply be strings of numeric code that is
encrypted _ scrambled and unscrambled _ or it could involve more
sophisticated devices, like scanners that read thumb prints or
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Since many consumers remain nervous about conducting these kinds
of transactions online, many institutions will probably try to
improve online security. Congress, too, has a role to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a lot more focus on watchdogging against
hackers,'' said Wyden. ``A hacker today is sort of like the guy who
goes around rattling all the windows and doors in a neighborhood,
and there is a pretty good chance he will find one open.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that develop this kind of security clearance online
are already scrambling to offer their services. One Utah company,
iLumin, plans to launch a ``digital handshake system'' next week
that would gather all parties involved in a cyber signing room to
help them securely complete their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The law would enable consumers to choose whether to do business
online or on paper. Certain sensitive legal documents will still
have to be produced on paper. For example, insurance and utility
companies must still send cancellation and termination notices
through the mail, wills cannot be executed over the Internet, and
products may not be recalled online. Mortgages must be foreclosed
on paper.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``My mantra through this all was consumer rights can't be
virtual rights,'' said Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who helped draft the
bill. ``They have to exist in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill made several serious stumbles during negotiations
between the House and the Senate versions, mostly over consumer
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Companies said Friday that their paperwork saving as a result of
the bill would be matched by new convenience and time-saving for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Crocker, a lobbyist who represents Charles Schwab, the
discount brokerage firm, said the bill would save Schwab and its
customers time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you open a Schwab account now, most of it can be done
online,'' he said. ``But you still have to print it out and do a
wet signature on the account agreement.'' Under the law, the
requirement of a paper signature is ended.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is also expected to benefit business-to-business
transactions. ``For instance, an automobile manufacturer will be
able to have complete contract negotiations with parts suppliers
online,'' said David Colton, a lobbyist for the Information
Technology Association of America. ``There are huge cost savings
associated with this, and the cost savings will ultimately be
passed on to the consumers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
