<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ESTATETAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDFALL FOR THE WEALTHY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, June 19, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With horror stories about family farmers forced off their land
and small business owners driven from their stores and offices,
Republican leaders in Congress have taken steps to eliminate the
federal estate tax. They have won the initial public relations
campaign and the first key vote. The House passed the measure by a
margin almost large enough to override a promised veto from
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate should avoid a veto fight by rejecting the
measure outright.
</P>
<P>
   Several issues are involved. Some small businesses do face a
threat from the tax now, but this problem can be cured with
targeted provisions. The loss to the Treasury _ the tax now brings
in some $20 billion a year _ raises the question of whether the
money could be used better elsewhere, for a prescription drug
program for the elderly, for instance, or even a tax cut for
persons more in need. Additionally, charities may lose an estimated
$1 billion a year if the tax is eliminated, since it now provides
an incentive for the rich to give tax-sheltered donations.
</P>
<P>
   Overriding all these considerations is the fact that the
proposal is enormously regressive, a colossal giveaway to the
nation's wealthiest families, at a time when the nation's income
gap is already growing relentlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, individuals can leave $675,000 (and couples
$1.35 million) to their heirs free of tax. That is scheduled to
increase to $1 million ($2 million for couples) by 2006. Less than
2 percent of Americans pay any estate tax at all, and most of those
pay modest amounts. Half of all estate taxes are paid by less then
10 percent of those who pay, or less than 0.2 percent of those who
die.
</P>
<P>
   It is amazing that the windfall for the wealthy inherent in
repeal of the estate tax is so popular. While Al Gore would retain
it, George Bush proudly says, ``I intend to abolish it.''
</P>
<P>
   This at a time when the real incomes of the poorest 40 percent
of society have actually declined in the last 20 years, while the
incomes of the wealthiest 1 percent have more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there is a sound reason or time for eliminating the
estate tax, this is not it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 2002EDT &QL; 
