<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ECORIDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIBBLING NATURE TO DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, June 19, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a continuing threat both to the environment and to orderly
lawmaking, Congress is being asked repeatedly to attach riders to
bills unrelated to the environment, riders that in the aggregate
would seriously erode protections won in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these riders arrive on the floor with little or no
debate and are pasted on to legislation deemed immune to defeat
because of their importance and unlikely to face a veto.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 of these riders have been identified in House or
Senate legislation, according to Defenders of Wildlife, drawing
from a variety of conservation organizations. They range from
relatively specific issues, like the transfer of 327 acres of land
in Maryland from the Fish and Wildlife Service to the Treasury
Department for a firearms training facility, to broad questions
like funding for prevention of global warming under the Kyoto
Protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Others would prohibit any change in oversight of the Army Corps
of Engineers, alter hardrock mining rules, affect land transfers in
the Cape Hatteras National Seashore, ease restrictions on slaughter
of bison in Yellowstone Park, reduce funding to cut greenhouse gas
emissions, freeze auto efficiency standards, cut funds for
protection of endangered species, expand cattle grazing on
vulnerable public lands, strengthen Army veto power over new
wildlife refuges, eliminate funding for protection of American
Heritage Rivers (like the recently designated Connecticut River),
and continue subsidized lumbering in the Tongass rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   A few of these proposals may be justified, but the manner in
which they are being run through the legislative mill, with neither
serious review nor debate, entitles skeptics to fear the worst.
Individually, few of the riders would have a profound environmental
effect, but together they constitute a serious threat. Equally
troubling, passing such riders would serve as precedent for further
attacks on unique national assets. Congress should shun them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
