A6290 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-DIV-OLY-CULPEPPER0617     06-16 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIV-OLY-CULPEPPER0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Culpepper endures hard knocks in Olympic bid
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ashley Culpepper might not be able to remember
it, but she did have at least one bad day this year.
</P>
<P>
   It came on May 11, when the former high school diver was warming
up for the 3-meter springboard competition in the FINA/USA Diving
Grand Prix at Fort Lauderdale, Fla. She came down too close to the
board and slammed her head against it, suffering a concussion and
opening a deep gash that required two staples to close. She not
only had to withdraw from the international meet, she had to be
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hit my hands and feet before, but never my head,''
Culpepper said. ``At first I didn't remember what happened to me
three days before that. I didn't remember coming to Florida. Some
of the stuff has come back, but I still don't remember that entire
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Even taking that accident into account, however, Culpepper said,
``Overall, this ytremendous. It's my best year so far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way better than we even dreamed,'' added Coach Scott
Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper, who now dives for Louisiana State, won the 3-meter
title at the NCAA championships this year. An even bigger moment,
though, came when a surgeon opened up her knee again.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper is one of many divers who came to the sport from the
sport of gymnastics, and she arrived with a body that showed the
battering of four-hour-a-day practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I came to diving, my body had pretty much had
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 11, she had her first knee surgery. She had another
at 16, which left her with no more cartilage to remove, just a lot
of bone spurs and bone chips. And that wasn't the scary part. When
she was about 9, doctors discovered that she had a bone disease in
her femur, the same kind that Bo Jackson had in his hip and which
ended the football and baseball careers of that incredible athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bone just dies,'' said Culpepper. ``I thought I was going
to have to have a full knee replacement when I was 25 instead of
65. The doctor was expecting to find a disaster area.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he found signs that the bone was becoming healthy
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disease just upped and disappeared. I don't know how, but
thank God it did,'' Culpepper said.
</P>
<P>
   After the surgery she was scheduled to be out of the water for
six to eight weeks. She was back in by four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did tons of rehab. It took a lot out of me,'' Culpepper
said. Until this year she had been known mainly as a platform
diver. But, with an improved knee and jumping ability, her
springboard diving dramatically improved.
</P>
<P>
   At the NCAA championships, Culpepper not only won the 3-meter
title, she finished third in the 1-meter springboard and fifth in
the platform. At the U.S. National Indoor Diving Championships this
April, she led the 3-meter and platform competitions heading into
the final dive. She didn't nail either effort and finished second
in the 3-meter behind Sara Reiling and fourth behind winner Kathy
Pesek in the platform. Yet she and Reich were very encouraged that
she was that close in both events.
</P>
<P>
   The head injury in May was a setback, and Culpepper is still
coping with that accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a couple of weeks to get going on that dive,'' she
said. ``Now I do it about four feet from the board. I used to do it
a foot and one-half. I'm going to have to bring it back in before
the trials or I won't score as well. I just have to suck it up and
forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic diving trials in Federal Way, Wash., begin on
Tuesday (June 20) and Reich said, ``She has to be one of the
favorites. She's made a ton of improvement, and she has always been
a great competitor. She's qualified in two events, so she has two
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my chances are pretty good in both events,'' Culpepper
said. ``I don't have that much pressure going in. I just started
getting really good this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich added, ``She's always been a hard worker. I think she's
grown as a person. She's learned how to deal with adversity and how
to set priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, it looked as if this would be Culpepper's only
shot to make an Olympic team, and that it would be something of a
long shot. Now, she said, 2004 might not be out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper said, ``I don't know . . . If I can stay healthy for
another four years. With all the progress I've made this year I
don't think I've peaked.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
