A6291 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HARVARD-STARTUPS-BOS &LR;      06-16 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-STARTUPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY SCHOOL TIGHTENS DOWN ON FACULTY-STUDENT BUSINESS LINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to avoid conflicts between academic standards and the
new economy, Harvard's Kennedy School of Government has set some of
the strictest limits to date on faculty involvement in student
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The school told professors in a memo last week to avoid
advising, investing in, or consulting for commercial ``enterprises
in which Kennedy School students are involved'' until three months
after they graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules go beyond some adopted by Harvard's business
school last fall, when professors were warned against taking on
financial roles in companies run by students still at the school.
Both policies come at a time when when every classroom idea seems
loaded with commercial possibilities on the Internet, and when many
students _ especially those at schools that stress
entrepreneurialism and innovation, such as the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology _ are spending more efforts on their
business plans than on thesis work.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty connections can be key to the success of these
start-ups. But some, like the Kennedy School's dean, Joseph Nye,
worry professors might lose credibility if they become too involved
with student companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one student in class gets an A, and one gets a B, if
student A is in a position to make the professor a lot of money,
compared to student B . . . you can see how over time it could have
a corrupting effect on the morale of the student body,'' Nye said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Nye and William Sahlman, a Harvard Business School
professor, say the rules aren't meant to discourage faculty from
discussing business plans informally.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some young capitalists still regard the new limits as red
tape. Venture capital and other support comes easier to companies
with big-name connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole business concept can be validated'' by participation
of the faculty members, said Gilberto Carrasquero, who just
received a master's degree from the Kennedy School.
</P>
<P>
   Carrasquero, 36, helped prompt the school's new policy when he
tried unsuccessfully to sign up Nye as a formal adviser to a
company he is creating, govXchange.com.
</P>
<P>
   The company will sell government procurement services online in
developing nations and record the transactions publicly, which
Carrasquero says will help reduce corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Carrasquero said he agrees a student shouldn't be allowed to
hire a professor whose class he is taking. But once the course is
over, faculty or administrator participation can play a key role in
determining whether a business succeeds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Harvard graduate, Anish Rajparia, called the limits on
faculty involvement ``not the most advantageous'' for students.
</P>
<P>
   Rajparia created the Parlo.com languages Web site in New York
after he received his MBA in 1997 and counts a Harvard marketing
professor among his advisers and credits him with ``a lot of help
in defining our strategy.'' Students in the Kennedy School could
use the same help, he said, and faculty know their limits. The
chance a professor might compromise a student's grade, Rajparia
said, ``doesn't seem like much of a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what roles faculty should take in private ventures is an
old debate, but never in memory have so many enticements come from
students themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Also, schools such as Harvard, Northeastern, and Bentley College
are busy promoting entrepreneurship, licensing out research and
hosting contests in which students submit their business plans for
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts have done much to develop the region's technology
sector. Perhaps the best-known success story is routing-software
maker Akamai Technologies Inc. of Cambridge, Mass., created in 1998
by several students and faculty at MIT. At the close of Friday's
trading its stock was worth around $9.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many fret the success of such companies could blur academic
and commercial distinctions. John Guttag, head of MIT's computer
sciences department, said three years ago he discouraged students
and professors from joining in for-profit ventures while in school,
in order ``to make MIT look clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, contemplating the fortunes amassed by Akamai and others,
Guttag insists only that professors don't directly oversee the
academic work of any student with whom they have a financial
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company is being built around ideas that were really
partly the students', it doesn't make sense to deprive the students
of the opportunity to be involved,'' he said. ``That also means
it's wrong to deprive the faculty from being involved, because that
would limit the chance of the company to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Sticky situations are likely to increase as more schools become
business-incubators. Dartmouth's Tuck School of Business, for
instance, will introduce a new curriculum this fall to encourage
students and faculty to create companies together.
</P>
<P>
   According to a draft description, the new courses are needed
because ``a top school of management can no longer tolerate a
boundary between itself and the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuck's dean, Paul Danos, said he expects to decide soon just how
the spoils of the new ventures should be divided among students and
faculty. ``We'll definitely have to be creating rules between
grading and investing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Kennedy School, which traditionally fed graduates into
jobs in government or nonprofit organizations, lately has seen more
students looking to start their own companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this idea everybody has that they have to rush'' to
start a business, said Steve Kelman, a professor of public
management at the school. ``They feel they have to do it right now
or they'll lose their window.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the new rules, Kelman says he has become an adviser to
Carrasquero's company, govXchange.com, and may receive stock
options. The role is permitted because it was arranged before Nye
issued the new rules, Kelman said, and it doesn't present a
conflict because he didn't teach Carrasquero directly.
</P>
<P>
   After the three-month waiting period ends, Carrasquero said, he
also hopes Nye will take a role with his company.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he might still be interested, Nye responded by e-mail:
``No commitments till three months!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
