<HEADLINE>
GALAXY HEALTHY, MAYBE POISED FOR PUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The last month seemed like a long year for
Los Angeles Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid, but now the excuses are over.
With his team's tank nearly full again, it's time to make a serious
push. The Galaxy will get its first chance to do so when the Tampa
Bay Mutiny (8-6-0, 24 points) and Mamadou Diablo visit the Rose
Bowl tonight at 6:30.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy striker Cobi Jones and defender Greg Vanney have returned
from a two-week stint with the U.S. National team. Defender Robin
Fraser's injured ankle is healed and newly acquired Mexican striker
Luis Hernandez has had a full week of uninterrupted training.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Galaxy's eight-match slide - L.A. is 1-3-4 during that
span - actually turn into a positive?
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you come out of it,'' Schmid said. ``If you don't,
you're in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``But yes, a bad stretch can always help, it makes you work a
little harder, brings you closer as a team because you overcome
adversity together. It can also give you the feeling that you can
accomplish anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said he would like to see the players mentally assert
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to regain our confidence, our arrogance and our belief
in ourselves that we know we're going to figure a way to win,''
Schmid said. ``I don't think we've had that lately.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy (6-3-6, 24 points) has another home match Wednesday
against Chicago, then embarks on a 10-day, three-match road trip.
Schmid has been given permission by Major League Soccer to take his
entire roster of 18 players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next month is very important,'' Schmid said. ``This is our
time to really get together as a team, almost like our preseason
again.''
</P>
<P>
   He's already witnessed signs of cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the airport after the Colorado game, Luis was held up doing
something so Mauricio (Cienfuegos) bought his breakfast. Luis also
went to a record store with a few of the guys. This is the stuff
that brings you closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez scoring goals would bring everyone closer. The
two-time Mexican scoring champ has yet to record his first MLS
points after four MLS matches and a U.S. Open Cup match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luis has to be a little frustrated,'' Galaxy assistant Ralph
Perez said. ``What we are hoping for is that with Cobi back, we'll
play them up front together and hopefully they will find each other
with Mauricio also finding them in good position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
