<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XEROX-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XEROX WARNS STREET ON EARNINGS, PROMPTING SHARES TO PLUMMET 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Xerox Corp., besieged by strong competition in its
highest-margin product lines, debt problems in Mexico and upheaval
in its sales force, warned investors Friday that its second-quarter
earnings would be as much as 12 cents below analysts' expectations
of 42 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox issued similar warnings in the third and fourth quarters
of last year. Investors who had hoped the bad news was over when
the company met expectations last quarter demonstrated their
disappointment swiftly and harshly. They drove shares of Xerox down
almost 19 percent, to close at $20.563, down $4.75.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Xerox ousted its chief executive, G. Richard Thoman,
and returned its former chief, Paul Allaire, to the top spot. Anne
Mulcahy, 47, head of the company's general markets organization,
became president and is seen as the likely heir apparent. Analysts
doubt, however, that the new team has a quick fix for Xerox's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul and Anne found more maggots under the rock than they
expected,'' said David Nadler, a consultant to Xerox. ``They have
tremendous credibility with employees and customers, but they still
have to earn credibility on Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, although Xerox did not comment on future earnings,
analysts flooded First Call-Thomson Financial with lowered earnings
estimates for this year and next. ``No one thinks this is just a
one-quarter problem,'' said Charles Hill, director of research at
First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Xerox's problems stem from last year's sales force
reorganization in which the company made sales representatives
responsible for specific industries, not geographic territories.
Xerox also consolidated its customer administration offices,
resulting in numerous customer service problems. Thus, sales people
had to cope with new clients even as they fielded irate calls from
old ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients tell us it can take Xerox salesmen a week to return
calls,'' said James Lundy, a director at the technology research
firm Gartner Group. ``Xerox has to learn how to compete again.''
</P>
<P>
   Xerox management did not try to sugarcoat the company's
responsibility for its current woes. ``Most of our difficulties are
of our own making,'' Allaire told analysts in a conference call.
``The issues that led us to this point are largely the issues we've
talked about previously.''
</P>
<P>
   It is exactly that all-too-familiar ring that worries many
analysts. ``You could have listened to that conference call, and
said it's June 16, 1999, not 2000,'' said Jack Kelly, a Goldman,
Sachs analyst. ``The longer this turn-around takes, the higher the
probability that the problem is strategy, not execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Others worry that even one-time earnings disappointments may
point to deeper problems. Take, for example, Xerox's warning that
unexpected problems with customer receivables in Mexico could pare
more than 5 cents a share off the quarter's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Gibboney Huske, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston,
said, ``I'm less concerned that this will be a recurring item than
I am about the company's financial controls.''
</P>
<P>
   Xerox said the worries were misplaced. ``Our internal
investigation spotted the problem,'' said Christa Carone, a Xerox
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors, meanwhile, like Germany's Heidelberger
Druckmaschinen AG, Japan's Canon Inc., and most recently, IBM _
with a high-speed copier that uses a Heidelberger engine _ are
making deep in-roads into the market for super high-speed copiers,
Xerox's most profitable product line.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Xerox picture is not all bleak. The flood of
experienced sales representatives out of the company has slowed to
a trickle. Sales of color copiers have been brisk. Many analysts
have applauded the company's joint venture with Microsoft Corp. to
sell software, and its recent distribution deal with Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox will soon introduce high-priced office copiers and a line
of low-priced printers. Analysts say Xerox also is negotiating a
deal to bundle Xerox inkjet printers with a large computer
company's personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turnaround will take longer than we thought, but the long
term picture is bright,'' Huske said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
