<SLUG> BC-CAISSE-NVEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NVEST SOLD TO FRENCH MONEY MANAGER FOR $2.2 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHRYN TONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Asset manager Nvest LP, which has seen money flow out
of its funds for 10 straight quarters, was sold Friday to France's
second largest money-management company, $2.2 billion in cash and
debt.
</P>
<P>
   CDC Asset Management, the money management arm of Caisse des
Depots et Consignations, will pay $40 per limited partnership unit
for Nvest, double Nvest's closing price on Thursday. CDC also will
assume the Boston firm's $311 million in debt. Nvest and CDC said
that the combined company will have more than $300 billion in
assets. Nvest's stock priced more than doubled, to $37.625, as
investors responded to the news.
</P>
<P>
   The sale ends MetLife's four-year ownership of a 48 percent
stake in NVest. The New York insurance giant gained its stake in
NVest when it purchased The New England in 1996. MetLife is
retaining its ownership of State Street Research &AMP; Management,
another Boston fund firm.
</P>
<P>
   CDC hopes that the purchase will give the company a foothold in
the $7 trillion US mutual fund market, after its failed past
attempts to enter on its own. ``The acquisition of Nvest is an
important part of our strategy to become a global investment
house,'' said Gerard Barbot, chairman of the supervisory board of
CDC Asset Management. The joint company plans on developing a
presence in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Nvest, formerly known as New England Investment Cos., owns some
well-known investment firms including Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co., which
specializes in bonds; Capital Growth Management, run by star fund
manager Kenneth Heebner; the Kobrick family of funds; and
Chicago-based Oakmark funds. NVest manages $134 billion for
individuals and institutions.
</P>
<P>
   CDC oversees about $170 billion for investors, $5 billion of
which is in US hedge funds that invest in mortgage backed
securities. The company was founded by  &UR; Louis XVIII  &LR; in 1816 and
remains state-owned.
</P>
<P>
   Nvest's buyout follows a trend of European banks acquiring US
fund companies, including the purchase of The Pioneer Group Inc.,
another Boston mutual fund house, last month by UniCredito Italiano
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The high price that CDC is willing to by shows the determination
that foreign banks have in entering the US mutual fund market, said
Dennis Gallant, a consultant for Cerulli Associates Inc. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   MetLife Inc., the biggest US life insurer, will receive $858
million from the sale for its 48 percent stake in Nvest. ``Nvest
didn't really benefit MetLife's core business venture,'' said
Gallant. He predicts that the buyout will not affect either company
because each had separate distribution channels. MetLife, which
went public in April, has held its Nvest stake since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other Nvest shareholders will receive a cash out of $40 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Voss, Nvest's CEO, will continue to head the company. He
will join the CDC Asset Management's executive committee. Nvest
said it expects no layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Company headquarters will remain in Boston and be renamed CDC
Asset Management-North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
