<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6322 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUSH-VEEP0618-COX     06-16 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VEEP0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday
 &HT;    Bush looks to Cheney for guidance in choosing running mate
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - George W. Bush's one-man vice presidential
search committee comes battle-tested and with mom's seal of
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney is ``as competent as they
come,'' Barbara Bush wrote in her diary on March 2, 1991, as the
success of Operation Desert Storm had become apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems very laid back and reassuring. He does not have a Dr.
Strangelove image that so many of our secretaries of defense get,
whether they deserve it or not,'' Mrs. Bush wrote in the diary note
recounted in her autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a man who was President George Bush's second choice
_ to Texan John Tower, who failed to win Senate confirmation _ and
had never served in the military before becoming defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated to steal from our congressional ranks,'' the
ex-president later wrote of his selection of Wyoming's only U.S.
House member, ``but I knew Dick would be accepted on the hill and
would do a great job. I was right on both counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the next Bush who wants to be president is counting heavily
on Cheney to help find the right running mate for the November
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I trust Dick Cheney's judgment; I know his character,'' Bush
said in announcing Cheney's assignment in April. ''It's obviously
an important decision for me and I can't think of a better person
to work with on making that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently said he talks with Cheney roughly once every four
days as the process continues.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, 59, born in Nebraska and raised in Wyoming, arrived in
Washington in 1966 for a congressional fellowship. He advanced to
the Nixon White House, including a stint as deputy to White House
counselor Donald Rumsfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney worked on the transition team when Nixon resigned and
then-Vice President Gerald Ford took over, rising to chief of staff
in November 1975 at age 34, the youngest person to hold that key
post.
</P>
<P>
   When Jimmy Carter ousted Ford in 1976, Cheney went home to
Wyoming as an investment adviser. He won a House seat in 1978 and
served six terms, suffering three heart attacks along the way.
Cheney developed a reputation as a moderate, though he supported
military aide to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua, the invasion of
Grenada and the bombing of Libya, and opposed the Equal Rights
Amendment and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the elder Bush tapped him for defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Cheney became chairman of Halliburton Co., a
Dallas-based oil, engineering and construction firm, a job he gave
up in 1998 after a merger, but regained in February.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney toyed with the idea of running for president in 1996 but
did not.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the search process, Cheney has demonstrated the trait
that Bush covets most _ loyalty _ by remaining tight-lipped about
any speculation on a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, there are many good candidates to choose from in
our party,'' Cheney said when he took the assignment. ``We will
look at them all. And we will make sure we have the best possible
ticket this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who has been a Bush adviser since the campaign was in
its embryonic stage, had been considered a potential running mate.
But he squelched that speculation when he became the search
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Halliburton stockholders at a May meeting in Dallas,
he said: ``I made a long-term commitment to the company and I have
absolutely no desire to go back to government.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
