<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ALBRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT TO VISIT SOUTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to capitalize on the momentum of the
Korean summit meeting, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has
decided to visit South Korea next week and will stop immediately
afterward in China, where officials said she would also focus on
Korean developments.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's mission in Seoul will be to bless the policies of the
South Korean leader, Kim Dae-jung, that resulted in the summit
accord, and to stress that the United States supports the ultimate
goal of reunification, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main objective of direct North and South Korean dialogue
is that if you can move the discussion on reunification, you begin
to get momentum on other issues,'' an administration official said.
``There are opportunities here we don't want to miss.''
</P>
<P>
   The major issues for the United States include North Korea's
long-range ballistic missile program for which the administration
has proposed a $60 billion missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official is to meet North Korean officials at the
end of the month to try to persuade Pyongyang to agree to a
permanent moratorium on the flight testing of its long-range
missile.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the administration will publish in The Federal
Register the provisions of a broad lifting of economic sanctions
that have been in place since North Korea invaded the South 50
years ago. President Clinton announced the easing of sanctions in
September as a reward for North Korea's suspending missile testing
while talks on a longer-lasting ban proceeded.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the importance that the Clinton administration
places on the broad accord that North and South Korea reached, the
national security adviser of South Korea, Hwang Won-tak, who
attended the summit meeting, briefed Clinton on Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Kim, who is receiving accolades from U.S.
officials for the success of his ``sunshine policy'' toward the
North, telephoned Clinton to tell him details of the meeting, a
senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who had been planning to visit China next month for
what would probably be her last trip there as secretary, pushed the
trip forward so she could encourage Beijing to continue to be
helpful on North Korea. The United States and China have some
shared interests on the Korean Peninsula, primarily in avoiding
armed conflict between North and South.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
