A6331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ARK-CLINTON-BAR-NYT &LR;      06-16 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARK-CLINTON-BAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT ARKANSAS BAR'S GATHERING, FEW WILLING TO DISCUSS CLINTON CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOT SPRINGS, Ark. _ Exchanging pinstripes and flannel for golf
shirts and madras trousers, the Arkansas Bar Association munched,
sipped and seminared its way through its annual summer meeting here
with no official mention that its most famous member is in danger
of not being a member much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Even amid the coffee break congeniality and the cocktail hour
comradery, many of the thousand Arkansas lawyers gathered here, the
city where Bill Clinton spent his boyhood, were reluctant to
discuss the president's pending disbarment case, or the impact it
could have on a profession seemingly in perpetual need of a
public-relations makeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hush-hush sort of subject,'' sighed H.A. Taylor, a
trial judge from Pine Bluff. ``Lawyers want to talk about it, but
they want to talk about it privately.```
</P>
<P>
   When they do, their opinion on the appropriateness of disbarring
Clinton tends to break along party or ideological lines, if only
barely. Interviews with more than two dozen lawyers indicate that
party affiliation and past voting behavior do not necessarily
translate into support for a less-severe sanction than disbarment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's appropriate,'' said Laura E. Partlow, 44, of
Little Rock, an attorney for the Arkansas Human Services
Department, who said she had campaigned for Clinton and had twice
voted for him for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can make a contribution to society without a law license,''
Partlow said. ``I hear he's a great teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   John P. Lewis of Hot Springs, who was once a clerk at the 8th
Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in St. Louis, said he did not believe
that Clinton's conduct ``'s conduct ``rises to the level of
disbarment _ I don't know if it would even require a suspension of
his license.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the lawyers in my circle see it as a political
issue,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one condones lying under oath, but I'm ambivalent'' about
disbarment, said Ron C. Wilson, 41, of Marion, , one of a handful
of African-American lawyers at the convention. He said he
considered the case against Clinton to be ``somewhat political.''
</P>
<P>
   David K. Harp, a 51-year-old lawyer from Fort Smith, said that
while stripping Clinton of his law license ``seems extreme to me,
the consensus I hear is that another lawyer would have been
disbarred a long time ago'' for the same offense.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than a year since U.S. District Court Judge
Susan Webber Wright cited Clinton for contempt for giving what she
described as ``intentionally false, misleading and evasive''
testimony in a deposition in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
case.
</P>
<P>
   Wright fined Clinton $90,000 and referred the matter of his
testimony to the Arkansas Supreme Court's Committee on Professional
Conduct, which on May 19 recommended that the president be
disbarred. Clinton has said he will vigorously contest the action,
first in Circuit Court at Little Rock, and, if need be, at the
Arkansas Supreme Court, the state's ultimate arbiter on law
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   People with knowledge of the disbarment referral say that the
professional conduct committee has retained a special counsel to
press its case against Clinton and that it should be formally filed
by month's end. They also say preliminary maneuvering could delay
the case until after Clinton leaves office in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
