<HEADER>
A6337 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV18-B     06-16 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV18-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY IT HELPS TO GESTICULATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 18, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Micklethwait and Adrian Wooldridge are cosmocrats.
Oxford-educated, they travel the world relentlessly for London's
Economist magazine, as its United States editor and Washington
correspondent, respectively, poking noses into nooks and crannies
of interest to them. A few years ago they wrote a sprightly survey
of the management consulting industry, which they called ``The
Witch Doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   They also are, so far as I can tell, the coiners of the term
``cosmocrat'' _ meaning any cosmopolitan entrepreneur, corporate
executive, or bureaucrat who is involved extending the new world
order. Their new book, ``Future Perfect: The Challenge and Hidden
Promise of Globalization,'' is a higher, drier version of Thomas L.
Friedman's ``The Lexus and the Olive Tree: Understanding
Globalization''
</P>
<P>
   Future perfect is the verb tense of the English language wherein
human will and possibility are expressed together in terms of an
imagined concrete reality in some time from now, as in (they quote
from Tennyson), ``the wonder that would be.'' Most of the book
consists of an engaging tour d'horizon of those regions for which
The Economist functions as something of a weekly roadmap.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the three engines of globalization are described in some
detail under the headings of technology, capital flows, and modern
management. Five ``myths of globalization'' are controverted: that
size trumps all; that universal products triumph; that economics
must be rewritten; that globalization is a zero-sum game; that
geography no longer matters. Paradoxes are elucidated: that nation
states mean more in an age of globalization as world government
such as the United Nations means less; that winner-take-all market
means more for everyone else as well. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   One chapter in particular breaks new ground. The suspected
existence of a shadowy global ruling class has been a familiar
bugaboo for most of 20th century: the Masons, the Protocols of the
Elders of Zion, the Comintern, the Trilateral Commission and all
that. Yet the past 25 years of rapid globalization have finally
begun ``to produce a group of people who have the classic
characteristics of a class,'' the authors say. These are, of
course, the cosmocrats.
</P>
<P>
   Where do you find them? Not necessarily at the Swiss ski resort
of Davos in the winter, nor Nantucket and Easthampton on Long
Island in August, those being just the most exclusive annual
meetings of certain portions of the group. To see cosmocrats at
work, it is better to visit instead the enormous annual MIPCOM film
market in Los Angeles, for example; or the Comdex electronic trade
show in Las Vegas, the Academy of Management meetings in shifting
convention cities in the summer and the Frankfurt book fair in
Germany in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Who qualifies for membership? The backbone of the cosmocracy
still comprises the executives of the multinational corporations,
say the authors. But the proprieters of more and more start-ups are
finding their way in, often equpped with little more than a server
and and a web of contacts. There are the staffers of the ubiquitous
NGOs (non-governmental organizations, from the World Bank to the
Worldwatch Institute); of governments themselves and of the
universities. Professional services have become international:
money management, law, accounting, advertising, public relations,
and even political consultants now spin around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Not all cosmocrats are Westerners, naturally. McKinsey &AMP; Co.,
which the authors call the Vatican of the cosmocracy, is run by an
Indian; so is Bain &AMP; Co., which must be its Society of Jesus. Half
the teachers at the London Business School speak English as a
second language. But the culture of the international class is
denatured American. The authors offer Jack Welch's definition of
General Electric's ``universal values'': meritocracy, dignity,
simplicity, speed, and a hatred of bureaucracy. In the end,
membership is available to any who possess ``ideas, connections,
and sheer chutzpah'' to master the international economy.
</P>
<P>
   Where do you get in? The royal road remains the business school.
Where a college education from a fancy university used to be
enough, entry into the new elite may require an MBA, a law degree,
or something like it. Micklethwait and Wooldridge describe a
business school wedding to illustrate the bonding power among those
who spend their lives on global circuits. But in fact it is
probably the language acquired in school, the ``way of seeing,''
that unites alumni more deeply than anything else _ that and the
periodic reunions.
</P>
<P>
   A second institution that binds the cosmocracy together is the
professional service firm, consulting firms especially. (It used to
be investment banks.) Each year McKinsey screens 50,000 resumes to
hire 500 new associates. Arthur Andersen recruits receive 26 weeks
of training during their first five years. New consultants work
long hours in demanding jobs, moving rapidly from city to city and
industry to industry. In time, most move on to corporate jobs, and
in due course many of them become top leaders. ``The result is that
former consultants are beginning to form a quasi-masonic elite at
the summit of modern business,'' the authors write. Among the 5,000
alumni of McKinsey, they note, are the leaders of IBM, American
Express, and the Conservative Party of Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The final institution of importance is the Internet. Indeed, it
is not too much to say that the Net was designed by (academic)
cosmocrats, for cosmocrats. For them it is more than just a medium
of exchange for information. It is a community, unrestrained by
national rules and gender neutral, not to mention a potent source
of metaphor. Marriage is a great way of doubling your Rolodex, one
cosmocrat tells the writers; another refers to it as the ``ultimate
hotsynch,'' resorting to the language of _ what else? _ the Palm
Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the cosmocracy is described as an ``anxious'' elite.
Placelessness has its perils, it turns out. There's only so much
that can be learned in a succession of hotel rooms. For Ellen
Knapp, chief information officer of PricewaterhouseCoopers ever
since the two giant accounting firms merged in 1997, this
vulnerability is an opportunity. She spends nine days out of 10 on
the road teaching people to cooperate. Technology depends on trust,
Knapp tells the authors, and trust depends on personal
communication. E-mail often doesn't do the job unless its way has
been prepared by _ at least _ an introduction. ``It is important to
gesticulate,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen just how much clout the cosmocrats will
have, apart from organizations in which they serve. Even
Micklethwait and Wooldridge describe their hold on power in modern
politics as ``fragile.'' Many other organizations have more
leverage: political parties, the business community, trade unions,
the disciplines, the press and, yes, the family. At least in
successful organizations, all of the networks, the message traffic,
and reunions may count for less than a gesture, a touch, a joint
project, or even a shared cigarette between meetings. (That it must
be outside the building only increases the tightness of the bond!)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
