<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6341 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-U.N.-ISRAEL-LEBANON-1     06-16 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-ISRAEL-LEBANON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. CLEARS WAY FOR PEACEKEEPERS IN SOUTHERN LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for additions and reorganization. Changes throughout.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary General Kofi Annan Friday certified
Israel's withdrawal from southern Lebanon, opening the way to a
more robust U.N. peacekeeping presence along Lebanon's
often-troubled border with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end of the long road toward peace in the
region, but I hope it will be seen as the beginning of the end,''
said Annan, who promptly departed on a weeklong trip to a
half-dozen countries in the Middle East to discuss ways for the
United Nations to build on the achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The certification was challenged a few hours later when
Lebanon's prime minister, Salim Hoss, contended in Beirut that
Israeli troops still controlled some parts of the border are. He
did not identify the areas or their size, or threaten to withhold
cooperation with the U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary general's confirmation of the Israeli pullout to
the Security Council is significant because it credits Israel with
fulfilling an essential condition of Resolution 425, which the
Council passed in 1978. The resolution demanded that Israeli troops
pull out of the territory they had just occupied in southern
Lebanon to create a security buffer zone and now, Annan says,
Israel has done just that.
</P>
<P>
   With that accomplished, the 22-year-old resolution authorizes
U.N. peacekeepers to be deployed across southern Lebanon to help
the Lebanese government restore peace and security in the area and
reassert its lost authority.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the United Nations appeared to be embarking on yet
another peacekeeping operation at a time when its financial and
troop resources are already thinly stretched. As of this month, the
United Nations had 35,469 military personnel and police officers
deployed in 14 peacekeeping operations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike another operation being planned for Congo, the
mission in southern Lebanon offers unusually high prospects for
success at comparatively modest physical risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a happy day for Lebanon, but also for Israel,'' Annan
said. ``And it is a day of pride for the United Nations. It shows
that U.N. resolutions, when fully implemented by all parties
working together, can be the building blocks of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hoss said in a statement released in Beirut: ``There are
still several Israeli military outposts inside the Lebanese border.
And there are several tracts of Lebanese territory under Israeli
control in a flagrant act of encroachment.'' He did not specify
where the tracts were.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Lebanon's president, Emile Lahoud, warned that
his country might not recognize the U.N. findings if they were
``confined to a fictitious nonexisting line that does not reach the
existing internationally recognized frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary general and other officials have repeatedly
stressed that the United Nations is not demarcating the border
between Lebanon and Israel but merely confirming the line to which
the Israelis have withdrawn. This has meant verifying Israel's
pull-back across a frontier imperfectly defined in 1923, with
subsequent small adjustments, according to contemporary maps.
</P>
<P>
   After Annan telephoned Lahoud Friday to allay his concerns, the
announcement went ahead. But the mixed signals seem unlikely to be
clarified before Annan visits Beirut in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   During the inspection of the border, Lebanese officials have
repeatedly expressed reservations, and then supported the U.N.
effort. Some diplomats here suggested that the complaints of Hoss
and Lahoud were in good part for domestic consumption, to assure
the Lebanese people that their government will not cede any border
territory.
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat here said that Lebanon was worried that the
Israelis might try to turn the line of withdrawal identified by the
United Nations into their international border, causing the
Lebanese to forfeit some land.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the peacekeeping mission in southern Lebanon, called
by its acronym UNIFIL, was largely limited to looking on _ and
ducking _ while Islamic guerrillas in southern Lebanon fired
artillery and rockets into northern Israel and the Israelis
retaliated with airstrikes and cross-border raids. The peacekeepers
can now occupy fixed positions and conduct mobile patrols along the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Annan confirmed that the peacekeepers' main task now would be to
help the Lebanese government and its armed forces assume their
responsibilities along the border and throughout the area that
Israel has vacated.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary general's special representative in the region,
Terje Roed-Larsen, said that the peacekeeping mission would be
expanded to 5,600 troops, from the 4,400 now stationed in southern
Lebanon, in the first two weeks of July.
</P>
<P>
   Roed-Larsen, who was entrusted with handling the complex and
politically sensitive verification process, said that the Lebanese
government has already deployed 1,000 soldiers and internal
security troops in the border area.
</P>
<P>
   In his announcement, the secretary general said he hoped that
the international community would help Lebanon rebuild its economy
in the south and re-establish ties to the rest of the country.
``This will help move the whole country closer to peace and
stability,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed hope that the successful implementation of the
Council's resolution on Lebanon would encourage others in the
Middle East, ``especially Syrians, Palestinians and Israelis, as
well as Lebanese,'' to move faster in negotiating other peace
treaties based on two earlier Council resolutions, which also
called for Israel's complete withdrawal from occupied Arab land.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal from southern Lebanon got under way after
Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak, set a self-imposed deadline of
July 7 for Israeli troops to leave. When the Israelis started
pulling out last month ahead of schedule, their allies, the
surrogate Southern Lebanese Army, collapsed, abandoning heavy
weapons and fortifications to the guerrillas and forcing the
Israelis to accelerate their departure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
