<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6367 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-VP-BUSH0618-COX     06-16 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VP-BUSH0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Advice from many, decision made by twoBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Behind closed doors, as quietly and deliberately
as possible, Gov. George W. Bush is exercising what could be the
most power granted to any one person in a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In picking a running mate, Bush, who will be the GOP
presidential nominee, will have the one-man authority to grant
near-world leader status to the person of his choice.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, White House chief of staff under President Gerald
Ford, is Bush's one-man search committee. But Bush has made it
clear that he is the one-man selection committee. Though he said
the list of potential running mates is ``getting shorter,'' Bush
insists the criteria have not changed.
</P>
<P>
   He wants a running mate who is loyal, qualified to serve as
president and generally shares his political philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   He talks names, publicly, only in the most general of ways.
Virtually anyone who has not publicly withdrawn from consideration
gets praise from Bush as someone worth review.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's longtime political guru, says this decision is
being made above his level. If that's true, it's a new category for
Bush, who has trusted Rove for input on most decisions, including
the appointment of Texas Supreme Court justices and other top-level
officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is that this is a process in which only
two people are involved: George W. Bush and Dick Cheney,'' Rove
said en route home from a five-day retreat with the candidate and
staff in Maine last week. ``How the process is shaped and who they
are talking to is known only to them, and maybe their wives.''
</P>
<P>
   Also under consideration is when to make an announcement.
Revealing the name weeks before the Republican National Convention
(which begins July 31 in Philadelphia) could create some early
excitement, but it also would jump-start press scrutiny of the
choice.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the speculation has rotated among a small herd of
possible picks. Retired Gen. Colin Powell and Arizona Sen. John
McCain, favorites of many, have ruled themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating has confirmed that Bush asked him to
fill out a questionnaire. Others still under consideration include
Govs. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin,
George Pataki of New York and Christine Todd Whitman of New Jersey;
Sens. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, Fred Thompson of Tennessee and
George Voinovich of Ohio; U.S. Reps. John Kasich of Ohio and
Christopher Cox of California; and former Red Cross President
Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides have been characteristically closed-mouth about the
process, but there is no shortage of tea leaves to read. Last year,
before selling his political company to go full-time with the
campaign, Rove bought a long list of Web domain names, including
BushEngler.net, BushRidge.net, BushWhitman.net and BushPataki.net.
He also bought the .org version of each name.
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign now cautions against assuming that Engler,
Ridge, Pataki or Whitman are pre-ordained for the No. 2 slot.
Spokesman Ray Sullivan said the names were gobbled up by an
``overzealous'' staffer who had been told to reserve a number of
``Bush-related domain names.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bush headquarters in downtown Austin, the files are not short
on outside advice.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter to Bush, conservative leader Paul Weyrich
said Bush's selection criteria ``are vague enough that those of us
on the outside have few clues as to who you have in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Weyrich declined to recommend a candidate
``because any candidate so designated by any of us publicly would
soon become a target. You would be accused of caving in to us if
you selected someone we named.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weyrich urged Bush to pick someone who can energize the
``conservative coalition.'' And he urged Bush to look above for
guidance in picking the candidate below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the Holy Spirit grants the sort of wisdom required to
make such an extraordinary decision. He is waiting to be asked,''
Weyrich concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The advice to stick with a conservative came as former President
Ford urged Bush to balance the ticket by choosing someone who
supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need, as I've said repeatedly, a team that reflects
the broadest possible spectrum of the Republican philosophy,'' Ford
told the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of talk sparked reaction from people like Merrill
Matthews Jr. of the American Conservative Union, who believes a
ticket should be balanced by experience, not ideology. That means
Bush, a state politician, needs a running mate with Washington
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush campaign knows that,'' Matthews concluded, ``which is
why concern over Bush picking someone like Gov. Tom Ridge is
misplaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge presents an interesting potential dilemma. He will be the
homestate governor when the Republicans gather in Philadelphia for
their national convention. But his support of abortion rights puts
him out of step with Bush (who has said no single issue would be a
litmus test) and his party's platform.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge, a Catholic, has been barred by the bishop in his hometown
of Erie, from speaking at Catholic events in that part of the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Ridge, Weyrich said in his open letter to
Bush that ``a VP candidate who is perceived to be pro-abortion will
produce a noisy and divisive walkout'' at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   That could make for bad TV. And TV is what a national convention
is all about.
</P>
<P>
   MANY PETITIONS, ONE VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Though picking a running mate may be the most undemocratic part
of democracy, there are plenty of amateurs trying to petition or
lobby their favorite candidate onto the ballot. The files of the
Bush campaign include input from folks convinced they have just the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, The BplusK Committee will deliver petitions it hopes
will bear more than 25,000 signatures from people who want Bush to
pick Kasich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a Bush-Kasich ticket can win the election and
provide responsible leadership for our country,'' Larry Emmet,
director of BplusK, told the Bush campaign in a recent letter
seeking a meeting with Bush and Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the files is correspondence from American Women
Presidents, a Sacramento-based group urging both major parties to
put a female on the ticket. The group recently sent petitions, with
1,400 signatures, to both campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   And though Bush insists he does not make major decisions by
reading polls, there is no shortage of surveys about potential
running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Most independent polls show Republicans' favorites are Powell,
McCain and Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the top three, polls indicate a scrambled field.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Powell and McCain on the not-me list last week was
former Missouri Sen. John Danforth, who enjoyed a brief run in the
spotlight. No thanks, Danforth said last week after he and wife
Sally pondered how life might change.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth told the St. Louis Post-Dispatch that he awoke recently
in the middle of the night with the memory of a long-ago visit from
then-Secretary of State George Shultz.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of Secret Service people standing in our
back yard in the dark, and I remembered that,'' Danforth said.
``It's the fact that if you do that (high level of a) job, it
crowds out everything else in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   And in some cases, being No. 2 can mean a reduction in political
power. In 1988, then-Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas shocked some of
his staffers by accepting Michael Dukakis' invitation on to the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had independence and power as chairman of the (Senate)
finance committee. I was surprised when he agreed to run,'' said
former longtime Bentsen aide Jack DeVore.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis-Bentsen lost to Bush-Quayle, but Bentsen easily won
re-election to the Senate. The experience, according to DeVore,
offered an insightful look at the running mate selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can figure out how it gets done until you
get to the one guy who makes the decision. It varies widely from
person to person,'' he said. ``In many ways you are campaigning for
an office in an election and there is only one voter. It's hard to
figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
