<HEADER>
A6372 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ANTICANDIDATE-     06-16 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ANTICANDIDATE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGE FOR OUTSIDER MAY CHANGE MATHEMATICS OF MEXICAN ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   URUAPAN, Mexico _ His hair is shot through with gray, his
shoulders slope, and his ravine jowls have grown even deeper. But
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the battle horse leader of the leftist
opposition, is running for president for the third time. And
despite the long odds, his determination seems unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   After months when Cardenas' stolid campaign seemed stalled, it
has picked up steam. He is still well behind the two leading
candidates. But because of the peculiar arithmetic of three-way
politics here, Cardenas' surge has made him the pivotal player in
the most contested presidential race in Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   His gain mainly takes votes away from Vicente Fox, who is also
battling to oust the Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as
the PRI, from the presidency that it has controlled for seven
decades. Because polls show that Fox is locked in a tie with the
candidate of the governing party, Francisco Labastida, Cardenas'
pull on opposition voters could be just enough to cost Fox the
election on July 2.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And if Cardenas threw any support to Fox, he could tip the
balloting the other way.
</P>
<P>
   But Cardenas has disdained the idea of exercising his kingmaking
powers. Instead, he is tenaciously riding his campaign bus from
village to village, just as if he were on the cusp of victory,
pitching his nationalist platform, opposing free trade and
showering rebuke equally on his two rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have seen me in the these lands for 40 years, always
maintaining the same principles,'' Cardenas, 66, said before an
eager crowd of farm workers in straw cowboy hats jammed into the
quaint square of this rural city. ``I come to you exactly as I am,
and I say exactly what I believe. I have never moved from my
positions, because they represent the majority of the Mexican
people.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas made his first presidential run in 1988, after he had
defected as a reformist rebel from the PRI and had generated a
wildfire popular movement against its corruption. Many Mexicans say
that they believe that Cardenas really won that election but that
PRI vote-rigging stole it from him in favor of Carlos Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Cardenas placed a lackluster third. But three years
later, he became the first opposition mayor of Mexico City, the
post he left for his current effort.
</P>
<P>
   In that first presidential race, Cardenas discovered his style
as an anticandidate, and he has been running that way since then.
He distrusts television and hesitates, against advisers' pleas, to
shape his campaign to feed its habits. Late at night, long after
the newscasts, he holds teeming rallies. He is the opposite of
telegenic, because his demeanor is formal and his natural
expression is a furious frown. While Fox and Labastida rushed in
early to fill the airwaves with trendy commercials, Cardenas moved
only recently to produce modern-toned spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political ads can't govern Mexico!'' he railed in one speech
from the stump.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it was television that gave him the recent lift.
Cardenas was the moderator of a testy spontaneous encounter among
himself, Fox and Labastida late last month that was carried live
for more than two hours nationwide. Cardenas won the argument,
about whether or not to hold a formal televised debate, and he also
cracked several jokes at Fox's expense, the first time that
Mexicans could recall him being funny in public.
</P>
<P>
   When the three candidates finally met to debate on May 25,
Cardenas gave another spirited performance that further helped his
showing in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   A poll on June 5 by Reforma, the newspaper, showed that Cardenas
had risen to 17 percent of voter preferences, up from 12 percent in
April. Several polls show Fox and Labastida tied at around 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, Cardenas' defense of his leftist convictions has
done little to build his popularity. During three days of
whistle-stops in Michoacan, an agricultural state here in central
Mexico, he called repeatedly for the release of jailed student
strikers from the national university, saying they were political
prisoners. But Mexicans, especially the working class, were
outspoken in their disapproval of the strike that paralyzed the
most important public university for nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Although opinion surveys show that crime is a burning issue,
Cardenas pledged to disband a new federal police force created to
confront the problem, calling it a repressive unit.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Michoacan villagers by the thousands poured out to
hear Cardenas and gathered in unscheduled rallies along his route,
blocking the road to make him stop and visit. His followers are
devoted less to his positions than to his persona, as the son of
Lazaro Cardenas, a beloved president in the 1930s who was from
Michoacan; as the standard-bearer for the faltering welfare state,
as a politician who has long battled the PRI and as a man who does
not cut his suit to fit political fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does what he says,'' said Rafaela Vazquez de Herrera, 60, a
farm woman who prepared a beef stew for the candidate's lunch. ``He
sees a poor person who is down and lifts him up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In one town, the crowd lifted him on to a dappled grey walking
horse and marched behind him through the streets. In another,
supporters jammed a square in the shadow of a mighty statue of his
father to chant: ``Down with the system! Throw out the PRI!''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a passionate speech in Uruapan (pronounced oor-WAH-pan),
Cardenas ruled out renouncing his candidacy at the last minute or
making any other effort to help Fox, who represents the
right-of-center National Action Party. After a volley of attacks he
had aimed at Fox days earlier, his exasperated opponent accused
Cardenas of ``betraying himself and many Mexicans who believed in
him,'' and even disparaged Cardenas' mother, a breach of etiquette
that signaled a permanent break between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   The rift has caused a painful dilemma for Mexicans who are fed
up with the PRI, especially those on the left. Fox's strategists
have appealed for their support, arguing that a vote for Cardenas
is tantamount to a vote for the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some experts contend that Cardenas does not grasp the damage
that he is causing for the opposition's larger anti-PRI cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt the experience of winning in 1988, and it traumatized
him,'' a political expert, Jose Antonio Crespo, said. ``He is
stuck. He has not been able to measure the enormous changes in
Mexico since then.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Cardenas said he has no fear that history will judge him
harshly as having deprived the opposition of its best chance to
unseat the world's longest-governing party. His first concern, he
insisted, is to build the base of his own Democratic Revolutionary
Party. And although Fox is conducting his campaign as a wholesale
political assault on the PRI, Cardenas said Fox's positions are not
really different from those of the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell me that Vicente Fox is the opposition,'' Cardenas
said in an interview, ``I will say you are wrong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Along the trail, some voters said they admired Cardenas'
steadfastness, but felt that his moment was past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a change of power,'' said Dr. Rodolfo Robledo Montes,
a physician who was curious to see Cardenas, but thought that he
would vote for Fox. ``I admire his principles. But I feel that time
has left him behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas maintains that he is timeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico changes,'' he said. ``Campaigns change. But I don't
change. I am always the same.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
