<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILCH-TV (Los Angeles) _ On the face of it, David Milch, who is
the co-creator and architect of ``NYPD Blue, '' lives an affluent,
somewhat predictable life. He works out at a fancy sports club, has
a summer estate in Martha's Vineyard and dotes on his wife, Rita
and their three children. But the 55-year-old Emmy Award-winning
writer is also a heroin addict and alcoholic, a compulsive gambler,
a man who once destroyed a police car's roof lights with a shotgun
blast, spent time in a Mexican jail and came close to death several
times. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MACBETH-THEATER (London) _ Antony Sher is the first to
acknowledge that the majority of ``Macbeth'' productions don't
work. Added to that was his first exposure to the text, as a
schoolboy, where, the actor said, ``It was taught appallingly, so I
had no real experience of it.'' It is easy, then, to imagine the
mixture of excitement and trepidation with which Sher and his
director approached the play when they chose to revive it for the
Royal Shakespeare Company last November. The production went on to
be praised as the RSC's best in decades and is now moving to the
United States. By Matt Wolf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDS-THEATER (New York) _ In the middle of Kirsten Childs'
first musical, ``The Bubbly Black Girl Sheds Her Chameleon Skin,''
which opens on June 20, the main character auditions for a famous
choreographer of sexy musicals called Director Bob. ``You're a
sweet kid, and you've got an irresistible smile,'' Bob tells her.
``So let's try that monologue one more time. But this time, don't
go white on me.'' More than two decades ago, Kirsten Childs
auditioned for the famous choreographer Bob Fosse for a role in the
touring company of ``Chicago.'' Fosse, as Childs recalls it, never
explicitly said she wasn't black enough, ``It was just implied.''
By Jonathan Mandell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTIMATE-MOVIES (Undated) _ What makes a movie intimate? The
word suggests sex and romance on one hand or small, earnest,
slice-of-life films on the other. But intimacy in movies has less
to do with subject than with subjectivity, the filmmakers' and the
characters. By Karen Durbin.
</P>
<P>
   APARTMENT-FILM (Undated) _ Forty years ago, Billy Wilder's ``The
Apartment'' and Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho'' opened the same week
_ the kind of double whammy that reminds us we now live in
impoverished times. Each is an American classic, although ``The
Apartment'' has barely been acknowledged as such. By Graham Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   SATIRE-FILM (Undated) _ Why do movie audiences squirm and
critics pay scant attention when a gloves-off satire of our tabloid
television culture is brought to the screen? Is it that we're
inured to satire by living in a society where grotesque reality
(Monicagate, the Anita Hill hearings) seems to trump fiction at
every turn? Or can savage mockery of our bottom-feeding popular
culture shame us enough to arouse discomfort? Or have we became so
arrogant and thick-skinned in our prosperity that needling humor is
incapable of penetrating anyone's gold-plated hides? By Stephen
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-COMPETITION (Undated) _ Competition is the lifeblood of
sports, where players are asked to put aside their personalities to
serve a goal that can be represented statistically. In the
performing arts, however, where audiences and critics reward
spontaneity and emotional risk, and where standards of excellence
are intensely personal and organic, competition can be hell. By
Mindy Aloff.
</P>
<P>
   JAFFE-DANCE (Undated) _ Susan Jaffe, the luminous classical
ballerina with the flashing turquoise eyes, gets straight to the
point. ``It's neat that I've lasted this long,'' she says.
Longevity is admirable, particularly in a profession where careers
are notoriously short. Two decades spent in the same company,
American Ballet Theater, is also estimable. But to many people,
what has made Ms. Jaffe's career so remarkable was her breathtaking
transformation from a pleasing, technically proficient dancer with
an easy extension into a powerful dramatic artist and dancer of
amazing classical purity. By Terry Trucco.
</P>
<P>
   WHELAN-DANCE (New York) _ Wendy Whelan is the most American of
ballerinas. Tall and thin, unself-consciously inscrutable and
unstoppable-seeming, the New York City Ballet principal dances with
a tangy lack of adornment that is seldom found in Europe. But she
is also something of a mystery, a quintessentially American colt of
a dancer who has suddenly grown into a ballerina of new depth and
dramatic power. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOZART-DUET-MUSIC (Undated) _ What's in a name? If the name is
Mozart, plenty. The playbill for the premiere of the ``brand new
heroic-comic opera'' ``Der Stein der Weisen, oder Die Zauberinsel''
(``The Philosophers' Stone, or The Enchanted Island'') in 1790,
listed as author Emanuel Schikaneder, but no composer. The New
Grove Dictionary of Opera credited the score to Benedikt Schack and
Franz Xaver Gerl, noting that one comic duet was orchestrated ``and
perhaps partly composed'' by Mozart. The existence of the duet and
its attribution never sufficed to raise the opera from the
obscurity in which it had lain since its last known performance, in
1814. Fortune smiled in 1997. By Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   GROOVEBOX-MUSIC (Undated) _ The Roland MC-505 Groovebox, a small
programmable synthesizer, is an impressive musical plaything. It
has been called a ``band in a box,'' capable of producing a wild
variety of vintage keyboard sounds, as well as the trademark thuds
and thumps of some of the most popular rhythm machines of all time,
including Roland's 303 bass synthesizer and its 808 and 909 beat
boxes. While those instruments have been out of production since
the early 1980s they remain the objects of a fervid cult among
dance music cognoscenti. By Jody Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   DOWLAND-MUSIC (Undated) _ After successfully combining the jazz
saxophonist Jan Garbarek with the Hilliard Ensemble, ECM Records
now sets its sights on music of the great Elizabethan lute-song
composer John Dowland. The project began as a conventional Dowland
recital by John Potter and Stephen Stubbs, the lutenist and
director of the group Tragicomedia. But Manfred Eicher, ECM's
founder and producer, persuaded Potter and Stubbs to broaden their
interpretive horizons. What results, ``In Darkness Let Me Dwell,''
is a rarity: a crossover project that is both defensible and
listenable. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   COCTEAU-MUSIC (Undated) _ One of the most wide-ranging artists
of the 20th century, playwright, painter, essayist and filmmaker
Jean Cocteau re-defined the term eclectic. How fitting, then, that
the Criterion Collection's important new release of the three films
that make up Cocteau's ``Orphic Trilogy'' also touches on the many
facets of Cocteau's artistic makeup (VHS, $29.95 each; DVD, a
three-disc box set, 225 minutes, $79.95). By Kevin Filipski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-CRITICISM (Undated) _ An examination of the differences
between music criticism and art criticism. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   CONTE-SECRET-MUSEUM (Undated) _ ``And now to western Formosa and
a song for the gathering of tea,'' intones a calm, sonorous voice
during an installment of ``The Secret Museum of the Air,'' which
may just be the most singular world music show on radio. The
selection was part of ``Herds and Pastures,'' a program in which
listeners heard a Peruvian Indian song recorded by an Yma Sumac
sound-alike, a choral ode to the Sumatran rice goddess, a tune
featuring the Serbian bagpipe and what the host considers ``some of
the most emotional yodeling on record.'' The idiosyncratic voice
belongs to Pat Conte, and the vintage discs from which his shows
are culled belong to what he calls ``The Secret Museum of
Mankind.'' By Jon Kalish.
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARCHITECTS (New York) _ Architects are Freudian figures in a
Marxian landscape. This was one clear message that emerged from the
final ANY conference, a three-day architectural talent fest held
earlier this month at the Guggenheim Museum. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
