<P>
   HARVARD-BSCHOOL (Boston) _ The Harvard Business School, the West
Point of big business, has transformed itself to maintain its
dominance in the new economy. Its general management course has
been replaced with ``the entrepreneurial manager'' and it has so
many initiatives in Silicon Valley, where Stanford, its rival, is
pre-eminent, that it's almost a satellite campus. The
transformation involves some significant risks. By David
Leonhardt. &QL; 
With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-BUSH (Undated) _ For the first time in its 92 years of
training corporate presidents, the Harvard Business School has a
chance to claim the ultimate chief executive, the president of the
United States. John Solomon, also a Harvard Business School
graduate, writes that George W. Bush's style _ generalist, big
picture, highly delegative _ is the archetypal Harvard Business
School-trained manager. Is the world ready for a Harvard MBA as
president? After all the generals and lawyers, one of Bush's
classmates suggests, ``Why not give an MBA a shot?''
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-NETWORKING (Undated) _ 3Plex went from incorporation to
two rounds of funding in four months largely because of the alumni
network of the Harvard Business School. Harvard says 20 percent of
the partners at major venture-capital firms hold Harvard MBAs. By
David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-BUSH-GORE _ Jim Reece, a professor of accounting and
operations management at the University of Michigan Business
School, has the distinction of having taught George Bush and Al
Gore: Bush at Harvard and Gore at St. Albans School in Washington.
So who gets Reece's ultimate job recommendation?
</P>
<P>
   WAVE-RISK (Marengo, Ill.) _ Infatuated with a tiny Nasdaq stock
called Wave Systems, two brothers caught the ride of their lives.
David and Douglas McCoy were just two of many ``wavoids'' who road
the stock from $1 to $50. One day it was a $500,000 gain and
shopping for Porsches; the next selling the Honda to meet margin
calls. Their experience is used to discuss the arguments for
diversifying, the little-known fact that the federal clearing house
can raise margin requirements on risky ventures, the difficulties
of transferring accounts and the eternal search for the next
Microsoft. By Danny Hakim &QL; 
With graphic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ Edward Kerschner, chief investment
strategist at Paine Webber, believes that the instant dissemination
of information today carries a cost: the tendency among investors
to act first and think second creating volatility in the stock
market. Kerschner has tracked volatility on the major stock indexes
against the growth in household viewership of CNBC, the investing
cable channel. As viewership has exploded, so has volatility,
particularly among Nasdaq stocks. By Gretchen Morgenson. &QL; 
With graphic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE-SAEKI (Tokyo) _ A profile of Ted Saeki, chief of Nasdaq
Japan, which opens Monday thanks to Saeki's ability to steer the
organization through one of the most hidebound, idiosyncratic,
bureaucratic financial systems in the world. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN _ Shedding the chief executive has become so popular
that last August a Chicago firm, began tracking turnover of ceos.
The total through last Thursday was 706 chiefs of publicly-owned
companies, an average of 15 a week. Some retired or jumped to
better jobs, but the vast majority were dismissed. Another study
found that 40 percent of new chief executives lose their jobs
within 18 months. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   PROCTER-ADVICE (Undated) _ Experts, and general know-it-alls,
advise P&AMP;G on how to get its house in order. By Kate Berry.
</P>
<P>
   ETHICS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Nearly three-quarters of the companies
that responded to a survey by the American Management Association,
said they monitor employees' e-mail, phone calls, computer calls or
Internet connections. So the ethical question of whether to monitor
or not will soon be moot. Jeffrey L. Seglin advises companies on
how to avoid witch hunts, speed traps and lawsuits. His advice: he
snoops fairest who snoops least, and then only with cause. By
Jeffrey L. Seglin.
</P>
<P>
   GRASSROOTS-BUSINESS (Manning, Iowa) _ A tale of two rural Iowa
towns _ one thriving, one diving _ and what it tells us about the
Internet's influence on small-town survival. By Joel Kotkin.
</P>
