   &UR; INVESTING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-NEWSLETTERS (Undated) _ For 20 years Mark Hulbert has
been monitoring investment newsletters. Now he has done a
comparison of those that deliver advice via e-mail, fax and hot
lines and those that use conventional mail. He concludes there is
no difference in investment performance: a 10.9 percent annualized
return for the quick delivery group, versus 10.5 percent for the
regular-mail group. Why? Quick information leads to quick exits in
a field that benefits from longterm relationships. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Q&AMP;A with Heather Hay of Merrill Lynch.
She says P&AMP;G's size could slow a turnaround. By Kenneth N. Gilpin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-MONTGOMERY-GLOBAL (Undated) _ The ``Investing With''
column this week features Oscar Castro of Montgomery Global
Communications. Castro attributes the fund's outperformance for the
past 12 months _ 66.7 percent vs. 35.9 percent for the industry
average _ in part to the fund's proprietary research process. In an
interview with Joanne Legomsky, Castro explains how it works,
including his dictum that he will drop a stock if executives take
too long to return his calls. He sees it as a sign of possible
trouble. &QL; 
With photo and graphic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-CALIF.-PIZZA (Undated) _ California Pizza Kitchen will
complete its public offering in July. Will investors buy? The
company has grown slowly and the new issue market is even slower.
By Sana Siwolop.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-VALUE (New York) _ Geraldine Fabrikant reports on the
annual value investing seminar at Columbia University Business
School that executives used to line up for, but which last week
attracted only a dozen participants. Many were Warren Buffett
loyalists who could not be swayed from his value view, but one
professor noted most people don't care about value. ``The fact is
they love to buy lottery tickets,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL INVESTING  &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRENUPT-COLUMN (New York) _ Abby Ellin reports in her monthly
column that the dot-com set is turning to prenuptial agreements as
never before. Experts such as Raoul Felder, the divorce lawyer, say
an example of one of his new clients is a sneaker-clad ``kid'' he
mistook for a delivery boy. The client said he didn't have any
money, but he did have stock options _ worth $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-SCORING (Undated) _ Since Fair, Isaac, which dominates
the field of credit reporting, has published details of its
methodology for the first time, consumers are getting a closer look
at this mysterious system. Mickey Meece points out some pitfalls in
trying to improve the score.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-DONATIONS _ When he's giving to one candidate or party
and she's giving to the other, there's no such thing as ``soft
money.'' By Robert Hershey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOTORCYCLES-RDP (Undated) _ This story is a roundup of
highlights of the season's motorcycle market, including
Harley-Davidson's introduction of the Blast, a $4,395, no-frills
model; the online sales of Ducatis, and the rescue from bankruptcy
of Excelsior-Henderson. By Jim McCraw.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (The following stories moved in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   PYTHON-FASHION (Undated) _ Once snakeskin had all the fashion
panache of Joey Buttafuoco's boots, but this season designers
satisfied cash-rich consumers with python. Even Yves Saint
Laurent's python-skin trench coats sold out at $9,250. The hip
image is world's away from Indonesia where 4.5 million pythons are
exported annually _ alive or skinned. By C.J. Chivers. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   JONG-FAST-NOVELIST (New York) _ Having a famous mommy (Erica
Jong), a famous daddy (novelist Jonathan Fast) and a famous grandpa
(novelist Howard Fast) isn't a guarantee to celebrity. But Molly
Jong-Fast, 21, is on her way to being, in her own words, TNBT _ the
next big thing as her first novel, ``Normal Girl,'' is published.
``If I weren't me, I would hate me, too,'' Jong-Fast says. By Alex
Witchel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEL-PARADISE _ Mel Cheren, a founder of Paradise Garage, the
legendary and influential discotheque, has written a history of it
all. ``Keep on Dancin''' details the makings of modern dance music
in a tangle of friendships, business deals and sexual liaisons.
Then the good times of the late 1970s unravel with the AIDS
epidemic, the decline of disco and Cheren's own setbacks. In
Sunday's story, he reminsces about the sound that some call simply
``garage.'' By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-MYSTICS (New York) _ A niteout in Manhattan with three
members of the Washington Mystics, the WNBA team, as they search
for celebrities and find Donald Trump and Monica Lewinsky. ``Us
with Monica,'' said Vicky Bullett. ``Now I can die and go to
heaven.'' By Nancy Hass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-AWARDS (New York) _ Oscar de la Renta received the top
women's wear award last week, winning over Donna Karan and Helmet
Lang. Cathy Horyn covers the awards of the Council of Fashion
Designers of America.
</P>
<P>
   DADS-FASHION (Undated) _ It's easy to look like a rebel at 19 or
29, but at 39, it's a challenge. David Eddie writes about what it's
like to be a dad who wants to look dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   These stories from The New York Times Week in Review for Sunday,
June 18, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-SYRIA-REVIEW (Washington) _ It was pure coincidence that
presidential succession in Syria and the rapprochement between
North and South Korea took place the same day. But there were
profound similarities in what was happening. Both North Korea and
Syria are relics of another age _ dictatorships where power has
been based internally on terror and externally on hostility to
neighbors. In both places, power has passed from a dictator to his
son, and the son shows signs of a more modern, outward-looking
approach to solving his country's problems. Perhaps that can make
the world more peaceful. But there is also the disquieting feeling
that it won't be easy; terror and isolation remain hallmarks of the
systems in which these two sons rule. By Elaine Sciolono. (Moving
in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTISTS-SECRECY-REVIEW (Undated) _ As secrets on nuclear
terrorism and miniaturized warheads apparently slip out of Los
Alamos National Laboratory and other federal labs, the message here
would seem to be obvious: do not give dangerous secrets to
scientists. There is a flaw in this solution. Governments need the
scientists and their culture of openness to produce weapons that
are worth keeping secret in the first place. That in a nutshell, is
why science and secrecy have clashed. By James Glanz. (Moving in
`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   ECON-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Politics is still catching
up with prosperity. After decades in which the two parties fought
over how to slice up a shrinking pie and maneuvered to claim credit
for periodic good news, they now operate in a climate in which
economic strength seems a given and the biggest issue is not a
scarcity of money but a surfeit. By Richard Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-PLATFORMS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Conventional wisdom holds
that party platforms are archaic. But many experts say platforms
can be revealing documents. At a time when everything else is so
stage-managed, poll-driven and homogenized in politics, platforms
are where the activists often have their say. This can be
troublesome for the nominees. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   STUDENT-SORTING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Lusting after the academic
successes of European and Japanese schoolchildren, American
educators in recent years have imported the idea of a rigorous
system of tests, which other countries use to cull the elite from
the merely literate. But educators here insisted that America,
being the land of second chances, would instead use testing to snap
schools to attention, forcing them to raise standards for everyone.
They would lift up, not weed out. But the evidence so far suggests
that schools here are doing the very sort of gardening they
promised to avoid, employing tests to sort children, and at a far
earlier age than elsewhere. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION-REVIEW (Undated) _ Just a few years ago, lawmakers
were in full cry about the supposed dangers of immigration _ from
crime to welfare cheats to lost jobs. Yet now Congress is poised to
pass a bill that would grant visas to tens of thousands more
temporary high-tech workers from abroad. An unlikely coalition of
business and immigrants rights groups is pushing to fling the door
open wider: to unskilled workers who could fill shortages in hotels
and on farms, and even to roll back an array of restrictive
measures passed with great fanfare in 1996. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HMOS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Patients may be wondering
whose side the Supreme Court is on in the wake of its decision
shielding health maintenance organizations from some lawsuits by
patients in federal court. The decision favored HMOs but included
some blunt comments about their role in rationing health care. Such
rationing, the court said, is intrinsic to design and mission of
HMOs. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   MOB-WALLSTREET-REVIEW (Undated) _ A humorous imaginary look at
the mob's new lines of business.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS-REVIEW (Moscow) _ By any standard measure of
democracy, political opposition is just what Russia desperately
needs. But until last week, President Vladimir Putin didn't have
any. Now, with the jailing of Vladimir Gusinsky, Putin may have
actually stirred up some real opposition, setting the stage for an
acid test of Russia's young democracy: how is the opposition to
act, and how will it be treated? By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-REVIEW (Washington) _ To hear some in NATO talk,
Montenegro _ the last republic of Tito's Yugoslavia remains
alongside Serbia in today's rump Yugoslavia _ is the unsinkable
aircraft carrier in the West's unfinished war against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic. But last week, the carrier was given
a significant holing by Montenegro's voters, a sizable minority of
whom want to remain inside Yugoslavia. By Steve Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-CIA-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some lessons to be learned from
the recently leaked CIA history of the agency's role in the 1953
coup that overthrew Iran's prime minister and restored the shah to
power.
</P>
