<HEADLINE>
FOR CHIEFS, MORE PRESSURE TO PERFORM (OR ELSE) 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 18) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Firing workers, like capital punishment, is applauded in
America. Just the announcement of a mass downsizing in the
mid-1990s would raise a company's stock price. Now that happens
when a chief executive's head rolls. A faltering company seems
somehow cleansed.
</P>
<P>
   We even have a self-appointed scorekeeper: Challenger, Gray &AMP;
Christmas, a Chicago firm that helps companies find new jobs for
workers they lay off. As a sideline, Challenger in the 1990s began
tracking layoff announcements and issuing grim monthly tallies. In
the current robust economy, mass layoffs are way down and out of
fashion. Shedding the chief executive is increasingly popular, and
Challenger began last August to keep this new score.
</P>
<P>
   The total through June 15 was 706 chiefs of publicly owned
companies, an average of 15 a week. Some retired in the usual way
or jumped to better jobs, but the vast majority were dismissed.
Durk Jager's ouster from Procter &AMP; Gamble on June 8 was departure
No. 36 this month, and the toll has since risen to 48.
</P>
<P>
   More formal studies confirm the trend. One found that 40 percent
of new chief executives lose their jobs within 18 months. Another,
by Rakesh Khurana at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
found that for the same poor performance, a chief executive was
three times as likely to be fired in 1996 than in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking them to pitch no-hitters every day,'' said John
Challenger, chief executive of Challenger, Gray. The game, in sum,
rides entirely on the pitcher, not on the other players or on
field-tested team strategies. As Peter Cappelli, a management
professor at the Wharton School, put it: ``We are substituting
people for strategy. Instead of working out plans and goals,
directors look at another company that is doing what they think
they want to do, and they hire an executive from that company and
hope'' he will do the same for them.
</P>
<P>
   Failure is defined as two or three quarters in which profits
fail to rise at a 15 percent annual rate, and the stock price fails
to keep up with the expectations of the bull market. That was the
background music for Jager's departure. Or a new chief executive
fails to bring about a merger or reorganization. Four out of five
directors expect their chief executives to lead in this direction,
according to surveys by the National Association of Corporate
Directors.
</P>
<P>
   Hold the tears, of course. Ordinary workers, even middle
managers, are lucky if they walk away from a downsizing with enough
in savings and severance to support their families for a year. The
chief executives depart with enough not only for their families but
their descendants for several generations. Knowing the high risk of
being fired, they negotiate huge pay and severance packages,
granted by the very directors who will later do the firing.
</P>
<P>
   Just 25 years ago, a typical American chief executive was deeply
entrenched. His cronies dominated the board, his company made money
despite its inefficiencies and he resisted change. The rise of
corporate raiders and leveraged buyouts brought an end to such
inertia, and the increasingly powerful financial markets took
control of most boards; today, directors are more likely than not
to speak for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, if a big institutional shareholder like a pension
or mutual fund did not like management, it sold the stock. Now it
presses the board to drop the chief executive. Instead of being
deeply rooted, the boss sways on a limb.
</P>
<P>
   Is that an improvement? Probably, said Cappelli _ provided that
directors become more committed, participate in strategic planning
and shift more management authority to lower levels. Above all,
they must be patient, giving the chief executive time to carry out
a strategy, even if profits and the stock price do not quickly
respond. The Eaton Corp. behaved this way, according to Stephen
Hardis, who will retire next month at 65 after five years as chief
executive. ``My predecessor owned the board,'' he said. ``My board
owned me. But they always gave me a lot of support.''
</P>
<P>
   New technologies and product innovation force companies today
into constant, risky change. Eaton manufactures auto and truck
parts and transmissions, and in the Hardis years, the product line
was redesigned to add electronic controls. The process involved the
kind of staff upheaval that might have brought a chief down
elsewhere. ``You cannot change a company without changing people,''
Hardis said.
</P>
<P>
   He wonders, then, whether Durk Jager, who led Procter &AMP; Gamble
for just 17 months, lacked skills, or the board lacked patience.
``When I read about Jager,'' he said, ``I wondered if it would make
other chief executives more risk averse. If you have to
fundamentally reshape a business, it takes time, and makes people
unhappy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
