<HEADER>
A6389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-SHOOTING-395&AMP;ADD     06-16 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-SHOOTING-395&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB OPPOSITION LEADER SAYS MILOSEVIC ORDERED ATTEMPT ON HIS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDVA, Yugoslavia _ Vuk Draskovic, a Serbian opposition leader,
returned Friday to his home here in Montenegro, the scene of his
close scrape with death Thursday night, and accused President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia of ordering an assassination
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certain they did it,'' he said of Serbian secret
services, ``and also it is certain that if there was a decision to
kill me, the Serbian government would know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days before the shooting attack that left him slightly
injured, he said, he had been warned by a contact in the Serbian
government that an attempt on his life was being planned.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Friday evening that they had arrested suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police are in possession of the attack weapon and are holding
the persons who carried it out, together with those who assisted
them,'' said Vuk Boskovic, Montenegro's deputy interior minister.
``But we also know who ordered this crime.'' The identifies of the
men would be disclosed on Saturday, he told Montenegrin state
television in the capital, Podgorica, adding that the men had
followed Draskovic from Serbia to carry out the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his vacation home in Budva after his release from a
hospital, Draskovic looked tired and strained, wearing dressings on
wounds to his right temple and left ear. ``I felt two bullets,'' he
said. ``One made a hole in my ear and the other one hit me when I
was falling down.''
</P>
<P>
   One or more gunmen fired five or six bullets through the
shutters into his living room, where he was sitting watching
television, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As leader of the Serbian Renewal Party, Draskovic is the most
important political opponent to Milosevic and as such represents a
threat to his power. Still, the attack came at a low in Draskovic's
fortunes, when his campaign to force Milosevic out of office by
peaceful protest or elections appears to be faltering.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting in this small seaside resort has nevertheless
caused grave concern among Montenegrin officials, who see it as
another step in an effort by Belgrade to destabilize its smaller
partner republic in the Yugoslav Federation. The shooting of
Draskovic, who had sought the protection of the Montenegrin
government, came just two weeks after the killing of Goran Zugic, a
security adviser and close friend of Montenegro's president, Milo
Djukanovic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Montenegro's interior minister, Vukasin Maras, sat beside
Draskovic as he spoke with reporters, and denounced the attack as
one not only on Draskovic but also on democracy and Montenegro,
which has been trying to distance itself from the Belgrade
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who think that by shooting at Vuk Draskovic they are
achieving anything are making a mistake,'' Maras said. ``This will
only give more strength to democracy in Montenegro.''
</P>
<P>
   The two shooting attacks, he said, showed that the police had to
be more aware that the recent increase of violence in Serbia was
now transferring itself to Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the series of disparate killings in Serbia
that have seen at least one high-level figure gunned down every
month this year, including Yugoslav Defense Minister Pavle
Bulatovic and the paramilitary leader Zeljko Raznatovic, better
known as Arkan.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade has denied any involvement in the death of Zugic.
Yugoslav Information Minister Goran Matic blamed it on a plot
orchestrated by the Central Intelligence Agency and an internal
power struggle within Montenegro. Maras denied that scenario
vigorously Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As Draskovic described the shooting, there were two bullet holes
in the wall above the sofa where he sat, and several more holes
marked the wall to the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw myself to the ground, rolled over and crawled up the
steps,'' he said, showing how he had scrambled into the adjoining
kitchen area and sought cover behind a pillar. There was a trail of
blood on the floor to the front door he used to escape to a
neighbor's home.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic said he had received a warning from a high-level
contact in the Serbian government a few days ago that an ``order''
had gone out to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Moscow also knew about this,'' he added. He did not
explain further, but last month he visited Moscow with other
opposition politicians and met with Foreign Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the warnings, it appears that he had dispensed with the
police security provided by the Montenegrin government during his
few days in Budva. His personal bodyguards were not on hand because
they had been arrested recently in Belgrade, charged with not
having permission to carry weapons.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Danica, who flew from their home in Belgrade to be
with her husband, blamed Montenegrin authorities for failing to
protect him. But Draskovic appeared to admit that he had allowed
the lapse in security.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were probably following me,'' he said of his attackers.
``They probably knew I do not like security. I was here working
alone for two or three days and they saw I was on my own and saw
the opportunity for an attack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is completely clear they will try to attack again, and will
attack other people,'' he said. ``This is the way they rule,
without laws or constitution. In Serbia it is a worse situation. It
is like the postwar years of 1946 to 1947,'' he said, a reference
to the postwar communist purges under Tito.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on Draskovic, 53, has intensified since last
October, when four members of his political party, including his
brother-in-law and his security chief, were killed in a collision
between their car and a truck in Serbia. Draskovic insists that
Milosevic was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   In May the government took over the Belgrade television station
run by the opposition-led city government, apparently another move
against Draskovic and his party.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic had no doubts as to who was behind the attempt against
her husband. ``Slobodan Milosevic and Mira Markovic, who else?''
she asked, referring to the Yugoslav president and his wife. ``I
think they will repeat themselves until they finish their work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
