<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-TRAVELOFFICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT DUE ON WHITE HOUSE TRAVEL DISMISSALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel who has been investigating
the Clintons on several fronts is expected to file his final report
next week with a special judicial panel on what role Hillary Rodham
Clinton played in the firing of several longtime employees in the
White House travel office.
</P>
<P>
   The report will not be made public, but lawyers familiar with
the investigation say it is highly unlikely to include a
recommendation that anyone be prosecuted. The independent
prosecutor, Robert W. Ray, who replaced Kenneth Starr last October,
may announce that conclusion publicly at the same time he files the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The report itself, which will not be available to the public for
at least three months, will deal with whether Hillary Clinton was a
moving force behind the decision to fire the seven longtime
employees in 1993 and whether she or other White House aides tried
to conceal whatever role she played.
</P>
<P>
   Under the independent counsel law governing Ray's operations,
Clinton's lawyers will be given an opportunity to review any
reference to her in the report. She is entitled to include any
dissenting comments in the next 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   After that 90-day period, the three-member judicial panel is
allowed to make the report public, meaning that its disclosure
could come in the final stages of Clinton's Senate campaign in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The report will deal with two starkly contradictory accounts of
Clinton's role in the dismissal of the travel office employees just
a few months after she and her husband moved into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The workers who helped plan arrangements for news organizations
as they accompanied the president on his travels found themselves
suddenly barred from the White House grounds on May 19, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has regularly depicted herself as largely uninvolved in
the dismissals. Her lawyer told the General Accounting Office, an
investigative arm of Congress, that she had no idea how the firings
were initiated.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, a House committee began an investigation, and
Clinton offered a more detailed response, insisting that she was
only interested in being kept informed about what was happening in
the travel office.
</P>
<P>
   She also told congressional investigators that she was too busy
at the time helping her daughter get adjusted in a new school,
tending to her father who had suffered a stroke and trying to plan
a national health care system.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel began investigating the matter at the
request of Attorney General Janet Reno after a memorandum was
discovered in which a senior White House official said that the
first lady had instigated the firings and created a climate of
anxiety in the White House about doing it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The official, David Watkins, said in his memorandum to Thomas
McLarty, then the White House chief of staff, that ``we both knew
there would be hell to pay'' if ``we failed to take swift and
decisive action in conformity with the first lady's wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins also wrote a chronology of his role in the firings that
was obtained by investigators in Congress and the independent
counsel's office that appeared to show that Clinton was regularly
pressing for the travel office employees to be fired. In one
section, he recorded that Clinton told a meeting, ``We need those
people out, and we need our people in.''
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the former workers were rehired in other jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
