<SLUG> BC-LEHMAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN BROTHERS' QUARTERLY EARNINGS UP 15 PERCENT OVER '99 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite a sharp slowdown in domestic stock and bond
markets, Lehman Brothers Holdings reported Friday that its
quarterly earnings rose 15 percent from a year earlier, though they
were 33 percent lower than in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, the fourth-biggest securities firm, said it had net
income of $378 million in the quarter, up from $330 million in the
corresponding period in 1999 but down from a record $541 million in
the first quarter of 2000. On a diluted basis, its earnings were
$2.78 a share, compared with $2.09 a year earlier and with
analysts' lowered consensus estimate of $2.49 for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Lehman's gains came from stock trading at home and in
Europe, where the firm has been building its investment banking and
trading operations. Lehman derived 49 percent of its revenue from
outside the United States in the quarter, up from 37 percent a year
earlier, said David Goldfarb, its chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw some extraordinary strength in trading profitability
considering the market environment we were in,'' said Guy
Moszkowski, a Salomon Smith Barney analyst. Moszkowski said
Lehman's results boded well for two bigger competitors that are
scheduled to report earnings next week, the Goldman Sachs Group and
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second quarter will turn out to have been quite strong
really, considering the kind of market conditions we had,'' he
said. But, he added, ``I still think we're looking at a much weaker
third quarter than we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldfarb said that the quarter had a split personality: For the
first several weeks, starting in March, the stock markets were on a
tear and investment banks were underwriting new stock issues as
fast as they could. Then, after technology stocks took a dive in
mid-April, business slowed markedly though investors rushed to
adjust their portfolios for the end _ at least temporarily _ of the
run-up in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the quarter, concerns about rising interest rates
bogged down the bond markets, the traditional source of most of
Lehman's revenue. Of the $1.76 billion in revenue last quarter,
only about 30 percent came from trading and underwriting bonds,
Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody still had a thought process that we're a
fixed-income house, this should be a wake-up call that we're a
diversified investment bank,'' Goldfarb said.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive quarter, Lehman spent about 52 cents
of every dollar it took in on compensation and benefits for its
9,300 employees. Like other Wall Street firms, Lehman has had to
increase pay and perks to retain and attract young investment
bankers. Goldfarb said Lehman was also spending heavily on new
technology and an Internet-based system for communicating and
trading with clients.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet proved treacherous for Lehman last week when the
firm discovered that www.secinfo.com, a Web site for investors, was
still publishing a long list of the firm's investments that had
been filed erroneously with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-May, Lehman sent a standard quarterly filing to the SEC
that was supposed to contain a list of its biggest stock holdings,
totaling about $5 billion. Instead, it sent a much longer list of
about $25 billion of positions, including currency contracts and
stock options it had purchased as bets that certain stocks would
either rise or fall.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, big investors like Lehman closely guard such
information out of fear that other investors will use it for their
own trading purposes. Lehman thought it had erased the first filing
when the SEC deleted it and replaced it with a corrected one, but
secinfo.com has a policy of providing all versions of such
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a Lehman lawyer asked the site's operators to remove
the original filing. At first, they complied. But then, thinking
like Wall Street traders, they reposted the document and asked
Lehman to make them an offer to remove it. Lehman chose not to bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
