u s BC-GOLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-     06-16 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TRENT JONES' LEGACY ... MAKE THEM THINK 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ At the U.S. Open, the golfers always had
something to say about what Trent Jones had wrought. Seldom was it
complimentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jones has so many doglegs on this course,'' Bob Rosburg said
at Hazeltine National in 1970, ``he must have laid it out in a
kennel.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning at Oakland Hills in 1951 with a 67 in the final
round, Ben Hogan said, ``I'm glad I brought this course, this
monster, to its knees.''
</P>
<P>
   And at a reception later, Hogan turned to Trent Jones' wife,
Ione: ``If your husband had to play this course for a living,''
Hogan said, ``you'd be on the bread line.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the golfers have come to expect an Open course
to be altered simply to make them do what they don't want to do:
think. As it was here at Pebble Beach with a few new tees as well
as new seawall bunkers on the 17th and 18th holes. All created
explicitly for this 100th Open.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Trent Jones is smiling. For half a century now, the
Open has been played on famous courses, no matter how old and how
traditional, that are always altered to make life more exacting for
the world's best golfers. And that's the legacy of Robert Trent
Jones Sr., the celebrated golf architect who died in his sleep at
93 just as this Open was about to begin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing of his death was spooky,'' his son Rees was saying.
``For years the Open was his stage.'' Rees Jones is now what his
father was, the architect often hired by the U.S. Golf Association
to perform a face lift on an Open course. He and his brother,
Robert Trent Jones Jr., have been involved in designing more than
250 courses worldwide after having studied under their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought of himself as the defender of par,'' Rees Jones
said. ``He thought that a tournament with a lot of subpar rounds
was a fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 1951 Open at Oakland Hills outside Detroit, Trent Jones
was the first to redo an Open course. Oakland Hills had been used
for two previous Opens _ in 1924 when Cyril Walker finished two
strokes ahead of Bobby Jones and in 1937 when Ralph Guldahl won.
But for the 1951 Open, the USGA knew that it needed a more
difficult look.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rebunkered Oakland Hills,'' Rees Jones said. ``And his
contoured greens made the golfers think about whether to go for the
flag or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Hills was suddenly golf's ``monster.'' In that 1951 Open
none of the world's best golfers broke par 70 until the final round
when Hogan shot 67 for a seven-over-par 287 to win by two strokes.
Clayton Haefner shot 69 to finish second.
</P>
<P>
   Others also complained about the severity of Jones' changes, but
Gene Sarazen, then the only golfer to have won all four of the
major tournaments, praised them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course was a masterpiece,'' Sarazen wrote in a letter to
the USGA hierarchy. ``It was a challenge to the players, but the
best players finished on top.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, the USGA hired Trent Jones whenever it thought an
Open course needed changes, whether subtle or drastic.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest uproar occurred in 1970 at Hazeltine National
outside Minneapolis, a relatively new course that Jones had
designed. After a practice round, Jack Nicklaus, who had already
won two of his four Open titles, complained that Hazeltine lacked
definition.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father told Jack, `You won't play well because you're
already fighting the course,''' Rees Jones said. ``He was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus shot 81-72-75-76 to tie for 51st as England's Tony
Jacklin won with a seven-under-par total of 281, but that Open is
remembered for Dave Hill's comment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Hazeltine lacked, Hill, who would finish second with
even par 288, replied, ``Eighty acres of corn and a few cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Rosburg, others complained about all the dogleg holes
that created too many blind shots, either from the tees or to the
greens, but Ben Crenshaw, now a two-time Masters winner and a
celebrated golf architect who was low amateur in that 1970 Open,
defended Jones' design.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those blind shots,'' Crenshaw said, ``aren't blind after
your first practice round.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent Jones was just trying to make the world's best golfers
play golf. Trying to make them think instead of just teeing it high
and letting it fly. Trying to make par important. And because of
what he wrought, the Open is based on that philosophy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
