<SLUG> BC-STATES-VOTE-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 227.
WASHINGTON, June 16 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday approved, 95-3, a $288 billion Defense
Department budget plan for next year that raises military payrolls
and funds new weapon programs. Supporters said the budget would
keep more military personnel from seeking employment in the private
sector. Opponents said the new spending on weapons was not needed.
A ``yes'' vote favors the budget plan.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday rejected, 83-15, an amendment to the
Defense Department budget plan that would cut weapons spending by
one billion and reallocate funds to unrelated education programs.
Supporters said the $922,000 sought for the programs would benefit
impoverished children. Opponents said the amendment would eliminate
needed funding for the military. A ``yes'' vote rejects the
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: SPENDING
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday rejected, 65-32, an amendment to the
Defense Department budget plan that would cut air travel funding
for high-ranking officials in the military. Supporters said the
spending was unnecessary and wasteful. Opponents argued that
military travel was vital to the nation's defense. A ``yes'' vote
rejects the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday approved, 380-49, a measure to investigate
the Department of Education for fraud. The measure authorizes the
General Accounting Office to conduct the audit following recent
thefts at the agency. Supporters said the measure could prevent
future theft of millions. Opponents said the investigation was not
necessary. A ``yes'' vote supports the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: SIGNATURES
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 426-4, a bill that gives
electronic contracts the same status as those signed on paper,
legalizing transactions made with an electronic signature.
Supporters said it would reduce paperwork for businesses and
consumers. Opponents said it did not go far enough to protect
privacy online. A ``yes'' vote supports the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 217-214, a bill to increase
spending for health and education. The bill would appropriate
$339.5 billion to the Departments of Labor, Health and Human
Services and Education. Supporters said it would boost spending for
needed federal programs. Opponents said the funding was not
sufficient for education, childcare and worker training.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: MONUMENTS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 243-177, an amendment to the
Interior Department spending bill that limits funding for new
national monuments. The amendment would have prohibited the agency
from planning or managing national monuments designated by the
President this year. Supporters said it would stem government
attempts to acquire more land. Opponents said it would infringe on
presidential authority. A ``yes'' vote rejects the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The attendance record is not part of the
current vote chart because the company that supplied us with the
information is no longer in service. We are looking for a new
source.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
