<HEADER>
A6419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE0617-COX     06-16 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Professionals to replace students in designing and carrying out
future bonfiresBy Laylan Copelin and Jaime Adame
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen, admitting that he
seriously considered eliminating the traditional bonfire that
turned deadly last fall, on Friday ordered a two-year moratorium to
plan a dramatically ``restructured'' event.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen outlined a bonfire designed, overseen and, in some
instances, executed by professionals instead of students, altering
a major tradition dating to 1909. The bonfire is burned just before
the annual football game between Texas A&AMP;M and the University of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen, who worked on Bonfire as a student, challenged students
to change the Aggie culture. A $1.8 million investigation of the
collapse concluded that the culture surrounding A&AMP;M contributed to
what Bowen repeatedly referred to as ``the horror'' that occurred
Nov. 18. A dozen people died, 27 were injured and dozens of others
narrowly escaped harm as the 59-foot tower of logs toppled without
warning about 2:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do what is right,'' Bowen said Friday, ``even though my
decision could be judged as `tough' on the students.''
</P>
<P>
   He said any bonfire must be designed by engineers and overseen
by construction professionals. He shrank the months-long event to a
couple of weeks by forbidding students to cut the bonfire's logs
themselves. He said professionals would cut and deliver the wood.
The bonfire site also would be fenced and monitored by video
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction was as strong as the emotions surrounding the tragedy
and the tradition. It ranged from endorsements from trustees and
the former students association to predictions of unauthorized
bonfires on private land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's going to be a lot of bogus bonfires across
Texas, from El Paso to Texarkana to the Gulf,'' said Don Ganter,
who owns five restaurants and bars that cater to Aggie students.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's already talked with students about the possibility
of an unauthorized bonfire, perhaps on his land, although he said
any bonfire would have to be safe and without alcohol. In the past,
Bonfire had been marred at times with allegations of drinking and
hazing by students.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen said he would discourage unauthorized bonfires but added
that the university could do little to punish students for
activities conducted off campus if they are not portrayed as
university events.
</P>
<P>
   He said it would take almost two years for students, faculty
members and outside professionals to plan the 2002 bonfire within
his guidelines. For this fall and perhaps in 2001, he said he
anticipated a memorial service for the victims of the bonfire
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   From the day of the collapse, Bowen said he considered
eliminating the tradition. But the university paid for a
four-month, $1.8 million investigation into the cause of the
accident. The investigation, chaired by Houston construction
executive Leo Linbeck Jr., criticized the bonfire's design,
evolving construction techniques, lack of supervision by A&AMP;M
officials and the lack of blueprints for the complicated, six-stack
structure of 5,000 or more logs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would resign because of the findings regarding
a lack of supervision by the administration, Bowen said no. The
report even noted a ``cultural bias'' at the university that
discouraged anyone from questioning the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the harsh tone of the report, Bowen said he saw a way of
making a safer bonfire by returning to the simpler, teepee style
used in the 1950s when he attended A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen also said students will have to accept changes in how
their bonfire leaders are chosen. Each generation of bonfire
leaders, called red pots for the helmets they wear, selected and
trained their successors. All were male, although women have been
allowed to work on the project in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   A floor below where Bowen delivered his remarks on campus, about
120 students, including about 10 Corps Cadets in military uniform,
watched his televised remarks mostly in silence.
</P>
<P>
   When Bowen said Bonfire is not the defining activity of the
former all-male, all-military school, many scoffed. Students hissed
when he said they would not be allowed to cut logs for future
bonfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonfire is built by students, for students and taking
construction out of students' hands defeats the purpose'' of
developing leadership, said Martin Hoover, a Lampasas junior who
witnessed the bonfire collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Krista Frederick, a Midland sophomore, said, ``The consensus
from a lot of students is that, `Something will burn next year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Woods, a junior, said students have been unfairly
criticized for the zealous culture surrounding bonfire. She
objected to the two-year moratorium: ``They are just trying to
flush out 'the bad seeds.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many praised Bowen's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Braus, whose son lost his right arm in the collapse, said,
``I applaud any words about safety and responsibility. I wished
they had focused on it sooner, but that's hindsight.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrest Lane, student body president, said it is up to students
``to move forward and come up with a safe, reconstructed event.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mayo, a 1970 graduate of A&AMP;M and president of the
Association of Former Students, said the association supports
Bowen's decision and he believes most Aggies will accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been the desire of the former student body that a way
can be found to continue Bonfire _ in a safe manner. That's the
caveat.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hugh Wilson, an A&AMP;M biology professor and bonfire critic
since 1990, said Bowen should have scrapped the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an opportunity for A&AMP;M to abandon what most people
see as a flawed enterprise,'' he said. ``Keeping it indicates A&AMP;M
is pretty much business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the administration has now taken responsibility for
what it always had contended was a student-run project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very difficult for them to blame the
students, the faculty or other entities when something goes
amiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the administration in the past ``paid lip service''
to its rules against hazing and drinking, but he expects that will
change after the deaths of a dozen people.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said stricter oversight by adults may undermine the
future of Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just may not be the attraction to students it once was,''
he said. ``With regulation, I have a feeling that enthusiasm for
bonfire will wane.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
