<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL DEMANDS WITHDRAWAL OF RWANDA AND UGANDA FROM
CONGO 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council unanimously passed a
resolution Friday night demanding the immediate withdrawal of
Rwandan and Ugandan forces from Congo and expressing outrage over
their fighting earlier this month in the Congolese city of
Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   But the council resolution, which was unanimously adopted by the
council's 15 members, dropped a four-month deadline set in an
earlier draft after the United States and Britain pointed out that
there had been no similar deadlines set in the cease-fire agreement
reached by the warring parties at the Zambian capital, Lusaka, last
July.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the council called on all the warring factions to halt
their hostilities throughout Congo and to meet their obligations
under the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was approved in the presence of members of the
Lusaka accord's political committee, who came to the United Nations
for two days of talks with council members to try to find a way to
keep the situation in Congo from deteriorating further.
</P>
<P>
   The political committee's chairman, Amama Mbabazi of Uganda,
said that while there had been violations, the cease-fire agreement
had generally succeeded, despite some violations. Mbabazi confirmed
that Rwandan and Ugandan troops had stopped fighting over Kisangani
and that their withdrawal had begun.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that an exchange of prisoners had begun and that
181 prisoners had so far been freed, most of them from Rwanda,
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Congo itself.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, a spokesman for the United Nations, Manoel De
Almeida e Silva, said the Rwandans and Ugandans has agreed to pull
back a little more than 60 miles each in a week's time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the council members showed increasingly little patience
with the lack of progress in ending the war, which has devastated
Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's representative, Jeremy Greenstock, said the council
was ``fed up to the back teeth'' by the parties who promised to
take action and then failed to do it.
</P>
<P>
   And the U.S. representative, Richard C. Holbrooke, said, ``the
parties have been responsible for the problem, and they cannot
simply create a mess and expect the world to clean it up.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Tunisia agreed to send some troops by June 30 to set
up a headquarters for a U.N. peacekeeping presence in the battered
Congolese city of Kisangani. A diplomat said that the Tunisians
would send about 100 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the secretary general's special representative to
Congo, Kamel Morjane, appealed for two companies of peacekeepers
that are needed to fill the vacuum left by the departure of warring
Rwandan and Ugandan forces, who have fought over Kisangani at a
heavy cost of at least 160 civilians killed and 1,000 injured.
</P>
<P>
   The Congo war was also joined by Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia on
the side of President Lauren Kabila of Congo, while Rwanda and
Uganda initially came in to support rival rebel movements before
they turned to fighting each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
