<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-W.VA-UNDERWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME AND POLITICS STILL A MARVEL FOR NATION'S OLDEST GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, W. Va. _ ``I was first diagnosed as a tumor,'' said
Gov. Cecil Underwood, grinning at age 77 as he spoke of the many
tricks of time, beginning with the suspicion by his mother, Della,
that she was more likely ill than pregnant with him when she was
43.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood has turned out a hearty offspring, challenging time at
either extreme. He became the nation's youngest governor when he
was first elected here in 1956 at the age of 34, and now he has
returned as the nation's oldest governor after winning a second
term 40 years later.
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder that his crowded executive desk does not bother
with framed mottoes about where the buck stops. ``Age is a matter
of the mind,'' reads his desk marker. ``If you don't mind, it
doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in this spirit that Underwood is running again this year.
He is aiming to be chosen one more time by the voters _ naturally
becoming the oldest re-elected governor _ not so much to defy time
as to simply ignore its accumulation.
</P>
<P>
   Partisan politics aside, Underwood may be presaging the
geriatric advancements looming before American democracy, not to
mention before the American workplace with its receding retirement
age. This unpretentious hard-scrabble state already has the
distinction of bearing the oldest median age of any in the Union _
older than Florida with its legions of retirees. Job hunting often
force its natives to emigrate, but a number eventually return home
to settle after their careers. Their ballot choices regularly
include Secretary of State Ken Hechler, an 85-year-old Democratic
legend from the New Deal era who, like his Republican rival the
governor, simply refuses to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time here, my wife spent one night in the governor's
mansion, then had to be rushed to the maternity ward,'' the
governor happily recalled. The occasion was the birth of the second
of three children of Hovah Underwood, who is first lady once more,
presiding over family holiday gatherings that now pack six
grandchildren into their old executive homestead. Underwood will
turn 78 two days before the next election. He registered to vote as
soon as he was 21. Immediately afterward, he listed himself as a
Republican candidate for the state's House of Delegates. He won, at
the age of 22. He served 12 years in the Legislature, then won the
governorship, prevailing as if age were beside the point, when
President Dwight D. Eisenhower's coattails swept the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very stimulating,'' Underwood said of the gilded
Statehouse dome that greets him, same as his first time around,
outside his bedroom window. ``It makes me want to go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   As he briskly moves about the executive chamber, he flashes past
the darkly handsome ghost of himself in photos of 40 years ago,
when his hair was thick and black, his ambition keen. Now his hair
is thick and gray, his ambition keen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's much better the second time,'' he said of incumbency
resumed. ``I had been a legislator and done some high school
teaching, but I didn't have any real management experience the
first time,'' said the governor, a graduate of Salem College with a
master of arts degree from West Virginia University. ``Now I have a
much broader understanding,'' he said of varied experience garnered
in four decades of jobs between governorships.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood was a coal mining executive, a chemical company
lobbyist, president of Bethany College and, dearest in his memory,
a founder of the Software Valley Foundation, an early business and
government effort to create high-tech jobs that has taken root in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I ran again, I decided to focus on one issue I believed
passionately in,'' said Underwood. The issue was fiber optics and
its industrial promise for this splendidly hilly but remote state.
``But one morning my wife said: `What are you talking about?
Nobody's paying attention to you!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``So I started carrying this with me,'' he said, displaying a
handy length of fiber-optic cable neatly peeled open, as if a
modern mystery unveiled. ``I never made another public appearance
without it,'' said the governor, shaking the futuristic training
aid that became his swagger stick on the stump as he overcame early
poll deficits.
</P>
<P>
   The governor does like to go back in time to the 35-acre farm in
Joseph Mills where he grew up, and where he now works the family
fields any open weekend for his leisure. ``That's Silas, my
father,'' he said, pointing behind the governor's chair to a photo
of his father sweating in those fields at the age of 83, seven
years before his death. ``He never got beyond the second grade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He voted the first time in 1896 and never missed an
election,'' said the governor, reflecting on why he himself loved
politics and refused to retire from it. ``In contrast, my mother
didn't believe in women's suffrage. But she called me one day in
1948 and said she was ready to vote,'' he said, smiling at what
time and politics could accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the people who came by the farm, it was the political
candidates who made the biggest impression on me,'' Underwood said,
remembering how they had always stopped to chat, as determined as
salesmen. Just so, he began developing his candidate's touch as a
young student when he got a job as a Fuller Brush salesman going
door to door. It was his first venture into that nice-to-see-you
world of selling himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very shy, and this was a big help,'' Underwood said of
that far-from-last approach to the people. ``You just had to do
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
