<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-GA-FLA-ADVANCE0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida seeks to halt win streak of Georgia
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This week has been one of both obstacles and oddities
for Florida. The team missed its initial flight into Atlanta on
Sunday, had a bus break down on Tuesday and coach Al Morrell had an
anxiety attack on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida hasn't lost its focus entering the Georgia-Florida
High School All-Star game tonight at 6 p.m at Georgia Tech's Grant
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Georgia's won three in a row and we're here to end
that,'' Florida defensive lineman Santonio Thomas said. ``We're
here to make Florida go up one.''
</P>
<P>
   After 15 games, the series is tied at 6-6-3. And if this game is
like most, it should be relatively low scoring. Last year, Georgia
won 13-7 and only once has the game gotten into the 30s. In 1988,
Thomas County Central quarterback and eventual Heisman Trophy
winner Charlie Ward led Georgia to a 38-32 victory. Morrell doesn't
think there'll be a shootout this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see either side scoring more than 21 points,'' Morrell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Stringer, coach for the Georgia Team, has been impressed
with linebacker Daryl Smith (Georgia Tech) and cornerback Terrell
Butler (Nebraska). Northside teammates William Thompson (Georgia)
and Kenny Parker (Florida) shore up the defensive front.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be expected to stop Florida quarterbacks Jared Clark
(Notre Dame) and Matt Redding (Georgia) and an offensive line that
has one player weighing less than 300 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's defensive line already is wagering chicken wings for
the guy who makes the most tackles. They'll be focused on slowing
Cartersville running back Ronnie Brown (Auburn).
</P>
<P>
   And Stringer said speedy receiver Kelvin Kight, a Super 11 pick
last year who signed with Florida, runs on ``another gear.'' That's
all Florida defensive back/receiver Matt Jackson, a fellow Gator
signee, needed to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is for bragging rights, not just Georgia and
Florida,'' Jackson said, ``but me and him, the competition is
starting early. I'm excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
