<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-KNOBLAUCH-PSYCHOL     06-16 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KNOBLAUCH-PSYCHOLOGY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS PSYCHOLOGISTS EXAMINE KNOBLAUCH'S PROBLEMS  
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Va., Ohio)  (See also BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT2, 21 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What does a desperately frustrated Yankees second
baseman have in common with a famous 19th century Russian novelist?
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch may think not much. But in a way, he is in the
same pickle as Leo Tolstoy was as a child, when his brother
challenged him to stand in a corner until he could stop thinking
about white bears.
</P>
<P>
   Tolstoy, legend has it stood in that corner for quite a while,
with white bears _ like the exquisitely maddening image of a
baseball speeding effortlessly to first base _ trooping endlessly
through his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Tolstoy's brush with obsession was trivial, but Knoblauch, who
left a ballgame in frustration Thursday night after his inability
to complete a simple throw to first base resulted in three errors,
has a lot more at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, sports psychologists surmised Friday, is that an
action that Knoblauch has instinctually performed 1000 times is
suddenly the object of conscious thought. In the past two years,
the infielder who once won a Gold Glove award for his defense, has
been plagued by a rash of throwing errors.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine, suggested Rick Wolff, who worked with the
Cleveland Indians from 1989 to 1994 and now is private practice in
Westchester, consciously analyzing how to place your legs each time
you go down a flight of stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ballplayers, by the time they get to the major leagues, know
how to automatically run from home to first, they know how to throw
a ball,'' Wolff said. ``They don't think about that stuff. But when
you start thinking about these things, when you start thinking `How
much pressure should I put into my throw? Should I try to grip the
ball a certain way?' you're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as the baseball axiom goes: ``Thinking is stinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the more a ballplayer _ or a golfer or a football
player or anyone else abruptly thrust into obsession _ tries to
stop thinking, the more stubborn the thoughts become.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Daniel Wegner, a psychologist at the University of Virginia,
knows a lot about such problems, having become interested in such
lapses of mental controls because of the Tolstoy legend. But he
studies these problems mostly in the laboratory, though he has also
carried his experiments to the putting green. .
</P>
<P>
   Wegner and his colleagues have found that they can ``create an
obsession in a matter of minutes'' just by instructing their
subjects, usually college students, to try not to think about
something _ sex, for example, or an old flame.
</P>
<P>
   And stressful situations, Wegner said, make the struggle for
mental control even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiny little things just grow, mostly by our attempts to stop
them,'' he said. ``It's almost like trying to put it out of your
mind causes it to be put into indelible type.''
</P>
<P>
   Wegner has a reverse strategy for combatting such obsessional
thoughts (and Yankees manager Joe Torre, take note): He tells
people that they should think about _ rather than banish _ the
unwanted thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is that the thought gets tired and goes away,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's situation, he said, ``sounds like an extreme case.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that perhaps the infielder should try to throw
badly; after making 100 such throws, he might stop focusing on it
and thereby start tossing perfect strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Sports psychologists who work with major league players have
their own methods, and some said Friday that they were dubious
about Wegner's approach.
</P>
<P>
   But they agreed that ballplayers who have problems like
Knoblauch's are struggling more with their minds than with their
bodies. And while there are famous cases involving other baseball
players _ most notably Steve Sax, another second baseman, and
Mackey Sasser, a catcher _ such difficulties are more common than
fans realize, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying cause and the solution may be different for each
struggling athlete, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff, who estimates that three or four major league and college
players falter in similar ways each season, said that his strategy
is to try to get players to focus on something else. ``I call it,
for the lack of a better term, distraction therapy,'' he said,
``meaning that instead of letting them get caught up in paranoia or
gripped by fear, you try to distract them with another thought.''
That strategy was parodied in the movie ``Bull Durham,'' in which
Susan Sarandon made Tim Robbins, playing ``Nuke Laloush,'' a wild
pitcher, wear a garter.
</P>
<P>
   The pressures on a stumbling ballplayer are so immense, Wolff
said _ great enough Thursday night to drive Knoblauch from the
stadium _ that some athletes try to hide them. As in Knoblauch's
case, the problem escalates in the glare of media attention and
becomes a label the player often finds it hard to shed. The
ballplayer's teammates, he added, are also under pressure, often
not knowing what to do or how to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you say to a guy like that?'' Wolff said . ``Don't
worry about it? No sweat? Take it easy? Deep down in their mind,
they're thinking, `I hope it's not contagious.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Maher, a professor at the Graduate School of Applied
and Professional Psychology at Rutgers University, who also works
with the Cleveland Indians, said that the Cleveland team tries to
spot ballplayers who are having difficulties early on, and work
with them before things get worse.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not a player successfully overcomes his problem often
depends on how strong a support system he has, Maher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are confused. They are tense. They have to see that the
people who are trying to help them have a plan, and feel
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that last season two Cleveland players _ whom he
declined to name _ started having problems with basic technique.
Maher and other team psychologists began working with the
ballplayers immediately, he said, and successfully headed off
further difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who did not respond to calls asking for comment,
had Knoblauch talk to a team counselor during the playoffs two
years ago, after the second baseman had argued with an umpire
rather than complete a play.
</P>
<P>
   While fans and commentators have speculated that stresses in
Knoblauch's personal life _ his father suffers from Alzheimer's _
might be contributing to his troubles, Maher and Wolff said that in
their experience, there is little correlation between such stresses
and the mental glitches that for a major leaguer can turn every
game into torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no rhyme or reason to this,'' Wolff said. ``We all
have stress in our lives, and major leaguers have stress. I've seen
guys who have no care in the world and they say `Rick, I can't make
this play.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sax, who in 1983 as a second baseman for the Dodgers had
difficulties almost identical to Knoblauch's, said he does not
remember being under particular stress at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But he remembers, he said, what it felt like, and can guess at
what Knoblauch is feeling now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the toughest thing I've ever gone through,'' said Sax,
now an analyst for Fox Sports Net's Baseball Today. ``It's
completely unexplainable. It's so awful, and everybody in the world
is watching you.''
</P>
<P>
   When his problem was at its peak, he said, he stood on the field
and prayed ``Please, please don't hit it to me, please don't hit
the ball to me!''
</P>
<P>
   Then, when a small white sphere was hurtling in his direction,
he felt sorry for himself. Then he got mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got really ticked and I beat this thing,'' Saks said. ``I
didn't turn my back on it. I bit it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he is glad he went through the ordeal. ``It made
me a better person. It put things in perspective and it made me a
better player.''
</P>
<P>
   The following years, he added, were the best in his career,
years when his second-base prayers changed to ``Please hit the ball
to me because when you do, this game is over.''
</P>
<P>
   All Knoblauch has to do, Sax said, ``is to get his confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could just turn our brains off, we'd be fine,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 2108EDT &QL; 
