</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA SKEPTICS STALK HUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Sammy Sosa trade speculation has taken an
interesting twist in Boston. Wednesday's unbridled optimism gave
way to Friday's skepticism. By the time I got through reading the
papers, checking e-mail, and listening to nitwit radio, it was
pretty clear that Sosa is a bum not worth a sack of inner tubes;
certainly not worth a future superstar like Trot Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Only in Boston. It's part of our (itals)can't do(unitals)
mentality. We don't want Ken Griffey. Not if we're going to have to
part with Steve Lomasney. Forget about Randy Johnson. If the
Diamondbacks are asking for Tomo Ohka, the price is too high. Same
with Sosa. No thank you, Cubs. Don't try unloading your baggage for
the Sox' best right fielder since Dwight Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Sox prospects should love it here because most of them are stars
before they set foot in Fenway. Few become stars when they get
here, but that doesn't stop us from touting the can't miss kids
down on the farm. It's the Juan Bustabad Syndrome. In his lengthy
reign as the Globe's god of baseball, the estimable Peter Gammons
regularly enlarged kids on the farm. He had us convinced Bustabad
was the next Luis Aparicio. I believe Juan was last seen parking
cars outside the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And now we have legions of Sox fans who don't want Sosa.
Afterall, the bum has only knocked in (itals)299(unitals) runs the
last two years and hasn't hit more than 63 homers since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   There are various reasons for not wanting Sammy. He'll make too
much money and that will make Pedro mad. Sammy's lofty salary will
make it tough for the Sox to get a handout from the city and state
for a new Fenway. He isn't a great defensive outfielder. He hasn't
made the Cubs winners. He'll disrupt that perfect Dan Duquette
clubhouse chemistry. He strikes out too much. He's an ex-Cub and
the last big-name ex-Cub the Sox acquired was Bill Buckner. He's an
old 31. When you really think about it, he's no better than Troy
O'Leary. Blah. Blah. Blah.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and here's the biggie. The Cubs are asking way too much.
They want Trot Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Please. We all like Nixon. He's earned his spot in the everyday
lineup. He plays smashmouth baseball. He gets his uniform dirty and
goes all out on every play. He spit nails in Roger Clemens's face,
then hit a game-winning homer off the Rocket in the greatest
regular-season game of the last two decades. He's got fire. He went
into friday night's game hitting .298 with seven homers and 36
RBIs. Trot's teammates love him. His wonderful wife ran the Boston
Marathon for the Jimmy Fund.
</P>
<P>
   When Nixon ripped a first-inning double off the Wall against the
Blue Jays, 30,000 fans said, ``Let's see Sosa do that!'' They said
it again in the fourth when Nixon uncorked a Roberto Clemente-like
throw to home plate from right field.
</P>
<P>
   Trot says he avoids newspapers and sports radio, but he knows
he's getting much fan support during this rumor frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good,'' he said. ``I've always enjoyed these fans. I've
tried to go out and represent the organization and fans the best
way I know how. I go out and play hard and for these fans to back
me like that, what else could I ask?''
</P>
<P>
   With John Valentin and Scott Hatteberg, Nixon is the last
remnant of the Lou Gorman administration. The Sox gave him a hefty
signing bonus and guaranteed him No. 7, then waited patiently while
he struggled through the minors. He seemed to have a lot of
injuries for a young guy, and with last season's abysmal start,
there was fear he might never be an everyday big-league player. Now
he's a fan favorite _ too good to give up for Sammy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They waited for me forever and I've only played one year, and
for the fans to want to keep me here now, it means as much as the
game-winning homer against the Yankees,'' said Trot. ``And that's
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Okay. But if you were a general manager, would you give up Trot
Nixon for Sammy Sosa?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Nixon said with a smile. ``The front office is
gonna do their job the way I do my job. They know I love to play
for 'em. But things happen in baseball, whether it's trades or
retirements. I'm just going to continue. If it happens, it happens.
Right now, I'm just trying to get back on track and get back on the
winning track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to let these other things bother me and it hasn't
bothered me. I think my name was tossed around when Petey (Pedro
Martinez) was coming over here. Hey, if it's gonna happen, it's
gonna happen. Right now, I'm just going to go out and put it on the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping he would understand, I told Nixon, ``nothing personal,
mind you, but I would trade you to the Cubs for Sammy Sosa. In a
heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't offend me,'' he said. ``He's a great ballplayer.
He'd help any team.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Boston. We don't need 60 homers. Not if it means parting
with Nixon or a legend like Ohka.
</P>
<P>
   Think they'll take Bustabad?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by
e-mail at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
