<HEADER>
A6467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-2TAKES     06-16 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP IS WORKING TO AVOID ANOTHER BUDGET FIASCO 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It seems as if two sequels are being produced in
Washington these days.
</P>
<P>
   In front of Union Station, the city's main railroad terminal,
camera crews have been busily filming ``Hannibal,'' the follow-on
to the hit movie ``Silence of the Lambs.'' In the Capitol a few
blocks away and in the White House down Pennsylvania Avenue,
Republicans and Democrats seem to be making a reprise of last
year's budget battle.
</P>
<P>
   In their drama, however, Republicans are fervently hoping for a
happier outcome, praying that in the end President Clinton _ their
version of the cannibalistic Hannibal Lecter _ will not eat them
for lunch again.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republicans, speed is the watchword, especially in the
House: Pass spending bills quickly so that ample time is allowed to
negotiate a final budget deal with the president, who has already
threatened to veto six of the 13 spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to negotiate with the president, and we have to
negotiate with the president,'' said Bill Young, the amiable
Florida Republican who is chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee. ``But if you don't pass bills before September and
October, you don't have time to leisurely negotiate with the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Those negotiations are expected to be contentious. With the veto
threats, the White House complains that the bills provide $23
billion less than what Clinton has requested and scale back some of
the president's favorite programs, such as providing more money for
classroom teachers and setting aside more land for national
monuments.
</P>
<P>
   With the Treasury awash in a budget surplus, Clinton and his
advisers feel they are on firm policy and political grounds to
oppose what they see as Republican miserliness.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time of affluence, in a time of surplus, you make
different kinds of judgments than you do when you're facing a
crippling deficit,'' said Jack Lew, director of the Office of
Management and Budget.
</P>
<P>
   So far, House leaders have been making good on their promise.
With the expected passage Friday of a spending bill to fund the
Interior Department, the Environment Protection Agency and other
agencies, the House has approved four spending measures, and its
leaders predict that all 13 spending measures will be cleared for
action on the floor by the time the House adjourns for its July 4
recess.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Senate has approved three spending measures,
though providing money at far different levels from the House
versions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, action has been slower in the Senate, and the House
leaders have been able to maintain unity on the measures only by
convincing some of their moderate members to vote for measures just
to keep the process going.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're replaying a record that has been played for each of the
previous three years,'' said Robert Reischauer, the former head of
the Congressional Budget Office. ``The year starts off with the
Republican leadership saying, `This year will be different. We'll
get the appropriations bills through in a timely fashion and use
the month of September and maybe a little bit of October to
negotiate with the White House.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then what happens is that the press of other business slows
things down, and divisions within the Republican Party slows things
down.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey acknowledges a certain
inevitability in this year's budget fight, saying that the
``essential model will be the same.'' But Armey disputes the idea
that the Republicans were routed last year. ``The president is the
biggest spin doctor in this town,'' he said. ``We got some of what
we wanted. They got some of what they wanted. But they jumped up
and down celebrating like they won the whole ball of wax.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Republicans who have been critical of their party's
leaders in the past say they have little choice but to follow the
course they have set. If the Republicans crafted spending bills
that would attract the support of Democrats and the president, they
would lose the backing of conservative Republicans, possibly
ensuring that no measures were approved. That could lead to a
government shutdown, which Republican leaders fear most.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's their alternative?'' said Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y., who
has often been at odds with his leadership. ``If they get one or
two Democrats, they would lose five to 10 Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Looming over Congress as it completes its constitutionally
required work on spending bills that allow the government to
continue operating are the coming elections. With all of the House
and one-third of the Senate up for re-election, lawmakers are eager
to finish their work and return home to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And many lawmakers are well aware that with Republicans holding
a wafer-thin six-vote majority in the House and lacking the ability
to break a filibuster in the Senate, Congress has achieved little
this session. Measures such as a patients' bill of rights,
liberalization of trade with China and reform of election law have
languished.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the spending bills have become magnets for the
ideological and policy divisions that are always found in Congress.
Vetoes have been threatened not only because the White House feels
Republican spending bills do not provide enough money for programs
but also because a number of the measures contain amendments known
as riders which do things like blocking agencies such as Veterans
Affairs or Health and Human Services from transferring money to the
Justice Department to help its suit against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Armey's assurances, congressional Republicans want to
avoid a repeat of last year, when Congress and the White House did
not put the final touches on the last spending bills until Nov. 19,
49 days after the fiscal year began on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the crush of last-minute negotiations, with the threat of a
government shutdown looming over their heads, and needing to ladle
out pork-barrel projects to bring reluctant lawmakers on board,
Republican leaders eventually agreed to a budget that was over $30
billion more than the limits placed on spending by the Balanced
Budget Act of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Such an explosion in spending is heatedly opposed by a small
group of House Republicans who call themselves the Conservative
Action Team and are known on the Hill as the ``cats.'' With the
Republicans holding only a slim majority, the lawmakers have
tremendous sway with the House leaders, who know they can scuttle
any bill by withdrawing their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that bodes well for us is that we've only got a
six-vote majority, and I'm going to stretch that as much as I can
to not spend your grandchildren's money,'' said Rep. Tom Coburn,
R-Okla., a leading voice among the ``cats.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
