<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6468 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SOSA-BOS &LR;      06-16 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA   TAKES A SWING AT TRADE RUMORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Sure, they still love Sammy in Chicago, but judging by
the banner in the window of the souvenir shop across the street
from Wrigley Field, the unthinkable has become the anticipated:
</P>
<P>
   ``SAMMY SOSA CLEARANCE SALE.''
</P>
<P>
   The message is almost as unmistakable as Sosa's gesture to his
fans: Tap your heart, blow a kiss, tap your heart again, and blow
out the candles on Sosa's reign as the Cubs' most beloved player.
Those Cubs jerseys with Sosa's name stitched on the back are about
to become collector's items.
</P>
<P>
   The team won't say it and neither will the slugger, who Friday
was visibly annoyed friend Manny Alexander was saying it, but there
is a growing sense Sosa will be traded before the July 31 trading
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have no problem here,'' Sosa said Friday morning to
the daily cluster of reporters that gather around his locker. ``I'm
employed like everybody else. I'm here. I'm here. (itals)I'm
here.(unitals)''
</P>
<P>
   It was true. To borrow the pet phrase of Pedro Martinez, his
across-the-street neighbor in Santo Domingo and rumored future
teammate, Sammy was in the house. Before the game, with batting
practice canceled because of rain, he sat at his locker next to the
biggest boombox in the clubhouse, speaking up when he could no
longer bear an especially slow Michael Jackson ballad. ``What
happened, did somebody die in here?'' he asked no one in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter from Boston mentioned having spoken to
Alexander, the former Cub and Sosa pal who said the slugger wants
to come to Boston, Sosa grew edgy. ``I don't think it was
appropriate, what he said,'' Sosa said. ``I'm not saying what he
said was wrong. But I'll talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   He was just getting warmed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Manny, but I didn't tell him to say anything,''
Sosa said. ``Whatever he's saying, he's saying from his point, not
my point. It's possible I could go a lot of places. Manny is not
here no more. He's happy in case something happens, but nothing has
happened. I don't know where I'm going to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe everything is going to settle down. If not, I don't
have any control over it. Manny's not my agent. He said something
he's not supposed to be saying. There are rumors all over, and one
of the things I'm trying to correct is that he cannot say something
like that because he's not my agent.''
</P>
<P>
   At no time, however, did Sosa suggest Alexander had falsely
quoted him, or attributed thoughts to him that were not his own. He
just didn't appreciate Alexander sharing his confidences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be talking no more,'' Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the skies parted and the stands filled, Sosa sprinted
out to his position in right field, like he does every game, and
greeted his admirers in the bleachers. He singled in his first
at-bat, then came up with the bases loaded and cleared them with an
opposite-field triple, hustling around the bases like a man who had
a plane to catch.
</P>
<P>
   The three RBIs in the Cubs' 9-8 win over the Expos gave Sosa
1,002 for his career. He has 61 RBIs in the Cubs' first 65 games
and he should easily knock in 100 runs for the sixth straight
season. He and Hall of Famer Hack Wilson are the only Cubs ever to
do so in five straight.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't hit a home run in a week, but he has 19 home runs this
season and has hit 148 home runs since Opening Day 1998, a number
second to Mark McGwire. And since a 3-for-28 start through seven
games, Sosa is batting .335 (76 for 227) in his last 59 games,
including Friday's 2 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   Why wouldn't he still be here? ``I'm one of his closest
friends,'' said Cubs outfielder Glenallen Hill, ``and Sammy doesn't
want to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be pretty hard to trade Sammy. When you look at what his
value is on and off the field, it's unbelievable. This guy's an
icon. He makes a lot of money for everybody. What I'd like to see
is Sammy Sosa finish his career as a Chicago Cub. He loves it
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's as clear to Hill as it is to the owner of the souvenir
shop across the street why that is unlikely to happen. ``With
Sammy,'' Hill said. ``It's just about money.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who will turn 32 in Nov. 12, is being paid $10 million
this seson, $11 million in 2001. He will be a free agent after
next year. Sosa would like a contract extension that will pay him
$15 million to $20 million a year, which would make him the game's
highest-paid player _ at least until Alex Rodriguez signs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, who are a fourth-place team even with Sosa, say they
haven't decided what they intend to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can trade him, extend him, or let the contract run its
course,'' said Cubs general manager Ed Lynch. ``It's too early to
say what we're going to do. It's not like we have to trade him. But
if there is a deal that makes us noticeably better, it's my job to
listen to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But privately, numerous baseball sources believe the Cubs
already have made the decision not to grant him a contract
extension. Trade Sosa? Like Cubs first baseman Mark Grace said,
plenty of superstars have been dealt before, including McGwire, the
slugger with whom Sosa has conducted celebrated home run duels in
each of the last two seasons. The Cubs are also the team that
couldn't pay enough to keep pitcher Greg Maddux from escaping as a
free agent to Atlanta, where he won three more Cy Young Awards to
add to the one he'd already won in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they've been one of those teams that have been
willing to pay one player a third of their budget,'' Hill said. ``I
think that's something they would try to steer away from.''
</P>
<P>
   One Chicago newspaper columnist even ventured into grassy-knoll
territory, suggesting the Tribune Company, which owns the ball
club, was using its flagship newspaper to cast aspersions at Sosa
so that Cubs fans would be more receptive to a deal involving the
city's most popular athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's trade value may never be higher, and there are some
deep-pockets clubs that have indicated a willingness to enter the
bidding for his services, namely the Yankees, Red Sox, and Mets.
One of those teams is likely to package the three or four players
it will take to acquire Sosa, who may be better suited to finish
his career in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there are high-profile players involved,'' Lynch said,
``you have people who are calling to say, `I just want to be able
to say that I did,' '' Lynch said. ``You can tell their interest is
lukewarm at best. Then you have other people who, based on your
previous dealings with them and based on the tone of the
conversation, you know they're players in the thing and they want
to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask the question, in any trade, `Is it worth me getting my
people out there to look at your system?' If the guy says, `Yeah,'
right away, then you know they're serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox obviously fit in the latter category. Friday night,
Cubs scouts were in Pawtucket. They've already done their homework
on the Yankees and Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa will command a package of at least three players, and more
likely four, with at least one already in the big leagues. ``The
Cubs can't trade the guy for players who may someday play in the
big leagues,'' one source said. ``They have to be getting someone
of impact in return. It wouldn't surprise me if the Cubs ask the
Sox for (Carl) Everett, for example, even if they know they can't
get him. (Trot) Nixon is a better possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch refused to speculate on what he would want in return for
Sosa. ``I can do everything I want to determine the value of a
player, but the other people are going to determine his value, what
the demand is on their end. The offers that come in for any player
determine what his value is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch cautioned if a trade does happen, it will need time to
take place. ``The Red Sox have been talking about a righthanded
power hitter for years over there,'' said Damon Buford, who played
two seasons for the Red Sox before coming here in a trade for
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the premier power hitters of the last century.
This is just me talking, but for what the Red Sox want over there,
I'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Sosa had a very public dispute with manager Don
Baylor, who had questioned the outfielder's defensive skills and
had suggested he steal more bases. They later had a clear-the-air
session, but it may be an uneasy truce at best. How does that
impact on whether Sosa stays with the Cubs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Irrelevant,'' said one Cubs player. ``This is all about
economics.''
</P>
<P>
   The souvenir shop across the street is not alone in weighing in
on Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``A player of his caliber, everybody's got an opinion about
Sammy Sosa,'' Lynch said. ``Good or bad, there's no indifference
out there, and justifiably so. He's the most visible player in the
National League at this point, other than Mark McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth was sold. Reggie Jackson was traded. Frank Robinson.
Mark McGwire. Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Even Manny Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   There's a shop window in Chicago betting Sosa's name will be on
that list, too, and soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
