<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6469 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-2NDTAK     06-16 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the ``cats.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week's action on a spending bill to fund the departments of
Health and Human Services, Labor, and Education, and other social
services agencies, displayed all the promise and the potential
pitfalls of the Republicans' strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The massive $342 billion measure _ the largest of the 13
spending bills _ is traditionally a lightning rod for fights over
health and education policy, even though 71 per cent of its funds
goes to programs like Medicare and Medicaid. Last year the bill was
so controversial that the House never approved it, instead rolling
it into a larger, broad-based spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   This year Republicans were determined to push the bill through.
The amount allocated to the bill's discretionary programs _ nearly
$6 billion less than what Clinton had requested _ was small enough
to placate conservatives. Republican moderates and heads of the
appropriations committees grumbled, but they held out the hope that
in negotiations with the White House later this year more money
would be found for some of their pet programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some areas in some of the bills already passed, and
some that are coming up, where we could use some extra money,''
said Young.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the measure moved towards passage, Democrats were
relishing using those votes against Republicans in marginal
districts. ``This is an important day for us on the road to winning
back the House,'' said Laura Nichols, spokeswoman for House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt. She added, ``We think it's going to
come back to haunt them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the last minute, however, conservatives used a parliamentary
maneuver Tuesday night to strip the bill of the ``emergency
spending'' designation for $500 million in funds for public health
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Without that emergency designation the measure was not half a
billion dollars over the limit. Young's staff scrambled to find a
way to keep the measure within the spending limits, finally
settling on an amendment to cut by 0.6 percent all discretionary
programs covered by the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But when Democrats released a list of how much that cut would
affect popular programs like funding for the National Institutes of
Health, Pell Grants and Head Start, Republican moderates revolted
and, much to the dismay of their conservative brethren, helped
defeat the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six-tenths of 1 percent!'' said Coburn incredulously. ``We
couldn't even live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   With the $500 million in public health funds safe for now, even
though it will mean cutting that amount out of another spending
bill later, the House leaders put the spending bill up for a vote.
But even then its passage was rocky. At the end of the 15-minute
voting period the measure looked as if it was going down to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican leaders held the voting time open a few extra
minutes and rounded up enough votes to pass the bill by a scant
three votes. Clinton has said he will veto the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
