<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MOSLEY-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY, DE LA HOYA HAVE PLAN OF ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like Robert Frost's man stopping by a snowy wood,
Oscar De La Hoya and Shane Mosley have promises to keep Saturday
night. But, unlike Frost's man, neither has any idea how many miles
they will go before they sleep.
</P>
<P>
   All they know for sure is that if either of them is true to his
word, somebody is going to sleep early at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya is making the first defense of the WBC welterweight
title he was handed after Felix Trinidad vacated it to move to 154
pounds. De La Hoya has promised four knockouts in four fights this
year, and knows to deliver on that he has to deliver Mosley to a
place he's never been: the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, the undefeated former lightweight champion who is
challenging De La Hoya for a lot more than that belt, has promised
he will take De La Hoya ``soul searching'' before knocking him out.
For him to deliver, Mosley has to do what no man has done: render
De La Hoya unconscious, or so near to it that referee Lou Moret
steps in and ends what is anticipated to be a fierce affair.
</P>
<P>
   Such promises have been made far more often in boxing than
they've been fulfilled. Derrell Coley, De La Hoya's last victim,
promised to do terrible damage to him, for example, and then tried
to fight with his fists covering his ears most of the night. This
led to his being destroyed in seven rounds. He was far from the
first De La Hoya opponent to talk one fight and produce another.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, in contrast, has delivered on every promise he's made in
boxing, with the exception of making the 1992 Olympic team. That
failure came as a shock because Mosley was considered the best
139-pound amateur in the United States at the time, yet he was
beaten soundly by Vernon Forrest in the trials in what was arguably
the biggest fight of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that failure, Mosley (34-0, 32 KOs) became the most
dominant lightweight in the world, winning the IBF title from
Philip Holiday and then easily defending it eight times before
moving up two weight classes to challenge De La Hoya. It was a move
Mosley made the right way.
</P>
<P>
   He made it slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley has fought three times at his new weight before
challenging De La Hoya. This has allowed him to get used to
carrying more weight in the ring. Bigger and stronger than most
people understand, Mosley has actually been stronger at 147, but
just as fast as he was as a lightweight. It is a combination that
has some saying he will be the one who exposes De La Hoya's
weaknesses and takes him apart.
</P>
<P>
   To do that Mosley must first get inside De La Hoya's deadly left
jab. Once there, he will surely do what he has always done before,
which is rip at his opponent's ribcage with some of the sport's
best body punches. They are the kind of punches that wear a man
down like each swing of a lumberjack's ax until his opponent
finally collapses from their sheer volume. It is a difficult way to
do a dangerous task, but it is effective and Mosley knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar knows he can't just run in and do what he wants,''
Mosley said. ``He knows I can hit him and I can hurt him. I know I
can knock him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Mosley's speed and willingness to throw punches, De
La Hoya is sure to be hit more than in any of his previous 33
fights (32-1, 23 KOs). But the same is likely for Mosley, who too
often opens himself up to be hit by the left hand when he becomes
preoccupied with offense. Since that happens to be De La Hoya's
greatest weapon, this could prove to be a fatal stylistic flaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pick Oscar for the very reason people are picking Mosley,''
says veteran fight trainer Teddy Atlas. ``Mosley stays busy for
three minutes while Oscar picks his spots. I think Mosley will walk
right into a De La Hoya punch.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, it will likely be a left hook or left uppercut, the
champion's two most devastating punches. Many, including Mosley,
have labeled De La Hoya a one-handed fighter, because he seldom
uses his right hand to do anything but grip a golf club. Although
that may be true, his left has been so murderous that only Trinidad
has been truly competitive against it, and even he was far from his
normal self because of his inability to adjust to De La Hoya's hand
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley should not have that problem, but he may face another.
Although he will be the only fighter De La Hoya has faced who has
faster hands, he will also, for the first time, be in with someone
nearly as fast and clearly more powerful with a single punch. What
that should mean is Mosley will be hit more than in any of his
previous fights and he will be getting hit harder. How he reacts
will have as much to say about the outcome as anything because some
fighters who have never been close to trouble _ as Mosley has not _
find it wearing mentally when they are and at some point they
crack.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley has promised he will be the one to break down De La Hoya.
Perhaps so, but veteran trainer Tommy Brooks hit on Mosley's
dilemma when he said, ``I haven't seen Mosley get hit yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news there is that he is an elusive target. The bad
news is that his 32 knockouts have all come because he has worn his
opponents down with barrages of punches. If he is unable to hurt De
La Hoya enough to prevent the champion from countering, what then?
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya believes he knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect this fight to be very, very explosive,'' De La Hoya
said. ``My plan is to attack, attack, attack. I'm not going to show
him any boxing skills, the way I did with Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking him lightly, but he doesn't have a knockout
artist's punch. He really doesn't possess one-punch knockout power.
He wears you down. But with the spark of aggression I have now, I
feel I can easily match his speed, no problem. He's so aggressive
at times, it's like he can't control his temper. If he rushes me,
it will be fun to stick my jab on his chest or in his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's tendency to attack with wild fury is something De La
Hoya believes he will be able to capitalize on. At some moment when
Mosley least expects it, De La Hoya thinks his challenger will stay
one punch too long at close range and pay a dear price.
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't, De La Hoya may still beat Mosley, but it will be
a long, hard pull. But if Mosley makes that one mistake, De La
Hoya's promise will be kept and Mosley will have gone to sleep a
few miles short of the welterweight championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
