<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREPSCHOOL-LIFE-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING CONCERN FOR THE DARK SIDE OF PREP SCHOOL LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Mass. _ Carved into the flesh of a 17-year-old
student's back, block letters spelled out an anti-gay slur, a
punitive label left by fellow students at Northfield Mount Hermon,
a grand old boarding school here.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a gay-bashing hate crime, though. The victim of the
carving last year was not gay. He simply liked the band ``Queen,''
and, prosecutors said, had irritated Matthew Rogers, 20, the
captain of the football team, by saying that he knew Rogers liked
the band, too.
</P>
<P>
   At Rogers' plea hearing this spring, prosecutors said the attack
had been part of a broader pattern of bullying in the dormitory
rooms of Northfield Mount Hermon. Renee Steese, a prosecutor, told
the court that the investigation had indicated that such assaultive
behavior had been going on throughout the school year. There was
some evidence, Steese said, that school officials were aware of it
to some degree.
</P>
<P>
   School officials deny that the carving assault was anything but
an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   That may be. But around the country, some national experts on
dormitory life report growing problems with the behavior of
residents, and widening efforts by boarding schools to improve
residential life by putting greater emphasis on it. Some schools
even talk about turning it into a ``third curriculum,'' added to
academics and extracurricular activities.
</P>
<P>
   It has never been simple to control buildings full of simmering
adolescence, but in recent years, some experts say, boarding
students, like their public school counterparts, have been
increasingly bringing the effects of troubled childhoods to school
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the challenges over the last 10 years have become
greater than ever,'' said Ed Kowalchick, who runs workshops on
residential life for the Association of Boarding Schools, a
national organization. ``Look at the statistics: Binge drinking is
up, suicide attempts are up, eating disorders among men as well as
women are up, depression and anxiety are up _ these are things that
kids come to us with, some real concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Although national organizations keep no statistics on assaults
and other violence in boarding schools, experts agree that the
troubling behavior of dorm residents sometimes escalates into
crime.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, four students at the Winchendon School in Massachusetts
kicked a fellow student so hard they were charged with attempted
murder. The charge was later reduced to assault and battery with a
deadly weapon and the students were sentenced to one year
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year a cadet at the Marine Military Academy in
Harlingen, Texas, sneaked into the room of a classmate and slashed
his throat, requiring 28 stitches. The student was given 10 years'
probation after serving four months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The academy, a private boarding school for boys, is also the
target of a pending lawsuit by parents of several former students
who said that classmates had physically and sexually abused their
sons and the school had failed to provide proper supervision. The
academy denies the charges.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, the Groton School in Groton, Mass., one of the
most prestigious boarding schools in the country, was rocked by a
boy's announcement at an assembly, before the whole school and
dozens of prospective students and their parents, that there had
been a series of homosexual molestations there. He was referring,
his lawyer said, to assaults, corroborated by several peers, in
which boys in grades 9 and 10 were held down by students and
molested.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two very dangerous issues,'' said Peter Hawkins, the
father of the boy who spoke out at Groton, and a financial planner
in Darien, Conn. ``One is, there are some very disturbed children
out there that your child is being put in contact with, but just as
scary is the school that you're dealing with when the leadership is
so corrupt they won't deal with the problem, where they refuse to
recognize the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Groton, Karen Schwartzman, rejected Hawkins'
accusations that the school had mishandled the allegations, noting
that two students had been disciplined in connection with the
assaults. ``The school undertook a very thorough internal
investigation and questioned every student on campus,'' Schwartzman
said. ``What resulted was a series of extremely conflicting
accounts and it was very hard to know, therefore, where truth began
and ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the assault at Northfield Mount Hermon, the school
had been instituting new programs to help students develop morally
and socially by interacting more with adults. These included
seminars on issues like gender relations and a program to have
students keep journals that would then be read and discussed with
consulting adults.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Groton instituted additional training programs for
students and faculty members on how to best handle hazing, sexual
harassment, bullying and taunting.
</P>
<P>
   But a major problem for boarding schools is structural, the
experts say. Students tend to have excellent supervision until late
afternoon, they say, and then, sometimes, a hint of a style of life
out of ``Lord of the Flies'' _ youth rules _ can creep in, as some
faculty members go home and others try to cope with exhaustion from
their roles as teachers, coaches and dormitory supervisors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Northfield Mount Hermon, one of the biggest boarding schools in
the country, with 1,158 students on separate campuses that used to
be schools for boys and girls, is also one of the most diverse. It
tends to attract students who want strong academics but also plenty
of freedom to find themselves, officials say. With a tuition of
$27,000, it offers many things a college would envy: 230 major
courses and 130 minor ones, a teacher-student ratio of 1 to 6, 65
sports teams, an art gallery, a radio station, and more.
</P>
<P>
   The school requires students to work a few hours a week and
seeks to instill an ethic of service in them, a tradition that
dates back to its 19th-century founder, D.L. Moody, a Christian
evangelist.
</P>
<P>
   When students arrive, the school gives them seven basic rules
they must not break, such as not abusing drugs or alcohol, not
stealing and not ``impinging on the rights of others.'' But in most
cases, it allows students who break the rules a second chance
before expelling them.
</P>
<P>
   At the plea hearing, it came out that two days before the
carving attack, Rogers had slashed two vertical lines down the
shoulder blade of another student.
</P>
<P>
   One parent, in an angry letter to school administrators that was
forwarded to The New York Times, complained: ``From what I have
heard from students at NMH, date rape, rape and sexual harassment
are not limited to the occasional isolated incident. Much of it
goes unreported out of fear.'' It is fear ``of isolation, physical
threats, being called a liar, a slut,'' the parent wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Raymond Jr., a local therapist who treated Northfield Mount
Hermon students for a dozen years, said they had told him about
other dorm bullies and sexual assaults and other problems as well,
for example easy access to drugs, both prescription drugs like
Ritalin, and illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Several students who were interviewed on condition of anonymity
confirmed the drug problem and described occasional hazing style
bullying in the boys' dorms.
</P>
<P>
   Of the illicit Ritalin supply, a student said: ``On any given
day, if you ask one of your friends, and they talk to someone else,
you've got it. You just have to have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond, who also taught some elective classes, had proposed
changing the school's counseling and discipline system to encourage
students to speak to adults. Months ago, Raymond applied for but
did not get a full-time job at the school and he is no longer
affiliated with it. He said he believed the school's increasingly
tough policies were driving the hidden and sometimes risky student
life further underground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults need to recognize that kids will talk honestly when we
stop making it detrimental to their well-being to do so,'' Raymond
said.
</P>
<P>
   School officials declined to respond directly to Raymond's
views. But Randy Stevens, the dean of student life, said that he
commonly fielded criticism from both those who thought he was too
strict and those who thought he was too lenient. The school offers
an ``elaborate web of support'' for students, from peer counselors
to adult advisers, Stevens said, and students have told him they
feel safe there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that for 85 percent of our kids here at this
school, they're very high-achieving kids,'' he said in an
interview. ``They make it through here very successfully and have a
wonderful experience. For 15 percent of our kids there are
challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said that as part of the new residential life
curriculum, students had four monthly seminars or talks on such
issues as gender relations, hazing, harassment and racial identity.
The school has also been consulting with researchers on how to
handle adolescent boys' cruelty, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other schools are taking similar route.
</P>
<P>
   At the Thatcher School in Ojai, Calif., the focus on residential
life ranges from the headmaster's schoolwide Saturday night
invitation to a movie or cookie-baking at his house, to newer
required courses on human development and sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The Rumsey Hall School in Washington Depot, Conn., has begun
trying to address girls' specific problems, giving them programs on
leadership training and the skills needed to live in a residential
community.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Hotchkiss, assistant head of Saint Mary's School in
Raleigh, N.C., and a faculty member of the Association of Boarding
Schools, said: ``A lot of different schools I've consulted with, 10
years ago they couldn't have cared less what was going on in the
dorms, just, `Keep them quiet, have them study and don't let them
crawl around outside.' Now they're coming to people like me and
saying, `Help us develop a residential curriculum,' the words for
which didn't exist 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, few would argue that crime among the estimated 2
percent of the nation's students who live in boarding schools is
worse than at day schools. But the students' 24-hour-a-day presence
at schools leaves them vulnerable to assaults at times when most
day students would be safe at home.
</P>
<P>
   At the plea hearing the Northfield Mount Hermon carving assault,
the victim's father told the court that his son's back, though
healing, was still scarred, and the boy refuses to take off his
shirt or swim in public. Prosecutors say the letters were about
three or four inches tall, that they bled but did not require
stitches, and that the boys who carved them also swabbed hydrogen
peroxide on the cuts afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who wielded the knife, pleaded guilty to two charges of
assault and battery and was given a suspended sentence of two and a
half years and placed on probation for three years. He had
previously been accepted on full scholarship into the U.S. Naval
Academy, but that offer was rescinded after the carving assault.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' accomplice, Jonathan Shapiro, 19, pleaded guilty to
assault and battery and was sentenced to three years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he had done the carving, Rogers told the Superior
Court judge: ``There was no point. It was a terrible error on my
part.''
</P>
<P>
   But the victim's father said: ``We all make choices about our
conduct. The choice that Matt made, and Jonathan, was to exhibit
power over people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
