<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MONTGOMERY-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH OSCAR A. CASTRO OF MONTGOMERY GLOBAL COMMUNICATIONS
FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT24, is beging sent to NYT photo clients and a
graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, June 18)  
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You need to learn the game well to play it well,'' said Oscar
A. Castro, manager of the $590 million Montgomery Global
Communications fund, over breakfast at the Mark Hotel in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In the ever-changing global telecommunications markets, learning
the game well means gaining a thorough understanding of industry
dynamics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Montgomery Asset Management in San Francisco, where Castro
has worked since 1993, that is the task for the Global Research
Platform, an 18-member team of analysts and managers that Castro
oversees. The unit is the source of investment ideas for Global
Communications and two smaller funds that Castro helps run.
</P>
<P>
   Global Communications has returned 47.2 percent a year, on
average, for the three years through June 9, versus 43.3 percent
for its peers, according to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, 45, attributes his fund's performance, at least in part,
to its research process. While many analysts and money managers
focus on information gleaned from corporate management, the
Montgomery analysts pay special attention to company rivals,
suppliers and industry regulators.
</P>
<P>
   After a visit with telecommunications regulators in Italy two
years ago, for instance, Castro and Montgomery analysts concluded
that the details of the country's impending deregulation plan would
favor the large incumbent operators. So Castro added to his
holdings of Telecom Italia, which has risen.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Castro and his team favor stocks with lower
multiples than their peer group, based on their prices compared
with both past and expected future earnings or cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   But he is willing to pay more for a company that is growing
faster than its peers. So he looks at the company's peg ratio _
defined as its price-to-earnings ratio, in turn divided by its
long-term earnings growth rate. The lower the peg, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Using Montgomery analysts' forecasts, Castro wants a stock to
have an expected return of 25 percent in the first year he owns it,
50 percent in two years and 100 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures are more esoteric. For example, he looks at a
company' enterprise value _ the market value of its equity and
debt, less its cash _ in relation to future cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   Geography plays only a minor role selecting the portfolio's 90
or so stocks. At the end of April, 42.1 percent of its assets were
in Europe, 34.9 percent in the United States, 14.9 percent in Asia
and the small remainder elsewhere or in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, with an annual turnover rate of 146 percent, uses a
fairly strict discipline for selling stocks. Castro is likely to
unload a stock that breaches its upside price target, or if he
foresees deteriorating sales. He will also drop a stock if he
believes management has steered him wrong, or sometimes if
executives take too long to return his phone calls _ a sign of
possible trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The spring sell-off has provided some opportunities, and Castro
has been buying of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a chance to get into stocks we've always wanted to
own but that were too expensive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Castro is bullish on the Atmel Corp., a San Jose, Calif., maker
of high-performance memory chips. He said the company was
benefiting from strong demand for its flash memory chips, used in
personal digital assistants and other wireless devices, and that it
was gradually becoming a global player.
</P>
<P>
   The fund started buying Atmel shares in May 1999 when they were
trading for less than $10. They are now at $42.9375, down 27.8
percent from their peak on March 22 and 28.1 times his 2001
earnings estimate of $1.53 a share. His 12-month price target is
$70, and he calculated the company's peg ratio at 0.37 recently,
versus 0.75 for peer companies like LSI Logic.
</P>
<P>
   One recent purchase was Bookham Technology of Oxfordshire,
England, which makes components that generate and control light
signals in fiber-optic networks. He bought shares at 10 pounds at
the initial offering on April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Castro recently raised his 12-month price target on Bookham to
65 pounds, from 50 pounds, because of stronger-than-anticipated
revenue growth. At his new target, the company would trade at a 50
percent premium to the shares of peer companies like JDS Uniphase,
based on its price-to-sales multiple. But Bookham has ``much higher
growth prospects at this stage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed on Friday at 35 pounds. He expects Bookham to
turn a profit of 4 pence a share in 2001 versus a loss this year.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus in Australia. The company
provides a wide range of telecommunications services, including
long-distance and mobile telephone, pay television and Internet
connections. ``They've assembled a huge broadband network that can
soon deliver all of these services,'' Castro said. He expects
earnings to nearly double, to 16 Australian cents a share for the
year ending in March 2001, from 8.3 cents in the most recent fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   He bought the shares at an average price of 4.46 Australian
dollars, starting in April 1999; they now trade at 4.26 dollars. He
calculates that the company's enterprise value as a multiple of
2001 cash flow is 18, and has a 12-month price target on the stock
of 8.60 dollars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
