<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6501 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ROOTS-BUSINESS-$ADV18     06-16 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOTS-BUSINESS-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNLOADING SOME LIFE BACK INTO DOWNTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT22 and 23 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, June 18) 
 By JOEL KOTKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANNING, Iowa _ Joan Phillips had seen it before. A small town
that once prospered on the rolling Iowa countryside, unable to
adjust to a changing economy, loses population and most of its
businesses. It gradually experiences a kind of living death, marked
by peeling paint and an aging population.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Phillips, a 65-year-old retired insurance agent, and a group
of her neighbors were determined not to let that happen here in
Manning, a town of 1,400 about 100 miles west of Des Moines. In the
last five years, Phillips and her neighbors, through membership on
town boards and by promoting referenda, have pushed Manning to tap
money from the city's publicly owned utilities and through bonds
and low-interest loans from the state and federal government. The
city has used the proceeds to give its Main Street an $850,000
facelift, is in the midst of a $4.5 million expansion of the local
hospital and the adjoining nursing home and has poured an
additional $880,000 into its local schools, in part to upgrade
computers and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important action, Phillips said, was the 1996
decision by 86 percent of the city's voters to issue $3.5 million
in bonds to set up a locally owned local telephone service to
compete with the long-time operator, the GTE Corp. The new service,
the Manning Municipal Communication and Television Systems Utility,
now provides residents with cable television, high-speed Internet
connections and, starting later this summer, improved telephone
services, including voice mail, three-way calling, speed dialing
and call forwarding, that have not been available.
</P>
<P>
   These telecommunications services, Phillips said, would have
arrived only slowly, if at all, from GTE. ``Their attitude was to
let the small town go and die,'' suggested Phillips, who has served
for 12 years as coordinator for the Manning Area Development Corp.,
a local nonprofit group that works closely with state and federal
agencies. ``It doesn't fit into their business plan. For them it's
a business issue. For us it's about a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   A GTE spokesman, Don Neely, denied that his company served rural
communities like Manning poorly. But he said that the company had
been trying to unload many of its rural lines, including those in
Iowa, to invest in wireless services and other new ventures.
</P>
<P>
   GTE's impending sale of its largely rural lines across the state
to the smaller Iowa Telecom _ expected to be completed later this
summer _ has exacerbated the sense of urgency among communities in
the state about positioning themselves to meet the challenges of
the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, like other states, has been promoting the Internet as a
rural development tool. The state has some strong advantages,
notably its educated population, generally excellent public schools
and the absence of crime and other more urban ills. Yet hopes that
the Internet can help revive the state's rural communities have not
widely materialized.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, said Peter Korsching, a sociologist at Iowa
State University, the winners in Iowa's emerging new economy have
not been small towns, but rather larger urban centers like Cedar
Rapids and Des Moines, which serve as major switching centers for
telecommunications and boast the best airport and highway
connections. The state's two major college towns, Ames and Iowa
City, also have done well, drawing on local graduates and
well-educated residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The population is coming back in growth centers, while rural
Iowa is shrinking,'' noted Korsching, who is co-author, with Eric
A. Abbott and Patricia Hipple, of the forthcoming ``Having All the
Right Connections: Telecommunications and Rural Economic
Viability,'' to be published by Praeger next month. ``We have
islands of prosperity where Internet-related jobs are clustering.''
</P>
<P>
   Another, somewhat less prototypical standout has been Fairfield,
a city of 15,000 that is home to Maharishi University. Fairfield
boasts among the highest number of Internet domain names per capita
of any community in the nation, one indications of the density of
Web activity. Locals trace the area's successful telecommunications
business to the presence of thousands of adherents of
transcendental meditation, among them many well-educated migrants
from major cities, who have been instrumental in starting Internet
and other high-tech related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Korsching said that for many rural communities, the rise of the
Internet and the digital economy resembles something closer to
``information Armageddon'' than salvation. These areas, he said,
have remained dependent on agriculture at a time when the economics
of farming have changed drastically. The rise of ever larger
corporate farms, he noted, combined with the ability to buy on the
Internet, has reduced the role of smaller towns as vital trading
areas.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, roughly 78 percent of Iowa's counties _ like
Carroll, the home of Manning _ have lost population since 1900,
according to Bruce Babcock, an Iowa State University economist.
This is largely the result of the 1930s Dust Bowl and more recently
the industrialization and consolidation of agriculture. Some small
towns, like Grand Junction in Greene County just to the east, have
Main Streets that are largely abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The decay can be seen as what a state economist, Harvey
Seigelman, has called the ``Dakotaization'' of small-town Iowa. In
the end, Seigelman and other observers agree, there will be a
painful reshuffling of Iowa's rural geography, with a handful of
communities prospering while a large number of small towns
virtually disappear.
</P>
<P>
   That is the prospect that haunts Manning's leading citizens and
businesspeople. Although the town looks prosperous enough, per
capita income remains as much as $5,000 below that of more
urbanized areas of the state. The town's population has also
fallen, having peaked at 2,200 in 1920. It also has been aging
rapidly, with its school-age population dropping from 800 to 550
since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in danger of becoming a totally middle-aged community,''
said Howard Roe, senior vice president of the First National Bank
of Manning and one of the leaders of the revitalization efforts.
``We have to create opportunities for younger people here. ''
</P>
<P>
   Manning's investment in infrastructure, particularly
telecommunications, may yet be able to stem the decline, said Rick
Haunsacker, executive director of Region XII Council of
Governments, a development agency for six counties, including
Greene and Carroll. ``A lot of it has to do with the culture, ``
Haunsacker said. ``In Manning, people are willing to open their
pockets and use public funds to save their communities. In other
places, they don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   That spirit clearly drives people like Joan Phillips, who says
Manning has many advantages _ a low cost of living, good schools
and a disciplined, literate and motivated work force _ attractive
to information-age industries. The city's expanding
telecommunications net, she said, has persuaded Enterprise Corp.
International, a Des Moines-based company that offers technical
support and software for Sony and other electronics manufacturers,
to double its current staff of 28 in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offers a real chance for us,'' said Brenda Steck, the
company's local manager, who graduated from Manning High School in
1983. ``Of the people I graduated from high school with, only 10 or
so stayed. I'm hoping this kind of industry will bring people back
_ and keep people here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
