<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday approved, 380-49, a measure to investigate
the Department of Education for fraud. The measure authorizes the
General Accounting Office to conduct the audit following recent
thefts at the agency. Supporters said the measure could prevent
future theft of millions. Opponents said the investigation was not
necessary. A ``yes'' vote supports the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: SIGNATURES
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 426-4, a bill that gives
electronic contracts the same status as those signed on paper,
legalizing transactions made with an electronic signature.
Supporters said it would reduce paperwork for businesses and
consumers. Opponents said it did not go far enough to protect
privacy online. A ``yes'' vote supports the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 217-214, a bill to increase
spending for health and education. The bill would appropriate
$339.5 billion to the Departments of Labor, Health and Human
Services and Education. Supporters said it would boost spending for
needed federal programs. Opponents said the funding was not
sufficient for education, childcare and worker training.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: MONUMENTS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 243-177, an amendment to the
Interior Department spending bill that limits funding for new
national monuments. The amendment would have prohibited the agency
from planning or managing national monuments designated by the
President this year. Supporters said it would stem government
attempts to acquire more land. Opponents said it would infringe on
presidential authority. A ``yes'' vote rejects the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
