<HEADER>
A6511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-16 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGING GORE'S TAX PROPOSAL; POLL GIVES BUSH EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   CHALLENGING GORE'S TAX PROPOSAL
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas Friday accused his Democratic
rival, Vice President Al Gore, of doubling the size of a proposed
tax cut as a result of polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely America doesn't want a focus-group-driven presidency,''
Bush said. ``America wants somebody who makes decisions based on
what's right, and what's right is sharing some of the surplus with
the people who pay the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush called his proposal for a 10-year, across-the-board tax cut
of $1.3 trillion preferable to Gore's latest plan for $500 billion
in tax credits and deductions aimed at particular needs like
education and child care. ``Everybody who pays taxes ought to get
tax relief,'' Bush said in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hattaway, Gore's spokesman, said, countered that Bush
``obviously thought the tax cut would be politically popular when
he made it the centerpiece of his campaign.'' Hattaway added, ``We
need to use our prosperity wisely and give tax relief to working
middle-class families.''
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   AN EDGE TO BUSH
</P>
<P>
   A day after Gore replaced his campaign manager, he awoke to yet
another sign of the struggle he faces. A nationwide poll by The Los
Angeles Times found Bush leading Gore by a 10-point margin, 50
percent to 40 percent, and it found that Bush's support among
Republicans was stronger than Gore's support among Democrats. Nine
of 10 Republicans said they backed Bush, while seven of 10
Democrats said they supported Gore. Bush also had substantially
more support among Democrats than Gore had among Republicans. The
poll surveyed more than 1,600 voters in the past week and has a
margin of error of plus or minus three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   A STAND-IN WITH A PUNCH
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife, Laura, often say that when she agreed to
marry him, it was on the condition that she would never have to
give a political speech. But Friday, Bush addressed more than
10,000 people at the Texas Republican Party's convention in
Houston. She was substituting for her husband, who was campaigning
in swing states, and she was mixing just a little vinegar into her
remarks. She said that at the beginning of her husband's quest for
the presidency, she had vowed to avoid newspapers and the
inevitably critical articles. But then, she said, ``I learned that
some of the best fiction is published on editorial pages.''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ Kissimmee and Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ No events
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
