<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-FARMER0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    `Choice is not first-rate '
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELVIDERE, Ill. _ Bob Newport of Belvidere, Ill., is a
Republican in a Republican county, but that doesn't mean the
Republican can chalk up his presidential vote.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates must earn that vote, and so far, Newport remains
unimpressed by his choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess probably the only conclusion I've drawn is that it is
the lesser of two evils again,'' Newport said recently after a day
helping his son work the son's farm on the city outskirts in
northern Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the problem. I don't know which one I want yet. The
choice is not first-rate as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   A farmer all his life, Newport, 76, has watched as the
agriculture economy lagged even as the national economy surged. In
Illinois, while agriculture is still king, pressure from
development and low prices have led some farmers to wonder if
politicians realize where the food chain really starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are beginning to realize that agriculture has not
shared in the bonanza, so called, that seems to be expanding the
economy,'' Newport said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Mary, raised two children by farming. Their
son, Mark, worked in agribusiness before taking over the farm when
Newport retired. A daughter, Claudia Newport, lives in the Miami
Valley, in Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   Both the campaigns of Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush touted their candidates' support for free trade with
China, in part to help export farm produce.
</P>
<P>
   Newport doesn't give either man much credit for supporting what
he sees as a sensible decision to trade with the world's most
populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Newport is waiting for some message from either Gore
or Bush that they are worth his vote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
