u p BC-HEARTLAND-SWING0618-C     06-16 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-SWING0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    `Al Gore is OK. He's the best of the two'
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACOMB COUNTY, Michigan _ Demonica Sykes, 22, a student at
Macomb County Community College in suburban Detroit, takes voting
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been voting since I was 18,'' said Sykes, who hopes to be
a pediatric surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   The first time she cast a vote in a presidential election, she
picked Democrat Bill Clinton, ``because he was pro-choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He (also) believed everyone should have an opportunity to
afford college,'' Sykes said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's contest between Democrat Al Gore, the vice
president, and Republican George W. Bush, the Texas governor,
hasn't excited her very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is OK. He's the best of the two,'' Sykes said.
</P>
<P>
   He, however, has not exactly overwhelmed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not very personable,'' Sykes said. ``He doesn't really
talk to people. He talks at them. He's too iffy.'' The lack of
enthusiasm among some voters like Sykes is presenting a challenge
for Gore in the early days of the campaign. By fall, he must
solidify and energize these people, who are part of his natural
political base. Their lukewarm support gives Bush hope he might
snag some of these voters _ or that they'll sit out the election.
</P>
<P>
   While Sykes leans toward Gore, she also voted in Michigan's
Republican primary last Feb. 22. She cast her ballot for Arizona
Sen. John McCain. The primary was open to all voters and McCain won
with strong support from Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes voted for McCain even though she disagreed with him on key
issues such as abortion, which McCain opposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (McCain) was up front. He spoke to you,'' she said.
``McCain is a people person. . . . It's like talking to your
neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
