A6534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-HEARTLAND-UNDECIDED06     06-16 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-UNDECIDED0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    `I can be swayed to vote for either guy'
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Jim Hamulock walks by an abandoned green Chevy
Impala with broken windows, steps over four bags of rotting garbage
and drops the letters into the house through a rusted mail slot.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Cleveland the nation doesn't see.
</P>
<P>
   Hamulock, 53, has been a mail carrier in these south side
Italian and Latino neighborhoods for 32 years. He grimaces at the
thought of what these streets and homes used to be and what they
are now.
</P>
<P>
   In the background, only a few miles away, is the Cleveland the
nation does see. The new ballpark. The renovated lake front. The
Flats.
</P>
<P>
   Hamulock, who is married and has three grown children, is one of
the thousands of undecided voters that Texas Gov. George W. Bush
and Vice President Al Gore are desperate to win over by November.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong Democrat, Hamulock said the people in these
neighborhoods haven't found the booming economy that Gore is taking
credit for and promises to keep going. The letter carrier, who has
never voted for a Republican presidential candidate, isn't sure who
he'll vote for this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone sees the new stadiums and says how beautiful
Cleveland is now. Well, those two guys ought to walk with me on my
route one day and see the real Cleveland, the people they need to
be helping,'' Hamulock said. ``There used to be so much pride in
this community. I don't know if either Bush or Gore would do much
to help people in neighborhoods like this help themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the issues, Hamulock presents a mixed bag. He likes
Gore's plan for improving health care and thinks the vice president
will protect average workers like him. But he likes Bush's tax cut
ideas that might put a few bucks back into his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll admit it, I can be swayed to vote for either guy,'' he
said. ``I just don't want to keep hearing from Gore or Bush about
how everybody is doing so well in this economy. Because not
everybody is.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
