</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-STEELWORKER0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E`I'm split, split right down the middle'
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVERTOWN, Pa. _ Nelson Azeff is a gleeful ticket-splitter.
</P>
<P>
   In November, he will vote for his conservative Republican
congressman, as he always does, and closely consider the roster of
candidates the GOP _ his party _ has nominated for state and local
offices.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that will mean a thing when Azeff, a Republican
voter in the thoroughly Republican suburbs of Philadelphia, looks
at the presidential race. He twice voted for President Clinton and
at the moment is favoring Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm split, split right down the middle,'' he said,
before adding, ``If I'm leaning at all, it's toward Gore. I haven't
heard of anything great coming out of Texas, except that it has the
most executions of any state in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Azeff's penchant for following his nose to either side of the
political spectrum is common in Pennsylvania, where the governor's
office seems to switch between a Democrat and a Republican every
eight years with a pendulum's precision.
</P>
<P>
   Azeff, 61, of Havertown, Pa., is a retired marketing executive
who specialized in companies that develop environmental testing
equipment _ including several years with a Yellow Springs firm that
had him traveling to Ohio for weeks at a time. His wife is a school
teacher near retirement herself, which has them talking about
getting a part-time place in Florida, where both their children
live.
</P>
<P>
   A back disability forced Azeff into early retirement five years
ago, and left him slightly hobbled and loaded with free time. He
uses it to study politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got those campaign fliers in the mail, I actually read
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Azeff, it's all about issues. He said he believes in
affordable health care for everyone, an end to American military
involvement ``in all these little places all over the world,''
limited immigration and a Social Security program left entirely in
the hands of the federal government. No individual control of
investing that money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things that our government has to be involved
in, right up to the neck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, he's conflicted over who would handle the whole
job best. He said he thinks Texas Gov. George W. Bush would do a
better job on the foreign policy issues (``. . . because of his dad
. . .''), but he thinks Gore may be better prepared for domestic
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the things I'm talking about aren't Republican or
Democrat things, they're just good for the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
