<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ACCUSES ITS RIVALS OF GARBAGE-CAN TACTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. accused its rivals Friday of
masterminding an attempt to buy the trash generated by a
Microsoft-backed lobbying organization, apparently hoping it would
yield valuable information about the company.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation came as the Justice Department filed another
brief in the antitrust case against the company. It sought to
counter a Microsoft brief filed Thursday opposing the government's
effort to send the company's appeal in the case directly to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The trash-buying effort was first reported by Wired.com on
Thursday evening and The Wall Street Journal Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this month, on June 1 and June 6, a woman identifying
herself as Blanca Lopez offered to pay a worker from a cleaning
service to hand over the trash from the offices of the Association
for Competitive Technology in downtown Washington, according to
documents from the company that manages the association's office
space.
</P>
<P>
   The workers refused both times _ even when, on the second
attempt, they were offered $500 each, plus another $200 for their
supervisor. The second attempt came the day before U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson issued his order to break up
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The association, chartered in 1998, is heavily financed by
Microsoft and has been a an unwavering supporter of the company in
its antitrust battle with the government, as well as other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that our competitors have pursued an
orchestrated and aggressive campaign against us,'' said Vivek
Varma, a Microsoft spokesman, ``and this suggests that they are
willing to go to extraordinary and unseemly lengths to attack our
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Zuck, head of the association, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But Zuck and Varma both acknowledged that they had not been able
to determine which competitor, if any, was behind the trash-buying
effort _ though they did say they considered it reasonable to
surmise that a Microsoft rival was involved. The Washington police
are investigating the episode but have not said what they may have
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Zuck said a private investigative company, Investigative Group
International, appeared to have been involved, though he and others
said they did not know who might have hired the company.
Investigative Group International said it would not discuss its
clients or activities.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, according to the documents, gained after-hours entrance
to the office building and the office suite where the Association
for Competitive Technology has its offices using the pass key of an
entity called Upstream Technologies, which had rented an office
nearby last month. But Upstream appears to be a dummy company;
association officers say they believe the private investigators
rented the space under the name of Upstream just to be near the
association's offices.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, someone broke into Microsoft's offices near Dupont
Circle, two miles away, earlier this week, the company said.
Nothing has been found to be missing, and the offices of two other
unrelated companies in the same building were broken into the same
night. So Microsoft officials say they have drawn no conclusions
about that break in.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest move on the legal front, the government responded
to an assertion by Microsoft that the Expediting Act, allowing
direct appeal to the Supreme Court of important federal antitrust
cases, does not apply to the companion case against Microsoft filed
by 19 states.
</P>
<P>
   The government brief Friday noted that even if the Microsoft
argument was correct, the states would file a motion allowing
defendants or plaintiffs to petition the Supreme Court for direct
appeal of any case before the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court seldom agrees to such requests. But Tom
Goldstein, a Washington lawyer who argues cases before the Supreme
Court, said, ``This is the sort of circumstance when it is
permitted, when there's a sister case already up there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
