u s BC-BBO-KNOBLAUCH-PSYCHOL     06-16 0235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KNOBLAUCH-PSYCHOLOGY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: this play. '''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Sax, who in 1983 as a second baseman for the Dodgers had
difficulties almost identical to Knoblauch's, said he does not
remember being under particular stress at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But he remembers, he said, what it felt like, and can guess at
what Knoblauch is feeling now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the toughest thing I've ever gone through,'' said Sax,
now an analyst for Fox Sports Net's Baseball Today. ``It's
completely unexplainable. It's so awful, and everybody in the world
is watching you.''
</P>
<P>
   When his problem was at its peak, he said, he stood on the field
and prayed ``Please, please don't hit it to me, please don't hit
the ball to me!''
</P>
<P>
   Then, when a small white sphere was hurtling in his direction,
he felt sorry for himself. Then he got mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got really ticked and I beat this thing,'' Saks said. ``I
didn't turn my back on it. I bit it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he is glad he went through the ordeal. ``It made
me a better person. It put things in perspective and it made me a
better player.''
</P>
<P>
   The following years, he added, were the best in his career,
years when his second-base prayers changed to ``Please hit the ball
to me because when you do, this game is over.''
</P>
<P>
   All Knoblauch has to do, Sax said, ``is to get his confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could just turn our brains off, we'd be fine,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
