<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, JUNE 17
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-UKRAINE-ECON-NYT (moved on Monday, June 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service Article sent on Monday, June 5,
about Ukraine's announcement that it will close the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant by Dec. 15 referred incorrectly to the number
of deaths and illnesses caused by the accident there in 1986. The
Nuclear Energy Agency of the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development said in a report that 31 people died in the first
weeks after the accident. Other estimates of deaths ultimately
caused by the accident range from dozens to tens of thousands;
estimates of illnesses range from hundreds to tens of thousands. It
has not been established that the accident caused untold thousands
of deaths and illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CONGO-U.N.-NYT (moved on Thursday, June 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, June 15,
about talks at the United Nations on the war in Congo misspelled
the name of Secretary General Kofi Annan's special representative
to Congo. He is Kamel Morjane, not Kamal Moranje. The article also
misstated Congo's size ranking in Africa. It is not the largest
country; Sudan is.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TEXAS-EXECUTIONS-NYT (moved on Saturday, May 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, May 13
about executions in Texas during the tenure of Gov. George W. Bush
misstated the year in which a federal judge in Austin ruled that
the Texas pardons and paroles board barely met minimal procedural
safeguards required by the United States Constitution. It was 1998,
not 1988.
</P>
<P>
   BC-EXECUTIONS-CASES-NYT (moved on Saturday, May 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times New Service article sent on Saturday, May 13,
about five Texas criminal cases that resulted in executions,
referred incorrectly to the trial lawyer for James Lee Beathard,
who was executed in 1999. The lawyer was retained, not appointed.
The article included an erroneous tally from the parole board for
its vote in the case of Troy Farris, who was also executed in 1999.
Five members, not seven, voted for clemency
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
