<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6609 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-PROCTER-ADVICE-$ADV18     06-16 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROCTER-ADVICE-$ADV18-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE ADVICE FOR PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Iowa, Ill., Mich.)  (For release Sunday, June 18) 
(Editors: Also See INVEST-Q&AMP;A) 
 By KATE BERRY and ELLEN ALMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How did Procter &AMP; Gamble, arguably the world's pre-eminent
marketer of consumer products, fall so far? The company stunned
investors on June 8 by announcing that it would miss earnings
projections for the third straight quarter and that Durk I. Jager,
its chief executive, would step down after just 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Jager himself was supposed to get the company going
again, his departure has raised doubts about whether it can squeeze
more growth from mature brands like Tide, Pringles and Crest, and
whether it can develop new brands that are nearly as promising.
</P>
<P>
   To provide answers, the company named Alan G. Lafley, the head
of North American operations, as its new president and chief
executive, and called John Pepper, a P&AMP;G former chairman and chief
executive who came back from retirement, to lead the board again.
Pepper admitted that, under Jager, the company took on ``too much
change, too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts including scholars, consultants, managers of other
corporations and former P&AMP;G executives have their own perspectives
on what went wrong and what the company should do to set things
right. Here are some of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Malamatinas, chief executive, Burger King Corp., a unit
of Diageo PLC and former marketing and brand manager, P&AMP;G. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G needs to focus on some core brands. They need to put
ruthless focus on brands that create value down the road _ about 20
brands out of 400.
</P>
<P>
   They need to accelerate the introduction of new products and
support them. It's a fine balance between becoming a nimble,
flexible, agile, less bureaucratic organization, while at the same
time preserving great ingredients of the culture.
</P>
<P>
   The company has some great attributes. But they tried to take
out costs too quickly and they tried to shift the culture. The art
of the CEO is to preserve the culture while focusing on growth.
</P>
<P>
   They need to grow their top 10 brands in the top 6 markets. At
Burger King, I operate in 67 markets, but I know there are 6
markets that will deliver 80 percent of shareholder value and we
have to be ruthless in terms of allocating resources.
</P>
<P>
   Durk Jager tried to change the culture so quickly that he didn't
get the best out of the people. He tried to change the company
overnight. Most of the people have been there forever.
</P>
<P>
   When I talk to my people, I always talk about culture. If I was
the CEO, I would bring in some fresh blood from outside. They
always grew from within. I would bring in two or three top people.
</P>
<P>
   They are going to come back. They need the right leader and they
need to move quickly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karen Francis, chief marketing officer, Internet Capital Group;
former manger, Oldsmobile division, General Motors; former manager,
Crest brand, P&AMP;G &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was there from 1984 to 1987, and it really was the boot camp
of marketing training. Their marketing approach was focused on
really understanding a customer, honing in on them, and that was a
very smart and proven strategy for building brands.
</P>
<P>
   But the business economy, and the number of choices people have
today, are accelerating in ways we haven't seen before. So they
should be taking a little bit more risk, and getting involved in
trying more offerings.
</P>
<P>
   An excellent example is their new product Febreze [a spray for
removing odors from household fabrics). It was a risk. A company
the size of P&AMP;G, with their marketing penetration, should be able
to generate more of those products. Everyone is looking for what's
new. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sanmjay Dhar, professor of marketing, University of Chicago
Graduate School of Business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G is a company that needs a little bit of rethinking of its
vision. If you go back a few years, P&AMP;G essentially started getting
rid of people in-house who were doing analytic work. And that
doesn't make sense to me, because the marketing environment today
is very data intensive. This happened at the same time that other
consumer products companies, like Kraft, were adding more marketing
people and doing this very successfully.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G is good at innovation, and spinning new products. They are
not good at cost-cutting. A few years ago, they tried to reduce
coupons. Now, I have a baby and I end up buying Huggies all the
time because they have coupons available and P&AMP;G cut that out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Cook, chairman and founder, Intuit, maker of software
including Quicken and Turbo Tax. Former Crisco brand manager, P&AMP;G &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I left, I applied the P&AMP;G method to an industry that sorely
needed it. Now we have the two best-selling software titles in
retail history. We put it through consumer tests, asked them what
they wanted. This software is written for consumers, not technical
people.
</P>
<P>
   The key at P&AMP;G was research and development. The products were
the best. You would do blind taste tests and give the customer
Brand X and ours, and they'd always pick ours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bernd Schmitt, professor of business, Columbia University;
author of ``Experiential Marketing'' (The Free Press, 1999). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the problems are not confined to just P&AMP;G Unilever,
Nestle _ it's almost an industry disease. It's not just about the
individual products, it's about the companies behind them. It's
similar to the situation that faced IBM in the late 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Markets are conversations, not transaction tools. You have to
talk to customers in a human voice. You can't just project your
image on a screen; nowadays customers want different approaches.
</P>
<P>
   When you look at the products in the supermarkets that are on
the cutting edge, like fruit juices and those directed at New Age
lifestyles _ this entire culture is missing at P&AMP;G There's very
little product innovation.
</P>
<P>
   I would suggest that they start experimenting with new product
categories and new approaches. Their focus has to be looking at
young consumers and how they live.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Faith Popcorn, consultant and author on marketing and consumer
trends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble has such great strengths, and you'd never know
it. Usually you have companies that can't shut up about themselves
and exaggerate what they do, but here you have a company that is so
inhibited.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, this company cut the cord to the washboard by
creating all these products _ Ivory soap, which was invented in the
1920s; Tide, which came out in 1938 _ and they don't really talk
about it. They're such a product-oriented company that they think
the products speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They need to really leverage women. Women don't buy brands, they
join them. Without being aware of it, women have joined P&AMP;G If they
knew more about the company, the club could get bigger. It could be
the biggest female club in the world.
</P>
<P>
   If P&AMP;G did that successfully, the stock price would go up. Women
bond to a brand, and one generation of female consumers can lead
you to the next _ we call that ``brand-me-downs.'' And women would
put all their money into P&AMP;G if they understood what an incredibly
female-supportive company this is.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Thane Pressman, chief executive, Tone Brothers Inc., food
distributor based in Des Moines; former associate advertising
manager, P&AMP;G &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Procter and Gamble is historically very successful at what it
does, and it was always a process-driven organization. It was
hierarchical and highly centralized. My sense is it is trying to
change, and they must to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   The things Jager was trying to do must be done. They've
absolutely got to be faster, more responsive, and accept the
reality of product life cycles. They just keep reinventing
products, like new, improved Tide. And that worked for a while. But
they will have a very challenging future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keven L. Keller, E.B.Osborn Professor of Marketing at Dartmouth
College and author of ``Strategic Brand Management,'' (Prentiss
Hall, 1998). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest issue I think with their culture now is they're
dealing with a market that has changed so much in the last few
years that they need to have more people now that are tuned in to
that market.
</P>
<P>
   I think the savvy marketers are at high-tech firms. If anything,
there needs to be some reverse flow. There are a number of good
marketers, but there are a lot fewer great marketers. I think that
is an issue when you lose those kinds of people. They're just not
getting that young talent now.(BOX) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
