<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      06-16 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SENATE UNANIMOUSLY PASSES ELECTRONIC SIGNATURE BILL
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted unanimously to approve a bill that catapults
electronic commerce to a new level by allowing consumers and
businesses to sign contracts online and know that their
e-signatures are just as binding as those in ink. The bill has been
passed by the House and now goes to President Clinton, who said
that he would sign it into law.
</P>
<P>
   By giving electronic signatures the legal weight of paper
signatures, the law would offer consumers the chance to sign
legally enforceable contracts for health insurance, bank loans and
brokerage accounts over the Internet. But certain legal documents
will still have to be produced on paper. For example, insurance and
utility companies must send cancellation and termination notices
through the mail, wills cannot be executed over the Internet and
products may not be recalled online.
</P>
<P>
   BANK STOCKS SEND DOW DOWN 2.5 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks fell, led by financial issues, as two banks
warned that higher interest rates would reduce profits. The Dow
Jones industrial average fell 265.52 points, or 2.5 percent, to
10,449.30. The Nasdaq composite index gained 14.82 points, to
3,860.54, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index lost 14.27
points, or nearly 1 percent, to 1,464.46.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER PROFIT WARNING FROM XEROX
</P>
<P>
   Facing strong competition in its highest-margin product lines,
problems collecting accounts in Mexico and upheaval in its sales
force, Xerox warned that its second-quarter earnings would be as
much as 12 cents below expectations of 42 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT CONFRONTS RIVALS' TACTICS
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft accused its rivals of masterminding an attempt to buy
the trash generated by a Microsoft-backed lobbying organization,
apparently hoping it would yield valuable information about the
company. The accusation came as the Justice Department filed still
another brief in the antitrust case against the company. It
countered a Microsoft brief filed Thursday that was aimed at
undermining the government's effort to send the company's appeal in
the case directly to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   NET INCOME CLIMBS 15 PERCENT AT LEHMAN
</P>
<P>
   Despite a sharp slowdown in domestic stock and bond markets,
Lehman Brothers Holdings reported that its profits rose 15 percent,
to $378 million, or $2.78 a diluted share, up from $330 million, or
$2.09 a share.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA UNICOM RAISES $4.9 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on the recent popularity of telecommunications
stocks and the enduring appeal of the world's most populous
country, China Unicom, China's second-largest telephone carrier,
raised $4.92 billion in the largest initial public offering in Asia
outside Japan.
</P>
<P>
   TWA AND AIRTRAN HOLDING TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Trans World Airlines and AirTran Holdings rose on
reports that they were holding merger discussions. But people close
to the talks said that there was little chance of a deal. Shares of
TWA rose 31.25 cents, to $2.875, while AirTran shares jumped 25
cents, to $4.5625. TWA would not confirm that it was in
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   CDC ASSET IN $700 MILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The investment management company Nvest agreed to be acquired by
CDC Asset Management for $40 a share, or $700 million. CDC will
also assume $1.5 billion of debt. CDC is the investment management
arm of Caisse des Depots of France.
</P>
<P>
   DRESDNER RENEWS EFFORTS TO MERGE
</P>
<P>
   Two months after it broke off merger talks with a larger rival,
Deutsche Bank, Dresdner Bank has held preliminary discussions with
Commerzbank, Germany's fourth-largest private bank. Both banks are
under pressure to consolidate and reduce costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
