<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KAPONO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAPONO TO STAY AT UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA will not be siphoning as much talent from
the UCLA men's basketball team as was originally expected. Jason
Kapono, part of a threesome of underclassmen who declared
themselves eligible for the June 28 draft, withdrew his name Friday
as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono, who averaged a team-high 16 points per game as a
freshman last season, was supposed to complete a trio of defectors
along with forwards Jerome Moiso and JaRon Rush. With Wednesday's
deadline to withdraw his name approaching, Kapono sent a letter to
the NBA to be delivered today which outlines his desire to resume
his UCLA career.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso and Rush are still expected to enter the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I would have been a first-round selection in this
draft,'' said Kapono, the Pacific-10 Conference's co-Freshman of
the Year. ``The deciding factor for me was being able to come back
to UCLA, be with my teammates, play for the Bruins and continue my
college experience and education.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to leading the team in scoring, Kapono, 6-foot-7 and
199 pounds, was fourth in rebounding (4.4 per game) and was one of
only two players - with Earl Watson - to start all 33 games for
UCLA last year.
</P>
<P>
   And despite having only one year with the program, Kapono has
already established himself in UCLA's tradition-rich annals by
setting the Bruins' single-season record for 3-pointers with 82.
</P>
<P>
   He broke Tracy Murray's 1992 record (78). Also, Kapono's scoring
average was the second-highest in team history among freshmen,
behind Don MacLean, who averaged 18.6 points per game in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono's change of heart means a change in outlook for the
Bruins in 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inside-outside attack will be that much more effective
because of his ability to make shots from long distance; it will
open up (the interior),'' a relieved UCLA coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great example for why it's good that this system is in
place that allows players to explore their options and gather
information but still have the opportunity to come back. He got an
accurate read that he was the best shooter in the draft but also
realized it was in his best interest in the long term to come back
to school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
