devil's music.'' But Johnson said his mama always told him that
that man, the blues singer Robert Johnson, was his father. On
Thursday the Mississippi Supreme Court agreed. The justices ruled
that Johnson, a 69-year-old retired gravel truck driver, was the
singer's heir and entitled to about $1 million in royalties. Blues
legend Robert Johnson in 1935. (The New York Times) MAGS OUT - NO
SALES
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- June 16, 2000 -- BLACK-PANTHER-MEMOIR --
Thirty years ago, Kathleen Neal Cleaver, instantly recognizable by
her iconic Afro and knee-high leather boots, was writing to agitate
for the Black Panther Party. Today, Cleaver is engaged in a rather
different writing project. She is plumbing her buried past for a
book aptly entitled ``Memories of Love and War.'' Cleaver last
month in her office at the Center for Scholars and Writers, of the
New York Pulic Libaray, where she is working on her book. (Michelle
V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
