<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-NEWDRUG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GENENTECH STOCK DOWN 4% AFTER HEART DRUG FAILS TESTS  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares in Genentech Inc. slipped 4 percent
Friday after the South San Francisco, Calif., firm said an
experimental drug to treat heart disease had failed the second of
three stages of human trials.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech had been testing anti-CD18 to see whether it minimized
the aftereffects of heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Most heart attacks are caused by blockages in the blood vessels
that supply the heart. Doctors today can bust these blockages with
drugs that dissolve the fibers that hold clots in place.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Dr. Hal Barron, director of cardiovascular
research at Genentech, 20 to 30 percent of the time, the flow of
blood through the heart remains sluggish even after the clot is
busted, weakening the muscle and the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-CD18 had been intended to solve this aftereffect and
restore normal blood flow. As Barron explained, Genentech had
theorized that the sluggishness in the blood flow is caused when
white blood cells, one of the body's defense mechanisms, congregate
in the locale of the former clot.
</P>
<P>
   Barron said anti-CD18 is an antibody designed to bind to white
blood cells in a way that would prevent them from clumping up and
slowing down the blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   To test this theory, Genentech did a Phase II clinical trial,
involving 415 heart attack patients at 60 hospitals nationwide. All
of the patients got a clot-busting drug. Two-thirds also got either
a high or low dose of anti-CD18.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech had hoped to show that heart attack patients who got
anti-CD18 had better blood flow than the group treated only with
the clot buster. But, said Barron, ``the study did not meet its
primary objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Genentech scientists will now review these preliminary results
to ascertain what went awry. Were they wrong to theorize that
clumps of white blood cells slow blood flow? Or, if the white blood
cell theory is correct, was there something wrong with the way they
designed or administered anti-CD18?
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Genentech fell $5.25 to $132.25 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts took the disappointment in stride, saying it was more
important to the company's financial health that Genentech recently
won approval to sell a new, faster-acting clot buster, TNK.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a modest negative _ you never want a Phase II trial not
to work, but that is the nature of drug development,'' Eric
Schmidt, a biotechnology analyst with SG Cowen Securities, told
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
