<SLUG> BC-UNION-BANK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UNION BANK'S LOAN PROBLEMS SPOOK MARKET  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An earnings warning by San Francisco's Union
Bank of California raised fears of an epidemic of bad loans among
the nation's banks, causing the stocks of lenders to plunge Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The shocker late Thursday from Union, the No. 2 bank
headquartered in the West, came just hours after another major
regional bank, North Carolina's Wachovia Corp., issued a similar
warning. The twin revelations of mounting loan problems spooked
investors, who already had been worrying that rising interest rates
would end the boom times U.S. banks have enjoyed for the last six
years.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Union's parent, UnionBanCal Corp., plummeted $8.75 to
$19.94 yesterday, a 30 percent drop. The stocks of other major
banks, including San Francisco's Wells Fargo and Co. and North
Carolina's Bank of America Corp., were also hit. The
Philadelphia/KBW bank index of major bank stocks fell 10.1 percent
in the two days ended Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said signs of credit problems at Union and Wachovia
appear to be the tip of an iceberg that extends widely throughout
the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   As interest rates creep up, the longest economic expansion in
U.S. history is beginning to show stresses and strains, they noted.
Now, some large corporate borrowers are having trouble repaying
loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had easy credit for an extended period,`` said Sutro &AMP; Co.
analyst Campbell Chaney. ``You had loans that should not have been
made or should have been structured more tightly.``
</P>
<P>
   Union said Thursday that it plans to set aside $70 million to
cover bad loans in the current quarter, seven times more than it
reserved in the second quarter of 1999, amid a jump in delinquent
credits.
</P>
<P>
   Union's case suggests the problem might be broad indeed. In a
conference call yesterday, bank officials said they had written
down nine corporate loans this quarter, spread throughout a range
of industries, including retailing, health care, technology and
finance.
</P>
<P>
   Bank officials did not identify the borrowers. But one person
close to the bank confirmed that the largest troubled credit,
representing about one-third of the $52 million in loan charge-offs
that Union expects to take this quarter, is Stage Stores, a Houston
clothing store chain that filed for bankruptcy a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Credit problems appear to be concentrated among the giant loans
that banks make by forming syndicates to spread the risk. Federal
bank examiners are in the midst of their annual review of such
shared loans, and the industry is rife with stories of a regulatory
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators said they won't talk about their review until they
have completed it in about a month. But government officials have
been speaking out for months against what they say is a rise in
imprudent lending, especially to corporate borrowers that are
already tapped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is quite a bit of risk out there,`` said David Gibbons,
deputy comptroller for credit risk at the Office of the Comptroller
of the Currency, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
