<SLUG> BC-BLUELIGHT-KMART-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BLUELIGHT.COM PUTS KMART ON WEB  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's the ultimate Kmart special: free Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   All year, the giant retailer has blanketed its stores with discs
and flyers touting its BlueLight Net service; it stepped up the
campaign this month, sending greeters to stand under a flashing
blue light at Kmart entrances and hand out software.
</P>
<P>
   The objective: Reach out to ``everyday Americans,'' especially
the 44 percent of the population not yet online, and assemble them
into a ready, willing and able audience of Kmart shoppers on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff will come Saturday, with the launch of Kmart's store
in cyberspace, also called BlueLight, after the beacon Kmart used
in the 1970s to identify an aisle with special sales items.
</P>
<P>
   With the nation's No. 2 mass market retailer backing it,
BlueLight has lofty goals and expects to realize them fast. ``If we
can't do $100 million in revenue over the next 12 months, we might
as well all start looking for new jobs,'' said Mark Goldstein,
chief executive of BlueLight, which is run as a stand-alone company
in San Francisco, far from Kmart Corp.'s Troy, Mich., headquarters.
He expects the online store to turn a profit by the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart owns 60 percent of BlueLight and is giving the tiny Net
firm access to the resources that come with size: ads in the 72
million newspaper circulars Kmart distributes every week; presence
in its 2 billion direct mail pieces a year; clout in purchasing
from suppliers; and a database of 92 million households and their
buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kmart is definitely shooting to capitalize on all of the
synergies between the stores and the Web site,'' said Ken Cassar,
Internet analyst with Jupiter Communications Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   BlueLight calls its integration with the brick-and-mortar stores
``sticky bricks.'' Customers will be able to return their Internet
purchases to any Kmart store (80 percent of Americans live within
15 minutes of a Kmart); the 2,171 Kmart stores will feature kiosks
where shoppers can call up the Web site to order items that are out
of stock in the store.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the site finishes ramping up this fall, BlueLight
will carry many more items than the average Kmart, which is
constrained by shelf space to about 75,000 products. BlueLight will
offer extra colors, styles and variations of Kmart products and
will have additional higher-ticket merchandise such as big-screen
televisions, digital cameras and above-ground swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   Products that overlap with Kmart stores will account for about
one-quarter of BlueLight's inventory. For those products, the
online firm will be able to buy from suppliers at the same prices
as Kmart, which enjoys gross margins in the low 20-percent range.
Goldstein said those margins will allow BlueLight to subsidize
lower prices on other items. BlueLight hopes suppliers will cut it
good deals to impress Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're drafting everything Kmart does,'' Goldstein said, using
the bicyclist's term for tailing another rider who acts as a wind
block.
</P>
<P>
   Distribution will be handled at a new warehouse in Memphis,
Tenn., where Federal Express has its hub. BlueLight has invested in
a fulfillment company called SubmitOrder, which will be in charge
of shipping and returns.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Kmart, BlueLight is backed by Martha Stewart Living
Omnimedia, which bought a 5 percent stake for $13 million; Softbank
Venture Capital, which has invested more than $60 million; and
Yahoo Inc. The Yahoo alliance means that BlueLight ISP users will
see a ``MyYahoo'' page whenever they log on to the Internet; about
a quarter of the page is devoted to a column of links to BlueLight
sales and departments.
</P>
<P>
   But heavy-duty backing doesn't necessarily translate into
success online. In just the past few weeks, online ventures
supported by Disney Co. (Toysmart), Viacom Inc.'s Nickelodeon unit
(Red Rocket) and Hearst/ Maytag (Brandwise.com, comparison
shopping) have shut down.
</P>
<P>
   And a still bigger question is whether the pricey proposition of
using the free ISP as a Trojan horse to get BlueLight onto
shoppers' PCs will pay off.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 2.3 million subscribers have signed up with BlueLight;
1.38 million, or 60 percent, are active users who have logged on in
the past 30 days. BlueLight says its customer acquisition costs are
remarkably low: about $3 to reach each new BlueLight subscriber.
But that excludes the cost of subsidizing their free Net access,
which is about $5 per month per user. That translates into $6.9
million a month right now just to carry people who may never spend
a dime with BlueLight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The activity of getting Internet access is a different
behavior than the activity of shopping,'' said Andrew Bartels, an
analyst with the Giga Information Group in Cambridge, Mass. ``It's
not clear to me whether there will be synergy.''
</P>
<P>
   Scale matters: BlueLight's cost per subscriber will go down as
more people sign up. But most PC owners in the United States
already have Internet access. So to grow dramatically, BlueLight
will have to achieve an even more ambitious goal: increase PC
penetration.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart and BlueLight are stepping up to the plate by offering a
very low-cost PC beginning this fall. (Goldstein said they
considered and rejected Internet appliances as too limited in
functionality.) PCs are a new product area for Kmart, which carries
few electronics.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the sweet spot comes, when they attract a person
buying their first computer and get them to sign up for the free
ISP'' _ and then shop on BlueLight, Cassar said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Amazon.com holds the e-tailing crown and is BlueLight's
biggest competitor. But a far bigger one is in the wings. Wal-Mart
Stores Inc., the nation's leading retailer, towers over Kmart with
$165 billion in annual sales versus Kmart's $46 billion; 90 million
shoppers a week versus Kmart's 30 million; and a market
capitalization of $243.6 billion versus $3.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Wal-Mart's ventures online have been surprisingly
feeble. But it has been moving forcefully this year. It has linked
up with powerful venture capital firm Accel Partners, hired a
respected Banana Republic veteran to head the online arm, set up
offices in Silicon Valley instead of Arkansas to attract top-tier
talent, and linked up with powerhouse America Online Inc. to offer
a low-cost Internet service _ expected to be about $10 a month,
half the price of AOL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wal-Mart executes very well,'' Goldstein said. ``We don't
underestimate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, BlueLight will move into a new building near
Fisherman's Wharf, but for now, its 110 employees are crammed into
a rabbit's warren of offices near Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   To stay in touch with the middle America sensibilities of their
target audience, all the BlueLight employees are required to wear
Kmart-purchased outfits every Tuesday. ``A lot of these folks had
never even been to Wal-Mart or Kmart before,'' said Goldstein,
pointing out that most of the twentysomething dot-com workers had
lived only in San Francisco or New York _ ``not cities where you
grab the essence of what America is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Now once a week they sport bright orange jumpsuits from Kmart's
Dickie's work-wear line, full-camouflage hunting gear complete with
caps, dresses with the tags still on to prove the provenance, or
sometimes just regular khakis and blue shirts, all purchased at
Kmart's bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
