<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON RELEASES ATTACK ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton released her first television
advertisements attacking an opponent by name on Friday, assailing
Rep. Rick Lazio for his opposition to legislation on hate crimes
and health care, as she intensified her effort to sow doubts about
her new opponent among New Yorkers who know little of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you know, the more you wonder,'' the announcer says
ominously at the conclusion of each of the two stark 15-second
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually short advertisements, each presented as a ``News
Update,'' are staccato presentations of white type on a black
screen that mimic the clatter of type on old teletype machines.
They describe Lazio's position on two issues as out of step with
political thinking in New York: regulation of health-maintenance
organizations, and legislation that provides additional penalties
for crimes in which victims were chosen because of _ among other
things _ their race, gender or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements provide the latest evidence of the extent to
which Clinton is trying to discredit Lazio, who became her opponent
after Mayor Rudolph Giuliani stepped aside for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past month, Lazio, R-Suffolk County, has sought to
present himself as a moderate Republican, to the evident concern of
Clinton's advisers. The television advertisements come at the end
of a week in which Clinton has begun attacking Lazio for his votes
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has now become the first candidate in the Senate race to
use negative television advertisements, an event that several
politicians described as an early watershed in the rapid escalation
of this race. Typically, candidates for office refrain from running
negative advertisements until relatively late in the campaign,
instead using their advertising budgets to present their views and
backgrounds to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers said that her campaign had decided to move
now as part of an aggressive attempt to lead voters to form
opinions of Lazio. This is the first in what is likely to be a
series of such advertisements. ``This is going to be a race of
clear contrasts, and voters deserve to know where the candidates
stand on the critical issues,'' said Clinton's campaign manager,
Bill de Blasio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign manager, Bill Dal Col, asserted that Clinton in
both advertisements distorted Lazio's record in attempt to
discredit him. He described the ads as ``a desperate act by a
desperate campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``History teaches us that the first victim of a
Clinton campaign is the truth, and that is apparently the case in
this race as well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first of the two advertisements focuses on Lazio's
opposition to a Democratic version of a so-called patients' bill of
rights that, among other things, gives patients the right to sue
health-maintenance organizations for mistreatment. Lazio supported
a Republican bill that instead focuses on giving tax deductions to
help people pay their medical premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The second advertisement focuses on Lazio's initial opposition
to a hate-crimes bill passed by the state Senate in Albany. Lazio's
spokesman, Dan McLagan, said the candidate opposed it because he
believed that additional penalties should not be built into the
statute but should instead be addressed by judges during
sentencing. He said Lazio later decided to support the legislation
because ``something is better than nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
