<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANTS-PRICES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Giants Fans Have Great Expectations _ For Profits  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How bad do you want to see the Giants go up
against the Houston Astros, a team with the worst record in Major
League Baseball?
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, there are some Giants season-ticket holders
who think demand for Sunday's matchup is so intense that they're
offering their seats at a markup of more than $200 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The sky-high ticket prices were posted Friday on the Giants' own
Web site  &LR; (www.sfgiants.com), &LR;  where the team recently introduced
an online trading post for season-ticket holders to unload seats
for games they can't attend.
</P>
<P>
   After just one week of operation, this much is clear: Giants
season-ticket holders have a pretty high opinion of the value of
their seats. The majority of tickets offered are going for more
than $100 over the approximately $30 face value.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just wrong,'' said Bryan Ferreira, information services
manager for a financial services Web site called MetaMarkets.com
and a season-ticket holder himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are paying that kind of money for tickets, that's
definitely an idiotic thing to do,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, although just about every Giants game on the horizon is
sold out _ thank the new Pacific Bell Park for that _ there are
plenty of other ways for fans to score last-minute seats, and most
are a whole lot cheaper than what's available at the Giants' online
``Double Play Ticket Window.''
</P>
<P>
   Online auction site eBay, of course, offers bargains galore,
including, as of Friday afternoon, a pair of tickets for Sunday's
game for just $49.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the numerous resellers in the Bay Area that offer
tickets for about a 100 percent markup from the face value, which
is still just a fraction of what some of the season-ticket holders
are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five hundred dollars for a pair of tickets?'' asked Susan
Hubley, co-owner of reseller Infield Advantage, which is one of the
few to offer tickets over the Net. ``That's just ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   At her site, a $23 Lower Box seat might go for about $40, while
an $18 Upper Reserve might sell for about $30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand isn't that great,'' Hubley said. ``There are some games
where we have to eat tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   So what would compel the owner of Field Club, Section 121, Row
K, Seats 9 and 10 to think that his or her tickets for tomorrow's
game are worth $275 apiece on the open market?
</P>
<P>
   Or why would the holder of Lower Box, Section 102, Row 2, Seats
1 and 2 think that anyone would be willing to cough up $220 each
for the tickets?
</P>
<P>
   Tom McDonald, the Giants' senior vice president of marketing,
was silent for a moment when asked these questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a free market,'' he finally replied. ``If people want to
try to get these amounts, they're welcome to.''
</P>
<P>
   He added quickly that he didn't think these high-end sellers
would get the prices they're asking. ``But if our customers want to
speculate, that's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The online Double Play Ticket Window was launched June 9. The
idea is to provide a venue for ``charter'' season-ticket holders _
those who ponied up an average $4,000 extra for lifetime rights to
the seats _ to sell off unwanted tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers can have the proceeds credited to future ticket
purchases or can redeem them for Giants merchandise. Or, if they so
choose, they can request that a check be sent at the end of the
season, with the Giants pocketing any interest earned from
investing the funds in the interval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a service we're providing for the people who committed to
the program early,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   In its first week, he said 1,004 tickets changed hands via the
service. The total value of the transactions was not available.
</P>
<P>
   But fully three-quarters of all tickets posted at the site were
at or near the original face value, McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   If so, then a sudden wave of greed overcame season-ticket
holders yesterday because only a precious few seats offered were
for anywhere near the original price.
</P>
<P>
   (Confidential to the owner of Lower Box, Section 115, Row 26,
Seat 7, offering the ticket for Sunday's game for a mere $25.30:
Way to go, dude.)
</P>
<P>
   Extending into July, most seats up for grabs at Double Play are
being offered by their owners for between $100 and $200 over the
face value.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are posting as high as they can, seeing what
the interest is, and then reposting to sell,'' said Larry Baer, the
Giants' chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, many fans may want to look around before
buying tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all relative,'' said Kevin Pursglove, a spokesman for
eBay and longtime Giants fan. ``I guess this is the great thing
about the Internet, that there's so many options available.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
