u a BC-TEXAS-BONFIRE-HNS &LR;      06-16 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BONFIRE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TEXAS A&AMP;M BONFIRE SNUFFED UNTIL 2002 &HT;    By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M University's annual Bonfire
will be canceled until 2002 to allow time to plan a safer, simpler
event, university President Ray Bowen said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes doing the right thing involves making a very tough
decision,'' he said at a news conference on campus. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In Bowen's view, doing the right thing will mean a drastically
scaled-back Bonfire, much smaller than the 55-foot tower that
collapsed Nov. 18, killing 11 students and one former student.
</P>
<P>
   It will also mean a design by licensed engineers, logs cut by
professionals, a two-week time frame to build it and much more
university supervision of a project that for 90 years has been a
student-run affair.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen's decision came slightly more than six weeks after a
sharply worded report criticized Texas A&AMP;M for being lax in
allowing the Bonfire to grow into a towering, dangerous structure
put together by students with no professional help or oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a Bonfire if it's completely restructured,''
Bowen said. But he also tried to make the point more than once that
even ``if we did not have a Bonfire, we would still have the Aggie
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Many students and other Aggie supporters were not appeased by
that, however. Some students vowed to hold a ``rebel Bonfire''
off-campus until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   One A&AMP;M staff member who asked not to be identified, groused:
``I could build something out of Popsicle sticks, but that ain't
gonna make it Bonfire.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bowen seemed to get widespread support from alumni groups,
state leaders, faculty members and many of the parents whose
children died in the Bonfire collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The Bonfire, which precedes the annual football matchup with
archrival University of Texas, will be replaced this November and
in 2001 with memorial services.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a task force involving students, faculty,
construction experts and others will design a one-tier ``teepee''
structure that should take far less time to build and won't
endanger lives, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bonfire is relit in 2002 on the same polo field where
the stack fell last fall, it will be professionally engineered.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen announced his anguished decision after months of
consultation with experts, students, ``Aggie Moms'' and others. He
said everyone agreed that the tradition should be continued only if
the participants' safety could be insured.
</P>
<P>
   ``That horrible event took from us 12 fine young people and
injured 27 other young people and inflicted really unspeakable pain
on their families and the ones that were injured,'' Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we think about the Bonfire in the future, understand that
we do this with this one thought in mind: We had this horror visit
our campus,'' Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   To insure that unsafe construction practices and faulty design
features don't creep back into the process, the university will
require annual certification by professional advisers. If the
construction in 2002, is ``judged successful by the certification
process, then we will have a 2003 construction,'' Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   The event will remain a student-run, university-sanctioned
``Aggie spirit'' activity.
</P>
<P>
   But it will not be the project that in the past has been tackled
at a feverish, adrenaline-pitched pace with some students spending
much of a semester in planning, cutting and building a log tower so
large that it would burn for days.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bonfire will depend on donated logs that are
professionally cut and the ritual is likely to become more
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how much yet, but it will definitely cost
more,'' said the president. ``Presumably, the design, the safety
plan, the construction plan would be principally a one-time
investment with improvements over time.''
</P>
<P>
   The university president's decision, which came as a
disappointment to students who will graduate before November 2002,
was supported by the A&AMP;M chancellor and regents, the Faculty
Senate, Association of Former Students and most of the families
affected by the 1999 accident.
</P>
<P>
   Porter Garner, director of the alumni group representing 200,000
former students worldwide, said: ``Our membership is going to be
extremely pleased that Bonfire will eventually continue. The
pre-eminent concern from every former student we've heard from is
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Faculty Senate speaker Bob Strawser said shortening the Bonfire
preparation time from several months to about two weeks ``is going
to make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The elimination of the `cut' (tree-cutting) is a very positive
step. There were many injuries there. That will also significantly
reduce the time that students might be involved in Bonfire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the students will accept it,'' he added. ``They really
don't have a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bowen said he was inclined to permanently cancel the
Bonfire ``the moment it fell,'' he said he was convinced it could
be restructured safely in part by the report of a special
investigative commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the May 2 report, the commission expressed doubt that
students could be equipped with adequate knowledge and skills, but
Bowen said his decision challenges students to ``protect this
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Regents Chairman Donald E. Powell said: ``I think, at the end of
the day, everyone will support his decision, as painful as it may
be to some.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Bowen made a ``hard decision'' after ``an extraordinary
amount of listening to the commission, faculty, students and all
others who have an interest in the university. Foremost in his mind
was that something like this will never happen again because of
some decision he had made.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowen's announcement also drew the endorsement of Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Lexington, Ky., Bush said the decision
represented ``a very cautious approach, and I appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's highest-ranking Aggie in politics, Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry, likewise was supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing all along has been guaranteeing the
safety of students,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Chronicle reporter Richard Stewart contributed to this report. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
