<HEADER>
A6685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE0617-C     06-16 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace takes fifth pole; win would be nicer
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG POND, Pa. _ When drivers and team owners talk about parity
on the Winston Cup circuit this year, they are definitely not
referring to qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Time trials have been a one-man show, with Rusty Wallace
capturing his fifth pole of the season at Pocono Raceway Friday.
Only one other driver, Dale Jarrett, has won two poles through 14
events.
</P>
<P>
   However, starting the race in first and finishing it there are
different things. Wallace has been able to transform all the No. 1
starts into only one victory (Bristol).
</P>
<P>
   ``Closing the deal, that what's been missing . . . probably the
only that's missing from our season so far,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a stronger team this year than we've had in
years. The engine program is second to none. (Crew chief) Robin
Pemberton and the guys have built probably the best race cars I've
ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got to start closing the deal. Winning poles and
leading laps has got to lead to more checkered flags.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the Penske-Kranefuss team is enjoying a banner
year. Not only has the No. 2 Ford owned qualifying, it has
dominated the circuit in laps led with 764 _ more than twice as
many as runner-up Dale Earnhardt Jr. (364).
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is also sixth in the Winston Cup points standings, 13
away from cracking the top five. But failing to take advantage of
pole positions is bothering the veteran driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew how to close a race the right way, I would have done
it,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Rockingham was Wallace's first pole; pit problems caused a
12th-place finish. At Martinsville he led 343 of 500 laps, but was
devastated by a blown tire and questionable pit strategy. At
Richmond, Wallace led the most laps again and finished fifth. He
blew his chances of winning at Dover when he got a stop-and-penalty
for an illegal pass during a restart.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wallace has failed to capitalize on the majority of his
pole positions, he's not apologizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's always important to start up front,'' Wallace
said. ``Everybody is trying to do all they can for their sponsors,
so it's important when people turn on the TV on Sunday and see the
No. 2 car up front.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they are going to be able to talking about (my car) a lot
(at the beginning of the race). After the third lap, they might not
_ but I plan on talking about it all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
