<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-INTERNET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC BISHOPS WARN PARENTS TO BE VIGILANT ON INTERNET &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE, Wis. _ ``User beware,'' the nation's Roman Catholic
bishops warned parents Friday, adopting a statement on the Internet
acknowledging its benefits but urging consumers use it judiciously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you find it on the Web doesn't mean it's true,
and just because a site uses `Catholic' in its name doesn't mean it
reflects the teaching and practice of the Catholic faith,'' says
the prelates' 2,500-word statement, ``Your Family and Cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   Adopted with no discussion in a voice vote, the statement
responds to concerns about obscene and ``hate-filled'' material in
cyberspace. Offering everything from stock prices to travel
information, the Internet is becoming ``an invaluable educational
tool'' as government assistance enables more schools to go online,
the statement says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, this technology comes at a different kind of
price,'' it says, noting some people feel ``the apparent
anonymity'' of the Internet ``relieves them of responsibility for
their actions.'' Some of the highest traffic is to pornography
sites or to sites purveying hatred, the statement says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet use, then, can be a little like visiting the best
theme park in the world and coming across a toxic waste dump,'' the
statement says.
</P>
<P>
   It recommends parents apply the same rules to Internet use as in
the real world, discouraging their children from talking to
strangers and being as safety conscious when children go online as
when they are not at home.
</P>
<P>
   Other recommendations include using an Internet service provider
that filters access to objectionable sites, spending time on the
Internet with children and guiding them in responsible use of
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Texas bishops applauded the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the technology must come attention to moral, personal and
character values,'' said Bishop James A. Tamayo, auxiliary bishop
of the Diocese of Galveston-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Curtis Guillory, bishop designate for the Diocese of
Beaumont, said the statement calls on Catholics to evaluate what
they find on the Internet. ``It helps Catholics to view or approach
the media out of their faith experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing principles of good taste, tolerance and civility to
bear on U.S. media _ whether Catholic or secular _ was uppermost in
the bishops' minds during their spring session. In addition to the
statement on the Internet, the prelates adopted three other
statements related to media.
</P>
<P>
   One on protocol for Catholic media stresses that newspapers,
radio, television, Web sites and other media that want to be
considered ``Catholic'' in content should obtain clearance from
diocesan bishops. But compliance with the standard is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Another on civility in media urges journalists avoid allowing
coverage of policy disagreements to degenerate into personal
attacks. It encourages them to respect the ``worth and dignity of
every person,'' check facts, report accurately and not presume to
know a person or institution's motive without evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Search for the truth, report the truth, and respect the human
dignity of those about whom you report,'' the statement says,
``whether you find them worthy of praise or blame.''
</P>
<P>
   A third, titled ``Renewing the Mind of the Media,'' asks the 60
million U.S. Catholics to pledge support to encouraging morally
worthy media content and discourage that which is immoral or
demeans dignity.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage a ``more responsible, moral and ethical media,''
individual Catholics are asked to pledge they will take one of 10
actions including: talk with family about responsible media use,
contact a media outlet with praise or complaints, trade one hour a
week using media for an hour in prayer and skip a few movies or
rental videos and use the money saved to help someone in need.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to keep reminding our people that we cannot let the
pervasive culture of the entertainment media make us feel that
being a religious person is somehow unnatural or unAmerican,'' said
Bishop Joseph Fiorenza, leader of the Diocese of Galveston-Houston
and president of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
