<HEADER>
A6688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-JAZZ-CAMP0617-COX     06-16 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-CAMP0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Camp gives kids summertime blues
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ The neck of his Fender Jazz Bass seems almost
too long for Jason Turner. With his left hand, the 13-year-old
squeezes down a chord for a blues number. He stretches his arm out
as if he were dancing with a partner twice his diminutive size.
</P>
<P>
   Turner may not have reach but he does have rhythm. During a
class on improvisation, he is rhythm. Along with nearly 100 other
summer campers, Turner is learning how to swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I jam by myself,'' said Turner, who lives in
suburban Birmingham and has been playing bass for almost a year.
``I have a drum set in my basement. Sometimes my friend comes over
and we'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   That's music to the ears of Earlie Billups, director of the
11th-annual City Stages Jazz Camp. The professional musicians he
corralled to train aspiring jazz artists are preparing students for
a performance today (12:30 p.m. Atlanta time) at City Stages, a
downtown music festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the future of jazz staying alive,'' said Billups a
professional musician. ``And when I say jazz, I mean real jazz, not
modern jazz, not light jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   This is your grandmother's jazz, Billups said. Dixieland. Blues.
These are the smoking riffs built in the Deep South in the early
1900s. It's the stuff of Louis Armstrong, John Coltrane, Miles
Davis, Ella Fitzgerald. It's not Kenny G.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get my drift,'' Billups said.
</P>
<P>
   Bright lights rain down on the jazz beginners sitting in a
theater, where the curtains and chairs are pitch black in a theater
at the Alabama School of Fine Arts. Five sax players sit up front.
Trumpets are in back, guitars and piano on the side, drums in the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh-grader Andrew Watkins taps the pedal of the bass drum
with his right foot, which is covered by a dirty Asics sneaker. The
stick in his right hand strikes a cymbal, delivering a tin sound.
The stick in his left hand raps the silver rim of a Mapex snare
drum.
</P>
<P>
   They're learning to jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody, let's noodle a little bit,'' commands instructor
Willie Thomas, a veteran trumpeter.
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble runs through a scale, improvising on a blues
arrangement called ``Bossa for Valerie.'' Find the form, find the
scale, find the rhythm, Thomas tells them. ``It's like having a
computer and finding the password,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Improvisation is something new to the campers. Some are still
learning to read music. So just making it up can be intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' said 14-year-old drummer Kristen Suberre,
``because you don't know what you're going to end up playing or if
it's going to sound good.''
</P>
<P>
   In a beginning saxophone class, students stand back to back. One
plays a reedy tone, the other tries to match it. The exercise
develops their musical ear _ a critical sense in jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out with a chick, you can stand back to back and
start a relationship,'' said instructor Ralph Lalama, who plays
tenor sax with the Carnegie Hall Jazz Band in New York. ``What's
music? You don't see it. You hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lalama's students work on ``Take the A Train.'' The tenors carry
their parts. The altos struggle. There's a semblance of the tune
there, the same way a chalk outline resembles a dead body.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're rushing it. You're rushing it,'' Lalama tells his class
of six. ``That whole note, move off that.'' Lalama starts singing
the instrumental: Bop-dee-bop-bop-bee-aaaaaaaa-baaaaaaaaaa.
</P>
<P>
   In a drum class, instructor Newman Taylor Baker works with his
students on a Caribbean island rhythm. Student Chris Rodgers, 17,
is playing too fast, as if he were in New York. ``This is an island
beat,'' Baker says. ``They take their time.''
</P>
<P>
   They work on the beat. Rodgers' snare drum snap is a fraction
off from striking at the same time as the bass drum. He tries
again. Baker closes his eyes and shakes to the groove.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a kid, Baker would play Tchaikovsky as much as he
would jam to the recordings of jazz legends Max Roach and Charlie
Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this age, the kids just don't know about jazz, so they're
open,'' Baker said. ``I don't know that they see anything when they
get here, but hopefully they find something when they leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
