<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6795 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SINGER-HEIR-1STLD-WRI     06-16 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-HEIR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSISSIPPIAN IS SON OF FATHER OF THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to correct verb tenses in grafs 7, 14 and 28 and to add
missing word in graf 15.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. _ The legend was that if you touched Robert
Johnson you could feel the talent running through him, like heat,
put there by the devil on a dark delta crossroad in exchange for
his soul. It is why Claud Johnson's grandparents would not let him
out of the house that day in 1937 when Robert Johnson, his father,
strolled into the yard.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson, the famous, almost mythical blues man, had come
to Lincoln County, Miss., to see Virgie Jane Smith, a young woman
he had been intimate with, and a son he had never seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were living in my granddaddy and grandmama's house,'' Claud
Johnson said, thinking back. ``They were religious people, and they
thought that the blues was the devil's music. People back then
believed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told my daddy they didn't want no part of him. They said
he was working for the devil, and they wouldn't even let me go out
and touch him,'' Johnson said. ``I stood in the door, and he stood
on the ground, and that is as close as I ever got to him. Finally,
he said, `Well, I might as well go on.' He wandered off, and I
never saw him again.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants to believe that Robert Johnson came for him that day,
and he has always wondered what would have happened if he had run
across that porch to him, so that everyone would know he was Robert
Johnson's son.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 63 years later, the Mississippi Supreme Court has ruled
that Johnson, a retired gravel truck driver who lives quietly in
Crystal Springs, Miss., truly is the flesh-and-blood of a man so
mythologized that many people do not know where the legend ends and
the truth begins.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, after years of legal battles between Johnson and
other, more distant relatives, the state Supreme Court ruled that
Johnson was the son and sole heir of one of the most influential
musicians of the 20th century, and that he could rightfully receive
more than $1 million dollars in music royalties amassed in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life I have known that he was my father,'' said
Johnson, whose mother had a romantic fling with Robert Johnson in
1931, resulting in his birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was a famous man, but he didn't live to see his
fame,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would never forget the sight of Robert Johnson, still
a young man at 26 or 27, ``clean-cut,'' and sharply dressed as he
walked into the yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was fortunate,'' Claud Johnson said. ``At least I got to
see him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mississippi, and in the broader world of music, Robert
Johnson's name evokes rich, dark and mysterious images of the delta
that gave birth to his music.
</P>
<P>
   Every guitar picker knows the story of how Robert Johnson, just
a raggedy farm worker who wanted badly to play the blues on his old
guitar, sold his soul to Satan at that dark crossroads in
Mississippi, how the devil put fire in his fingers and brimstone in
his throat, fusing him with talent and promising him fame.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone, at least most folks in Mississippi, knows that the
devil is a liar. Some people here blame the devil for Robert
Johnson's demise, saying he tricked him and gave him just enough
fame to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who wrote such blues standards as ``Rambling on My
Mind,'' ``Crossroads Blues'' and ``Me and the Devil Blues,''
produced 41 records, and his haunting, plaintive vocals and guitar
work influenced countless blues and rock 'n' roll musicians. But he
died penniless at age 27 in 1938 in Greenwood. He left no will
because he had nothing to pass on except his music, which few
people seemed interested in at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Guralnik, the author of ``Searching for Robert Johnson,''
(Dutton Books, 1989), said that some have called Johnson the father
of blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so remarkable is not that he struck such an original
chord, but what was new was the way each song was focused in a way
a lot of blues songs aren't,'' Guralnik said.
</P>
<P>
   He was so unappreciated at the time of his death that no one is
even sure where Johnson is buried.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi Supreme Court Justice Mike Mills said in his ruling
that it was impossible to get DNA evidence from a body that does
not exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, Johnson is buried `down by the highwayside,
so his old evil spirit can get a Greyhound bus and ride,''' the
justice wrote in the ruling, quoting one of Johnson's songs, ``Me
and the Devil Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a body forced Claud Johnson's lawyers to turn to
other means to prove his connection to his father, including, as it
turned out, an eyewitness to his conception.
</P>
<P>
   Claud Johnson's mother, the late Virgie Jane Smith Cain, swore
in a 1992 deposition that Robert Johnson had fathered her child.
</P>
<P>
   That might not have carried much weight in court, but Cain's
testimony had collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   A childhood friend, Eula Mae Williams, testified in a 1998 trial
that she watched Robert Johnson and her friend have sex in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   Claud was born nine months later.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson grew up hearing his mother say that he was the son of
the famous blues man, and that made him proud, though he said he
never thought that his father's legend, ``would amount to anything
in money.''
</P>
<P>
   When his mother married a man named Marshall Cain, she insisted
that he take Cain as his last name. But as soon as he was grown, he
legally changed his name to Johnson. ``I got it on my first Social
Security card,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of his lawyers, Jeffrey Ellis of Crystal Springs, said that
no one could say that Claud Johnson started claiming his kinship
only after Robert Johnson's recordings became valuable in the
1980s. ``Mr. Claud had been claiming this all his life,'' Ellis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other relatives questioned the validity of his blood ties to
Johnson. Annye C. Anderson, of Amherst, Mass., and Robert M.
Harris, of Annapolis, Md., are the half-sister and grandson of
Carrie Harris Thompson, who was Robert Johnson's half-sister.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson died in 1983 and left the rights to Robert Johnson's
music to them.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Johnson filed suit in Mississippi seeking to
have himself declared the legal heir and the one entitled to $1.2
million in royalties from the blues artist's recordings.
</P>
<P>
   A trial court ruled in favor of Johnson in 1998, but that ruling
was appealed, leading to the decision on Thursday by the state
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   James Craig, the lawyer representing the other relatives, said
Friday that he was considering filing a motion for the court to
reconsider the ruling. But he said he did not expect extensive
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Craig also disputed the evidence presented to show Johnson's
parentage. Johnson's birth certificate lists Robert Johnson as the
father, Craig said, but Johnson himself never signed the
certificate. Under Mississippi law, birth certificates for children
born out of wedlock must have the father's signature to be valid
proof of paternity, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
