<SLUG> BC-NYCBALLETT-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIEBESLIEDER WALTZER': CITY'S INTIMATE BALANCHINE BALLET SHINES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some ballets can be faked. ``Liebeslieder Walzer'' is
not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Without first-rate performers, the ballet is like too much
chocolate cake. But the New York City Ballet presented a shining
performance of this problematic ballet on Thursday night at the New
York State Theater, with finely meshed dancers alert to every
nuance.
</P>
<P>
   The two-part ballet, choreographed in 1960 to music for piano
and voice, does not illustrate its songs about the agonies of love,
delicious and otherwise. Instead, particularly in the first
section, Balanchine suggests the manners of lovers both gallant and
impetuous, experienced and innocent, in a pell-mell suite of
waltzes for four couples confined to an elegant, intimate drawing
room.
</P>
<P>
   The glass doors have blown open in the second section, and the
lovers, the women now in less formal costumes, dart through as if
blown by the wind. Balanchine said that real people populated the
first act. In the second, their souls danced.
</P>
<P>
   An elegiac Kyra Nichols and Jock Soto were one of two central
pairs of lovers. Wendy Whelan and Nilas Martins were the second,
more unruly pair. All that they are is expressed in small details,
like a slight bow of the head or curve of the arm or repeated
pullings away. There is a hint of approaching death when Soto
carries Nichols' body stretched parallel to the floor. But then,
this is choreography filled with subtle, unexpected bits of odd
partnering and staging that prefigure Balanchine's later anarchic
choreographic urges.
</P>
<P>
   Youth laps at the two couples, personified by a mysterious Maria
Kowroski, partnered by an elegantly restrained Philip Neal, and a
lush Jenifer Ringer, new in the role, who danced with an
extra-gallant Damian Woetzel. But all of this comes from the
movement alone. There is no story here.
</P>
<P>
   The score was eloquently performed by the singers Elissa
Johnston, Teri Medley, William Hite and Mark W. Uhlemann and the
pianists Richard Moredock and Susan Walters.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolaj Huebbe and Yvonne Borree, in a role debut, came close to
faking Balanchine's ``Donizetti Variations'' in bold,
larger-than-life dancing that was enjoyable at first but a little
wearing toward the end. Hugo Fiorato conducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
