<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET CERTIFIED, GET A GOOD JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I am interested in pursuing MCSE certification.
How do you see the potential breakup of Microsoft affecting the
value of this certification? _ Needs New Career
</P>
<P>
   Dear New Career: You know, I wish everybody would stop running
around like Windows is going to disappear just because some goofy
judge thinks he's more powerful than Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I have some news for you, Judge Doofus: Even if the split
actually happens, all you've managed to do is morph Microsoft from
THE most influential software company in the world into the TWO
most influential software companies in the world. Way to go, pal.
I'm sure that will look good on the ol' resume.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Certified Systems Engineer training is just about the
most valuable education you can get if you intend to be a
Poindexter. You can spend as much as $7,500 for an intensive course
with guaranteed results, or you can go the cheap route by buying
the study materials and teaching yourself. The bottom line is that
once you pass that test, you shouldn't have any trouble getting a
good job. Well, unless you're a total loser, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I can't help but suspect that all of these
destructive viruses are being written by Macintosh enthusiasts. How
often do you hear about a virus that targets the Mac? It's as if
the idiots who write the viruses are just trying to discredit all
non-Macintosh equipment. _ Suspicious
</P>
<P>
   Dear Susp: No, these nematodes aren't that smart. A plot like
that would require Machiavellian cunning and insight. All a virus
writer wants to do is to drop a cockroach in our collective punch
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   If I were going to write a virus, I'd target Windows PCs not
because I know where all the little security holes are, but because
I'd be striking about 90 percent of the world's computers. I'd get
more press, I'd be cooler, and all the women would yearn for me
tragically. I hit Macintoshes, and who cares? There just aren't
enough of them to make an attack that newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Macintoshes are susceptible to many of the same kinds of viruses
that bedevil PC users: Trojan horses, macro viruses, file-killers
and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   If somebody really wanted, he or she could write a virus that
would attack any specific platform, and the more popular a platform
it is, the bigger a target it is. Just a few weeks ago, some zero
released a virus that attacked a Spanish cellphone network. It not
only clogged up the network's computers the way the Love Bug did,
but it also sent derogatory e-mail to users' phones. What's next?
Palm Pilots? Gameboys? Furbys?
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: How the heck can I change my Windows 98
settings so that my icons will auto-arrange across the bottom of my
screen instead of down the left side? _ Bottom Feeder
</P>
<P>
   Dear Bottom: You mean you don't want to walk in lock step with
every other Windows user in the world? What would Bill think?
</P>
<P>
   Right-click an empty part of the desktop, go to Arrange Icons on
the menu that pops up, and unclick Auto Arrange. Now stick your
icons wherever you want them. Use Line Up Icons from that same menu
to make the spacing uniform. Download WinTidy from www.hotfiles.com
to keep things arranged. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay has his icons arranged in what appears to be
either an obscene gesture or a lovely daffodil. We can't decide
which. Write him at drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax:
390-7257.)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
