A6800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CLINTON-MUSIC-EDUC-52     06-16 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MUSIC-EDUC-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT JOINS EFFORT FOR MUSIC IN SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A little help from his best friend helped Ishmael
Acevedo slip into the auditorium of his East Harlem school Friday,
one of two New York City schools that President Clinton visited to
express his support for music education and to lobby for billions
of dollars in school construction bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Ishmael, 10, had brought in a yellow slip signed by his parents
that would allow him to participate in the presidential visit. But
as he earnestly explained, ``I ain't have the right tie.''
</P>
<P>
   His best friend, on the other hand, had forgotten the permission
slip but had worn the regulation maroon plaid tie that is part of
the Public School 96 uniform, and he generously gave it to Ishmael.
</P>
<P>
   So while his friend was sequestered with 250 others in the
lunchroom, Ishmael was among four or five dozen lucky students in
the auditorium, sitting just a few rows away as Clinton reminisced
about three of his childhood music teachers and stood by as a music
foundation promised $5 million worth of musical instruments to city
schools over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton charmed Ishmael and the audience of children, teachers
and officials from the Board of Education as he recounted how his
mother had tolerated his squawking on the saxophone until he became
good at it, and how Hillary Rodham Clinton had set up a private
music room for him ``way down a hall'' on the top floor of the
White House, ``where nobody could hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he said, he retreats there to play the saxophone for
15 or 20 minutes and comes out ``full of energy, ready to start
again.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of campaignlike stops for the president, who was
not actually campaigning for himself. He was joined at both schools
by Harold Levy, the schools chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton never mentioned his wife's campaign for the Senate. But
coincidentally or not, Clinton used his next stop, at PS 130, an
overcrowded school in Queens, to lobby for a $25 billion school
construction bond act that has also been mentioned by Hillary
Clinton in her recent campaign appearances. Her opponent, Rep. Rick
Lazio, has opposed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   When the president lamented that the House and Senate leadership
had not adequately supported his school financing proposals,
someone in the audience shouted, ``Hillary,'' and Clinton quipped,
``That's not a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation would help modernize 6,000 schools
across the country, Clinton said, with much of the money going to
the poorest districts, including $1.5 billion to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The most eloquent speech came from Mary Minnick, a fourth-grade
teacher who has worked at PS 130 for over 33 years, since, as she
said, Lyndon Johnson was president. When she started, she said, the
school had 400 children, with two classes for each grade, an indoor
play area, a library, a music room and ``even a dental clinic.''
All the students ate lunch at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she said, it is ``a traffic jam,'' with 900 children, many
housed in portable classrooms outdoors, reading classes in the hall
and music in the lunchroom. There are three lunch shifts, beginning
at 10:30 a.m., and the playroom is long gone.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Clinton's appearance in Queens had the tone of a stump
speech, complete with local elected officials, his visit to East
Harlem was a bit quirkier.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education had installed air conditioners in two
rooms at PS 96 for the president's visit, but the auditorium was
still sweltering, because windows were closed for security reasons.
As teachers distributed bottled water, Clinton shared the stage
with the singers Billy Joel and Brian McKnight, in a testament to
the clout of VH1, the cable music station, which sponsored the
event with Viacom, its parent company.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Viacom, Sumner Redstone, whose net worth is
$12.1 billion, according to Forbes magazine, was also there but did
not say a word, letting his money do the talking as the VH1 Save
the Music Foundation announced its donation of $5 million worth of
musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   A student at PS 96, Kelvin Eusebio, gamely told the audience
that his speech had been written for him by an adult, and then
delivered it _ full of big words and bigger sentiments _ with great
polish and flair.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton congratulated PS 96, one of the worst-performing schools
in the city, for what he said was a rise in third-grade reading
scores by over 300 percent, to 74 percent of the children reading
above grade level from 20 percent. The improvement for the school
as a whole was much more modest, with 22.3 percent of the students
meeting state and city standards this year, compared with 16
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has known his share of mischief, never met Ishmael
Acevedo, but if he had, he might have identified with this
particular third-grader. Ishmael plays the drums at home and the
trumpet at church, but he said he had not been accepted into the
music program at PS 96, because of his behavior. He tries to
behave, Ishmael said, but his devilish streak keeps getting the
better of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in it, but you have to deserve it,'' Ishmael
explained. ``If there's too much kids, sometimes they choose a kid
that be good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
