<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECYCLING-CENTERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECYCLING COMPANY TRIES NEW APPROACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAZON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tomra Pacific, the operator of recycling centers
typically located behind grocery stores, is converting its centers
to a more customer-friendly concept it calls RePlanet.
</P>
<P>
   The new centers feature extended hours, a cleaner look and two
buy-back machines that automatically recognize containers and give
customers a receipt that can be redeemed inside the store.
</P>
<P>
   They're proving so popular, they are being moved to the front of
the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction has been terrific. It has gone exceptionally
well,'' said Jack Brown, chief executive officer of Stater Bros.
Markets. ``The broader scope of what they take will only make it
more convenient for customers to recycle.''
</P>
<P>
   The more appealing appearance, longer hours and more visible
location have resulted in more volume at the recycling centers
already converted, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the first 10 RePlanet recycling centers brought in 50
percent more materials, said Randy Gusikowski, president of Tomra
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Once converted, the centers will continue to accept the same
materials they previously did. Only containers redeemable through
the buy-back machines will be accepted during the hours the center
is not staffed, though.
</P>
<P>
   Each machine accepts aluminum, glass or plastic and is equipped
with a digital camera that takes 25 snapshots per second. Those
photos are compared with a shape database to determine what type of
container is being returned.
</P>
<P>
   Tomra, a Norwegian company with recycling centers around the
world, entered the California market in February 1998 by acquiring
existing companies.
</P>
<P>
   The company then set out to create a new image, Gusikowski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that if we could get some centers here in the state,
we believed there was an opportunity to re-engineer some of those
centers and create a concept that was going to be more appealing to
the public,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gusikowski said Tomra is responding to customer complaints about
short hours, safety and cleanliness by introducing the RePlanet
concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, it wasn't terribly convenient,'' Gusikowski
said. ``Customers were concerned the centers weren't clean and
well-maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   The RePlanet centers are designed with a cleaner, more
professional-looking front end, and the employees are better
trained and held to higher standards of quality and cleanliness,
Gusikowski said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot project was launched at 10 Stater Bros. stores in the
Inland Empire, and Tomra officials tracked their performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``On average, those centers are doing 250 percent more
traffic,'' Gusikowski said.
</P>
<P>
   The volume of material they take in is up by 50 percent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was that if we could provide convenience to people
... they would make recycling part of their regular trip to the
grocery store,'' Gusikowski said.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 75 recycling centers converted to RePlanet, and
Tomra's goal is to have 200 completed by the end of the year. By
the end of 2001, all of Tomra's 400 California centers will be
renovated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a competitive advantage we can have in the
marketplace,'' Gusikowski said. ``Most Californians are so busy,
anything we can do to make it more convenient for them to recycle
helps. It's just one less trip you have to make.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their more appealing look, the centers eventually
will be used for fund raising by community groups.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations will have the ability to receive bar-code tags to
give to members and supporters that they can scan at the buy-back
machines before redeeming their containers.
</P>
<P>
   Any proceeds, instead of being paid to the customer, will be
paid to the organization, Gusikowski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have the whole community using the recycling center
as a means to raise money,'' Gusikowski said. ``We can have many
different types of organizations using this center as a means to
raise funds, and it's something that's good for the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
