<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CLINTON-SIDE0618-COX     06-16 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SIDE0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday
 &HT;    Clinton's influence still looms
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ He may not be on the ballot this year, but
President Clinton draws stronger reactions from many voters across
the heartland states than do either Democrat Al Gore or Republican
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because he is a larger-than-life political
figure,'' said John Green, director of the Ray C. Bliss Institute
of Applied Politics at the University of Akron.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, 53, took the White House back for the Democrats in 1992
after 12 years of Republican rule. He toned down his party's
liberal rhetoric, ``borrowed'' Republican themes such as welfare
reform and presided over an unprecedented economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   His victories in Ohio, Michigan, Illinois and Pennsylvania were
crucial to his 1992 election over incumbent Republican George Bush.
Clinton also carried the states in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He also took up with White House intern Monica Lewinsky, got
impeached by the House but escaped conviction in the Senate, and is
working hard now to settle the world's trouble spots _ and create a
statesman's legacy in the process.
</P>
<P>
   He remains popular enough, analysts say, to give Republicans
pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Clinton. I wish he could run again,'' said Lynne
Hollins, 35, a barber at Rayfields Friendly Barber Shop in Detroit.
``I like his issues and I know how he's tried to help minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   When the president visited a Columbus elementary school in early
May, admirers lined the streets outside, hoping for a glimpse of
the educator-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's very nice,'' said Diane Smoot, a child-care
provider. ``I wish he would run again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution prohibits Clinton from seeking a third-term,
but doesn't prevent critics from tarring Gore, Clinton's vice
president, with the fallout from the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing that went on with Clinton. I personally don't
think it was right,'' said Andrea McLelland, 29, a nurse in Mt.
Clemens, a Detroit suburb. ``That's basically what I know about
Gore. He stood behind the president.''
</P>
<P>
   McLelland, who voted for Clinton, won't vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't cut the mustard for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ability to charm the voters has become the standard
against which would-be successors are measured.
</P>
<P>
   When George W. Bush visited Cincinnati last summer he first
schmoozed amicably with voters at an inner-city black church and
then wooed Republican big shots at a downtown fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's Clintonesque without the baggage,'' Alex Arshinkoff, the
Summit County Republican chairman, said approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
