<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT MATCHUP SURPRISES STEWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Emanuel Steward, Oscar De La Hoya's former
trainer, was surprised he took this fight with Shane Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, the WBC welterweight champion, has been less than
devastating in big fights in recent years and has been criticized
as a result. So what'd he do? He took another one, on Saturday at
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still surprised when I think about it,'' Steward said.
</P>
<P>
   And excited. This, Steward said, is a great matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Who does he think will win? He said he's ``straight down the
middle'' but seems to lean toward Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very dangerous fight for Oscar,'' Steward said. ``I
know people are picking him because of the physical thing. They
think his punches are more powerful and he's bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then they say he's more experienced in big fights. Well,
with Mosley's (easy-going) psychological makeup, that's not going
to be a factor. Shane is very calm, very comfortable in this
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he has other things going for him: intensity, desire, hand
speed. That word intensity is important. I wouldn't want any of my
fighters to fight Shane Mosley right now, not even Tommy Hearns in
his prime. He so much desire. He's in that combat mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali had it when he was on top, Tyson had it. Look at him. You
leave Mosley alone for five seconds and the guy's shadow boxing.
That's big.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Oscar can hurt him, that might change things. If he can't,
well, it'll be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Weigh-in: De La Hoya weighed in at 146 pounds on Friday, Mosley
at the 147-pound weight limit.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, who some believe is at a disadvantage because he only
recently moved up to the weight class, probably will weigh
considerably more than De La Hoya come fight time.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley said his walk-around weight is about 162, De La Hoya 157.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, De La Hoya was the more antsy of the two
during the weigh-in, as he has been the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   During a final news conference on Wednesday, he tapped his
fingers incessantly on the table in front of him and shadowboxed
before and after the weigh-in. It's as if he can't wait to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, by contrast, seemed to be as calm and cool as ever only
a day before the biggest fight of his life, which many believe has
helped him cope with the magnitude of this event. He stood
relatively still at the weigh-in, only smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Both looked very confident.
</P>
<P>
   Pay-per-view: Promoter Bob Arum has said he expects pay-per-view
buys to exceed $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Others, more realistic, believe the fight could approach the
$760,000 DeLa Hoya-Pernell Whitaker did in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The fact the fight is taking place during the Lakers' run to the
NBA championship hasn't helped, at least not in this town. The
fight has received only a fraction of the coverage it might have
received otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Star-studded: Saturday's fight could break all records for the
number of celebrities expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   The fight promoters issued a preliminary list of about 50,
including Dustin Hoffman, Mark McGwire, Will Smith, Denzel
Washington, Sylvester Stallone, Jennifer Lopez and Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   However, there's no question as to who will receive the biggest
ovation when they're introduced to a crowd expected to exceed
21,000: Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal will be sitting front row, center, according to the
promoter.
</P>
</TEXT>
