<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THEY'RE NOT JUST THROWS IN THE DIRT 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 2nd graf with result of game)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Torre loosely compared it to the year he went
``from hitting .363 to being a babbling idiot.'' That would have
been the 1971 and 1972 seasons, when Torre dropped from the year of
a lifetime to .281, from 137 runs batted in to 81, from National
League Most Valuable Player to ordinary Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``To not doing what I did the year before,'' he said, relaxing
in the Yankees dugout before settling in for the stress of sending
Chuck Knoblauch back out to second base where he had no throws to
make Friday night as the Yankees lost again, this time by 3-1 to
the Chicago White Sox at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch showed up, ready and willing, or ready for anything,
which was an improvement on the previous night, when he committed
three painful throwing errors and had a look in his eyes that
convinced his manager it was time for his second baseman to hitch
an immediate ride home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Knoblauch said when asked who the driver was,
which, hopefully, meant he didn't know the name of the appointed
chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   The experience was so discomforting that several Yankees later
called, Knoblauch said, to make sure he didn't do anything rash,
and we're not talking about emptying the refrigerator of fruit to
practice his soft tosses out the window. In his hour of emotional
need, Knoblauch would have preferred to speak to his mother, but
Linda Knoblauch wasn't in and he had to wait for Friday, when she
told him she wished she could give him a hug.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived early in the clubhouse Friday afternoon and received
a group embrace from his close-knit team. Torre told him, ``You're
my second baseman,'' and the core veterans acted as if he had gone
home early Thursday night with an upset stomach, and they all
continued to refute the contention that Knoblauch has become
anything more than an occasional threat to the fans behind first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I throw the ball low, it's not the talk of the town,''
Derek Jeter said. ``If he throws the ball low, all of a sudden,
everyone's bringing it up again. Every player goes through
stretches where they are not catching or throwing the ball the way
they like to, and if they don't tell you, they're lying.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were lying to themselves, if they believed that
Knoblauch's throwing problem, which he struggled through so
publicly and commendably during last season's postseason, was just
going to go away. It wasn't a cycle. This isn't a slump. Torre's
reduced batting average from one season to the next had a little to
do with pitchers and fielders. Knoblauch, to the contrary, is
unable to execute what in better times was the most natural play he
could make on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something that happened and then you start thinking
about it and then it consumes you,'' said Torre, hoping again that
the problem is rooted in the flaw of the act.
</P>
<P>
   A sports psychologist I know once told me that the most
difficult aspect of treating athletes is getting them to understand
that therapy is not necessarily the act of correcting the
dysfunction, but getting to the bottom of what caused it. Therapy
is open-ended and nonguaranteed. Athletes by nature are a more
scientific breed, staking their careers on mysteries that can be
solved with mechanics and muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch hinted that he had, contrary to public opinion, sought
some form of off-season assistance, though his later comments
suggested that it might have been along the lines of the 24-hour,
self-help course that baseball ordered for another troubled soul
currently lost in the wilds.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker is in his own league, but Knoblauch, when asked if
he had any knowledge of whether his problem might be bigger than
baseball, said: ``That's something maybe a psychologist or some
kind of professional would know. I can't pinpoint when this all
started, or if there was an event in my life that made this happen.
Maybe these people will have the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Blass and Steve Sax and anyone else who has lived through
something like this don't have them. There is no formula here.
Knoblauch's issues are his own. Only he can solve them. The fans
booed him Thursday night, but they stood and cheered
compassionately Friday night when he led off the home first inning.
He promptly singled into right field and soon turned an ankle
sliding into second. He remained in the game, limping, grimacing.
</P>
<P>
   Fans appreciate tough guys _ the smaller, the better _ and
Knoblauch, optimistically listed at 5 foot 9 inches, was showing
them that he wasn't afraid to come back to the ball park, to face
them and the news media and the meanest ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   If only it was that easy for him to look within himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000616.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-BONFIRE-1STLD-W     06-16 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BONFIRE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M SUSPENDS BONFIRE FOR TWO YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (CHANGES ``tragedy'' to ``accident'' in lede.)  
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In response to the worst accident in the history of
Texas A&AMP;M University, the president of the university Friday
suspended its traditional football bonfire ritual for two years to
allow time to plan a scaled-down, tightly supervised event that
will better ensure student safety.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the university's president, Dr. Ray Bowen,
reverberated across Texas and punctuated a seven-month period of
criticism and Texas A&AMP;M soul-searching after a four-tier stack of
logs nearly 60 feet tall collapsed last Nov. 18, killing 11
students and a former student and injuring 27 others.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tragedy was a wake-up call for everyone here and everyone
in the country,'' said Bowen in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   University officials said the bonfire could resume in the fall
of 2002 provided that students meet conditions established by
Bowen. He said that when classes resumed in late summer, he would
convene a committee of administrators, faculty members and students
to begin reorganizing the event.
</P>
<P>
   Canceling the next two bonfires will allow appropriate time to
plan, Bowen said. He predicted that a smaller, safer bonfire tower
would be built, with increased oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are quite optimistic we can create a safe structure,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire, a tradition that began in 1909 at Texas A&AMP;M on the
eve of its football game against its archrival, the University of
Texas, annually draws thousands of people to the A&AMP;M campus about
90 miles northwest of here in College Station.
</P>
<P>
   Student crews working with little supervision stacked and bound
thousands of logs felled from nearby forests into a tower shaped
like a wedding cake. The final week of construction, known as Push,
required round-the-clock efforts as students raced to finish in
time to set the stack afire at a pep rally before the game.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a five-member independent commission appointed by Texas
A&AMP;M issued a report saying that design flaws in the log tower were
largely to blame for the collapse. The report also said students
building the tower were inadequately trained, and criticized
university officials for failing to provide adequate supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to Friday's announcement was quiet on the A&AMP;M campus.
The academic year ended several weeks ago and most students had
left the campus. Only about a dozen students and faculty members
attended Bowen's news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good they're making this decision, though I don't
know about the two-year period of holding off,'' said Justin
Lightsey, 19, a sophomore from nearby Bryan. ``I think it's good
they're making it safer. My parents, though, told me not to
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Braus, whose son Dominic remains in physical therapy after
suffering extensive injuries to his arm in the collapse, said she
was pleased with the new safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Braus also said that she did not blame the university for her
son's injury and that she was elated that one of A&AMP;M's oldest
traditions would eventually continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stop Christmas trees, you can't stop Easter eggs,''
Braus said. ``These traditions have to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to continue the bonfire tradition has been
enormous. More than 8,000 students have signed a petition
supporting its continuance.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Texas A&AMP;M Faculty Senate recommended
that Bowen suspend the tradition for at least one year. And on
Wednesday, the Texas Board of Professional Engineers voted to
conduct an inquiry to determine whether state engineering laws were
violated.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, an alumnus of the university, endorsed the
new policy. ``He supports the administration,'' said Eric Bearse, a
spokesman for the lieutenant governor. ``The most important thing
is to ensure the safety of the students, and they have put together
a process that puts safety first and foremost.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the restructured bonfires would differ greatly
from those of recent years, when students spent up to three months
cutting down thousands of trees and then building the tower of
logs. In the future, the event will last only two weeks. The trees
will be donated from companies and students will not participate in
the harvest. Also, Bowen said, the reduced size of the tower will
lessen the environmental damage, a point criticized even before the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, construction will end by midnight, and university
officials will provide continual supervision. A fence will surround
the site and a video camera will record construction. The hierarchy
of the student organization, which had been run by upperclassmen
known as Red Pots and Brown Pots, will be reorganized.
</P>
<P>
   And the unstable wedding cake shape will be abandoned in favor
of a teepee shape used in the 1950s and '60s. Professional
engineers will draft the design and establish the construction
protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the bonfire structure would be assessed and
certified every year and that failure to meet the specifications
would result in penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't comply, if the rules are broken, there will be
no bonfire the following year,'' said Cindy Lawson, the school's
executive director for community relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-00 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
