<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN OF BELCHER CALLED A `LITMUS TEST'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ It has taken longer than anticipated, but Tim
Belcher will finally make his 2000 debut tonight for the Anaheim
Angels against the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher had surgery to repair a torn muscle in his right elbow
on Dec. 2, and has spent the past 6 months trying to get the elbow
strong enough to pitch again. Initially the club had hoped to have
him back in the first week of May, but he went through a ``dead
arm'' stage that forced him to stop throwing completely for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia said he's hoping to get up to 100 pitches
from Belcher tonight, which ideally would translate into about six
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready,'' Scioscia said. ``I think he's at a point were
he's very confident about the health of his arm and very confident
about his velocity. His command is where it should be. When you get
into a major league game, that'll be the litmus test to see how far
he's come.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher went 14-14 for Kansas City in 1998, and signed a free
agent contract with the Angels for two years (plus a club option)
worth $10.6 million before the 1999 season. But last year, injuries
limited Belcher to 24 starts and a 6-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   Lineup changes: After scoring only three runs in the past two
games combined against Tampa Bay, Scioscia shook up the lineup
Friday. The most notable change was that center fielder Garret
Anderson, whose average is down to .245, was not in the lineup.
Anderson will not start today's game either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the most part Garret has worked very hard to play
himself out of this mini slump,'' Scioscia said. ``But we know he's
not at the level he will end up. Sometimes guys are banging their
head against the wall, and you do plug through it. We've seen Mo
(Vaughn) do it. We've seen Timmy (Salmon) do it. But we've reached
a point where it was time to take a step back.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has played in 150 or more games in each of the
past four seasons, hates to take a day off. And now he's getting
two off in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's different,'' Anderson said. ``That's how he feels. He
definitely feels strong about it. I'll just deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia also said he has considered putting Anderson in a
different spot in the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn steps up: One of the young pitchers who has stepped up
and pitched well in the absence of Belcher and other injured
pitchers is Jarrod Washburn. In seven starts, Washburn is 2-1 with
a 3.92 ERA. He has been particularly good in his past two starts,
in which he's allowed only two runs and seven hits in 14 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for his recent success is a new routine
before each game. Washburn had been so keyed up at the start of
games, he had a tendency to overthrow and consequently was wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going out there so excited,'' Washburn said. ``I'm
more under control. I throw a little more in the bullpen and get
more focused and a little less excited going into the first
inning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
