<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE MOVES TO SMOOTH TIES WITH LABOR OVER DALEY'S APPOINTMENT TO
CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore moved quickly Friday to try
to tamp down unrest among labor leaders over his appointment of
Commerce Secretary William Daley, a chief labor nemesis during the
recent fight over the China trade bill, as chairman of his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters that the first person outside of his
campaign circle whom he called with the news on Thursday was John
Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   But Sweeney said in an interview Friday that he was traveling on
Thursday morning and that he and Gore did not actually speak until
afternoon, long after he had learned of Daley's appointment through
news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Others said Sweeney, one of the vice president's most consistent
allies, had been left fuming because he was not alerted in advance.
Sweeney issued a statement saying Daley's advocacy of the China
trade bill and the North American Free Trade Agreement put him
``squarely on the opposite side of working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney then accepted an urgent invitation by the vice president
to meet with him Friday. And so Sweeney and Gerald McEntee,
president of the American Federation of State, County and Municipal
Employees and chairman of the AFL-CIO's political arm, trooped to
Gore's official residence here this afternoon and stayed for an
hour to discuss the Daley appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Daley was not present.
</P>
<P>
   ``That comes later,'' Sweeney said. ``Before we talk to the
appointee, we talk to the one making the appointments.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney described the session as frank and blunt. ``I expressed
concern about what effect this might have on our rank and file,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the selection of Daley was especially disappointing
because it came so soon after the bitterly divisive House vote last
month to normalize trade relations with China. Daley was the point
man for the Clinton administration in advancing the bill over
labor's fierce objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we said yesterday still stands,'' Sweeney said. ``Bill
Daley, in his new position, will need to prove he can fight just as
hard for America's working families as he fought for America's
trade deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said Gore had reflected on ``how unfortunate it was that
this all developed, that the timing was difficult and it happened
very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He recognized that the communication was not as good as it
could have been,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether Gore made any promises to the labor
leaders to make up for this appointment, although Sweeney said he
expected Gore to continue advancing his agenda for working families
and would perhaps ``accelerate'' it.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney also suggested a silver lining to the Daley appointment:
``Maybe we're doing something good as far as getting him out of any
more trade agreements,'' he said with a laugh. Despite the
discomfort of his constituency, particularly in the industrial
unions, Sweeney has remained a staunch Gore supporter. And he
reflects the view of many in labor that the unions will ultimately
be able to overlook the vice president's pro-trade activity because
they are determined to keep the White House in Democratic hands.
</P>
<P>
   Aides of Gore said he believed that Daley would be an asset to
the campaign, despite his having crossed swords with labor.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president ``has tremendous confidence in Secretary
Daley, and they had talked about this job before,'' a Gore
confidant said, adding: ``It would be a mistake to take today as a
snapshot of where we will be in November. It's an issue that will
be worked through, but in the end the interests of labor and the
Democratic Party are so consistent with one another that everyone
will be working toward the same goal.''
</P>
<P>
   But the notion that labor has nowhere else to go in the
presidential election infuriates some. The Teamsters union, which
called the Daley appointment a ``slap in the face,'' and the United
Auto Workers have both declined to endorse Gore and are toying with
endorsing Ralph Nader or Pat Buchanan instead. And the United
Steelworkers, which has endorsed Gore, remains detached from his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the assessment mode on the politics,'' said Gary
Hubbard, a spokesman for the steelworkers. ``We've had a lot of
members bailing out from the Democratic Party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
