<HEADER>
A6824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-NY     06-16 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE EXCELS BUT THE YANKEES FALL SHORT
</HEADLINE>
  By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Cone pitched three hitless innings last Sunday
against the Mets, a burst of hope in an otherwise dismal season,
until the rains washed his effort away and a deluge of distractions
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa trade rumors ballooned, Roger Clemens went on the
disabled list, and then Chuck Knoblauch bobbled one ball too many
Thursday night and ducked out of the ballpark before the Yankees
stumbled, 12-3, to the best team in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting happily, if not eagerly, off to the side of the
maelstrom was Cone, whose last and only victory in 13 starts this
season was on April 28.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night Cone walked into the Yankees clubhouse wearing a
smile that would later fade to a fixed and determined stare on the
mound. With a six-inning performance as dominating as it was
reassuring to the Yankees, Cone proved that aborted outing last
Sunday was not a fluke. He had control, location and confidence.
All that he lacked was the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Cone got a no-decision, and even though he set the tone on a
night swirling with redemption, the Yankees lost their second
straight to the Chicago White Sox, this time by 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   James Baldwin recorded his 10th victory of the season, and even
though the Yankees had been the only team to blemish his record,
they could not get to him Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees reliever Mike Stanton, who came in for Cone in the top
of seventh inning, got the loss. He put the winning run on base,
when the leadoff hitter Paul Konerko cracked a ball to deep right
that was carrying home run ambitions in thick, humid air. While
outfielder Paul O'Neill snagged it a foot above the wall, he could
not bring it down with him, and Konerko held up on third base. Two
outs and three batters later, pinch-hitter Tony Graffanino singled
him home.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago added an insurance run off closer Mariano Rivera in the
top of the ninth, when he allowed a double to Graffanino and Mark
Johnson singled him home. It was only Rivera's second appearance
since June 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had a good scoring opportunity in the eighth inning.
Baldwin had departed the game after 7 1/3 innings and reliever
Bobby Howry entered the game to face O'Neill, with Derek Jeter on
base with a walk. O'Neill flied to right.
</P>
<P>
   Now with two outs, and Jeter having stolen second, Bernie
Williams drew a 3-2 count. But he looked at an outside fastball
belt high from Howry and was called out on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago came into the game tied with Atlanta for the best record
in the major leagues. The Yankees still led Boston in the East by a
half-game coming into Friday night, but it was hard to tell by the
unsettled clubhouse, with owner George Steinbrenner's expression of
concern and interest in Sosa, not to mention the shaken starting
pitching. After Friday night's loss, they trail the Red Sox by a
half-game.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday night, Cone had been the main culprit, compiling a
1-6 record and a 6.49 earned run average coming into Friday night.
But there was something different about him Friday night, something
that began last Sunday in an outing that may not have counted
statistically, but did count personally.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night he struck out five batters in six innings and gave
up four hits. But he allowed just one run, his fewest since his
6-0, seven-inning victory at Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Cone was the second-billed Yankee looking for
redemption, if not absolution, Friday night. Knoblauch, just a
night after his three-error debacle, went 2 for 4 but had just one
defensive chance all night, a pop-up. Yet when Clay Bellinger came
in to replace him in the top of the ninth, Bellinger got the first
ground ball hit to second base.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 41,910 first showered Knoblauch with a rousing
round of applause when he came up to bat in the first inning. But
with little fanfare at first, Cone began the game exactly where he
left off last Sunday _ pitching three hitless innings and retiring
the first 10 batters.
</P>
<P>
   His fastball was sharp, the slider even crisper, and he was
ahead of the hitters all night.
</P>
<P>
   In each of his first five innings, Cone recorded a strikeout,
never facing more than four batters an inning. This was not the
same pitcher who had given up 16 earned runs in his last 161/3
innings and had carried a 6.49 ERA. into this game.
</P>
<P>
   His tough inning Friday night was the sixth. Catcher Mark
Johnson led off the inning with to single to right. Cone, who had
given up 14 walks in his last four starts, allowed his first walk
of the game to Ray Durham and followed by surrendering a bunt
single to Jose Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   But after Frank Thomas lined out to Brosius, Magglio Ordonez hit
a sacrifice fly to left that tied the score, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Cone ended the inning by snaring a chopper back to the mound
from Paul Konerko. And that would be his last act in a performance
that not only doubled his last start in duration, but in effort. He
threw 60 strikes in 88 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees' run production consisted of a Scott Brosius home run
off Baldwin, hitting the first-pitch for a shot to left-center
field.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch set the tone for a game. He began the game by
drawing a sympathetic roar when he led off the first inning, as the
fans seemed to be seeing him as something so familiar, seeing him
as human. He hit a bloop single to right, and then on a hit and run
he slid safely yet awkwardly on his left ankle into second base.
But Tino Martinez ended the inning striking out and stranding
Knoblauch at third.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Knoblauch got his first chance, when Paul
Konerko hit a pop fly. Again the fans cheered, hanging signs in
support of their second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   There were no signs for Cone. And no victories either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
