<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK WINDFALL SIMPLY FORTUITOUS, REPUBLICAN SENATE CANDIDATE LAZIO
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENDICOTT, N.Y. _ U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio Friday defended a stock
windfall in a company controlled by some of his contributors as a
good investment that had involved no inside information.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the Republican candidate for Senate, said he had made the
investment on the advice of a broker, whom he declined to name, but
not through representatives of Quick &AMP; Reilly, the brokerage in
which he invested. He invested in special securities, known as
options, in the company, whose executives had given Lazio's
congressional campaigns $35,000 since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio reaped a 600-percent gain on the investment in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some stocks you get lucky on and some stocks you're unlucky
on,'' Lazio said in an interview in this town a few miles west of
Binghamton after one of four campaign stops he made upstate. Asked
if he attributed his good fortune on the investment to luck, he
replied, ``I would say I think that it was a good company and one
that got batted down, and I thought that was an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   He said of the executives, ``I never had a single discussion
with any of the people I know,'' and their contributions, he added,
had never influenced his votes on the House Banking and Commerce
Committees.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said that his overall stock portfolio showed modest gains
of about 10 percent or 15 percent, and that he had been diligent
about disclosing the financial information required by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty clearly, anyone who looks at my financial transactions,
which are completely disclosed every year, can tell that I am not
somebody who's getting rich on public service,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only wish I had Hillary Clinton's stock adviser,'' Lazio
said, a reference to his Democratic opponent's success in reaping
$100,000 over 10 months after investing $1,000 in volatile
commodities. Hillary Rodham Clinton was assisted by executives of a
food company that had business before the state of Arkansas while
her husband was attorney general and then governor.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio in fact attributed news reports on the investments in part
to what he called an emerging pattern of negative campaigning by
Clinton. He was asked about the investments after an article
appeared Friday in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said, ``This is an effort by the Clinton campaign to draw
me down in the mud, which I'm not going down to their level on.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Clinton's spokesman, called the response from
the Lazio campaign inadequate. ``Instead of pointing fingers,
Congressman Lazio should answer legitimate questions that the story
raises,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, in his speech to supporters here, decried two critical
television commercials he said Clinton's campaign was about to
broadcast. But he acknowledged that he did not have proof that the
Clinton campaign had influenced the articles on the options deal.
``That's just my presumption after you see this and that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also noted that the Clinton campaign had a worker known as
a tracker videotaping him at virtually every campaign stop, a
common practice among candidates, but one Lazio called ``cloak and
dagger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened to the Hillary Clinton who was
complaining in the first couple days of this campaign about
negative campaigning. But she has disappeared. I wish she would
come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
