<HEADLINE>
PARK'S DREAM: UNIFIED KOREA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chan Ho Park reminds himself he's a baseball
player first. But he pauses at the news from his native Korea and
hopes for unification.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of family in South Korea got a lot of family in North
Korea,'' he said. ``Hopefully, we'll live together. That's my
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   He's one step closer to realizing his dream. On Friday, South
Korean president Kim Dae-Jung declared ``the danger of war on the
Korean peninsula has disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Park knows the history: Fifty years ago, on June 25, 1950,
Communist and anti-Communist forces, aided by the Chinese in the
North and United States/United Nations in the South, began a war.
It ended three years later at the 38th parallel, or about where it
started.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in South Korea, Park was educated that North Koreans
are poor and don't live in the best Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Korea wants to go to North Korea and help them,'' Park
said. ``We tried, but they don't want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he met a North Korean baseball player at the Asian Games in
Australia in 1993 and found the man to be ``nice, more than we
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, thousands of miles away, Park hears about the historic
meetings between Kim and North Korean ruler Kim Jong Il. The two
Koreas agreed to pursue peace, economic and other changes, the New
York Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   Park remains hopeful, but he's focused on playing baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Roster moves: The impending suspensions stemming from the melee
in Chicago has Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson juggling
his personnel. He has decided he doesn't need 12 pitchers and needs
depth at catcher, so on Friday, the Dodgers sent down pitcher Al
Reyes (who came over from Baltimore in the Alan Mills trade
Tuesday) and recalled Adam Melhuse from Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need 14 positions players,'' Johnson said. ``Also, I feel I
don't have enough innings to keep the bullpen sharp. They're not
overworked at all. Eleven pitchers is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, of L.A.'s last five games, three starters went the
distance and the other two went seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Dodgers have Chad Kreuter (though he soon will serve
his suspension), Paul LoDuca, Melhuse and Dave Hansen in an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley remains disabled since May 31 with a strained right
oblique muscle. He took some swings left-handed on Friday, but
Johnson said Hundley needs more time.
</P>
<P>
   Olson update: Pitcher Gregg Olson, disabled with April 11 with a
left forearm strain, pitched in a simulated game Friday and felt
better than he did in Wednesday's simulated game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we go from here, I don't know,'' Olson said. ``I'm
staying here, but everybody knows I'm way past chomping at the
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Olson was fine but would wait until Sunday to see
how Olson feels. Olson will throw Sunday, possibly in a cage or in
another simulated game and also will throw in some fashion next
week in Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
